/**
 * Hand-written monthly travel briefs per region.
 * Key: region slug → month number (1–12) → brief text.
 * Written in phases — regions without briefs gracefully show nothing.
 */
export const MONTHLY_BRIEFS: Record<string, Record<number, string>> = {
  'id-bali': {
    1: "January drops you right into monsoon season — expect daily downpours, 309mm of rain, and 92% humidity that'll have your sunglasses fogging up the moment you step outside. The upside? Crowds thin out to low-season levels, the rice terraces around Ubud are at their most electric green, and you can snag villa deals that would make July visitors weep. Sea temps sit at a balmy 28°C, though jellyfish are present and visibility takes a hit, so divers may want to stick to calmer sites. Dengue-carrying mosquitoes are active, so pack repellent and long sleeves for dusk. This is prime time for temple-hopping, Balinese cooking classes, and working your way through plates of Nasi Goreng without the summer crowds elbowing in.",
    2: "February is still firmly monsoon territory with 282mm of rain, but the showers tend to be shorter and more theatrical than January's — think dramatic afternoon cloudbursts followed by golden light. Crowds remain refreshingly low (busyness 3/5), and the warmth never dips below 20°C, so it's hardly suffering. The sea is 28°C and calm enough for snorkeling off Amed, though jellyfish linger and dive visibility stays modest. Dengue season continues, so keep that repellent handy. If you don't mind planning around the rain, February rewards you with lush jungle hikes, empty beach clubs in Seminyak, and satay vendors who actually have time to chat.",
    3: "March is the monsoon's grand finale — and it goes out swinging with 315mm of rain, the wettest month on the calendar. Humidity hovers around 91%, but sunshine hours actually start climbing to nearly 9 per day, hinting at the dry season ahead. Nyepi (Balinese New Year) often falls in March, when the entire island goes silent for 24 hours — no lights, no travel, no noise — and it's genuinely one of the most extraordinary cultural experiences in Southeast Asia. The sea warms to 28°C, crowds stay low, and the jungle canopy is impossibly dense and green. Just respect the jellyfish warnings and keep those mosquito defenses up through the month.",
    4: "April marks the glorious pivot — monsoon retreats, rainfall nearly halves to 198mm, and sunshine pushes past 9 hours a day. This is shoulder season done right: crowds tick up slightly (4/5) but the island hasn't hit full tourist throttle yet. The sea hits a gorgeous 29°C with improving visibility, making it a sweet spot for divers and freedivers heading to Nusa Penida or Tulamben. Jellyfish season wraps up and dengue risk finally drops, so you can bare those ankles without anxiety. The rice paddies are lush and actively being planted — grab a Rendang at a warung in Sidemen and watch the farmers work the terraces below.",
    5: "May is Bali's quiet overachiever — 10+ hours of sunshine, only 151mm of rain, and sea temps peaking at a bathtub-warm 29.5°C, the highest all year. Crowds are moderate and the vibe shifts: Uluwatu's swells start building for surf season, and underwater visibility sharpens beautifully for diving around Menjangan Island. The rice paddies are growing tall and vivid green, humidity is manageable, and you're paying shoulder-season prices for what feels like peak-season weather. Indonesian cuisine shines year-round, but there's something about eating fresh Klepon on a quiet Canggu porch with 10 hours of daylight that just hits different. Arguably Bali's best-kept-secret month.",
    6: "June ushers in the dry season proper — 136mm of rain, over 10 hours of daily sunshine, and that perfect 29°C sea temperature that makes every beach day feel earned. Temps cool slightly to a pleasant 21°C average, meaning nights on the Ubud ridgeline are actually comfortable without AC. Surf season is in full swing at Uluwatu and Padang Padang, with consistent swells and offshore winds. Crowds build to 4/5 as European summer holidays begin, so book your Seminyak beach club daybed in advance. The rice paddies are tall and luminous, dive conditions are excellent around Nusa Lembongan, and this is arguably when Bali's food scene peaks — night markets buzz and every warung is firing on all cylinders.",
    7: "Peak season hits hard — July is Bali at its busiest (5/5) with sun-chasing tourists from every hemisphere claiming their patch of sand. But they're not wrong to come: only 123mm of rain (the driest month), over 10 hours of sunshine, and those cool 20°C nights that make sleeping blissful. Uluwatu delivers world-class surf, Amed and Tulamben offer crystal visibility for divers, and the Kecak fire dance at sunset is pure magic. The catch? Prices spike, Seminyak traffic becomes a contact sport, and you'll need reservations everywhere. Pro tip: escape to Sidemen or the northern coast for that quieter Bali the Instagram accounts promise. Rice paddies are browning now (harvest season), so temper your terrace photo expectations.",
    8: "August matches July's peak crowds (5/5) and keeps the dry-season party going — 136mm of rain, 10+ hours of sun, and comfortable 20°C evenings. The rice paddies are in their brown, post-harvest phase through October, so if emerald terraces are your dream shot, recalibrate toward the jungle waterfalls instead. Surf conditions at Uluwatu remain excellent, diving visibility is outstanding, and the sea at 28.5°C stays inviting. Galungan and Kuningan festivals often fall in August, draping every temple and home in bamboo penjor poles — it's breathtaking. Budget for peak pricing and book early, but know that Bali in August, even crowded, still delivers moments that make you forget anyone else is on the island.",
    9: "September is the dry season's graceful exit — sunshine actually peaks at 10.6 hours per day, crowds ease back to 4/5, and you get that golden-hour light that photographers live for. Rain creeps up to 154mm but rarely disrupts plans. Sea temperature rebounds to 28.8°C and diving conditions remain stellar, especially for manta ray encounters off Nusa Penida. The rice paddies are still in their drier phase, but new plantings begin and green slowly returns to the terraces. Surf swells start to mellow, making it friendlier for intermediate surfers. This is smart-traveler Bali: nearly peak-season weather at shoulder-season prices, with shorter queues for everything from Tirta Empul to the best Rendang in Denpasar.",
    10: "October straddles the line — the wet season officially returns with 220mm of rain, but you still get a generous 10.3 hours of sunshine and the sea stays at 29°C. Crowds drop to low-season levels (3/5), prices soften, and the rice terraces begin their transformation back to vivid green as new plantings take hold. The first monsoon showers are usually manageable afternoon affairs, nothing like the January deluges. Jellyfish start appearing and mosquito season kicks in, so pack accordingly. This is an underrated month for food-focused travel — hit the warungs in Gianyar market, take a cooking class in Ubud, and enjoy having Bali's temples largely to yourself.",
    11: "November means business — 293mm of rain, jellyfish in the water, dengue mosquitoes at dusk, and that thick 92% humidity that makes everything feel slightly tropical-apocalyptic. But here's the thing: the island is stunningly lush, the rice paddies glow neon green, and crowds are at their lowest. Sea temps hold at a warm 29°C, and between downpours you'll get nearly 9.5 hours of sunshine — the rain comes in dramatic bursts, not all-day grey. Diving visibility drops but snorkeling off the calmer northern coast stays decent. If you're the type who packs a rain jacket and rolls with it, November rewards you with rock-bottom prices, empty Uluwatu clifftops, and the full force of Bali's jungle beauty.",
    12: "December brings the heaviest rainfall of the year at 322mm and the return of holiday crowds (busyness 4/5) — it's a peculiar combination of monsoon and peak pricing that only the Christmas-NYE rush can produce. The upside is 29°C days, the rice terraces at maximum green intensity, and a festive energy as Seminyak and Canggu dress up for the holidays. Jellyfish and dengue mosquitoes are in full effect, so ocean time requires caution and evenings demand repellent. Surfing shifts to the eastern breaks, and divers should manage visibility expectations. The island's Hindu-Balinese culture carries on beautifully beneath the tourist buzz — catch an offering ceremony at a sea temple between rain showers and you'll remember why everyone keeps coming back.",
  },

  'jp-kyoto-kansai': {
    1: "Kyoto in January is quiet, cold, and absolutely magical — think frost-dusted zen gardens, steaming bowls of ramen, and temples blanketed in occasional snow, all with highs around 8°C and almost no crowds. Hatsumode (New Year shrine visits) fill Fushimi Inari with lantern light in early January, and the crisp air makes hiking the bamboo groves of Arashiyama a refreshing experience. Warm up with matcha and mochi in a traditional tea house — you've earned it after braving temperatures that can dip below freezing. This is insider-season Kyoto: the beauty without the battle for elbow room.",
    2: "February keeps Kyoto chilly (hovering around 4-5°C average) and blissfully uncrowded, making it perfect for contemplative temple-hopping without the selfie-stick obstacle course. Early plum blossoms begin appearing at Kitano Tenmangu shrine, hinting at the floral explosion to come. The food scene is at its winter peak — think rich, warming kaiseki courses and the best seasonal sushi. Pack layers and a good scarf, but know that the low rainfall and increasing sunshine make this a surprisingly pleasant month to explore. You'll feel like you have the ancient capital almost to yourself.",
    3: "Spring stirs in Kyoto as temperatures climb to a pleasant 14-15°C and the first cherry blossoms start budding in late March — the anticipation is electric. Crowds begin building (busyness 4/5) as word spreads that sakura season is imminent, so book accommodation well in advance. The Higashiyama Hanatoro illumination lights up temple paths and bamboo groves with thousands of lanterns, and the hiking trails through the eastern mountains come alive with early wildflowers. Rain picks up noticeably this month, so an umbrella is non-negotiable. Come for the blossoms, stay for the tempura and the sense that something spectacular is about to happen.",
    4: "April is peak Kyoto — cherry blossoms explode across every temple garden, canal, and mountainside, and the entire city transforms into a pink-and-white dreamscape around 18°C. But let's be honest: everyone else had the same idea, and busyness hits maximum (5/5), so expect shoulder-to-shoulder crowds along the Philosopher's Path and in Maruyama Park. Hanami picnics under the sakura are a must, and seasonal cherry blossom mochi appears in every sweet shop. Rain is significant at 163mm, so waterproof layers are essential between the photo ops. Worth every elbow? Absolutely — just book six months ahead and embrace the beautiful chaos.",
    5: "May brings Kyoto's sweet spot: warm days around 23°C, lush green bamboo groves, and the post-cherry-blossom crowd thinning that lets you actually enjoy the temples. The Aoi Matsuri festival (May 15) features an ancient imperial procession through the city that's one of Kyoto's three great festivals — genuinely spectacular. Fresh green tea season means the matcha is at its most vibrant, and the hiking in the surrounding mountains is superb with new foliage everywhere. Rainfall is notable at 183mm so afternoons can be showery, but mornings tend to be glorious. This is arguably the most underrated month to visit Kyoto.",
    6: "June marks the arrival of tsuyu (rainy season) and Kyoto gets properly wet — 228mm of rain and 78% humidity mean you'll want breathable clothing and a sturdy umbrella. But here's the secret: rain-slicked temple stones, misty bamboo forests, and hydrangeas blooming at their peak make this one of the most photogenic months of the year. Crowds drop to low (3/5) because most tourists flee the rain, leaving you with atmospheric temples and no queues for kaiseki restaurants. Temperatures are warm and pleasant around 22°C when the sun peeks through. If you don't mind getting a little damp, June Kyoto rewards you with a moody, intimate beauty that fair-weather visitors never see.",
    7: "July in Kyoto is hot, humid, and absolutely alive — temperatures push toward 30°C with 82% humidity and the heaviest rainfall of the year at 324mm, but the legendary Gion Matsuri festival (all month, climaxing July 17) makes it all worthwhile. Massive wooden floats parade through the streets, Gion fills with festival food stalls, and the energy is infectious. Beat the heat with kakigori (shaved ice), chilled soba noodles, and evening strolls along the Kamogawa river where restaurants set up kawadoko riverside dining platforms. The mountains surrounding Kyoto turn an impossibly deep green, and Japanese macaques are active in the highlands. Come prepared to sweat — and to be completely enchanted.",
    8: "August is Kyoto at its most intense: peak summer heat hits 32°C with persistent humidity, but the cultural calendar more than compensates. The Gozan no Okuribi (Daimonji) fire festival on August 16 lights massive bonfires on five surrounding mountains — it's breathtaking and deeply spiritual. Obon season brings traditional bon odori dancing and a contemplative atmosphere as families honor ancestors. Early mornings at the temples before the heat sets in are genuinely transcendent, and the nearly 10 hours of daily sunshine make everything glow gold. Hydrate aggressively, seek shade at bamboo groves, and let the evening festivals carry you through.",
    9: "September eases Kyoto out of summer — temperatures drop to a comfortable 24°C average and the crowds thin to low season (3/5), giving you breathing room at Kinkaku-ji and Fushimi Inari. The lingering warmth keeps outdoor dining pleasant, and this is prime season for seasonal kaiseki featuring matsutake mushrooms and early autumn ingredients. Rainfall is moderate and typhoon season can occasionally disrupt plans, so keep an eye on forecasts. The first hints of color appear on the Japanese maples by month's end, building anticipation for autumn. A genuinely smart time to visit — good weather, manageable crowds, and the food scene shifting into its richest gear.",
    10: "October is when Kyoto starts showing off again — temperatures settle around a perfect 17-22°C and the Japanese maples begin their slow burn from green to gold to crimson. Crowds pick up (4/5) as autumn-leaf chasers arrive, but it's not yet at November's fever pitch. The Jidai Matsuri (Festival of Ages) on October 22 is a stunning historical costume parade through the city center. Hiking in the Higashiyama hills is superb with cool air and developing fall color, and the food scene features autumn specialties like chestnut sweets and persimmon. If November scares you with its crowds, October gives you 80% of the autumn beauty at 80% of the madness.",
    11: "November is Kyoto's other showstopper — the autumn leaves reach their peak and every temple garden becomes a composition in scarlet, amber, and gold that honestly makes you gasp. Busyness maxes out at 5/5 again (yes, the same as cherry blossom season) as the world descends on Tofuku-ji and Eikan-do for koyo viewing. Temperatures are crisp and pleasant (7-17°C) with low rainfall, making it excellent hiking and temple-wandering weather. Evening illuminations at Kiyomizu-dera and the bamboo grove are absolutely unmissable. The crowds are real, the hotel prices are steep, but seeing those maples reflected in a temple pond at golden hour — there's simply nothing else like it.",
    12: "December wraps Kyoto in winter stillness — crowds vanish (3/5), temperatures hover around 5-11°C, and the bare branches of the Japanese maples reveal temple architecture you couldn't see behind the foliage. Year-end traditions bring special temple ceremonies and the Kaomise kabuki performances in Gion, giving you a taste of old Japan at its most ceremonial. The food scene pivots to warming comfort: hot pot, thick udon, and seasonal wagashi sweets paired with matcha. Occasional dustings of snow on Kinkaku-ji's golden pavilion create one of Japan's most iconic photographs. It's cold, it's quiet, and it's deeply rewarding for travelers who prefer atmosphere over spectacle.",
  },

  'pt-lisbon': {
    1: "Lisbon in January is the city at its quietest — think empty miradouros, no queues at Belém Tower, and pastéis de nata still warm from the oven without the fight. Highs hover around 15°C with frequent rain showers (95mm worth), so pack layers and an umbrella, but you'll still catch crisp sunny spells between the grey. The Atlantic sits at a bracing 15°C — surfing at Ericeira is for wetsuit warriors only. Fado sounds better in the rain anyway, and with budget-friendly prices and almost no crowds, you get the real Alfama experience minus the selfie sticks.",
    2: "February brings the first whispers of spring to Lisbon's seven hills, with temps creeping up to 16°C and slightly less rain than January. Carnival hits the streets mid-month — expect parades, sardine costumes, and a general disregard for Monday productivity. The Atlantic remains a chilly 14°C (its coldest), so beach days are strictly for looking, not swimming. Crowds are still blissfully thin, restaurant reservations are easy, and a steaming bowl of caldo verde after climbing those hills feels earned. This is one of Europe's best-value city breaks if you don't mind a jacket.",
    3: "March is when Lisbon starts to shake off winter — rainfall drops to 50mm, sunshine climbs to seven hours a day, and the bougainvillea begins plotting its colourful takeover. Highs reach 18°C, perfect for wandering Alfama's azulejo-lined streets or taking that tram 28 ride without being sardine-packed. The sea is still cool at 15°C, but Ericeira's swells are excellent for surfers who own decent neoprene. Tourist numbers tick up to moderate, so you're sharing Sintra with some company but nothing painful. A sweet spot for those who like pleasant weather without peak-season prices.",
    4: "April is arguably Lisbon's best-kept secret — 20°C highs, eight hours of sunshine, and spring wildflowers carpeting the hills around Sintra. The rain hasn't fully retreated (55mm), so you'll still dodge the odd shower, but the city's energy shifts from cosy to electric. Outdoor terraces fill up, the Atlantic warms to a still-brisk 16°C, and the surf scene at Ericeira starts buzzing. Crowds are building but manageable, and every bakery is competing for your pastel de nata loyalty. Pair a day trip to Cascais with bacalhau by the water and you'll wonder why anyone comes in August.",
    5: "May delivers the Lisbon dream: 23°C highs, ten hours of sunshine, and rain that's mostly packed its bags at just 40mm. The city is alive — rooftop bars open, sardine season kicks off, and the scent of grilled fish drifts through every bairro. Atlantic waters reach 17°C, tolerable for a quick plunge and increasingly fun for surfers chasing Ericeira's consistent breaks. Crowds are moderate-to-busy but the queues haven't hit full absurdity yet, making this prime time for Belém Tower and Jerónimos Monastery. Honestly, if you can only pick one month, May is the cheat code.",
    6: "June is when Lisbon throws its biggest party — the Santos Populares festivals turn the city into a whirlwind of grilled sardines, cheap wine, and dancing in streets draped with paper decorations. Highs hit 27°C under eleven hours of blazing sunshine, and rain essentially stops (10mm for the whole month). The Atlantic warms to 19°C — refreshing rather than punishing — and the surf is reliable. Fair warning: this is peak season, so Alfama's streets are shoulder-to-shoulder and booking ahead is non-negotiable. But biting into a sardine at a Santo António street party on June 12th? Worth every elbowed queue.",
    7: "July is Lisbon at full throttle — 30°C highs, twelve hours of relentless sunshine, and almost zero rain. The city is packed (peak busyness), prices are at their highest, and tram 28 is basically a mobile sauna of tourists. But the energy is undeniable: beach days in Cascais, surf sessions at Ericeira, and the Atlantic finally hits a swimmable 20°C (by Portuguese standards, that's practically tropical). Evening brings relief as Atlantic breezes sweep through outdoor fado shows and rooftop cocktail bars. Come for the buzz, but book everything months ahead and hydrate aggressively on those seven hills.",
    8: "August delivers more of July's scorching formula — 30°C highs, twelve hours of sun, and crowds that turn Belém into a theme park. Here's the twist: many Lisboetas flee the city for their own holidays, so you'll find some local spots oddly quiet while tourist magnets overflow. The Atlantic holds at 20°C, making beach escapes to Cascais and Costa da Caparica essential survival tactics. Surf conditions at Ericeira remain solid, and outdoor dining is glorious if you snag a terrace with a breeze. Budget-wise this is the priciest month, but a late-evening pastel de nata run through a warm, empty side street is priceless.",
    9: "September is the savvy traveller's July — still 27°C and sunny (nine hours), but the hordes thin out noticeably and prices soften. The Atlantic clings to its summer peak of 20°C, making this genuinely the best month for beach time and surf without the August madness. A bit of rain returns (25mm), usually in quick afternoon bursts that just cool things down. The wine harvest is underway in nearby regions, so day-trip to a vineyard and pair a glass of port with some bacalhau. If you want Lisbon's summer without Lisbon's summer crowds, September is your answer.",
    10: "October is Lisbon's moody-beautiful transition — still a pleasant 22°C but the rain returns in earnest (75mm), painting the azulejo tiles in that glossy, photogenic sheen. Crowds drop to moderate levels, and the Atlantic stays surprisingly warm at 19°C, offering a last gasp of beach-viable conditions. This is prime food season: chestnuts roasting on street corners, hearty caldo verde, and francesinha cravings finally making sense in the cooler air. Sintra in autumn fog is genuinely magical, and surfers at Ericeira catch increasingly powerful swells. Pack a rain jacket and an appetite — October rewards both.",
    11: "November is when Lisbon gets honest about being an Atlantic city — 95mm of rain, 78% humidity, and highs of just 18°C. But here's what you gain: rock-bottom prices, virtually no queues, and the cosy, fado-soaked atmosphere that made Alfama famous. The sea cools to 17°C (surfers in thick wetsuits only), and those five hours of sunshine between rain spells are genuinely gorgeous. This is the month for slow mornings in tiled cafés, custard tarts without the Instagram queue at Pastéis de Belém, and meaningful eye contact with your server. Lisbon's melancholy season has its own quiet magic.",
    12: "December in Lisbon is surprisingly festive — think twinkling lights draped across the Baixa, Christmas markets, and 100mm of rain that keeps things atmospheric (read: wet). Highs sit around 15°C, which by northern European standards is practically mild, and five hours of winter sunshine still light up those famous seven hills. The Atlantic drops to 16°C, firmly in the 'admire from a distance' category, though hardy surfers still hit Ericeira. Crowds are low-to-moderate, spiking around Christmas and New Year's Eve when the Praça do Comércio fireworks draw big numbers. A glass of port wine, a warm pastel de nata, and fado echoing through rain-slicked streets — December does cosy Lisbon better than you'd expect.",
  },

  'tz-serengeti': {
    1: "The southern plains around Ndutu are teeming with wildebeest preparing to calve, and predators know it — expect lions, cheetahs, and hyenas in peak hunting mode. Daytime highs reach 28°C with manageable humidity around 64%, though afternoon showers can roll in (82mm for the month). It's a busy period and lodges book fast, so plan ahead and budget for peak-adjacent pricing. Malaria risk is real year-round here — prophylaxis and long sleeves at dusk are non-negotiable.",
    2: "This is the month. The Great Calving unfolds across the Ndutu short-grass plains: hundreds of thousands of wildebeest drop their young in a frantic two-week window, and every predator on the savanna shows up for the feast. The landscape is lush green, temps hover around 22°C, and the 74mm of rain keeps things dramatic with moody skies perfect for photography. Crowds match the spectacle (busyness: 4/5), so expect premium rates and book your safari vehicle early. Bring your longest lens and your malaria tablets.",
    3: "The herds are still on the southern plains but beginning to stir northward as the calving season winds down. Green savanna stretches endlessly under partly cloudy skies, and temps push toward 29°C — warm but not oppressive. Crowds thin slightly compared to February, and you may find better lodge availability and softer pricing. The rains pick up a touch (82mm), making some tracks muddy, but that golden hour light through scattered clouds is worth every bump. Don't skip the antimalarials.",
    4: "Welcome to the long rains — 129mm of them, to be specific. The herds begin their push west and the savanna turns an almost absurd shade of green, but many tracks become challenging and some camps close entirely. Visitor numbers drop to quiet levels, which means those who brave the mud get the plains practically to themselves and significantly lower rates. Temperatures stay mild around 22°C but humidity climbs to 69%, and the tall grass makes spotting smaller predators trickier. Pack waterproof everything and take your malaria prevention seriously.",
    5: "The tail end of the long rains brings relief — rainfall drops to just 42mm and the savanna starts drying at the edges, though the Western Corridor is greening up as the migration pushes that way. This is one of the quietest months (busyness: 2/5), so budget-savvy travelers take note: lodges are negotiable and vehicles are uncrowded. Afternoon temps around 28°C feel pleasant in the drying air. The birdlife is outstanding right now with resident and migratory species overlapping, and the Big Five are present as always. Malaria meds remain essential through the transition.",
    6: "Dry season clicks on and the Serengeti transforms: just 15mm of rain, humidity dropping to 53%, and that famous tawny-gold savanna asserting itself against the last green patches. The migration hits the Western Corridor and the first Grumeti River crossings begin — crocodiles stake out their positions and the drama is astonishing. Lodges fill back up (busyness: 4/5) and rates climb accordingly, but the clear skies and reliable game viewing justify every shilling. Morning game drives start cool at 16°C, so layer up for the pre-dawn starts.",
    7: "Peak season in full force — the driest month of the year at barely 4mm of rain, with golden plains, enormous skies, and virtually guaranteed Big Five sightings. The herds are moving through the Western Corridor toward the northern reaches, and the Grumeti crossings are in full swing. Expect maximum crowds (5/5), premium pricing, and the need to book six-plus months out for the best camps. Humidity is a comfortable 47% and highs reach 28°C, making this one of the most pleasant months weather-wise. Balloon rides at dawn over the migration columns are unforgettable — if you can stomach the price tag.",
    8: "The main event: herds stream into the northern Serengeti and the legendary Mara River crossings begin — thousands of wildebeest hurling themselves into crocodile-infested waters in a spectacle that's as harrowing as it is mesmerizing. At 10mm of rain and 46% humidity, conditions are bone-dry and the bush is thin, meaning wildlife has nowhere to hide. This is absolute peak season (5/5) with prices to match; a night in a prime northern camp can easily top $400 per person. Temps reach 29°C by midday but mornings dip to 16°C, so that fleece earns its luggage space.",
    9: "Still peak season and the Mara River crossings continue — arguably the best month for catching one, as the herds mill back and forth across the northern plains. The savanna is at its most stripped-back: dry, open, excellent visibility, with afternoon temps hitting 30°C and humidity still mercifully low at 49%. Crowds remain at maximum (5/5) and top-tier lodges are sold out months in advance, but the sheer density of wildlife makes this feel like the nature documentary you always wanted to walk into. Short rains begin teasing at month's end (25mm), signaling the herds to start thinking south.",
    10: "The herds begin their long trek south through the eastern Serengeti, spreading across vast open landscapes that are starting to show early hints of green as rains return (42mm). Temperatures are the warmest of the year at nearly 24°C average, and the wind picks up noticeably to 16 km/h, keeping things from feeling stuffy. Crowds ease from peak to busy (4/5), offering a slightly more relaxed atmosphere while the wildlife remains abundant and visible in the thinning bush. It's a strategic sweet spot: better availability than the peak months, but before the heavy rains arrive. Malaria prophylaxis remains a must as standing water increases.",
    11: "The short rains arrive in earnest — 145mm worth, the wettest month of the year — and the Serengeti erupts back into brilliant green. The migration is pushing south through the central and eastern plains, and the dramatic storm-lit skies make for extraordinary landscape photography between downpours. Crowds drop to moderate (3/5) and rates soften noticeably, making this a smart choice for those who don't mind afternoon showers and occasional muddy tracks. Newborn gazelles dot the plains and resident predators are active, though the tall grass requires a patient eye. Malaria risk ticks up with the rains — take your tablets religiously.",
    12: "The herds are arriving back onto the southern short-grass plains, completing the great circle, and the Ndutu area begins its annual transformation into a wildlife nursery. Rains are heavy (122mm) and humidity sits around 69%, but the storms tend to be dramatic afternoon affairs that clear to golden evenings. Moderate crowds (3/5) and gentler pricing make December a savvy alternative to the January-February rush, especially if you catch the early concentrations of wildebeest before the peak calving chaos. The landscape is strikingly green against the grey kopjes, and birdlife is at a yearly high. Layer on the insect repellent alongside your sunscreen — the mosquitoes are as enthusiastic about the rains as the wildebeest are.",
  },

  'gr-cyclades': {
    1: "January in the Cyclades is for the brave and the curious — temperatures hover around 12°C, the sea is a bracing 15°C, and winds regularly top 27 km/h, so forget beach lounging. Most tavernas and hotels on smaller islands are shuttered, though Santorini and Naxos keep a skeletal pulse going with a handful of open spots and rock-bottom prices. You'll have those iconic caldera views and whitewashed lanes entirely to yourself, which is either hauntingly beautiful or hauntingly lonely depending on your temperament.",
    2: "February is still deep off-season with temperatures barely nudging 12°C and that Aegean wind refusing to let up at nearly 28 km/h. Rain eases a bit compared to January, and you'll get more sunshine hours, but the sea at 14.5°C is strictly for polar-bear types. The upside: Carnival season (Apokries) brings unexpected life to Naxos and Tinos with parades and local celebrations, and accommodation prices remain at their absolute lowest — think half or less of summer rates.",
    3: "March starts whispering about spring — highs reach 15°C, wildflowers begin dotting the hillsides, and the light turns that particular Cycladic gold photographers chase. The sea is still too cold for swimming at 14.5°C and ferries run reduced schedules, but hiking is glorious, especially on Naxos and Amorgos. Most tourist infrastructure remains closed on the smaller islands, though early-bird restaurants start opening on Santorini and Mykonos toward month's end.",
    4: "April is when the Cyclades start to wake up — temperatures climb to a pleasant 18°C, Orthodox Easter often falls here and transforms the islands with candlelit processions and spit-roasted lamb on every corner. The sea at 16°C is still nippy but swimmable for the determined, and ferry routes ramp up significantly. Restaurants and hotels are opening their doors, prices are still very reasonable, and you can visit Santorini's Oia without being shoulder-to-shoulder with strangers — a genuine luxury.",
    5: "May is arguably the sweet spot for the Cyclades: 23°C days, 12+ hours of sunshine, minimal rain, and the sea warming to a dippable 19°C. Everything is open and running, the wildflowers are still blooming, and the meltemi winds haven't yet arrived, making island-hopping by ferry smooth and reliable. Crowds are noticeable but nowhere near suffocating — you can still snag a good table without a reservation on most islands, and prices sit comfortably below peak-season madness.",
    6: "June brings proper summer heat with highs near 27°C, virtually no rain, and the sea reaching a lovely 22.5°C — this is when the Cyclades look exactly like the postcards. All islands are fully operational with daily ferry connections, beach bars are pumping, and the early meltemi winds start picking up mid-month, keeping things breezy but occasionally choppy. It's busy and prices are climbing, but you still get more breathing room than the July–August crush, making it the pragmatist's choice for peak experience without peak chaos.",
    7: "Peak season hits hard: 29°C highs, zero rain, 13 hours of blazing sunshine, and the sea a blissful 25°C — it's undeniably gorgeous but you'll share it with everyone. The meltemi winds blow fierce at 26+ km/h, which is a blessing for cooling down but a curse for ferry schedules and beach umbrellas. Mykonos and Santorini command eye-watering prices, restaurant reservations become essential, and the smaller islands like Folegandros and Koufonisia fill up fast too. Come prepared to pay, to queue, and to be dazzled.",
    8: "August is July's twin but somehow even more intense — it's the month all of Greece takes vacation, so domestic tourists flood in alongside international visitors. Temperatures peak around 30°C, the sea hits its warmest at 26°C, and the meltemi winds remain strong enough to strand you on an island for an extra day (not always a bad thing). The Feast of the Assumption on August 15th is a major celebration island-wide with fireworks and packed ferries. Budget generously, book everything months ahead, and embrace the beautiful mayhem.",
    9: "September is the insider's month — the crowds thin noticeably after the first week, temperatures still hit a gorgeous 27°C, and the sea remains at a bathwater-warm 25°C. The meltemi winds calm down, making ferry crossings smooth and beach days peaceful. Prices start dropping, tables open up at those impossible-to-book cliffside restaurants, and the light turns softer and more photogenic. Nearly everything is still open, making this the month where you get 90% of the summer experience at 60% of the hassle.",
    10: "October is a gamble that usually pays off: you'll still see 23°C days and the sea holds at a swimmable 22°C, but rain starts creeping in and some businesses begin their winter shutdown after mid-month. Early October on Naxos, Paros, or Milos feels like a private paradise — warm enough for the beach, quiet enough for long hikes, and cheap enough to splurge on a nicer hotel. Ferry schedules start thinning toward month's end, so plan your island-hopping for the first three weeks.",
    11: "November signals the Cyclades pulling up the drawbridge — temperatures drop to around 18°C, rain returns in earnest with nearly 50mm, and the winds pick back up. Most smaller islands go into hibernation mode with limited accommodation and dining. Santorini, Naxos, and Syros keep some life going year-round, and the upside is genuinely empty archaeological sites, moody seascapes, and prices that'll make you feel like you're getting away with something. Just bring layers and a good book for stormy ferry-day contingencies.",
    12: "December is as quiet as it gets — 15°C days, 65mm of rain, and a 16.5°C sea that nobody is swimming in. The vast majority of tourist businesses are closed, ferry schedules are skeletal, and those postcard-perfect beach clubs are shuttered and eerie. That said, Christmas in a whitewashed Cycladic village has its own magic, particularly on Syros where Ermoupoli's Catholic and Orthodox traditions create a uniquely festive atmosphere. Prices are basement-level and solitude is guaranteed — it's the Cyclades stripped bare, and some travelers find that's exactly what they were looking for.",
  },

  'by-belarus': {
    1: "Minsk in January is proper Eastern European winter — minus 6°C averages, snow blanketing the brutalist architecture, and about six hours of pale daylight. Crowds are nonexistent, making it ideal for exploring the Belarusian State Museum and warming up with draniki (potato pancakes) and a shot of krupnik in a cosy stolovaya. Cross-country skiing in Loshitsky Park is surprisingly lovely if you embrace the cold.",
    2: "February remains bitterly cold at -5°C with reliable snow cover, but the city has a quiet resilience that grows on you. Maslenitsa (pancake week) brings blini stalls, folk music, and bonfires to city parks — a genuine slice of Slavic winter culture. The Minsk Opera and Ballet is world-class and practically empty, and hotel rates are about as low as they get anywhere in Europe.",
    3: "March is the slow thaw — temps climb to 1°C and the snowmelt turns streets slushy but the days stretch noticeably past 11 hours. It's still firmly off-season with minimal tourists, and the art galleries along Independence Avenue are peaceful and rewarding. The first hints of spring bring locals out to Gorky Park, and a bowl of borscht has never tasted better than after a crisp afternoon walk along the Svislach River.",
    4: "April finally breaks winter's grip with highs around 12°C, budding trees lining the boulevards, and that first real warmth in the air. The parks come alive — Chelyuskintsev Park is especially pretty with early blossoms — and outdoor cafes cautiously open their terraces. Tourist numbers remain very low, meaning you can explore Mir Castle and Nesvizh Palace on day trips with barely another visitor in sight.",
    5: "May is genuinely lovely in Belarus — 19°C, long sunny days, and the countryside exploding into green around the Belovezhskaya Pushcha forest, where European bison roam. Victory Day (May 9) is a major event with parades and deeply felt commemorations in Minsk. The food markets overflow with fresh produce, and cycling along the Svislach becomes a real pleasure. Shoulder-season pricing with near-summer weather makes this an underrated window.",
    6: "June delivers warm 22°C days, 17 hours of daylight, and Belarusian nature at its most lush. Kupalle (midsummer night) celebrations feature bonfires, flower wreaths, and folk rituals in the countryside — utterly enchanting. The national parks are prime for hiking and birdwatching, and Minsk's restaurant terraces buzz with life. Moderate tourist numbers keep things relaxed without feeling deserted.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 24°C highs, occasional thunderstorms, and the Belarusian lakes warm enough for swimming. Braslaw Lakes National Park is a hidden gem for kayaking and wild camping, and the Slavianski Bazaar festival in Vitebsk draws music lovers from across Eastern Europe. Crowds are at their modest peak but nothing overwhelming; this isn't exactly a tourist hotspot, which is precisely the appeal.",
    8: "August holds summer's warmth at 23°C with the longest dry spells of the year. The countryside is golden and ripe — berry picking in the forests is a genuine local pastime, and the mushroom foraging season begins. Minsk's parks host open-air concerts and cinema, and day trips to the Augustow Canal or the eerie beauty of the Chernobyl exclusion zone border area are most accessible now. Still uncrowded and refreshingly affordable.",
    9: "September brings a gorgeous autumn transition — 16°C, golden birch forests, and that crisp clarity in the air. The crowds (such as they were) dissipate entirely, and Belovezhskaya Pushcha is stunning with fall colors and active wildlife. Harvest festivals pop up in rural towns with local honey, apples, and homemade spirits. Minsk's cultural season kicks off with theater and gallery openings. A genuinely rewarding month for those who like their travel quiet.",
    10: "October gets properly autumnal — 8°C highs, the forests ablaze in amber and crimson, and the first grey drizzly days settling in. This is ideal for museum-hopping in Minsk and exploring the sobering history at the Khatyn Memorial and the Museum of the Great Patriotic War. Warm up with machanka (pork stew with pancakes) and cheap local beer. Daylight shrinks noticeably, so front-load your outdoor plans.",
    11: "November is grey, cold (2°C average), and raw — the trees are bare, the first snow flurries appear, and daylight dips below eight hours. It's unquestionably low season, but the city's indoor culture shines: excellent ballet, hearty Belarusian comfort food, and the kind of atmospheric moodiness that suits reflective travel. Prices are rock-bottom and you'll have every castle and gallery to yourself.",
    12: "December transforms Minsk with Christmas markets, twinkling lights along Independence Avenue, and proper snow cover at -3°C. New Year's Eve is the bigger celebration here (Orthodox Christmas is January 7), and the festive atmosphere is genuine and unpretentious. Ice skating at the outdoor rinks, warming up with glintwein, and watching snow fall over the National Library's diamond-shaped silhouette — winter done right, at a fraction of Western European prices.",
  },

  'bz-belize': {
    1: "January is prime Belize — dry season in full swing with 27°C highs, minimal rain, and the Caribbean at a gorgeous 27°C. The Barrier Reef is crystal-clear for diving and snorkeling, and the inland jungle is accessible without the mud. It's peak tourist season so Ambergris Caye and Caye Caulker book up fast, but the crowds are modest by Caribbean standards. Howler monkeys are vocal in the morning mist at Lamanai — bring binoculars and reef-safe sunscreen.",
    2: "February keeps the dry-season magic going — warm, sunny, and perfect for the Blue Hole dive or a lazy catamaran day around the cayes. Carnival hits Belize City and San Pedro mid-month with colorful parades and punta music. The reef visibility is at its annual best, making this arguably the top month for underwater adventures. Prices are at their peak but Belize's laid-back vibe means 'crowded' still feels manageable.",
    3: "March is the driest month — barely any rain, 29°C highs, and that Caribbean blue that defies photography. Spring breakers bump up the crowds on the cayes but the mainland stays relaxed, and Caracol and Xunantunich ruins are blissfully uncrowded. The season for whale sharks begins building off Gladden Spit. Prices remain high but the weather is essentially flawless, so every dollar feels justified.",
    4: "April straddles dry and wet seasons — temps push to 30°C, humidity creeps up, and the odd afternoon shower hints at what's coming. Easter brings Belizeans to the coast and things get lively in a local-festival way. The diving remains excellent, whale shark encounters peak at Gladden Spit around the full moon, and the jungle rivers are perfect for tubing near Caves Branch. Shoulder-season pricing starts appearing at mainland lodges.",
    5: "May officially kicks off the wet season but it's a gentle start — short afternoon downpours followed by sunshine, with temps around 30°C. Tourist numbers drop noticeably, prices soften across the board, and the jungle turns impossibly lush and green. The lobster season opens June 15 so anticipation builds, and diving visibility remains decent between rain events. Birdwatching in the Mountain Pine Ridge is outstanding as migratory species linger.",
    6: "June brings heavier rain (200mm+) and thick humidity, but mornings are typically gorgeous and the reef doesn't care about rain. Lobster season opens mid-month and every beach shack celebrates with lobster fests — San Pedro's is legendary. Crowds are thin and rates are at their lowest, making this a budget-traveler's window for the Barrier Reef. The inland rivers swell nicely for kayaking, and the rainforest canopy is at its densest and most alive.",
    7: "July is wet season with regular afternoon deluges, but the rain is warm and dramatic rather than miserable, and mornings deliver reliable sunshine. Hurricane season is technically active though July storms are rare for Belize. The country feels authentically local with few tourists — perfect for connecting with Garifuna culture in Dangriga or exploring Mayan villages near San Ignacio. Prices are low, the jungle hums with life, and fresh lobster is everywhere.",
    8: "August is the heart of wet season — expect 180mm+ of rain, high humidity, and seriously green jungle. The upside: this is the cheapest month to visit, and the marine life is thriving with manta rays and sea turtles nesting on the southern cayes. The Costa Maya Festival in San Pedro celebrates mestizo culture with music and dancing. Keep an eye on tropical weather forecasts, but don't let the rain scare you off entirely — it usually clears by noon.",
    9: "September is statistically the highest hurricane risk month, so travel insurance is non-negotiable. Rain is heavy, some roads wash out inland, and a few dive shops reduce operations. But if the weather cooperates, you'll find rock-bottom prices, empty beaches, and some of the most dramatic skies you'll ever photograph. The Battle of St. George's Caye celebrations on September 10 bring patriotic energy to Belize City. Only for the flexible and adventurous.",
    10: "October remains wet and hurricane-aware, but the rain starts easing in the second half. The jungle rivers are swollen and perfect for cave tubing, and the Barrier Reef is less visited than at any other time. Manatee sightings increase in the southern lagoons as waters cool slightly. Prices are still very low and the few travelers who venture here get a raw, uncurated Belize experience. Pan American Day on October 12 is celebrated with local flair.",
    11: "November marks the transition back to dry season — rain drops off sharply in the second half, temps settle around 27°C, and the reef visibility improves week by week. Garifuna Settlement Day (November 19) is a major cultural celebration in Dangriga and Punta Gorda with drumming, dancing, and storytelling — one of Belize's most authentic festivals. Tourist numbers begin creeping back up and prices tick higher, but availability is still easy.",
    12: "December brings the return of prime conditions — dry sunny days, 27°C warmth, and the Caribbean sparkling clear. Holiday crowds arrive for Christmas and New Year's, particularly on Ambergris Caye and Caye Caulker, so book early. The reef is in superb condition for diving, and the cooler evenings (22°C) make jungle lodges and ruins visits extremely pleasant. It's the beginning of high season and prices reflect it, but Belize's small scale keeps everything feeling intimate rather than overrun.",
  },

  'ca-maritime': {
    1: "January in the Maritimes is Arctic-level commitment — highs barely hit -4°C in Halifax, snow blankets everything, and the North Atlantic churns grey and cold at 2°C. But the seafood is outstanding (lobster season runs on PEI), the craft breweries are cozy refuges, and snowshoeing through Cape Breton Highlands is hauntingly beautiful under leaden skies. Crowds are essentially zero and prices are at their lowest — this is for hardy souls who like their travel with character.",
    2: "February doubles down on winter — expect blizzards, -5°C averages, and enough snow to bury a fence post. Winter Carnival events pop up across Nova Scotia and New Brunswick with ice sculptures and outdoor skating, and the cross-country skiing in Fundy National Park is genuinely world-class. The frozen landscape has a stark beauty, and a bowl of seafood chowder in a Halifax pub after a day in the cold is one of Canada's great pleasures.",
    3: "March is winter's stubborn last stand — still hovering near 0°C with snow on the ground, but the days are stretching and the light is returning. Maple syrup season begins in New Brunswick's sugar bushes, offering cabin visits and pancake breakfasts that are worth the drive. The ocean remains frigid and the trails slushy, but there's a palpable sense of spring approaching. Still very uncrowded with low-season pricing.",
    4: "April is mud season — the snow melts, trails turn to slush, and temps crawl to 7°C. It's not glamorous, but the first migratory birds return to the Bay of Fundy, and the lobster fishing picks up. The shoulder-season prices are excellent and you'll have restaurants and B&Bs practically to yourself. Pack waterproof boots and embrace the rawness — by late April, the first crocuses push through and optimism is in the air.",
    5: "May is when the Maritimes finally exhale — temps reach 13°C, the landscape greens up fast, and whale watching season kicks off in the Bay of Fundy as humpbacks and right whales arrive. Lupins begin carpeting the roadsides of PEI in purple, and the Cabot Trail opens fully after winter closures. Tourist season hasn't started in earnest so you'll find great availability everywhere. Lobster is abundant and affordable at roadside shacks.",
    6: "June is gorgeous — 19°C, long 16-hour days, and the wildflowers peaking across PEI and Cape Breton. The ocean warms to a still-bracing 10°C but kayaking and coastal hiking are superb. Whale watching in the Bay of Fundy is excellent as feeding season intensifies. Crowds begin building but it's early enough to enjoy popular spots like Peggy's Cove without the August crush. The seafood is at its freshest and every harbor village feels picture-perfect.",
    7: "July brings summer proper — 23°C highs, the ocean pushing past 15°C on sheltered PEI beaches, and the lobster suppers that this region is famous for. The Cabot Trail is at its most stunning with full green canopy, and the Celtic Colours warm-up festivals start in Cape Breton. It's peak season with prices to match, and popular spots get genuinely busy, but the Maritimes' scale means you're never far from a quiet cove or empty trail.",
    8: "August is peak Maritime summer — warmest month at 24°C, the ocean at its most swimmable (18°C on PEI's north shore), and blueberry season in full swing. The Halifax Busker Festival and various lobster festivals keep things lively. Crowds max out this month and accommodation on PEI requires advance booking, but the long warm evenings, fresh seafood, and that famous Maritime hospitality make it all worthwhile. Tidal bore rafting on the Shubenacadie is a unique August thrill.",
    9: "September is arguably the Maritimes' best-kept secret — still warm at 19°C, the first fall colors appearing on the highlands, and the summer crowds evaporating after Labour Day. The ocean holds its warmth (16°C) and whale watching remains excellent. Harvest festivals and farmers' markets overflow with apples, squash, and fresh-pressed cider. Prices drop, availability opens up, and the Cabot Trail in early autumn color is genuinely breathtaking.",
    10: "October is peak fall foliage and it's spectacular — the Cape Breton Highlands blaze in crimson and gold, and the Celtic Colours International Festival fills the island with fiddle music and ceilidhs. Temps drop to 11°C and the ocean cools to 12°C, so pack layers. Tourist numbers spike briefly for leaf season but remain manageable. Apple picking, cranberry bogs, and Thanksgiving (second Monday) round out one of the most photogenic months in all of Canada.",
    11: "November is the grey transition — 5°C, frequent rain and the first snow flurries, bare trees, and the North Atlantic getting seriously angry. Most tourist operations wind down and the region gets quiet. But the indoor pleasures are real: Halifax's restaurant scene is underrated, the museums are peaceful, and a stormy day watching waves crash at Peggy's Cove is its own kind of dramatic. Prices plummet and availability is unlimited.",
    12: "December brings full winter — -1°C averages, snow, and short days of about 8 hours. But Maritime Christmas is genuinely magical: Halifax's waterfront lights up, Lunenburg decorates like a Dickens village, and every kitchen is producing holiday seafood chowder and gingerbread. The quiet solitude of a snow-dusted fishing village has a romance that summer can't match. Bundle up, drive the coastal roads slowly, and let the season's stillness settle in.",
  },

  'ca-montreal': {
    1: "Montreal in January is gloriously, brutally cold — minus 10°C averages, snowbanks taller than children, and a wind chill that tests your commitment. But the Underground City keeps millions moving in climate-controlled comfort, Igloofest (outdoor electronic music festival) proves Montrealers are delightfully unhinged, and a steaming bowl of poutine at La Banquise at 2 AM is a rite of passage. Ice skating on the Old Port rink with the city skyline glowing is genuinely magical.",
    2: "February is peak winter and Montreal leans all the way in — Fete des Neiges transforms Parc Jean-Drapeau into a winter playground, while the city averages a teeth-chattering -8°C. Cross-country skiing on Mont Royal feels like wilderness minutes from downtown. The comedy and jazz clubs are packed, the BYOB restaurants are at their cosiest, and if you've never tried tire sur la neige (maple taffy on snow), this is your month. Crowds are low and hotel deals are real.",
    3: "March is the slow thaw nobody trusts — one day it's 5°C and sunny, the next it dumps 20cm of snow. The maple syrup season kicks off and sugar shacks (cabanes a sucre) outside the city serve obscene quantities of maple-everything with live folk music. The St. Patrick's Day parade is one of North America's oldest and rowdiest. Layers are mandatory, optimism is optional, and the first patio sighting causes city-wide celebration.",
    4: "April finally breaks winter's back — temps climb to 10°C, the ice on the St. Lawrence cracks and flows, and the city's energy shifts from survival to celebration. The terrasses aren't quite open yet but the parks fill with joggers and the restaurant scene buzzes with spring menus. The Montreal Museum of Fine Arts and the Biodome are excellent rainy-day options. Still uncrowded with shoulder-season pricing — a smart time to visit.",
    5: "May is Montreal's glow-up — 18°C, the trees burst into green practically overnight, and the festivals start their legendary run. Terrasse season officially opens and every sidewalk sprouts cafe tables. The Botanical Garden is magnificent with tulips and lilacs, and cycling the Lachine Canal is pure joy. Crowds build but the city's scale absorbs them easily. This is when Montreal starts reminding you why it's one of North America's great cities.",
    6: "June is peak Montreal — 24°C, endless daylight, and the Grand Prix transforming the city into a glamorous party. The Jazz Festival begins its takeover of downtown with free outdoor concerts that are genuinely world-class. The food truck scene ignites, Mount Royal's trails are lush, and Old Montreal's cobblestones buzz with energy until midnight. It's busy and prices are up, but the sheer cultural density per square block justifies every cent.",
    7: "July is summer at full blast — 27°C, the Just for Laughs comedy festival filling every venue, and Tam-Tams drum circles on Mount Royal every Sunday creating an impromptu outdoor party. The city lives outdoors: rooftop bars, Piknic Elektronik, canal-side cycling, and the beaches at Parc Jean-Drapeau. Humidity can be thick and afternoon thunderstorms dramatic, but evening relief comes reliably. Peak crowds and peak prices, but peak Montreal is worth it.",
    8: "August keeps the summer heat rolling at 25°C with the Osheaga music festival turning Parc Jean-Drapeau into a massive outdoor concert venue. The Quartier des Spectacles hosts rotating free performances, and the city's BYOB restaurants are perfect for long warm evenings. Humidity remains high and occasional storms break the heat dramatically. It's still peak season but the pace mellows slightly as Montrealers start savouring the last weeks of summer.",
    9: "September is Montreal's golden month — 20°C, the leaves on Mount Royal beginning their famous color show, and the summer crowds thinning to reveal the city's more intimate side. The POP Montreal music festival brings indie culture to Mile End, and the food scene peaks with harvest menus at every serious kitchen. Cycling is perfect, the cafe terrasses are still open, and the light turns warm and photogenic. Arguably the best month to visit if you want the full experience without the summer intensity.",
    10: "October is full autumn — stunning foliage on Mount Royal, crisp 10°C days, and Montreal's cultural season in high gear with gallery openings and theater premieres. Festival du Nouveau Cinema draws film buffs, and the farmers' markets overflow with apples, squash, and cider. Halloween in the Plateau is a neighbourhood-wide production. Daylight shortens noticeably and the first frost arrives, but the city's indoor-outdoor balance is at its best.",
    11: "November is the grey prelude to winter — 4°C, bare trees, and a dampness that cuts through jackets. But Montreal's indoor culture peaks: the restaurants are outstanding, the comedy clubs and live music venues are in full swing, and the Christmas decorations start going up mid-month. Black Friday shopping on Sainte-Catherine is an event unto itself. Crowds are minimal and prices are gentle — a solid choice for culture-focused travelers who pack warm.",
    12: "December transforms Montreal into a winter wonderland — Christmas markets in Old Montreal, the Luminothérapie light installations, and proper snow at -7°C making everything sparkle. The Underground City is a godsend for shopping, and the holiday food scene (tourtiere, raclette, buche de Noel) is magnificent. New Year's Eve on the waterfront draws big crowds. Hotel prices spike for the holidays but early December offers value and full festive atmosphere.",
  },

  'ca-rockies': {
    1: "January in the Canadian Rockies is serious winter — minus 10°C in Banff, deep powder at Lake Louise and Sunshine Village, and frozen waterfalls in Johnston Canyon that you can hike right up to on ice cleats. The mountains are staggeringly beautiful under snow, and the northern lights occasionally dance over Jasper. Crowds are moderate (ski season), prices reflect peak winter, and the dry cold is surprisingly bearable with proper layers. Hot springs at Banff Upper are mandatory post-ski recovery.",
    2: "February delivers the Rockies' best skiing — consistent cold (-8°C), deep snowpack, and bluebird days that make Lake Louise look like it was rendered by a visual effects studio. The ice sculpture competition at Lake Louise and SnowDays festival in Banff bring creative energy to the frozen landscape. Frozen Bubble Lake (Abraham Lake) is a surreal photo opportunity. Days are stretching past 10 hours, and the après-ski scene is at its peak.",
    3: "March brings longer days (12+ hours of light), slightly warmer temps at -3°C, and arguably the best spring skiing conditions — soft snow, sunshine, and the ability to ski in just a base layer. Snowshoeing and cross-country skiing in Kananaskis are superb. The elk are bolder as winter thins, and the frozen lakes begin their slow transformation. Prices start softening from peak and the crowds thin on weekdays. A sweet spot for winter sport enthusiasts.",
    4: "April is shoulder season at its most awkward — ski resorts wind down, hiking trails are still buried in snow, and the valleys are slushy at 6°C. It's genuinely the quietest month and prices reflect it, making it ideal for budget-conscious travelers who want the scenery without the activity. Lake Louise is still frozen and stunning, and the Icefields Parkway is driveable but dramatic with lingering snow. Wildlife is active as bears emerge from hibernation — keep your distance.",
    5: "May is the Rockies waking up — 12°C in the valleys, waterfalls at peak flow from snowmelt, and the first wildflowers pushing through in lower elevations. Higher trails remain snow-covered, but valley hikes like Johnston Canyon and the Bow River trail are clear and gorgeous. The turquoise lakes are beginning to thaw, creating incredible two-tone ice-water compositions. Crowds are light, prices are reasonable, and the sheer volume of water cascading off every cliff is breathtaking.",
    6: "June is when the high country opens — temperatures hit 18°C, most trails are snow-free below treeline, and the wildflower meadows begin their legendary show. Lake Louise and Moraine Lake achieve that impossible turquoise, and the Icefields Parkway is one of the world's great drives. Bear and elk sightings are common along roadsides. Summer crowds begin building but early June still feels manageable. Book your Lake O'Hara shuttle lottery well in advance — it sells out months ahead.",
    7: "July is peak Rockies — 22°C, alpine meadows carpeted in wildflowers, and the high passes finally clear for backcountry hiking. Moraine Lake at dawn, Lake O'Hara's alpine circuits, and the Columbia Icefield are at their most accessible. It's the busiest month with packed parking lots at trailheads by 8 AM, so start early or hike the less-famous gems. The Stampede in nearby Calgary adds rodeo energy. Long 16-hour days mean you can pack in a sunrise hike and a sunset paddle.",
    8: "August matches July for weather at 21°C with marginally fewer crowds in the second half as families head home. The wildflowers are fading at lower elevations but peaking in the alpine, and the larch trees start their slow turn to gold in the high valleys. Thunderstorms build most afternoons, so plan your summit attempts for morning. The stargazing in Jasper Dark Sky Preserve is phenomenal as the Milky Way arc becomes visible. Still peak pricing but the trails reward every early alarm.",
    9: "September is the Rockies' secret weapon — the larch trees turn blazing gold against dark evergreens, creating some of Canada's most iconic landscapes. Temps drop to 13°C, the summer crowds vanish after Labour Day, and the elk rut fills the valleys with bugling bulls. Larch Valley and Sentinel Pass are unmissable in their golden glory. First snow can dust the peaks any time, adding drama. Prices ease and availability opens up — the smartest month to visit by a wide margin.",
    10: "October brings proper autumn — 5°C, the larches have dropped their needles, and the first serious snowfalls hit the higher elevations. Many facilities start closing for the season, and the shoulder-season quiet returns. The Icefields Parkway with fresh snow on the peaks and golden valley floors is breathtaking. Wildlife is active preparing for winter — bears are in hyperphagia, eating everything in sight. Pack for winter conditions at elevation and enjoy having the park nearly to yourself.",
    11: "November is the deep shoulder — ski resorts haven't opened yet, hiking trails are snow-covered, and temps drop to -5°C. It's the quietest and cheapest month, and while options are limited, the frozen landscape has a stark grandeur. Lake Louise freezes into a skating rink, and the early winter light on snow-covered peaks is extraordinary for photographers. Jasper's dark skies are at their best with long, clear nights. Strictly for those who find beauty in winter's austerity.",
    12: "December reignites the Rockies — ski season opens in full force, Banff's main street twinkles with holiday lights, and the mountains are draped in fresh powder at -9°C. Lake Louise hosts the annual World Cup ski races, and the frozen waterfalls at Johnston Canyon are accessible again. Christmas in a mountain lodge with snow falling outside and a fireplace crackling inside is the Canadian winter fantasy made real. Book well ahead — holiday weeks sell out months in advance.",
  },

  'ca-toronto': {
    1: "Toronto in January is a test of character — minus 5°C averages, biting winds off Lake Ontario, and grey skies that make the PATH underground city feel like a genuine gift to humanity. But the cultural scene is firing on all cylinders: the Royal Ontario Museum, the AGO, and the theatre district along King Street offer world-class indoor escapes. Winterlicious restaurant week serves prix fixe meals at the city's best kitchens. Pack your warmest coat and earn your poutine.",
    2: "February is the deepest freeze — hovering around -5°C with the occasional -20°C wind chill that makes your face hurt. The Scotiabank Caribbean Carnival gets an early start with indoor events, and the Toronto Light Festival illuminates the Distillery District with art installations. Skating at Nathan Phillips Square under the Toronto sign is iconic and free. Restaurant reservations are easy, Raptors and Maple Leafs games are in full swing, and hotel prices are at their lowest.",
    3: "March teases spring but rarely delivers — 3°C average with snow, rain, and occasional sunshine all in the same day. The St. Patrick's Day parade is a city-wide affair, and the Canadian Music Week festival brings live shows to every venue in town. The Toronto International Film Festival's spring programming offers previews, and brunch culture is always in season. Still solidly off-peak with good prices, and the first patios open on that one warm day everyone celebrates like a holiday.",
    4: "April is Toronto's messy awakening — 10°C, cherry blossoms in High Park (timing is everything, usually late April), and a collective city-wide sigh of relief that winter is over. The waterfront trails along the Martin Goodman Trail are suddenly populated with joggers and cyclists. The Blue Jays home opener at Rogers Centre is practically a civic holiday. Shoulder-season pricing with improving weather makes this a savvy time to visit.",
    5: "May is when Toronto becomes the city it brags about — 18°C, the islands in bloom, and the first weekend patios packed with locals who've earned their vitamin D. Doors Open Toronto lets you peek inside architecturally significant buildings for free. The food scene peaks with spring menus, the Distillery District buzzes with artisan markets, and cycling to the Toronto Islands for a beach picnic feels almost Mediterranean. Crowds are building but manageable.",
    6: "June kicks off festival season with Pride Month turning the city into a massive celebration of diversity, culminating in one of North America's largest Pride parades. Temps hit 24°C, the waterfront is alive, and the Luminato arts festival fills venues across the city. Restaurant patios are in full bloom, Kensington Market is at its most vibrant, and the Toronto Islands offer perfect afternoon escapes. Summer energy without July's humidity — a top-tier month to visit.",
    7: "July is peak Toronto — 27°C, high humidity that makes the streetcar feel tropical, and the city in full outdoor mode. The Toronto Caribbean Carnival (Caribana) is an explosion of music, costume, and energy, and the Beaches Jazz Festival keeps the east end swinging. Crowds pack the waterfront, the Islands require early ferry queuing, and restaurant reservations at the good spots need advance planning. The thunderstorms are theatrical but brief. Hot, busy, and completely alive.",
    8: "August sustains the summer heat at 26°C with the Canadian National Exhibition (The Ex) taking over the waterfront for its final hurrah — rides, food on sticks, and that uniquely Canadian fall-fair energy. The Toronto International Film Festival announces its lineup, building anticipation. Beach days at the Islands are at their peak, and the Taste of the Danforth Greek food festival is a carb-lover's paradise. Still peak season but the back-to-school energy signals the turn.",
    9: "September belongs to TIFF — the Toronto International Film Festival turns the city into Hollywood North with celebrity sightings, premieres, and a collective buzz that electrifies King Street. Temps ease to a perfect 21°C, the humidity breaks, and the city feels sophisticated and alive. The fall food scene launches with harvest menus, the waterfront is still warm enough for evening strolls, and the crowds are film-buff flavored rather than tourist-generic. One of the best months.",
    10: "October is gorgeous — 12°C, the ravine system blazing with fall color, and Nuit Blanche transforming the city into an all-night contemporary art exhibition. Thanksgiving weekend (second Monday) brings harvest celebrations, and the farmers' markets at St. Lawrence and Evergreen Brick Works overflow with apples and squash. The Raptors season opens, Halloween in the Annex is creative and community-driven, and hotel prices ease from summer peaks. A genuinely lovely time to explore the city's neighborhoods.",
    11: "November settles into grey — 5°C, bare trees, and that Lake Ontario dampness that seeps into everything. But the Santa Claus Parade kicks off the holiday season in grand style, the Royal Agricultural Winter Fair is uniquely Toronto, and the restaurant and theater scene is in full swing. Early holiday shopping in the Distillery District's Christmas Market begins late month. Crowds are light, prices are gentle, and the city rewards those who look past the weather.",
    12: "December brings the holiday magic — Christmas Market in the Distillery District is a European-style wonderland with mulled wine and artisan gifts, and the Cavalcade of Lights illuminates Nathan Phillips Square. Temps hover around -2°C with regular snow, making everything look properly festive. NYE celebrations on the waterfront draw crowds. It's cold but the city's cultural offerings — ballet, concerts, hockey — more than compensate. Book Distillery-area hotels early; they spike for the market season.",
  },

  'ca-vancouver': {
    1: "Vancouver in January is the mildest winter in Canada — 5°C and rainy rather than frozen, with the North Shore mountains offering excellent skiing just 30 minutes from downtown. Grouse Mountain and Cypress get regular dumps of Pacific powder while the city itself stays green (and very wet — 150mm of rain). Crowds are light, prices are reasonable, and the dim sum in Richmond is the best on the continent year-round. Pack a rain jacket, not a parka.",
    2: "February is still grey and wet (120mm of rain) at 6°C, but the first cherry blossoms start appearing in select neighborhoods and everyone collectively loses their minds with joy. Skiing on the North Shore mountains remains excellent with deep snowpack. The Chinese New Year parade in Chinatown is vibrant and the restaurant scene, especially along Main Street, is outstanding. Dine In Vancouver's prix fixe festival offers the city's best kitchens at accessible prices.",
    3: "March is when Vancouver starts its famous transformation — 9°C, the cherry blossoms peak and turn entire streets into pink tunnels, and the rain starts easing (115mm). Stanley Park's seawall is gorgeous with fresh blooms, and whale watching season begins as grey whales migrate north. The ski season is still going strong at higher elevations. Crowds are light but growing, and the city's optimistic energy as spring arrives is genuinely infectious.",
    4: "April brings spring proper — 12°C, noticeably less rain (85mm), and the city's parks and gardens in full bloom. The Vancouver Sun Run (one of the world's largest 10K races) fills the streets, and the farmers' markets at Granville Island kick into high gear. Hiking in Pacific Spirit Regional Park and the lower North Shore trails is superb with wildflowers everywhere. Shoulder-season pricing with near-summer conditions — a savvy traveler's choice.",
    5: "May is Vancouver's sweet spot — 16°C, the rain retreating to just 65mm, and the mountains still snow-capped above a green, blossoming city. The craft brewery scene in East Van is buzzing, whale watching for orcas begins in earnest, and you can ski in the morning and kayak False Creek in the afternoon. Victoria Day weekend starts the outdoor season officially. Crowds are moderate and the long days (15+ hours of light) make everything feel possible.",
    6: "June delivers Vancouver's promise — 19°C, long sunny days, and the mountains-meet-ocean setting at its most photogenic. The Dragon Boat Festival fills False Creek with racing and cultural performances, and the Bard on the Beach Shakespeare festival opens in Vanier Park with the mountains as backdrop. Hiking the Grouse Grind, kayaking Deep Cove, and cycling the seawall are all at peak conditions. Summer crowds begin but the city's outdoor scale absorbs them gracefully.",
    7: "July is peak Vancouver — 22°C, minimal rain, and over 16 hours of daylight that make you understand why people pay Vancouver housing prices. The Celebration of Light fireworks competition lights up English Bay, and the Folk Music Festival fills Jericho Beach with sound. Hiking in Garibaldi Provincial Park is stunning, the beaches at Kitsilano and Third Beach are packed, and the craft beer patios are buzzing. Peak prices and crowds, but the city earns every superlative.",
    8: "August matches July for perfect weather at 22°C with virtually no rain and that golden Pacific light that makes everything glow. The Pride Parade is one of the city's biggest celebrations, and the Pacific National Exhibition (PNE) brings carnival energy to Hastings Park. Wild salmon runs begin in local rivers, orca sightings peak in the Strait of Georgia, and the hiking in the Sea-to-Sky corridor is at its absolute best. Still peak season but the relaxed West Coast vibe keeps things chill.",
    9: "September is Vancouver's golden month — 19°C, the summer crowds evaporate, and the city settles into that sophisticated autumn groove. The Vancouver International Film Festival draws cinephiles, the salmon run peaks with bears fishing at nearby rivers, and the hiking through early fall color on the North Shore is exceptional. Restaurant patios still work with a light sweater, and the harvest wines from the Okanagan are arriving. Arguably the best month to experience the city.",
    10: "October paints Vancouver in rain and gold — 13°C, the fall foliage peaking in Stanley Park and Queen Elizabeth Garden, and the rain returning in earnest (115mm). But the city's indoor culture thrives: Vancouver Writers Fest, the restaurant scene shifting to cozy fall menus, and the craft breweries releasing their autumn seasonals. Storm watching at nearby Tofino becomes a thing. Prices drop, crowds thin, and the city shows its moody, atmospheric side.",
    11: "November is the rain month — 175mm of it at 7°C, grey skies, and early darkness by 4:30 PM. But the ski season begins on the North Shore, the Christmas Market at Jack Poole Plaza lights up mid-month, and the dim sum in Richmond is unaffected by weather. The Vancouver art gallery scene is excellent for rainy days, and the absence of crowds means every restaurant has a table. Embrace the rain culture — good coffee and a window seat is its own art form here.",
    12: "December in Vancouver is mild by Canadian standards — 4°C with rain rather than snow (at sea level, anyway), and the city sparkles with holiday lights at VanDusen Garden's Festival of Lights and the Capilano Suspension Bridge canyon lights. Skiing opens in full force on the North Shore. Christmas shopping on Granville Island and in Gastown is atmospheric, and New Year's Eve at Canada Place features fireworks over the harbor. Cozy, festive, and far less brutal than the rest of Canada.",
  },

  'cd-drc': {
    1: "January in Virunga is deep in the short dry season — warm at 26°C with lower humidity and reduced rainfall making trekking conditions more manageable. This is prime gorilla trekking season in Virunga National Park, with clearer trails and better visibility in the mountain forests. Permits are essential to book months ahead through the park authority. Security conditions require checking current travel advisories and using reputable operators — Virunga has improved dramatically but diligence is non-negotiable.",
    2: "February continues the short dry season with pleasant 26°C days and the most reliable trekking conditions. Mountain gorilla families in the Mikeno sector are more predictable in their movements, and Nyiragongo volcano's lava lake hike (when open) is most accessible now. The lowland sectors near Lake Edward offer excellent birding and hippo sightings. Malaria prophylaxis is essential year-round, and travel insurance covering evacuation is mandatory, not optional.",
    3: "March brings the return of heavy rains — expect muddy, challenging trails, 200mm+ of precipitation, and a thick green canopy that makes wildlife harder to spot. Gorilla trekking continues but treks are longer and slipperier, requiring serious fitness and waterproof gear. The compensation is fewer trekkers and a forest that feels primordially alive with sound and growth. Permit availability improves as fair-weather visitors stay away.",
    4: "April is the wettest month — relentless rain, swollen rivers, and trails that test even experienced trekkers. Some park sectors may restrict access, and Nyiragongo volcano treks are often suspended. The lowland forests are alive with birdlife but the conditions are grueling. This is only for the truly committed: those who come find an almost mystical landscape and deeply uncrowded encounters with the gorillas. Prices may soften through operators, but logistics are harder.",
    5: "May is still rainy but easing — the tail end of the long wet season with decreasing daily downpours. The forest is at maximum lush intensity and the gorillas move through a verdant, dripping landscape. Trekking is physically demanding but rewarding, and the reduced visitor numbers mean more intimate encounters. Chimps in the Tongo Forest are also tracked here, offering a remarkable primate double. Always check security updates before finalizing plans.",
    6: "June marks the start of the long dry season — drier trails, 25°C days, and the best overall trekking conditions beginning. Gorilla permits become harder to get as this is the start of peak season, so book four to six months ahead. The Nyiragongo volcano hike reopens reliably, and the overnight summit camp overlooking the lava lake is one of Africa's most extraordinary experiences. The park's conservation efforts are visible and inspiring — your permit fee directly funds protection.",
    7: "July is peak season — dry conditions, comfortable 24°C temperatures, and the highest demand for gorilla permits. Virunga buzzes with international visitors and the infrastructure (such as it is) operates at full capacity. The mountain hiking is superb with clear views across the Albertine Rift, and the wildlife in the savanna sectors near Rwindi is most visible with animals concentrated near water. Book everything as far ahead as possible and use established operators.",
    8: "August continues peak conditions — dry, clear, and busy by DRC standards (which still means intimate compared to Rwanda). The gorilla families are accessible on relatively dry trails, and the Nyiragongo crater is at its most dramatic on clear nights. The fishing villages on Lake Edward offer a fascinating cultural dimension. This is the month where everything aligns, but the premium pricing and limited permit availability mean spontaneity isn't an option.",
    9: "September is the tail of the dry season with the first rains threatening but not yet arriving — still excellent for trekking at 26°C. The savanna is at its driest and game viewing near Rwindi Plains improves as animals cluster at remaining water sources. Gorilla permits are slightly easier to secure than July-August. The transition period offers peak-quality conditions with marginally less competition — a smart choice for those who plan ahead.",
    10: "October brings the short rains — increasing afternoon showers, muddier trails, and a shift toward greener landscapes. Trekking continues but with more challenging conditions and longer approaches. The forest comes alive with new growth and amphibian activity, and the birding is outstanding as migratory species arrive. Tourist numbers drop and a certain rawness returns to the experience. Malaria risk increases with the rains — be rigorous with prophylaxis.",
    11: "November is solidly wet season — heavy rain, muddy conditions, and reduced access to some sectors. But the forest is magnificent in its fecundity, and the gorilla encounters, when you reach them through the rain and mud, feel earned in a way that dry-season visits don't. Permit availability is good and prices may be negotiable through operators. Not for the comfort-seeking, but deeply rewarding for adventurous travelers who understand that the journey is part of the point.",
    12: "December straddles the short rains and the approaching dry spell — conditions vary week to week, with improving access in the second half. Holiday travelers with advance permits find a quieter alternative to Rwanda's Volcanoes National Park at a lower price point. The Nyiragongo trek is hit-or-miss depending on rain, but the gorilla trekking in the mountain sectors continues year-round. The combination of conservation impact and raw adventure makes any month worthwhile — December offers a decent compromise between conditions and crowds.",
  },

  'cf-car': {
    1: "January in CAR is deep dry season — searing 35°C heat, harmattan haze, and bone-dry conditions in the savanna. Dzanga-Sangha Reserve in the southwest is the main draw, offering extraordinary forest elephant and western lowland gorilla tracking through dense tropical forest that stays green year-round. Tourism infrastructure is minimal and security requires careful planning with specialized operators. The Ba'Aka pygmy communities offer guided forest walks that are culturally profound and ecologically illuminating.",
    2: "February continues the dry season with temperatures pushing to 37°C — the hottest period. The bais (forest clearings) at Dzanga become critical water points, concentrating forest elephants in groups of 50+ for one of Central Africa's most remarkable wildlife spectacles. Gorilla habituation groups are visited with expert trackers. The infrastructure remains basic, and this is expedition-level travel requiring self-sufficiency. The rewards, however, are encounters that few places on earth can match.",
    3: "March brings the first tentative rains to southern CAR while the north stays dry and hot. The forest around Dzanga-Sangha begins greening further, and the fruiting trees attract primates and birds in numbers. This transitional month offers slightly softer temperatures (33°C) and improving forest conditions for tracking. Bongo antelope sightings improve along forest streams. The window for accessible travel before the heavy rains is narrowing — experienced operators know the timing well.",
    4: "April signals the wet season's arrival — increasing afternoon storms, rising humidity, and forest trails that begin to muddy. The savanna greens up dramatically and the birdlife is extraordinary as migratory species arrive. Gorilla and elephant tracking continue but become more physically demanding. River levels rise, affecting some access routes. This is when the less-committed turn back, leaving the forest to a handful of dedicated wildlife researchers and the most adventurous travelers.",
    5: "May is solidly wet season — heavy daily rains, swollen rivers, and challenging logistics throughout the country. Dzanga-Sangha remains operational but access roads can become impassable, and trekking through the forest requires waterproof everything and a tolerance for mud. The compensation is a forest at its most biologically active — insects, amphibians, and birds create a wall of sound. Only specialists and the deeply committed visit; permits and logistics require months of advance planning with expert operators.",
    6: "June is the wettest period — expect 200mm+ of rain, flooded forest clearings, and extremely difficult travel conditions. Most casual tourism is effectively impossible outside of Dzanga-Sangha, and even there, conditions are challenging. The forest elephants continue visiting the bais but the approach can require wading. This is research-season territory: the few visitors are typically scientists, filmmakers, or extreme adventure travelers. Not recommended without significant Central African experience.",
    7: "July maintains heavy rains and high humidity (85%+) with temps around 27°C. The forest is at maximum density and the rivers are full. Butterfly diversity peaks with hundreds of species along forest trails — a genuine spectacle for entomology enthusiasts. Gorilla tracking continues year-round but treks are longest and most demanding now. CAR's security situation requires constant monitoring; always consult current advisories and rely on operators with deep local relationships.",
    8: "August is similar to July — wet, humid, and logistically challenging, but the rains begin to ease slightly in the second half. The forest floor is alive with mushrooms and the undergrowth is impenetrable in places. For the few visitors who make it to Dzanga, the intimacy of the experience is unmatched — you might be the only tourist in the entire reserve. Lowland gorilla encounters in these conditions feel like true exploration. This is Africa at its most raw and undiluted.",
    9: "September marks the transition — rains begin decreasing, access routes start drying, and the forest opens up slightly. The bai visits by elephants remain consistent and the tracking conditions gradually improve week by week. This is a smart window for experienced travelers who want the lush forest without the worst of the wet season. Temperatures hover around 30°C with moderating humidity. Book through operators who know the exact road conditions.",
    10: "October accelerates the dry transition — rainfall drops, the savanna starts browning in the north, and the forest trails become more manageable. The elephant gatherings at Dzanga bai intensify as water concentrates, and gorilla tracking improves with drier conditions underfoot. Tourist numbers (such as they are) tick up marginally. The birding remains excellent with both resident and lingering migratory species. This is when the serious wildlife operators begin recommending visits.",
    11: "November is dry season in earnest — 33°C, low humidity, and the best overall access conditions for Dzanga-Sangha. The forest elephant congregations are spectacular, gorilla treks are at their most accessible, and the network of forest trails is in good condition. This is the emerging sweet spot for the handful of operators running trips to CAR. Ba'Aka-guided net hunts and forest walks are culturally fascinating. The country requires commitment, but November delivers the most consistent rewards.",
    12: "December continues excellent dry-season conditions — hot at 35°C with clear skies and the best access of the year. The bais are at peak activity as water becomes scarce, and the contrast of the dry savanna north with the evergreen forest south is striking. Holiday travelers with the right operator can have genuinely once-in-a-lifetime encounters. The year ends with CAR at its most accessible — which, to be clear, still means expedition-grade travel, but the wildlife experiences rank among Africa's finest.",
  },

  'cg-congo': {
    1: "January in the Republic of Congo is wet season — expect heavy rain (200mm+), steamy 30°C heat, and thick humidity in Brazzaville. The Odzala-Kokoua National Park in the north is the star attraction, offering western lowland gorilla tracking through dripping, intensely green forest. Conditions are muddy and challenging, but the forest is alive with primates and birds. Tourism infrastructure is extremely limited — this is expedition travel requiring specialized operators and serious advance planning.",
    2: "February continues the wet season with similar conditions — 30°C, daily downpours, and a forest canopy so dense that the rain takes minutes to reach the ground. Gorilla habituation groups in Odzala are visited by a tiny handful of travelers, making encounters extraordinarily intimate. Forest elephants visit the bais (clearings) regularly, and the birdlife is at a peak. Malaria prevention is critical year-round. The Congo Basin in its wet glory is primordially beautiful — if you can handle the logistics.",
    3: "March keeps the rains coming but the intensity begins to moderate in some areas. The forest floor in Odzala is carpeted with fallen fruit, attracting primates and forest hogs in numbers. Tracking conditions remain wet and demanding, but the experienced guides know the gorilla families' movements intimately. Brazzaville's markets and riverside promenade along the Congo River offer an urban counterpoint, with views across to Kinshasa making for one of the world's most surreal city panoramas.",
    4: "April is transition month — the rains ease, trails begin to firm up, and temperatures stay warm at 29°C. Odzala's gorilla tracking becomes slightly less grueling, and the network of rivers and streams is perfect for pirogue (canoe) excursions through flooded forest. The butterfly diversity is extraordinary, and chimpanzee encounters supplement the gorilla tracking. This is still deep-expedition territory, but the improving conditions make April more accessible than the preceding months.",
    5: "May eases into the dry season — rainfall drops significantly, the forest trails become more manageable, and the 28°C temperatures feel less oppressive with lower humidity. This is when Odzala starts its prime season: gorilla tracking conditions improve markedly, and the forest elephants concentrate at key bais as water sources reduce. The handful of eco-lodges in Odzala operate at their best, and the guides can cover more ground. A sweet spot for serious wildlife travelers.",
    6: "June is the start of the main dry season — minimal rain, comfortable 26°C days, and the best overall conditions for exploring the Congo Basin forests. Gorilla and elephant encounters are at their most reliable, and the reduced foliage makes wildlife spotting easier. The Congo River is navigable for longer excursions, and the fishing communities along its banks offer cultural immersion. Tourist numbers peak (by Congo standards, meaning perhaps a dozen visitors in the entire park).",
    7: "July is peak dry season — 25°C, very little rain, and the forest at its most accessible. Odzala delivers its finest gorilla encounters with dry trails, predictable family movements, and the kind of intimate wildlife experiences that make East African safaris look like bus tours. The bais are focal points for extraordinary biodiversity, and nighttime forest walks reveal a different world of bush babies, genets, and insects. This is the month operators recommend — book six months ahead.",
    8: "August continues the dry-season peak with similar excellent conditions — comfortable temperatures, minimal rain, and the forest in its most visitor-friendly state. The savanna-forest mosaic of northern Congo is particularly scenic, and the opportunity to combine gorilla tracking with forest elephant encounters and Congo River exploration creates a trip unlike anything else on the continent. Still minimal tourist infrastructure, but the few operations running are well-oiled by this point in the season.",
    9: "September marks the end of the dry season — still good conditions with 27°C days, but the first rains begin appearing as afternoon showers. The forest starts its greening cycle and the animal movements shift accordingly. Gorilla tracking remains excellent in the first half, and the transition period brings its own beauty as the landscape transforms. This is the last reliable window before wet-season logistics complicate access. A strategic month for those who couldn't secure peak-season spots.",
    10: "October brings the rains back — increasing precipitation, rising river levels, and trails returning to their muddy baseline. The forest explodes with new growth and the amphibian chorus at night is deafening. Gorilla tracking continues but treks lengthen and difficulty increases. The birding is outstanding as migratory species arrive from the north. Tourist operations begin scaling back, and flexibility becomes essential — plans may change with the weather. For the adaptable and adventurous only.",
    11: "November is wet season in full — heavy rains, challenging access, and the forest at its most impenetrable and beautiful. The few travelers who make it to Odzala find gorilla encounters that feel like genuine exploration, not tourism. Forest elephants continue their routines regardless of rain, and the smaller wildlife — duikers, pangolins, pottos — become more active. Conditions demand total commitment: waterproof gear, physical fitness, and tolerance for discomfort. The payoff is experiencing one of Earth's last great wildernesses.",
    12: "December is solidly wet season with 180mm+ of rain, but the holiday period occasionally draws a handful of dedicated wildlife travelers. Conditions are challenging but the forest is spectacular, and the intimacy of visiting a world-class gorilla site with virtually no other tourists is extraordinary. Brazzaville has a modest festive atmosphere along the river, and the cultural contrast between the capital and the deep forest is jarring and fascinating. Come prepared for adventure in its truest sense.",
  },

  'ch-geneva': {
    1: "Geneva in January is grey, cold (3°C highs), and draped in that particular Lake Leman mist that makes the city feel like a watercolor painting. The Escalade festival aftermath lingers in chocolate shops, and the fondue and raclette scene is at its peak — every restaurant worth its Gruyere has a bubbling pot waiting. Skiing in nearby Chamonix and Verbier is just an hour away with fresh January powder. Crowds are at their annual lowest, and the international organizations keep the city's cosmopolitan pulse steady.",
    2: "February stays cold (4°C) but the days are lengthening and the ski resorts in the surrounding Alps are in prime condition. The Geneva Motor Show (when held) or other trade events can spike hotel prices unpredictably. The Old Town's cobblestoned streets are quiet enough for contemplative wandering, and a chocolate-tasting tour through the city's master chocolatiers is the finest indoor activity imaginable. The lake is steely grey but the steamers still run, offering dramatic mountain views on clear days.",
    3: "March marks the transition — highs reach 10°C, the first spring flowers appear in the Parc des Bastions, and the city begins shaking off winter. The lakefront promenade gets its first joggers and the cafe terraces crack open on sunny days. Skiing is still excellent at higher elevations (late-season powder in Verbier), and the Salon International du Livre brings literary culture to Palexpo. A shoulder-season sweet spot with improving weather and moderate crowds.",
    4: "April is Geneva coming alive — 15°C, cherry blossoms along the Rhone, and the Jet d'Eau fountain restarting its iconic 140-meter spray over the lake. The vineyards in Lavaux (a short train ride) begin budding, and hiking in the Jura mountains and Saleve is superb with wildflowers. Restaurant terraces fill up, the weekend markets buzz, and you can still get a table at Michelin-starred spots without the summer wait. One of the loveliest months for the city.",
    5: "May is gorgeous — 19°C, the lake turning from grey to blue, and the city's parks and gardens in full flower. The Fete de la Musique fills streets with live performances, and the farmer's markets along Plainpalais sell the first local asparagus and strawberries. A day trip to Chamonix for hiking with Mont Blanc views is spectacular as the high trails open. Crowds build to moderate levels but Geneva's international-city scale absorbs them. The outdoor cafe season is officially in full swing.",
    6: "June brings reliable summer — 23°C, long evenings, and the lake warming enough for the first brave swimmers at Bains des Paquis (the city's beloved lakefront lido). The Fete de la Musique fills every square with free concerts, and evening cruises on Lac Leman with the Alps turning pink at sunset are unforgettable. The Lavaux vineyards are lush and green, and hiking in the Pre-Alps is at its best. Crowds are present but Geneva's sophistication keeps things orderly rather than chaotic.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 26°C, the lake hitting a swimmable 22°C, and the Fetes de Geneve lighting up the waterfront with fireworks and festivities. Bains des Paquis becomes the city's living room, with locals swimming, sunbathing, and eating fondue (yes, fondue in summer — Geneva is committed). The Montreux Jazz Festival is a short train ride along the lake. Prices peak and hotel availability tightens, but the combination of Alpine scenery, cultural richness, and lakefront living is hard to beat.",
    8: "August sustains the summer at 25°C with the highest average sunshine hours of the year. The city empties slightly as Genevois take their holidays, which means easier restaurant reservations and a slightly more relaxed pace. The lake is at its warmest (23°C) and perfect for sailing and paddleboarding. Day hikes in the Alps are at peak conditions with clear trails and wildflower meadows. The Paleo Festival in Nyon brings world-class music nearby. Luxurious without being hectic.",
    9: "September is Geneva's golden month — 21°C, grape harvest in Lavaux, and that September light that makes the lake shimmer. Crowds thin, prices ease, and the city settles into its sophisticated autumn rhythm. The Vendanges (grape harvest) celebrations in nearby villages feature wine tastings and traditional food. Hiking remains superb with clear mountain views and the first hints of color on the Jura slopes. Restaurant terraces stay open and every bistro is pouring the new vintage. Quietly perfect.",
    10: "October brings autumn — 13°C, golden leaves in the Parc des Eaux-Vives, and the first fondue-weather evenings. The lake steamers offer fall-foliage cruises with Chablais vineyard views, and the mountain trails show their autumnal colors. Art and theater season launches in earnest, and the city's museums (Red Cross Museum, Ariana Museum) are uncrowded and excellent. Prices drop, availability is easy, and Geneva shows its contemplative, cultural side rather than its summer sparkle.",
    11: "November goes grey — 7°C, frequent rain, and the fog rolling in off the lake. But the Escalade festival preparations begin, the chocolate shops ramp up for winter, and the fondue-raclette season returns in full force. Early-season skiing opens at Verbier and other high resorts. The city's international cultural calendar fills theaters and concert halls. It's moody and atmospheric, and the prices make Geneva almost affordable — which, if you know Geneva, is saying something.",
    12: "December is festive and cold — 4°C with occasional snow, the Christmas market filling the Jardin Anglais, and the Escalade festival (mid-December) celebrating Geneva's victory over Savoyard invaders with chocolate cauldrons and costumed parades. The Old Town glows with holiday lights, and every restaurant is serving its finest winter menu. Skiing in the nearby Alps is in full swing. Prices spike for the holidays but the combination of Swiss precision and French joie de vivre makes Geneva's December genuinely enchanting.",
  },

  'ch-ticino': {
    1: "Ticino in January is Switzerland's Mediterranean surprise — even in winter, Lugano sees 5°C highs (mild by Swiss standards) and occasional sunny days that feel like a different country from Zurich. The palms along the lakefront are evergreen, the grottos serve polenta and brasato year-round, and the cultural offerings in Lugano's LAC arts center are excellent. Monte Bre and Monte San Salvatore offer winter hiking with lake views when the higher Alps are buried in snow. Crowds are at their lowest and prices reflect it.",
    2: "February is still chilly at 7°C but the Carnival of Bellinzona (Rabadan) is one of Switzerland's wildest — think confetti battles, elaborate floats, and risotto served in the streets to thousands. The camellias in Locarno start blooming astonishingly early, and the lakefront walks are peaceful and photogenic. Skiing at Airolo and the Gotthard region is accessible for a quick day on the slopes. The Italian-speaking warmth of Ticino's culture shines especially bright in the grey winter months.",
    3: "March brings the first genuine spring — 11°C, the camellia festival in Locarno in full swing, and the lakeside promenades coming alive with magnolias and forsythia. Lake Lugano and Lake Maggiore shimmer in the lengthening light, and the hiking trails up to mountain villages like Brè and Gandria are muddy but rewarding. Restaurant terraces start opening on sunny days, and the first local asparagus appears on menus. A beautiful shoulder-season window before the summer crowds discover Ticino.",
    4: "April is Ticino at its most floriferous — 15°C, wisteria draped over every pergola, azaleas blazing in the parks of Isole di Brissago, and the mountain meadows carpeted with wildflowers. The hiking is superb as the lower trails dry out and the views of snow-capped peaks above green valleys are quintessentially Swiss-Italian. Easter brings traditional processions in the villages and a foodie calendar of spring menus in the grottos. Crowds are light and the lakes are too cold for swimming but perfect for scenic boat cruises.",
    5: "May is arguably Ticino's finest month — 20°C, long sunny days, and that magical combination of snow on the peaks and blooming gardens at lake level. Swimming season begins for the bold (the lakes hit 17°C), and the Via dei Monti trail network opens fully with stunning panoramic routes. The grottos — those rustic stone restaurants hidden in chestnut forests — are at their most atmospheric with outdoor seating under ancient trees. Moderate crowds, excellent pricing, and perfect conditions for every outdoor activity.",
    6: "June delivers full summer — 24°C, the lakes warming to a pleasant 21°C, and the longest days of the year illuminating Ticino's dramatic landscapes. Locarno's Piazza Grande hosts outdoor cinema screenings, and the beach lidos along Lake Lugano buzz with swimmers and sunbathers. Hiking to destinations like Lavertezzo's emerald rock pools in Valle Verzasca is at its best. Crowds build to moderate-busy as Swiss-German weekenders discover their southern escape. The gelato is excellent and the pace is decidedly Italian.",
    7: "July is peak season — 27°C, the lakes at their warmest (24°C), and every beach, grotto, and trail well-patronized. The Moon and Stars music festival in Locarno fills the Piazza Grande with international acts, and the swimming at Lavertezzo's crystal-clear river pools is the stuff of Instagram legends. Afternoon thunderstorms are common and dramatic, clearing to spectacular evening skies. Prices peak and the best grottos need reservations. Hot, social, and thoroughly Mediterranean in character despite the Swiss postal code.",
    8: "August sustains the summer peak — 26°C, the Locarno International Film Festival transforming the town into a cultural epicenter with open-air screenings on Piazza Grande (one of Europe's great cinema experiences). The lakes are perfect for swimming and sailing, the mountain trails are in prime condition, and the ferragosto holiday brings Italian tourists who add to the convivial atmosphere. Thunderstorm season continues with dramatic afternoon buildups. Peak prices, peak crowds, but peak Ticino character.",
    9: "September is Ticino's golden month — 22°C, the grape harvest underway in the Mendrisiotto vineyards, and the summer crowds receding like the lake waters. The grottos serve new-season Merlot del Ticino alongside plates of local salumi and polenta, and hiking trails like the Sentiero del Castagno (chestnut trail) are at their most atmospheric with early autumn color. The lakes hold their summer warmth at 21°C. Prices ease, tables open up, and the light turns amber and soft. Quietly, confidently the best month.",
    10: "October paints Ticino in gold and amber — 15°C, chestnut harvest season, and the annual Festa delle Castagne celebrations filling mountain villages with roasted chestnuts, grappa, and live music. The foliage around the lakes is gorgeous, and hiking through the chestnut forests above Lugano is peak autumn beauty. The first fog rolls into the valleys, adding atmosphere, and the grottos shift to hearty winter menus. Crowds thin further and the entire region feels like a secret the rest of Switzerland forgot to share.",
    11: "November brings the quiet season — 9°C, bare branches revealing lake views that the summer foliage hid, and the occasional grey day that makes a grotto lunch by the fire feel essential. The LAC Lugano arts center and local galleries offer cultural depth, and the markets sell late-season produce and new olive oil from the lake shores. It's moody and atmospheric rather than postcard-pretty, and the prices are the most accessible of the year. A contemplative, food-focused month for those who appreciate slow travel.",
    12: "December in Ticino is festive and mild — 5°C in Lugano (balmy compared to north of the Alps), Christmas markets lighting up the lake towns, and the grottos serving winter specialties alongside warming grappa. The Monte Bre funicular offers panoramic views of a snow-dusted landscape with the lake below, and midnight mass in the Romanesque churches is genuinely moving. New Year's Eve along the Lugano waterfront has fireworks and prosecco. A gentler, warmer Swiss Christmas than the alpine stereotype suggests.",
  },

  'ch-zurich': {
    1: "Zurich in January is proper Central European winter — 3°C, grey skies, and a cold that the lake wind turns into a blade. But the Bahnhofstrasse sparkles with lingering holiday lights, the fondue restaurants are in peak form, and the Kunsthaus and Swiss National Museum are world-class indoor escapes. Skiing in Flumserberg or Laax is just an hour by train. The city's efficiency means nothing stops for weather — trams run, cafes steam, and a fresh Birchermusli at a Zurich institution is the best winter breakfast in Switzerland.",
    2: "February remains cold (4°C) and grey, but the Fasnacht carnival celebrations bring welcome chaos — costumes, confetti, and a brief departure from Swiss orderliness. The ski resorts nearby are in prime condition with February snow, and the city's chocolate shops deserve devoted exploration (Sprungli on Paradeplatz is non-negotiable). The opera and theater season is in full swing, and a walk along the Limmat on a crisp, clear day offers stunning views of the Alps. Low crowds and reasonable (by Zurich standards) hotel rates.",
    3: "March is the slow turn — 9°C, the first crocuses in the botanical garden, and enough sunshine to remind you that Zurich isn't actually Scandinavia. The Sechselauten spring festival preparations begin, and the lakefront restaurants start opening their terraces on brave days. Day trips to the surrounding hills for spring hiking are excellent as the lower trails clear. The city's farmers' markets at Burkliplatz offer early spring produce. Shoulder season with improving weather and gentle tourist numbers.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring — 14°C, the cherry trees blooming along the lake, and the Sechselauten festival where a cotton snowman (Boogg) is burned atop a bonfire to predict the summer (the faster it explodes, the better). The lake promenade is gorgeous, the Old Town's guild houses host special events, and hiking on the Uetliberg (Zurich's local mountain) offers wildflower meadows with city panoramas. Restaurant terraces fill on sunny days, and the city shakes off winter's reserve.",
    5: "May is Zurich at its most pleasant — 18°C, the lake turning blue, and the city's parks and gardens in full bloom. The weekly lakeside markets sell local cheese, bread, and flowers, and cycling along the lake toward Rapperswil is a perfect day out. The outdoor Badi (public swimming) season begins as water temperatures become tolerable for the determined. Street food festivals and open-air cultural events multiply. Crowds are moderate and the famous Swiss efficiency feels like it exists purely to maximize your good time.",
    6: "June is summer arriving — 22°C, the longest days, and Zurich's famous Badi culture in full swing as the city descends on its lakeside and river swimming spots. Frauenbadi and Barfussbar offer cocktails and swimming in the Limmat — a uniquely Zurich experience. The Street Parade electronic music festival preparations begin. Farmers' markets overflow with strawberries and cherries, and evening dining on the lake is magical with the Alps turning pink. Busy but not overwhelming; the city's infrastructure handles it smoothly.",
    7: "July is peak Zurich — 25°C, the lake hitting 22°C for comfortable swimming, and the city fully in outdoor mode. The Zurich Festival brings opera, theater, and concerts to open-air venues. Hiking in the Albis hills and the nearby Pre-Alps is excellent, and the Old Town's cafe terraces buzz until late. Afternoon thunderstorms are common and dramatic, often clearing to gorgeous evenings. Prices peak and popular restaurants require reservations. The efficiency-meets-hedonism balance is Zurich at its most characteristic.",
    8: "August sustains the summer — 24°C, the Street Parade (one of the world's largest electronic music events) filling the lakefront with hundreds of thousands of dancing bodies in mid-month. The swimming in Lake Zurich is at its best, and day trips to Lucerne, Rhine Falls, or the Appenzell hills are all excellent. The city takes a slightly relaxed August holiday tone as many locals travel, meaning easier reservations and a pleasant, unhurried atmosphere. Still peak season pricing but the lakeside living is worth every franc.",
    9: "September is golden Zurich — 19°C, the Weinlese (grape harvest) celebrations in nearby villages, and the city settling into its sophisticated autumn stride. The lake holds warmth for late-season swimming, and the Uetliberg offers stunning autumn panoramas. The cultural season launches with new exhibitions and performances, and the restaurant scene shifts to hearty fall menus with game and mushrooms. Crowds ease, prices soften, and the quality of light over the Old Town is at its most photogenic.",
    10: "October is crisp and colorful — 12°C, the trees along the lake and Lindenhof turning gold and amber, and the first fog wrapping the city in atmospheric mystery. Knabenschiessen (the city's traditional shooting competition) and the Zurich Film Festival add cultural texture. The fondue and raclette season returns, and the hiking on Uetliberg through autumn foliage is lovely. Museum-hopping becomes more appealing as the outdoor season winds down. Prices are moderate and the city feels authentically local.",
    11: "November goes grey — 6°C, frequent fog, and the days shrinking fast. But the Christmas preparations begin in earnest: the Bahnhofstrasse lights up with the famous illumination, and the early Christmas markets start opening. The city's indoor cultural life — opera, museums, jazz bars — is at its finest, and the cozy wine bars in Niederdorf are perfect for rainy afternoons. It's the cheapest month for hotels and the quietest for sightseeing. Embrace the hygge (or Gemutlichkeit, as the Swiss say) and eat more fondue.",
    12: "December is Zurich at its most magical — multiple Christmas markets (the Old Town's Wienachtsdorf and the Singing Christmas Tree at the train station), the Bahnhofstrasse twinkling, and the cold (3°C with occasional snow) making everything feel properly festive. Mulled wine, raclette stands, and roasted chestnuts fuel the shopping crowds. The Opernhaus Zurich's holiday programming is world-class. Prices spike for the holiday weeks, but early December offers the full festive experience at gentler rates. A Swiss Christmas done to predictable perfection.",
  },

  'ec-galapagos': {
    1: "Warm season is in full swing — 28°C air, 25°C seas, and daily afternoon showers that keep the islands lush. This is prime snorkeling with sea lions at Kicker Rock and watching blue-footed boobies court on Española. Crowds are moderate and rising toward peak; book your cruise or day-tour permits well ahead.",
    2: "The warmest, wettest month brings 30°C days and calm, bathtub-warm seas perfect for snorkeling with marine iguanas at Fernandina. Green sea turtles are nesting on the beaches and the landscape is at its most verdant. Tourist numbers tick up but the archipelago's strict visitor caps keep things civilized — just expect premium pricing.",
    3: "Still warm season with the heaviest rains (up to 100mm) and the warmest seas of the year around 26°C — visibility dips but marine life is at its most active. Giant tortoises are breeding in the highlands of Santa Cruz and waved albatrosses begin returning to Española. Crowds ease slightly after the February rush, making boat availability a touch easier.",
    4: "The transition month — rains taper off, seas stay warm at 25°C, and you get the best of both seasons. Sea lion pups are playful and approachable, and the snorkeling remains excellent with green turtles everywhere. This is a smart time to visit: fewer visitors than peak months, pleasant weather, and prices that haven't yet climbed to high-season territory.",
    5: "The cool, dry garúa season begins settling in — air temps drop to 24°C, seas cool to 22°C, and a persistent misty drizzle replaces the tropical downpours. Penguin activity picks up around Isabela and Bartolomé as the cooler Cromwell Current brings nutrient-rich upwellings. Crowds thin to moderate levels and the landscape starts browning, trading lush greens for a stark volcanic beauty.",
    6: "Garúa season proper: overcast skies, 22°C air, and 21°C seas that bring incredible marine productivity — think hammerhead sharks at Gordon Rocks and massive schools of fish. On land, marine iguanas on Fernandina are at their most colorful during mating season, flushing red and green. Tourist numbers are low-to-moderate, making this a diver's paradise without the crowds.",
    7: "The coolest month with 20°C air and seas dipping to 19°C — wetsuits are non-negotiable but the diving is world-class with whale sharks appearing at Darwin and Wolf. Waved albatrosses are nesting on Española and blue-footed boobies are mid-courtship. The misty garúa keeps things grey but atmospheric, and visitor numbers sit at moderate levels with decent availability.",
    8: "Cool and dry continues with 20°C temps and the roughest seas of the year — sensitive stomachs beware on inter-island crossings. But the marine megafauna is extraordinary: whale sharks, manta rays, and humpback whales all pass through. Galápagos penguins are nesting around Isabela and the snorkeling, while chilly, rewards with unreal visibility. Peak season for serious wildlife enthusiasts.",
    9: "The coldest seas (18-19°C) bring the richest marine life and the best diving conditions of the year — hammerheads school at Wolf and Darwin in staggering numbers. Humboldt penguins are active, sea lions are pupping on San Cristóbal, and the garúa mist gives the highlands an eerie, mossy beauty. Crowds are moderate and the cool air (21°C) keeps hiking comfortable.",
    10: "The transition back to warm season begins — seas start warming past 20°C, skies clear, and the islands shift from grey garúa to golden light. Giant tortoises begin migrating from the highlands to lowland nesting areas on Santa Cruz, and marine iguanas are actively nesting. A quiet month visitor-wise with good prices and increasingly pleasant snorkeling conditions.",
    11: "Warm season reasserts itself with 25°C air, clearing skies, and seas warming to 22°C. Brown pelicans and blue-footed boobies begin nesting, and the snorkeling improves weekly as visibility returns. This is a genuine sweet spot: uncrowded, warming, and affordable, with the islands greening up and wildlife transitioning into breeding mode. Book now before December prices kick in.",
    12: "Holiday crowds arrive alongside the warm season — 27°C air, 24°C seas, and daily sunshine broken by short tropical showers. Giant tortoise hatchlings emerge on Isabela and marine iguanas are nesting across the archipelago. Peak pricing and busy boats, but the warm, calm seas make this excellent for families and snorkelers who prefer not to shiver. Book permits months ahead.",
  },

  'ec-quito': {
    1: "Quito's dry-ish season continues with pleasant 20°C highs and cool 10°C nights at 2,800m elevation — pack layers, not shorts. Afternoon showers are possible but mornings are reliably sunny, perfect for wandering the colonial Old Town and its gilded churches without breaking a sweat. Crowds are moderate post-holidays and the Mitad del Mundo monument is mercifully queue-free.",
    2: "The wettest month brings daily afternoon downpours and misty mornings, but temperatures stay mild at 20°C — this is the equatorial highlands, not a monsoon. Carnival celebrations bring colorful water fights to the streets (you will get drenched, willingly or not). The cloud forests near Mindo are at their most lush and birdwatching is superb with quetzals active.",
    3: "Still firmly in the wet season with heavy afternoon rains and the greenest landscapes of the year — the surrounding volcanoes are often shrouded in dramatic clouds. Temperatures hold steady at 20°C and the colonial center is uncrowded, making it ideal for museum-hopping and lingering over locro de papa in cozy restaurants. Cotopaxi is hit-or-miss for visibility.",
    4: "Peak rainy season wraps up but April stays wet — expect overcast mornings clearing to sunny spells before the inevitable afternoon cloudbursts. Semana Santa (Holy Week) brings elaborate processions through the Old Town that are genuinely moving and deeply photogenic. The Otavalo market runs rain or shine, and at 19°C with few tourists, haggling feels more like conversation.",
    5: "The rains ease significantly and Quito enters its most pleasant stretch — 20°C days, increasingly clear mornings, and the surrounding páramo grasslands turning gold and green. Excellent month for day trips to Cotopaxi (visibility improves dramatically) and the Papallacta hot springs feel earned after the drive through misty passes. Moderate crowds and fair prices across the board.",
    6: "Dry season arrives properly with clear skies, crisp 20°C days, and cold nights dropping to 7°C — bring that fleece for evening walks through La Mariscal. The volcanoes reveal themselves in full glory: Cotopaxi, Chimborazo, and Antisana all visible on clear mornings. This is prime hiking season in the highlands, and Quito's restaurant scene buzzes with locals dining outdoors.",
    7: "The driest, coolest month — highs around 19°C, almost no rain, and that thin highland air feels sharp and clean. Fiestas de Quito preparations begin stirring, and the clear skies make this the best month for volcano-viewing and highland trekking. Tourist numbers tick up with Northern Hemisphere summer travelers. Bundle up for mornings at the Equator line — it's not warm up here.",
    8: "Dry season continues with near-zero rainfall and pleasant 20°C days, though the high-altitude sun is fierce — sunscreen at 2,800m is not optional. The Avenue of Volcanoes is at peak visibility and Cotopaxi treks are in prime condition. Crowds are at their busiest as international visitors and domestic holidaymakers converge. Book highland lodges and Galápagos connections well ahead.",
    9: "Still dry and clear with 21°C highs — arguably the warmest month — and the equatorial sun pounding through thin atmosphere. The highlands are golden-brown and dramatic, perfect for photography along the Panamericana. Fiesta de la Mama Negra in nearby Latacunga (late September) is a wild, colorful celebration worth the day trip. Tourist crowds begin easing.",
    10: "The rains return tentatively with afternoon showers resuming, but mornings stay clear and pleasant at 20°C. The páramo begins greening again and hummingbird activity in Mindo's cloud forests explodes. A smart shoulder month: fewer tourists, fair prices, and enough dry weather to enjoy the colonial center and day trips. Pack a compact umbrella and layers.",
    11: "Wet season builds with regular afternoon downpours and occasionally gloomy mornings, but 20°C temps keep things comfortable. Día de los Difuntos (Day of the Dead, November 2) brings beautiful cemetery vigils and the traditional colada morada drink paired with guaguas de pan. The cloud forests are dripping and magical, and tourist numbers stay low.",
    12: "Fiestas de Quito (December 6) transforms the city into a week-long party — bullfights, street parades, and chivas (party buses) rumbling through the night. The weather is wet but mild at 20°C, and the colonial center is festively lit. Holiday crowds build toward Christmas and New Year, pushing prices up, but the city's energy is infectious. Don't miss the roast pork and hot canela.",
  },

  'ee-tallinn': {
    1: "Tallinn in January is dark, cold, and hauntingly beautiful — temperatures average -4°C, daylight barely stretches past six hours, and the medieval Old Town wears a dusting of snow like a film set. Crowds are essentially nonexistent, meaning you can wander Toompea Castle and Alexander Nevsky Cathedral in solitude. Warm up with glögi (mulled wine) and black bread in a vaulted cellar restaurant.",
    2: "Still firmly in winter's grip at -4°C with short days and frequent snowfall, but the light starts returning — by month's end you're gaining minutes daily. Estonian independence celebrations on February 24 bring flags, concerts, and a patriotic buzz to the Old Town. Cross-country skiing in Lahemaa National Park is excellent, and the frozen-over harbors have a stark Nordic beauty.",
    3: "The great thaw begins: temperatures climb toward 2°C, snow turns to slush, and daylight pushes past eleven hours. It's not pretty — the transitional mud season is Tallinn's least photogenic — but the Old Town's medieval taverns and craft beer scene provide excellent shelter. Crowds remain very thin and prices stay low. By late March, the first hints of spring reach the Kadriorg Park gardens.",
    4: "Spring arrives with real conviction — 10°C highs, twelve-plus hours of daylight, and the parks around Kadriorg Palace bursting into bloom. The Old Town shakes off its winter hibernation as café terraces open and ferry services to Helsinki ramp up. A great month for walking the city walls and exploring the Telliskivi Creative City without summer crowds. Pack layers for the Baltic wind.",
    5: "May is genuinely lovely: 16°C days, 17 hours of light, and Tallinn's Old Town glowing in that long Nordic golden hour. The Song Festival Grounds come alive with spring concerts, and the coastal trails around Pirita Beach are perfect for walking. Tourist numbers are still moderate, restaurant terraces are buzzing, and you can island-hop to Naissaar without booking a week ahead.",
    6: "Near-endless light (19 hours of it), 19°C days, and Tallinn at its most vibrant — the Midsummer's Eve (Jaanipäev) celebrations on June 23-24 are a wild bonfire-and-beer affair across the country. The Old Town is busy but not yet peak-packed, and the Baltic Sea warms enough for the brave to dip at Pirita. Outdoor dining in Town Hall Square is at its best, and day trips to Lahemaa are superb.",
    7: "Peak summer: 22°C highs, nearly 19 hours of daylight, and the Old Town humming with cruise-ship visitors by day. The Baltic hits a swimmable 19°C (by local standards, that's tropical), and Tallinn's beach bars at Stroomi are surprisingly lively. Crowds are at their highest but the long evenings mean you can wait them out — the Old Town at 10pm in golden light with no one around is worth the patience.",
    8: "Still warm at 21°C with long days, though the light starts noticeably fading toward month's end — a bittersweet reminder that Baltic summers are precious. The Birgitta Festival brings open-air opera and theater to the medieval convent ruins, and the forest mushroom and berry season begins in Lahemaa. Crowds thin slightly from July's peak, making this a pragmatic alternative.",
    9: "Autumn arrives swiftly: 15°C days, rapidly shortening light, and the forests around Tallinn and Lahemaa turning gold and russet. The cruise ships depart and the Old Town quiets down to a pleasant bustle. This is prime season for the food scene — wild mushrooms, game, and root vegetables dominate menus. Pack a rain jacket; September showers are regular but rarely all-day.",
    10: "The Baltic autumn deepens with 9°C days, grey skies, and the Old Town taking on a moody, medieval atmosphere that feels more authentic than any summer postcard. Tallinn Black Nights Film Festival preparations begin, and the Kadriorg art museums are perfect rainy-day havens. Crowds are low, prices drop, and you can feel the city settling into its contemplative winter rhythm.",
    11: "November is Tallinn at its darkest and quietest — barely eight hours of pale light, temperatures around 3°C, and the first snow often arriving mid-month. The Black Nights Film Festival (PÖFF) is northern Europe's biggest, screening hundreds of films across the city. Christmas market preparations begin in Town Hall Square by month's end. This is a city best experienced through warm interiors, candlelight, and strong coffee.",
    12: "Tallinn's medieval Christmas market in Town Hall Square is the main event — a genuine fairy tale of twinkling lights, mulled wine, handmade crafts, and gingerbread against a Gothic backdrop. Temperatures hover around -1°C and snow often cooperates with the aesthetic. Holiday crowds are moderate and festive, and the Old Town's vaulted restaurants serve up hearty Estonian winter fare. One of Europe's most atmospheric Christmas destinations, full stop.",
  },

  'eg-cairo-nile': {
    1: "Cairo's coolest month and a perfect window for the Pyramids — 19°C highs, low humidity, and clear skies mean you can actually enjoy Giza without melting. Crowds are moderate (post-holiday dip) and the Egyptian Museum is navigable without the summer crush. Evenings dip to 9°C, so bring a jacket for felucca rides on the Nile at sunset. Rain is virtually nonexistent.",
    2: "Still pleasant at 21°C with that crisp desert air that makes pyramid-gazing a genuine pleasure rather than a survival exercise. Occasional khamsin sandstorms can blow in but they're rare this early. Tourist crowds are low-to-moderate, making this an excellent month for exploring Islamic Cairo's mosques and the Khan el-Khalili bazaar without the elbow wars. Nile cruise prices are reasonable.",
    3: "Spring arrives and temperatures climb to 24°C — still comfortable for sightseeing but the khamsin winds become more likely, occasionally turning the sky a dramatic amber. Sham el-Nessim (spring festival) falls here or in April, filling parks with picnicking families and feseekh (fermented fish — an acquired taste). Crowds build slightly but remain manageable. Good balance of weather and value.",
    4: "Warming to 28°C and the khamsin season peaks — hot, sand-laden winds can ground plans for a day or two, so build flexibility into your itinerary. Between storms, the weather is glorious for exploring Coptic Cairo and the Citadel. Ramadan often overlaps (check dates), transforming the city's nights into lively iftar feasts and lantern-lit streets. Crowds moderate and thinning.",
    5: "The heat arrives in earnest: 33°C highs and almost zero rain, signaling the end of comfortable outdoor sightseeing past midday. Smart travelers hit the Pyramids at dawn and retreat to air-conditioned museums by noon. The Nile is calm and felucca rides at sunset remain gorgeous if you hydrate aggressively. Tourist numbers drop as the heat discourages casual visitors — prices soften accordingly.",
    6: "Summer grips Cairo at 36°C with relentless sun and bone-dry air — the Pyramids shimmer in the heat haze and midday exploration is genuinely inadvisable. But the city doesn't stop: the Khan el-Khalili comes alive at night, Nile dinner cruises offer breeze and relief, and air-conditioned museums become your best friends. Crowds are at yearly lows, so you'll have Saqqara practically to yourself.",
    7: "Peak heat at 36°C with humidity creeping up from the Delta — Cairo is not messing around, and neither should your hydration strategy. The upside: rock-bottom prices, empty monuments, and the city's nocturnal character at its most authentic, with street cafés buzzing until 2am. Sunrise visits to Giza are magical in the golden light before the furnace kicks in. Not for the faint of heart, but deeply rewarding.",
    8: "Still scorching at 35°C and the most humid month as Nile flood season (now controlled by the Aswan Dam) historically peaked. The heat thins tourist ranks to their lowest, meaning genuine solitude at major sites. Evening feluicca rides catch a Delta breeze that makes the Nile feel almost pleasant. Budget travelers take note: this is Cairo at its most affordable, if you can handle the sweat.",
    9: "The heat starts its slow retreat — 33°C is still hot but the worst is past, and the light turns warmer and more photogenic. Tourist numbers begin trickling back and Nile cruise operators start their peak-season schedules. Evenings cool enough for comfortable walks through Islamic Cairo's lantern-lit alleyways. The date harvest is underway, filling markets with fresh, caramel-sweet fruit.",
    10: "October hits the sweet spot: 29°C highs, virtually no rain, comfortable humidity, and the Pyramids bathed in that perfect autumn-desert light. Tourist season ramps up (moderate-to-busy) and Nile cruise prices climb accordingly. This is when Cairo reminds you why it's been drawing travelers for millennia — the weather cooperates, the monuments awe, and a koshary from a street cart tastes like victory.",
    11: "Excellent sightseeing weather at 24°C with cool evenings and minimal humidity — you can spend a full day at Giza without wilting. High season builds and Nile cruises fill up, so book ahead for Luxor itineraries. The Egyptian Museum and new Grand Egyptian Museum are comfortably busy but not overwhelming. This is arguably Cairo's finest month: the heat is gone, the crowds haven't peaked, and the sunsets over the Nile are extraordinary.",
    12: "Peak tourist season meets perfect weather — 20°C days, 10°C nights, and skies so clear the Pyramids look Photoshopped. Crowds are at their highest, particularly around Christmas and New Year, so expect queues at Giza and premium prices on Nile cruises. But the atmosphere is electric, holiday lights twinkle along the Corniche, and there's a festive energy in the bazaars. Book everything early and bundle up for those surprisingly chilly desert evenings.",
  },

  'eg-luxor-upper': {
    1: "Luxor at its absolute best: 23°C days, cool nights around 8°C, and that crystalline Upper Egypt light illuminating the Valley of the Kings like a spotlight. Peak tourist season means queues at Karnak and Hatshepsut's temple, but the weather justifies every minute of waiting. Hot-air balloon rides over the West Bank at dawn are transcendent — book days ahead. Nile felucca rides at sunset are the perfect nightcap.",
    2: "Still prime season with 25°C highs and virtually zero rain — you could plan an outdoor itinerary with complete confidence. Crowds remain high but slightly less frantic than January, and the early wildflowers along the Nile banks add unexpected softness to the monumental landscape. The West Bank tombs are comfortable to explore without the summer oven effect, and evening temperatures around 10°C are perfect for dining riverside.",
    3: "Temperatures push to 29°C and the first whispers of heat arrive, though it's still perfectly manageable for full days of temple-hopping. The occasional khamsin wind can blow gritty air through the valley — sunglasses and a scarf are wise. Tourist crowds ease from peak levels, giving you breathing room at Luxor Temple and the Colossi of Memnon. Felucca prices are negotiable and the light for photography is magnificent.",
    4: "It's warming fast — 34°C highs signal that summer is coming, but mornings and late afternoons remain excellent for exploring the monuments. Ramadan sometimes overlaps, which means quieter daytime streets and magical iftar evenings by the Nile. Crowds thin noticeably and prices drop, making this a value-conscious traveler's window before the heat becomes prohibitive. Drink water like it's your job.",
    5: "The heat becomes serious at 38°C — the Valley of the Kings lives up to its oven reputation, and midday tomb visits are genuinely uncomfortable. Dawn balloon rides and early-morning temple visits become essential strategy, with afternoons best spent in your hotel pool or the air-conditioned Luxor Museum. Tourist numbers drop sharply and so do prices, rewarding those with heat tolerance.",
    6: "Full desert summer at 41°C — Luxor is one of the hottest inhabited places on Earth this month, and the monuments bake in white-hot light. Only the most dedicated (or budget-conscious) visit now, finding the temples virtually empty and prices at their lowest. Stick to pre-dawn and post-sunset excursions, and treat any air-conditioned space as a sacred refuge. The Nile at night offers the only real relief.",
    7: "Peak heat at 41°C with highs occasionally touching 45°C — this is truly extreme, and the Valley of the Kings feels like walking into an oven, which it basically is. Tourist infrastructure keeps running (the locals are used to it) and you'll have Karnak's hypostyle hall entirely to yourself, which is genuinely awe-inspiring. Budget accommodation is at rock-bottom. For heat warriors only.",
    8: "Still blistering at 40°C but humidity ticks up slightly, adding a sticky dimension to the relentless heat. The Nile is at its highest level and felucca rides offer the best breeze you'll find. Balloon rides operate at the very earliest dawn to beat the thermals. If you can handle the conditions, the solitude at major sites borders on surreal — imagine having Hatshepsut's temple to yourself at sunrise.",
    9: "The heat begins its long retreat but 37°C is still formidable, and the season hasn't quite turned yet for most tourists. Smart early risers can enjoy comfortable mornings at the temples before noon turns oppressive. Tour operators are gearing up for high season, and you'll find increasing availability of Nile cruise departures. Prices remain favorable and the autumn light starts developing that rich golden quality.",
    10: "A turning point: 33°C is hot but workable, tourist numbers ramp up, and Nile cruises between Luxor and Aswan hit their stride. The Valley of the Kings becomes genuinely pleasant for morning visits, and Karnak at sunset returns to its atmospheric best. Balloon rides are in prime season with stable morning air. This is the month that balances good weather, manageable crowds, and reasonable prices.",
    11: "The golden window reopens: 27°C highs, crystalline air, and the full Luxor experience without summer's brutality. High season is building fast and Nile cruises sell out — book weeks ahead. The West Bank tombs are comfortable all day, the Sound and Light show at Karnak hits different in cool evening air, and the date palms along the Nile are heavy with fruit. One of the best months to visit Upper Egypt.",
    12: "Peak season at its peak: 23°C perfection, maximum crowds, and Nile cruise prices at their highest. Every monument is busy, balloon rides book out days in advance, and the West Bank buzzes from dawn to dusk. But the weather is so flawless — cool, clear, and golden — that it's hard to argue with the masses. Christmas and New Year bring a festive energy to the Corniche, and watching the sunset over Thebes from a felucca is timeless.",
  },

  'eg-red-sea': {
    1: "Winter on the Red Sea means 22°C air, 22°C water, and crystal visibility for diving — Hurghada and Marsa Alam are at their most pleasant for reef exploration without the summer scorch. Winds can be brisk (kitesurfers rejoice at El Gouna), and evenings cool to 12°C, so pack a windbreaker for boat trips. Moderate crowds and reasonable resort prices make this a solid escape from European winter.",
    2: "Still the sweet season: 23°C air, calm seas most days, and the reefs at Elphinstone and the Brothers Islands teeming with life including the occasional oceanic whitetip shark. Visibility is outstanding at 30m+ and water temps hold at 22°C — comfortable with a 3mm wetsuit. Crowds are moderate, wind is manageable, and the desert coastline glows amber at sunset.",
    3: "Spring creeps in at 25°C with lengthening days and the sea warming to 23°C — the diving is consistently excellent and snorkeling at Abu Dabbab reveals dugongs and turtles. Winds start mellowing, making liveaboard trips to the southern reefs smoother. Tourist numbers are building from the European spring-break crowd but the coast is long enough to absorb them without feeling cramped.",
    4: "The golden shoulder season: 28°C air, 24°C water, and that perfect intersection of warm-enough and not-yet-hot. Kitesurfing at Soma Bay and El Gouna is in prime condition with consistent thermal winds. Diving visibility remains excellent and the reefs are alive with spawning activity. Crowds are moderate and prices haven't yet hit summer peaks — arguably the best overall month for the Red Sea.",
    5: "Proper heat arrives at 32°C but the sea breeze keeps the coast tolerable, and water temperatures climb to a lovely 25°C. Diving conditions are superb with manta rays appearing at the southern sites and reef fish in full breeding colors. The beaches get busier as European tourists arrive in force, but the underwater world remains uncrowded. Sunscreen is now a survival tool, not an accessory.",
    6: "Summer kicks in hard — 35°C air and relentless sun, though the 27°C sea offers genuine relief. This is peak season for European package tourists and resorts fill up, particularly in Hurghada and Sharm-adjacent areas. Diving is excellent (hammerheads at the Brothers, dolphins at Sataya Reef) but surface intervals on boats can be sweltering. Book liveaboards well ahead and hydrate constantly.",
    7: "The hottest stretch at 37°C — the desert coast doesn't pretend otherwise. The sea hits 28°C and feels like a warm bath, which is either delightful or disappointing depending on your expectations. Peak crowds and peak prices at the resorts, but the underwater realm is spectacular with whale sharks occasionally passing through the Strait of Tiran. Dive before 10am, siesta through midday, repeat.",
    8: "Still peak heat at 36°C and peak tourism — every resort pool is claimed by 9am and the reefs host more divers than usual. But the Red Sea delivers regardless: 28°C water, visibility rarely dropping below 20m, and the marine biodiversity that makes this one of the world's great dive destinations. Night diving at the house reefs is a revelation in the warm water. Budget for premium pricing.",
    9: "The heat eases to 34°C and the summer crowds begin thinning — smart timing for divers who want the warm 27°C seas without fighting for boat spots. Oceanic whitetip sharks return to the deeper sites, and the reef fish are in peak numbers post-summer breeding. Kitesurfing conditions improve as thermal winds strengthen. Prices start softening and availability opens up at the better liveaboard operators.",
    10: "October is the insider's month: 30°C air, 26°C sea, diminishing crowds, and the diving at its absolute peak with mantas, oceanic whitetips, and hammerheads all active at the southern sites. Visibility is exceptional and the winds are calm enough for smooth liveaboard crossings. Prices are firmly shoulder-season, making this arguably the best value-to-experience ratio on the Red Sea calendar.",
    11: "The coast cools to a pleasant 26°C with water at 25°C — still excellent for diving and snorkeling without the summer broil. Crowds are low-to-moderate and resort prices drop noticeably. The reefs are in superb condition and the calmer seas make boat trips comfortable. This is prime time for Marsa Alam's dugong encounters and Elphinstone's shark action. Pack a light wetsuit for the cooling water.",
    12: "Winter divers arrive: 23°C air, 23°C water, and that desert-coast clarity that makes the Red Sea famous. Holiday crowds push prices up around Christmas and New Year, but otherwise December is quiet and excellent. Winds can be gusty (great for kitesurfing, less great for snorkeling), and evenings are genuinely cool at 14°C. A fantastic warm-winter escape with world-class reefs just off the beach.",
  },

  'eg-sinai': {
    1: "Sinai in January is crisp and spectacular — Dahab sits at a pleasant 21°C while the mountains around St. Catherine's can drop below freezing at night, occasionally dusting the peaks with snow. The Blue Hole is at its clearest for freediving, and Bedouin camps in the interior are uncrowded and atmospheric. Sunrise from Mount Sinai is magical (and genuinely cold — bring everything warm you own).",
    2: "Still cool and dry with 22°C days on the coast and cold desert nights inland — perfect for hiking the colored canyons near Nuweiba and the trails around St. Catherine's Monastery. Diving in the Strait of Tiran is excellent with 25m+ visibility and 21°C water. Tourist numbers are low, giving the Dahab waterfront a laid-back, locals-only vibe. The wildflower season in Wadi Feiran can surprise.",
    3: "Spring warmth arrives with 25°C coastal days and the Sinai's stark desert landscape softening with rare wildflowers after any winter rain. Dahab's dive sites are in prime condition and the water warms to 22°C. Rock climbing season at Wadi Rum-adjacent crags is excellent in the cooler interior. Crowds begin building from the European spring-break set but capacity is rarely an issue.",
    4: "The sweet spot: 28°C on the coast, dry desert air, and the sea warming to 23°C for comfortable no-wetsuit diving. Ras Mohammed National Park's reef wall is spectacular for both divers and snorkelers. Bedouin-guided treks into the interior are at their most pleasant temperature-wise. Shoulder-season pricing and moderate crowds make this ideal for combining coast and mountains in one trip.",
    5: "Summer announces itself at 32°C — still manageable on the coast where the sea breeze helps, but interior desert hiking becomes a morning-only affair. The 25°C sea is bathwater-warm and the diving is excellent, with pelagics active around Tiran Island. Dahab fills with a mix of divers, yogis, and digital nomads. This is the last comfortable month for the Mount Sinai sunrise trek before the heat gets serious.",
    6: "Full desert summer at 35°C with zero rain and sun that feels personal — the coast survives on sea breezes and 27°C water, but inland excursions require pre-dawn starts. Freediving at the Blue Hole is at its most popular, and the dive sites are busy with European summer visitors. St. Catherine's remains relatively cool at altitude but the approach is scorching. Night diving becomes the most comfortable option.",
    7: "Peak heat at 37°C and the coast is packed — Dahab buzzes with international freedivers and backpackers, and the Strait of Tiran boats are full. The sea at 28°C is gloriously warm and the marine life is excellent, but any inland ambitions should be firmly shelved until October. Resort prices peak in Sharm and booking ahead is essential. Drink water, then drink more.",
    8: "Still scorching at 36°C with maximum humidity for the Sinai (which is still low by tropical standards). The coast is the only viable destination — forget the desert interior — but the diving remains superb with warm, clear water and active marine life. The backpacker scene in Dahab is in full swing with nightly beach gatherings. This is budget travel done in flip-flops, provided you can handle the heat.",
    9: "The heat starts loosening its grip at 34°C and the coast empties of summer crowds — a welcome recalibration. The sea holds at 27°C with excellent visibility, and the dive sites feel spacious again. Ras Mohammed is magnificent for snorkeling in the warm, uncrowded water. Inland treks become cautiously possible by late September, and Dahab's vibe shifts back to its bohemian, long-stay character.",
    10: "The return to perfection: 30°C days, 26°C seas, and the interior desert finally accessible again for trekking and Bedouin camping. The colored canyons near Nuweiba glow in the autumn light, and St. Catherine's Monastery is comfortable to visit without the winter chill or summer broil. Crowds are low, prices are fair, and the Red Sea reefs are in peak condition with manta rays at the offshore sites.",
    11: "November is genuinely excellent: 25°C coast days, 24°C water, and the entire Sinai accessible from coast to summit. The Mount Sinai sunrise trek is at its most comfortable, diving conditions are first-rate, and the Bedouin camps in the interior valleys are atmospheric without being freezing. Tourist numbers are low and the pace feels unhurried. Pack a fleece for mountain evenings and enjoy having the peninsula to yourself.",
    12: "Winter chill returns: 22°C on the coast but sub-zero possible at altitude, and the desert nights are genuinely cold. Holiday crowds push up Sharm el-Sheikh prices over Christmas, but Dahab and the interior stay mellow. The diving is crystal-clear with 22°C water, and the stark winter light on the desert mountains is hauntingly beautiful. Mount Sinai at sunrise in December is an experience that rewrites your understanding of cold.",
  },

  'er-eritrea': {
    1: "Dry season in the highlands means Asmara sits at a comfortable 22°C under clear skies — the Art Deco capital is at its most walkable, with the Fiat Tagliero building and Cinema Impero gleaming in the sunshine. The Dahlak Archipelago off the coast is hot but excellent for diving with whale sharks occasionally spotted. Very few tourists visit, giving you genuine exploration-grade solitude.",
    2: "Still bone-dry and pleasant in the highlands at 23°C, with the Italianate architecture of Asmara looking particularly sharp against blue skies. The Red Sea coast heats up to 30°C but the diving around Massawa and the Dahlak Islands remains superb and virtually untouched. You'll encounter almost no other tourists — this is one of Africa's most under-visited destinations, for better and for complicated political worse.",
    3: "The warmest highland month at 24°C before the rains, and Asmara buzzes with café culture — espresso at a Modernist bar feels like stepping into a 1930s Italian film. The coast is heating up toward 33°C but the Red Sea reefs are pristine and completely uncrowded. Eritrea's infrastructure is limited, so plan logistics carefully. The Keren camel market is worth the day trip from Asmara.",
    4: "The belg (small rains) sometimes bring brief afternoon showers to the highlands, though many years stay dry. Temperatures hold at 23°C in Asmara and the countryside begins greening. The coast is hot (34°C) and increasingly humid. Orthodox Easter celebrations are beautiful if they fall this month, with elaborate processions in Asmara's cathedral. Travel permits and logistics require patience.",
    5: "Transitional month — the highlands are warm at 23°C with increasing cloud cover, and the coast is oppressively hot at 36°C. This is the quietest tourism period (not that Eritrea is ever busy). If you're heading to the Danakil Depression on the Ethiopian border, May is one of the less-extreme months, though \"less extreme\" is relative when you're visiting one of the hottest places on Earth.",
    6: "The kremti (main rains) begin in the highlands, bringing afternoon downpours and lush green landscapes — Asmara cools to 21°C and the surrounding hills turn emerald. The coast remains dry and brutally hot at 38°C. Highland hiking is atmospheric but muddy. Independence Day celebrations on May 24 often carry festive energy into early June. Infrastructure challenges intensify in the rain.",
    7: "Peak rainy season in the highlands: daily downpours, muddy roads, and temperatures around 20°C in Asmara. The countryside is stunningly green and the waterfalls in the escarpment valleys are at their most dramatic. The coast bakes at 40°C+ and is essentially off-limits for comfort. This is Eritrea at its most challenging logistically but its most beautiful visually — for the genuinely intrepid only.",
    8: "Still deep in the rains with Asmara at 20°C and regular afternoon showers — the highland plateau is a green tapestry of teff and sorghum fields. The Dahlak coast is at peak heat (40°C) and most visitors avoid it. Asmara's indoor attractions — museums, cinema houses, and those wonderful Italian-Eritrean restaurants — become the focus. Expect slow travel on unpaved roads.",
    9: "The rains taper off in the highlands and the landscape is at maximum green — fields of wildflowers carpet the escarpment and the air feels clean and cool at 22°C. The coast begins cooling to a mere 36°C. This is a beautiful time for highland exploration: the road from Asmara to Massawa through the escarpment is one of Africa's great drives, especially with the post-rain clarity.",
    10: "Dry season returns with 23°C highland days and clear skies — Asmara is at its most photogenic with golden light on those Deco facades. The Red Sea coast becomes tolerable again at 33°C and diving season reopens in the Dahlak Archipelago. Meskel (Finding of the True Cross) celebrations in September/October bring bonfires and dancing to the streets. The best month to attempt a coast-to-highland itinerary.",
    11: "Excellent conditions continue: 22°C in Asmara, dry and clear, with the coast cooling to 30°C and dive conditions improving weekly. The Dahlak Islands are at their most accessible, with calm seas and good visibility. This is arguably the best month to visit Eritrea — weather cooperates across all elevations and the cultural calendar is active. Logistics remain the main challenge, not the climate.",
    12: "The coolest highland month at 20°C with crisp mornings and that luminous dry-season light. Asmara's Christmas (January 7 for Orthodox, December 25 for Catholic) preparations create a unique dual-calendar festive atmosphere. The coast is pleasant at 28°C and the Dahlak reefs offer world-class diving in near-total solitude. If you can navigate the permits and infrastructure, December Eritrea is a genuinely unforgettable experience.",
  },

  'es-andalusia': {
    1: "Andalusia's winter is Mediterranean mild — Seville hits 16°C, Granada 10°C, and the Sierra Nevada is blanketed in ski-worthy snow. Crowds are at their absolute lowest, meaning the Alhambra is actually bookable without six weeks' notice and you can wander Córdoba's Mezquita in near-solitude. Rain is moderate (60mm) but interspersed with brilliant blue-sky days. Tapas bars are cozy, sherry is warming, and flamenco feels most authentic in an intimate winter setting.",
    2: "February nudges toward spring: almond trees bloom across the countryside turning hillsides pink and white, and Seville's orange trees are heavy with fruit. Highs reach 17°C with increasing sunshine, and Carnival in Cádiz is one of Spain's most raucous — think satirical street theater, costumes, and late nights. The Alhambra and Mezquita are blissfully uncrowded. Sierra Nevada skiing remains excellent at higher elevations.",
    3: "Spring announces itself properly: 20°C in Seville, wildflowers carpeting the dehesa grasslands, and Semana Santa (Holy Week) processions building to their dramatic late-March or April climax. If Easter falls in March, Seville and Málaga are transformed by hooded processions, incense, and saetas (spontaneous flamenco singing). Crowds spike during Holy Week but drop back to moderate otherwise. The hiking in the Alpujarras is superb.",
    4: "April is arguably Andalusia's finest month — 23°C in Seville, the Feria de Abril exploding in a week of flamenco dresses, horses, and sherry drinking that borders on Olympic-level. The countryside is carpeted in poppies and wildflowers, and the patios of Córdoba begin their legendary flower displays. Tourist numbers are building but the region absorbs them well. The coast is warm enough for walks but still too cool for serious swimming (16°C).",
    5: "The last month before summer's hammer falls: 27°C in Seville, the Córdoba Patio Festival in full bloom, and the beaches of the Costa de la Luz warming to 18°C. Ronda, the white villages, and the Caminito del Rey hike are all at their most pleasant. Crowds are moderate-to-busy and prices creep up, but you're getting peak-season beauty at shoulder-season rates. The tapas terraces are buzzing every evening.",
    6: "Summer arrives with conviction — Seville hits 33°C and the interior starts its famous slow-roast toward July's extremes. The coast (Málaga, Cádiz) is more bearable at 28°C with sea breezes, and the beaches finally reach a swimmable 20°C. This is when Andalusia splits: the coast thrives while inland cities enter siesta survival mode. Granada's Alhambra at sunset, when the heat breaks, is transcendent. Book evening everything.",
    7: "Seville at 37°C is not for the faint-hearted — locals know to stay indoors until 9pm, and so should you. The coast is your refuge, with Cádiz and Tarifa offering breezy relief at 29°C and the Atlantic a refreshing 21°C. Tarifa is Europe's kitesurfing capital and July's winds are world-class. Tourist numbers peak along the coast while inland empties. The Alhambra's night visits are the civilized way to see it. Gazpacho becomes a food group.",
    8: "Peak heat continues — Córdoba regularly tops 40°C, and the phrase \"but it's a dry heat\" stops being comforting at those numbers. Coastal Andalusia is packed with Spanish and European holidaymakers, and the beaches from Nerja to Zahara buzz until midnight. The Atlantic coast stays windswept and slightly cooler. August 15 (Assumption) brings local fiestas everywhere. This is Andalusia at maximum intensity — scorching, crowded, and somehow still irresistible.",
    9: "The great exhale: temperatures ease to 32°C inland and 27°C on the coast, crowds thin dramatically after mid-month, and the Mediterranean warms to a lovely 22°C (its annual peak). This is the smart traveler's summer — genuinely warm, swimmable seas, and the Alhambra bookable again. The grape harvest is underway in Jerez, sherry bodegas are in full production swing, and the quality of light for photographing white villages is extraordinary.",
    10: "October is golden Andalusia: 25°C, minimal rain early on, and the countryside awash in amber light. The olive harvest begins in the hills around Jaén, and fresh-pressed aceite nuevo (new oil) starts appearing at restaurants — drizzled on bread, it's liquid gold. Crowds drop to low-moderate, the coast is still swimmable at 20°C, and the cultural calendar features flamenco festivals in Jerez. One of the most underrated months.",
    11: "Autumn deepens with 19°C days, increasing rain (60mm), and the Andalusian countryside at its most dramatic — storm light over Ronda's gorge, misty mornings in the Alpujarras. The Alhambra and Mezquita are quiet enough for contemplation, and the tapas bars shift to hearty stews and roasted chestnuts. Sierra Nevada skiing opens toward month's end. Budget-friendly with genuine atmosphere.",
    12: "December is festive Andalusia: Seville's Christmas lights are among Spain's best, Málaga's Calle Larios becomes a light tunnel, and the holiday markets sell turrón and polvorones. Temperatures hold at a pleasant 16°C, rain is moderate, and the vibe is warmly local — this isn't a tourist month, it's a lived-in one. The Alhambra in winter light, nearly empty, is an entirely different experience than the summer crush. New Year's Eve in any plaza, eating twelve grapes at midnight, is pure Spain.",
  },

  'es-balearic': {
    1: "The Balearics in January are hibernating — Mallorca sits at a cool 15°C with regular rain, Ibiza's clubs are shuttered, and Menorca is wind-scoured and nearly empty. But Palma de Mallorca stays lively year-round, with excellent galleries, the cathedral lit by the winter solstice light phenomenon, and ensaïmadas fresh from the bakery. Rock-bottom prices and no queues anywhere — ideal for hikers tackling the Serra de Tramuntana without the heat.",
    2: "The almond trees bloom across Mallorca in February, carpeting the valleys in pale pink — one of the Mediterranean's most underrated natural spectacles. Temps hover at 15°C with improving sunshine, and the hiking along the Tramuntana is superb. Ibiza and Formentera remain deep in off-season slumber, but Palma's restaurant scene doesn't miss a beat. Carnival brings a brief burst of costumed energy to the streets.",
    3: "Spring arrives tentatively: 17°C, longer days, and the wild herbs on the hillsides releasing that unmistakable Mediterranean scent. The cycling season kicks off in earnest as professional teams arrive in Mallorca for training camps — the roads through the Tramuntana are a cyclist's paradise. Tourist numbers begin climbing but beaches remain quiet, and Menorca's prehistoric talayotic sites are wonderfully uncrowded.",
    4: "April is the Balearics at their most charming — 20°C, wildflowers everywhere, and the sea warming to a brisk 16°C (swimmable for the brave). Semana Santa processions in Palma are atmospheric, and the restaurants begin opening terraces. Ibiza starts its slow awakening with early-season club openings and quiet cala (cove) explorations. Mallorca's interior is lush and green — rent a car and get lost in the olive groves.",
    5: "The real season begins: 23°C, 10 hours of sunshine, and the sea hitting 18°C — warm enough for a proper swim without the gasp. Ibiza's beach clubs open, Formentera's turquoise waters are stunning without July's boat traffic, and Mallorca's calas are swimmable and uncrowded. Prices are reasonable, flights are frequent, and you get 90% of summer's beauty at half the intensity. The locals call this the best month, and they're right.",
    6: "Summer proper: 28°C, near-zero rain, and the Mediterranean climbing to a lovely 22°C. Ibiza's club season is in full swing and the party-island reputation comes roaring to life, while Mallorca and Menorca offer a more refined alternative with excellent beach days and sailing conditions. Crowds are building fast — book the popular calas and restaurants ahead. Paella by the sea with a cold hierbas ibicencas is peak Balearic living.",
    7: "Peak season hits: 31°C, wall-to-wall sunshine, and every cala, club, and chiringuito operating at maximum capacity. The sea is a divine 25°C and the sailing is superb with reliable afternoon thermals. Ibiza is at full throttle — superclubs, sunset at Café del Mar, boat parties — and Mallorca's coast is busy from Alcúdia to Cala d'Or. Prices are at their highest and booking anything last-minute is a fantasy. Come prepared to pay and to share paradise.",
    8: "August matches July's heat (31°C) and adds the August exodus — half of Spain decamps to the Balearics, and the islands feel it. Every beach has a reservation system, every restaurant a wait, and the ferries between islands are sold out weeks ahead. But the water is at its warmest (26°C), the nightlife peaks, and the long Mediterranean evenings are genuinely magical. Formentera's beaches, even crowded, remain some of Europe's finest.",
    9: "The sweet September pivot: 28°C air, 25°C sea (still bathwater), and the crowds melting away after the first week like a spell breaking. Ibiza's closing parties mark the end of club season with legendary final sets, while Mallorca and Menorca shift to a mellow, golden-light mode that's ideal for cycling, sailing, and long lunches. Prices drop, availability opens, and the vibe is decidedly grown-up. The best month for most visitors.",
    10: "October extends the summer dream — still 23°C, the sea holds at 22°C, and you can swim comfortably through mid-month. Ibiza goes quiet and soulful, revealing the rural interior and quiet northern beaches that the party season hides. Mallorca's wine harvest brings new vintages and vineyard tours, and the hiking through the Tramuntana is back in prime condition. Rain returns tentatively but rarely ruins a day. Outstanding value.",
    11: "The islands wind down: 18°C, increasing rain, and most beach infrastructure closing for the winter. But Palma thrives year-round, and November's restaurant scene is excellent — fewer tourists means better tables and chef's attention. Menorca goes very quiet but atmospheric, and Mallorca's mountain towns feel genuinely local. Olive oil season is in full swing, and the markets overflow with seasonal produce. A contemplative, food-focused month.",
    12: "December brings cozy Mediterranean winter: 15°C, occasional rain, and Christmas markets in Palma's old town. Ibiza and Formentera are effectively closed, but Mallorca maintains a warm hospitality scene with festive lights along the Passeig des Born and excellent holiday dining. The Tramuntana mountains can see snow at the highest peaks, and the absence of crowds gives the island a peaceful, village-life rhythm. Midnight mass in Palma's cathedral is genuinely special.",
  },

  'es-barcelona': {
    1: "Barcelona in January is the city without the queue — 13°C, minimal rain, and the Sagrada Família visible from inside without a three-month advance booking. The Barri Gòtic is atmospheric in the cool air, and the city's food markets (Boqueria, Santa Caterina) are buzzing with locals rather than tourists. Pack layers for the Montjuïc winds and settle in for a calçotada (grilled spring onion feast) if you catch the early season.",
    2: "Winter loosens its grip: 14°C with more sunshine, and Barcelona's outdoor terraces start reopening optimistically. Carnival brings costume parades to the Raval, and the calçot season hits peak form — day-trip to a farmhouse outside the city for the full smoky-onion-and-romesco experience. The sea at 13°C is for looking only, but the seafront promenade walk from Barceloneta to the Forum is brisk and beautiful.",
    3: "Spring creeps in at 16°C and the city's energy lifts noticeably — Gaudí's buildings start glowing in the strengthening sun, and the Eixample's leafy boulevards come alive. Tourist numbers build toward moderate as European weekenders arrive, but nothing compared to summer. This is an excellent museum month: MACBA, Fundació Miró, and the Picasso Museum without the summer crush. Rain is moderate but rarely all-day.",
    4: "April is Barcelona done right: 19°C, nine hours of sunshine, and a Sant Jordi's Day (April 23) celebration that fills the Ramblas with books and roses in one of Europe's most charming traditions. The beaches are too cool for swimming (15°C) but perfect for walking, and Park Güell is manageable without the summer mob. Restaurant terraces are in full swing and the cava flows freely. Smart visitors know this is the move.",
    5: "The city hits its stride at 22°C with long, warm evenings that make every chiringuito on Barceloneta feel like the right call. The sea warms to 17°C — bold swimmers only — and the Primavera Sound festival brings world-class music to the Parc del Fòrum. Crowds are building to busy but haven't peaked, and the light on the Sagrada Família's facades at golden hour is extraordinary. Vermouth hour on a terrace in Gràcia is essential.",
    6: "Summer begins: 26°C, 11 hours of sunshine, and the city fully pivoting to beach mode. Barceloneta fills up, the chiringuitos are packed until midnight, and the sea finally reaches a swimmable 21°C. Sonar music festival mid-month adds an electronic edge to the city's already buzzing nightlife. Tourist numbers are high but the city's scale absorbs them. Book La Boqueria visits early morning and the Sagrada Família well in advance.",
    7: "Peak Barcelona: 30°C, tourists everywhere, and the Mediterranean at a gorgeous 24°C that makes you forgive every queue. The beaches are packed from morning to night, the Ramblas becomes a slow-moving river of humanity, and the Barri Gòtic's narrow streets offer welcome shade. Festes de Gràcia in late July or August deck out streets with competitive artistic installations. Hydrate, book ahead, and embrace the Mediterranean summer at full volume.",
    8: "The hottest month at 30°C with occasional humid spells, and the city divided between tourists filling the center and locals fleeing to Costa Brava villages. Festes de Gràcia (if in early August) is a neighborhood party worth rearranging your trip for. The sea at 25°C is perfection, and night swimming at Barceloneta is a local ritual. The Assumption (August 15) empties some local businesses. Expect peak pricing and book restaurants.",
    9: "The golden month: still 27°C, the sea at its warmest (25°C), but the crowds dropping noticeably after the first week. La Mercè festival (around September 24) is Barcelona's biggest party — human towers (castellers), fire runs (correfocs), and free concerts everywhere. The light is soft and warm, restaurant terraces feel spacious again, and you can actually enjoy the Sagrada Família without feeling herded. Arguably the best month to visit.",
    10: "Autumn Barcelona is deeply appealing: 22°C, the trees along Passeig de Gràcia turning gold, and the sea still holdng at 21°C for late-season swims. Tourist numbers drop to moderate, prices soften, and the food scene shifts to mushroom season — rovellons and other wild fungi dominate market stalls and menus. Rain increases but comes in Mediterranean bursts, not all-day drizzle. The city feels like it belongs to the locals again.",
    11: "November brings the first properly cool air at 16°C and the seasonal shift to cozy mode — think thick hot chocolate at Granja Viader, vermut in El Born, and uncrowded gallery-hopping. The sea is 17°C (wetsuit territory), and the beaches empty out to a few hardy joggers. Prices are favorable, the Sagrada Família is bookable same-week, and the city's Modernista architecture looks stunning against moody autumn skies.",
    12: "December Barcelona is festively Catalan: the Fira de Santa Llúcia Christmas market fills the cathedral square with nativity figurines (including the cheerfully irreverent caganer), and the city sparkles with lights. Temperatures are a mild 13°C with occasional rain, and the holiday atmosphere is warm without the tourist crush. New Year's Eve on the Magic Fountain of Montjuïc is a free spectacular. Cava and turrones keep the chill at bay.",
  },

  'es-basque': {
    1: "The Basque Country in January is moody, wet, and wonderfully uncrowded — San Sebastián sits at 10°C with 130mm of rain, but the pintxos bars in the Parte Vieja are steamy, packed with locals, and serving some of Spain's best food at every price point. The surf at Mundaka and Zarautz is at its most powerful (experienced surfers only), and the green hills are lush from the rain. Txakoli wine tastes better when it's grey outside.",
    2: "Still wet and grey at 11°C, but February brings the extraordinary Tamborrada — San Sebastián's 24-hour drumming festival that fills every street with noise, costumes, and civic pride. The Basque mountains are occasionally snow-dusted and the hiking trails are quiet and atmospheric. Bilbao's Guggenheim is a perfect rainy-day destination, and the cider houses (sagardotegiak) open for their legendary txotx season of pouring straight from the barrel.",
    3: "The cider house season is in full swing — txotx runs from January to April, and March is prime time for the communal dinners of salt cod, steak, and unlimited cider poured from height. Temperatures reach 14°C with rain still frequent but less persistent. The countryside begins greening, Bilbao's riverside walks are pleasant between showers, and San Sebastián's Concha beach looks dramatic under spring storms. Still very few tourists.",
    4: "Spring properly arrives: 16°C, longer days, and the Basque hills exploding in wildflowers and new-growth green. Semana Santa is celebrated with atmospheric processions, and the pintxos bars shift toward lighter seasonal ingredients. Surf conditions at Mundaka are still solid, the coast is walkable and empty, and you can snag a table at a Michelin-starred restaurant without the summer waitlist. Rain persists but sunshine increases noticeably.",
    5: "May is when the Basque Country starts showing off — 19°C, increasing sunshine, and the countryside at its most impossibly green. San Sebastián's beaches warm enough for walking but not swimming (15°C), and the coastal Camino de Santiago path is in prime hiking condition. The pintxos scene is at its seasonal best with fresh anchovies, white asparagus, and baby squid. Crowds are still low and every village feels like a local secret.",
    6: "Summer arrives gently: 22°C, the beaches of La Concha and Zurriola filling with sunbathers, and the sea warming to 18°C (refreshing rather than warm). The Basque coast is in its finest form — dramatic cliffs, green headlands, and cove beaches without the Mediterranean crowds. Bilbao buzzes with outdoor dining along the Nervión river, and surf conditions are consistent. Tourist numbers are moderate and the long evenings are perfect for extended pintxos crawls.",
    7: "Peak Basque summer: 25°C, 10 hours of sunshine, and San Sebastián at its most irresistible — Zurriola beach hosts surfers by day and pintxo-hopping revelers by night. The Jazz Festival (mid-July) fills the city with world-class music in outdoor venues. Crowds are at their highest and hotel prices spike, but the weather justifies it — this is one of Europe's most beautiful coastlines in full glory. The sea hits 20°C, which the locals consider bathwater.",
    8: "August matches July's warmth (25°C) and the Semana Grande festivals in both Bilbao and San Sebastián bring fireworks, concerts, and a carnival atmosphere. Every Basque is on holiday and the beaches are packed, but the food scene somehow gets even better — the competition among pintxos bars is fierce and the results are spectacular. Book everything months ahead. The countryside is gorgeous for driving, with every village hosting its own fiesta patronal.",
    9: "September is the insider's Basque Country: 23°C, the crowds evaporating, and the sea still at a pleasant 20°C for swimming. The San Sebastián Film Festival (late September) brings Hollywood glamour to the Belle Époque promenade, and the first autumn mushrooms appear on pintxos menus. Surf conditions are excellent, the hiking trails are empty and golden-lit, and you can actually get a table at Arzak or Mugaritz without a three-month wait.",
    10: "Autumn arrives with rain and atmosphere in equal measure — 18°C, the hills turning russet and gold, and the pintxos bars shifting to hearty seasonal fare: wild mushrooms, game, and cider-braised dishes. The surf is powerful at Mundaka (this is the region's most famous wave) and the beaches are beautifully empty. Crowds are low, Bilbao's Guggenheim feels intimate, and walking the Parte Vieja on a rainy evening with a glass of txakoli is pure contentment.",
    11: "Deep autumn at 14°C with persistent rain and the Basque Country at its moodiest — grey skies, churning surf, and mist-draped mountains. But the food scene is at its winter peak: cider houses reopen, game season is in full swing, and the world's highest concentration of Michelin stars per capita is cooking its most soulful dishes. The Guggenheim hosts major winter exhibitions, and San Sebastián's covered markets are warm, aromatic havens.",
    12: "December is cozy Basque winter: 11°C, wet, and festively lit — San Sebastián's old town twinkles and the food markets overflow with Christmas provisions. Santo Tomás market (December 21) fills the streets with traditional Basque food stalls selling chistorra sausages and txistorra sandwiches. New Year's Eve is celebrated exuberantly, and the pintxos bars are packed with locals in holiday mode. Rain is certain, but so is the warmth indoors.",
  },

  'es-canary': {
    1: "The Canaries in January deliver exactly what winter-weary Europeans need: 21°C, seven hours of sunshine, and a volcanic landscape that feels like another planet. Tenerife's Teide National Park is dusted with snow at the summit while the coast basks in warmth — swimming in the Atlantic at 19°C is genuinely possible. Carnival preparations are underway, and the hiking in La Gomera's laurel forests is lush from winter rains. Peak European escape season means moderate-to-busy crowds.",
    2: "February brings the main event: Carnival. Santa Cruz de Tenerife and Las Palmas host celebrations that rival Rio — think elaborate costumes, samba rhythms, and a week of parties that make the islands feel deliriously festive. Weather holds at 21°C with the best whale-watching season offshore (pilot whales and occasional blue whales). The almond trees bloom on Gran Canaria's highlands, adding pink to the volcanic palette.",
    3: "Spring transition at 22°C with decreasing rain and the islands at their greenest — Lanzarote's volcanic landscapes contrast dramatically with pockets of wildflowers, and La Palma's Caldera de Taburiente is lush and magnificent. The sea stays at 19°C (wetsuits for extended swims) and the hiking across all islands is in prime condition. Tourist crowds ease from peak carnival season, offering better prices and availability.",
    4: "Warming to 23°C with excellent visibility for Teide and the inter-island volcanoes — this is when the Canaries feel most purely spectacular. The wind picks up on the eastern islands (Lanzarote, Fuerteventura) making them a kitesurfing paradise. The sea warms to 19°C and the beaches are pleasant without the summer crowds. An excellent month for island-hopping with regular inter-island flights and ferries running full schedules.",
    5: "The sweet spot: 24°C, minimal rain, and the trade winds keeping things fresh without the summer heat. Fuerteventura and Lanzarote's beaches are stunning and uncrowded, and the diving off El Hierro (Europe's youngest volcanic island) offers visibility beyond 30m. The hiking on Tenerife's GR-131 trail is comfortable, and the local food scene — papas arrugadas with mojo, fresh fish — tastes best at an uncrowded guachinche.",
    6: "Summer eases in at 26°C — warmer than the eternal-spring months but tempered by the trade winds, especially on northern coasts. The sea climbs to 21°C, genuinely comfortable for swimming, and the beaches start filling with European families. Whale-watching tours are reliable year-round but June's calm seas make for smoother trips. The calima (Saharan dust haze) occasionally blows in, turning the sky orange and pushing temps up sharply for a day or two.",
    7: "Peak European summer brings 28°C to the southern resorts and the busiest beaches of the year, particularly on Tenerife and Gran Canaria. The trade winds keep northern coasts cooler and breezier. The sea is a lovely 22°C and the water sports scene — surfing, windsurfing, diving — is in full swing. Prices peak and booking ahead is essential for the popular resorts. The volcanic highlands offer cooler respite and excellent stargazing (Teide is a world-class dark-sky site).",
    8: "August matches July's heat (28°C) and adds the Spanish August exodus — mainlanders join the international tourists and every resort is at capacity. The beaches from Maspalomas to Los Cristianos are packed, but the diversity of the archipelago means you can always find a quieter cove, especially on La Palma, El Hierro, or La Gomera. The sea peaks at 23°C. Expect maximum prices and book well in advance.",
    9: "September is the clever pick: still 27°C, the sea at its warmest (23°C), but the crowds draining away after the first week. The trade winds calm and the ocean smooths out for the best diving and snorkeling conditions. Fuerteventura's endless beaches feel spacious again, and the sunsets from Tenerife's west coast are extraordinary. Prices drop noticeably and the shoulder-season vibe is relaxed and rewarding.",
    10: "Still warm at 26°C with the sea holding at 23°C — you can swim comfortably all month. Rain starts returning, particularly on the northern (greener) slopes, and the first autumn storms create dramatic light over the volcanic landscapes. Crowds are moderate, prices fair, and the hiking picks up again as the heat eases. The Fiesta del Vino on Tenerife celebrates the grape harvest with tastings and village parties.",
    11: "The eternal spring reasserts itself at 23°C with more rain greening the northern valleys and the southern coasts staying dry and warm. Tourist numbers tick up as winter-sun seekers arrive early, but it's still uncrowded by peak standards. The sea is 21°C and swimming remains viable. This is excellent hiking weather on La Gomera and La Palma, and the stargazing on Teide and Roque de los Muchachos is superb in the clear autumn nights.",
    12: "Christmas in the Canaries means 22°C and sunshine while mainland Europe shivers — it's no wonder the islands fill up over the holidays. Nativity scenes (belenes) pop up across the towns, and New Year's Eve celebrations on the beaches are festively warm. The sea holds at 20°C, whale-watching is reliable, and the festive markets are charming without being overwhelming. Peak holiday pricing applies, but the warmth and light feel like a genuine gift.",
  },

  'es-madrid': {
    1: "Madrid in January is crisp, clear, and culturally firing on all cylinders — 10°C highs under that famous blue Castilian sky, with the Reyes Magos (Three Kings) parade on January 5 filling the Gran Vía with elaborate floats and excited children. The Prado, Reina Sofía, and Thyssen are blissfully uncrowded, and the tapas bars of La Latina are cozy with cocido madrileño (chickpea stew) and good Rioja. Snow sometimes dusts the Sierra de Guadarrama, perfect for a day of skiing just 45 minutes away.",
    2: "Still cold at 12°C with occasional rain, but the sunshine is increasing and Madrid's café terraces start cautiously reopening. Carnival brings costume fun to the streets before Lent settles in, and the cultural calendar is dense with exhibitions and theater. The Rastro flea market on Sunday mornings is less crowded than spring, and a caña (small beer) with jamón ibérico at a bar in Malasaña hits differently when you've earned it walking in the cold.",
    3: "Spring stirs: 16°C, the Retiro's cherry trees hint at blooms, and the city's energy lifts palpably. Semana Santa processions wind through the center if Easter falls early, and the restaurant terraces fill up at the first sign of warmth. Tourist numbers are moderate and building, but you can still snag same-day Prado tickets and walk the Plaza Mayor without a crowd obstacle course. The light in the late afternoon is pure Velázquez gold.",
    4: "Madrid in April is glorious — 19°C, the Retiro Park in full bloom, and outdoor living exploding across every barrio. The terrazas (outdoor bar terraces) become the city's living rooms, and San Isidro festival preparations bring traditional chotis dancing to the streets. The food scene peaks with spring ingredients: artichokes, lamb, and the first strawberries. Crowds are moderate-to-busy but the city's scale keeps things manageable. Walk everywhere — the architecture rewards it.",
    5: "May is peak Madrid: 23°C, the San Isidro festival (mid-May) in full swing with bullfights, concerts, and verbenas (street parties) in the parks. The Retiro is gorgeous, the rooftop bars of Gran Vía are buzzing, and the evening paseo through Sol and Malasaña feels like all of Madrid is out celebrating simply being alive. Tourist numbers are high but the city handles it. The day trips to Toledo, Segovia, and Aranjuez are at their weather-optimal best.",
    6: "Summer announces itself at 30°C — Madrid's continental heat is dry and intense, but the city adapts: life shifts to late evenings, restaurants don't fill until 10pm, and the rooftop pools and terraces become essential. The Prado in air conditioning is a strategic retreat, and the Retiro's shade-dappled paths offer midday respite. Crowds are at their summer peak. The terrazas along Paseo de la Castellana buzz until well past midnight.",
    7: "Madrid bakes at 35°C and the locals who can flee to the coast do exactly that — the city is simultaneously at its emptiest of Madrileños and busiest with tourists. The museums are cool refuges, the public pools (piscinas municipales) are packed, and evening dining al fresco doesn't really start until the sun drops at 10pm. Day-trip to the cool mountains of Guadarrama or the walled city of Ávila for relief. Veranos de la Villa festival brings free concerts to the parks.",
    8: "Peak heat at 35°C and August in Madrid is a study in extremes — many local restaurants and shops close entirely for vacaciones, while tourist-facing businesses thrive. The city has a strange, half-empty quality that's either desolate or liberating depending on your mindset. The summer festival programming continues and the Verbena de la Paloma (August 15) is a beloved neighborhood fiesta in La Latina. By month's end, the first hints of autumn arrive in the evening air.",
    9: "Madrid's renaissance month: 28°C but cooling fast in the evenings, locals returning from vacation, and the cultural season opening with a bang. The terrazas are still glorious, the Retiro turns gold at the edges, and the food scene kicks into high gear with mushroom season and game. Tourist crowds thin after mid-month and the city feels authentically alive rather than performatively so. Arguably Madrid's best-kept secret month.",
    10: "Autumn Madrid is magnificent: 20°C, golden light streaming down the Gran Vía, and the Retiro ablaze with autumn color. The chestnut roasters appear on street corners, the cocido stew returns to menus, and the cultural calendar is dense with art openings and theater premieres. Crowds are moderate, hotel prices are reasonable, and a Sunday morning at the Rastro followed by vermut in La Latina is close to perfect urban living.",
    11: "November settles in at 13°C with shorter days and the first real cold — the city pivots indoors to its exceptional museum, theater, and food scenes. The tapas bars of Lavapiés and Malasaña are at their coziest, and the autumn menu at any good Madrid restaurant features wild mushrooms, roasted peppers, and hearty Castilian fare. Tourist numbers are low and the city feels genuinely local. The Sierra gets its first serious snow.",
    12: "Festive Madrid is a revelation: the Christmas lights along Gran Vía are spectacular, the Plaza Mayor Christmas market sells handmade figurines and sweets, and the Corte Inglés window displays rival any department store in Europe. At 10°C it's cold but not brutal, and the holiday atmosphere is genuinely warm with churros con chocolate at San Ginés and midnight mass at the Almudena Cathedral. New Year's Eve in Puerta del Sol, eating the twelve grapes at midnight, is a Spanish rite of passage.",
  },

  'es-pyrenees': {
    1: "Peak ski season in the Spanish Pyrenees — Baqueira-Beret and Formigal are in prime condition with heavy snow cover, sub-zero temperatures at altitude, and that bright Aragonese sunshine between storms. The valleys are quiet and stunning, and après-ski in the stone villages involves hearty migas, grilled lamb, and local Somontano wines. Crowds are manageable outside school holidays, and the cross-country skiing in the Ordesa valley is world-class.",
    2: "February delivers the deepest snowpack and the best skiing conditions of the year — the resorts are busy during school half-term weeks but otherwise spacious. Temperatures hover around -2°C at resort altitude with long sunny spells between snow dumps. Snowshoeing through the beech forests of Ordesa and Monte Perdido is magical, and the mountain refugios offer warming bowls of aranesa soup. Carnival celebrations add festive energy to the valley towns.",
    3: "Late-season skiing with spring snow — warm days (5°C at altitude) and still-deep coverage, plus the joys of skiing in a t-shirt on sunny afternoons. The days lengthen noticeably and the lower valleys start thawing, revealing waterfalls and the first wildflowers. Tourist numbers ease and ski-pass deals appear. The transition from winter to spring creates dramatic landscapes of snow-capped peaks above green valleys.",
    4: "The mountains transform: snow recedes to higher elevations, the valleys flood with wildflowers, and the hiking season begins in earnest on the lower trails. Temperatures reach 12°C in the valleys with cool, clear air. The Ordesa and Monte Perdido National Park reopens fully, and the waterfalls are at their most powerful with snowmelt. Very few tourists and the mountain villages feel authentically lived-in. Excellent month for bird-watching — lammergeiers and griffon vultures soar over the limestone cliffs.",
    5: "Spring in full glory: 16°C in the valleys, the high meadows carpeted in gentians and orchids, and the hiking trails from easy valley walks to serious GR-11 traverses all in excellent condition. The Pyrenean villages host traditional fiestas, and the food scene revolves around spring lamb, wild herbs, and fresh mountain cheese. Rafting on the snowmelt-swollen Noguera Pallaresa river is thrilling. One of the most beautiful months in the mountains.",
    6: "Summer hiking season opens properly — 22°C in the valleys, the high passes finally clear of snow, and the full GR-11 trans-Pyrenean route becomes viable. Ordesa's Cola de Caballo waterfall trail is magnificent, and the mountain lakes (ibones) are clear enough to swim in (briefly — they're cold). Crowds build around the main national park entrances but the backcountry stays empty. Long days mean you can hike until 9pm in golden light.",
    7: "Peak summer in the Pyrenees: 26°C in the valleys, warm enough for river swimming, and the high mountains at their most accessible. The refugio-to-refugio hiking across the range is in prime condition, and the mountaineering routes on Aneto (the Pyrenees' highest peak) are at their safest. Crowds are at their highest in Ordesa and Aigüestortes, so start hikes early. The village festivals bring traditional music, food, and dance to every hamlet.",
    8: "Still peak season at 26°C with the warmest temperatures and occasional afternoon thunderstorms that roll dramatically across the peaks. The river canyoning in the Sierra de Guara is at its best with warm water and manageable flows. Spanish holidaymakers fill the valleys and the main trails are busy — escape to the less-known Posets-Maladeta or Cadí-Moixeró ranges for solitude. The local cheeses and charcuterie pair perfectly with post-hike wine.",
    9: "The golden month: crowds vanish, the beech and oak forests begin turning amber and gold, and temperatures drop to a pleasant 20°C. The hiking is superb with clear air, cooler temperatures, and the mountain light at its most dramatic. The mushroom season begins in earnest (rovellons and other prized fungi), and the shepherds drive their flocks down from the high pastures in the traditional transhumance. Possibly the best month for serious hikers.",
    10: "Peak autumn color transforms the Pyrenean valleys into a spectacular palette of gold, russet, and crimson — the beech forests of Irati (bordering Navarra) are Europe's second-largest and the autumn display is genuinely world-class. Temperatures drop to 14°C and the first snow dusts the highest peaks. Mushroom foraging is at its peak, and the mountain villages host harvest festivals. Crowds are very low and the mood is contemplative.",
    11: "Winter returns to the heights: the first serious snowfall blankets the peaks, ski resorts begin opening toward month's end, and the valleys are cold (7°C) and atmospheric. The hiking season closes on the higher trails but the lower valleys and gorges remain walkable. This is the quiet interlude between autumn and ski season — village life is slow, the food is hearty, and a bowl of sopa de ajo by a fire feels like the right answer to everything.",
    12: "Ski season opens in earnest with fresh snow, sub-zero nights, and the Pyrenean resorts cranking up for the Christmas holidays. Baqueira-Beret fills with Spanish and French skiers, and the valley towns dress up with Christmas markets and nativity scenes. The food is peak mountain comfort: roasted meats, hearty stews, and local wines by roaring fires. Holiday crowds spike but the atmosphere is festive and warm. The mountains under fresh snow are breathtaking.",
  },

  'et-addis': {
    1: "Dry season in Addis: 23°C highs under blue skies at 2,400m, with Timkat (Epiphany, January 19-20) bringing one of Ethiopia's most spectacular celebrations — thousands gather at Jan Meda for dawn processions and holy water blessings. The Merkato, Africa's largest open-air market, is at its most navigable without the rains. Coffee ceremonies are a daily ritual, and the injera-and-wat scene in the capital is endlessly rewarding. Moderate tourist numbers.",
    2: "Still dry and pleasant at 24°C — arguably the warmest month — with excellent conditions for exploring the Entoto Mountains above the city and day-tripping to the Blue Nile Gorge. The jacaranda trees begin their purple bloom, lining the city's avenues in color. Tourist numbers are moderate and the cultural calendar is active with Orthodox celebrations. The Ethiopian coffee harvest is winding down, so the beans are fresh and the ceremony ubiquitous.",
    3: "The dry season starts yielding to occasional afternoon showers by late March, but conditions are still excellent at 24°C with increasing humidity. The countryside around Addis is turning from brown to green, and the highland markets are full of fresh produce. Ethiopian Easter (Fasika) often falls in April but preparations begin now, and the Orthodox fasting season means outstanding vegetarian food at every buna bet (coffee house).",
    4: "The belg (small rains) bring intermittent afternoon showers, but mornings are typically clear and pleasant at 22°C. Fasika (Ethiopian Easter) usually falls here, climaxing in all-night church vigils and massive post-fast feasting — the kitfo (raw beef) and doro wat (chicken stew) that break the fast are extraordinary. The city is green and lush, and the Entoto eucalyptus forests are atmospheric in the mist. Tourist numbers are low.",
    5: "Transitional month — the rains increase and the city is cooling to 21°C with regular overcast skies. Not the most photogenic time for Addis, but the cultural depth remains: museums like the National Museum (home of Lucy) and the Ethnological Museum at the university are excellent rainy-day options. The food scene is year-round superb and less crowded now. Good prices and genuine local immersion.",
    6: "The kiremt (big rains) begin in earnest with daily downpours, cool 19°C temperatures, and the city's infrastructure occasionally strained by the water. The surrounding hills turn impossibly green and the waterfalls outside the city are gaining force. Tourist numbers drop to their lowest, and the experience becomes deeply local — the coffee ceremonies, the jazz bars in the Piassa district, and the tej (honey wine) houses carry on regardless of weather.",
    7: "Peak rainy season: heavy daily rains, 18°C temps, and the city wrapped in clouds and mist. The countryside is stunningly green but many roads outside Addis become challenging. This is the quietest tourist month, making it ideal for cultural immersion — Addis's music scene (Ethiopian jazz, traditional azmari houses) is vibrant year-round. The food markets are full of fresh highland produce. Pack serious rain gear and flexibility.",
    8: "Still deep in the rains at 18°C with daily downpours, though the end is in sight — by late August the showers begin spacing out. The Entoto hills are draped in wildflowers and the air is the freshest of the year. Tourist numbers begin ticking up in anticipation of the dry-season turn. The tej houses and live-music venues of the Piassa neighborhood are particularly rewarding as shelter from the rain.",
    9: "The rains retreat and Meskel (Finding of the True Cross, September 27) arrives — one of Ethiopia's most visually spectacular celebrations, with massive bonfires lit in Meskel Square and flower-draped processions across the city. Temperatures climb to 21°C and sunshine returns. The countryside is at peak green, covered in Meskel daisies (yellow wildflowers). Tourist season officially begins, and the energy is palpable.",
    10: "Post-rains Addis is magnificent: 23°C, clear skies, and the highlands carpeted in wildflowers. This is the beginning of prime tourist season, with excellent conditions for exploring the capital and launching trips to the historic northern circuit. The Merkato is buzzing, the jazz bars are packed, and the injera is served on fresh, slightly sour perfection. Moderate crowds with good availability at hotels and restaurants.",
    11: "Dry season in full swing: 23°C, blue skies, and the best weather of the year for combining Addis with the northern historic route. Genna (Ethiopian Christmas, January 7) preparations begin in the churches, and the city's cultural institutions are in peak form. The coffee is fresh from the latest harvest, and the ceremony — with roasting, grinding, and three rounds of increasingly lighter brews — is an essential daily ritual.",
    12: "December is excellent: 22°C, dry, and festive — Ethiopian Advent adds a spiritual dimension to the city's already rich cultural life. The Merkato is packed with holiday shoppers, the tej houses are celebratory, and the injera at Addis's top restaurants is arguably the country's best. Tourist numbers climb toward the Christmas peak (January 7), making December a smart window for beating the holiday rush while enjoying peak conditions.",
  },

  'et-lalibela': {
    1: "Peak season at Lalibela and for good reason — 25°C days, dry skies, and the rock-hewn churches in their most dramatic state with sharp shadow play across the carved facades. Timkat (January 19-20) is celebrated with extraordinary intensity here, with white-robed processions and singing that echoes off the ancient stone. Crowds are at their highest and guesthouses book up, so plan well ahead. The surrounding countryside is golden and dry.",
    2: "Still prime visiting conditions: 26°C, clear skies, and the 11 rock-hewn churches comfortable to explore without rain-slicked stone. Tourist numbers ease slightly from the Timkat peak, and you can negotiate better rates at the guesthouses. The surrounding Lasta Mountains are dry but dramatic, with excellent trekking to remote churches and communities. The dawn ceremony at Bet Giyorgis (St. George's) is profoundly beautiful in the clear morning light.",
    3: "Warming to 27°C with the first hints of pre-rain humidity — still excellent for the churches and the surrounding hiking trails. The belg (small rains) sometimes arrive by late March but are typically brief. Tourist numbers are moderate, making this a sweet spot for both value and experience. The Ethiopian Orthodox fasting season means the town's restaurants serve exceptional vegetarian injera platters. The light for photography is superb.",
    4: "The belg rains become more regular with afternoon showers, but mornings are usually clear and the churches remain accessible. Fasika (Ethiopian Easter) brings the town's most intense spiritual celebration — all-night vigils, chanting, and the emotional post-fast feast. At 25°C with lush green surroundings, Lalibela feels alive and sacred in equal measure. Tourist numbers spike briefly for Easter, then drop. A deeply memorable time to visit.",
    5: "Transitional weather: increasing cloud cover and showers at 23°C, but the churches are covered by modern protective roofing and visitable year-round. The surrounding mountains are greening rapidly and the countryside is beautiful for walking. Very few tourists, giving you the remarkable experience of having millennium-old, UNESCO-listed churches virtually to yourself. Some trails may be muddy. Simple, genuine hospitality at its best.",
    6: "The kiremt (big rains) arrive properly with daily downpours and 20°C temperatures — the access roads to remote churches can become muddy and challenging. The main rock-hewn complex in town remains accessible, though the stone can be slippery. The surrounding landscape turns a vivid green that contrasts dramatically with the pink tuff of the churches. Tourist numbers are at their lowest — this is Lalibela at its most intimate and raw.",
    7: "Peak rains: heavy daily rainfall, muddy paths, and 19°C temperatures that feel cool in the highland air. The churches are stunning in the rain — water cascading around the carved rock faces — but getting around requires patience and good waterproof gear. The few visitors who come now are rewarded with extraordinary solitude and the town's genuine rhythm. The priests continue their ancient liturgies regardless of the weather, and the singing is hauntingly beautiful.",
    8: "Still firmly in the rains at 19°C, but by late August the showers begin to lighten. The countryside is at maximum green and the waterfalls in the surrounding gorges are spectacular. The church complex is quiet and atmospheric, with the resident priests more available for conversation. This is budget-friendly Lalibela — simple guesthouses at their lowest prices, home-cooked injera, and the spiritual experience undiluted by tourism.",
    9: "The rains retreat rapidly and Meskel (September 27) brings bonfires and celebrations. The countryside is carpeted in yellow Meskel daisies, creating one of Ethiopia's most iconic landscapes — the golden flowers against the carved stone churches. At 22°C with clearing skies, this is the moment Lalibela transitions from rainy-season solitude to dry-season accessibility. Tourist season begins and prices start climbing. Genuinely magical timing.",
    10: "Prime conditions return: 24°C, dry skies, and the rock churches bathed in clear highland light. The Meskel daisies linger into early October, and the surrounding trekking routes are in excellent condition with green valleys and flowing streams. Tourist numbers build to moderate, and the guesthouses fill up on weekends. The priests welcome visitors to dawn services — arriving in darkness as the chanting begins is unforgettable.",
    11: "Dry season established at 24°C with the best weather of the year. The northern historic circuit (Lalibela-Gondar-Simien-Axum) is in peak condition, and many visitors use Lalibela as the anchor of a multi-week itinerary. Crowds are moderate-to-busy and booking ahead is wise. The morning light on Bet Giyorgis — that cruciform church carved downward into the rock — is arguably one of the most extraordinary sights in Africa.",
    12: "December delivers excellent conditions (23°C, dry) and building tourist numbers as the holiday season approaches. Ethiopian Christmas (Genna, January 7) preparations begin with increasing ceremony at the churches — the chanting intensifies, the priests don their finest vestments, and pilgrims begin arriving from across the country. If you can time it for late December through January 7, the spiritual energy at the rock churches is at its most powerful.",
  },

  'et-omo': {
    1: "Dry season in the Omo Valley means dusty trails, 33°C heat, and the tribal communities at their most accessible along the river banks. The Mursi, Hamar, and Karo peoples host their most photogenic market days (Turmi's Saturday market is essential), and river crossings are straightforward. This is peak tourist season for the valley — which still means very few people by global standards — and prices reflect the logistical effort of getting here.",
    2: "Still bone-dry at 34°C with excellent conditions for visiting the remote communities. The bull-jumping ceremony (ukuli) of the Hamar people may occur (timing is set by the community, not a calendar). The Omo River is at its lowest and calmest, making boat trips feasible. Travel is rough but reliable on the dirt roads, and the birdlife along the river is extraordinary. Bring sun protection like your life depends on it.",
    3: "The hottest and driest month: temperatures push toward 36°C and the valley is parched — the communities gather close to the Omo River and the smaller streams still flowing. The Mursi lip-plate villages are accessible if you travel with a respectful guide. This is the last comfortable month before the rains begin transforming the roads. The night skies are spectacular — no light pollution for hundreds of kilometers.",
    4: "The first rains arrive: afternoon thunderstorms bring dramatic skies and the valley begins greening, but the roads start deteriorating rapidly. At 32°C with rising humidity, the heat becomes sticky rather than dry. Some communities become harder to reach as rivers swell. Tourist numbers drop and the experience becomes more adventurous — the Omo in transition is raw and beautiful. Malaria risk increases with the rains.",
    5: "Rainy season sets in with regular downpours and the Omo River rising fast — many roads become impassable and some communities are cut off entirely. At 30°C with high humidity, travel is challenging and uncomfortable. Most organized tours don't operate May through August. If you're here, you're genuinely intrepid, and the lush green landscape and swollen river create a dramatically different Omo. Malaria prophylaxis is essential.",
    6: "Deep rainy season: the valley is flooded in patches, roads are largely impassable, and the river is a brown, swollen force. Most tourism shuts down entirely. The communities continue their lives — farming, fishing, and ceremonies — but access for outsiders is extremely limited. At 28°C with high humidity, conditions are oppressive. Not recommended for visitors unless you have specific local contacts and serious off-road capability.",
    7: "Peak rains continue with the valley at its wettest and most inaccessible. The Omo River floods its banks, creating rich alluvial farmland that the communities will plant. Temperatures hover around 27°C with persistent humidity. Tourism is effectively impossible in most areas. The natural world thrives — bird populations peak and the vegetation is explosively green — but this is not a time for casual visitors.",
    8: "Still rainy but the end approaches: by late August the showers begin spacing out and the river starts its slow retreat. Temperatures climb back to 30°C and the valley begins its transformation from flooded green to the accessible dry-season landscape. Some early-season travelers start arriving if roads are passable. The communities begin post-flood activities and the first bull-jumping ceremonies of the season may be planned.",
    9: "The transition month: rains diminish, roads begin drying (though mud remains), and the valley turns from waterlogged to lush green. At 32°C with decreasing humidity, travel becomes cautiously feasible again. The Hamar and Mursi communities are active with harvest-related ceremonies. Tourist infrastructure slowly reopens but conditions are still unpredictable — only come if you're flexible and experienced with rough African travel. Malaria risk remains high.",
    10: "Dry season clicks in: roads firm up, river levels drop to manageable crossings, and the valley is at its greenest and most beautiful — the contrast with the dry-season brown is striking. At 33°C, the heat is intense but dry and more bearable. Tour operators resume full schedules and the tribal market days restart in earnest. This is arguably the most beautiful month to visit: green landscapes, accessible communities, and relatively few tourists.",
    11: "Prime season returns at 33°C with dry conditions and the best access to the remote communities. The Omo River recedes to its navigable state, market days are vibrant, and the cultural ceremonies (including potential bull-jumping rituals) are in full swing. Tourist numbers are moderate but the valley is vast — you'll never feel crowded. The birdlife is outstanding along the river margins. Bring everything you need — infrastructure here is minimal.",
    12: "Excellent conditions persist: 33°C, dry roads, and the communities welcoming the peak tourist season. The Turmi, Jinka, and Key Afer markets are at their most colorful and active. Holiday pricing applies through the organized tours (which are essentially required for respectful and logistically viable visits). The Omo is a genuinely once-in-a-lifetime cultural experience — just approach with respect, a good guide, and fair compensation for the communities.",
  },

  'fi-helsinki': {
    1: "Helsinki in January is properly Nordic winter: -5°C average, barely six hours of pale daylight, and the city blanketed in snow that makes the pastel-colored neoclassical buildings glow. The cold is bracing but the Finns have it figured out — duck into a public sauna (Löyly or Allas Sea Pool), then jump in the frozen Baltic if you dare. Design District galleries, the Helsinki Art Museum, and the Ateneum are warm, world-class refuges. Crowds are nonexistent.",
    2: "Still deep winter at -5°C but the light is returning — each day adds minutes, and by month's end there's a real difference. The frozen sea allows ice walking and even sea ice swimming for the truly committed (always with a sauna nearby). Lux Helsinki light festival sometimes extends into early February, illuminating the dark city beautifully. Cross-country skiing in Central Park (Keskuspuisto) is excellent right in the city. Comfort food season: salmon soup and Karelian pies.",
    3: "The great brightening: daylight reaches 12 hours by month's end and the sun feels real again, though temperatures hover around 0°C and the snow is still deep. The Finns emerge from hibernation mode — outdoor terraces appear optimistically, and the mood lifts citywide. The sea ice begins thinning but still holds for walks. Skiing season continues and the March light on the snow-covered Senate Square is photographically gorgeous. Still very few tourists.",
    4: "Spring arrives in a rush: 7°C, the snow melting fast, and Helsinki shaking off winter with an energy that's almost giddy. The harbor opens up and the first ferry trips to Suomenlinna sea fortress become pleasant rather than punishing. Vappu (May Day Eve, April 30) preparations build — students in white caps flood the Esplanade. The thaw is messy but the lengthening 14-hour days feel like a gift. Restaurant terraces open in earnest.",
    5: "Vappu on May 1 is Finland's biggest party — picnics in Kaivopuisto park with sparkling wine and munkki (doughnuts), and the entire city seemingly outdoors in the 13°C air. By mid-May, Helsinki is genuinely lovely: 16 hours of daylight, parks greening rapidly, and the archipelago ferries running full schedules. The Design District buzzes, the food halls at Hietalahti are excellent, and you can walk the waterfront in long golden evenings. Tourist season begins gently.",
    6: "Near-endless daylight (19 hours), 18°C days, and Midsummer (Juhannus, late June) — when the city empties as Finns head to lakeside cottages to drink, sauna, and not sleep because the sun never sets. Helsinki before Juhannus is vibrant, after it is eerily quiet. The Baltic warms to a swimmable 15°C (Finns consider this fine), and the outdoor restaurants and island-hopping are at their best. Helsinki Day (June 12) celebrates with free events citywide.",
    7: "Peak summer: 22°C, 18 hours of light, and Helsinki's waterfront terraces in full glory. The sea warms to 17°C — genuinely swimmable at the public beaches — and island-hopping to Suomenlinna and the outer archipelago is essential. Restaurant Day and Helsinki Festival add cultural energy, and the farmers' markets overflow with Finnish berries and new potatoes. Crowds are at their highest (still modest by European standards) and the city feels joyful.",
    8: "Still warm at 20°C with slightly shorter days — the first hints that the endless summer is finite. The Helsinki Festival brings world-class music, theater, and art across the city, and the archipelago is at its most accessible. Berry season peaks: Finnish blueberries and lingonberries appear on every menu and market stall. The sea is at its warmest (18°C) and the city has a relaxed, late-summer energy. Tourist numbers ease from July's peak.",
    9: "Autumn arrives swiftly: 14°C, shortening days, and the city's parks turning gold and russet — the ruska (autumn colors) in Central Park are stunning. The cultural season kicks off with theater, gallery openings, and Helsinki Design Week. The Baltic cools to 14°C (end of swimming season), but the sauna-to-sea contrast is at its most invigorating. Mushroom foraging season in the forests surrounding the city. Crowds thin and the city belongs to locals again.",
    10: "The descent: 8°C, rapidly darkening days, and the first frost. Helsinki pivots indoors with a vengeance — the museum and gallery circuit, the legendary coffee culture, and restaurant weeks offer warmth and culture. The autumn colors peak early October then fade to bare branches. This is a city for slow mornings, strong coffee, and cinnamon buns (korvapuusti) in design-forward cafés. Tourist numbers are low and prices follow.",
    11: "November is Helsinki at its darkest — barely seven hours of grey light, 2°C, and the first snow often arriving mid-month. The Christmas season begins: Helsinki Christmas Market opens in Senate Square, and the city's illumination schedule brings warmth to the darkness. Independence Day (December 6) is approaching and the national mood is reflective. Sauna culture becomes essential, not optional. The food scene is in peak winter comfort mode.",
    12: "Christmas transforms Helsinki: the Senate Square market glows with wooden stalls selling glögi and handmade ornaments, and the city is wrapped in lights. Temperatures hover around -2°C with frequent snow, and the darkness (barely five hours of light) makes the illuminations feel magical. Finns celebrate Christmas Eve with a sauna, salmon, and casseroles. New Year's Eve on the Senate Square is a public celebration with fireworks over the cathedral. Deeply atmospheric.",
  },

  'fi-lakeland': {
    1: "Finnish Lakeland in January is a frozen wonderland — the lakes are under thick ice, temperatures average -10°C, and the landscape is a white-and-blue dreamscape. Cross-country skiing on groomed lakeside trails is superb, and ice fishing from a hole in a frozen lake (with a thermos of coffee and a portable stove) is quintessentially Finnish. The darkness (six hours of light) is offset by cozy cottage stays with wood-burning saunas. Almost zero tourists.",
    2: "The coldest month with temperatures touching -12°C and the deepest snow — but also the most magical, as the days lengthen noticeably and the winter light turns the frozen lakes into vast mirrors of blue and white. Snowshoeing through the forest, ice skating on cleared lake surfaces, and the nightly sauna-to-snow-plunge ritual define the experience. The town of Savonlinna is quiet but its medieval Olavinlinna Castle looms dramatically over the frozen lake.",
    3: "Spring light arrives while winter holds on: -4°C but with 11+ hours of increasingly bright sunshine that makes the frozen landscape sparkle. This is peak season for spring skiing and snowmobile tours across the lake ice. The locals are in excellent spirits as the light returns, and cottage stays become more appealing with the longer days. Ice fishing season continues and the lake perch are biting. Still virtually no tourists — Finnish nature at its most authentic.",
    4: "The great melt begins: 5°C, the lake ice cracking and retreating, and the forests releasing that extraordinary spring smell of birch and pine. It's muddy and transitional, not the prettiest month, but the birdlife is spectacular as migratory species return in force — crane, swan, and goose flocks arrive at the wetlands. The sauna tradition never stops, and the lakeside cottages start their spring awakening. A month for naturalists and solitude-seekers.",
    5: "Spring explodes: 13°C, the lakes finally open, and the forest floor carpets in wildflowers and fresh green growth. The first boats hit the water and fishing season opens for pike and perch. The days stretch to 17 hours and the light is extraordinary — soft, golden, and seemingly endless. Savonlinna and Kuopio begin their summer preparations, and the lakeside restaurant terraces open. Tourist season starts gently with canoeists and hikers arriving.",
    6: "Midsummer magic: 18°C, near-constant light (the sun barely dips below the horizon), and Juhannus celebrations at lakeside cottages with bonfires, sauna, and swimming in the 18°C lakes. This is quintessential Finland — a country of introverts collectively deciding to party outside for one weekend. After Midsummer, the lake region enters its glorious summer mode: canoeing, fishing, berry-picking, and sauna every single day. Tourist numbers are moderate.",
    7: "Peak Lakeland summer: 21°C, the lakes at their warmest (20°C), and Savonlinna Opera Festival filling the medieval Olavinlinna Castle with world-class performances on the lake's edge. Canoeing, kayaking, and lake swimming are at their best, and the wild blueberry and lingonberry picking begins in the forests. The midnight twilight is enchanting and the cottage life — swimming, sauna, grilling, repeat — is Finland's gift to the stressed-out world.",
    8: "Still warm at 19°C with the lakes holding at 19°C and the berry season in full swing — every Finn is in the forest with a bucket, picking blueberries, lingonberries, and cloudberries. The first chanterelles appear and the markets overflow with foraged goods. Summer festivals continue and the cottages are in prime demand. By month's end, the first cool evenings hint at autumn, and the lake mists at dawn become more frequent and atmospheric.",
    9: "Ruska season begins: 13°C, the birch and aspen forests turning gold and flame around the mirror-still lakes in one of Europe's most underrated autumn displays. The mushroom foraging is at its peak (chanterelles, porcini) and the fishing is excellent as the lakes cool. Tourist numbers drop and the cottages become affordable again. The first frost paints the mornings silver, and the sauna feels more necessary than ever. Genuinely magical month.",
    10: "Deep autumn: 5°C, the last leaves falling, and the lakes beginning to steam in the cold air. The forests are mostly bare but the landscape has a stark, Nordic beauty. Mushroom season extends into early October, and the dark evenings bring out the first aurora borealis sightings of the season. Lakeland is very quiet now — cottage life becomes about fireside reading, sauna, and the contemplative Finnish relationship with nature. Very few visitors.",
    11: "The freeze begins: -2°C, the smaller lakes icing over, and the first snow dusting the landscape. Daylight shrinks to seven hours and the mood is deeply introspective — this is not a tourist month, it's a Finnish-winter-soul month. The saunas are the warmest places in the world, and the darkness is offset by candlelight, fireplaces, and hearty Finnish food: salmon soup, reindeer stew, and rye bread. The aurora appears on clear nights.",
    12: "Full winter settles in: -8°C, the lakes frozen solid, and the landscape white and silent. Christmas in a Lakeland cottage — with a wood sauna, candles, and a traditional Finnish ham — is one of Europe's most peaceful holiday experiences. Cross-country skiing resumes on the frozen lakes, and the aurora can be spectacular on clear nights. The darkness (five hours of light) creates an intimacy that screens can't replicate. Zero tourists, maximum authenticity.",
  },

  'fi-lapland': {
    1: "The polar night is ending but January is still dark, cold, and magical — temperatures average -14°C, the aurora borealis dances overhead on clear nights, and the landscape is a frozen white expanse under star-filled skies. Husky safaris, reindeer sleigh rides, and snowmobile treks across the fells are in peak season. The handful of daylight hours produce a blue twilight that's otherworldly. Crowds peak around New Year then ease. Book glass igloos months ahead.",
    2: "The light returns in earnest — by month's end the sun is above the horizon for several hours, and the combination of fresh snow, blue skies, and -12°C temperatures makes this arguably the most visually stunning month. Cross-country skiing and snowshoeing in Pallas-Yllästunturi and Urho Kekkonen national parks are exceptional. Aurora viewing remains excellent on clear nights. The Sámi people celebrate their national day (February 6) with reindeer racing and traditional joik singing.",
    3: "Spring light floods the Arctic: 12+ hours of sunshine reflecting off vast snowfields in a dazzling display. Temperatures climb to -5°C and the skiing conditions are some of the best in Europe — long days, reliable snow, and that champagne-powder quality the Nordics are famous for. This is peak season for snowmobile safaris and ice fishing on the frozen lakes. The aurora season winds down as the nights get shorter. A genuinely spectacular month.",
    4: "The great melt begins in the lowlands while the fells stay snowy — a split-season feel with 3°C days and rapidly lengthening light (heading toward 24-hour daylight). Late-season skiing on the higher fells is excellent, and the reindeer begin their calving season in the forests. The Midnight Sun approaches and the landscape transitions from white to patchy green and brown. Not the prettiest moment, but the light is extraordinary and tourist numbers drop.",
    5: "The ice breaks up on the rivers and lakes in dramatic fashion, the snow recedes to the highest fells, and Lapland enters its brief, frenetic spring — 8°C with the Midnight Sun arriving by month's end above the Arctic Circle. Birdlife is remarkable as Arctic species return to nest, and the brown bears emerge from hibernation. Hiking begins on the lower trails while skiing continues at elevation. A transitional month that rewards flexibility and a sense of adventure.",
    6: "The Midnight Sun is here — 24 hours of daylight, 14°C in the valleys, and a landscape transformed from winter white to green and golden. Hiking season opens in earnest across the national parks, river rafting on the Muoniojoki and Ounasjoki rivers is thrilling with snowmelt volume, and the mosquitoes arrive with a vengeance (bring head nets and DEET). The Sámi reindeer are scattered across the fells with their calves. This is wild Lapland at its most alive.",
    7: "Peak summer: 16°C, continuous daylight, and the hiking in Lapland's national parks is magnificent — the Kungsleden and Hetta-Pallas trails offer Arctic tundra, pristine rivers, and isolation that few places on Earth can match. Salmon fishing season peaks on the Teno River, and the berry season begins with cloudberries (liquid gold in Finnish culture). Mosquitoes are intense. The midnight sun golf tournaments are surreal. Moderate tourist numbers for hikers and nature lovers.",
    8: "Still warm at 14°C with the first hints of autumn appearing in the fell birches — ruska (autumn colors) arrives earlier in the Arctic than anywhere else in Europe. The berries are at their peak: cloudberries, blueberries, and lingonberries carpet the forest floor. Hiking remains excellent and the mosquitoes finally diminish. By late August, the first dark nights return and aurora season stirs. A month of transition that rewards with beauty at every turn.",
    9: "Ruska season in Lapland is one of Europe's greatest natural spectacles — the fell birches and tundra turn crimson, gold, and amber against the dark green spruce, and the scale of color in places like Kilpisjärvi and Utsjoki is staggering. At 7°C with clear skies and the aurora returning, this is arguably Lapland's most beautiful month. Hiking is superb with dry trails, no mosquitoes, and the rivers still crossable. Tourist numbers are surprisingly low. A true secret season.",
    10: "The first snow arrives on the fells while the valleys cling to autumn's last colors — a dramatic contrast that photographers travel thousands of miles to capture. Temperatures drop to 0°C and the aurora borealis becomes increasingly spectacular as the nights lengthen. Hiking wraps up on the higher trails and the landscape prepares for winter. Reindeer roundups (ero) are underway as the Sámi gather their herds for the season. Quiet, raw, and beautiful.",
    11: "Winter descends: -8°C, the polar night (kaamos) begins in the far north, and the snow blankets everything in white. The first husky and reindeer safari operators open for the season, and the aurora displays are at their most powerful — long, dark nights with minimal light pollution create ideal conditions. Christmas tourism builds toward December, with Santa Claus Village in Rovaniemi awakening. The silence of a Lapland forest in fresh snow is genuinely transformative.",
    12: "Lapland at Christmas is a fairy tale made real — -12°C, deep snow, aurora overhead, and Santa Claus Village in full festive swing. Reindeer sleigh rides through the Arctic forest, husky safaris under starlit skies, and glass igloo stays watching the northern lights are bucket-list experiences that actually deliver. Peak tourism season means peak prices and booking months ahead, but the magic is undeniable. The polar darkness is offset by the warm glow of cottages, candles, and the Sámi culture that predates Christmas by millennia.",
  },

  'fj-fiji': {
    1: "Peak wet season: 31°C, high humidity, and regular tropical downpours that can be torrential — cyclone season is real and should factor into your planning. The upside: the islands are lush and intensely green, the resorts offer deep discounts, and the warm 29°C seas are perfect for snorkeling when the sun breaks through. The Coral Coast and Mamanuca Islands are quieter than usual. If you're flexible with weather, January rewards with value and solitude.",
    2: "The wettest month with the highest cyclone risk — 31°C, heavy rainfall, and seas that can be rough. But between storms, Fiji is staggeringly beautiful: vivid greens, dramatic skies, and reef systems teeming with life in the warm 29°C water. Dive operators still run trips (visibility varies), and the cultural experiences — village visits, lovo feasts, and meke dancing — are rain-proof and deeply rewarding. Budget travelers take note: this is the cheapest month.",
    3: "Still wet season but the cyclone risk starts to diminish. Temperatures hold at 30°C with afternoon downpours and morning sunshine — the rhythm of tropical life. The Yasawa Islands are quiet and the snorkeling at Manta Ray passage is building toward peak season. Village life carries on warmly, and the kava ceremony is an essential Fijian experience regardless of weather. Resorts offer shoulder pricing.",
    4: "The transition begins: rainfall decreases, humidity eases slightly, and the islands start their shift toward the dry season. At 29°C with a mix of sunny and showery days, April is a gambler's month — you might get perfect weather, you might get soaked. The reefs are healthy and the sea at 28°C is sublime for diving. Crowds are low and the Fijian hospitality — the warmest in the Pacific, genuinely — shines.",
    5: "Dry season arrives: 28°C, decreasing rain, and the trade winds bringing freshness to the air. The Mamanuca and Yasawa Islands enter their golden stretch with reliable sunshine and calm seas for island-hopping. Manta ray season at Manta Ray Passage is building, and the diving visibility improves weekly. Tourist numbers start climbing but the islands are vast enough to absorb them. An excellent month to visit.",
    6: "Prime Fiji: 26°C, dry trade winds, and the sea cooling to a refreshing 26°C that's still warm enough for hours of snorkeling. The coral reefs are at their most vivid with excellent visibility, and surfing at Cloudbreak and Restaurants reaches world-class conditions. Crowds are moderate-to-busy as the dry season draws visitors from the Southern Hemisphere winter. The Hibiscus Festival in Suva adds cultural energy. Peak season pricing begins.",
    7: "The driest, coolest month — 25°C by day with fresh trade winds and virtually no rain. This is peak surf season at Tavarua's legendary breaks, and the diving across the archipelago is in prime condition with 30m+ visibility. The Bula Festival brings music and celebration to Nadi. Crowds are at their highest and resort prices peak, but the weather justifies every dollar. Evening bonfires on the beach with a bowl of kava — that's the Fijian sweet spot.",
    8: "Still peak dry season: 26°C, minimal rain, and the reefs looking their absolute best. Whale season begins as humpbacks migrate through Fijian waters — the whale-watching off Taveuni and the Bligh Waters is outstanding. Surf continues at world-class levels and the trade winds make sailing between islands glorious. Maximum crowds and prices, but the conditions are undeniable. Book the best reef-front bures months in advance.",
    9: "Dry season continues with 27°C days, calm seas, and the humpback whales still passing through — snorkeling with these gentle giants (where permitted) is a once-in-a-lifetime experience. The trade winds keep things fresh and diving conditions remain superb. Crowds begin easing from peak levels, and September offers a slightly more relaxed atmosphere with similar weather to July-August. The Fijian Regatta is a colorful sailing event.",
    10: "The shoulder month: 28°C, the occasional shower returning, and the transition toward wet season beginning gently. Crowds thin noticeably and prices soften, making this excellent value for what's still essentially dry-season weather most days. The reefs remain spectacular, whale season winds down, and the manta rays at Yasawa are increasingly active. A smart traveler's pick — 90% of the experience at 70% of the cost.",
    11: "Wet season approaches with afternoon showers becoming more regular and humidity climbing — 29°C with the lush tropical greenery intensifying. The diving remains good though visibility starts to vary, and the sea warms to 27°C. Tourist numbers drop and the resorts begin offering deals. The Fijian hospitality somehow gets even warmer when there are fewer guests to share it with. Bula spirit in the rain is still bula spirit.",
    12: "Wet season with holiday crowds: 30°C, regular tropical rain, and cyclone season officially starting — but the Christmas-New Year rush brings visitors regardless. Resorts deck out for the holidays and the Fijian celebrations are genuinely festive with lovo feasts, meke performances, and church singing that'll move you to tears. The reefs are warm (28°C) and the snorkeling between showers is excellent. Book holiday stays well in advance and watch the weather forecasts.",
  },

  'fm-micronesia': {
    1: "Micronesia's drier season is well underway on the eastern islands (Kosrae, Pohnpei) though \"dry\" is relative — this is one of the wettest places on Earth. Expect 30°C, 85% humidity, and afternoon showers even now. The diving is spectacular year-round, and January brings excellent visibility at Chuuk Lagoon's legendary WWII wreck sites. Tourists are few — this is one of the Pacific's most remote and least-visited destinations.",
    2: "The driest stretch continues with slightly less rainfall and 30°C heat — the best window for exploring Pohnpei's Nan Madol ruins (the \"Venice of the Pacific\") without constant downpours. Chuuk's ghost fleet of Japanese warships offers world-class wreck diving in warm 28°C water with superb visibility. Tourist numbers are minimal. Getting here requires commitment (multiple flights from Guam or Honolulu), but that's exactly the filter that keeps it special.",
    3: "Still relatively dry at 30°C with excellent diving conditions across the islands. The manta ray encounters at Yap are building toward peak season, and the traditional Yapese stone money exchanges continue their ancient ritual. Kosrae's jungle-covered ruins and pristine reefs are accessible with dry forest trails. This is Pacific travel at its most authentic — limited infrastructure, genuine cultural encounters, and underwater experiences that rival anywhere on Earth.",
    4: "Transitional month as the wetter period approaches — rainfall increases on the western islands (Yap, Palau-adjacent) while eastern islands stay drier. At 31°C with building humidity, the climate is tropical-intense. Yap's manta rays are increasingly reliable, and Pohnpei's barrier reef offers pristine, uncrowded diving. The cultural depth here — traditional navigation, weaving, and community ceremonies — is extraordinary for those who seek it out.",
    5: "The wet season builds across the archipelago: regular heavy rains, high humidity, and 31°C heat. Pohnpei, the wettest of the islands, gets particularly soaked. But the diving doesn't stop — the wrecks at Chuuk are always there, 27°C water and all, and the reef systems thrive in the nutrient-rich runoff. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, making this the most affordable and most solitary time to visit. Pack rain gear and patience.",
    6: "Deep wet season on the western islands while the east gets moderate rain — 30°C and steamy throughout. The upside of the rains: the jungle-covered ruins on Pohnpei and Kosrae are at their most atmospheric, draped in mist and vine. Diving continues with slightly reduced visibility. Yap's traditional culture is accessible year-round with stick dances and community gatherings. Infrastructure is basic everywhere — that's part of the charm.",
    7: "Wet season continues with heavy rainfall across most islands, particularly Pohnpei and Kosrae. At 30°C with persistent humidity, this is tropical Pacific at its most intense. Chuuk Lagoon diving remains excellent (the wrecks don't care about rain), and Yap's manta cleaning stations are active year-round. Very few visitors — you may be the only tourist on entire islands. The isolation is profound and genuinely restorative.",
    8: "Still in the wet season but some islands (Yap) begin seeing decreased rainfall. Temperatures hold at 30°C and the diving remains the primary draw — Chuuk's wrecks, Pohnpei's walls, and Yap's mantas all deliver regardless of surface conditions. Typhoon season is a consideration for the western islands, so monitor forecasts. The few guesthouses and dive operators are attentive when business is slow. Raw, real Pacific travel.",
    9: "The wet season starts easing on the eastern islands while the west remains soggy. At 30°C, the climate is predictably tropical. Diving visibility begins improving, and the manta encounters at Yap become more reliable. Nan Madol on Pohnpei is atmospheric but muddy. This is a destination for serious divers, cultural explorers, and people who find peace in remoteness. Don't come expecting resort amenities — come expecting the real Pacific.",
    10: "Transitional month with decreasing rainfall on most islands and improving conditions. The sea at 28°C is warm and calm, and diving visibility ticks up across the archipelago. Chuuk's WWII wrecks — submarines, fighters, supply ships — are among the world's most evocative dives, and October conditions are increasingly favorable. Tourist numbers remain minuscule. The traditional cultures of Yap and Pohnpei are more accessible when you're the only visitor asking questions.",
    11: "The drier season establishes itself with 30°C days and notably less rainfall, particularly on the eastern islands. Diving conditions are excellent with improving visibility and warm water. Yap's manta rays are reliable, Chuuk's wrecks are crystal-clear, and Kosrae's pristine reefs are among the Pacific's best-kept secrets. A handful more divers arrive as word spreads about the conditions, but \"crowded\" is a word that simply doesn't apply in Micronesia.",
    12: "Peak dry season begins properly with the best weather of the year: 30°C, reduced rainfall, and excellent diving visibility across all islands. Holiday visitors bump numbers slightly but we're talking single digits, not crowds. The Yapese stone money banks, the ghost fleet of Chuuk, the jungle temples of Pohnpei — December delivers all of it in the best possible conditions. If you've ever wanted to feel like a genuine explorer, this is the month and the place.",
  },

  'fo-faroe-islands': {
    1: "January in the Faroes is dark, wet, and wild — 5°C (mild for this latitude thanks to the Gulf Stream), gale-force winds, and barely six hours of grey daylight. The cliffs at Vestmanna and Mykines are dramatic in the storm light, but boat tours are weather-dependent and often canceled. The upside: the woolly Faroese food scene (fermented lamb, dried fish) is at its coziest, and you'll share the islands with almost no one. Pack for horizontal rain.",
    2: "Still winter-wild: 4°C, persistent rain and wind, but the days are lengthening and the seabird colonies begin stirring on the outer cliffs. Ólavsøka preparations start in the villages, and the Faroese chain dance (an ancient tradition) continues in community halls. Driving the mountain passes requires caution in fog and ice, but the tunnels connecting islands make winter travel surprisingly feasible. A month for moody photography and solitary coastal walks.",
    3: "The light returns in earnest: 12 hours of daylight, 5°C with less rain than winter's worst, and the first signs of spring on the grassy hillsides. The puffins haven't arrived yet but the fulmars and kittiwakes are back on the cliffs. Hiking the coastal trails is bracing but rewarding, with that trademark Faroese landscape of sheer cliffs and vivid green turf. Tourist numbers are minimal and guesthouse prices are low.",
    4: "Spring proper: 7°C, longer days, and the grass turning that impossible Faroese green that makes photographers weep. The first hiking season visitors arrive and trails like the Sornfelli ridge become accessible without ice gear. The villages are quiet and welcoming, and the food scene features new-season lamb. Weather remains unpredictable (you can see all four seasons in an hour), but that's the Faroese charm. The light is extraordinary.",
    5: "The magic month: puffins arrive at Mykines (the westernmost island) in their thousands, the days stretch past 18 hours, and the hillsides are carpeted in wildflowers. At 9°C with improving weather (still bring rain gear for sudden squalls), the hiking is superb — Trælanípa above Sørvágsvatn and the cliff path to the Múlafossur waterfall are world-class. Tourist numbers build but the islands feel spacious. Early booking for Mykines ferry is essential.",
    6: "Near-endless light (20+ hours), 11°C, and the Faroes at their most accessible — the puffin colonies are thriving, the hiking trails are in prime condition, and the landscape is dizzyingly green against the blue-grey sea. National Day (Ólavsøka) preparations build toward the late-June festivities. The weather is as good as it gets (still changeable), and boat tours to Vestmanna's bird cliffs run regularly. Tourist numbers peak but the islands absorb them well.",
    7: "Peak Faroese summer: 13°C (this is as warm as it gets), the longest days, and the puffin-watching at Mykines at its absolute best. The hiking across Streymoy, Vágar, and Eysturoy is spectacular, and the village of Gjógv with its natural harbor is heartbreakingly beautiful. Maximum tourist numbers — which still means nothing like Mediterranean crowds — and the best weather odds of the year. The Faroese food festival G! Festival combines music and cuisine in a fjord-side village.",
    8: "Still summer conditions at 12°C with the puffins starting to depart by month's end. The hiking remains excellent and the weather, while always unpredictable, tends toward less wind than winter. The Festival of Ólavsøka (if in late July/early August) is the national celebration — rowing competitions, chain dancing, and a patriotic energy that feels genuinely communal. Late August brings the first hints of autumn with shorter days and moodier skies.",
    9: "Autumn arrives swiftly: 10°C, the grasses turning gold, and the tourist season winding down. The puffins have gone but the cliffs remain dramatic with fulmars and gannets. Hiking is still excellent if you're prepared for rain and wind, and the shorter days bring atmospheric light that photographers prize — golden hour lasts for hours when the sun is low. Accommodation becomes easier to find and the Faroese villages feel delightfully local again.",
    10: "The transition to winter: 8°C, increasing rain and wind, and daylight shrinking to 10 hours. The landscape turns tawny brown and the seas become rough, making boat excursions less reliable. But the Faroese food scene enters its richest season — fermented lamb (skerpikjøt), wind-dried fish (ræst), and the annual ræst festival celebrate traditions that go back centuries. Very few tourists and the islands feel authentically, beautifully remote.",
    11: "Dark, wet, and wild again: 6°C, relentless horizontal rain, and barely eight hours of grey light. The Faroes are at their most primal — waves crash against the basalt cliffs, the wind howls across the treeless hills, and the warmth of a village restaurant serving ræst and pilot whale feels like civilization itself. Not for everyone, but for those who love wild, empty landscapes and genuine cultural encounters, November is the uncut version of the Faroes.",
    12: "Midwinter: 5°C, storms, and just six hours of twilight — but the Faroese Christmas traditions (Jólafundurin) bring warmth to the darkness with community gatherings, traditional food, and singing. The villages glow with lights and the hospitality is genuine. Driving conditions can be challenging but the tunnel system keeps most islands connected. A December visit to the Faroes is a commitment to atmosphere over sunshine, and it delivers profoundly.",
  },

  'fr-alps': {
    1: "Peak ski season in the French Alps: Chamonix, Val d'Isère, and the Three Valleys are in full swing with deep snow, -5°C at altitude, and that champagne-powder freshness after each new dump. The resorts are busy (school holidays in early January, then easing) and the après-ski scene — fondue, raclette, vin chaud — is in its element. Off-piste in Chamonix's Vallée Blanche is legendary if conditions allow. Book early for the premium chalets.",
    2: "The best snow conditions of the year: February brings the deepest snowpack, reliable cover, and increasing sunshine between storms. School holidays fill the resorts mid-month, but the skiing is worth the crowds. At -3°C at resort altitude with seven hours of sunshine, the days are getting longer and the spring skiing energy starts building. Cross-country skiing in the Aravis or around Megève is superb. Tartiflette and Beaufort cheese are the fuel of champions.",
    3: "Spring skiing at its finest: 5°C at mid-mountain, long sunny days, and the ability to ski in a t-shirt by afternoon. The snowpack is still deep at altitude but the lower slopes begin softening. Crowds ease after school holidays and the resorts shift to a more relaxed vibe — extended lunch on a sunny terrace with a carafe of Savoyard wine is practically mandatory. The Vallée Blanche route is in prime condition with stable snow bridges.",
    4: "The season winds down in the lower resorts while the glacial areas (Tignes, Les Deux Alpes, Val Thorens) keep running. At 10°C in the valleys, the spring wildflowers carpet the lower meadows while the peaks stay white — a stunning contrast. Early-season hiking begins on the valley trails, and the mountain restaurants transition from ski-lodge hearty to spring-fresh menus. A beautiful transitional month with few tourists and excellent light.",
    5: "The Alps between seasons: the ski lifts close (except glacier areas), the hiking trails open at lower elevations, and the mountain meadows explode with wildflowers — gentians, alpine roses, and orchids paint the hillsides. At 15°C in the valleys with the peaks still snow-capped, the scenery is breathtaking. The climbing and via ferrata season opens around Chamonix. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, making this a hiker's paradise with empty trails and open refuges.",
    6: "Summer begins: 20°C in the valleys, the high trails clearing of snow, and the Alps transforming into Europe's finest hiking destination. The Tour du Mont Blanc opens fully, refugio-to-refugio, and the views from the Aiguille du Midi cable car are extraordinary. Mountain biking and paragliding take over the ski slopes, and the lakeside towns (Annecy, Évian) enter their beach-club mode. Crowds build but the mountains are vast. Alpine cheese at every altitude.",
    7: "Peak Alpine summer: 25°C in the valleys, the high trails fully accessible, and the Tour du Mont Blanc in prime condition. Chamonix buzzes with trail runners and mountaineers, and the mountain lakes are warm enough for bracing but refreshing swimming. The Fête Nationale (July 14) brings fireworks to mountain villages, and the farmers' markets overflow with Reblochon, tomme, and summer berries. Maximum crowds at the popular sites — hit the trails early.",
    8: "Still peak season at 24°C with occasional afternoon thunderstorms that build dramatically over the peaks. The hiking remains excellent (keep an eye on the weather for high-altitude routes), and the Ultra-Trail du Mont-Blanc (UTMB) in late August transforms Chamonix into the trail-running capital of the world. The mountain lakes are at their warmest, and the evening light on Mont Blanc is liquid gold. Prices and crowds match July's intensity.",
    9: "The golden month: crowds vanish, the larch forests begin turning gold, and temperatures drop to a pleasant 18°C with crisp, clear air. The high trails are still open and the conditions are arguably the best of the year — stable weather, cool temperatures, and visibility that stretches to infinity. The cheese season shifts to the alpine-pasture varieties being brought down for the season (alpages), and the mountain restaurants feel intimate again. Superb month.",
    10: "Autumn deepens: 12°C in the valleys, the larches at full golden glory, and the first snow dusting the highest peaks. The hiking season closes on the high passes but the valley and mid-altitude trails are spectacular with autumn color. Mushroom foraging season is excellent (ceps, chanterelles), and the wine harvest in the Savoie valleys brings new-vintage tastings. Very few tourists and the mountain villages shift to their quiet, authentic rhythm.",
    11: "The quiet before ski season: 5°C with increasing snow at altitude, the lifts still closed, and the Alps in their most contemplative mood. The valleys are grey and the peaks are white, and the mountain towns feel genuinely local. This is the month for spa towns (Évian, Aix-les-Bains) and indoor pursuits — the restaurants serve peak-season comfort food and the wine cellars are worth exploring. Early snow reports fuel anticipation for December's opening.",
    12: "Ski season opens with a bang: fresh early-season snow, -3°C at resort altitude, and the Christmas-New Year crowds bringing festive energy to every mountain village. The early skiing at Val d'Isère, Tignes, and the Three Valleys is excellent if natural snow cooperates (snowmaking fills gaps). Christmas markets in Annecy and Chamonix are charming, and the mountain cuisine — fondue, raclette, and tartiflette — is at its most welcome. Peak holiday pricing, but the Alpine winter atmosphere is irresistible.",
  },

  'fr-bordeaux': {
    1: "Bordeaux in January is calm, uncrowded, and surprisingly pleasant at 10°C — the honey-colored limestone buildings along the Garonne look gorgeous in low winter light, and the wine bars of Saint-Pierre are cozy with off-season locals. The vineyards are dormant and the châteaux run private tastings without the summer crowds. Rain is regular (80mm) but interspersed with crisp blue-sky days. Oysters from Arcachon are in peak season — order a plate with Graves blanc and mean it.",
    2: "Still quiet at 12°C with the first hints of spring in the parks — the buds appear on the plane trees lining the quays and the café terraces start cautiously opening. The wine scene never sleeps: en primeur tastings from the latest vintage begin in the major châteaux, and the city's wine bars pour excellent bottles at winter prices. Carnival brings a brief burst of color. The Cité du Vin museum is an excellent rainy-day destination.",
    3: "Spring arrives properly: 15°C, the vineyards greening with new growth, and the riverside promenade (Miroir d'eau) sparkling in the strengthening sun. Bordeaux's restaurant scene starts its outdoor season, and the Marché des Capucins (the city's beloved covered market) is full of spring asparagus, strawberries, and lamb. Tourist numbers are moderate and the wine regions are peaceful — a great month for cycling through Saint-Émilion without dodging tour buses.",
    4: "April is Bordeaux at its most charming: 17°C, the city's 18th-century architecture glowing in the spring light, and the vineyards in that delicate new-leaf green that makes the rolling landscape photogenic from every angle. The châteaux open for tours with manageable queues, and the canelés from Baillardran are always in season. This is the sweet spot for wine tourism — knowledgeable but uncrowded — and a long lunch at a Saint-Émilion terrace feels like a human right.",
    5: "May delivers: 21°C, the longest days approaching, and Bordeaux's cultural calendar humming with the Bordeaux Wine Festival (in some years). The vineyards are lush and the cycling routes through Médoc, Graves, and the Right Bank are in prime condition. River cruises on the Garonne and Dordogne resume full schedules, and the seafood from the Bassin d'Arcachon is excellent. Crowds are building but the region is vast. Outdoor dining weather every evening.",
    6: "Summer mode: 25°C, long golden evenings, and Bordeaux's quayside buzzing with open-air concerts, markets, and the Fête du Vin (biennial, even years). The vineyards are in full growth and the châteaux are at their most welcoming (and busiest). The Dune of Pilat and the beaches of Cap Ferret and Arcachon are popular day trips. Wine prices in the city are fair year-round but restaurant bookings fill up. The Miroir d'eau at sunset is mandatory.",
    7: "Peak Bordeaux summer: 28°C, the vines heavy with green grapes, and the region at its most touristed. The Atlantic beaches at Lacanau and Arcachon are packed with Bordelais escaping the city heat. The wine route is busy with tour buses, so book private château visits for the best experience. The Médoc Marathon (in some years) combines running and wine tasting — gloriously French. Evenings on the Garonne are warm and wine-soaked.",
    8: "The hottest month at 28°C with occasional heatwaves pushing past 35°C — Bordeaux bakes and the locals decamp to the coast. The city is quieter mid-August as French vacations thin out the local population, giving an oddly peaceful feeling to normally buzzing neighborhoods. The grape harvest approaches (véraison turns the grapes from green to color), and the anticipation of vendange fills the wine world. Beach days at Arcachon are essential survival.",
    9: "Harvest time — the vendange transforms the vineyards into a hive of activity as the grapes are picked, sorted, and pressed. At 24°C with golden light, this is the most exciting month in Bordeaux wine country. Some châteaux allow visitors to participate in the harvest, and the new juice (moût) is tasted with reverence. Crowds ease from summer's peak and the city returns to its elegant, local rhythm. The food scene features game, ceps, and new-season walnuts.",
    10: "Golden autumn in Bordeaux: 19°C, the vine leaves turning crimson and gold in one of Europe's most beautiful agricultural landscapes. The harvest is complete and the châteaux shift to a post-vintage glow — tastings are relaxed and celebratory. The Marché des Capucins overflows with mushrooms, chestnuts, and late-season figs. Rain returns (75mm) but the quality of light between showers is stunning. Moderate crowds, excellent value, and peak food season.",
    11: "November settles in at 13°C with grey skies, shorter days, and the vine leaves falling to reveal the structural beauty of the vineyards. The wine bars and restaurants pivot to hearty Bordelaise cuisine — entrecôte, duck confit, and the first truffles from Périgord. Tourist numbers are low and the château visits feel intimate. The Cité du Vin and the CAPC contemporary art museum are perfect for rainy afternoons. Oyster season returns to its glory.",
    12: "Festive Bordeaux: Christmas markets fill the Allées de Tourny and Place Pey Berland with wooden chalets selling foie gras, vin chaud, and canelés. At 9°C with regular rain, the city is atmospheric rather than sunny, and the golden limestone glows under the holiday lights. New Year's Eve on the quays is a lively affair with fireworks over the Garonne. The wine bars are in full winter mode — a glass of aged Pauillac by a fire is December at its finest.",
  },

  'fr-brittany': {
    1: "Brittany in January is raw Atlantic weather at its most honest — 8°C, frequent rain and gales, and the coast battered by dramatic winter storms. Mont-Saint-Michel is atmospheric and nearly empty, and the crêperies of Saint-Malo's walled city are warm refuges serving buckwheat galettes and bowls of cidre. Oysters from Cancale are at their winter best. Very few tourists, rock-bottom prices, and the kind of moody coastal beauty that sticks with you.",
    2: "Still winter-wild at 8°C with persistent Breton drizzle, but the days lengthen and the light turns silvery on the granite coastlines. The Pink Granite Coast (Côte de Granit Rose) is stunning in storm light, and the seafood platters in Perros-Guirec are world-class with no queue. Carnival season brings Breton folk music and dance to village halls. Cider and calvados by a fireplace after a coastal walk is peak Breton living.",
    3: "Spring stirs along the Breton coast: 11°C, the first wildflowers on the clifftop paths, and the camellias blooming in the Gulf of Morbihan's subtropical microclimates. The GR34 coastal hiking path is in excellent condition (muddy in spots) and blissfully empty. The standing stones of Carnac are accessible without the summer tour groups, and the markets fill with spring artichokes and early strawberries. Tourist numbers begin building gently.",
    4: "April is Brittany coming alive: 13°C, the apple orchards blooming in a pink-and-white wave that signals the cider and calvados harvest to come. Mont-Saint-Michel is gorgeous with moderate crowds and spring tides creating that famous island-to-causeway transition. The coastal hiking is superb with wildflowers, sea pinks, and dramatic cliff views. Fresh seafood — langoustines, scallops, spider crab — is at its seasonal best. A genuinely underrated French destination.",
    5: "May delivers: 16°C, 8 hours of sunshine, and Brittany's coastline at its most accessible — the beaches from Saint-Malo to Quiberon are beautiful without the summer masses. The Celtic music festival scene begins warming up, and the Breton language and culture feel particularly alive in the village markets and fest-noz (night festival) dance events. The sea is still brisk (13°C) but the coast is spectacular for walking and kayaking.",
    6: "Summer begins with 19°C days, long evenings, and the beaches filling with French families testing the water. Brittany's sea stays cooler than the Med (16°C) but the coast compensates with beauty — think dramatic cliffs, hidden coves, and that distinctive Breton light. The Festival Interceltique de Lorient preparations build, and the crêpe-and-cider culture peaks on every terrace. Crowds are moderate and the region's scale keeps things spacious.",
    7: "Peak Breton summer: 22°C (yes, that's peak), the beaches buzzing, and the Festival Interceltique de Lorient (early August in some years, late July in others) bringing the biggest Celtic music gathering in the world. Surfing at La Torche and Quiberon is in season, and the seafood plateaux at every port are spectacular. The Breton coast is busy but nothing like the Côte d'Azur crush. The sea warms to 18°C — refreshing by any standard.",
    8: "August is Brittany at full capacity: French families on vacation fill every campsite, gîte, and beach from Dinard to Concarneau. At 22°C with long days, the coast is irresistible — kayaking around the Belle-Île-en-Mer, sailing in the Gulf of Morbihan, and beach days on the Emerald Coast. The Festival Interceltique draws huge crowds to Lorient if it falls here. Book everything well ahead. The Breton butter and salted-caramel crêpes deserve a Michelin star of their own.",
    9: "September is the smart choice: 19°C, the crowds dispersing after the first week, and the coast bathed in warm golden light. The sea holds at 17°C and the beaches feel private again. Scallop season opens (coquilles Saint-Jacques from the Bay of Saint-Brieuc are legendary), and the apple harvest begins across the cider country. Walking the GR34 in September light, with the heather blooming purple on the cliffs, is world-class coastal hiking.",
    10: "Autumn Brittany is moody and magnificent: 14°C, the forests turning gold, and the coast battered by the first autumn storms. Mont-Saint-Michel in autumn fog is genuinely magical, and the oyster season in Cancale returns to full glory. The markets overflow with mushrooms, chestnuts, and new-press cider. Very few tourists, atmospheric villages, and a quality of light that watercolorists have been chasing for centuries. Pack waterproofs and an appetite.",
    11: "November is wild Brittany: 10°C, Atlantic gales, and that particular grey-silver light on the granite coast. The crêperies and seafood restaurants are at their coziest, and the absence of tourists means genuine local immersion — fest-noz events in village halls, morning markets in medieval towns, and oyster farmers happy to talk about their craft. Mont-Saint-Michel in a winter storm is humbling. Not a sunshine holiday, but deeply satisfying for the right traveler.",
    12: "Festive Brittany: Christmas markets in Rennes and Saint-Malo sell Breton biscuits, cider, and handmade goods against a backdrop of medieval architecture and twinkling lights. At 8°C with frequent rain, the atmosphere is more fireplace-and-blanket than sun-and-sand. The seafood is extraordinary — this is peak season for oysters, scallops, and lobster. New Year's Eve in Saint-Malo's walled city, overlooking the wild Atlantic, has a romance that warmer places can't match.",
  },

  'fr-corsica': {
    1: "Corsica in January is the island at its most private — 14°C on the coast, snow on the interior mountains, and almost no tourists. The maquis (aromatic scrubland) is green and fragrant even in winter, and the coastal towns of Ajaccio and Bonifacio maintain a quiet, lived-in charm. Hiking the lower coastal trails is excellent in the cool air, and the charcuterie-and-cheese scene (figatellu sausage, brocciu cheese) peaks in the cooler months. Rock-bottom prices everywhere.",
    2: "Still quiet and cool at 14°C with the mountains draped in snow and the coast enjoying crisp, sunny spells between rain. The citrus harvest is underway — Corsican clementines are sublime — and Carnival brings festive parades to Ajaccio. The interior villages feel like time capsules, and the food markets sell fresh brocciu, wild boar, and chestnuts. Skiing is possible at some of the small mountain stations. A deeply authentic month.",
    3: "Spring arrives on the coast: 16°C, the maquis erupting in wildflowers, and the hiking trails drying out for the season. The GR20 (Europe's toughest long-distance trail) is still under snow at altitude, but the lower coastal paths (Mare e Monti, Mare a Mare) are in beautiful condition. The citrus groves are fragrant, the fishing villages are quiet, and Bonifacio's limestone cliffs are dramatic against spring storm skies. Tourist numbers remain very low.",
    4: "April is Corsica's secret weapon: 19°C, wildflowers carpeting every hillside, and the Mediterranean warming to 15°C (cool but refreshing). The coastal towns open their terrace restaurants, and the seafood — red mullet, sea urchin, langoustine — is superb. Day hikes from Calvi, Porto, and the Bavella needles are spectacular without the summer crowds. The Corsican polyphonic singing tradition echoes through village churches during Easter. Genuinely magical.",
    5: "The sweet spot before summer: 22°C, the beaches accessible and empty, and the sea warming to 18°C. The GR20 begins its season in the lower sections, and the swimming holes in the mountain rivers (Cavu, Solenzara, Restonica) are irresistible. The maquis scent — rosemary, cistus, myrtle — is intoxicating in the warm air. Crowds are building but manageable, and the combination of mountain and coast is at its most rewarding. Book your ferries now.",
    6: "Summer arrives: 27°C, the beaches from Palombaggia to Saleccia looking like Caribbean postcards, and the sea reaching a beautiful 22°C. The GR20 opens fully and attracts serious hikers from across Europe. Crowds build significantly, especially on the southern beaches, but the interior mountains and remote coves still offer solitude. Corsican cuisine peaks with summer ingredients — fresh brocciu with fig jam, grilled fish, and muscat wine on a terrace above the sea.",
    7: "Peak Corsica: 30°C, the beaches packed, and the Mediterranean a blissful 25°C that makes every cove feel like paradise. The GR20 is at its busiest (book refuges months ahead), and the coast from Porto-Vecchio to Calvi is in full resort mode. The island's interior — chestnut forests, granite peaks, hidden villages — still offers escape. Corsican charcuterie, local wines from Patrimonio, and grilled fish define the table. Prices are at their peak but the beauty is overwhelming.",
    8: "August matches July's heat (31°C) and tops it for crowds — this is when all of France holidays simultaneously, and Corsica is a top destination. Every beach, every campsite, every ferry is at capacity. But the island is big enough to absorb it: find your hidden cove (they exist), hike above the treeline, or explore the interior villages where tourism barely penetrates. The sea is at its warmest (26°C) and the diving around the Réserve Naturelle de Scandola is world-class.",
    9: "The exodus: September empties the beaches while keeping the weather — 27°C air, 24°C sea, and golden light that makes the granite and maquis glow. This is arguably the best month for Corsica: warm enough for swimming, quiet enough for hiking, and the food scene shifting to autumn with chestnut flour, game, and new-press olive oil. The GR20 is still hikeable with fewer people, and the coastal towns feel relaxed and genuinely Corsican again.",
    10: "Golden autumn: 22°C, the chestnut harvest filling markets with flour, cream, and beer made from the island's defining tree. The sea holds at 21°C for late-season swimming, and the maquis turns from summer-dry to autumn-green. Tourist numbers are very low, prices drop significantly, and the interior villages host chestnut festivals (Fiera di a Castagna) with tastings and folk music. Hiking in the Bavella needles is stunning with autumn color.",
    11: "November brings the rains and Corsica retreats inward — 16°C on the coast, snow returning to the mountains, and the maquis releasing its winter perfume. The island is very quiet with many tourist businesses closed, but Ajaccio, Bastia, and Corte maintain year-round life. Olive oil pressing season brings fragrant new oil to the markets, and the charcuterie production is in full swing. A deeply local month for those who appreciate Corsica beyond its beaches.",
    12: "Winter Corsica: 14°C coast, snow-capped mountains, and Christmas celebrations in the villages with polyphonic singing, nativity scenes, and traditional Corsican feasts of wild boar, brocciu, and chestnut cake. The island is almost empty of tourists and prices are at their lowest. The coastal walks are beautiful in the cool air, and Bonifacio at sunset in December — the limestone cliffs glowing above the empty harbor — is arguably more beautiful than in the tourist-packed summer.",
  },

  'gy-guyana': {
    1: "January sits in the middle of Guyana's short dry season — expect warm 31°C days, lower humidity than the wet months, and excellent access to Kaieteur Falls before the rains swell it to full fury. Birding in the Iwokrama rainforest is superb with clear trails, and Georgetown's markets hum without tourist crowds. Malaria prophylaxis is essential everywhere outside the capital.",
    2: "February keeps the dry spell rolling with pleasant 32°C highs and the lowest rainfall of the year, making it prime time for interior expeditions to Surama and Rewa villages. The Rupununi savanna is golden and navigable, and jaguar-spotting trips along the rivers are at their most productive when animals congregate near shrinking water sources. Expect modest visitor numbers — Guyana never really gets crowded.",
    3: "March marks the transition as early showers hint at the approaching wet season, but trails remain passable and temps hold at a sticky 33°C. Kaieteur Falls is still accessible by charter flight and the flow is building impressively. Birdwatchers should target the canopy walkway at Iwokrama for harpy eagles and Guianan cock-of-the-rock before the heavy rains complicate logistics.",
    4: "April brings the long wet season's opening act — rainfall ramps up significantly and the interior roads start getting dicey, though Georgetown stays functional and steamy at 32°C. River levels rise, which actually improves boat access to remote Amerindian communities and opens up waterways that were too shallow in the dry months. Pack serious rain gear and waterproof bags for electronics.",
    5: "May is deep wet season with heavy daily downpours, 89% humidity, and roads in the interior that can become genuinely impassable. The upside: rivers are full and lush, Kaieteur Falls is at its most thunderous, and the jungle canopy is explosively green. Tourism drops to a trickle, meaning any lodge you reach will treat you like royalty. Mosquitoes are relentless — long sleeves and DEET are survival tools, not suggestions.",
    6: "June continues the deluge with some of the heaviest rainfall of the year, but the forests are alive with wildlife activity and the rivers offer dramatic boat journeys through flooded savannas. Temperatures stay around 30°C with oppressive humidity. Giant otters are active along the Rupununi, and the birding remains exceptional if you can tolerate getting soaked. Very few visitors means rock-bottom lodge rates.",
    7: "July offers a brief reprieve as the inter-seasonal dry spell brings partial relief — rainfall drops, trails begin drying, and the Rupununi savanna starts firming up for overland travel. Temps hover around 31°C with lower humidity than the preceding months. This mini dry window is a smart time to attempt interior trips that the May-June rains made impossible, though the second wet season lurks around the corner.",
    8: "August straddles the gap between rainy seasons with moderate showers and warm 32°C days — it's one of the more manageable months for exploring the interior. The Rupununi is accessible, river levels are still good for boat travel, and Kaieteur Falls maintains an impressive flow. Wildlife viewing picks up as animals move more freely in the drier conditions. Visitor numbers remain minimal.",
    9: "September can swing either way — some years the second wet season arrives early with heavy showers, others stay relatively dry. Plan for 31°C heat and humidity either way, and keep itineraries flexible for interior travel. Georgetown's food scene, built on Creole, Indian, and Chinese influences, is a year-round reward, and the Demerara rum distilleries welcome visitors without advance booking needed.",
    10: "October is firmly in the second wet season with daily downpours that keep the jungle steaming at 30°C. Interior roads suffer again, but the rivers are navigable and the rainforest is at peak lushness. Black caiman sightings along the Essequibo improve as the reptiles become more active. This is strictly for adventure travelers who don't mind mud, humidity, and the genuine frontier feel that makes Guyana unlike anywhere else in South America.",
    11: "November dumps serious rain — rivers flood, trails turn to mud, and the interior becomes a challenge that only the most committed will attempt. Temperatures hold at 30°C with humidity that makes breathing feel like work. On the bright side, Kaieteur Falls is absolutely roaring, the jungle soundscape is deafening at dawn, and Georgetown's cultural life carries on regardless. Rock-bottom prices for those who show up.",
    12: "December marks the transition back to drier conditions as the second wet season winds down — rainfall eases, trails begin drying, and the Rupununi opens up again for overland exploration. Expect 31°C days with decreasing humidity and improving access to interior lodges. Christmas in Georgetown brings lively street celebrations with a uniquely Guyanese blend of Caribbean, South Asian, and Amerindian traditions.",
  },
  'hk-hong-kong': {
    1: "Hong Kong in January is crisp and clear — 18°C highs, low humidity, and some of the best hiking weather of the year along the Dragon's Back trail and Lantau Peak. Crowds are manageable except around Chinese New Year preparations, and the city's dim sum halls and dai pai dongs are at their atmospheric best in the cool air. Layer up for evenings that can dip to 10°C.",
    2: "February often hosts Chinese New Year, which transforms the city with flower markets, lion dances, and a spectacular fireworks display over Victoria Harbour — book hotels months ahead if it falls here. Temperatures hover around 17°C with grey, drizzly days that feel more London than tropical, but the cultural energy more than compensates. Night markets in Mong Kok buzz with festive snacking.",
    3: "March brings the fog — dramatic clouds wrapping around skyscrapers and obscuring the Peak, which is either atmospheric or frustrating depending on your photography ambitions. Temps climb to 22°C with increasing humidity, and the Art Basel crowd descends mid-month, spiking hotel prices in Central. The hiking is still excellent before the heat arrives, and rooftop bars start their warm-weather revival.",
    4: "April delivers warm 26°C days with building humidity and regular rain showers that can turn Victoria Peak into a cloud bath. The Cheung Chau Bun Festival usually falls around now — a brilliantly weird spectacle of bun-climbing towers and Taoist parades on a tiny outer island. Crowds are moderate, the food scene never sleeps, and this is your last comfortable window before summer's heat wall arrives.",
    5: "May is when Hong Kong flips the humidity switch to maximum — 30°C with 83% humidity and serious rainfall that can dump 300mm in a month. Typhoon season officially begins, so keep one eye on forecasts. The upside: the city's legendary indoor food scene thrives regardless, from Michelin-starred dim sum to hole-in-wall wonton noodles in Sham Shui Po. Dragon Boat Festival preparations add energy to the harbourfront.",
    6: "June is hot, wet, and wonderful if you embrace indoor Hong Kong — 31°C with monsoon-grade downpours and humidity that fogs your glasses the moment you leave any air-conditioned space. The Dragon Boat Festival brings thrilling races in Stanley and other harbours, and the summer sales hit the shopping malls hard. Evening temple visits and night markets in the cooler hours are the smart play.",
    7: "July cranks the heat to 33°C with punishing humidity and the ever-present threat of typhoons — when a T8 signal goes up, the city effectively shuts down and everyone retreats to bars. Between storms, the beaches at Repulse Bay and Shek O are packed with locals escaping the concrete furnace. The summer food scene pivots to cold desserts — mango pomelo sago at Hui Lau Shan is practically medicinal.",
    8: "August matches July's brutal heat at 33°C and adds the Hungry Ghost Festival, when joss paper burns on every corner and outdoor opera performances spring up in car parks — it's fascinatingly eerie. Typhoon risk peaks this month, so travel insurance is non-negotiable. The outlying islands offer slightly cooler breezes, and the city's air-conditioned mega-malls become genuine refuges rather than guilty pleasures.",
    9: "September begins the slow cool-down — still 31°C and humid, but typhoon frequency eases and the Mid-Autumn Festival lights up Victoria Park with thousands of glowing lanterns and mooncake stalls. The hiking trails start becoming bearable again, and the harbour views sharpen as autumn air begins pushing out the summer haze. Hotel prices soften after the summer rush.",
    10: "October is Hong Kong's golden month — 27°C, dropping humidity, clear blue skies, and that famous harbour skyline in razor-sharp focus. The hiking is magnificent (try the MacLehose Trail Stage 2), outdoor dining on the waterfront is perfect, and the crowds are moderate. Chung Yeung Festival sees families hiking to hilltops, and the food festivals kick off. This is the month to visit if you only visit once.",
    11: "November delivers pleasant 23°C days, minimal rain, and that sparkling clarity that makes the Star Ferry crossing feel cinematic. Crowds are low, hotel deals emerge, and the outdoor markets in Sham Shui Po and Temple Street come alive in the comfortable evening air. It's prime season for day trips to the New Territories and Sai Kung's hiking trails. The city's rooftop bar scene peaks before winter chill sets in.",
    12: "December in Hong Kong is festive and mild — 19°C days, the famous Tsim Sha Tsui Christmas light displays reflecting off the harbour, and a buzzy energy as the city's legendary shopping scene enters maximum overdrive. Crowds spike around Christmas and New Year but the weather is ideal: cool, dry, and perfect for walking. End the year watching fireworks explode over Victoria Harbour from the Kowloon waterfront.",
  },
  'hn-roatan': {
    1: "January on Roatan is the dry season at its finest — 28°C, low humidity, and the Caribbean water sitting at a gorgeous 27°C with visibility that'll make your snorkel mask feel redundant. The Mesoamerican Barrier Reef is in pristine condition for diving, and whale shark sightings begin around Utila. Peak season means higher prices and busy dive boats, but the weather justifies every lempira.",
    2: "February continues the dry-season dream with warm 28°C days, calm seas, and arguably the best diving visibility of the year along the reef. Whale sharks are reliably present near Utila, and the island's laid-back Caribbean vibe is at its most appealing. Crowds remain at peak levels — book dive courses and beachfront cabanas well in advance. Sunsets from West Bay Beach are unreasonably beautiful.",
    3: "March delivers the tail end of peak season with 29°C heat, minimal rain, and that crystalline Caribbean visibility that makes Roatan one of the world's best-value dive destinations. Spring breakers add energy (and noise) to West End's bar scene, but the reef doesn't care about crowds — the wall dives and coral gardens remain spectacular. Prices start to soften slightly toward month's end.",
    4: "April straddles the seasons — still mostly dry with temps pushing 30°C, but the first hint of afternoon showers appears late in the month. Semana Santa (Holy Week) brings a wave of Honduran visitors to the island, creating a festive, local-flavored atmosphere. Dive conditions remain excellent, the water is a bathtub-warm 28°C, and shoulder-season pricing starts kicking in for the patient.",
    5: "May marks the transition to wet season — afternoon showers become regular, humidity climbs, and the lush interior of Roatan starts greening up intensely. Dive visibility dips slightly but remains very good, and the 29°C water temperature makes long dives comfortable. Crowds thin noticeably and accommodation prices drop, making this a smart month for budget-conscious divers who don't mind a daily rain shower.",
    6: "June brings proper rainy season with warm 30°C days and regular afternoon downpours, though mornings are often sunny and perfect for early dive trips. The reef ecosystem thrives with the nutrient influx, and you'll spot more marine life activity including turtles and nurse sharks. Hurricane season officially begins, though Roatan's position means direct hits are rare. Low-season prices make PADI certifications a genuine bargain.",
    7: "July offers a surprising mid-rainy-season lull — the Veranillo brings a drier, sunnier window that feels like a second summer, with 31°C highs and reduced rainfall. Dive conditions improve markedly, and the island has a relaxed, uncrowded feel that regulars cherish. Water temps hold at 29°C, and the whale sharks sometimes make late-season appearances around Utila. Keep hurricane insurance current but don't let the season scare you off.",
    8: "August sits in the heart of hurricane season with increased rainfall and occasional tropical storm watches, though direct hits on the Bay Islands remain statistically unlikely. Temps stay at 31°C with high humidity, and the reef diving is lush and green with active marine life. Crowds are at their lowest and prices at their cheapest — a full open-water certification can cost half of January prices. Monitor weather forecasts and keep plans flexible.",
    9: "September is peak hurricane season and the wettest month — heavy rains, choppy seas, and the genuine possibility that a tropical system could disrupt plans. That said, plenty of weeks pass uneventfully with warm 30°C days and good diving between squalls. The reef is at maximum biological activity, and the handful of visitors who show up get VIP treatment at every dive shop and restaurant on the island.",
    10: "October still carries hurricane risk and heavy rainfall, but the tail end of the month often sees conditions improving as the wet season begins its retreat. Water visibility fluctuates but the 29°C temps keep diving comfortable, and the lush, rain-fed island interior is at its most jungle-beautiful. Garifuna cultural events along the coast add depth beyond the beach-and-reef routine. Budget travelers, this is your month.",
    11: "November transitions back toward dry season — rainfall drops, seas calm, and the diving visibility starts sharpening back up beautifully. Temps settle at a pleasant 28°C with decreasing humidity, and the island shakes off its sleepy wet-season mood. Early-bird peak-season travelers start arriving but haven't overwhelmed things yet, making this a sweet spot of good conditions and reasonable prices. The reef's coral spawning events can be spectacular.",
    12: "December kicks off peak season with 27°C days, calm Caribbean waters, and holiday crowds that fill West Bay's beachfront restaurants. Dive conditions are excellent with improving visibility, and the festive energy on this small island is surprisingly infectious — Garifuna drumming, Christmas lights on palm trees, and fresh lobster on every menu. Book ahead for the holiday weeks, but early December offers peak-season weather at gentler prices.",
  },
  'hr-dubrovnik': {
    1: "Dubrovnik in January is hauntingly quiet — 12°C highs, 120mm of rain, and the Old Town walls essentially yours to walk without a single cruise-ship passenger in sight. Most restaurants along the Stradun operate on reduced hours, but the ones that stay open serve hearty Dalmatian buzara and peka at local prices. The Adriatic sits at a chilly 14°C, strictly for admiring from the fortress walls.",
    2: "February keeps Dubrovnik in its winter shell — cool at 12°C with regular rain showers and that dramatic Adriatic light bouncing off wet limestone walls. The Feast of St. Blaise (February 3) brings the city to life with processions, folk costumes, and locals filling the churches, offering a rare glimpse of Dubrovnik as a living city rather than a museum. Hotel prices are at their annual low.",
    3: "March teases spring with 15°C afternoons and almond blossoms appearing on the hillsides above Lokrum Island. Rain is still frequent but the sunshine hours are building, and you can walk the city walls in genuine solitude — something that costs you two hours of queuing in July. The cable car to Mount Srd offers clear-day views down the coast, and oysters from nearby Ston are at their peak season.",
    4: "April is Dubrovnik's quiet renaissance — 18°C, wildflowers everywhere, and the Adriatic warming to a tolerable 16°C for the brave. Kayaking around the Old Town walls is magical without the summer armada, and day trips to the Elafiti Islands feel like private discoveries. Tourist numbers are building but manageable, restaurant terraces open for the season, and you can actually hear the Stradun's fountain over the crowd noise.",
    5: "May delivers the Dubrovnik sweet spot: 23°C, ten hours of sunshine, and the Adriatic hitting 19°C — still brisk but swimmable if you commit. The cruise ships are arriving but haven't reached full summer saturation, so mornings on the walls and afternoons on Banje Beach feel pleasantly civilized. Fresh grilled squid and local Plavac Mali wine on a harbour terrace is about as good as Mediterranean dining gets.",
    6: "June cranks up the heat to 27°C with almost no rain and the Adriatic reaching a lovely 23°C — proper swimming weather at last. The summer festival season launches, and outdoor concerts echo off the Old Town's stone walls. Cruise ships are now arriving daily and the Stradun gets packed by midday, so early mornings are essential for wall walks. Lokrum Island becomes the go-to escape for swimming and peacock-spotting.",
    7: "July is peak Dubrovnik — 30°C, 12 hours of blazing sun, and the Old Town at maximum human density between cruise ship arrivals that can dump 10,000 visitors before lunch. The Dubrovnik Summer Festival fills every courtyard and fortress with performances, the Adriatic is a perfect 25°C, and the island beaches are buzzing. Prices are at their highest and patience is at its thinnest, but catching a Shakespeare play inside Fort Lovrijenac at sunset is genuinely transcendent.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and crowds with 30°C days, packed beaches, and the Adriatic at its warmest (26°C). The Summer Festival continues through mid-month, and evening promenades on the Stradun are a social event in themselves, albeit a sweaty one. Day trips to Mljet National Park or the Peljesac Peninsula offer crucial breathing room. Budget for premium pricing on everything and book restaurants days ahead.",
    9: "September is the smart traveler's Dubrovnik — still 27°C and sunny, the Adriatic holds at a gorgeous 24°C, and the cruise ship volume drops dramatically after the first week. The Summer Festival wraps up but the warm evenings keep outdoor dining magical, and the Peljesac wine harvest means fresh grape festivals and cellar-door tastings. Prices begin their descent and you can actually enjoy the Old Town at a human pace.",
    10: "October brings Dubrovnik back to the Dubrovnikans — 21°C, moderate rainfall, and the Adriatic still a swimmable 21°C. The cruise ships thin to a trickle, the city walls are peaceful, and autumn light turns the limestone a warm honey gold. Good Dubrovnik Film Festival adds cultural texture, and the konoba restaurants serve seasonal game and truffle dishes alongside the coastal classics. Genuinely one of the best months to visit.",
    11: "November is off-season in full effect — 16°C, regular rain, and many tourist-facing businesses closing for winter. But the Old Town takes on a moody, cinematic quality that peak-season visitors never see, and the restaurants that stay open serve soul-warming peka and black risotto without the markup. The Adriatic drops to 18°C (wetsuit territory), and you can photograph Dubrovnik's iconic rooftops without a single selfie stick photobombing.",
    12: "December wraps Dubrovnik in a festive cloak — Christmas markets fill the Stradun with mulled wine and local delicacies, fairy lights drape the Old Town walls, and the winter atmosphere is genuinely magical. Temps hover around 13°C with rain likely, but the crowds are thin and the holiday energy is authentic rather than manufactured. New Year's Eve fireworks over the harbour are spectacular, and hotel prices remain firmly in the reasonable zone.",
  },
  'hr-islands': {
    1: "January on the Croatian Islands is solitary and raw — 11°C, strong bura winds, and ferries running on skeleton schedules that can strand you on Hvar for days (not always a bad thing). Most tourist infrastructure is shuttered, but the few open konobas on Korcula and Brac serve the most honest Dalmatian cooking you'll find. The Adriatic is a frigid 14°C and the beaches are yours alone.",
    2: "February remains deep winter with 12°C days and unpredictable weather — sunshine one moment, horizontal rain the next. Carnival celebrations on some islands, particularly the medieval Korcula sword dance traditions, offer rare cultural encounters. Ferry schedules are minimal so plan carefully, but accommodation prices are virtually nonexistent. Bring a good book and a taste for solitude.",
    3: "March starts the slow thaw — 14°C, longer days, and the first wildflowers carpeting the islands' limestone hillsides in purple and yellow. Hvar's lavender fields are still months from blooming but the hiking is excellent with cool temps and no crowds. Ferry frequency improves slightly, and the handful of open restaurants on larger islands like Brac and Korcula welcome you like a long-lost relative.",
    4: "April awakens the islands properly — 18°C, sunshine building to eight hours daily, and the Adriatic creeping up to 16°C. Seasonal restaurants and hotels begin opening, ferries ramp up schedules, and you can explore Hvar Town's fortress and Vis's Blue Cave without the summer mob. Wildflowers peak on the interior hiking trails and the air smells of rosemary and sage. This is shoulder season at its most rewarding.",
    5: "May is the Croatian Islands' secret weapon — 23°C, minimal rain, and the Adriatic warming to 19°C, which is genuinely pleasant for swimming if you're not spoiled by the tropics. Everything is open but nothing is overcrowded, making it ideal for island-hopping between Hvar, Vis, and Korcula without advance bookings. The lavender on Hvar is just beginning to bloom, and the seafood is impossibly fresh.",
    6: "June flips the switch to summer — 27°C, the sea hits a lovely 23°C, and the yacht crowd starts filling Hvar's harbour with their particular brand of glamour. Beach clubs open, cocktail bars multiply, and the island-hopping scene kicks into high gear with frequent catamaran connections. Crowds are building but there's still breathing room, especially on lesser-known islands like Lastovo and Solta. Fresh grilled fish and a glass of Posip white wine at sunset — perfection.",
    7: "July means peak everything — 30°C heat, the Adriatic at a perfect 25°C, and Hvar Town becoming a floating nightclub for the yacht set. Every beach, restaurant, and ferry is at capacity, and prices reflect the demand accordingly. But swim into the quiet coves of Vis or hike Brac's Vidova Gora for that sense of island escape, and the crystal-clear water never disappoints. Book accommodation months ahead or prepare to sleep on the ferry deck.",
    8: "August is the Mediterranean at full volume — 31°C, the warmest sea temps of the year at 26°C, and every Croatian family claiming their ancestral beach spot for the month. The islands are packed, ferries sell out, and Hvar's nightlife reaches its sweaty zenith. That said, a sunrise swim in a deserted cove on Vis before the world wakes up is still achievable and still magical. Budget generously and embrace the chaos.",
    9: "September is the savvy islander's reward — 26°C, the sea still holds at 24°C, and the yacht-party crowd evaporates after the first week. Hvar's lavender products fill the shops, the wine harvest on Korcula means fresh grape festivals, and you can finally snag a table at those harbour-front restaurants that were impossible in August. Ferry schedules remain robust, prices soften, and the light turns that golden Adriatic amber.",
    10: "October is the islands' gentle farewell — 20°C, some rain returning, and the Adriatic still a swimmable 21°C in the first half. Many restaurants and hotels close mid-month, so the window is narrow but beautiful: autumn colors on the hillsides, empty beaches, and fresh olive oil pressing season adding flavor to every meal. Korcula's medieval streets feel authentically lived-in rather than staged for tourists.",
    11: "November sends the islands into hibernation — 15°C, increasing rain and wind, and ferry schedules shrinking to bare minimums. The larger islands (Hvar, Brac, Korcula) maintain a pulse with year-round residents and a handful of open restaurants, but the smaller gems are effectively closed. If you come, it's for the raw beauty of empty Mediterranean landscapes and the kind of quiet that city dwellers forget exists.",
    12: "December is for the most committed island lovers — 12°C, frequent storms, and an isolation that's either deeply restorative or slightly maddening. A few konobas on the larger islands serve Christmas meals to locals and the rare visitor, creating intimate celebrations with home-cured prosciutto and local wine. Ferry schedules are at their sparsest but the winter Adriatic light — when it breaks through the clouds — is unlike anything the summer crowds ever see.",
  },
  'hr-istria': {
    1: "Istria in January is truffle season at its most glorious — the white truffle hunt is winding down but black truffles are going strong, and restaurants in Motovun and Buzet build entire menus around them at prices that would make Italian counterparts blush. Temps hover around 7°C with grey skies and frequent rain, but the hilltop towns are atmospheric and tourist-free. The Adriatic coast is blustery and empty.",
    2: "February keeps Istria in its cozy winter mode — 8°C, occasional frost in the interior, and the kind of quiet that makes the medieval hilltop towns feel genuinely timeless. Carnival celebrations in Rijeka (technically Kvarner, but the energy spills over) are among Croatia's wildest, with elaborate masked parades. Truffle dishes remain on every menu, olive oil is freshly pressed, and a warming Istrian soup called manestra is reason enough to visit.",
    3: "March brings the first spring warmth to Istria — 12°C, wildflowers on the hillsides, and the asparagus season launching in earnest across the peninsula. The food scene pivots from winter truffles to wild asparagus omelets and fresh seafood, and the hilltop towns of Groznjan and Motovun are stunning in early spring light. Coastal towns like Rovinj start opening their terraces, and accommodation prices remain firmly low-season.",
    4: "April is Istria waking up beautifully — 16°C, increasing sunshine, and the peninsula's interior draped in wildflowers and new vine growth. Rovinj's colourful harbour fills with fishing boats and early-season visitors, but there's no crowding whatsoever. The Adriatic is still cool at 15°C, but cycling through the Parenzana trail or hiking the hilltop villages is perfect in this weather. Wine cellars are happy to pour Malvazija for a curious visitor.",
    5: "May is arguably Istria's finest month — 21°C, long sunny days, and the landscape at peak green with vineyards, olive groves, and wildflowers in full force. The Adriatic warms to 18°C, tolerable for a first dip at Rovinj's rocky beaches. Truffle season gives way to fresh fish, local asparagus, and early-season Malvazija whites that pair perfectly with the coastal light. Crowds are light and prices haven't budged toward summer peaks.",
    6: "June brings proper summer to Istria — 25°C, the sea reaching 22°C, and Rovinj transforming into one of the Adriatic's most photogenic coastal towns as the yacht crowd arrives. Pula's Roman amphitheater starts hosting summer concerts, and the hilltop wine bars in Motovun come alive with sunset tastings. Tourist numbers climb but Istria's infrastructure handles them gracefully — it never hits Dubrovnik-level density.",
    7: "July is peak Istria — 29°C, the Adriatic at 25°C, and every beach bar and seaside restaurant firing on all cylinders. Pula's amphitheater hosts major concerts and film festivals, Rovinj's harbour is packed with day-trippers, and the Kvarner coast around Opatija channels old-school Riviera glamour. Accommodation prices peak but remain reasonable compared to the southern coast. Evening truffle-hunting excursions are a unique summer activity.",
    8: "August matches July's heat at 29°C and adds the full weight of European summer holidays — beaches are packed, Rovinj's old town is shoulder-to-shoulder by midday, and every konoba needs a reservation. The Adriatic is at its warmest (26°C) and the evening sea breeze makes outdoor dining delightful. Escape the coast for a day in the interior villages, where the truffle forests and wine cellars offer cool, uncrowded retreats.",
    9: "September is Istria's golden month — 24°C, the sea still a perfect 23°C, and the summer crowds thinning dramatically while the restaurants stay open and the weather holds. This is harvest season: grapes, olives, and the first white truffles of the new season arriving in late September, meaning the food scene hits its absolute peak. Cycling the Parenzana trail through golden vineyards is autumn perfection.",
    10: "October brings the real truffle magic as white truffle season peaks and the hilltop restaurants of Livade and Buzet host truffle festivals that draw food pilgrims from across Europe. Temps settle at 18°C with increasing rain but plenty of golden autumn days. The Adriatic drops to 19°C — still dippable — and the vine-covered hillsides turn copper and amber. Accommodation prices return to earth and the peninsula feels authentically Croatian again.",
    11: "November is Istria at its most gastronomic — white truffles still in season, new olive oil being pressed across the peninsula, and young wines being tasted in cellars that finally have time for you. Temps drop to 12°C with regular grey days, and the coast turns moody and windswept, but the interior konobas are warm, fragrant, and absurdly affordable. The Kvarner coast around Opatija has a faded-grandeur charm in the off-season mist.",
    12: "December wraps Istria in festive warmth — Christmas markets in Rovinj, Porec, and Pula light up the medieval streets, and the truffle-season menus get holiday upgrades with Istrian prosciutto and fresh pasta pairings. Temps hover around 8°C with rain likely, but the crowds are thin and the atmosphere is genuine. New Year's Eve in Rovinj's harbour, with fireworks reflecting off the Adriatic, is one of Croatia's most underrated celebrations.",
  },
  'hr-zagreb': {
    1: "Zagreb in January is cold, grey, and quietly rewarding — temperatures hover around freezing with occasional snow dusting the Upper Town's baroque rooftops. The Christmas market may be over, but the cafe culture thrives: locals pack the Tkalciceva Street bars with mulled wine and strukli (baked cheese pastry) while the Museum of Broken Relationships provides indoor entertainment with a side of existential reflection. Hotel prices are rock-bottom.",
    2: "February is Zagreb's coldest month — regular sub-zero mornings and grey skies that make the city's thermal baths and cozy kafanas feel like genius inventions. Carnival season (Fasnik) brings masked parades and irreverent humor to the streets, offering a welcome burst of color against the winter palette. The food scene leans hard into comfort: sarma (stuffed cabbage rolls) and hearty bean stews dominate menus.",
    3: "March hints at spring with 12°C afternoons that get Zagreb's park-bench culture stirring again, though mornings stay chilly and rain is frequent. The farmers' markets at Dolac burst with early spring produce, and the Upper Town's streets start filling with afternoon strollers. Cultural life ramps up with gallery openings and theater season, and accommodation remains pleasantly affordable.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring — 17°C, the chestnut trees in Maksimir Park budding, and outdoor cafe terraces springing back to life along Tkalciceva. The city's green spaces are gorgeous with fresh blooms, and you can visit Plitvice Lakes (90 minutes away) before the summer hordes arrive. Rain is possible but the longer days and warmer air make Zagreb feel energized and welcoming.",
    5: "May is Zagreb at its most livable — 22°C, sunny days stretching past 8 PM, and the city's outdoor-dining culture in full swing. The Cest is d'Best street festival turns the city center into a performance space, and day trips to Plitvice or the Zagorje castles are perfect in the mild weather. Markets overflow with strawberries and asparagus, and nobody is in a hurry. This is the Zagreb the locals love.",
    6: "June brings warm 26°C days and the occasional dramatic thunderstorm that clears the air and sends everyone scrambling under cafe awnings — it's a spectator sport in itself. INmusic Festival on Jarun Lake draws big international acts, and the city's swimming lakes become weekend destinations. The food scene is at peak freshness with local produce flooding the Dolac market. Tourist numbers build but Zagreb never overwhelms.",
    7: "July pushes Zagreb into proper summer — 29°C with sometimes intense heat that drives locals to the Jarun and Bundek lakes for swimming and picnicking. The city empties somewhat as Croatians head to the coast, giving Zagreb a pleasantly relaxed feel. Outdoor cinema screenings, rooftop bars, and evening strolls through the Upper Town's cobbled streets are the rhythm. Day-trip to the Plitvice Lakes with an early start to beat the midday heat.",
    8: "August is Zagreb's quietest month — much of the city is on the coast, temperatures hit 30°C, and the pace slows to a Mediterranean drawl that feels at odds with this Central European capital. Those who stay enjoy empty terraces, spontaneous lake afternoons at Jarun, and the discovery that Zagreb in summer has a lazy charm all its own. Prices are low and the festivals keep things culturally alive.",
    9: "September brings everyone back to Zagreb — 23°C, the cafe terraces buzzing with reunited friends, and the cultural season launching with new exhibitions and theater openings. The food scene shifts to autumn mode with mushroom dishes, fresh walnuts, and young wine making early appearances. The light turns golden over the Upper Town's orange rooftops, and Plitvice Lakes in early autumn color is quietly spectacular. An underrated month to visit.",
    10: "October dresses Zagreb in autumn colors — 16°C, the parks ablaze in copper and gold, and the farmers' markets piled with pumpkins, chestnuts, and fresh apple cider. Film festivals and cultural events fill the calendar, and the konobas serve game stew and truffle pasta that pair perfectly with the cooler evenings. Tourist numbers are low, prices reasonable, and the city's Central European character — equal parts Vienna and Mediterranean — shines through.",
    11: "November brings grey skies and 9°C temperatures that send Zagreb indoors — but indoors is where this city excels, from the quirky museums of the Upper Town to the thermal baths and the remarkably vibrant bar scene. The famous Advent in Zagreb Christmas market begins in late November, transforming the city center into one of Europe's most acclaimed holiday markets. Arrive early in the season for the magic without the December peak crowds.",
    12: "December is Zagreb's showpiece month — the Advent market regularly wins 'Best Christmas Market in Europe' and it's not hype. Mulled wine, roasted chestnuts, artisan gifts, and an ice rink beneath the city's towers create a fairytale atmosphere that draws visitors from across the continent. Temps hover around 3°C so dress warmly, but the festive energy and twinkling lights make it worth every shiver. Book hotels early as the secret is very much out.",
  },
  'ht-haiti': {
    1: "January is one of Haiti's more comfortable months — 31°C coastal highs with low humidity and minimal rainfall, making it the best time to explore the extraordinary Citadelle Laferriere and Sans-Souci Palace near Cap-Haitien. Carnival preparations begin, adding energy to Port-au-Prince's streets. Tourism infrastructure is limited and security requires careful planning, but the cultural richness and warm local hospitality reward those who come prepared.",
    2: "February brings Haiti's legendary Carnival to life — a riotous explosion of rara music, elaborate costumes, and street dancing that rivals anything in the Caribbean for raw energy and authenticity. Temps hold at 31°C with dry conditions, perfect for exploring the northern coast's beaches around Labadee. Crowds swell for Carnival week, so book accommodation early. The voodoo traditions woven into the celebrations offer genuinely unique cultural encounters.",
    3: "March stays dry and warm at 32°C — excellent conditions for visiting the Citadelle Laferriere at dawn when the morning light hits the mountain fortress dramatically. The beaches near Jacmel on the southern coast are uncrowded and beautiful, and the art scene in Jacmel itself is one of the Caribbean's most vibrant. The mango trees begin flowering, and the seafood — grilled fresh with piklis (spicy slaw) — is outstanding.",
    4: "April marks the transition to the wet season with afternoon showers becoming more frequent, though mornings typically stay sunny and hot at 32°C. Easter celebrations are deeply felt across the country with church services, feasting, and community gatherings. The lush interior around Kenscoff offers cooler temperatures and dramatic mountain scenery, and the waterfalls at Bassin Bleu near Jacmel are beginning to build their flow.",
    5: "May is wet season proper — heavy afternoon rains, 32°C heat, and humidity that makes everything feel tropical and intense. The countryside turns explosively green and the waterfalls, including the stunning Saut-d'Eau, reach impressive volumes. Road conditions in the interior can deteriorate, so 4WD is essential. The rara music traditions continue in rural areas, and the local Creole cuisine — griot, diri ak djon djon — is a year-round revelation.",
    6: "June brings consistent heavy rainfall and 33°C heat that tests even seasoned tropical travelers. Hurricane season officially begins, so monitor forecasts closely. The upside: the countryside is at peak lushness, Bassin Bleu is spectacular, and the July Saut-d'Eau pilgrimage preparations begin creating a spiritual energy in the region. Tourism is at its lowest, which means genuine cultural immersion for those who navigate the logistics.",
    7: "July offers a brief dry window in some years, with temps around 34°C — Haiti's hottest month. The Saut-d'Eau voodoo pilgrimage draws thousands of devotees to sacred waterfalls in one of the Caribbean's most extraordinary spiritual gatherings. Hurricane risk demands vigilance, but the cultural calendar is rich, and the beaches at Ile-a-Vache offer Caribbean beauty without Caribbean resort pricing.",
    8: "August continues the humid, rainy pattern at 34°C with peak hurricane season demanding flexible travel plans and solid insurance. For those who navigate the weather, Haiti's beaches remain stunning — Ile-a-Vache and the northern coast offer turquoise water without a tourist in sight. The local food scene doesn't care about seasons: fresh-caught lobster with rice and beans, fried plantains, and soursop juice are daily pleasures.",
    9: "September is the wettest and most hurricane-prone month — travel requires real flexibility and risk tolerance, with heavy rains, 33°C heat, and roads that can become impassable. It's not the month for casual tourism, but relief organizations and committed cultural travelers will find Haiti's resilience and creativity fully on display in the art galleries and music venues of Port-au-Prince and Jacmel.",
    10: "October maintains wet season conditions with gradually decreasing rainfall and 32°C temps as hurricane season begins winding down. The countryside remains lush and the waterfalls impressive. Port-au-Prince's art scene — from the Iron Market to gallery-lined Grand Rue — is worth braving the logistics for, and the Creole cuisine in local restaurants offers some of the most underappreciated flavors in the entire Caribbean.",
    11: "November marks the transition back to dry season with decreasing rain and 31°C days that start to feel more manageable. The northern coast around Cap-Haitien dries out first, making it prime time for Citadelle visits without the peak-season company. The Fete Gede (Day of the Dead) in early November is a uniquely Haitian voodoo celebration that's equal parts somber and jubilant — genuinely unlike anything else in the world.",
    12: "December brings dry, comfortable conditions — 30°C, low humidity, and the start of the peak visiting window. Christmas celebrations across Haiti blend Catholic traditions with Creole warmth, and the festive markets are colorful and authentic. The beaches at Labadee and Ile-a-Vache are in perfect condition, the mountain air at Kenscoff is refreshingly cool, and the year-end energy in Port-au-Prince has a hopeful, celebratory quality.",
  },
  'hu-balaton': {
    1: "Lake Balaton in January is frozen silence — literally, as the lake occasionally freezes enough for ice activities, and temperatures regularly hit -3°C. The summer resort towns are ghost-quiet, but the thermal spas at Heviz (Europe's largest thermal lake) are magnificently steamy, and the wine cellars of the Badacsony region welcome visitors for hearty Olaszrizling tastings beside wood-fired stoves. Accommodation is nearly free by summer standards.",
    2: "February keeps the freeze going with temps around 0°C and snow dusting the vineyard-covered hills — it's beautiful in a stark, Central European way that summer visitors never see. The Heviz thermal lake remains the star attraction, with 38°C water surrounded by frosty air creating a surreal steaming landscape. Farsang (Carnival) celebrations bring masked parades to villages around the lake. A deeply local experience.",
    3: "March begins the thaw — 9°C days, the lake shaking off its winter grey, and the first almond blossoms appearing on the Tihany Peninsula. It's too cold for swimming (lake temp around 6°C), but the hiking trails through the Balaton Uplands National Park are excellent in the crisp air. Wine cellars are happy to pour, village restaurants start extending hours, and the shoulder season means you'll have the landscape to yourself.",
    4: "April warms to 16°C and the Balaton region springs to life — vineyards bud, the lake's famous reed beds turn green, and the lavender fields near Tihany begin their pre-bloom growth. Swimming is still ambitious (water around 13°C), but cycling the 200km lake circuit is perfect in the mild weather. The Tihany Abbey and surrounding village feel pristine without the summer crowds, and fresh fish soup from the lake appears on menus.",
    5: "May is Balaton's quiet opening act — 21°C, sunshine stretching the days, and the lake warming to a still-brisk 17°C that deters all but the bold. The sailing community launches their boats, vineyards are lush and green, and the charming towns of Balatonfured and Keszthely come alive with restaurant terraces and farmers' markets. June's crowds haven't arrived yet, making this ideal for cycling, wine tasting, and unhurried lakeside lunches.",
    6: "June is when Balaton transforms into Hungary's summer playground — 25°C, the lake hitting a pleasant 22°C, and families staking out their spots on the southern shore's shallow beaches. The Badacsony wine hills host tastings with stunning lake views, Tihany's lavender blooms in purple waves, and the evening promenade in Balatonfured has an old-world charm. Crowds are building but the lake is so large it absorbs them gracefully.",
    7: "July is peak Balaton — 28°C, the lake a bathtub-warm 25°C, and every Hungarian family with a summer house converging on the shore. The Balaton Sound music festival draws huge crowds to Zamardi, the sailing regattas color the lake with spinnakers, and the langos (fried dough) stands on every beach operate at maximum output. It's busy, festive, and genuinely fun — just book well ahead and embrace the holiday atmosphere.",
    8: "August matches July's energy at 28°C with the warmest lake temperatures of the year (26°C) and unrelenting sunshine. The Sziget-adjacent crowd often extends their Hungarian holiday to Balaton, and the wine harvest approaches on the northern shore. Street food festivals, open-air concerts, and sunset sailing create a holiday mood that's distinctly Hungarian — less polished than the Mediterranean but more authentic and vastly cheaper.",
    9: "September is Balaton's golden month — 22°C, the lake still a comfortable 21°C, and the summer crowds vanishing as school resumes. The wine harvest (szuret) is the headline event, with festivals across the Badacsony and Csopak regions offering tastings of the new vintage alongside roasted chestnuts. Cycling is superb, the evening light turns the lake amber, and the small-town restaurants serve end-of-season freshwater fish dishes that deserve your full attention.",
    10: "October wraps Balaton in autumn grandeur — 14°C, the vineyards blazing in gold and crimson, and the lake reflecting stormy skies between sunny spells. Most tourist infrastructure begins closing after mid-month, but the wine cellars stay open and the Heviz thermal spa becomes increasingly appealing as temperatures drop. The Tihany Peninsula's hiking trails are spectacular in fall color, and you'll share them with more deer than people.",
    11: "November is Balaton retreating into winter — 7°C, frequent grey skies, and the summer resort towns looking beautifully desolate. The thermal spa at Heviz becomes the primary draw, its steaming waters surrounded by bare trees and misty air. New wine (ujbor) is being tasted in the Balaton cellars, and the hearty Hungarian cuisine — goulash, fisherman's soup, dobos torte — is at its most comforting. Deep off-season prices and genuine solitude.",
    12: "December at Lake Balaton is quiet and cold — 2°C, occasional snow, and the lake taking on that silvery winter appearance that locals find romantic and tourists find challenging. Christmas markets pop up in Keszthely and Balatonfured, small and authentic compared to Budapest's blockbusters. The Heviz thermal lake is magical in the frost, and a glass of Badacsony Olaszrizling by a fireplace feels like the reward for braving a Hungarian winter.",
  },
  'hu-budapest': {
    1: "Budapest in January is properly cold — hovering around 1°C with grey skies and occasional snow that turns the Buda Castle district into a storybook scene. The thermal baths are the city's genius move: sinking into 38°C water at Szechenyi while snowflakes melt on your face is a top-ten travel moment. Crowds are minimal, ruin bars in the Jewish Quarter are cozy, and a bowl of goulash at the Great Market Hall costs next to nothing.",
    2: "February is Budapest's coldest stretch — sub-zero mornings are common and the Danube looks positively Siberian, but the city compensates with some of Europe's best thermal bath culture and a bar scene that doesn't care what the thermometer says. The Mangalica Festival (mangalica pork celebration) happens mid-month, and the opera and concert halls are in full winter-season swing. Bundle up and lean into the Central European coziness.",
    3: "March shakes off winter with 10°C afternoons and the first cafe terraces optimistically opening along Andrassy Avenue. The Spring Festival launches late in the month with concerts, dance, and theater across the city's grand venues. Buda's hillside neighborhoods burst with early blooms, and a walk across the Chain Bridge in the warming air feels like the city exhaling after months of cold. Prices remain pre-season reasonable.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring to Budapest — 17°C, the Margaret Island gardens in bloom, and outdoor dining along the Danube Promenade becoming irresistible. The thermal baths are still glorious (and less crowded than summer), Easter celebrations are festive, and the city's ruin bars start spilling onto terraces. Tourist numbers build but there's breathing room everywhere, and the views from Fisherman's Bastion are crisp and clear.",
    5: "May is Budapest at its most charming — 22°C, 14 hours of daylight, and the entire city seemingly outdoors. The ruin bars of the Jewish Quarter are in full swing, Margaret Island is perfect for cycling, and the Danube cruise boats offer golden-hour tours past a Parliament building that looks absurdly beautiful in the evening light. The Great Market Hall overflows with paprika, sausages, and cherries. Book now before June's price jump.",
    6: "June turns up the heat to 26°C with long, luminous evenings that make the Danube embankment feel like a living postcard. Outdoor festivals multiply — rooftop cinema, concerts at the Buda Castle, and the ruin bars becoming open-air compounds of creativity. The thermal baths are busier now but the rooftop pool at Rudas, overlooking the river at sunset, is worth any queue. Tourist season is fully underway with prices to match.",
    7: "July brings proper summer heat — 29°C with occasional thunderstorms that clear the air and send everyone scrambling under the ruin bar awnings. The city is busy with international visitors and the Sziget Festival (held on an island in the Danube) preparations begin. The outdoor pools at Palatinus on Margaret Island are packed, and evening strolls along the Pest embankment, watching the Buda Castle light up, are peak Budapest. Hydrate between the palinka tastings.",
    8: "August peaks at 30°C and the Sziget Festival (mid-month) transforms Obuda Island into one of Europe's biggest music festivals, drawing hundreds of thousands. The thermal baths offer relief from the heat, and the city's population thins as Budapestians flee to Lake Balaton. Late evenings on a rooftop ruin bar, watching the Chain Bridge sparkle, are magical. Prices are at their highest around Sziget week.",
    9: "September cools to a perfect 23°C and Budapest enters what locals consider its finest month — the crowds ease, the light turns golden over the Danube, and the wine harvest brings fresh Hungarian vintages to the city's wine bars. The Budapest Wine Festival at Buda Castle is a highlight, offering tastings with panoramic views. Thermal baths are less crowded, restaurant terraces linger in warm evenings, and prices soften noticeably.",
    10: "October is gorgeous — 15°C, the parks along Andrassy Avenue ablaze in autumn color, and the city settling into its cultural season with opera premieres and jazz festivals. The thermal baths are supremely pleasant as the air cools, and the Great Market Hall is piled with paprika, mushrooms, and autumn produce. Tourist numbers drop to comfortable levels and the ruin bars take on a cozier, candlelit character that suits the season.",
    11: "November brings grey skies and 7°C temperatures that send Budapest indoors — which is exactly where this city shines, from the ornate New York Cafe to the underground ruin bars and the soul-warming thermal baths. Late November launches the Christmas markets at Vorosmarty Square and St. Stephen's Basilica, among Europe's most atmospheric. Mulled wine, chimney cake, and the first frost on the Danube: Budapest's cozy season has officially arrived.",
    12: "December is Budapest's fairytale month — the Christmas markets are in full swing, the Danube embankment glitters with lights, and Szechenyi Baths has a festive 'sparty' atmosphere on weekend evenings. Temps hover around 3°C so thermal baths become daily necessities rather than luxuries. The New Year's Eve celebrations along the river are spectacular, and a late-night bowl of goulash at the Great Market Hall is the perfect midnight fuel. Book holiday-week accommodation early.",
  },
  'id-east-java': {
    1: "January is deep wet season in East Java — expect heavy afternoon downpours, 30°C heat, and humidity that makes climbing Mount Bromo feel like ascending through a steam room. The volcanic landscapes are lush and dramatic between rain clouds, and the lack of tourists means you might have the Tengger caldera virtually to yourself at dawn. Ijen's blue flames are still accessible but the trail is slippery — headlamps and good boots are non-negotiable.",
    2: "February continues the monsoon with similar rainfall but the reward is East Java at its most verdant — the rice paddies around Malang glow an impossible green and the waterfalls near Tumpak Sewu are thundering at full power. Bromo sunrise trips still run daily (clouds permitting), and the Javanese coffee plantations in the highlands offer aromatic refuge from the lowland humidity. Dengue-carrying mosquitoes are active, so repellent is essential.",
    3: "March is the monsoon's last act — rainfall eases slightly and sunshine hours increase, though afternoon storms remain likely. The rice terraces are at peak green, Bromo's caldera is dramatic with passing clouds, and the trail to Ijen Crater starts drying out, making the pre-dawn hike to the blue flames more pleasant. Crowds are building slightly as dry-season anticipation grows. Excellent month for food exploration in Surabaya's street stalls.",
    4: "April straddles the seasons as the dry period begins asserting itself — rain drops noticeably, mornings clear earlier, and the Bromo sunrise becomes more reliably spectacular. The Ijen blue flame trek is in good condition and far less crowded than July-August. Temperatures stay at 31°C in the lowlands but the highland volcanic areas cool pleasantly to 15°C at dawn. A sweet shoulder-season window with moderate prices and manageable crowds.",
    5: "May locks in the dry season — clear skies, low humidity, and that golden volcanic light that makes Bromo at sunrise look like another planet. Ijen Crater's turquoise acid lake is at its most vivid, and the sulfur miners' predawn trail is well-maintained. Crowds tick up to moderate levels and prices reflect the improved conditions, but East Java never approaches Bali-level saturation. The highland coffee harvests produce some of Indonesia's finest beans.",
    6: "June is prime East Java — dry, clear, 30°C in the lowlands but refreshingly cool at altitude, with Bromo sunrise reliability at its peak. The tourist season is now firmly underway, so expect company at the caldera viewpoint, but the sheer scale of the Tengger landscape absorbs the visitors. Tumpak Sewu waterfall is in its drier, more accessible phase, and the hiking across the volcanic plateau is magnificent. Book Bromo-area guesthouses a week ahead.",
    7: "July is peak season with dry, clear conditions that deliver postcard-perfect Bromo sunrises and reliable Ijen treks. Crowds are at their highest — the Penanjakan viewpoint gets packed before dawn, so consider the alternative Kingkong Hill viewpoint for slightly fewer elbows. Temperatures at the crater rim can drop to 5°C, so layer up seriously. The dry landscapes have a stark, lunar beauty that contrasts with the wet season's lush palette.",
    8: "August matches July for crowds and conditions — bone-dry, clear, and the most reliable month for that iconic Bromo sea-of-sand shot at sunrise. Ijen's blue flames are spectacular in the clear, dry air. The highland temperatures are at their coolest (possible frost at Bromo), which actually makes the predawn hike more comfortable than the lowland alternative of sweating through Surabaya's 32°C streets. Peak pricing but peak payoff.",
    9: "September starts the transition — still mostly dry with excellent visibility, but the first hints of moisture appear in afternoon clouds. Crowds thin noticeably after the first week, creating a sweet window of dry-season conditions with shoulder-season pricing. The Bromo sunrise and Ijen blue flames remain reliable, and the rice paddies begin their pre-planting preparation, turning the lowland landscape into a patchwork of muddy and golden fields.",
    10: "October brings the wet season's advance guard — afternoon showers return, clouds can obscure Bromo's sunrise, and the Ijen trail gets its first muddy patches. But the emerging green transforms the landscape, and the waterfall season begins rebuilding dramatically. Crowds are low, prices drop, and the adventurous traveler who accepts a 50/50 sunrise gamble at Bromo gets the reward of volcanic solitude that peak-season visitors can only dream about.",
    11: "November is wet season in earnest — heavy rain, steamy 31°C heat, and Bromo sunrise trips becoming a genuine lottery. The compensation: East Java at maximum lush, Tumpak Sewu thundering with renewed flow, and the volcanic highlands wrapped in dramatic cloud formations. Few tourists attempt the Ijen blue flame trek in the rain, which means those who do get an almost private encounter with one of nature's most surreal spectacles.",
    12: "December dumps heavy monsoon rain across East Java — the rice paddies flood into brilliant mirrors, the waterfalls roar, and the volcanic landscape is wrapped in theatrical cloud drama. Bromo sunrise is hit-or-miss, but a clear morning feels like a personal gift from the volcano gods. Holiday crowds from Jakarta and Surabaya arrive for Christmas and New Year, briefly spiking guesthouse demand around Bromo. Pack waterproofs and flexibility in equal measure.",
  },
  'id-komodo-flores': {
    1: "January is peak wet season on Flores — heavy rains, rough seas, and the boat trips to Komodo National Park becoming genuinely challenging with limited departures. Temperatures sit at 31°C with thick humidity, and the dragons themselves are less active, often sheltering from the downpours. The rice paddies around Ruteng are stunningly green, and the Kelimutu crater lakes remain accessible by road. This is strictly for flexible, adventurous travelers.",
    2: "February continues the monsoon pattern with rough seas that can cancel Komodo boat trips for days at a time. The upside: Flores's interior is explosively lush, Spider Web rice fields near Ruteng are at their most photogenic, and the few visitors who make it out to Komodo get remarkably intimate dragon encounters. Expect 31°C heat, high humidity, and the need for serious patience with transportation logistics.",
    3: "March sees the rains easing and the seas beginning to calm — Komodo boat trips become more reliable, and the dragons start stirring with increased activity as the wet season retreats. Flores's legendary Kelimutu volcano with its three differently-colored crater lakes is accessible with muddy but manageable trails. Crowds are minimal, dive visibility is improving, and the Wae Rebo traditional village is lush and atmospheric.",
    4: "April is the transition month — seas calm significantly, Komodo liveaboard boats resume regular schedules, and the diving around Komodo and Rinca islands improves dramatically with visibility climbing. Dragon activity picks up in the drying conditions, and the famous manta ray cleaning stations at Makassar Reef start delivering encounters. Temps hold at 31°C but humidity drops. Shoulder-season pricing and low crowds make this a smart choice.",
    5: "May locks in the dry season and Komodo comes alive — calm seas, excellent dive visibility, reliable boat schedules, and the dragons active and visible on Komodo and Rinca islands. Manta rays are reliably present at the cleaning stations, and the Pink Beach is accessible and uncrowded. Flores's interior offers excellent hiking to Kelimutu and through the traditional villages near Bajawa. This is when the region starts showing its full hand.",
    6: "June is prime Komodo — dry, warm (31°C), clear waters with 20m+ visibility, and the manta ray encounters at their most reliable. Dragon encounters on Rinca and Komodo islands are excellent, with the animals active and photogenic. Liveaboard dive trips fill up quickly now, so book weeks ahead. The famous Padar Island viewpoint delivers that iconic three-beach panorama under cloudless skies. Flores's interior is golden and dry, perfect for Kelimutu sunrise.",
    7: "July is peak season — the best diving conditions of the year coincide with maximum tourist arrivals, meaning Komodo liveaboards and Labuan Bajo hotels book out months ahead. Sea conditions are perfect, manta rays are everywhere, and the dragons are cooperative subjects. Prices are at their highest but the underwater and overland spectacles justify the spend. Pink Beach gets busy by midday, so hit it early on your boat trip.",
    8: "August rivals July for peak conditions and crowds — dry, clear, 30°C, and the marine life around Komodo at its most spectacular. Strong currents in the channels deliver thrilling drift dives for experienced divers, and the manta aggregations can number in the dozens. Flores's Kelimutu crater lakes are at their most vivid in the dry air. Book everything months in advance; Labuan Bajo has grown rapidly but still fills up in peak season.",
    9: "September delivers dry-season perfection with slightly fewer crowds than August — the diving remains excellent, manta rays are still present, and the dragons are active on their island lairs. The Komodo sunset from Padar Island is legendary in the clear September light. Flores's interior is dry and ideal for the overland journey from Labuan Bajo to Ende, passing through traditional villages and volcanic landscapes. Prices begin their gentle descent.",
    10: "October is the savvy diver's pick — conditions remain largely dry with the first hints of afternoon cloud, diving visibility stays excellent, and the liveaboard boats have breathing room in their schedules. Manta ray encounters are still good though tapering, and the dragons remain active. Kelimutu's lakes often shift color in the transitional weather, adding an element of surprise. Prices drop meaningfully while conditions stay strong.",
    11: "November brings the wet season's return with increasing afternoon rains, rougher seas, and Komodo boat schedules becoming less reliable. Diving is still possible but visibility drops and currents shift. The dragons are less active in the heat and humidity, though encounters are still guaranteed with ranger guides. Flores's interior starts greening up beautifully, and the dramatically reduced tourist numbers mean genuine interactions with local communities.",
    12: "December is full wet season — heavy rains, choppy seas, and limited Komodo boat departures that require flexibility and patience. The handful of visitors who make the journey get remarkable dragon encounters without the crowds, and the snorkeling remains decent in sheltered bays. Holiday pricing around Christmas bumps costs slightly, but Labuan Bajo's growing restaurant scene offers excellent Indonesian seafood year-round. Come for the dragons, stay for the quiet.",
  },
  'id-lombok-gili': {
    1: "January drops Lombok into the deep wet season — heavy monsoon rains, 32°C heat, and the Gili Islands' turquoise waters turning murky with reduced visibility. The upside: crowds are at their lowest, beachfront bungalow prices crater, and the lush green interior around Mount Rinjani is at its most dramatic (though the volcano trek is closed for rain). Sea turtles still appear at the Gili Trawangan snorkeling sites. Dengue mosquitoes are active — repellent is survival gear.",
    2: "February continues the monsoon with heavy afternoon downpours and choppy seas between Lombok and the Gilis, occasionally disrupting boat transfers. The surf breaks on Lombok's south coast (Desert Point, Gerupuk) get interesting swells mixed with storm energy. Mount Rinjani remains closed, but the waterfalls near Senaru — Sendang Gile and Tiu Kelep — are thundering at their most impressive. Very few tourists, very low prices, very high humidity.",
    3: "March marks the monsoon's fade — rains ease, seas calm, and the Gili Islands start showing their famous clarity again. Temps hold at 31°C but the humidity drops noticeably, and the diving at the Gili Meno wall starts improving. Rinjani stays closed but the lowland hiking and waterfall trails are in excellent shape. This is smart shoulder-season territory: improving conditions, low prices, and the beaches largely to yourself.",
    4: "April kicks off the dry season and Lombok transforms — blue skies, calming seas, and the Gili Islands' underwater visibility jumping to 15m+. Mount Rinjani reopens for trekking (check local conditions), and the surf season begins building on the south coast. Crowds are light, accommodation is affordable, and the snorkeling around Gili Air and Gili Meno delivers reliable turtle encounters. The Sasak village visits around Sade offer cultural depth between beach sessions.",
    5: "May is Lombok hitting its stride — 30°C, dry, and the Gili Islands in pristine condition with calm, clear water perfect for diving and freediving. Rinjani treks are in full swing (the three-day summit hike is life-changing), and the south coast surf builds to consistent, quality waves. Crowds are moderate and prices fair, making this the sweet spot before peak season arrives. The seafood barbecues on Gili Trawangan's beach are worth every rupiah.",
    6: "June brings prime conditions — dry weather, 29°C days, and the Gili Islands' diving at its best with 20m+ visibility and manta ray sightings possible. Rinjani is in excellent trekking condition, and the south coast surf — particularly Desert Point — draws international surfers chasing one of Indonesia's best left-hand barrels. Tourist numbers climb but the three Gilis absorb them: Trawangan parties, Air chills, Meno romances. Something for everyone.",
    7: "July is peak Gili season — blue skies, 28°C, the clearest water of the year, and every beachfront bar and dive shop at maximum capacity. The Rinjani trek is at its most popular (book permits well ahead), and the south coast surf is pumping. Gili Trawangan's nightlife reaches full volume, which is either your thing or your cue to ferry over to the quieter Gili Air. Prices are at their highest but the conditions are undeniably perfect.",
    8: "August matches July blow for blow — peak crowds, perfect weather, and the Gili Islands at their postcard best. The diving is exceptional with sea turtles at virtually every site, and the freediving community on Gili Trawangan is at its most active. Rinjani is crowded at the summit campsite but the views of the crater lake are worth the company. Desert Point surf barrels attract serious wave riders. Book everything a month ahead minimum.",
    9: "September begins the gentle slide from peak season — still dry, 29°C, and the Gilis remain in excellent condition, but the crowds thin after the first week. Diving visibility stays strong, turtles are ever-present, and the Rinjani trek has more breathing room on the trail. The south coast surf stays consistent as the swell season winds down. Prices soften and restaurant tables open up — this is the practical person's peak season.",
    10: "October straddles the seasons — mostly dry but with the first afternoon showers signaling the wet season's approach. The Gili Islands are still beautiful with decent visibility, and the reduced crowds mean dive sites feel more personal. Rinjani closes mid-to-late month as the rains approach, so early October is the last window for the summit trek. Prices drop meaningfully and the island pace slows to something genuinely relaxing.",
    11: "November brings the wet season back — daily rains, dropping visibility, and the Gili boat transfers getting choppy again. Rinjani is closed for trekking, and the party scene on Gili Trawangan shifts to a smaller, more laid-back crowd of long-term travelers and dive professionals. Snorkeling is still decent in calm-morning windows, and the Lombok interior's waterfalls start building back up. Low-season pricing for those who don't mind afternoon downpours.",
    12: "December is peak wet season with heavy rains and holiday crowds creating an unusual combination — the Gili Islands are soggy but festive, with Christmas and New Year celebrations drawing backpackers and families despite the monsoon. Diving visibility is at its lowest but sea turtles remain reliable. Accommodation spikes for the holiday weeks then drops. The monsoon sunsets, when the rain clears, are actually some of the most dramatic of the year.",
  },
  'id-raja-ampat': {
    1: "January in Raja Ampat sits in the transition between monsoon seasons — the northwest monsoon brings some rain and choppy seas, but diving conditions remain remarkably good with 15-20m visibility and warm 29°C water. Manta ray encounters at Manta Sandy are reliable, and the staggering coral biodiversity (the highest on Earth) is present year-round. Crowds are low and liveaboard prices reflect the slightly rougher conditions. Dengue precautions are essential.",
    2: "February is similar to January — northwest monsoon continues with occasional rain squalls and rougher passages between islands, but the diving remains world-class. The coral reefs are indifferent to surface weather, and the marine life density is staggering: pygmy seahorses, wobbegong sharks, and schooling fish in numbers that beggar belief. Homestay prices on Kri and Arborek are at their most reasonable, and the birdwatching (red bird of paradise!) is excellent.",
    3: "March sees the northwest monsoon easing and conditions improving — seas calm, visibility stretches to 20m+, and the diving transitions into its prime season. Manta rays remain reliably present, and the macro diving for nudibranchs and tiny critters is phenomenal. The jungles on Waigeo and Batanta are lush and alive, and the iconic karst islet landscapes are at their most dramatic against clearing skies. Tourist numbers start building from their dry-season trickle.",
    4: "April is Raja Ampat entering prime time — calm seas, clear skies, 30°C heat, and underwater visibility that can stretch to 25m on good sites. The dive sites around Misool, Dampier Strait, and Wayag are all in excellent condition, and manta encounters are near-guaranteed. Liveaboard season kicks into higher gear with boats arriving from across Indonesia. The famous Wayag viewpoint hike offers lagoon panoramas that look computer-generated. Book well ahead.",
    5: "May delivers some of Raja Ampat's best conditions — dry weather, calm seas, and the marine biodiversity at a level that makes experienced divers emotional. The coral gardens at Cape Kri hold the world record for fish species counted in a single dive (374!), and the mantas are in top form. Liveaboard prices are climbing toward peak but the diving justifies it completely. The bird of paradise displays on Waigeo are in full courtship mode at dawn.",
    6: "June is peak Raja Ampat — blue skies, flat seas, 29°C water with visibility reaching 30m on the best sites, and every liveaboard and homestay at capacity. The manta aggregations can be enormous, the reef fish clouds defy description, and night dives reveal a parallel universe of crustaceans and cephalopods. Prices are at their highest and popular boats sell out six months ahead. This is diving's Serengeti, and it knows its worth.",
    7: "July continues the peak with the southeast trade winds beginning to influence conditions — mostly favorable, keeping the air dry and the seas manageable, though some exposed dive sites in the Dampier Strait can get current-swept (which is actually where the best action is). Whale sharks make occasional appearances, and the reef manta season is still going strong. The Wayag lagoon viewpoint is at its most photogenic under cloudless skies.",
    8: "August is still prime season but the southeast trades strengthen, creating choppier passages between dive sites — experienced divers love the current-driven action this brings, with massive schools of fish and pelagic encounters increasing. Visibility remains excellent at 20-25m and the water stays at 28°C. Liveaboard demand is at maximum; prices and availability reflect this. The bird of paradise dawn displays continue on Waigeo for the rare diver who surfaces for air.",
    9: "September sees conditions begin shifting as the trade winds transition — seas can be variable, with calm days interspersed with choppier passages. Diving remains outstanding with good visibility and the full cast of Raja Ampat's marine celebrities: mantas, wobbegongs, walking sharks, and reef fish in astonishing abundance. Liveaboard prices ease slightly and the homestay experience on smaller islands becomes more intimate as peak crowds thin.",
    10: "October marks the transition to the northwest monsoon with increasing rainfall and variable seas — some days are glassy and perfect, others bring squalls that test your sea legs. Diving visibility can be excellent between weather systems, and the reduced boat traffic means some sites feel genuinely unexplored. Manta encounters continue, and the reefs are as biodiverse as ever. Liveaboard operators offer shoulder-season rates that represent genuine value.",
    11: "November is the wet season establishing itself — more frequent rain, choppier seas, and some liveaboard operators winding down their Raja Ampat season. But the diving remains remarkable, the coral doesn't care about rain, and the homestay experience becomes more intimate with fewer guests. Water temperature stays at 29°C and the nutrient-rich conditions bring excellent marine life activity. For the flexible traveler, this is Raja Ampat at its most affordable.",
    12: "December brings the northwest monsoon in earnest with rain, rough passages, and reduced liveaboard traffic — but also holiday visitors willing to brave the conditions for a Christmas dive on the world's richest reefs. Visibility drops to 10-15m on average but can spike dramatically between squalls. The homestays on Kri and Arborek offer a uniquely atmospheric wet-season experience, and the reef fish don't take holidays. Pack waterproofs for topside; underwater, it's paradise regardless.",
  },
  'id-sulawesi-togean': {
    1: "January in the Togean Islands means monsoon conditions — heavy rains, rough seas on the crossing from Ampana, and the kind of tropical isolation that either thrills or tests you. The 30°C water stays warm and the coral reefs remain stunning, but visibility drops and boat connections can be delayed for days. The upside: the few travelers who make it out are rewarded with pristine, crowd-free island life and Bajau stilt villages at their most authentic.",
    2: "February continues the wet pattern with similar rain and sea conditions. The Togean reefs — some of Indonesia's most pristine — are still diveable in calm windows, and the jellyfish lake on Kakaban Island remains accessible by kayak. Sulawesi's interior around Tana Toraja is also in wet season but the elaborate funeral ceremonies happen year-round, offering one of Southeast Asia's most profound cultural encounters. Pack extreme patience for transport logistics.",
    3: "March sees the monsoon easing across Sulawesi, with the Togean Islands getting longer dry windows and the sea calming enough for more reliable boat crossings from Ampana. The snorkeling improves noticeably, and the coconut-palm beaches emerge from the grey into tropical-postcard territory. Tana Toraja's highland scenery is lush and dramatic, and the local warung cooking — freshwater fish, Torajan coffee — is extraordinary. Crowds remain effectively nonexistent.",
    4: "April marks the proper transition to dry season — the seas calm, visibility improves to 15m+, and the Togean Islands reveal their full beauty: untouched reefs, mangrove channels, and that crystalline water over white sand that Indonesia does better than anywhere. The boat crossing from Ampana becomes reliable, and the small guesthouses on Kadidiri and Malenge islands start their (very modest) busy season. Tana Toraja funeral season picks up with elaborate multi-day ceremonies.",
    5: "May delivers excellent conditions — dry, calm, and the Togean reefs in crystal-clear water perfect for snorkeling and diving. The isolation that makes these islands special remains intact: no ATMs, limited electricity, and a pace of life set by tide and sunset. Sulawesi's Bunaken Marine Park (near Manado, north) is also entering prime diving season with wall dives that rival anything in the Coral Triangle. The few visitors who find this place tend to extend their stay indefinitely.",
    6: "June is prime Togean time — dry weather, flat seas, and the underwater world at its most vivid. The reefs around Kadidiri support an astonishing diversity for such a remote location, and the jellyfish lake swims are magical in clear conditions. Getting here still requires effort (flights to Luwuk or Gorontalo, then overland, then boat), and that's exactly the filter that keeps the islands unspoiled. Sulawesi's unique wildlife — tarsiers, maleo birds — is active in the dry forests.",
    7: "July continues peak conditions with dry weather and excellent diving, and the few dedicated travelers who navigate the logistics are rewarded with some of Indonesia's most pristine marine environments. Tana Toraja's funeral season is in full swing with elaborate ceremonies that can last weeks — witnessing one (with respectful permission) is genuinely life-changing. The highland coffee around Rantepao is freshly harvested and outstanding.",
    8: "August is the driest month across Sulawesi and the Togean Islands are at their absolute best — flat seas, 25m+ visibility, and a tropical silence broken only by waves and birdsong. This is as close to peak season as the Togeans get, which means maybe a dozen other visitors on the entire archipelago. The Bajau sea-nomad villages are fascinating to visit respectfully, and the night diving reveals an active cast of reef creatures. Deeply remote, deeply rewarding.",
    9: "September maintains dry-season excellence with the first hints of transition — afternoon clouds may build but rain is rare and the diving remains superb. The isolation of the Togean Islands means the seasons affect access more than experience: the reefs are world-class year-round. Sulawesi's northern tip (Bunaken, Lembeh Strait) offers complementary diving that's more accessible but equally spectacular. The crested black macaques in Tangkoko Reserve are active and photogenic.",
    10: "October begins the shift toward wet season with occasional afternoon showers and the seas starting to build — boat crossings from Ampana become less predictable, so build buffer days into any Togean itinerary. The diving is still good when you get out, and the islands' character shifts as the tropical light becomes more dramatic with storm clouds. Tana Toraja stays accessible by road and the funeral ceremonies continue. Flexibility is the price of paradise.",
    11: "November brings the wet season back to the Togean Islands with increasing rain, rougher seas, and boat connections becoming genuinely unreliable. Only the most determined reach the islands, and those who do find a raw, authentic experience: rain drumming on palm-thatch roofs, warm water diving between squalls, and the kind of isolation that modern travel rarely offers. Sulawesi's interior remains accessible, with Tana Toraja's landscape at its most lush.",
    12: "December is full monsoon in the Togeans — heavy rains, rough seas, and transport that requires days of flexibility and genuine adventure tolerance. A few backpackers arrive for the holidays and find themselves marooned in paradise, which is either horrifying or the best Christmas they've ever had. The reefs don't care about rain, and the diving between squalls can be magical. Sulawesi's broader attractions — Tana Toraja, Bunaken — remain more accessible alternatives.",
  },
  'ie-dublin': {
    1: "Dublin in January is dark, damp, and cheap — 8°C highs, rain on most days, and sunset at 4:30 PM, but the pubs are warm, the Guinness tastes better when it's miserable outside (scientifically unproven, universally believed), and the museums are blissfully empty. TradFest usually kicks off late January with trad music sessions filling Temple Bar's venues. Layer up, embrace the drizzle, and let a creamy pint at the Long Hall be your reward.",
    2: "February is marginally brighter than January — the days stretch past 5 PM and the odd sunny afternoon lights up the Georgian doorways like a film set. Still cold at 8°C with reliable rain, but Valentine's season fills Dublin's restaurants, and the Six Nations rugby brings an electric atmosphere to pubs across the city. The Book of Kells at Trinity is practically queue-free, and a day trip to the Wicklow Mountains reveals stark, beautiful winter landscapes.",
    3: "March belongs to St. Patrick's Day — Dublin transforms into a four-day festival of parades, music, and a cheerful green chaos that's genuinely more fun than the stereotype suggests. Temps creep to 10°C, daffodils appear in Stephen's Green, and the city buzzes with international visitors and locals alike. Book accommodation weeks ahead for the 17th, but arrive early in the month for the pre-festival calm. The Howth cliff walk in March light is magnificent.",
    4: "April is Dublin shaking off winter — 12°C, the parks turning green, and the first brave cafe terraces appearing on South William Street. Rain remains a fixture (roughly every other day) but the sunshine hours jump noticeably, and the city's cultural scene shifts to outdoor events and markets. The Dalkey and Howth coastal walks are at their springtime best, and the seafood at Howth Harbour — crab claws, fish and chips — tastes better with a sea breeze.",
    5: "May is Dublin at its most inviting — 15°C, evenings stretching past 9 PM, and the Georgian squares bursting with cherry blossoms and tulips. The Bloom garden festival in Phoenix Park draws crowds, and the outdoor dining scene along the canals comes alive. The DART to Bray for a coastal walk, followed by fish and chips and a pint overlooking the sea, is about as good as a Dublin day gets. Tourist numbers building but not yet suffocating.",
    6: "June delivers Dublin's best weather odds — 18°C, up to 17 hours of daylight, and the occasional glorious day that makes locals abandon their desks for Stephen's Green. Bloomsday (June 16) celebrates Joyce with readings and pub crawls along Leopold Bloom's route, and the summer festival season launches in earnest. Crowds are building to peak, hotel prices climbing, but the long evenings — a pint on the canal at 10 PM in soft golden light — are worth every euro.",
    7: "July is peak Dublin — 20°C (which counts as a heatwave here), the longest days of the year, and every pub garden and rooftop bar packed with visitors and sun-starved locals. Rain still happens (this is Ireland), but the warm showers dry fast and nobody cares. Kilmainham Gaol and the GPO Museum require advance booking, and hotel prices peak. A DART ride to the Forty Foot for a sea swim is a time-honored Dublin summer ritual.",
    8: "August holds July's warmth at 20°C with slightly shorter days but the same festive energy — outdoor cinema screenings, food festivals, and the Horse Show at the RDS drawing the county set to town. The Liffey sparkles on good days, and day trips to Glendalough and the Wicklow Mountains are green, warm, and gorgeous. Prices remain at peak but start softening toward month's end as families head home from holidays.",
    9: "September is Dublin's secret weapon — still 17°C with decent weather, but the summer crowds evaporate and the city settles into its cultured, literary self. The Dublin Fringe Festival and Culture Night fill the calendar with performances, and the pub sessions return to their intimate, locals-led character. The Howth cliff walk in September light, followed by oysters at the pier, is quietly perfect. Hotel prices drop and booking becomes easy.",
    10: "October brings autumn in earnest — 13°C, the leaves turning in Phoenix Park and Merrion Square, and the evenings drawing in early enough to justify that third pint. The Dublin Theatre Festival is one of Europe's best, and Halloween (Samhain, after all, is Irish) brings the Bram Stoker Festival with gothic tours and events. Rain picks up but the city's indoor culture — galleries, bookshops, pubs — was built for exactly this weather.",
    11: "November is when Dublin gets cozy — 9°C, dark by 4:30 PM, and the Christmas lights switching on along Grafton Street and Henry Street in late November. The pub sessions are at their atmospheric peak with fiddles, bodhrans, and a fire crackling in the corner. A warming Irish stew at a Stoneybatter gastropub followed by a whiskey flight at the Jameson Distillery is solid November programming. Prices are low and the city feels authentically, unapologetically itself.",
    12: "December in Dublin is festive and famously atmospheric — the Christmas markets around the Docklands twinkle, carolers fill Grafton Street, and the pubs overflow with holiday cheer and mulled wine. Temps hover around 8°C with regular rain, but the warmth inside more than compensates. The Twelve Pubs of Christmas is a dubious local tradition you'll inevitably encounter. New Year's Eve on the Liffey is lively, and the pantomime season at the Gaiety Theatre is an unexpectedly brilliant Irish institution.",
  },
  'ie-wildatlantic': {
    1: "The Wild Atlantic Way in January is raw, elemental, and not for the faint-hearted — gale-force winds, 8°C temps, horizontal rain, and seas that crash against the Cliffs of Moher with theatrical fury. The tourist infrastructure is largely hibernating, but the pubs in Doolin and Dingle keep their fires lit and their sessions going. Storm-watching from a warm window is a legitimate activity here, and the Burren's limestone landscape looks otherworldly under winter skies.",
    2: "February is similarly wild — relentless Atlantic weather with 8°C and regular storms, but the light starts returning and the first hints of spring appear in sheltered valleys. The pubs of Dingle are cozy and the seafood is outstanding: Galway Bay oysters, chowder thick enough to stand a spoon in, and pints of stout that taste like they were brewed for exactly this weather. Very few tourists, which means genuine conversations with locals.",
    3: "March brings longer days and the first real warmth (10°C feels tropical after February) as the Wild Atlantic Way begins its awakening. St. Patrick's Day celebrations in small-town Ireland are more authentic than Dublin's spectacle — think village parades, fiddle music, and everyone knowing everyone. The Burren's wildflowers start their extraordinary limestone-garden display, and the coastal walks along the Beara Peninsula are dramatic and deserted.",
    4: "April is the Wild Atlantic Way coming alive — 12°C, lambs in every field, and the Burren exploding with rare wildflowers that grow nowhere else in Europe. The coastal walks along the Cliffs of Moher, Skellig Ring, and Loop Head are stunning without the summer bus traffic. Dingle's dolphins and Galway's food scene are in fine form, and accommodation prices remain pre-season reasonable. Pack layers and a waterproof — showers are guaranteed but so are rainbows.",
    5: "May is arguably the best month — 14°C, the longest dry spell of the year (by Irish standards), and the Wild Atlantic Way at its most verdant with hedgerows blooming white and yellow. The Aran Islands are accessible without the summer queues, Skellig Michael's puffins return to nest, and the light on the Connemara coast can reduce photographers to tears. Tourist numbers are building but the roads are still pleasantly quiet for that iconic coastal drive.",
    6: "June delivers the closest thing to reliable good weather — 16°C, up to 17 hours of daylight, and the coastal scenery at its most photogenic under long golden evenings. Skellig Michael's seabird colonies are in full nesting mode (book the boat trip months ahead), the surf at Lahinch is warming up, and Dingle's seafood restaurants are in peak form. Peak season is arriving and prices reflect it, but those endless June evenings on the coast are genuinely magical.",
    7: "July is peak Wild Atlantic Way — 18°C (practically Mediterranean by Irish standards), the busiest month on the coastal roads, and every B&B from Kinsale to Donegal at capacity. The Galway Arts Festival and Races transform the city into a cultural-social whirlwind, and the surf at Bundoran and Lahinch attracts wetsuit-clad wave riders. Skellig Michael visits are at their most popular, so book months ahead. Accept that rain will happen, and let it become part of the adventure.",
    8: "August matches July for crowds and conditions — 18°C, busy roads, and the coastal towns humming with festivals, food markets, and traditional music sessions that spill out of every pub. The Connemara pony show, Puck Fair in Kerry, and countless local regattas define the social calendar. Surfing the Atlantic swells at Mullaghmore is for the experienced, while Lahinch caters to learners. The Wild Atlantic Way at full volume is noisy, colorful, and irresistible.",
    9: "September is the connoisseur's month — 16°C, the summer crowds vanishing, and the Atlantic light turning that soft gold that makes the coast look like a watercolor painting. The Galway Oyster Festival (late September) is a legendary celebration of shellfish and stout, and the surfing season builds with bigger autumn swells. Accommodation prices drop, the roads clear, and the Burren's autumn wildflowers offer a second bloom. Possibly the smartest time to drive the WAW.",
    10: "October turns dramatic — 12°C, autumn storms building across the Atlantic, and the coastal scenery taking on a moody intensity that fair-weather visitors never experience. The Dingle Food Festival is a must for anyone who thinks Irish cuisine is just potatoes, and the pubs retreat to their firesides with sessions that feel genuinely intimate. The Beara and Sheep's Head peninsulas in autumn fog are hauntingly beautiful. Layer up and embrace the elements.",
    11: "November is the Wild Atlantic Way at its most unfiltered — storms, rain, 9°C, and that wonderful Irish phrase 'soft day' being deployed with heroic understatement. The tourist circuit is effectively closed, which means the pubs, restaurants, and communities you encounter are living their real lives. A seafood chowder in Clifden after a wind-blasted Connemara walk is a peak life experience. Accommodation is dirt cheap and everywhere has availability.",
    12: "December wraps the Wild Atlantic Way in festive Atlantic weather — 8°C, storms likely, but the small-town Christmas celebrations along the coast are genuinely magical: carol services in stone churches, traditional music sessions beside roaring fires, and seafood dinners that rival anything in summer. The Wren Day (December 26) traditions in Dingle and other Kerry towns are delightfully peculiar. Pack your warmest waterproofs and lowest expectations for sunshine.",
  },
  'il-jerusalem': {
    1: "Jerusalem in January is cold and wet by Israeli standards — 12°C highs with regular rain showers and the occasional dusting of snow that turns the Old City into a scene from a medieval painting. The Western Wall, Church of the Holy Sepulchre, and Dome of the Rock are blissfully uncrowded, letting you experience these sacred sites with genuine reverence rather than tourist chaos. The Dead Sea (30 minutes away) offers warm, surreal floating even in winter.",
    2: "February keeps the winter chill going with 13°C and reliable rain, but almond blossoms begin appearing across the hillsides, hinting at the spring transformation ahead. The Old City's four quarters are navigable without the peak-season crush, and the Israel Museum's Dead Sea Scrolls exhibit deserves the unhurried attention winter crowds allow. Tu BiShvat (New Year of the Trees) celebrations add seasonal cultural flavor.",
    3: "March brings spring to Jerusalem with 17°C afternoons, wildflowers carpeting the Judean Hills, and the city entering its most beautiful seasonal window. Purim celebrations fill the streets with costumes and festivities, and the hiking around Ein Gedi and the Dead Sea is at its most pleasant before the summer heat descends. Tourist numbers build as Easter and Passover approach — book ahead if they fall in late March.",
    4: "April is Jerusalem at its most intense — Easter and Passover often overlap, bringing massive crowds of pilgrims and tourists to the Old City's narrow lanes. Temps climb to a pleasant 22°C with minimal rain, and the religious energy across all faiths is palpable and moving. The Via Dolorosa, Garden of Gethsemane, and Kotel are packed but the atmosphere is electric. Book months ahead and budget for peak-season pricing.",
    5: "May delivers warm 27°C days with virtually no rain and clear desert light that makes the Old City's limestone glow gold. The spring pilgrimage crowds have thinned, leaving behind manageable visitor numbers and a city settling into its sunny routine. Shavuot celebrations add cultural texture, and the hiking season around Masada and Ein Gedi is still excellent before summer's full intensity. The Dead Sea is warm and inviting.",
    6: "June is hot — 30°C and climbing — with bone-dry conditions and the fierce Middle Eastern sun making midday Old City exploration a sweaty endeavor. But the extended daylight (14+ hours) means early morning and late evening visits are magical, with golden light on the Western Wall and a peaceful energy as the day cools. The Dead Sea hits its stride as a year-round destination, and Jerusalem's restaurant terraces come alive after dark.",
    7: "July pushes Jerusalem into serious summer heat — 32°C with zero rainfall and a dry intensity that demands hydration and sun protection. The tourist season is busy but not at Easter-level capacity, and the Old City's stone corridors provide some natural shade. Dawn visits to the Temple Mount area and sunset from the Mount of Olives are the smart plays, leaving midday for the Israel Museum's excellent air conditioning. The Dead Sea is scorching but mesmerizing.",
    8: "August is the hottest month — 33°C and relentlessly dry — but the city maintains its magnetic pull for pilgrims and history enthusiasts. The heat actually thins some tourist crowds, creating an odd window of relative quiet at major sites during the blistering midday hours. Evening cultural events, the outdoor sound-and-light show at the Tower of David, and the cool Dead Sea breeze offer relief. Carry water everywhere — the desert is not negotiable.",
    9: "September brings the Jewish High Holidays — Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur transform the city with prayer, reflection, and the extraordinary experience of Jerusalem's streets falling completely silent on Yom Kippur. Temps ease to 29°C and the light softens beautifully. Sukkot follows with outdoor sukkah structures appearing everywhere. Religious tourism peaks during this window, so book accommodation far in advance. A deeply spiritual month to visit.",
    10: "October is Jerusalem's autumn grace period — 25°C, the last of the High Holiday energy fading into a relaxed calm, and the Old City returning to manageable crowd levels. The hiking season reopens with pleasant temperatures at Ein Gedi and Masada, and the Dead Sea is warm without the summer's punishing heat. Olive harvest celebrations in surrounding villages offer cultural encounters, and the restaurant scene thrives in the cooling evening air.",
    11: "November brings the first rains back to Jerusalem with 19°C and a freshness that the parched summer months make you appreciate deeply. Tourist numbers drop to shoulder-season levels, the Old City's wet stone lanes are atmospheric and photo-worthy, and the holy sites welcome visitors without the peak-season gauntlet. The Dead Sea remains warm year-round for that surreal floating experience. An underrated month for meaningful, unhurried exploration.",
    12: "December in Jerusalem is cold (12°C), wet, and extraordinarily atmospheric — Christmas celebrations center on Bethlehem (just minutes away) with midnight masses and processions, while Hanukkah menorahs light up the Jewish Quarter. The convergence of holiday traditions makes this one of the most culturally rich months to visit. Crowds spike around Christmas week but are otherwise moderate. The Old City in winter rain, lit by candles and lanterns, is unforgettable.",
  },
  'il-telaviv': {
    1: "Tel Aviv in January is the city at its most Mediterranean-moody — 18°C, regular winter rains, and a grey sea that locals jog along stoically in puffer jackets. The beaches are empty (by Tel Aviv standards), which means you can actually find a seat at the beachfront cafes. The food scene never hibernates: shakshuka at Dr. Shakshuka in Jaffa, hummus at Abu Hassan, and the Carmel Market buzzing with rainy-day energy. Hotel prices are at their annual low.",
    2: "February is similar to January but with the first whispers of spring — 18°C, intermittent rain, and almond trees blossoming in Yarkon Park. The city's nightlife is year-round world-class, and Purim celebrations (if they fall here) turn the streets into a massive costume party. The restaurant scene is at its creative peak during the cooler months, with chefs doing interesting things with winter produce. The sea is a bracing 17°C — for looking, not swimming.",
    3: "March is Tel Aviv's spring awakening — 21°C, the rain retreating, and the beach culture starting to stir as locals shed their winter layers with visible relief. The Bauhaus-era White City architecture looks stunning in the clear spring light, and the cycling along the tayelet (promenade) is perfect. Passover and Easter can spike hotel prices if they fall here. The Carmel Market is piled with strawberries, and the outdoor bar scene along Rothschild Boulevard comes back to life.",
    4: "April is delightful — 24°C, mostly sunny, and Tel Aviv's beaches transitioning from quiet morning-jog territory to genuine sunbathing destinations (sea temp around 20°C). Independence Day celebrations bring parties, air shows, and a patriotic energy that's fun to experience as a visitor. The Jaffa flea market is buzzing, the food scene is at peak seasonal freshness, and rooftop bars reopen with Mediterranean views. Crowds building but not yet peak.",
    5: "May is Tel Aviv at its most appealing — 27°C, cloudless skies, and the sea warming to a swimmable 23°C. The beaches are lively but not yet sardine-packed, the cycling infrastructure shines in the dry weather, and the Jaffa port area buzzes with restaurants and galleries. Shavuot brings dairy-heavy food celebrations (cheesecake everywhere), and the nightlife spills onto every available sidewalk and rooftop. Book beachfront accommodation ahead as summer pricing kicks in.",
    6: "June means summer is here — 30°C, zero chance of rain, and Tel Aviv's famous beach culture at full throttle. The Pride Parade (one of the world's largest) electrifies the city with a week of parties and celebrations. The sea hits 26°C and the beach scene at Gordon, Frishman, and Alma becomes a daily ritual. Humidity creeps in from the coast, making AC essential. The city doesn't sleep before 2 AM, and the rooftop cocktail scene is in peak form.",
    7: "July is hot, humid, and completely alive — 32°C with the sea at a bathtub-warm 28°C, and the entire city organized around beach, pool, and air conditioning. The nightlife is legendary, the beach bars pump until dawn, and the food scene pivots to refreshing dishes: cold watermelon with feta, fresh-squeezed pomegranate juice, and sabich from street stalls. Tourist numbers peak alongside the heat. Start every day with an early swim and you'll handle anything.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 32°C, humid, and the beaches packed from dawn to long after sunset. This is peak tourist season and the city pulses with international visitors mixing with locals who haven't fled to cooler mountains. The sea stays at 29°C (its warmest), making ocean dips genuinely refreshing rather than symbolic. Night markets in Jaffa, rooftop dining in Neve Tzedek, and the endless Rothschild Boulevard scene define the month.",
    9: "September begins Tel Aviv's golden season — still 30°C and sunny, but the humidity eases and the crowds thin as the Jewish High Holidays shift the city's energy toward reflection and family. Rosh Hashanah brings communal meals and the haunting sound of the shofar; Yom Kippur empties the streets entirely (one of the most surreal urban experiences anywhere). After the holidays, the city bounces back with renewed energy and excellent weather.",
    10: "October is Tel Aviv at its most balanced — 27°C, clear skies, the sea still a lovely 26°C, and post-holiday calm settling over the city. Sukkot fills neighborhoods with decorated outdoor shelters, and the beach season extends through the month without the summer intensity. The food and nightlife scenes are in top form with seasonal-menu changeovers, and hotel prices retreat from summer peaks. An excellent month that somehow flies under the radar.",
    11: "November cools to 22°C with the first rains returning — just enough to clean the dust and make the Bauhaus buildings gleam. The sea drops to 23°C (still swimmable for most) and the beach scene transitions to a more local, joggers-and-surfers vibe. The autumn cultural calendar brings film festivals and gallery openings, and the shorter days make Jaffa's lantern-lit old city even more atmospheric. Shoulder-season prices and genuine Tel Aviv character.",
    12: "December is Tel Aviv's mild winter — 18°C, intermittent rain, and Hanukkah celebrations lighting up the city with menorahs and sufganiyot (jelly donuts) on every corner. Christmas in Jaffa's Christian quarter adds festive warmth, and the restaurant scene leans into seasonal comfort food. The sea is a fresh 19°C — still surfable with a thin wetsuit. Hotel prices drop (except around the holidays), and the city has a relaxed, off-duty energy that reveals its residential charm.",
  },
  'in-delhi': {
    1: "Delhi in January is at its foggiest and coldest — 21°C days but mornings can drop to 4°C, with dense fog that delays flights and wraps the Red Fort in an atmospheric haze. Republic Day (January 26) brings a spectacular military parade down Rajpath that's genuinely impressive regardless of politics. The street food is at its winter peak: piping hot paranthas in Chandni Chowk and gajar ka halwa (carrot pudding) on every corner. Layer up for morning rickshaw rides.",
    2: "February brings the fog lifting and Delhi entering its most pleasant window — 24°C, clear skies, and the Mughal gardens at Rashtrapati Bhavan opening for the annual bloom. Rajasthan's palace cities (Jaipur, Jodhpur, Udaipur) are in perfect condition for touring, with warm days and cool nights. The Surajkund Crafts Mela draws artisans from across India. This is the sweet spot before the heat arrives — take advantage of every comfortable day.",
    3: "March warms rapidly to 31°C and the Holi festival (usually mid-March) transforms Delhi and Rajasthan into a kaleidoscope of colored powder, water balloons, and uninhibited celebration — it's chaotic, joyful, and absolutely unmissable. The weather is still manageable for sightseeing at Humayun's Tomb and Qutub Minar, though afternoons get warm. Rajasthan's desert forts are comfortable before the furnace of April-May arrives.",
    4: "April starts getting serious about heat — 36°C and climbing, with a dusty intensity that makes air-conditioned museum visits suddenly very appealing. The crowds thin as casual tourists flee the thermometer, leaving the Mughal monuments in relative peace. Rajasthan is hot but the desert light at Jaisalmer and Jodhpur is extraordinary for photographers. Evening street food in Old Delhi — chaat, kebabs, lassi — becomes the highlight as the day cools.",
    5: "May is Delhi at its most brutal — 42°C highs, dust storms (loo winds) that sting your eyes, and a pre-monsoon tension that makes the city feel like it's holding its breath. This is strictly for the budget-conscious or the heat-adapted: hotel prices crater and the major sites are virtually empty. Rajasthan's desert reaches furnace temperatures. If you come, plan around AC, early mornings, and the genuinely excellent indoor dining scene.",
    6: "June is the monsoon's dramatic overture — 40°C giving way to the first thunderstorms that break the heat with almost religious intensity. When the rains arrive (usually mid-to-late June), Delhi transforms: the air cools, the dust settles, and the parched parks turn green within days. Rajasthan's palaces in the rain are unexpectedly romantic, and the monsoon thali meals — featuring seasonal greens and fresh corn — are a revelation. Humidity soars but the relief is palpable.",
    7: "July is full monsoon — heavy daily rains, 35°C with extreme humidity, and Delhi's streets alternating between flooded and steaming. The city is lush and green in a way that dry-season visitors never see, and the food scene peaks with monsoon specialties: pakoras during downpours, masala chai at every chai-wallah, and seasonal mango desserts. Rajasthan's lakes fill, Udaipur looks like a watercolor, and the Thar Desert briefly blooms. Bring waterproof everything.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon with daily downpours, 34°C heat, and humidity that makes every Auto rickshaw ride feel like a sauna. Independence Day (August 15) brings ceremonies at the Red Fort and patriotic energy across the city. The monsoon Rajasthan — green desert, full lakes, dramatic skies — is genuinely stunning if you don't mind the logistics of wet travel. Street food vendors are unfazed by rain, and a bowl of nihari in Old Delhi transcends weather.",
    9: "September is the monsoon's retreat — rainfall eases, the air remains humid but cooling, and Delhi's parks and gardens are at maximum green lushness. The monsoon light produces gorgeous golden evenings over the Mughal monuments, and Navratri celebrations begin building toward Dussehra, with the dramatic Ramlila performances across the city. Rajasthan is emerald-green and increasingly accessible. A surprisingly beautiful month that few tourists target.",
    10: "October is Delhi's redemption month — the monsoon is gone, temperatures settle to a perfect 33°C, and the festivals of Dussehra and Diwali light up the city (literally, in Diwali's case) with fireworks, oil lamps, and an infectious celebratory energy. Rajasthan is in prime condition: green from the rains, pleasant temperatures, and the palace hotels offering their best seasonal rates. The food, the light, the energy — October makes you understand why people love this city.",
    11: "November is Delhi at its most regal — 28°C, clear skies, and the pollution haze (acknowledged but real post-Diwali) giving way to crisp winter days. Rajasthan enters peak tourist season with perfect weather for Jaipur's Amber Fort, Jodhpur's Mehrangarh, and Udaipur's lake palaces. The Pushkar Camel Fair (if it falls here) is India's most photogenic cultural event. Hotel prices rise with the quality of the weather, and rightly so.",
    12: "December is peak Delhi and Rajasthan — 23°C, sunny days, chilly mornings (bring a jacket for pre-dawn Taj Mahal visits from Delhi), and every heritage hotel booked solid for Christmas and New Year. The street food scene in Chandni Chowk is glorious in the cool air, and the Ranthambore tiger safaris from Jaipur are in prime season. Budget for peak pricing and crowds at major monuments, but the golden winter light on red sandstone is worth every rupee.",
  },
  'in-himalaya': {
    1: "The Himalayan North in January is deep winter — heavy snowfall blankets Shimla, Manali, and Ladakh (which is largely inaccessible by road), with temperatures well below freezing at altitude. Ski season at Gulmarg in Kashmir offers surprisingly excellent powder on uncrowded slopes, and the Spiti Valley's frozen landscapes are stark and magnificent for those willing to brave -20°C mornings. Rishikesh and Dharamsala at lower elevations remain accessible with cool 15°C days.",
    2: "February maintains the winter freeze at high altitude — Ladakh roads are closed, Manali is snow-bound, and the Himalayan passes are firmly shut. But Gulmarg's skiing peaks this month with reliable snow, and the lower hill stations (Dharamsala, McLeod Ganj) offer crisp, clear days perfect for visiting Tibetan monasteries and trekking gentle trails. The Dalai Lama sometimes gives public teachings in Dharamsala during winter. Pack serious cold-weather gear.",
    3: "March begins the Himalayan thaw — lower elevations like Rishikesh warm to 25°C with the Ganges running cold and clear, perfect for white-water rafting season. The hill stations at mid-elevation see their first warm days between cold snaps, and rhododendrons begin their explosive bloom in Uttarakhand. High-altitude passes remain closed, but the anticipation of the approaching trekking season is palpable. Holi celebrations in the foothills are colorfully chaotic.",
    4: "April is the Himalayan spring — rhododendron forests explode in red, pink, and white at mid-elevations, and the trekking season opens in earnest with the Valley of Flowers beginning to thaw. Dharamsala and Shimla hit a pleasant 22°C, and Rishikesh's rafting season is in full swing. Ladakh remains closed (Manali-Leh highway won't open until June), but the Garhwal and Kumaon regions offer excellent early-season treks. Clear mountain views before the monsoon haze.",
    5: "May is peak pre-monsoon trekking — warm days (25-30°C at lower elevations, comfortable at altitude), clear Himalayan views, and the trails in full operation before the June rains arrive. The trek to Tungnath and Chandrashila offers panoramic snow-peak views, and the Kullu Valley is lush and accessible. Ladakh starts opening as the Manali-Leh highway clears (usually late May). The heat in the plains drives Indians to the hill stations, so expect crowds in Shimla and Mussoorie.",
    6: "June is a split month — the monsoon hits the lower Himalayas hard from mid-June, making trekking in Uttarakhand and Himachal wet and leech-heavy, but Ladakh (in the rain shadow) opens fully with the Manali-Leh highway accessible and the stark, high-desert landscapes at their most dramatic. Pangong Lake, Nubra Valley, and the monasteries of Leh are in prime condition. Rishikesh's Ganges is rising and rafting gets more exciting. Two different worlds on either side of the mountain wall.",
    7: "July is full monsoon in most of the Himalayan North — cascading waterfalls, lush green valleys, leeches on every trail, and the kind of dramatic weather that makes trekking in Himachal and Uttarakhand a serious wet-weather commitment. Ladakh, however, is bone-dry, sunny, and in peak season: the Zanskar trek, Pangong Lake, and the monastery festivals draw crowds to this high-altitude desert. Amarnath Yatra pilgrimage brings thousands to the sacred cave.",
    8: "August maintains the monsoon-Ladakh split — the lower Himalayas are soaked and green (the Valley of Flowers is at peak bloom, reaching it requires trekking through rain), while Ladakh bakes in dry sunshine at peak tourist capacity. The Hemis and Phyang monastery festivals in Ladakh feature spectacular masked dances. River rafting on the Zanskar is at its most thrilling with high water levels. Book Ladakh accommodation weeks ahead — supply has not caught up with demand.",
    9: "September is the monsoon's graceful exit — the rains ease across the lower Himalayas, revealing emerald-green valleys, snow-capped peaks freshly dusted, and trekking trails that are muddy but clearing. The post-monsoon window offers some of the clearest mountain views of the year as the atmosphere cleans up. Ladakh remains excellent though cooling rapidly at night. The Nanda Devi region and Kumaon hills are spectacular in the crisp, post-rain air.",
    10: "October is the Himalayan sweet spot — clear skies, crisp 15-20°C days at mid-elevation, and the mountain panoramas at their most sharp and dramatic. Trekking season peaks with perfect conditions for classics like Hampta Pass, Kedarkantha, and the Markha Valley in Ladakh (before it closes). Dussehra celebrations in Kullu are one of India's most spectacular festival experiences. The autumn colors in the Parvati and Spiti valleys are quietly stunning.",
    11: "November brings the first serious cold — high passes begin closing, Ladakh shuts down for winter (roads close), and the hill stations drop below 10°C with the first snowfall at higher elevations. But lower Himalayan treks (Triund from Dharamsala, Chopta-Tungnath in Uttarakhand) offer crisp, clear conditions with spectacular views. Rishikesh cools to a perfect 22°C for yoga retreats and gentle hiking. The tourist crowds thin to near zero at most destinations.",
    12: "December is deep Himalayan winter — Ladakh is closed, Manali is under snow, and the high passes are sealed until spring. But Gulmarg's ski season launches, Rishikesh is at its most serene and cool (18°C), and Dharamsala's Tibetan community celebrates Losar preparations. The brave can trek Kedarkantha through fresh snow for one of India's most magical winter experiences. This is the Himalayas stripped to its essence: quiet, cold, and profoundly beautiful.",
  },
  'in-kerala': {
    1: "Kerala in January is the south Indian dream — 32°C, minimal rain, and the backwaters around Alleppey gliding in a houseboat through palm-fringed canals is one of travel's most peaceful experiences. Pongal harvest celebrations bring color and feasting, and the beaches at Varkala and Kovalam are in prime condition with calm seas. Ayurvedic resorts in Kumarakom are booked solid — this is peak season with prices to match. The seafood thali is a daily revelation.",
    2: "February maintains peak conditions — 33°C, dry, and the backwaters at their most navigable and scenic. Theyyam festival season in northern Kerala brings extraordinary ritual performances where dancers channel deities through elaborate costumes and face paint — it's visceral and unforgettable. The beaches remain pristine, the Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary offers excellent elephant and birdwatching in the dry conditions, and the spice plantations in Munnar are wonderfully aromatic.",
    3: "March heats up to 34°C with humidity beginning to build, signaling the approach of the pre-monsoon season. The backwaters are still excellent and the beaches remain dry, but the increasing warmth makes midday activities less comfortable. The Holi festival adds color, and the wildlife viewing at Periyar is at its best as animals congregate near water sources. Prices begin softening from peak, making this a value sweet spot for those who handle heat well.",
    4: "April brings pre-monsoon showers and rising humidity — 34°C with afternoon thunderstorms that are dramatic but brief. The Thrissur Pooram (usually April/May) is Kerala's most spectacular temple festival, with caparisoned elephants, thundering percussion, and fireworks that shake the ground. The backwaters get their first monsoon energy, the hillside tea plantations of Munnar are refreshingly cool, and Vishu (Kerala New Year) brings festive family celebrations.",
    5: "May is hot and humid — 33°C with pre-monsoon storms becoming frequent and intense. The southwest monsoon's arrival (usually late May/early June) is one of nature's great spectacles as the Arabian Sea hurls rain at the Kerala coast. The snake boat race season begins with Vallam Kali practices on the backwaters, and Ayurvedic tradition considers monsoon the ideal time for rejuvenation treatments. Crowds thin and prices drop — the smart traveler's window opens.",
    6: "June welcomes the full monsoon — dramatic daily rains transform Kerala into an impossibly green landscape, with waterfalls at full thunder and the backwaters swelling to their most dramatic. Ayurvedic resorts enter peak treatment season (the monsoon humidity supposedly opens the body's pores for deeper absorption), and the rates at heritage properties drop significantly. The beaches are rough and grey, but a fresh fish curry eaten to the sound of monsoon rain is peak Kerala.",
    7: "July is deep monsoon — heavy, persistent rain that turns the Western Ghats into a cascading green waterfall and the Kerala coast into a grey, churning spectacle. This is considered the best month for Ayurvedic treatments, with dedicated visitors checking into Kovalam and Kumarakom retreats for multi-week panchakarma therapies. The Champakulam snake boat race is thrilling in the rain. Tourist crowds are at their lowest and the lush beauty is extraordinary if you embrace getting wet.",
    8: "August keeps the monsoon going strong with the legendary Nehru Trophy Boat Race on Punnamada Lake — snake boats with 100+ rowers competing in a spectacle that draws massive local crowds. The rains are relentless, the greenery almost aggressive in its intensity, and the Ayurvedic season continues. Onam (Kerala's harvest festival, usually August/September) brings elaborate flower carpets, feasting, and the stunning Onam Sadhya banana-leaf meal. Monsoon Kerala is not for everyone, but it's deeply authentic.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon easing — rainfall drops, the skies clear between showers, and Kerala begins revealing its post-monsoon beauty: every shade of green imaginable, refreshed waterfalls, and the backwaters at their highest and most navigable. Onam celebrations (if they fall here) are the cultural highlight of the Kerala year. The beaches start calming and the surf at Varkala gets interesting autumn swells. Periyar's wildlife emerges with the improving weather.",
    10: "October brings the northeast monsoon's last push — lighter but still regular rains, 31°C, and Kerala in a transitional beauty between monsoon lush and dry-season clarity. The backwaters are excellent for houseboat cruises, the tea plantations of Munnar are fog-draped and atmospheric, and the Sabarimala pilgrimage season adds spiritual depth. Tourist numbers start building toward the November-February peak, and prices begin their seasonal climb.",
    11: "November officially launches Kerala's tourist season — the monsoon is done, 32°C days are sunny and clear, and the backwaters, beaches, and hill stations are all in excellent condition simultaneously. Theyyam season kicks off again in northern Kerala, and the Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary offers increasingly good sightings as the dry season concentrates animals. Houseboat bookings fill fast, so reserve ahead. This is Kerala showing its full hand.",
    12: "December is peak Kerala — 32°C, dry, and every houseboat, beach resort, and Ayurvedic retreat booked solid for the holidays. The Cochin Carnival (end of December) fills Fort Kochi with street theater, music, and a spectacular New Year's Eve parade. The Christmas celebrations in Kerala's Syrian Christian communities are uniquely elaborate. Peak pricing is in full effect, but a Kerala fish curry in a thatched restaurant overlooking the backwaters is worth every inflated rupee.",
  },
  'in-kolkata': {
    1: "Kolkata in January is at its most pleasant — 26°C, low humidity, and a winter crispness that makes exploring the colonial architecture along the Hooghly River genuinely comfortable. The literary and arts festival season is in full swing, and the street food along Park Street and College Street is at its atmospheric best: kathi rolls, phuchka, and Bengali mishti doi in terracotta cups. The Sundarbans mangrove tigers are most active in the cooler months.",
    2: "February keeps the pleasant weather rolling — 29°C, still dry, and the Saraswati Puja celebrations draping the city in yellow flowers and music. The Sundarbans are in prime tiger-spotting season with calm waterways and cooler temperatures that bring the big cats to riverbanks for warmth. Kolkata's famous sweet shops are always worth visiting, but the fresh rosogolla and sandesh taste even better in the cool morning air. Book a sunrise boat on the Hooghly.",
    3: "March warms to 34°C with humidity building — Kolkata starts showing its tropical character as the pre-monsoon heat settles in. Holi celebrations are colorful and enthusiastic, and the city's nightlife and cultural scene (theater, music, galleries) maintain their year-round excellence. The Sundarbans become less comfortable as heat and humidity build, but the bird life is still excellent. The street food doesn't care about seasons — grab a plate of luchi-alur dom at any hour.",
    4: "April brings serious heat — 36°C with building humidity that makes Kolkata feel like a steam bath. Nababorsho (Bengali New Year, April 14) is celebrated with music, art, and feasting across the city, giving you cultural sustenance to match the meteorological challenge. The Sundarbans are hot and humid but the mangrove forests provide shade. Start every morning with a Kolkata-style chai from a street stall and plan indoor activities for the midday furnace.",
    5: "May is Kolkata's hottest month — 37°C with pre-monsoon storms (Nor'westers) that arrive with terrifying drama: black skies, lightning, and a 20-degree temperature drop in minutes. The storms are actually a highlight if you're safely indoors watching from a cafe. Rabindra Jayanti (Tagore's birthday) brings cultural celebrations, and the mango season hits Kolkata's markets with Alphonso and Langda varieties. The heat is punishing but the city's resilient energy endures.",
    6: "June brings the monsoon's dramatic arrival — the skies open, the temperature drops to 34°C (relief!), and Kolkata's streets transform into rivers during heavy downpours. The city has a complex relationship with the rains: flooding is a real issue, but the monsoon also brings cooling relief, fresh fish, and ilish (hilsa) season — the Bengali obsession. Kolkata's restaurants serve ilish in a dozen preparations, each more compelling than the last. Carry an umbrella and waterproof shoes.",
    7: "July is deep monsoon — heavy, persistent rain, 33°C with extreme humidity, and Kolkata at its most soggy and atmospheric. The Rath Yatra chariot festival brings enormous crowds to the streets despite the weather, pulling massive temple chariots through rain-soaked roads. Ilish season peaks and every Bengali table features the silver fish. The Sundarbans are green and wild but travel is difficult. This is Kolkata for the committed: raw, real, and deeply flavorful.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon with heavy rain and humidity, but Independence Day (August 15) brings patriotic celebrations to the Maidan, and the approach of Durga Puja season energizes the entire city with anticipation. Craftsmen begin building the elaborate pandals (temporary temples) that will house the goddess in October. The street food scene thrives regardless of weather, and a monsoon evening of kathi rolls and cold Kingfisher beer has its own charm.",
    9: "September is the monsoon's slow retreat — rains ease, the city dries out in patches, and the pre-Durga Puja energy reaches fever pitch. Mahalaya (the invocation of Durga, broadcast on All India Radio at 4 AM) is a genuinely moving cultural moment that wakes the entire city. The pandal constructions become visible across neighborhoods, and the food scene starts its festival preparations. Kolkata in pre-Puja mode is electric with anticipation.",
    10: "October is Kolkata's defining month — Durga Puja transforms the city into a five-day celebration that defies description: thousands of pandals, millions of people on the streets, artistic installations that rival gallery exhibitions, and an energy that's part religious devotion, part street carnival, part fashion show. Temps settle to 32°C with the monsoon gone, and the entire city stays up all night eating, socializing, and pandal-hopping. If you visit Kolkata once, make it October.",
    11: "November brings post-Puja calm and some of the year's best weather — 29°C, clear skies, and a relaxed city recovering from the festivities with a satisfied energy. The Kolkata International Film Festival usually falls this month, adding cultural depth. The Sundarbans reopen for prime tiger-tracking season, and the street food culture — always present — feels particularly rewarding in the comfortable evenings. Diwali adds another burst of festive light. A quietly excellent month to visit.",
    12: "December is Kolkata at its most comfortable — 24°C, crisp mornings, and the colonial-era Park Street Christmas celebrations giving this Hindu-majority city a surprisingly festive December character, complete with fairy lights and carol singing. The food scene peaks with winter specialties: pithe (sweet rice cakes), nolen gur (date palm jaggery) in every mishti, and fresh sandesh. The Sundarbans are in prime condition for safaris, and the city's literary cafes are at their atmospheric best.",
  },
  'in-mumbai': {
    1: "Mumbai in January is the city at its peak — 32°C, zero rain, and a pleasant sea breeze that makes Marine Drive's evening promenade (the 'Queen's Necklace') genuinely magical. The Kala Ghoda Arts Festival fills the historic Fort district with installations, performances, and street food stalls. Colaba Causeway buzzes, the Elephanta Caves are accessible with calm seas, and a vada pav from the stalls near Dadar station costs 20 rupees and tastes like Mumbai itself.",
    2: "February maintains January's perfect conditions — 33°C, bone-dry, and the city's restaurant scene at its most ambitious with outdoor dining events and pop-ups. The Mumbai International Film Festival (MAMI) brings global cinema to this most cinematic of cities, and the weekend trip to the Ajanta and Ellora caves from here is in ideal weather. The seafood at Mahesh Lunch Home or the street-side Juhu Beach stalls is year-round excellent but tastes best in the cool evening air.",
    3: "March heats up to 34°C with humidity beginning to build from the Arabian Sea — not yet monsoon-heavy but enough to make midday exploration sticky. Holi celebrations turn the city into a color-bomb zone of joyful mayhem, and the Gateway of India is atmospheric in the pre-monsoon light. The Elephanta Festival sometimes falls in March, bringing classical music and dance to the island amphitheater. Last comfortable month for long outdoor walks.",
    4: "April begins Mumbai's hot season — 35°C with rising humidity that makes the city feel like it's slowly being wrapped in a warm, damp towel. The beaches at Juhu and Versova are for evening visits only, and the air-conditioned malls and restaurants become genuine refuges. The Banganga Tank and the Chor Bazaar are atmospheric even in the heat, and Mumbai's legendary street food — pani puri, bhel puri, pav bhaji — doesn't skip a beat regardless of temperature.",
    5: "May is Mumbai at its most intense pre-monsoon — 35°C with suffocating humidity and dust that makes the skyline hazy and the local trains a sweaty endurance test. But the city doesn't slow down: the restaurant scene is year-round excellent, the nightlife in Bandra and Lower Parel thrives in AC comfort, and the mango season floods Crawford Market with Alphonso and Hapus varieties. The imminent monsoon creates a tension in the air that's almost palpable.",
    6: "June brings the monsoon — and in Mumbai, it arrives with spectacular force. The first rains send the city into celebration: people dance in the streets, chai sales skyrocket, and the Arabian Sea churns against Marine Drive's sea wall, sending spray 20 feet into the air. Temps drop to a manageable 30°C but humidity maxes out. Flooding is common and commutes become adventures. Bhutta (roasted corn) and pakoras in the rain are essential monsoon Mumbai experiences.",
    7: "July is peak monsoon — Mumbai receives more rain this month than London gets in a year, and the city's relationship with its flooding is a complex mix of frustration, resilience, and dark humor. The local trains become unreliable, the streets flood regularly, but the street food thrives: hot vada pav, steaming cutting chai, and monsoon-special items like batatawada. The city looks its greenest and Sanjay Gandhi National Park's waterfalls are thundering. Come for the experience, not the comfort.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon deluge with some of the heaviest rainfall of the year — Ganesh Chaturthi (usually August/September) brings millions into the streets with massive Ganesh idols, drumming processions, and the dramatic visarjan (immersion) in the Arabian Sea. It's Mumbai at its most passionately festive, rain be damned. The monsoon seafood (pomfret, surmai) is at its seasonal best, and a evening of live Bollywood music in Bandra is quintessential Mumbai.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon easing — rainfall decreases, the humidity starts dropping, and the city begins drying out with visible relief. Ganesh Chaturthi (if it falls here) is the highlight, and the Navratri celebrations bring dandia and garba dance nights to every neighborhood. The food scene transitions from monsoon comfort to festival feasting. The Gateway of India and Marine Drive start showing their dry-season beauty, and hotel prices begin climbing toward peak season.",
    10: "October is Mumbai's monsoon farewell — the rains stop, the city dries out, and the Diwali celebrations light up every neighborhood with oil lamps, fireworks, and an infectious festive energy. Temps hold at 33°C but the humidity drops dramatically, making Marine Drive evening walks pleasant again. The Elephanta Caves, Colaba's art galleries, and the revived street market scene are all in fine form. Diwali's mithai (sweets) shops are a destination in themselves.",
    11: "November brings Mumbai's best weather — 33°C, dry, and the post-Diwali city settling into its comfortable, cosmopolitan routine. The Prithvi Theatre Festival fills Juhu with cutting-edge performances, and the Mumbai Marathon preparations begin energizing the running community. The Arabian Sea calms, the Elephanta Ferry runs smoothly, and a sunset Chowpatty Beach stroll with bhel puri is Mumbai at its most iconic. Hotels fill with business and leisure travelers — book ahead.",
    12: "December is peak Mumbai — 32°C, dry, a festive holiday energy, and the city's restaurant scene pulling out all stops for the year-end celebrations. Christmas in Bandra's Catholic enclaves is colorful and warm, and New Year's Eve on Marine Drive draws lakhs of revelers for the midnight fireworks. The Gateway of India gleams, the street food never sleeps, and a glass of Sula Vineyards' Nasik wine at a Colaba rooftop bar feels like a fitting toast to one of the world's great cities.",
  },

  'ki-kiribati': {
    1: "January on the equator means one thing: heat. Expect 31°C, daily tropical downpours (around 200mm for the month), and humidity that clings like a second skin. The upside? You'll have these remote atolls almost entirely to yourself — bonefishing in the flats of Christmas Island is world-class, and the coral reefs are teeming with life beneath the warm 29°C lagoon water.",
    2: "February keeps the wet season rolling with heavy showers and 31°C days, but between squalls the Pacific light is extraordinary. Seabirds nest in vast colonies on the uninhabited motus, making this a birder's pilgrimage — sooty terns and red-footed boobies by the thousands. Crowds are essentially nonexistent; you're more likely to share the beach with a coconut crab than another tourist.",
    3: "March is peak wet season — expect 250mm+ of rain and thick humidity, but the lagoons are glassy calm and the bonefishing remains exceptional. The atolls feel impossibly remote and lush, with coconut palms swaying over turquoise shallows. Dive visibility can dip after storms, but patient snorkelers still find pristine coral gardens. Bring serious sun protection; equatorial UV is relentless even under cloud cover.",
    4: "April starts easing out of the wettest stretch, though showers remain a daily fixture at 31°C. The reef systems around Tarawa and Kiritimati are vibrant, with manta rays cruising the channels. This is still ultra-low-season — lodges are basic, flights are infrequent, and that's exactly the point. Pack reef-safe sunscreen and embrace the slow Pacific rhythm.",
    5: "May marks the transition toward drier conditions, with rainfall tapering and trade winds picking up to temper the 31°C heat. The bonefishing flats of Christmas Island enter their prime window — guides talk about May in reverent tones. Snorkeling visibility improves noticeably, and the coconut crab population is active on outer motus after dark. Logistics remain bare-bones, so bring everything you might need.",
    6: "June settles into the dry season with less rain, steady trade winds, and that endless equatorial sunshine pushing 31°C daily. The ocean calms to glass on the leeward sides, making kayaking across the lagoons genuinely magical. Birdlife peaks as frigatebirds display their inflated red throat pouches in elaborate courtship dances. You won't find crowds or luxury — just raw, magnificent isolation.",
    7: "July is dry-season prime: minimal rainfall, reliable winds keeping humidity bearable, and the Pacific stretched out impossibly blue in every direction. Kiritimati's bonefishing is in full swing and the flats shimmer under 12 hours of equatorial sun. The handful of visitors who make it here tend to be serious anglers or marine biologists. Bring a good hat, a stronger sunscreen, and zero expectations of nightlife.",
    8: "August continues the dry spell with the lowest rainfall of the year and those reliable easterly trades. Water temperatures hold at 28°C, and diving off the reef walls reveals sharks, rays, and schooling jacks in crystal visibility. The remoteness is the feature, not the bug — Tarawa's WWII relics are hauntingly quiet, and the outer atolls feel genuinely end-of-the-world. Flights connect through Fiji; book well ahead as schedules are thin.",
    9: "September stays dry and breezy at 31°C, with excellent reef conditions and some of the clearest water of the year. This is arguably the best month for diving and snorkeling — visibility can exceed 30 meters on the outer walls. The atolls remain blissfully empty of tourists, and the sunsets over the lagoons are absurdly photogenic. Just remember: the nearest hospital is a long flight away, so travel with a solid first-aid kit.",
    10: "October marks the slow turn back toward wetter weather, though rainfall is still modest and days remain hot at 31°C. Migrating seabirds begin arriving, adding to the already staggering resident colonies. Bonefishing stays strong, and the shoulder-season calm means any lodge bookings are easy to secure. The equatorial light has a particular golden quality in the late afternoon that photographers will lose their minds over.",
    11: "November brings increasing showers as the wet season approaches, but temperatures hold steady at 31°C and the lagoons remain warm and inviting. Reef fish are spawning, creating feeding frenzies that attract larger pelagics to the drop-offs. Tourist numbers — already minuscule — dip further, making this a true solitude seeker's month. Expect basic infrastructure, occasional flight delays, and the kind of silence that recalibrates your nervous system.",
    12: "December is solidly wet season with daily tropical downpours and thick humidity, but the Christmas Island name feels appropriate as the atolls take on a lush, green glow. Lagoon waters are bathtub-warm at 29°C, and the bonefishing flats remain productive despite the showers. A handful of intrepid travelers celebrate the holidays here in the most remote way imaginable — midnight mass in a thatched church on a coral atoll is an experience no resort can replicate.",
  },

  'km-comoros': {
    1: "January drops you into full tropical wet season on these volcanic Indian Ocean islands — 32°C, torrential rain, and humidity that fogs your lens instantly. But the lush hillsides of Grande Comore are impossibly green, and humpback whales are still in the channel between islands. Ylang-ylang plantations perfume the heavy air, and with virtually no tourists around, the local markets in Moroni feel wonderfully authentic.",
    2: "February is the wettest month with 300mm+ of rain and cyclone risk hovering in the background, so keep an eye on forecasts. Between downpours, the snorkeling off Mohéli Marine Park is extraordinary — hawksbill turtles nest on the beaches and the coral is pristine. Crowds are nonexistent and prices are at their lowest, making this the adventurous traveler's window into one of Africa's least-visited archipelagos.",
    3: "March remains firmly in monsoon territory with heavy rain and 32°C heat, but the diving around the volcanic reefs is superb when skies clear. Coelacanths — yes, the 'living fossil' fish — inhabit these deep waters, and local fishermen occasionally spot them off Grande Comore. The islands feel intimate and unhurried; share a plate of langouste grillée with locals and let the tropical pace wash over you.",
    4: "April sees the rains begin to ease, though afternoon showers are still a daily affair at 31°C. The hillsides remain lush from months of rain, and the waterfalls on Anjouan are running at full force. Turtle nesting season on Mohéli continues, and the handful of eco-lodges on the island offer front-row seats. This is shoulder season at its most raw — basic infrastructure, genuine warmth from locals, and nature running the show.",
    5: "May marks the real transition to dry season — rain drops sharply, humidity becomes more bearable, and those 30°C days feel genuinely pleasant with the coastal breeze. The diving visibility improves dramatically, revealing vibrant coral walls and reef sharks off Mohéli. Vanilla and ylang-ylang harvests begin, filling the air with intoxicating fragrance. Still almost no tourists, which means the beaches and hiking trails on Mount Karthala are yours alone.",
    6: "June is dry season done right: clear skies, 28°C days, calm seas, and diving conditions that rival anywhere in the Indian Ocean. The ascent of Mount Karthala, an active volcano on Grande Comore, is best attempted now when trails are dry and views extend across the archipelago. Humpback whale season begins in earnest, with pods passing through the Mozambique Channel. A handful of other travelers might appear, but 'crowded' is not in Comoros's vocabulary.",
    7: "July brings the coolest temperatures of the year at 26°C — practically sweater weather by Comorian standards — with bone-dry conditions and excellent visibility for diving. Humpback whales are everywhere in the channel, breaching and singing, and boat excursions from Mohéli are unforgettable. The dry hillsides reveal the volcanic architecture of the islands, and stargazing is spectacular with zero light pollution. Peak season here still means fewer tourists than a quiet Tuesday in the Maldives.",
    8: "August matches July's dry, comfortable 26°C conditions and remains the prime window for whale watching as humpbacks nurse their calves in the warm shallows. The diving off Mohéli Marine Park is at its clearest, and the reef walls drop away into deep blue where pelagics cruise. Comorian cuisine peaks with fresh-caught fish, coconut-based curries, and tropical fruit. Booking ahead is wise — not because of crowds, but because there are genuinely very few rooms on the islands.",
    9: "September stays dry and begins warming back toward 28°C, with the last of the humpback whales heading south. Diving remains excellent and the seas are calm enough for easy island-hopping by local dhow. The vanilla harvest is in full swing, and visiting a plantation on Anjouan is a fragrant education. Tourist numbers remain a rounding error, and the cultural rhythms of these Swahili-Arab-French islands feel completely unperformative.",
    10: "October is the shoulder month — still mostly dry but the first tropical showers begin appearing, and temperatures climb to 30°C. The sea warms up and coral spawning events create underwater spectacles for lucky divers. Green turtle nesting season starts on Mohéli's beaches, and the eco-lodges run nighttime patrol walks to witness hatchlings. Infrastructure is basic but the raw beauty and cultural richness make every logistical hiccup worthwhile.",
    11: "November signals the wet season's return with increasing showers and 31°C humidity, but the turtle nesting on Mohéli is in full swing and the snorkeling remains vivid. Cyclone season technically begins, so keep flexible plans. The ylang-ylang distilleries are working overtime, the markets in Moroni overflow with tropical produce, and you'll likely be the only tourist for miles. Come with patience and a waterproof bag.",
    12: "December is wet, hot (32°C), and wonderfully festive — Comorian culture blends Islamic traditions with tropical celebration, and the Grande Mariage wedding ceremonies are elaborate multi-day affairs if you're lucky enough to witness one. Rain falls heavily but in dramatic bursts that clear to steamy sunshine. Turtle hatchlings scramble toward the Indian Ocean on Mohéli's moonlit beaches. Getting here requires effort; staying is effortless.",
  },

  'kn-stkitts': {
    1: "January is peak Caribbean perfection on St. Kitts — 28°C, cooling trade winds, and just enough rain (80mm) to keep the volcanic slopes green without ruining a beach day. The crowds from Christmas linger but thin as the month progresses, and the Atlantic side delivers solid swells for bodyboarding. Hike up to the Brimstone Hill Fortress for panoramic views, then cool down with a rum punch at a Basseterre beach bar.",
    2: "February continues the dry-season magic with 27°C days and the island's lowest rainfall. Carnival season erupts in a whirlwind of calypso, soca, and spectacular costumes — the parades and J'ouvert morning fetes are electrifying. The seas calm to snorkeling perfection off the southern peninsula, and the Scenic Railway circles the island through sugarcane fields. Book early; the small island fills up fast during Carnival week.",
    3: "March delivers reliable 28°C sunshine with minimal rain, making it prime time for the St. Kitts & Nevis half-marathon and hiking to the crater rim of Mount Liamuiga through cloud forest. Peak season is winding down, so resort prices start softening and the beaches feel more relaxed. The water taxi to Nevis takes 45 minutes and deposits you on a beach that feels like a private Caribbean fantasy.",
    4: "April is the sweet shoulder month — still dry and warm at 29°C, but the winter crowds have departed and you can snag beachfront deals that would be impossible in February. Diving off the southeast peninsula reveals healthy reefs and the occasional nurse shark, and the volcano hike is lush without being muddy. Mangoes start ripening, the roadside BBQ joints fire up on weekends, and the whole island exhales into a slower rhythm.",
    5: "May nudges into the wetter season with afternoon showers appearing more frequently, but days remain sunny and 30°C. The island is quiet — genuinely quiet — and the locals reclaim the beaches. Green vervet monkeys are active in the rainforest canopy, and birdwatching along the Romney Manor nature trail is rewarding. Prices hit their lowest point, and a stay at one of the plantation inns feels like a steal wrapped in colonial-era charm.",
    6: "June brings proper Caribbean summer heat at 31°C with building humidity and more regular afternoon showers. The Music Festival draws a niche crowd of jazz and soca enthusiasts, adding buzz without overwhelm. Hurricane season officially begins, though June rarely sees direct hits. The snorkeling off Cockleshell Beach is warm and colorful, and fresh lobster season means every beachside restaurant is worth a visit.",
    7: "July turns up the heat to 31°C with regular tropical showers and thick humidity, but the mornings are usually clear and glorious. The island is in proper low season — budget travelers take note of the steep discounts. The rainforest trails on Mount Liamuiga are at their most lush (and most slippery), and the fruit stands overflow with sapodilla and soursop. Keep a casual eye on hurricane forecasts, but don't let the season keep you away.",
    8: "August is the hottest month at 32°C with peak humidity and the highest hurricane risk, which keeps visitor numbers at their lowest. Those who brave it get empty beaches, bargain rates, and the full-throttle Caribbean summer experience. Culturama festival on neighboring Nevis (a quick ferry ride) is a weeklong celebration of Nevisian heritage with pageants, music, and food. Just stay weather-flexible and keep your travel insurance current.",
    9: "September is statistically the peak hurricane month, so flexibility is essential — but between storms, the island is lush, warm (31°C), and practically deserted. Prices are rock-bottom, the sea is bathwater-warm at 28°C, and the diving is surprisingly good when conditions cooperate. The green vervet monkeys are everywhere, mangoes are still in season, and a rain-soaked sunset from Timothy Hill lookout is legitimately spectacular.",
    10: "October still carries hurricane risk but the weather begins stabilizing, with 30°C days and tropical showers that feel more routine than threatening. The island's lush post-rainy-season greenery is at maximum intensity, and the hiking through rainforest to the volcanic crater is extraordinary. Tourist numbers remain very low, meaning genuine interactions with the friendly Kittitian community come naturally. A transitional month that rewards the adaptable traveler.",
    11: "November marks the official end of hurricane season and the beginning of what locals call 'the good times' — temperatures settle to a comfortable 29°C, rain eases, and the trade winds return. Independence Day celebrations on November 19th bring parades and island-wide festivities. The beaches are still empty enough to feel private, prices haven't hit peak-season levels, and the sunset views from the Basseterre waterfront are reliably stunning.",
    12: "December brings the winter-escape crowds back with a vengeance — 28°C days, festive energy, and the Caribbean's signature turquoise waters at their calmest. Hotels command peak-season prices and the southern peninsula beaches get properly busy, especially between Christmas and New Year's. The Scenic Railway is running, Brimstone Hill is photo-perfect under clear skies, and a lobster dinner on the beach with a rum punch feels like exactly what December should be.",
  },

  'kp-northkorea': {
    1: "January in Pyongyang is brutal — highs barely reach -3°C, snow blankets the city, and the Taedong River often freezes solid. The handful of state-approved tour groups brave the cold for an eerily uncrowded experience of monuments like the Juche Tower and Mansudae Grand Monument. Outdoor time requires serious layering; indoor visits to the Pyongyang Metro's deep, ornate stations provide both warmth and genuine architectural wonder.",
    2: "February remains bitterly cold at -1°C highs with dry, grey skies and persistent snow. The Korean New Year (Seollal) brings rare festive energy, with locals in traditional hanbok visiting ice-skating rinks and participating in folk games. Tour groups are tiny and the surreal calm of the capital's wide boulevards amplifies the experience. Heating in hotels can be inconsistent, so thermal layers are non-negotiable survival gear.",
    3: "March hints at spring's approach with temps climbing to 6°C and the first thawing of the Taedong River, though nights still plunge below freezing. Pyongyang begins to stir as parks show the earliest buds. The Kumsusan Palace of the Sun and the massive Arirang-style performances (schedule permitting) are the main draws. Travel remains exclusively via state-approved tours, and the combination of warming weather and thin crowds makes March increasingly popular among the niche agencies that operate here.",
    4: "April is the surprise beauty month — cherry blossoms and magnolias bloom across Pyongyang, temperatures reach a pleasant 17°C, and the city looks almost approachable. Kim Il-sung's birthday (April 15) brings mass celebrations, military parades, and the city at its most animated and decorated. This is peak demand for the few tour operators, so book months ahead. The countryside around Mount Myohyang is green and gorgeous for day-trip hiking.",
    5: "May brings 22°C warmth, lush greenery, and Pyongyang's pleasantest weather — parks are full of locals picnicking, and the botanical gardens burst with color. The Mass Games (if running) are a jaw-dropping spectacle of coordinated human performance at May Day Stadium. Day trips to the DMZ at Panmunjom are available and as tense and fascinating as you'd expect. The spring light is beautiful and photography (within approved parameters) captures the city at its most photogenic.",
    6: "June pushes toward 27°C with building humidity as the monsoon approaches, but the rains haven't properly arrived yet. The countryside around Kaesong and the DMZ is green and atmospheric, and the Koryo Museum offers a quiet counterpoint to Pyongyang's monumental scale. This is the last comfortable month before summer's humidity hammer falls. Tour group sizes remain small, and the longer daylight hours allow for more extensive itineraries.",
    7: "July is monsoon season — heavy rain (250mm+), 29°C heat, and oppressive humidity that makes outdoor sightseeing genuinely taxing. The Taedong River swells and occasional flooding affects rural day-trip routes. Victory Day (July 27) commemorates the Korean War armistice with military displays and solemn ceremonies. Tour schedules may shift around weather and state events. Bring rain gear and patience; the cultural access during national holidays can be uniquely revealing.",
    8: "August is the wettest and hottest month — 30°C with 300mm+ of rain and suffocating humidity. The Liberation Day celebrations on August 15 mark the end of Japanese colonial rule with patriotic fervor and massive gatherings. Outdoor excursions to Mount Kumgang or Paektu (if accessible) are muddy but dramatically beautiful under storm-lit skies. Visitor numbers remain small by design, and the monsoon atmosphere lends the monuments an almost cinematic gravity.",
    9: "September brings welcome relief: rain retreats, temperatures settle to a pleasant 25°C, and the air clears to reveal crisp blue skies over the capital. The founding day of the DPRK (September 9) may feature celebrations and improved access to events. The countryside begins its autumn transformation, and day trips to Kaesong and Mount Myohyang benefit from golden light and comfortable hiking temperatures. One of the better months for the state-managed tour experience.",
    10: "October is arguably the best month to visit — 18°C, clear skies, spectacular autumn foliage, and the monuments of Pyongyang framed by golden and crimson trees. The Korean Workers' Party founding anniversary (October 10) often features large-scale events. Mount Myohyang's maple forests rival anything in South Korea (without the crowds), and the DMZ takes on an eerie beauty in autumn light. Book early; the limited tour slots for October fill quickly among the small community of DPRK travelers.",
    11: "November turns cold fast — 8°C highs, bare trees, and a stark beauty to Pyongyang's monumental architecture against grey skies. Tour groups thin to almost nothing, and the city takes on a contemplative quietness. The heating hasn't always kicked in consistently at this point, so bring warm layers. The Koryo Hotel's revolving restaurant offers sweeping views of the city transitioning to winter, and indoor cultural visits to theaters and museums become the focus.",
    12: "December is deep winter — highs around 0°C, snow likely, and the city buttoned up against the Siberian air that sweeps down the peninsula. Tourist visits are rare but not impossible, and the few who come find Pyongyang's monuments dusted with snow and almost otherworldly in their frozen grandeur. New Year's preparations bring a subtle festive energy, and the famous Pyongyang cold noodles (naengmyeon) are, counterintuitively, a winter tradition worth braving the chill for.",
  },

  'kr-busan': {
    1: "January in Busan is cold but manageable — 6°C highs, crisp ocean air, and far fewer tourists than Seoul. The Jagalchi Fish Market steams with fresh catches and hot seafood stews, and the Haedong Yonggungsa temple perched on the cliffs looks stunning under winter-grey skies. Haeundae Beach is deserted and dramatic, perfect for moody walks. Warm up with a bowl of dwaeji gukbap (pork bone soup), Busan's signature comfort food.",
    2: "February stays chilly around 7°C but sunshine hours increase noticeably, and the Nakdong River estuary fills with migratory birds — a magnet for birders and photographers. Lunar New Year (Seollal) brings festive energy and crowded train stations, but the temples and coastal trails are relatively quiet. The seafood is at peak freshness, and the hot springs at Dongnae are pure cold-weather luxury. Early plum blossoms appear by month's end at Tongdosa Temple.",
    3: "March is Busan shaking off winter — temps rise to 12°C, cherry blossom season begins in late March (earlier than Seoul), and the coastal paths come alive. The Samgwangsa Temple cherry blossom tunnel is a jaw-dropping spectacle that's somehow less famous than its northern counterparts. Crowds build moderately, restaurant terraces start reopening along Gwangalli Beach, and the famous BIFF (Busan International Film Festival) area buzzes year-round but starts humming louder.",
    4: "April is peak cherry blossom season in Busan — the entire city turns pink, with the tunnel of blossoms along the Nakdong River and at Samgwangsa absolutely spectacular. Temperatures reach a comfortable 17°C, and the beaches of Haeundae and Gwangalli fill with picnickers under the blooming trees. Crowds are at their spring peak, so arrive early for the best blossom spots. Fresh raw fish (hoe) season is in full swing at Jagalchi Market.",
    5: "May delivers near-perfect conditions: 21°C, long sunshine hours, and the city fully awake between cherry blossom comedown and summer humidity. The Gamcheon Culture Village pops with color against blue skies, and coastal hikes along the Haeparang Trail are ideal in the mild weather. Buddha's Birthday (early May) lights up temples across the city with spectacular lantern festivals. Crowds are moderate and the seafood remains outstanding.",
    6: "June ushers in the monsoon prelude — humidity climbs, temps hit 24°C, and the first significant rains arrive (200mm). But Busan's beaches start buzzing with pre-summer energy, and the seafood is extraordinary: live octopus, grilled shellfish, and that famous Jagalchi sashimi. The Taejongdae cliffs are lush and dramatic under moody skies. Bring an umbrella but don't let the rain deter you; Busan in June has a sultry energy all its own.",
    7: "July is monsoon season proper — expect 300mm+ of rain, 28°C heat, and thick humidity. But Busan leans into summer: Haeundae Beach opens its summer season with lifeguards, beach bars, and a carnival atmosphere. The rain comes in dramatic bursts between sweltering sunshine, and the Busan Sea Festival brings concerts and events to the waterfront. Hot and wet, yes, but the energy is infectious and a bowl of cold naengmyeon noodles is the perfect antidote.",
    8: "August is Busan's hottest month at 30°C with persistent humidity and lingering monsoon showers. Haeundae and Gwangalli beaches are absolutely packed — this is peak domestic tourism and the vibe is pure summer festival. The Busan Sea Festival continues, night markets blaze, and the fireworks over Gwangalli Bridge are legendary. Typhoon risk is real, so keep an eye on weather apps. Come for the chaos and the extraordinary street food; just bring a towel and patience.",
    9: "September is the great exhale — monsoon retreats, temperatures settle to a pleasant 26°C, and the beaches empty to manageable levels. The annual Busan International Film Festival (BIFF) in early October means September buzzes with pre-festival energy around Haeundae. The ocean is still warm enough for swimming (24°C), and coastal sunsets are spectacular with the clearing autumn air. The seafood shifts to autumn catches, and a twilight walk across Gwangalli Bridge is magic.",
    10: "October is arguably Busan's finest month: 21°C, crystal-clear skies, and autumn foliage painting the hills around Beomeosa Temple in amber and crimson. BIFF brings international glamour and packed screenings, adding cosmopolitan buzz to the port city's laid-back charm. The coastal trails are hiking perfection, Jagalchi Market is at peak form with fall catches, and the Gamcheon Culture Village glows under that clean autumn light. Book ahead for BIFF week.",
    11: "November cools to 15°C with increasingly bare trees and a mellow, end-of-season vibe. The crowds thin significantly, making this excellent for temple visits and unhurried market browsing. The Nakdong Estuary is alive with migratory birds again, and Taejongdae's coastal cliffs are dramatic against grey November seas. Late autumn seafood — especially crab — is sensational, and the hot springs at Hurshimchung Spa are the perfect warm-up after a breezy coastal walk.",
    12: "December brings proper winter chill (8°C highs) and Busan's famous Christmas lights along Haeundae and Gwangalli, creating a festive seaside atmosphere unlike anywhere else in Korea. The seafood stews and hot pots reach peak comfort-food status, and the Jagalchi dawn market feels most authentic when you're huddled over steaming crab soup at 6am. Crowds are low outside the holiday week, and the year-end fireworks display over Gwangalli Bridge is a spectacular send-off.",
  },

  'kr-jeju': {
    1: "Jeju in January is Korea's mildest winter escape — 7°C highs feel positively balmy compared to Seoul's -5°C, and the island's volcanic landscape takes on a stark, dramatic beauty. Hallasan's summit trail may be snow-capped, offering serious hikers a stunning winter ascent. The haenyeo (women divers) work the frigid 14°C waters year-round, harvesting abalone and sea urchin that end up in the most incredible seafood you've ever tasted. Tourist numbers are low and prices match.",
    2: "February remains cool at 8°C with the odd dusting of snow on Hallasan, but the first rapeseed blossoms appear on the southern coast, splashing yellow against the black volcanic rock — it's arrestingly beautiful. Seollal (Lunar New Year) brings domestic visitors briefly, but the island quickly quiets. The Jeju Folk Village feels most authentic in winter, and a bowl of heuk dwaeji (black pork) BBQ after a windy coastal walk is the definition of earned comfort.",
    3: "March is Jeju's spring awakening — cherry blossoms start popping around 12°C, the rapeseed fields hit full golden bloom along the south coast, and the island looks like it was art-directed. Crowds build to moderate as Korean travelers arrive for blossom season. The Jeju Olle coastal trails are perfect for hiking in the mild weather, and the tangerine orchards are still fragrant from the late harvest. The sea remains cold (14°C), but the coastal views more than compensate.",
    4: "April delivers Jeju at its most photogenic: cherry blossoms peak, azaleas bloom on Hallasan's slopes, and temperatures reach a comfortable 16°C. The island bustles with spring tourists, so popular spots like Seongsan Ilchulbong (Sunrise Peak) get crowded early — arrive at dawn and you'll understand the name. Horseback riding through the island's green interior pastures is idyllic, and the seafood restaurants in Seogwipo overflow with spring catches. Still shoulder-season pricing if you book smart.",
    5: "May is arguably Jeju's sweet spot: 20°C, hydrangeas beginning to bloom, and Hallasan's crater lake reflecting clear blue skies. The Olle trails are at their best with wildflowers lining the coastal paths, and the sea warms enough (18°C) for the bravest swimmers. The Gotjawal Forest is lush and mysterious, and tangerine ice cream from roadside stands becomes an essential food group. Moderate crowds, excellent weather, fair prices — the trifecta.",
    6: "June brings the start of monsoon season with 180mm of rain and climbing humidity at 24°C, but also Jeju's famous hydrangea bloom — the roadsides and temple grounds explode in blue, purple, and pink. Hallasan hikes are lush but slippery, and the dramatic waterfalls like Cheonjiyeon are at their most powerful. Domestic tourists arrive for early summer, but the rain keeps numbers in check. A rainy-day afternoon at a Jeju black pork restaurant is time exceptionally well spent.",
    7: "July is peak summer: 29°C, heavy monsoon rain (300mm+), and crowds surging as Korean summer holidays begin. Jungmun Beach and Hyeopjae Beach fill up fast, and the turquoise waters finally hit swimmable temperatures (23°C). The rain comes in tropical bursts between sunshine, and the lava tube caves like Manjanggul offer cool, dry refuge. Typhoon risk is real, so build in flexibility. The night markets in Jeju City are buzzing with grilled seafood and mandarin soju.",
    8: "August is Jeju's hottest and busiest — 30°C, thick humidity, and every beach on the island packed with vacationing Korean families. It's the most expensive month, and booking anything last-minute is a fantasy. But the energy is infectious: beach festivals, night diving off the coast, and the haenyeo demonstrations draw admiring crowds. Typhoon season continues, so weather can shift fast. If you can handle the heat and the company, the sunsets from Hallasan's mid-slopes are unforgettable.",
    9: "September is the smart choice — summer crowds evaporate, temps ease to a pleasant 25°C, and the typhoon risk drops after mid-month. The sea stays warm (24°C), the tangerine season approaches, and the Olle trails are blissfully uncrowded under early-autumn skies. Seongsan Ilchulbong at sunrise without the queue is the reward for timing it right. Jeju's food scene — black pork, abalone porridge, raw seafood — operates at full power with shorter waits.",
    10: "October paints Jeju in autumn colors — the Hallasan slopes turn gold and crimson, temperatures settle to 20°C, and the famed tangerine harvest begins, filling every market with fragrant citrus. Crowds are moderate, prices are reasonable, and the hiking conditions are ideal for the full Hallasan summit attempt. The silver grass fields at Saebyeol Oreum shimmer in the autumn wind, creating one of Korea's most iconic seasonal landscapes. Pack a light jacket and a large appetite.",
    11: "November cools to 14°C and strips Jeju to its volcanic essentials — the dramatic coastline, stark lava fields, and weather-beaten stone walls (dolhareubang guardians standing stoic) look most impressive under moody autumn skies. Crowds thin dramatically and hotel prices drop. The tangerine orchards are at peak harvest, and picking your own is a satisfying way to spend an afternoon. Hallasan's bare slopes reveal geological features hidden under summer foliage, and the wind — always the wind — reminds you this is an island.",
    12: "December brings Jeju's mild winter: 9°C highs, occasional rain, and a quiet atmosphere that's the polar opposite of summer's frenzy. The Christmas lights in Jeju City add festive cheer, and the indoor attractions — Teddy Bear Museum, Jeju Glass Castle, Hallim Park's lava caves — make sense on drizzly days. Black pork BBQ and citrus season combine for peak comfort dining, and a coastal walk with a mandarin in your pocket and wind in your face is Jeju at its most honest.",
  },

  'kr-seoul': {
    1: "Seoul in January is a test of character — highs around -1°C, Siberian winds, and the Han River occasionally frozen solid. But the city compensates with world-class indoor culture: jimjilbangs (bathhouses), K-pop venues, and some of the planet's best food from steaming kimchi jjigae to sizzling Korean BBQ. Gyeongbokgung Palace dusted in snow is genuinely magical, and Seollal (Lunar New Year) preparations fill the traditional markets with festive energy. Layer up and lean in.",
    2: "February stays frigid (-1°C to 4°C) but the days lengthen and early plum blossoms hint at spring's approach. Seollal celebrations (if they fall in February) bring folk games, traditional dress, and special temple events. Myeongdong's shopping arcades are a warm refuge, and the museum and gallery scene in Itaewon is thriving. The cold keeps tourist numbers low, meaning Bukchon Hanok Village's traditional alleyways are yours to photograph without the summer crowds.",
    3: "March is Seoul's thawing month — temps climb to 10°C, cherry blossom anticipation builds, and the city shakes off its winter bunker mentality. The Yeouido cherry blossom festival preps begin in late March, and the palaces start to look alive again against budding trees. Air quality can be poor with spring dust, so check the AQI before heading out. Korean street food shifts to lighter spring fare, and the rooftop bars of Itaewon cautiously reopen.",
    4: "April is Seoul's cherry blossom spectacular — Yeouido along the Han River becomes a tunnel of pink, Gyeongbokgung blazes with spring color, and temperatures hit a perfect 17°C. Everyone shows up (peak crowds), so popular spots require early mornings or weekday visits. The hiking at Bukhansan National Park is superb with spring wildflowers, and outdoor markets buzz with fresh bibimbap ingredients. One of the best months, period — just book well ahead and embrace the beautiful chaos.",
    5: "May is gorgeous: 23°C, long sunny days, and the cherry blossoms yielding to lush green canopies over the palaces. Buddha's Birthday brings spectacular lantern parades through Insadong and Jogyesa Temple. The hiking is prime — Bukhansan and Inwangsan offer clear views across the sprawling city. Crowds are present but manageable outside Golden Week, and the food markets (Gwangjang, Tongin) are at their most vibrant. Late spring Seoul is hard to beat.",
    6: "June marks the monsoon's arrival: 27°C, heavy rain (170mm+), and humidity that turns the city into a steam bath. But Seoul's indoor game is strong — world-class museums, underground shopping, and the K-beauty scene in Gangnam keep rainy days productive. When the sun breaks through, Bukchon Hanok Village glistens, and the Han River parks fill with picnickers. Korean fried chicken and beer (chimaek) on a humid evening is essentially a civic tradition.",
    7: "July is peak monsoon: 29°C, 350mm+ of rain, and humidity that makes stepping outside feel like entering a warm wet blanket. But Seoulites don't stop — the Boryeong Mud Festival is a gleefully messy affair, and summer night markets along the Han River are lively until late. The mountains surrounding the city are impossibly green, and samgyetang (ginseng chicken soup) is the traditional summer stamina food. Pack light, breathable clothing and embrace the sweat.",
    8: "August is Seoul's hottest month — 30°C with monsoon tail-end showers and humidity that won't quit. The city is still buzzing with domestic travelers on summer vacation, and Lotte World, N Seoul Tower, and the Dongdaemun night markets are packed. Typhoon risk exists but rarely hits Seoul directly. The naengmyeon (cold buckwheat noodles) rivalry between Pyongyang-style and Hamheung-style shops reaches fever pitch. An intense month that rewards the heat-tolerant with peak summer energy.",
    9: "September is the great reset — monsoon ends, temps drop to a comfortable 25°C, and the air clears to reveal those crisp blue Seoul skies. Chuseok (Korean Thanksgiving) brings family reunions and traditional food, and the city briefly empties as residents head to hometowns — leaving tourists with surprisingly quiet streets. Autumn approaches with the first hints of color on the mountains, and the food scene pivots to autumn flavors: roasted chestnuts, hotteok pancakes, and fresh persimmon.",
    10: "October is Seoul at its peak: 18°C, blazing autumn foliage, and the kind of clean, golden light that makes every palace photo look professional. Bukhansan explodes in red and gold, Gyeongbokgung's changing of the guard ceremony is set against crimson maples, and the hiking trails are at their absolute best. Crowds are significant but the city is big enough to absorb them. Street food season peaks with tteokbokki carts and fish-shaped waffles everywhere. Arguably Seoul's best month.",
    11: "November cools sharply to 9°C as the last autumn leaves fall and winter's approach becomes unmistakable. The crowds thin, the palace grounds are carpeted in golden ginkgo leaves, and the Deoksugung stone wall path is peak melancholy-beautiful. This is prime season for Korean BBQ, army stew (budae jjigae), and warming soju. The shopping scene in Myeongdong and Hongdae gears up for holiday sales, and the first Christmas decorations appear, adding sparkle to the shortening days.",
    12: "December plunges Seoul into proper winter — hovering around 0°C with occasional snow and that fierce Korean wind. But the city sparkles: massive Christmas light displays, ice skating at City Hall and Olympic Park, and the Myeongdong Christmas market create genuine festive magic. Year-end K-pop festivals (MAMA, SBS Gayo Daejeon) draw fans worldwide. Duck into a pojangmacha (street tent bar) for hot stew and soju, and you'll understand why Seoulites don't hide from winter — they celebrate through it.",
  },

  'kw-kuwait': {
    1: "January is Kuwait's most bearable month — 18°C highs, occasional rain showers, and a crispness to the desert air that makes outdoor exploration genuinely pleasant. The Souq Mubarakiya buzzes with activity, and the corniche along Kuwait Bay is perfect for evening walks. The Kuwait Towers gleam under clear winter skies, and the cultural calendar fills with exhibitions and concerts. This is the window for desert camping and falcon-hunting excursions — embrace the Bedouin heritage while the weather allows.",
    2: "February keeps the mild streak going at 20°C with the last of the winter rains greening the desert edges. National Day and Liberation Day (February 25-26) transform the city with fireworks, flag displays, and patriotic festivities that are genuinely spectacular. The seaside promenades are packed with celebrating families, and the modern skyline provides a dramatic backdrop. Outdoor dining along the marina is ideal, and weekend desert trips to the Failaka Island archaeological sites are comfortable.",
    3: "March starts the temperature climb — 25°C and rising — with increasing sunshine and the desert wildflowers making their brief, beautiful appearance. The last comfortable weeks for outdoor sightseeing before the heat arrives in earnest, so hit the Grand Mosque, Al Shaheed Park, and the mirror-clad Sheikh Jaber Cultural Centre now. Sandstorms become a possibility, so keep sunglasses and a scarf handy. The seafood at the fish market near Sharq is exceptional year-round.",
    4: "April pushes past 30°C and the writing is on the wall — summer is coming. But the evenings remain pleasant, and the city's mall culture (The Avenues, 360 Mall) provides air-conditioned refuge with serious shopping and dining. Weekend boat trips to Kubbar Island are popular as the Gulf waters warm to swimsuit-friendly temperatures. The expat brunch scene is thriving, and outdoor activities are best reserved for early mornings before the midday heat asserts itself.",
    5: "May is where Kuwait starts earning its reputation — 38°C highs, relentless sunshine, and the kind of dry heat that makes car door handles into branding irons. Outdoor tourism effectively stops between 10am and 4pm, and life shifts indoors. The upside: hotel prices drop, cultural venues are uncrowded, and the sunset over Kuwait Bay remains spectacular from an air-conditioned cafe. Ramadan may fall here, adding spiritual depth but altering dining hours dramatically.",
    6: "June is full-throttle summer at 43°C — one of the hottest urban environments on Earth. The Gulf waters are bathtub-warm (30°C+), outdoor activity is genuinely dangerous during midday, and the city runs on AC and determination. Tourist numbers are essentially zero, prices crater, and the malls become the primary social spaces. If you must be here, embrace the nocturnal lifestyle: late-night souq visits, midnight seafood dinners, and pre-dawn walks along the corniche.",
    7: "July holds steady at a scorching 45°C with zero rainfall and sunshine that feels personal. Even locals minimize outdoor time, and Kuwait's famously lavish indoor entertainment — from cinema complexes to themed restaurants — becomes the entire agenda. The Gulf is too warm for refreshing swims, and sandstorms can reduce visibility to zero. A month for transit travelers and oil industry workers, not leisure tourists. If stranded, the Scientific Centre aquarium is worth a visit.",
    8: "August competes with July for the hottest month — 45°C+ is routine, humidity can spike near the coast, and the combination is genuinely oppressive. The city feels muted, with many Kuwaitis abroad escaping the heat. But there's a certain apocalyptic grandeur to the empty corniche and shimmering skyline under the noon sun. Prices are at absolute rock bottom for luxury hotels. Come only if you have a specific reason, a high heat tolerance, and a fondness for aggressive air conditioning.",
    9: "September begins the long exhale — still 40°C+ but the worst of the peak heat is behind you, and the days start shortening noticeably. The city stirs back to life as expats return and the social calendar ramps up. Evening temperatures become bearable for outdoor dining by month's end, and the Gulf waters start cooling from their summer bath. Cultural events pick up, and the shopping scene gears up for the coming season.",
    10: "October is the true transition — temps drop to 33°C, evenings are pleasant, and Kuwait rediscovers its outdoor self. Beach clubs reopen, the desert camping season begins, and the Souq Mubarakiya fills with evening shoppers. The Hala February festival preparations begin early, and the restaurant scene buzzes with new openings and seasonal menus. This is when Kuwait becomes visitable again, and the city's modern architecture looks best under the softening autumn light.",
    11: "November settles into a comfortable 25°C — genuinely pleasant — and Kuwait enters its social season. Desert camping is in full swing, with elaborate Bedouin-style setups dotting the outskirts. The corniche comes alive with joggers and families, outdoor dining terraces fill up, and the cultural institutions host their marquee exhibitions. The Gulf waters are a refreshing 22°C, and day trips to Failaka Island are ideal. This is Kuwait at its most welcoming and accessible.",
    12: "December is peak season in Kuwait — 18°C, clear skies, and a festive energy as the city wraps up the year. The Liberation Tower and Kuwait Towers are beautifully lit, and the dining scene hits its stride with outdoor terraces and rooftop lounges. Desert camping reaches its peak, and the falcon-hunting heritage on display at traditional gatherings is fascinating. Tourist numbers are modest but at their annual highest, and the cool evenings along the marina are genuinely lovely.",
  },

  'kz-almaty': {
    1: "January in Almaty is a winter sports paradise — temps hover around -5°C, the Tien Shan mountains behind the city are blanketed in deep snow, and Shymbulak ski resort is in full swing with surprisingly uncrowded slopes. The city itself is wrapped in a cold, crisp stillness, with the Green Bazaar steaming with vendors selling horsemeat sausage (kazy) and fresh kurt. Ice skating at the Medeu outdoor rink — the world's highest — is a must, and the mountain views on clear days are staggering.",
    2: "February stays cold at -4°C but Almaty's winter culture thrives: the ski season peaks, the mountains are at maximum snow depth, and the city's cafe scene provides warm refuge between outdoor adventures. The Green Bazaar overflows with dried fruits, nuts, and warming beshbarmak (the national dish). Nauryz preparations begin as the month ends, adding anticipatory energy. Clear winter days offer the best views of the Tien Shan peaks from the city's southern avenues.",
    3: "March is the grand thaw — temps climb past 8°C, the snow line retreats up the mountains, and Nauryz (Persian New Year, March 22) erupts in one of Central Asia's biggest celebrations. Streets fill with yurts, horseback games, and tables groaning with traditional food. The skiing season winds down but the hiking season isn't quite ready, making this a cultural rather than athletic month. The apple orchards (Almaty literally means 'father of apples') start budding, hinting at the lush spring to come.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring warmth at 17°C with apple blossoms carpeting the foothills and the mountains still snow-capped behind them — the contrast is postcard-perfect. Hiking trails in Almaty National Park open up, and the famous Big Almaty Lake begins its transformation from frozen white to electric turquoise. Rain showers are frequent but brief, and the crowds are thin. This is arguably the most photogenic month, with wildflowers, snow peaks, and blooming orchards colliding.",
    5: "May is Almaty at full bloom — 23°C, long sunshine hours, and the foothills exploding in green and wildflowers. Big Almaty Lake hits its most vivid turquoise as glacial melt feeds in, and hiking to Kok-Zhailau plateau rewards with panoramic mountain views. Victory Day (May 9) brings patriotic celebrations and a public holiday. The bazaars overflow with fresh strawberries, cherries, and herbs. Moderate tourist numbers and comfortable temperatures make this a prime visiting window.",
    6: "June is summer's arrival at 28°C with warm, sunny days perfect for mountain trekking. The Turgen Gorge waterfalls are thundering with snowmelt, Charyn Canyon (Kazakhstan's mini Grand Canyon) is best visited now before peak heat, and the alpine meadows above the city are carpeted in edelweiss and poppies. Evenings are long and pleasant, and the outdoor restaurant terraces on Panfilov Street buzz until late. Crowds are moderate and the city hums with summer energy.",
    7: "July is the hottest month at 30°C with intense sunshine, but the mountains offer cool escape — trails above 3,000m stay comfortable, and Big Almaty Lake is at peak beauty. The Kolsai Lakes day trip is spectacular under clear summer skies, with emerald water set in dark spruce forests. The city itself can feel hot, but evening strolls through Panfilov Park and outdoor concerts at the Republic Square keep things lively. Peak tourist season means booking ahead for mountain lodges.",
    8: "August holds summer's heat at 29°C but the alpine adventures keep delivering: multi-day treks in the Tien Shan, horseback rides through the Assy Plateau, and the last best weeks for Charyn Canyon before autumn chill sets in. Fruit season peaks with extraordinary melons, peaches, and those famous Almaty apples at the Green Bazaar. Domestic tourism is heavy, particularly on weekends at mountain destinations. The city's craft beer scene has quietly become impressive.",
    9: "September is golden — literally. The temperatures ease to 22°C, the mountain birch and aspen forests ignite in amber and gold, and the hiking is arguably the best of the year. Crowds thin after the summer rush, Big Almaty Lake reflects autumn colors, and the bazaars transition to autumn harvest: pomegranates, walnuts, dried apricots. The Charyn Canyon glows in warm afternoon light, and clear skies make the Tien Shan views from the city unforgettable. Pack a light jacket for mountain evenings.",
    10: "October brings proper autumn at 12°C with the last golden leaves clinging to the mountain slopes and the first dustings of snow on the peaks. The hiking window narrows but early October still offers spectacular trails through autumn color. The Green Bazaar is at its most abundant with autumn preserves, honey, and smoked meats. Cultural life picks up with theater and concert seasons opening. A contemplative month — fewer tourists, shorter days, and the city's Russian-Kazakh-Korean fusion cuisine at its most comforting.",
    11: "November is the grey transition: 4°C, bare trees, and the first real snowfall in the city. The ski resort starts testing runs, and the mountains take on a stark, dramatic beauty. Tourist numbers hit their lowest, but the indoor cultural scene — opera at the Abay Theatre, contemporary art galleries, traditional music performances — is genuinely excellent. Beshbarmak season is in full effect, and the warmth of Almaty's hospitality shines brightest when the weather is at its bleakest.",
    12: "December blankets Almaty in proper winter — -3°C, snow-covered streets, and the Tien Shan mountains forming a dramatic white wall behind the city. Shymbulak ski resort opens for the season, Medeu ice rink gleams under lights, and the New Year celebrations (bigger here than Christmas) fill the city with festive markets, fireworks, and elaborate decorations. Hot lagman noodle soup from a street vendor, breath visible in the cold air, mountains glowing pink at sunset — December Almaty is genuinely magical.",
  },

  'kz-astana': {
    1: "January in Astana is not for the faint-hearted — average highs of -12°C, biting steppe winds, and a frozen landscape that stretches to infinity. This is one of the coldest capitals on Earth, and you'll feel every degree. But the futuristic skyline (Bayterek Tower, Khan Shatyr tent mall) looks dramatic against the white steppe, and the indoor attractions — the National Museum, EXPO sphere — are world-class. Bundle up in serious thermals and discover why Kazakhs consider surviving January a point of pride.",
    2: "February remains brutally cold at -10°C with wind chills that can push well below -20°C. The frozen Ishim River and snow-blanketed steppe create an almost lunar landscape. Nauryz preparations begin, adding warmth to the cultural calendar if not the thermometer. Khan Shatyr's indoor beach resort (yes, really) offers surreal tropical escape from the Siberian cold outside. The few tourists who brave February get the city's extraordinary architecture entirely to themselves.",
    3: "March starts the long climb out of winter — still cold at -2°C but the sun returns with increasing force, and Nauryz (March 22) transforms the city with yurts, horseback competitions, and feasting. The steppe begins showing patches of brown through the snow, and the modern architectural masterpieces of the left bank look particularly striking in the sharp spring light. This is a cultural highlight month — Nauryz in the capital is celebrated with genuine grandeur.",
    4: "April delivers spring in a rush — snow melts fast, temps jump to 13°C, and the steppe turns from white to green seemingly overnight. The wind remains fierce (this is the open steppe, after all), but the sunshine is generous and the city's parks and river walks start filling with relieved residents. The Botanical Garden awakens, and day trips to the Burabay National Park (the 'Kazakh Switzerland') become viable as roads clear. Pack layers — April can swing 15 degrees in a day.",
    5: "May is Astana reborn — 22°C, green steppe stretching endlessly, and the city buzzing with outdoor energy after months of hibernation. Victory Day (May 9) brings major celebrations at the Monument of Defenders of the Fatherland. The Ishim River walks are pleasant, and the left bank's futuristic architecture looks best against blue skies and fresh greenery. Burabay's pine-fringed lakes are gorgeous for weekend hiking. Tourist numbers pick up but remain modest by global standards.",
    6: "June brings proper summer at 27°C with long days (18+ hours of light) and the steppe blooming with wildflowers. The city is at its liveliest: outdoor festivals, concerts at the EXPO grounds, and bustling restaurant terraces along the river. Capital Day (July 6) preparations begin, and the vibe is optimistic and modern. Day trips to the Korgalzhyn Nature Reserve (home to flamingos — yes, on the Kazakh steppe) are a surreal highlight. Rain is modest and the skies feel enormous.",
    7: "July is the warmest month at 29°C and the steppe capital buzzes with summer energy. Capital Day celebrations (July 6) bring concerts, fireworks, and national pride. The hours of daylight seem endless, and the modern skyline shimmers in the heat haze. Swimming in the Ishim or day-tripping to Burabay's lakes is the local escape plan. Thunderstorms can be dramatic and sudden, rolling across the steppe with cinematic force. Peak domestic tourism, but international visitors remain few.",
    8: "August holds summer heat at 27°C with the steppe turning golden as grasses cure in the sun — the landscape takes on an almost African savanna quality. The cultural calendar fills with music festivals and outdoor events, and the city's growing restaurant scene (Kazakh, Korean, Uzbek fusion) is worth exploring. Evenings cool pleasantly, and the sunset over the futuristic left bank skyline is routinely spectacular. The last great month for outdoor exploration before autumn arrives fast.",
    9: "September cools rapidly to 17°C and the steppe enters its most beautiful phase — endless golden grasslands under enormous blue skies, with flocks of migrating birds sweeping through. The city's cultural season kicks off with theater, opera, and gallery openings. The Architecture of the capital hits differently in autumn light — Bayterek Tower and the Presidential Palace glow gold at sunset. Pack a proper jacket; temperatures can drop sharply after dark, and the steppe wind returns with attitude.",
    10: "October is autumn's last stand at 6°C — the steppe is brown and vast, the wind bites harder, and the first snow can arrive any day. The indoor cultural scene becomes essential: the National Museum's collection is genuinely impressive, and the Astana Opera is architecturally stunning and programs world-class performances. This is the month to appreciate Astana as a city of ambition — the futuristic buildings look most dramatic against stormy October skies. Warm clothing becomes non-optional.",
    11: "November plunges back toward winter — -4°C, snow returning, and those steppe winds cutting through anything less than a proper winter coat. The city hunkers down but doesn't stop: the indoor bazaars are warm and fragrant, the museums are uncrowded, and the restaurant scene keeps things interesting with hearty Kazakh cuisine. Ice formations on the Ishim River begin, and the city's LED-lit buildings glow against the early darkness. Tourist-free and oddly beautiful in its frozen determination.",
    12: "December is deep Kazakh winter — -10°C, snow-blanketed steppe, and the kind of cold that makes your nose hairs freeze. But Astana celebrates New Year with spectacular enthusiasm: the city is draped in lights, the ice sculptures in the parks are elaborate, and Khan Shatyr becomes a glittering winter wonderland. The futuristic skyline against a frozen, star-filled sky is genuinely awe-inspiring. Bring your best cold-weather gear and an appetite for beshbarmak — you'll need the calories.",
  },

  'la-luangprabang': {
    1: "January is Luang Prabang at its most serene — 28°C days, cool 14°C nights, and the Mekong running low and clear through the UNESCO-listed old town. The morning alms-giving ceremony with saffron-robed monks is at its most atmospheric in the cool dawn mist. Crowds are at their peak for high season, but the town absorbs them gracefully. Night markets sell handwoven silk and steaming bowls of khao piak sen (Lao noodle soup) under the palm trees.",
    2: "February continues the dry season dream: 30°C, cloudless skies, and the waterfalls at Kuang Si running at their most turquoise (lower water volume means the blue pigment concentrates beautifully). The Mekong is at its lowest, revealing sandy beaches perfect for riverside picnics. Boun Khoun Khao (rice festival) celebrates the harvest with temple offerings and communal feasting. High-season crowds and prices persist, but the weather justifies every kip spent.",
    3: "March turns up the heat to 33°C with dry, hazy skies as burn-off season fills the valleys with smoke — the views aren't as crisp, but the town's colonial architecture and gilded temples still glow. Crowds thin slightly, and the Pak Ou Caves boat trip up the Mekong is magical in the warm afternoon light. The French-Lao fusion restaurants along the main street serve extraordinary food, and evenings cool enough for comfortable riverside dining.",
    4: "April brings Lao New Year (Pi Mai) — the biggest festival of the year, a three-day water fight, parade, and temple celebration that transforms the entire town into joyful chaos. Temperatures peak at 35°C and the heat is serious, but everyone is too busy dousing each other with water and dancing to care. The Mekong is at its lowest and warmest, and the pre-monsoon atmosphere crackles with anticipation. Book well ahead; every guesthouse fills for Pi Mai.",
    5: "May marks the monsoon's dramatic entrance: afternoon thunderstorms arrive, temperatures ease to 32°C, and the parched landscape begins its transformation to electric green. Kuang Si waterfall gains volume and power, and the Mekong starts its annual rise. Crowds drop sharply (low season begins), prices soften, and the town's Buddhist temples feel more contemplative without the tour groups. Rocket festivals (Boun Bang Fai) in rural areas are exuberantly chaotic celebrations meant to summon the rains.",
    6: "June is full monsoon with daily afternoon downpours, 32°C heat, and lush vegetation overtaking every surface. The Mekong swells and turns muddy-brown, and the surrounding mountains disappear into clouds — but the town itself is magical in the rain, with wet temple roofs gleaming gold and the night market carrying on under tarps. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, guesthouse rates are bargain-level, and the morning alms ceremony feels most authentic with only locals and a handful of respectful visitors watching.",
    7: "July continues the monsoon rhythm: heavy rain (250mm+), thick humidity, and the landscape at peak tropical lushness. Kuang Si waterfall is thundering and powerful, though swimming may be limited by strong currents. The Mekong is high and fast, making boat trips more adventurous. This is budget season — the cheapest rooms, emptiest restaurants, and most genuine local interactions. Leeches on jungle trails are a reality, so tuck your pants into your socks with pride.",
    8: "August matches July's monsoon intensity with heavy rain and high humidity at 31°C, but the rhythm becomes familiar: mornings are often clear, afternoons dramatic. The rice paddies surrounding the town are luminous green, and the monks' procession through rain-slicked streets is hauntingly beautiful. The Boun Haw Khao Padap Din festival honors the dead with temple offerings and candlelit ceremonies. Low-season pricing continues, and the few travelers here share a camaraderie born of mutual dampness.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon at its peak — the heaviest rainfall of the year, swollen rivers, and waterfalls at maximum force. The town can feel genuinely isolated as mist and rain close in the valley, which is either meditative or maddening depending on your disposition. The rice paddies are at their most spectacular green, the temple gardens burst with frangipani, and Boat Racing Festival preparations begin. Prices remain low, and a rainy afternoon with a Lao coffee and a French baguette is a fine thing.",
    10: "October marks the monsoon's retreat: rain eases, the Mekong is high and dramatic, and the Boun Suang Heua (boat racing festival) fills the river with decorated longboats and the town with cheering crowds. Temperatures settle to a comfortable 30°C, and the landscape retains its lush post-monsoon beauty. Tourist numbers start climbing but haven't hit high-season levels. The end of Buddhist Lent (Awk Phansa) brings candlelit processions and a celebratory energy. A genuinely ideal time to visit.",
    11: "November is the golden transition — rain stops, skies clear to brilliant blue, and temperatures drop to a blissful 28°C with cool nights. The countryside is still green from the monsoon, Kuang Si waterfall runs strong with perfect swimming conditions, and the Mekong begins its slow retreat, revealing golden sandbars. That Luang Festival (Vientiane's biggest, but felt here too) adds cultural richness. High season begins, crowds build, but the beauty-to-crowd ratio is arguably the best of the year.",
    12: "December is peak season in full swing — 27°C days, 13°C nights perfect for sleeping, and the dry season firmly established. Christmas and New Year bring a cosmopolitan buzz to the night market and riverside restaurants, and every guesthouse is booked. The morning alms ceremony is heavily attended (sometimes problematically so — be respectful and follow local guidance). Kuang Si waterfall is turquoise perfection, the Mekong is calm for boat trips, and Hmong New Year celebrations in surrounding villages are culturally rich. Come early and book ahead.",
  },

  'la-vientiane': {
    1: "January in Vientiane is dry, warm (30°C), and surprisingly relaxed — the Laotian capital moves at a pace that makes other Southeast Asian cities look frantic. The Mekong runs low, revealing sandy banks perfect for sundowner drinks at the riverside restaurants. Pha That Luang (the golden stupa) gleams under clear skies, and the morning market along the river overflows with baguettes, pho, and fresh herbs. Tourist numbers are moderate — this is high season but Vientiane never really feels crowded.",
    2: "February pushes temperatures to 32°C with bone-dry conditions and hazy skies from agricultural burning in the region. The COPE Visitor Centre (documenting UXO clearance) is a sobering, essential visit, and the mix of French colonial and Buddhist architecture makes for an unusual walking tour. The night market on the Mekong is in full swing, and the beer gardens buzzing with Beerlao — possibly Southeast Asia's most drinkable lager. Crowds are at their high-season peak but the vibe stays mellow.",
    3: "March is the hottest month approaching 35°C, and the haze from burning season can make the air thick, but the Mekong sunsets take on surreal amber tones as a result. The Boun Pha Wet festival celebrates Prince Vessantara with temple ceremonies and merit-making. Air-conditioned cafe-hopping through Vientiane's growing coffee scene is a legitimate strategy. The city's French-Lao bakeries are among Southeast Asia's best-kept culinary secrets — flaky croissants with Lao coffee is a transcendent combination.",
    4: "April brings Lao New Year (Pi Mai Lao) and the entire city erupts in a three-day water festival — expect to be thoroughly soaked while 35°C temperatures make it not just welcome but necessary. The Mekong banks transform into party zones, and the temples host sand-stupa building ceremonies that are beautiful and communal. This is arguably the most fun (and wettest) time to visit. Book well ahead, prepare to get drenched, and bring a dry bag for your electronics.",
    5: "May signals the monsoon's arrival with dramatic afternoon thunderstorms, though mornings are usually clear and steamy at 33°C. The Boun Bang Fai (rocket festival) sees homemade rockets launched skyward to encourage rain — it's as chaotic and joyful as it sounds. The Mekong begins rising, the gardens and boulevards green up rapidly, and the tourist crowds thin to low-season levels. Hotel rates drop, and the city's temples feel serene without the tour groups.",
    6: "June is monsoon season proper: daily afternoon downpours, 32°C heat, and humidity that curls every page in your notebook. But the city is lush and alive, the Mekong swells with brown floodwater, and the rain brings a rhythmic beauty to temple visits. Vientiane's cafe culture thrives in the wet season, and this is the best time to explore the cooking schools and art galleries. Tourist numbers are low and the locals reclaim the night market — the food is better for it.",
    7: "July continues the wet rhythm with 250mm+ of rain and thick humidity at 31°C. The city's French-colonial shuttered buildings look particularly atmospheric in the rain, and a bowl of pho from a street stall while watching a downpour is peak Southeast Asian travel. The surrounding countryside is luminously green, and day trips to the Buddha Park (Xieng Khuan) feel mystical under monsoon skies. Budget travelers rejoice: this is the cheapest month with genuine off-the-beaten-path energy.",
    8: "August is the wettest month with relentless rain and 31°C humidity, but the city carries on with characteristic Lao calm. The Mekong is high and dramatic, occasionally threatening low-lying areas. Temple ceremonies and local life continue regardless, and the markets are full of seasonal produce. The Haw Phra Kaew museum and COPE Centre are excellent rainy-day options. If you're heading north to Luang Prabang, the road journey is lush but slow — plan for delays and pack patience.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon at full force — this is the peak of the wet season with heavy daily rain and the Mekong at its highest. The Boun Khao Padap Din festival honors ancestors with temple offerings. The rice paddies surrounding the city are at maximum green intensity, and the air clears briefly between storms to reveal dramatic cloudscapes. Boat racing preparations begin along the Mekong. Prices remain low and the city feels authentically Laotian without the tourist overlay.",
    10: "October marks the monsoon's retreat and the celebration of Awk Phansa (end of Buddhist Lent) with illuminated boat processions on the Mekong that are genuinely magical. Temperatures ease to 30°C, the rain becomes intermittent rather than daily, and the city emerges into golden autumn light. The Boun Suang Heua boat races bring festive energy. Tourist numbers begin climbing, and the night market picks up pace. A sweet transition month with cultural richness and improving weather.",
    11: "November is the start of the best season — dry, 28°C, and clear skies returning over the Mekong. That Luang Festival, centered on the golden stupa, is the biggest religious celebration of the year, with processions, markets, and a carnival atmosphere that draws visitors from across Laos. The city feels festive and proud. Riverside restaurants buzz, the night market expands, and the weather is genuinely perfect for walking the compact old town. High season begins, but Vientiane handles it with characteristic grace.",
    12: "December is peak dry season — 27°C days, cool 17°C nights, and the Mekong running low and golden in the afternoon light. Christmas and New Year bring a cosmopolitan energy to the riverside bars, and the night market is at its most vibrant. The morning market's baguettes and coffee are the legacy of French colonialism at its most delicious. Tourist numbers peak, but Vientiane's unhurried DNA means it never feels overwhelming. A perfect month for pairing temple visits with long riverside lunches and cold Beerlao.",
  },

  'lb-beirut': {
    1: "January is Beirut's rainiest month — 180mm of precipitation, 15°C highs, and grey Mediterranean skies — but the city's legendary resilience means the restaurants, bars, and cultural scene never slow down. The corniche is bracing in the rain, the Hamra neighborhood's cafes are thick with cigarette smoke and heated debate, and the food — hummus, manakish, shawarma — is at its most soul-warming. Ski season is underway just 90 minutes away in the mountains, making Lebanon's famous 'ski in the morning, swim in the afternoon' almost possible.",
    2: "February stays cool and wet at 16°C with the last heavy rains of winter, but the Mediterranean light starts brightening noticeably. The Mar Mikhael neighborhood's bar scene is electric regardless of weather, and the Sursock Museum hosts exhibitions worth braving the drizzle for. The Raouche sea rocks look most dramatic under stormy skies, and a meze lunch at a traditional restaurant in Gemmayzeh can easily stretch to three hours. Early almond blossoms appear in the hills above the city.",
    3: "March is Beirut's spring turn — 18°C, decreasing rain, and the first real terrace-sitting weather of the year. The city's legendary nightlife kicks into higher gear, and the seaside promenade fills with joggers and families. Day trips to the Jeita Grotto (spectacular limestone caves) and Byblos (one of the world's oldest cities) are ideal in the mild weather. The food markets overflow with fresh herbs, artichokes, and tabbouleh ingredients. A genuine shoulder-season sweet spot.",
    4: "April is gorgeous: 22°C, wildflowers in the surrounding hills, and the Mediterranean shimmering under increasingly generous sunshine. Easter celebrations (both Western and Orthodox) fill the churches and streets with processions and festive energy. The outdoor dining scene explodes — rooftop bars, beachfront restaurants, and sidewalk cafes compete for your evening. Byblos and Baalbek day trips benefit from perfect weather and manageable crowds. This is arguably when Beirut's famous joie de vivre peaks.",
    5: "May delivers near-perfect Mediterranean weather: 26°C, ten hours of sunshine, and virtually no rain. The beach clubs south of Beirut start their season, and the corniche buzzes from dawn to midnight. The Baalbek International Festival begins its buildup, and the city feels cosmopolitan and alive. Hiking in the Qadisha Valley through ancient cedar groves is spectacular. Crowds are building to summer levels, and the city's famous all-night energy is in full effect.",
    6: "June is summer proper: 29°C, zero rain, and Beirut fully committed to its dual identity as Mediterranean playground and cultural powerhouse. The beach clubs are packed, rooftop parties run until sunrise, and the fresh fish restaurants along the coast serve the day's catch under fairy lights. Baalbek Music Festival draws international artists to perform amid Roman ruins — one of the world's most extraordinary concert venues. Book ahead; the city fills with Gulf visitors escaping their own brutal summers.",
    7: "July is peak summer: 31°C, relentless sunshine, and Beirut's beach-club culture at maximum volume. The city is at its busiest and most expensive, with Gulf tourists, diaspora visitors, and European sunseekers all competing for seaside tables. The nightlife is legendary — Gemmayzeh and Mar Mikhael are alive until dawn. Baalbek festival continues with headline acts, and the Mediterranean is a warm 27°C. Book restaurants, clubs, and hotels well ahead, and prepare for a city that parties like sleep is optional.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 32°C, no rain, and Beirut running at full tilt. The city's diaspora returns en masse, giving everything a reunion-party energy. Beach clubs, mountain escapes (the Cedars region is 25°C compared to the coastal heat), and late-night meze sessions define the month. The Jounieh cable car offers cooler mountain air with bay views. Crowds and prices are at annual highs, but the energy is infectious and the seafood has never been fresher.",
    9: "September is Beirut's golden month — 30°C, still bone-dry, but the summer crowds begin thinning and the city exhales. The Mediterranean is at its warmest (28°C), making this the best month for swimming. The cultural calendar pivots to film festivals and gallery openings, and the restaurant scene launches autumn menus. Day trips to the Chouf Cedar Reserve catch the last summer light filtering through ancient trees. Prices start softening, and the city's rhythm slows from sprint to confident stride.",
    10: "October is the smart traveler's pick: 26°C, the first gentle rains returning, and Beirut's famous autumn light painting the Ottoman-era buildings gold. The wine harvest in the Bekaa Valley is underway — Lebanon's winemaking tradition is older than France's, and the tasting rooms are spectacular. Hiking in the Qadisha Valley is ideal in the cooling weather. Crowds are moderate, prices reasonable, and the food scene at its most seasonal and exciting.",
    11: "November cools to 21°C with increasing rain and shorter days, but Beirut's indoor culture fires on all cylinders — theater, live music, art exhibitions, and some of the Middle East's best restaurants. The Raouche Rocks look moody and magnificent under grey skies, and a long lunch at a traditional Lebanese restaurant with arak and meze is a perfectly valid day plan. Tourist numbers drop, hotel deals appear, and the city's famous warmth (both thermal and human) feels most genuine.",
    12: "December brings proper Mediterranean winter — 17°C, significant rain, and the city lit up with Christmas decorations (Lebanon's Christian community celebrates with gusto). The ski resorts in the mountains open, and the old dream of skiing and seaside dining in the same day becomes possible. New Year's Eve in Beirut is legendary, with every rooftop and restaurant competing for the most spectacular celebration. The food is comforting and abundant, and the city's indomitable spirit shines brightest in its darkest month.",
  },

  'lb-mount-lebanon': {
    1: "January blankets Mount Lebanon in snow above 1,500m — the cedar groves wear white caps, ski resorts like Mzaar and Cedars are in full swing, and the mountain villages are cozy with wood-fire warmth. Temperatures hover around 5°C at altitude with frequent precipitation. The Lebanese après-ski scene is surprisingly sophisticated, with excellent wine and mountain cuisine. On clear days, the views from the ridgeline down to the Mediterranean are staggering.",
    2: "February is peak ski season with reliable snow cover and daytime temps around 6°C at resort altitude. The Cedars of God forest under fresh snow is one of the Levant's most iconic winter scenes. Weekend crowds from Beirut fill the slopes, but midweek skiing is uncrowded and the powder surprisingly good. Village restaurants serve hearty kibbeh and fattoush by the fire, and the mountain air is bracingly clean after Beirut's bustle.",
    3: "March starts the spring transition — snow lingers above 2,000m but the lower villages see temperatures climbing to 12°C with wildflowers emerging on the hillsides. Late-season skiing remains viable, and the melting snow feeds waterfalls and streams throughout the Qadisha Valley. The ancient monasteries carved into the valley walls are accessible again, and the hiking trails start opening. A month of contrasts: snow on the peaks, spring flowers in the valleys.",
    4: "April is Mount Lebanon's spring glory — 16°C, wildflowers carpeting every slope, and the Qadisha Valley at its most lush and green. The apple and cherry orchards bloom in the Bsharri region, and Easter celebrations in the mountain villages are deeply traditional and moving. Hiking conditions are excellent, the cedar forests are fresh and fragrant, and the mountain restaurants open their terraces. The snow retreats to the highest peaks, creating dramatic backdrop for every trail.",
    5: "May brings warm, dry perfection at 22°C — the mountains are green, the valleys are in bloom, and the hiking is world-class through cedar forests, along the Qadisha Valley rim, and up to the peaks. The famous Cedars of God are at their most photogenic with new growth against blue skies. Mountain biking trails open, and the food shifts to fresh spring ingredients: herbs, greens, and local cheeses. A genuinely underrated destination for outdoor enthusiasts.",
    6: "June pushes to 27°C with long, sun-drenched days and the last green before summer browns the lower slopes. The mountain villages buzz with weekend visitors from Beirut escaping the coastal heat, and the restaurant terraces fill with locals enjoying arak and meze with panoramic views. The hiking trails through the Chouf Cedar Reserve are spectacular, and the Baatara Gorge waterfall is flowing strongly. Evenings cool pleasantly, making mountain stays far more comfortable than the coast.",
    7: "July is the mountain escape month — while Beirut swelters at 32°C, Mount Lebanon offers 25-28°C with breezy evenings and zero rain. The villages of Bsharri, Ehden, and Hasroun fill with vacationers, and the festivals, live music, and outdoor dining create a lively summer atmosphere. Hiking at dawn reveals the Mediterranean far below, and the cedar forests provide cool shade by midday. Accommodation books up fast; this is peak domestic tourism season.",
    8: "August matches July's summer rhythm with warm days, cool mountain nights, and the Lebanese diaspora returning to their ancestral villages for family gatherings and village festivals. The Assumption (August 15) is celebrated with particular fervor in the Christian mountain villages. The Qadisha Valley hikes are best attempted early morning before afternoon heat, and the stargazing from the high ridges is extraordinary. Book well ahead — every mountain guesthouse fills for August.",
    9: "September is the mountain's graceful autumn approach — 24°C, the first hints of color in the deciduous forests, and the summer crowds departing. The grape and apple harvests bring festive energy to the villages, and the winemaking in the Bekaa (just over the ridge) is in full swing. Hiking conditions are ideal: cool mornings, warm afternoons, and spectacular clarity. The cedar forests are peaceful again, and the mountain restaurants pivot to autumn comfort food.",
    10: "October brings proper autumn: 18°C, the forests turning gold and rust, and the mountain villages settling into a quieter rhythm. The Qadisha Valley in autumn color is breathtaking, and the crisp mountain air makes every hike feel revitalizing. The first rains return, greening the lower slopes and filling the waterfalls. Village wine festivals celebrate the harvest, and the food is at its most hearty — think slow-cooked lamb, fresh bread, and mountain herbs.",
    11: "November cools to 12°C with regular rain and the first snow dusting the highest peaks. The mountain villages grow quiet as the tourist season ends, but the atmosphere is contemplative and genuine. The ancient monasteries of the Qadisha Valley are most atmospheric in the autumn mist, and the Cedars of God stand ancient and resilient against grey skies. Early ski preparations begin at the resorts, and the mountain cuisine — warming stews, fresh bread, arak by the fire — hits its stride.",
    12: "December brings winter back to the mountains: 7°C at altitude, snow returning in earnest, and the ski resorts opening for the season. Christmas in the Maronite mountain villages is deeply traditional, with midnight masses, decorated cedar trees, and enormous family feasts. The Cedars under fresh snow are magnificent, and the first ski runs of the season draw weekend crowds from Beirut. Cozy guesthouses, wood fires, and mountain hospitality make December in Mount Lebanon a genuine winter wonderland.",
  },

  'lc-stlucia': {
    1: "January is prime Caribbean season on St. Lucia — 29°C, the Pitons rising dramatically against blue skies, and the trade winds keeping things comfortable while every beach bar competes for your rum-punch loyalty. Crowds are at their peak (high season), so the volcanic hot springs at Sulphur Springs and the Anse Chastanet snorkeling are busy. The rainforest canopy is lush from the wet season, and a catamaran sail between the Pitons is the postcard shot you came for.",
    2: "February keeps the dry-season dream alive: 29°C, minimal rain, and the island buzzing with Carnival energy (if it falls this month) — expect soca, calypso, and costume parades that rival Trinidad's. Valentine's Day here is practically a national sport, given the romantic setting. Diving off Anse Chastanet reveals healthy reefs, and the Tet Paul Nature Trail hike gives you Piton views without the full summit commitment. Peak pricing persists, but the weather delivers.",
    3: "March is St. Lucia at its driest — maybe 60mm of rain the entire month, 30°C days, and that Caribbean blue water at a perfect 27°C. Jazz & Arts Festival season begins, adding world-class performances to the natural beauty. Whale watching off the west coast occasionally yields sperm whale sightings, and the snorkeling in Soufriere Bay is at peak clarity. High season thins slightly after the February rush, offering marginally better hotel availability.",
    4: "April delivers the sweet spot: still dry and sunny at 30°C, but the winter crowds have largely departed and resort prices start their descent. The hiking up Gros Piton (a genuinely challenging but unforgettable climb) is best in the cooler morning hours. The rum distilleries welcome visitors, the chocolate estate tours are a revelation (St. Lucian cacao is exceptional), and the Friday night jump-up street party in Gros Islet is peak Caribbean vibes. A savvy traveler's month.",
    5: "May is the shoulder-season secret: temperatures hold at 30°C, brief afternoon showers green up the hillsides, and the tourist drop-off means genuine deals at properties that would cost double in February. The rainforest hikes are lush and the waterfalls flow strongly. St. Lucia Jazz Festival (if scheduled) brings music to venues across the island. The sea is calm and warm (28°C), perfect for snorkeling the reefs without the crowds. Hurricane season hasn't really started.",
    6: "June marks the official start of hurricane season, though direct hits in June are rare. Temperatures stay at 31°C with increasing afternoon showers that keep the volcanic landscape brilliantly green. The island is in low season — prices drop significantly, beaches are uncrowded, and the Pitons viewpoints feel almost private. The Anse Chastanet reef is teeming with marine life, and the roadside vendors' fresh mango and grilled fish are somehow even better without a queue.",
    7: "July brings proper wet-season energy: 31°C, regular tropical showers, and the rainforest at its most exuberant. The Carnival celebrations (if July dates) are spectacular, with elaborate costumes and soca music filling the streets. Swimming in the volcanic mud baths near Soufriere is surreally fun, and the hot springs feel most luxurious when rain patters on the canopy above. Budget travelers find exceptional value, and the island's charm is undiminished by a few daily showers.",
    8: "August is the peak of hurricane season — keep flexible plans and travel insurance current. That said, most days are sunny and 31°C with afternoon squalls rather than full-day storms. The island is at its quietest and cheapest, and the Pitons viewpoint without another soul in sight is worth every raindrop. Turtle nesting occurs on some northern beaches, and the diving remains excellent between weather systems. A calculated risk that usually pays off beautifully.",
    9: "September is statistically the highest hurricane risk month, and visitor numbers reflect that caution — the island is very quiet. But the weather between systems is gorgeous: 31°C, warm seas, and that post-rain tropical freshness that makes the rainforest hikes intoxicating. Prices hit rock bottom, and the few travelers here get the most authentic St. Lucian experience — local festivals, unhurried meals, and genuine connections with island residents.",
    10: "October is the tail end of peak hurricane season, but the weather is usually stabilizing with less rain than September. The island remains quiet and affordable at 31°C, and the rainforest is at maximum lushness. The Creole Heritage Month celebrations showcase St. Lucian culture through food, music, and storytelling — Jounen Kweyol (Creole Day) is vibrant and deeply local. The diving and snorkeling remain excellent, and the volcanic landscapes look impossibly green.",
    11: "November marks the transition back toward dry season — rain eases, hurricane risk drops sharply, and temperatures settle at a comfortable 30°C. The island starts waking up for the winter tourist season, but November still offers shoulder-season pricing and thin crowds. The Atlantic Festival of Lights begins decorating the streets, and Soufriere's volcanic hot springs are blissful in the cooler evenings. A smart window for those who want the beauty without the peak-season markup.",
    12: "December is high season's dramatic entrance: 29°C, festive lights strung between palm trees, and the Pitons silhouetted against spectacular sunsets. Prices climb steeply for the holiday period, and the beaches and restaurants fill with winter-escape travelers. The St. Lucia Jazz Festival's end-of-year events add musical flair, and Christmas celebrations blend Caribbean warmth with colonial-era traditions. Book months ahead for the holiday weeks, but early December still offers reasonable availability.",
  },

  'li-liechtenstein': {
    1: "January transforms tiny Liechtenstein into an Alpine winter gem — temperatures around -1°C, fresh snow blanketing the Rhine Valley, and the Malbun ski resort offering uncrowded slopes with views into Austria and Switzerland. Cross-country skiing through the Steg valley is serenely beautiful, and the capital Vaduz is quiet enough to hear snow falling on the castle turrets. Warm up with a bowl of Kasknopfle (cheese spaetzle) at a Gasthaus — you've earned it.",
    2: "February is peak ski season in Malbun with reliable snow, comfortable crowds (this is a small country, after all), and crisp -1°C days that make every run sparkle. The castle above Vaduz looks like something from a snow globe, and the Kunstmuseum's collection provides cultured shelter on stormy days. Fondue and Rosti are essentially medical necessities in this weather. The tiny country punches well above its weight in winter charm.",
    3: "March starts the thaw — temperatures climb to 8°C, the Rhine Valley greens up, and the last skiing at Malbun rewards with spring snow and lengthening days. The vineyards on the hillsides begin their annual awakening, and hiking trails at lower elevations open up. Vaduz's galleries and the Treasure Chamber (crown jewels and Faberge eggs) are perfect for the mix of sunshine and occasional showers. A transitional month that catches Liechtenstein between seasons.",
    4: "April brings proper spring: 14°C, wildflowers on the Alpine meadows, and the Rhine Valley looking impossibly green between the mountain walls. The hiking season officially begins, with trails climbing from the valley floor through forest to open pasture. The vineyards are budding, and the royal castle above Vaduz sits above it all with quiet authority. Tourist numbers are low, and the country's handful of restaurants serve increasingly fresh seasonal menus. Delightfully uncrowded.",
    5: "May is Liechtenstein in full bloom — 18°C, Alpine meadows carpeted in wildflowers, and the hiking at its absolute best before summer heat arrives. The Princes' Way trail from Vaduz to Malbun offers panoramic views of the Rhine Valley, Swiss Alps, and Austrian peaks. The local wine (yes, Liechtenstein makes wine, and it's surprisingly good) is available for tasting in Vaduz. Crowds are minimal by any standard — you might have an entire trail to yourself.",
    6: "June delivers warm Alpine summer at 22°C with long days and the mountains at their most accessible. The Augstenberg and Naafkopf summit hikes reward with 360-degree views across four countries. National Day preparations begin (August 15), and the open-air restaurants in Vaduz's pedestrian zone serve local trout and venison. Occasional thunderstorms roll through the valley but clear quickly. A genuinely lovely, thoroughly uncrowded Alpine destination.",
    7: "July is the warmest month at 24°C with the longest days and the best high-Alpine hiking conditions. The trails above Malbun reach wild, flower-strewn ridgelines with chamois grazing on the slopes. The Liechtenstein Trail (75km circumnavigation of the entire country) is at its prime. Summer concerts and outdoor events add cultural spark to the valley, and the vineyards are lush and green. Even at peak season, 'crowded' here means maybe twenty other hikers on a popular trail.",
    8: "August brings Liechtenstein's biggest day — National Day on August 15, when the prince invites the entire country (all 40,000 residents) to his castle gardens for a party with fireworks and free beer. At 23°C with occasional afternoon thunderstorms, the hiking remains excellent and the Alpine meadows are at full glory. The event is genuinely unique: how many countries fit their national celebration in a single garden? Book accommodation early for the holiday week.",
    9: "September is golden: 19°C, the Alpine forests beginning their autumn turn, and the grape harvest underway in the Rhine Valley vineyards. Hiking conditions are ideal with clear skies and cooler temperatures, and the trails are quiet after the summer visitors depart. The Vaduz wine festival celebrates the harvest with tastings and local food, and the castle looks particularly regal against early autumn color. One of the best months to experience this microstate's outsized charm.",
    10: "October paints Liechtenstein in autumn splendor — 12°C, golden larch forests on the mountainsides, and the Rhine Valley misty in the mornings. The hiking season winds down at higher elevations but the valley trails are beautiful under falling leaves. The farmers' markets feature autumn produce, game dishes appear on restaurant menus, and the wine from the recent harvest starts being sampled. Tourist numbers are very low, making the museums and castle viewpoints pleasantly empty.",
    11: "November is grey and contemplative at 5°C — fog fills the Rhine Valley, the mountains appear and disappear through clouds, and the first snow dusts the peaks. The ski resort hasn't opened yet, but the indoor attractions (Kunstmuseum, Landesmuseum, Postal Museum) are excellent for a small country. The restaurants lean into hearty Alpine comfort food, and the castle above the fog line creates an almost mystical scene. A quiet, atmospheric month for those who enjoy European autumn at its moodiest.",
    12: "December brings Christmas to Liechtenstein in miniature perfection — the Vaduz Christmas market, tiny but charming, fills the main square with mulled wine, handicrafts, and the scent of roasted chestnuts. Temperatures hover around 1°C, snow is likely, and the castle lit up above the valley is genuinely magical. Malbun opens for early skiing if conditions allow, and the fondue season is in full force. The entire country feels like a Christmas village you can walk across — because it essentially is.",
  },

  'lk-colombo-west': {
    1: "January is the west coast's dry-season sweet spot — 30°C, calm Indian Ocean waters, and Colombo buzzing with post-holiday energy. The beaches from Mount Lavinia to Negombo are at their best: fishermen haul in the morning catch while tourists bodyboard the gentle swells. Galle Face Green's food stalls serve isso wade (prawn fritters) at sunset, and the Pettah bazaar is a sensory overload of spices, textiles, and noise. Crowds are at peak levels, but the city absorbs them with cheerful chaos.",
    2: "February continues the dry streak with 31°C days, minimal rain, and the west coast in full tourist mode. Independence Day (February 4) brings parades and cultural performances in Colombo. The Negombo fish market at dawn is a raw, magnificent spectacle, and the rooftop bars in Colombo Fort serve creative cocktails with harbor views. The sea is calm and warm (28°C), perfect for diving the reef at Hikkaduwa further south. High-season pricing but high-quality weather.",
    3: "March pushes toward the year's peak heat at 32°C with building humidity but still minimal rain on the west coast. The Colombo food scene — a collision of Sri Lankan, Tamil, Muslim, and colonial influences — is reason enough to visit: hoppers with egg at a street stall, then a tasting menu at Ministry of Crab. The beaches remain excellent, and whale watching trips from Mirissa (south of here) are in prime season. Crowds are steady; hotel prices remain firm.",
    4: "April arrives with the Sinhala and Tamil New Year (mid-April), transforming the city with celebrations, traditional foods, and a festive shutdown that's the closest Sri Lanka gets to a national pause. Temperatures hit 32°C and the first inter-monsoon showers appear — brief but dramatic. The west coast still has good beach weather, but the transition to the southwest monsoon is imminent. The cultural experience of New Year celebrations alone makes April worth the humidity.",
    5: "May is the monsoon's dramatic entrance on the west coast — rainfall shoots up, seas turn rough, and the beaches from Colombo south become swimming-unfriendly. But the city itself remains vibrant at 31°C: museums, temples, and the emerging arts scene in the Slave Island neighborhood are excellent rainy-day options. Vesak (Buddha's birthday) in May fills the streets with illuminated pandals and lanterns — one of Sri Lanka's most spectacular festivals. Hotels drop prices noticeably.",
    6: "June is full southwest monsoon: heavy rain (200mm+), rough seas, and the west coast in its off-season. The beaches are not for swimming, but the rain brings a moody beauty to Colombo's colonial architecture and temple gardens. This is the time to pivot east — Trincomalee and the east coast are in their dry season. If staying west, embrace the indoor Colombo experience: cooking classes, the National Museum, and the country's best restaurants at their least crowded.",
    7: "July continues the monsoon with persistent rain and high humidity at 30°C. The west coast remains in its wet season, with rough seas and grey skies the norm. But Colombo's food scene doesn't hibernate: rice and curry lunch packets are everywhere, and a rainy afternoon at a Colombo art gallery or the Barefoot bookshop is a perfectly civilized way to spend the day. Hotel prices are at their lowest, and the city's genuine personality — without the tourist polish — shines through.",
    8: "August is still monsoon territory with heavy rain and rough seas on the west coast, though the city gets brief sunny breaks between downpours. The Esala Perahera procession from Kandy (a short train ride away) is one of Asia's most spectacular festivals. Colombo's restaurant and bar scene keeps buzzing regardless of weather, and the Independence Memorial Hall area is atmospheric in the rain. A legitimate time to visit if you focus on culture over beach.",
    9: "September sees the southwest monsoon beginning to weaken — rain decreases, the sun appears more frequently, and the west coast shows signs of recovery. The sea remains choppy but the beaches start looking inviting again. Colombo's cultural calendar picks up with art exhibitions and food festivals, and the afternoon light through clearing clouds creates spectacular photography conditions. A good transitional month with improving weather and still-low prices.",
    10: "October is the inter-monsoon period: short, sharp showers are likely, but sunny stretches are frequent and the west coast beaches start welcoming swimmers again at 30°C. The Deepavali (Diwali) festival lights up the Tamil neighborhoods with oil lamps and sweets. Surfing at Mount Lavinia picks up with cleaner swells, and the Colombo dining scene launches its holiday-season menus. Tourist numbers begin climbing, but October still offers value compared to the approaching high season.",
    11: "November is the second inter-monsoon month — expect unpredictable afternoon showers but increasingly long sunny periods and calming seas. The west coast is transitioning back to dry season, and the beaches from Negombo to Hikkaduwa become progressively more inviting. Colombo's Christmas decorations start appearing (the city has a significant Christian community), and the night markets on Galle Face Green are in full swing. Shoulder-season pricing with improving weather.",
    12: "December marks the return of the dry season and the west coast's tourist influx — 30°C, calm seas, and Colombo decked out for Christmas and New Year. The beaches are back to their best, hotel prices spike for the holiday period, and the city's rooftop bars are packed with revelers. The Pettah Christmas markets add festive chaos, and the seafood is exceptional as the calmer seas bring better catches. Book early for December; Sri Lanka's west coast is no longer a secret.",
  },

  'lk-galle-south': {
    1: "January is the south coast at peak form — 30°C, calm seas, and the UNESCO-listed Galle Fort looking magnificent under clear skies. The surf at Unawatuna and Weligama draws beginners and intermediates, while the snorkeling off Hikkaduwa's coral reef is at its clearest. Turtle hatcheries along the coast welcome visitors, and a sunset walk atop Galle Fort's ramparts with a king coconut in hand is the quintessential Sri Lankan moment. Peak season means peak prices and crowds.",
    2: "February continues the dry-season perfection: 31°C, barely any rain, and the Indian Ocean a warm, inviting 28°C. Whale watching from Mirissa is in prime season — blue whales, the largest animals on Earth, feed in these waters. The boutique hotels within Galle Fort are booked solid, so plan ahead. The southern beaches are busy but the coastline is long enough to find your own stretch. Fresh crab at a beachside restaurant in Ahangama is the kind of meal you plan trips around.",
    3: "March is the last of the reliable dry months: 32°C with building humidity and the inter-monsoon approaching. Stilt fishermen pose photogenically at dawn (yes, they really do fish this way, not just for tourists), and the surf at Hiriketiya — the south coast's hippest beach — is at its most consistent. The pace along the Matara-to-Galle coast road is languid and satisfying. Whale season begins winding down but March trips still yield sightings. Book now before the rains shift the calendar east.",
    4: "April brings the Sinhala and Tamil New Year celebrations (mid-month) and the first serious inter-monsoon rains — but the south coast is still largely enjoyable at 31°C with afternoon showers rather than all-day grey. The sea gets choppier, and some beach activities become weather-dependent. Galle Fort is atmospheric in the rain, with its colonial architecture gleaming wet, and the food scene inside the fort walls is extraordinary year-round. Prices soften as tourists thin.",
    5: "May is when the southwest monsoon arrives and the south coast pivots to its off-season — rough seas, 200mm+ of rain, and the beaches more for looking than swimming. But Galle Fort in the rain is hauntingly beautiful, the museums and boutiques inside the walls stay open, and hotel prices drop significantly. The surfing at Hiriketiya can actually improve for experienced riders who like bigger waves. A contemplative, budget-friendly time when the coast shows its moody, dramatic side.",
    6: "June is full monsoon on the south coast: heavy rain, rough grey seas, and the tourist infrastructure shifting to low gear. Many beachside restaurants close or reduce hours, but Galle Fort's year-round establishments carry on with atmospheric dining. The upside: hotel rates at half-price or less, and the fort without crowds feels almost private. If beach swimming is non-negotiable, head to the east coast instead — Arugam Bay's season is just beginning.",
    7: "July continues the monsoon pattern with persistent rain and choppy seas, though Galle Fort's solid stone walls have weathered far worse over 400 years. The literary festival (if scheduled) brings cultural life to the fort, and the rainy-day experience of exploring the fort's boutiques, cafes, and ramparts has its own charm. The surrounding cinnamon plantations are at their most aromatic, and a spice garden tour is a perfect wet-weather activity.",
    8: "August sees the monsoon persist but with slightly decreasing intensity — the sun breaks through more often, and the south coast begins its slow recovery. The Esala Perahera in nearby Kataragama is a magnificent religious procession worth the detour. Galle Fort's atmosphere in the clearing monsoon light is special, and the reduced tourist numbers mean genuine interactions with the fort's resident community. Prices remain low; the value proposition is strong.",
    9: "September marks the monsoon's retreat from the south coast — rain decreases noticeably, the sea begins calming, and the beaches start inviting again. The surf at Weligama and Hiriketiya returns to rideable conditions, and the reef snorkeling at Hikkaduwa improves weekly. Galle Fort emerges from its rainy-season quietude, and the boutique hotels start filling again. A smart traveler's month: improving weather, not-yet-peak prices, and the south coast shaking off its slumber.",
    10: "October is the inter-monsoon wild card: short, intense showers alternate with sunny stretches at 30°C, and the south coast is visibly coming back to life. The sea calms progressively, turtle nesting season begins, and the whale watching from Mirissa cautiously restarts. Galle Fort's evening atmosphere — golden light on ancient walls — is reliably stunning. Tourist numbers are building but haven't hit high-season intensity, making this a genuinely pleasant shoulder month.",
    11: "November sees the south coast firmly returning to dry-season form: rain tapers off, the Indian Ocean calms to swimming condition, and the surf breaks clean up. The first wave of high-season tourists arrives, but the month still offers reasonable pricing. Galle Fort's rampart walks at sunset are golden and uncrowded on weekdays. The seafood along the coast improves as calmer seas mean better fishing, and the turtle hatcheries see increasing hatchling releases.",
    12: "December is high season's grand return: 30°C, calm seas, and the south coast packed with holiday travelers from Europe and beyond. Galle Fort is at its most bustling, the beaches from Unawatuna to Mirissa are postcard-perfect, and every restaurant is full. Christmas celebrations in the fort's churches add festive charm, and New Year's Eve on the ramparts with fireworks over the Indian Ocean is genuinely special. Prices peak; book months ahead and don't expect bargains.",
  },

  'lk-kandy-hills': {
    1: "January in the hill country is Sri Lanka's most pleasant escape: 24°C in Kandy, cooler still at higher elevations around Nuwara Eliya (15°C), and the inter-monsoon dry spell making the tea plantations glow emerald under clear skies. The Temple of the Tooth is at its most serene for morning puja, and the scenic train to Ella (through tea estates and over the Nine Arch Bridge) is one of Asia's great rail journeys. Crowds are moderate; the hills absorb visitors gracefully.",
    2: "February stays dry and comfortable at 25°C — arguably the best month for the hill country. The tea plantations are in active plucking season, and a factory visit reveals the art behind Ceylon tea. Hiking from Ella to Little Adam's Peak or through the Horton Plains to World's End viewpoint rewards with crystal visibility. The Kandy Botanical Gardens (Peradeniya) are in bloom, and the morning mist over the lake creates postcard moments. High season without high stress.",
    3: "March warms slightly to 27°C with the first inter-monsoon showers beginning to appear, but the hill country remains largely pleasant and green. The tea estates look their best with new growth after picking, and the waterfalls around Nuwara Eliya run strongly. Train journeys through the hills are at their most photogenic with morning mist and afternoon clarity. The pace is slower here than the coast — embrace it with a cup of fresh-plucked Ceylon tea on a plantation veranda.",
    4: "April brings heavier inter-monsoon rains and the Sinhala New Year celebrations that fill Kandy's streets with traditional games, special foods, and genuine festive joy. Temperatures hover around 27°C with high humidity, and the hills are lushly green. The train to Ella is magical through rain and mist, and Horton Plains takes on an almost Scottish-moors atmosphere. The Temple of the Tooth holds special New Year ceremonies worth attending. A cultural highlight month despite the weather.",
    5: "May is when the southwest monsoon arrives, bringing significant rain (300mm+) to the hill country — but this is the tea plantations' growing season, and the landscape is impossibly, almost aggressively green. Vesak celebrations light up Kandy with lanterns and illuminated displays. The famous train ride is atmospheric in the mist, though views can be obscured. Nuwara Eliya feels properly English with rain pattering on colonial-era hotels. Prices drop, and the hills feel contemplative.",
    6: "June continues the monsoon with heavy rain and mist clinging to the mountains, but the tea estates are at peak production and the factories hum with activity. Kandy's indoor attractions — the Temple of the Tooth, the National Museum, the gem museum — are perfect for wet days. The Poson full moon poya day in June celebrates Buddhism's arrival in Sri Lanka with illuminated temples and processions. Leeches appear on jungle trails; tuck your trousers and carry salt.",
    7: "July sees the monsoon persist but with the Esala Perahera — Sri Lanka's grandest festival — transforming Kandy into a spectacular pageant of costumed elephants, fire dancers, and drumming processions over ten nights. At 26°C with regular rain, the festival's nighttime parades are electric, and the Temple of the Tooth is at the center of it all. This is peak cultural tourism in the hill country; book accommodation months ahead and embrace the magnificent chaos.",
    8: "August continues the Esala Perahera if it extends into the month, and the monsoon rain keeps the hills lush and dramatic. The train to Ella through clouds and mist is moody and beautiful, and the tea plantations shimmer with rain. Nuwara Eliya's colonial-era atmosphere — golf clubs, horse racing, mock-Tudor hotels — is most amusing when it actually rains like England. Horton Plains hikes require waterproof gear but reward with otherworldly cloud-forest scenery.",
    9: "September begins the monsoon's retreat from the hills — rain decreases, sunshine increases, and the tea country starts drying into its most photographable state. The plantations are still lush, the waterfalls flow strongly, and the morning mist over Kandy Lake creates atmospheric temple visits. Crowds thin after the Perahera season, and the hill stations feel peacefully uncrowded. The train journey reveals more views as clouds lift. A transitional month that rewards patience.",
    10: "October brings the second inter-monsoon: expect short, intense showers at 27°C, but plenty of sunshine between them. The Horton Plains are green and atmospheric, World's End viewpoint has its best visibility in the early morning, and the tea estates look freshly washed and vivid. Kandy's cultural scene picks up with temple festivals and dance performances. Tourist numbers remain moderate, and the combination of improving weather and reasonable prices makes October a smart choice.",
    11: "November sees the northeast monsoon bring rain to the eastern slopes, but the Kandy region stays relatively moderate with intermittent showers at 26°C. The tea country is transitioning toward the dry season, and the hillside views improve as clouds lift. The Temple of the Tooth's evening puja is atmospheric with rain on the temple roof, and the Botanical Gardens are lush and uncrowded. Accommodation prices remain competitive, making this a good-value month for the hill country experience.",
    12: "December brings drier conditions back to the hills: 25°C, clear mornings, and the tea plantations gleaming under returning sunshine. Tourist numbers climb for the holiday season, and the Kandy-to-Ella train becomes heavily booked — reserve your seat well ahead. Christmas in Sri Lanka's hill country has a unique charm: colonial-era churches hold midnight mass, and the cooler temperatures (15°C in Nuwara Eliya) make mulled wine actually appropriate. The cultural and natural beauty is at a comfortable high.",
  },

  'lk-trincomalee-east': {
    1: "January on the east coast is still monsoon territory — 26°C with heavy rain (300mm+), rough seas, and many beach operations closed. Trincomalee's Fort Frederick and the Koneswaram Temple perched on Swami Rock remain visitable between downpours, and the empty beaches have a dramatic, wind-swept beauty. This is firmly the off-season, with rock-bottom prices and minimal infrastructure. The west and south coasts are your better bet this month.",
    2: "February sees the northeast monsoon weakening — rain decreases and sunny spells become more frequent at 28°C. The sea begins calming, and the first brave swimmers return to Uppuveli and Nilaveli beaches. Trincomalee's natural harbor (one of the world's finest) is stunning as the weather clears. Whale watching season hasn't started yet, but the reef snorkeling off Pigeon Island begins to become viable. The east coast is waking up from its monsoon sleep.",
    3: "March is the transition month: rain tapers to light showers, temperatures climb to 30°C, and the east coast's famous turquoise waters start showing their true colors. Pigeon Island's coral reefs emerge as the seas calm, and the snorkeling is increasingly spectacular. Tourist infrastructure reopens gradually, and Uppuveli's beach restaurants fire up their grills. The Hindu temples of Trincomalee host colorful festivals, and the laid-back east coast vibe — less developed than the south — is its own reward.",
    4: "April brings the east coast to life: 32°C, calm seas, and the beaches of Nilaveli revealing their white-sand perfection. Sinhala and Tamil New Year celebrations add cultural richness, and the surf at Arugam Bay (further south) begins its famous season. Pigeon Island snorkeling is at its early-season best with reef sharks, turtles, and vibrant coral. The hot springs at Kanniya are an otherworldly experience. Tourist numbers are building but the east coast never gets truly crowded.",
    5: "May is when the east coast hits its stride: 33°C, dry skies, and the Indian Ocean a stunning, calm blue that makes the west coast's current monsoon look like another country entirely. Blue whale watching from Trincomalee begins, with sightings off the continental shelf that are among the world's most reliable. Pigeon Island is at peak snorkeling conditions, and the beaches are uncrowded and glorious. This is Sri Lanka's great seasonal flip — head east while the west sleeps.",
    6: "June is prime east coast season: 33°C, bone-dry, and those turquoise waters at their most inviting. Whale watching is in full swing — blue whales and sperm whales are regularly spotted on morning excursions. Pigeon Island's reef is crystal-clear, and the beach at Nilaveli stretches empty and white in both directions. The surf at Arugam Bay is pumping for experienced riders. Tourist numbers are moderate and the vibe is relaxed. Arguably the best month on the east coast.",
    7: "July continues the dry-season magic with zero rain, 33°C heat, and the sea at peak calm. The Vel festival in Trincomalee is a spectacular Hindu celebration with chariot processions and temple ceremonies. Whale watching yields consistent sightings, and Pigeon Island is snorkeling paradise. The east coast is at its busiest, which by Sri Lankan standards means pleasantly populated rather than overwhelmed. Evening walks along Uppuveli beach with the lighthouse glowing are quietly perfect.",
    8: "August holds steady: dry, hot (33°C), and the east coast at full tourist season — though crowds never approach west-coast December levels. The Hindu Vel festival may continue, and the beaches remain pristine. Whale watching enters its final peak month, so book morning excursions early. The food — fresh-caught fish, crab curry, Jaffna-influenced Tamil cuisine — is extraordinary. Arugam Bay's surf season is at its peak. A month of reliable excellence on a coast that deserves more fame.",
    9: "September marks the season's turn — the first inter-monsoon showers appear, and the dry streak ends with occasional afternoon rain at 31°C. The whale watching season winds down but late sightings are still possible. The sea stays warm and swimmable, and Pigeon Island's reef remains vibrant. Tourist numbers thin as the shoulder season approaches, and prices soften. The east coast's Hindu Tamil culture is most visible during the temple festivals this month.",
    10: "October brings increasing rain as the northeast monsoon approaches — expect building showers and choppier seas at 30°C. The beach season is ending, and some tourist operations begin closing. Pigeon Island snorkeling becomes weather-dependent, and the whale watching is over for the year. But the cultural sites — Koneswaram Temple, Fort Frederick, the hot springs — remain worthwhile. This is the last window for east coast beach time before the monsoon reasserts itself.",
    11: "November is the northeast monsoon's return in force: heavy rain, rough seas, and the east coast retreating into its off-season at 28°C. Beaches are not for swimming, and many tourist businesses close entirely. The west and south coasts are entering their prime season, so most travelers pivot accordingly. If you're here, the temple culture and local food scene carry on regardless of weather. Pack waterproofs and lower your beach expectations.",
    12: "December is peak monsoon on the east coast: 27°C, heavy rain (350mm+), and the sea too rough for any water activities. Trincomalee is in full off-season, and the smart play is the south coast or hill country. But the handful of travelers who come find genuine local life — temple ceremonies, bustling markets, and Tamil cuisine without any tourist dilution. It's raw, wet, and authentic. The east coast's time will come again in April; for now, it rests.",
  },

  'lk-yala': {
    1: "January is prime safari season at Yala — the dry weather (30°C, minimal rain) concentrates wildlife around the remaining waterholes, and leopard sightings are at their peak. Yala has the highest density of leopards anywhere on Earth, and January's dry scrub and open vegetation make them easier to spot. The birdlife is extraordinary with both resident and migratory species. Block 1 is the most popular zone and gets crowded with jeeps, so early-morning or late-afternoon drives are essential.",
    2: "February continues the dry-season safari prime time: 31°C, clear skies, and the waterholes acting as magnets for elephants, leopards, sloth bears, and crocodiles. The birdlife peaks with hundreds of species including flamingos at the coastal lagoons. This is Yala at its busiest — jeep traffic in Block 1 can feel like rush hour, but the wildlife density justifies the company. Block 5 offers a quieter alternative with its own leopard territory. Book your safari well ahead.",
    3: "March is the last of the prime dry months at 32°C, with vegetation at its sparsest and wildlife at maximum visibility. The leopards are active in the cooler mornings and evenings, and the elephants gather in impressive herds around the shrinking water sources. Heat becomes a factor by midday, so plan drives for the golden hours. The coastal section of the park offers surreal scenery: leopards on the beach are a real, if rare, possibility. Season starts winding down as the rains approach.",
    4: "April brings the first inter-monsoon showers and rising humidity at 31°C. Wildlife remains visible as the bush hasn't fully greened yet, and the leopards are still active. But Yala typically closes Block 1 for the dry-season recovery period (September), and the inter-monsoon rain makes some tracks challenging. The Sinhala New Year brings a brief pause. This is shoulder season — fewer jeeps, reasonable prices, and still-decent wildlife viewing for those who don't need peak conditions.",
    5: "May is when the southwest monsoon arrives and Yala begins its transformation: rain turns the dry scrub green, waterholes fill, and the wildlife disperses into the thickening bush. Leopard sightings become harder as cover increases, but the birdlife is spectacular with breeding plumage on display. Some areas may become inaccessible due to mud. This is low season — fewer visitors, lower prices, and a different, wilder Yala experience for those who embrace the wet conditions.",
    6: "June continues the monsoon with heavy rain and thick, green vegetation. Yala's Block 1 closes (typically September through mid-October), but other blocks remain open and the park has a raw, untamed beauty. The elephants are in their element with abundant water and fresh browse, and the birdlife is nesting and active. Safari drives require 4WD confidence and rain gear. A specialist's month — rewarding for wildlife photographers who enjoy the challenge and the dramatic monsoon light.",
    7: "July sees the monsoon persisting with regular rain and maximum greenery at 29°C. The park is quiet with minimal tourism, and the wildlife — while harder to spot in thick vegetation — is active and breeding. Peacock displays are spectacular during the monsoon, and the sloth bears are active as termite mounds soften in the rain. The coastline within the park is dramatic under stormy skies. A genuine off-season experience for the dedicated wildlife enthusiast.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon pattern with intermittent rain and thick bush. The park is in its green season — lush, dramatic, and demanding of patience from safari-goers. Elephant herds are healthy and active, and the crocodiles bask on every waterway. The Esala Perahera celebrations at nearby Kataragama draw pilgrims. Block 1 remains closed. For those who visit, the absence of other jeeps transforms the experience from theme-park safari to genuine wilderness encounter.",
    9: "September is the monsoon's tail end — rain eases, the bush remains thick and green, and the park begins preparing for its peak season return. Block 1 is still closed (reopening typically mid-October), but the other blocks offer decent wildlife viewing with improving conditions. The waterholes are full, the landscape is at maximum lushness, and the birdlife includes late monsoon breeding activity. A transitional month with rising anticipation.",
    10: "October marks the great reopening: Block 1 typically returns to service mid-month, the rains are transitioning, and the bush begins its slow dry-down that will concentrate wildlife over the coming months. Early sightings of leopards returning to their dry-season territories are exciting, and the elephants are still in large herds. The inter-monsoon showers keep the landscape green but photogenic. Tourist numbers start climbing — the countdown to peak safari season has begun.",
    11: "November sees Yala firmly transitioning to dry-season mode: rain decreases, temperatures settle at 29°C, and the waterholes start becoming focal points again. Leopard sightings improve as vegetation thins, and the migratory birds arrive from the north in impressive numbers. Tourist numbers build to moderate levels, and the morning safari drives start revealing the park at its best. Accommodation outside the park fills up on weekends. A smart month — good wildlife, fewer crowds than January.",
    12: "December is the start of peak safari season: 30°C, dry conditions returning, and the wildlife increasingly concentrated around water. Leopard sighting rates climb, the elephant herds are spectacular, and the birdlife includes both resident and freshly arrived migratory species. Holiday-season tourists push demand high, and Block 1 jeep slots book out well in advance. The coastal lagoons attract flamingos, and a sunrise drive through the park's ancient landscape is Sri Lanka at its wildest and most magnificent.",
  },

  'lr-liberia': {
    1: "January is dry season in Liberia — 32°C, dusty Harmattan winds blowing off the Sahara, and the hazy skies giving Monrovia an almost sepia-toned quality. The beaches around Robertsport are at their best for surfing, with consistent Atlantic swells and a growing community of local and expat surfers. Sapo National Park, the country's main rainforest reserve, is accessible on dry-season roads. Tourism infrastructure is minimal but genuine — this is West Africa at its most raw and welcoming.",
    2: "February continues the dry season with 33°C heat and Harmattan haze persisting. Robertsport's surf scene is in full swing, and the point breaks rival better-known West African spots. Monrovia's nightlife is lively, and the markets sell everything from dried fish to bright African print fabrics. Providence Island, the historic landing site of freed American slaves, offers a contemplative window into Liberia's unique founding story. Pack dust protection; the Harmattan can irritate sensitive lungs.",
    3: "March is the dry season's finale: 34°C, the hottest month, and the landscape parched and waiting for rain. The surf at Robertsport remains consistent, and the beach culture is relaxed and friendly. Monrovia's restaurants serve excellent jollof rice, pepper soup, and fresh cassava leaves — West African comfort food at its best. The roads to interior destinations are at their driest (and therefore most navigable). This is the last window for reliable overland travel before the rains transform everything.",
    4: "April marks the transition — the first heavy rains arrive with dramatic thunderstorms, temperatures ease to 31°C, and the landscape begins its rapid green transformation. The surf at Robertsport picks up with bigger swells, and the rainforest in Sapo National Park starts its spectacular wet-season display. Roads deteriorate quickly, so plan accordingly. Liberian Independence Day preparations begin, and the market energy in Monrovia intensifies. Bring rain gear and flexibility.",
    5: "May is full rainy season: 300mm+ of rain, 30°C humidity, and the country transforming into an impossibly green, waterlogged landscape. Monrovia's streets flood regularly, and overland travel becomes genuinely challenging. But the surfing at Robertsport is excellent for experienced riders, and the rainforest is at its most alive with wildlife activity and bird calls. Tourism is essentially nonexistent, meaning genuine cultural immersion is the reward for those who don't mind getting thoroughly wet.",
    6: "June continues the deluge with some of the heaviest rainfall on the West African coast — 500mm+ is possible. Monrovia hunkers down, but life carries on with characteristic Liberian resilience. The beaches are dramatic under stormy skies, and the local music scene (hipco and gbema) is best experienced live in the city's clubs. Malaria risk is at its highest, so prophylaxis is non-negotiable. Only for the adventurous and thoroughly prepared.",
    7: "July is the wettest month with relentless rain and the country essentially waterlogged. Liberian Independence Day (July 26) brings celebrations to Monrovia despite the weather — parades, speeches, and patriotic fervor. The surf can be wild and unpredictable, and the interior is largely inaccessible by road. This is deep off-season by any measure, but the cultural experience of Independence Day in a nation founded by freed American slaves is genuinely powerful.",
    8: "August continues the heavy rains at 28°C — the coolest month, which still feels tropical by any standard. The coastline is storm-battered and dramatic, and the rainforest is at peak density. Infrastructure challenges are real, and only committed travelers should attempt the interior. Monrovia's market culture continues regardless of weather, and a bowl of palm butter soup with fufu is the kind of meal that makes you forget you're soaking wet. Malaria prevention remains critical.",
    9: "September sees the rains beginning to ease slightly — still wet (350mm), but with more sunny breaks between storms. The landscape is at maximum green intensity, and the rivers run full and fast. The surf at Robertsport transitions to cleaner conditions, and the first tentative tourist season preparations begin. Sapo National Park's pygmy hippos and forest elephants are active but very difficult to spot in the dense vegetation. The transition toward dry season brings cautious optimism.",
    10: "October marks the rainy season's retreat — showers continue but with increasing dry spells at 30°C. The roads slowly improve, the beaches become more accessible, and the surf season picks up with cleaner swells. Monrovia's cultural life revives with events and festivals as the weather cooperates. The rainforest remains lush and alive, and birding is exceptional with both resident and migrant species. A good month for the adventurous traveler willing to work with imperfect conditions.",
    11: "November is the transition to dry season: rain drops sharply, temperatures climb to 31°C, and the country starts drying out. The beaches are clean and uncrowded, the surf at Robertsport is consistent, and the interior roads become progressively more navigable. This is when the adventurous surf-and-explore crowd arrives, finding genuine warmth from locals and minimal tourist infrastructure. The Harmattan hasn't arrived yet, so skies are clear and air quality is good.",
    12: "December brings the dry season proper: 32°C, clear skies, and the beaches at their most inviting. The Christmas celebrations in Monrovia are lively, blending Liberian, American, and West African traditions in a way that's unique to this country. Robertsport's surf scene is building for the season, and the coastal drives are scenic and manageable. Tourist numbers tick up slightly but remain tiny by global standards. A month of genuine discovery in one of West Africa's most underrated destinations.",
  },

  'ls-lesotho': {
    1: "January is midsummer in the Mountain Kingdom — 25°C in the lowlands, regular afternoon thunderstorms, and the highlands carpeted in green grass and wildflowers. The Sani Pass is open (4WD required) and the views from the top are limitless. Pony trekking through the Maluti Mountains reveals shepherds' villages and Basotho culture unchanged for centuries. The rain keeps things green and dramatic, but pack waterproofs — afternoon storms can be fierce. Lesotho is gloriously uncrowded year-round.",
    2: "February continues the wet summer: 24°C, afternoon thunderstorms building spectacularly over the mountains, and the waterfalls like Maletsunyane Falls (one of Africa's highest single-drop falls) running at full power. The highlands are brilliant green, the pony trekking is superb if you don't mind afternoon rain, and the Basotho blanket-wearing culture is on full display at the rural markets. Very few international tourists make it here, making every interaction genuinely authentic.",
    3: "March is late summer with the rains beginning to ease — 22°C, golden afternoon light, and the mountain passes at their most accessible. The Sehlabathebe National Park (a World Heritage Site) is spectacular with wildflowers and dramatic sandstone formations. The rural villages are harvesting their corn and sorghum, and the cultural rhythms of mountain life are captivating. The Sani Pass is reliable, and the border-crossing experience into this land-locked kingdom is an adventure in itself.",
    4: "April brings autumn to the highlands: temperatures drop to 18°C, the grass turns golden, and the first frosts dust the highest peaks. The landscape takes on a stark, beautiful quality that's unlike anywhere else in southern Africa. Hiking and pony trekking conditions are excellent with cool, dry days and clear visibility. The Morija Arts & Cultural Festival celebrates Basotho heritage with music, dance, and art. Tourist numbers (already tiny) drop further, making solitude almost guaranteed.",
    5: "May is early winter: 14°C in the lowlands, snow possible above 2,500m, and the mountain landscape stripped to its bones — golden grass, grey rock, enormous blue skies. The Basotho blankets become practical necessities rather than cultural accessories, and the wood smoke from village fires scents the crisp air. The Sani Pass is still open but can be icy. The dinosaur footprints at various sites across Lesotho are most visible with low, raking winter light.",
    6: "June is proper winter in the only country in the world that sits entirely above 1,000m — expect 10°C highs in the lowlands, below-freezing nights in the highlands, and snow on the peaks. Afriski Mountain Resort opens for skiing (yes, skiing in sub-Saharan Africa), and the runs are basic but the novelty is unbeatable. The clear, dry air means mountain views stretch endlessly. Pony trekking in winter requires serious cold-weather gear but rewards with extraordinary solitude and stark beauty.",
    7: "July is the coldest month: 9°C in the lowlands, well below freezing at altitude, and the mountain kingdom at its most dramatically austere. Afriski is in full season with the best snow conditions of the year, and the surreal experience of skiing in Africa draws a niche crowd from South Africa. The sandstone formations and frozen waterfalls create an almost lunar landscape. Rural tourism essentially pauses, but the mountain scenery is at its most photogenic under winter light.",
    8: "August begins the long thaw — still cold at 12°C with frosty mornings, but the days lengthen and the sun gains power. Afriski remains open, and the late-season skiing can be surprisingly good. The wildflowers are just weeks away from their spring explosion, and the anticipation builds. Pony trekking through the brown, open highlands reveals the country's geological drama: volcanic dikes, cave paintings, and dinosaur footprints. The dry conditions make the mountain roads most reliable.",
    9: "September is spring's arrival: 17°C, the first wildflowers appearing on the hillsides, and the mountain streams beginning their ice-melt swelling. The Sani Pass is at its driest and most navigable, and the views from Thabana Ntlenyana (southern Africa's highest peak) are extraordinary on clear spring days. Peach and cherry blossoms appear in the lowland villages, and the Basotho cultural scene stirs with spring festivals. A genuinely beautiful transitional month in one of Africa's most overlooked countries.",
    10: "October brings full spring: 20°C, green returning to the highlands, and the wildflowers beginning their spectacular display. The thunderstorms haven't properly arrived yet, so the hiking and trekking conditions are near-perfect. The mountain streams run clear, the waterfalls gain volume, and the birdlife picks up with spring breeding activity. The Roma Valley near Maseru is beautiful with blossoming orchards. Lesotho in October is one of southern Africa's great secrets.",
    11: "November is pre-summer at 22°C with the first afternoon thunderstorms heralding the wet season. The highlands are green and the wildflowers peak — the alpine blooms above 3,000m are a botanical treasure. The waterfalls run strongly, the hiking trails are in excellent condition, and the warm days paired with cool nights make outdoor activities ideal. The few travelers who discover Lesotho in November find an unspoiled mountain kingdom that rewards every kilometer of rough road getting there.",
    12: "December is full summer: 25°C, regular afternoon thunderstorms, and the Mountain Kingdom at its most verdant and alive. The highlands are carpeted in green, the rivers run full, and the pony trekking through mountain villages is at its most culturally rich as families gather for the holidays. The Maletsunyane Falls and other waterfalls are approaching their most powerful. Christmas in Lesotho blends Basotho traditions with Christian celebration, and the festive energy in Maseru's markets is infectious.",
  },

  'lt-vilnius': {
    1: "January in Vilnius is Baltic winter at its most committed — highs around -3°C, the baroque Old Town dusted in snow, and the kind of cold that makes ducking into a cozy cafe feel like a life achievement. The Christmas decorations often linger into early January, and the city's famous church spires look ethereal in the winter light. Warm up with cepelinai (massive potato dumplings stuffed with meat) and a shot of Starka. The Cold Night half-marathon in January is peak Lithuanian stoicism.",
    2: "February is still firmly winter (-2°C) but the days are lengthening noticeably, and Uzupis — Vilnius's self-declared independent artist republic — is at its most atmospheric under grey skies. Shrove Tuesday brings traditional celebrations, and the amber shops in the Old Town are less crowded than in summer. The indoor market halls serve hearty Lithuanian fare, and the contemporary art scene (Vilnius was European Capital of Culture 2009) keeps the cultural calendar full despite the weather.",
    3: "March teases spring: 4°C, thawing snow, and the first cafe tables cautiously appearing on the Old Town's cobblestones. Kaziukas Fair (early March) fills the streets with traditional crafts, dried flower bouquets, and heart-shaped gingerbread in one of Vilnius's most beloved traditions. The Gediminas Tower offers panoramic views of a city emerging from winter, and the restaurant scene serves the last of the hearty winter menus before spring lightens the plates.",
    4: "April is Vilnius in spring mode — 12°C, cherry blossoms in the parks, and the Old Town shaking off its winter quiet with street musicians and outdoor dining. The baroque churches look magnificent against blue spring skies, and the Walk of Uzupis (April 1 is their 'independence day') brings absurdist celebration. Hiking in the Vilnius city parks and nearby Trakai (island castle 30 minutes away) is beautiful as the birch forests leaf out. A lovely shoulder-season month.",
    5: "May is when Vilnius truly blooms — 17°C, long evenings, and the Old Town's courtyards overflowing with lilac and flower boxes. The outdoor restaurant terraces are in full swing, and a sunset walk along the Neris River feels like a scene from a European indie film. Day trips to Trakai Island Castle are quintessential, and the street food scene — traditional kibinai pastries, cold beet soup (saltibarsciai) — hits its stride. One of the most underrated capital cities in Europe.",
    6: "June brings the White Nights effect to the Baltics — 22°C, nearly 18 hours of daylight, and Vilnius absolutely glowing. The Midsummer Festival (Jonines) sees bonfires, folk singing, and flower-crown wearing along the Neris River. The Old Town's amber-lit streets stay lively until midnight under pale northern skies. The cafe culture reaches its peak, and the surrounding countryside — forested, lake-dotted — is perfect for day trips. A genuinely magical month in a genuinely magical city.",
    7: "July is the warmest month at 24°C with the longest days and Vilnius at maximum summer energy. The Street Music Day event fills the Old Town with performances, the beer gardens overflow, and the evening light on the baroque facades is golden and endless. Swimming in nearby lakes (Galve near Trakai) is a local tradition, and the food market culture is at its peak with fresh berries, mushrooms, and smoked fish. Tourist numbers are at their highest but the city never feels overwhelmed.",
    8: "August holds summer's warmth at 23°C with slightly shorter days and the first hints of autumn approaching. The Vilnius City Fiesta and other festivals fill the cultural calendar, and the outdoor dining season is still in full effect. The Old Town's churches, particularly the baroque masterpiece of Sts. Peter and Paul, are at their most photogenic in the warm afternoon light. Foraging for mushrooms and berries in nearby forests is a beloved Lithuanian pastime. Late summer at its languid best.",
    9: "September turns golden: 17°C, the birch and oak forests surrounding Vilnius erupting in amber and rust, and the summer crowds dispersing. The Sirenos Theatre Festival brings cutting-edge performances, and the cafe culture pivots from iced coffee to hot. Trakai Castle reflected in autumn-colored waters is one of Europe's most romantic images. The food scene shifts to autumn mushrooms, root vegetables, and game. A beautiful, contemplative month that showcases Vilnius at its most photogenic.",
    10: "October brings proper Baltic autumn — 10°C, the trees shedding their last gold, and the Old Town taking on a moody, literary atmosphere. The rain increases, but the cozy cafes and wine bars of the Old Town make every drizzly afternoon feel like a scene from a novel. The Vilnius International Film Festival (if scheduled) adds cultural weight, and the traditional markets shift to autumn produce: apples, honey, and smoked meats. Tourist numbers are low; the city belongs to its residents.",
    11: "November is when Vilnius hunkers down for winter — 4°C, short grey days, and the first snow sometimes arriving. But the city compensates with the earliest-in-Europe Christmas market, often opening in late November, transforming Cathedral Square with lights, mulled wine, and craft stalls. The indoor cultural scene — galleries, theaters, concert halls — is at its most vibrant. A bowl of beet soup and dark bread in a candlelit Old Town restaurant is November comfort done right.",
    12: "December is Vilnius at its most magical: the Christmas tree in Cathedral Square is famously inventive (and often Europe's most creative), the Old Town is wrapped in fairy lights, and the baroque architecture looks like something from a Dickens illustration under fresh snow. At 0°C, the cold is real but manageable with proper layering. Christmas markets serve hot wine and traditional sakotis (tree cakes). New Year's Eve in the Old Town square is festive and fun. December is when Vilnius proves it's one of Europe's great winter cities.",
  },

  'lu-luxembourg': {
    1: "January in Luxembourg City is quietly elegant: 3°C, the Old Town's UNESCO-listed fortifications dusted with frost, and the casemates (underground tunnels) feeling most atmospheric in the winter quiet. The restaurant scene — Michelin stars per capita rival any country on Earth — is at its most intimate, with truffle-heavy menus and excellent Moselle wines. The Grund (lower town) under light snow is postcard material. Tourist numbers are minimal, and the city's cosmopolitan energy (over 170 nationalities) keeps things lively.",
    2: "February stays cold (4°C) but the days lengthen and Carnival season (Buergbrennen/Burgsonndeg) brings bonfires, parades, and burning of winter effigies — a tradition that's charming and slightly pagan. The Philharmonie Luxembourg hosts world-class concerts, and the MUDAM contemporary art museum is perfect for a drizzly afternoon. The Moselle Valley wine towns are quiet but the cellars welcome visitors. A steaming bowl of Bouneschlupp (green bean soup) and a glass of Riesling is peak winter comfort.",
    3: "March brings the first spring warmth to 9°C with the Petrusse Valley below the fortifications turning green and the first outdoor cafe tables appearing on Place d'Armes. The financial district's sleek architecture contrasts beautifully with the medieval Old Town. Hiking the Mullerthal Trail (Luxembourg's Little Switzerland) becomes viable as paths dry. The food scene shifts to lighter spring menus, and the Saturday morning market in Place Guillaume II is worth the early start.",
    4: "April is Luxembourg at its spring loveliest: 14°C, cherry blossoms in the parks, and the Old Town's gardens in full bloom. The Casemates du Bock reopen for the season, and the view from the Chemin de la Corniche ('Europe's most beautiful balcony') is spectacular with spring color. Hiking in the Mullerthal's sandstone gorges is excellent, and the Moselle Valley vineyards are budding. Crowds are light, prices reasonable, and the city has a quiet confidence that's deeply appealing.",
    5: "May brings 18°C perfection: the parks and gardens are in full bloom, outdoor dining along the Grund's riverside is idyllic, and the National Day preparations (June 23) begin adding festive touches. The Mullerthal Trail is at its best with spring wildflowers and cascading streams, and the Moselle wine route is gorgeous for cycling. Luxembourg's trilingual culture (French, German, Luxembourgish) adds layers of charm to every interaction. A genuinely underrated European capital in its best month.",
    6: "June is summer in the Grand Duchy: 21°C, long evenings, and National Day (June 23) bringing fireworks, concerts, and the only time Luxembourgers really let loose — the celebrations are genuinely impressive for a country this size. The rooftop bars and riverside restaurants are buzzing, and the hike along the Wenzel Walk reveals 1,000 years of fortress history. The Moselle Valley wine terraces are lush, and the cycling infrastructure is impeccable. Peak season begins but never feels overwhelming.",
    7: "July is the warmest month at 23°C with long days and Luxembourg at its most outdoorsy. The Blues'n'Jazz Rallye fills the Old Town and Grund with stages and performers, creating a wonderful street-festival atmosphere. The Mullerthal trails are lush and the swimming spots along the Sure River are local secrets worth discovering. The financial district empties slightly as bankers vacation, giving the city a more relaxed rhythm. Thunderstorms can be dramatic but brief.",
    8: "August brings a peculiar charm: 22°C, the Schueberfouer (ancient funfair dating to 1340) arrives with rides, cotton candy, and a decidedly un-financial-district energy. The city thins out as residents vacation, but the restaurants and cultural venues carry on. The Moselle Valley grape harvest approaches, and the wine towns of Remich and Ehnen are beautiful in the late-summer light. The Mullerthal trails are at peak lushness, and the cycling along the river valleys is superb.",
    9: "September is golden Luxembourg: 18°C, the forests turning amber, and the grape harvest in the Moselle Valley bringing wine festivals and tasting events. The city's cultural season kicks off with theater, opera, and exhibition openings. The Chemin de la Corniche views are at their most dramatic with autumn color cascading down the valley walls. Hiking conditions are ideal, crowds thin after summer, and the food scene launches autumn menus featuring game, mushrooms, and new-season wine.",
    10: "October paints the Grand Duchy in full autumn: 12°C, the Mullerthal's sandstone gorges surrounded by golden forest, and the Old Town atmospheric under the first autumn rains. The restaurant scene pivots to hearty Luxembourgish classics — Judd mat Gaardebounen (smoked pork with broad beans) and Rieslingspaschteit (Riesling meat pie). The Moselle Valley's post-harvest calm is perfect for cycling. Tourist numbers are low, and Luxembourg's quality-over-quantity philosophy shines brightest in the quiet months.",
    11: "November is grey and cozy: 6°C, early darkness, and the first Christmas market stalls appearing in Place d'Armes. The cultural scene — Philharmonie concerts, MUDAM exhibitions, theater — is at full throttle. The Casemates close for winter, but the indoor attractions (including excellent museums and the city's extraordinary collection of Michelin-starred restaurants) more than compensate. A glass of Cremant de Luxembourg by a fireplace is the month distilled into a moment.",
    12: "December transforms Luxembourg into a Christmas fairy tale: the Winterlights festival fills the Old Town with markets, ice skating, and mulled wine. At 3°C, the cold adds authenticity, and the medieval setting — stone walls, narrow lanes, ancient churches — looks born for Christmas decorations. The food scene peaks with holiday menus and seasonal treats, and the Philharmonie hosts spectacular Christmas concerts. For a country often overlooked between its famous neighbors, December Luxembourg punches well above its postcard weight.",
  },

  'lv-riga': {
    1: "January in Riga is Baltic winter at full intensity — highs around -3°C, the Art Nouveau district dusted in snow, and the frozen Daugava River giving the city an almost Scandinavian severity. The Christmas market in Dome Square (often lingering into January) serves piping hot mulled wine, and the indoor Central Market — housed in enormous Zeppelin hangars — is a warm, fragrant refuge of smoked fish, rye bread, and local cheese. Opera season at the Latvian National Opera is in full swing.",
    2: "February holds the deep freeze (-2°C) but Latvians lean into winter: ice fishing on the frozen lakes, cross-country skiing in the parks, and warming shots of Riga Black Balsam (the city's famously intense herbal liqueur). The Art Nouveau facades along Alberta Street look dramatic against grey winter skies, and the museums — particularly the Latvian National Museum of Art — are uncrowded and excellent. Carnival celebrations bring a brief burst of festive energy before Lent.",
    3: "March begins the thaw: 3°C, ice breaking on the Daugava, and the first cafe tables appearing in the Old Town. The city feels like it's stretching after a long sleep. The Art Nouveau architecture is best explored on foot as the weather improves, and the Central Market shifts to early spring produce. The opera and ballet season continues with excellent programming. Riga's famously affordable dining scene serves hearty pork, potatoes, and sauerkraut — winter fuel that doesn't know it's almost spring.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring: 11°C, the parks greening rapidly, and Riga's charm coming into focus as the outdoor city emerges. The Old Town's medieval streets, Gothic churches, and hidden courtyards are best explored now before summer crowds arrive. A day trip to Jurmala's beach (30 minutes by train) reveals art nouveau wooden villas awakening from winter. The restaurant terraces open, and the local craft beer scene is surprisingly sophisticated. Shoulder season at its most rewarding.",
    5: "May is Riga in bloom — 16°C, white nights approaching, and the entire city green and flowering. The Latvian Song and Dance Festival preparations build (in festival years), and the outdoor cafe culture hits its stride. The Freedom Monument's surroundings fill with locals enjoying the evening light, and the parks along the canal are perfect for walking. Day trips to Sigulda's castles (the 'Gauja Switzerland') are stunning with spring foliage. One of Europe's most underpriced capitals at its most beautiful.",
    6: "June brings the White Nights: 21°C, nearly 18 hours of daylight, and Midsummer (Jani) celebrations on June 23-24 with bonfires, flower crowns, cheese, and beer — it's Latvia's biggest and most joyful holiday. The Art Nouveau district glows in the perpetual twilight, and Jurmala's beach season begins with the longest days of the year. The Riga Opera Festival features outdoor performances, and the Old Town's medieval courtyards host live music into the pale night. A genuinely magical month.",
    7: "July is peak summer: 23°C, the longest days of the year, and Riga at maximum energy. The beach at Jurmala fills with sunseekers, the Old Town's restaurant terraces are packed, and the cultural calendar overflows with festivals. The medieval Riga Cathedral hosts organ concerts in its acoustically perfect interior. The local cuisine lightens: cold beet soup (auksta zupa), smoked fish, and fresh berries from the Central Market. Tourist numbers peak but Riga's scale keeps things manageable.",
    8: "August holds summer warmth at 22°C with slightly shorter days and the first hint of autumn in the air. The city's beaches remain popular, the outdoor dining scene is in full effect, and the mushroom foraging season begins in the surrounding pine forests — Latvians take this seriously. The Riga City Festival brings concerts and events to the streets, and the Art Nouveau walking tours benefit from warm weather and soft late-summer light. A languid, satisfying month.",
    9: "September turns Riga golden: 16°C, the parks erupting in amber and rust, and the cultural season launching with opera, ballet, and gallery openings. The tourist crowds thin, leaving the Art Nouveau district pleasantly quiet for photography. The Central Market overflows with autumn mushrooms, apples, and preserves. A day trip to Sigulda in full autumn color is breathtaking, and the cozy wine bars and craft beer pubs of the Old Town are at their most inviting. Smart travelers come in September.",
    10: "October brings full Baltic autumn: 9°C, rain and wind stripping the trees, and Riga taking on a moody, literary quality. The Old Town's cobblestone streets glisten in the rain, and the Art Nouveau facades look mysterious under grey skies. The indoor cultural scene — opera, theater, concerts — hits its stride. The Central Market's hearty autumn offerings (smoked meats, root vegetables, dark bread) are perfect fuel for rainy-day exploring. Tourist numbers are very low; the city feels authentically Latvian.",
    11: "November is the dark transition: 3°C, short days, and the first snow sometimes arriving early. But Riga's Christmas preparations begin — the Old Town's Christmas market in Dome Square opens (Riga claims to have hosted the world's first Christmas tree in 1510), and the medieval setting makes it one of Europe's most charming. The Black Balsam tastes better when you need it, and the restaurant scene pivots to winter comfort: pork ribs, grey peas, and gingerbread. A quietly beautiful month.",
    12: "December is Riga's Christmas moment: the Old Town market in full swing under twinkling lights, medieval church spires rising above gingerbread stalls, and that famous Christmas tree tradition given full celebratory treatment. At 0°C, the cold is real but the mulled wine is strong and the wool mittens are handmade by Latvian grandmothers. New Year's Eve along the Daugava waterfront features fireworks reflected in the river. Riga in December proves the Baltics do Christmas better than almost anyone.",
  },

  'mx-puerto-vallarta': {
    1: "Dry season perfection — 26°C highs, virtually no rain, and humpback whales breaching in Banderas Bay make January a prime escape. Crowds are moderate (snowbirds and New Year stragglers), but you can still snag a beachfront palapa and devour ceviche on the Malecón without elbowing anyone.",
    2: "February keeps the dry-season magic rolling at 26°C with whale-watching at its absolute peak — mothers and calves play offshore daily. The international crowd swells for Valentine's season, but the Riviera Nayarit's quieter beaches absorb the overflow nicely.",
    3: "March is spring break territory — American college kids descend on the beach bars while temps climb to 28°C under cloudless skies. Whale season winds down but the snorkeling at Los Arcos marine park is crystal-clear, and if you venture south to Yelapa by water taxi, you'll dodge the party crowd entirely.",
    4: "April is the dry season's last hurrah — 30°C, bone-dry, and blissfully quiet as spring breakers go home and summer hasn't arrived. Surf picks up along the Riviera Nayarit, the jungle canopy tours above the Sierra Madre are comfortable in the heat, and taco stands along the Malecón operate at a civilized pace.",
    5: "The heat ramps up to 32°C and humidity starts creeping in, signaling the approaching rainy season. Crowds are at their lowest, hotel deals are excellent, and the birding in the Sierra Madre foothills is outstanding as migratory species pass through. Occasional afternoon showers dust the jungle without dampening the beaches.",
    6: "Rainy season begins in earnest — afternoon thunderstorms roll through almost daily, but mornings stay sunny and hot at 32°C. The jungle turns impossibly lush, baby sea turtles start hatching on Riviera Nayarit beaches, and you'll pay a fraction of winter prices for the same sunset views from the Malecón.",
    7: "July is peak rainy season with humidity cranking past 80% and daily tropical downpours — dramatic but usually short-lived. The ocean warms to bathtub temps ideal for snorkeling, and the deserted beaches south of Mismaloya feel genuinely wild. Budget travelers take note: this is when five-star resorts become surprisingly affordable.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and humidity but adds hurricane-season vigilance — keep an eye on weather forecasts. The upside: sea turtle release programs are in full swing, surfing at Sayulita and Punta de Mita delivers consistent swells, and the rain-fed waterfalls in the Sierra Madre are thundering.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — 350mm+ of rain turns the jungle electric green and the rivers run high for adventurous kayaking. It's hurricane season's peak, so flexibility is essential, but crowds are nonexistent and a perfectly grilled fish at a beachside palapa costs almost nothing. The brave are rewarded.",
    10: "Rains begin tapering off mid-month while the jungle stays magnificently green — a transitional sweet spot if you don't mind the odd downpour. Humpback whale season starts teasing by late October, surf remains solid, and the returning sunshine brings out street food vendors along the Malecón in force.",
    11: "November is the grand reopening — rain drops dramatically, temps settle to a perfect 28°C, and the first humpback whales arrive in Banderas Bay. Crowds are still thin, prices haven't peaked, and the Day of the Dead celebrations in the old town bring Vallarta's cultural side to vivid life.",
    12: "Peak season launches with a bang — 27°C, dry skies, and humpback whales performing daily. Snowbirds arrive, Christmas lights line the Malecón, and hotel prices climb accordingly. The Posadas processions through the cobblestone streets are enchanting, and a sunset cocktail overlooking the bay reminds you why this coast is legendary.",
  },

  'mx-riviera-maya': {
    1: "Dry season delivers — 28°C, minimal rain, and the Caribbean is that ridiculous turquoise that makes your phone camera look like it's lying. Cenote diving near Tulum is at peak visibility, and while the Cancún hotel zone is crowded with post-holiday visitors, the ruins at Cobá are blissfully manageable.",
    2: "February is the Riviera Maya at its most balanced — warm but not scorching at 28°C, dry, and busy enough to feel lively without the spring-break mayhem to come. Whale sharks occasionally visit offshore, cenotes are crystal-clear for snorkeling, and Carnival brings lively parades to Playa del Carmen.",
    3: "Spring break turns Cancún into a bass-thumping beach party, but escape 90 minutes south to Tulum or Sian Ka'an and you'll find quiet Caribbean perfection at 29°C. The dry season holds strong with almost no rain, cenote visibility is exceptional, and this is prime time for swimming with sea turtles at Akumal.",
    4: "April is arguably the sweet spot — spring breakers have left, summer crowds haven't arrived, and 30°C heat meets bone-dry skies. The Mesoamerican Barrier Reef is pristine for diving, the cenotes near Valladolid are refreshing escapes, and you can wander Chichén Itzá during the spring equinox light show without too much shoving.",
    5: "Heat builds to 32°C and humidity starts making itself known as rainy season approaches. Crowds thin considerably, whale shark season begins off Isla Holbox (running through September), and the jungle around Cobá is alive with howler monkeys and toucans. Afternoon showers start appearing but rarely last more than an hour.",
    6: "Rainy season arrives with warm afternoon downpours, but mornings stay bright and hot at 32°C — perfect for early cenote swims before the clouds build. Whale shark tours off Isla Mujeres are in full swing, sargassum seaweed can be an issue on some beaches (check conditions), and hotel prices drop to shoulder-season levels.",
    7: "July brings the heat and the humidity — 33°C with daily tropical showers and the possibility of hurricanes on the radar. Whale shark encounters peak this month, the reef diving stays excellent in calmer morning hours, and you'll find Tulum's famous beach clubs refreshingly uncrowded on weekdays.",
    8: "Peak hurricane season meets peak summer heat at 33°C — flexibility and travel insurance are your best friends. Between storms, the Caribbean is warm and diveable, whale sharks are still feeding offshore, and the underground rivers near Playa del Carmen offer rain-proof adventure. Prices are rock-bottom for the quality on offer.",
    9: "September is the wettest and riskiest month for hurricanes, but also the cheapest and emptiest — Tulum practically feels private. The jungle is at maximum lushness, cenotes overflow with fresh rainwater, and those willing to roll the weather dice get Caribbean luxury at backpacker prices.",
    10: "Rains start easing in the second half while remaining warm at 30°C — a transitional month that rewards the flexible traveler. The sargassum typically clears up, Day of the Dead preparations add cultural color to Playa del Carmen, and the reef systems off Cozumel are back to stellar visibility.",
    11: "November flips the switch back to dry season — rain drops sharply, 29°C skies clear up, and the Caribbean returns to that absurd shade of blue. Crowds remain moderate, cenote diving conditions are excellent, and the Hanal Pixán (Mayan Day of the Dead) celebrations in local villages are hauntingly beautiful.",
    12: "High season kicks in — 27°C, dry skies, and Christmas tourists fill every beachfront resort in Cancún. Tulum and the smaller cenote towns absorb the overflow more gracefully, reef snorkeling is at peak clarity, and the warm evenings along Playa del Carmen's Quinta Avenida have an undeniable festive buzz.",
  },

  'my-borneo-sabah': {
    1: "The tail end of the northeast monsoon means 250mm+ of rain, but Sabah's wildlife doesn't pause — proboscis monkeys along the Kinabatangan River are as theatrical as ever. Crowds are minimal, jungle lodges are negotiable on price, and the 30°C heat between downpours keeps things steamy and alive.",
    2: "February stays wet (200mm+) and gloriously uncrowded — the rainforest canopy drips with life, orangutans at Sepilok are active, and the Kinabatangan's pygmy elephants wade through swollen riverbanks. Mt. Kinabalu treks are feasible but expect cloud cover and slippery trails above 3,000m.",
    3: "The monsoon eases and March marks the transition — rain drops notably, the sun breaks through more often, and the diving around Sipadan Island starts hitting world-class visibility. Mt. Kinabalu's summit sunrise views improve dramatically, and the jungles of Danum Valley are alive with hornbills and gibbons.",
    4: "April is prime Sabah — rainfall drops to around 100mm, humidity is manageable by Borneo standards, and Sipadan's underwater walls teem with barracuda tornados and sea turtles. The Kinabatangan River runs calmer for wildlife cruises, and the jungle trails of Danum Valley are at their most walkable. Book Sipadan permits early — they sell out.",
    5: "May continues the dry-ish sweet spot with moderate rain and excellent diving visibility around Sipadan and Mabul. Mt. Kinabalu climbs are popular now — clear skies mean sunrise from the summit is almost guaranteed. Orangutan encounters at Sepilok are reliable, and the humidity, while ever-present, doesn't yet feel punishing.",
    6: "June is peak season for Sabah — schools are out, the Kaamatan harvest festival brings traditional celebrations across the state, and the weather cooperates with reduced rainfall. Sipadan diving is stellar, the Kinabatangan delivers reliable wildlife sightings, and the jungles hum with cicadas and birdsong at 31°C.",
    7: "July stays dry and busy — prime conditions for Mt. Kinabalu's via ferrata, world-class macro diving at Mabul, and sunset river cruises packed with proboscis monkeys. Book everything well ahead as this is peak international tourist season. The heat is relentless but the ocean at Semporna provides sweet relief.",
    8: "August matches July's dry, busy profile with excellent diving and trekking conditions across Sabah. Sea turtle nesting season is active around Turtle Islands Park, and the crystal-clear waters off Sipadan make this the best month for underwater photography. Budget for peak pricing — it's worth every ringgit.",
    9: "September is the dry season's quiet coda — visitors thin out but conditions remain excellent for diving, jungle trekking, and wildlife spotting. The transitional weather brings dramatic cloud formations over Mt. Kinabalu and the Crocker Range, and lodges along the Kinabatangan start offering shoulder-season rates.",
    10: "The northeast monsoon starts brewing — rain picks up to 200mm+ and the seas around Sipadan can get choppy, though diving is still possible most days. The rainforest responds with explosive new growth, and the birdwatching in Danum Valley is phenomenal as fruiting trees attract hornbills en masse.",
    11: "November brings the monsoon proper — heavy rain, swollen rivers, and the closure of some dive sites around Sipadan. But the Kinabatangan wildlife viewing actually improves as animals concentrate along riverbanks, and Sepilok's orangutans are reliably active. Expect the lowest prices and an authentic, rain-soaked Borneo experience.",
    12: "December is peak monsoon with 300mm+ of rain and rough seas making eastern island access unpredictable. The upside: the rainforest is spectacularly lush, wildlife is concentrated and visible, and you'll share the jungle lodges with almost nobody. Mt. Kinabalu treks are challenging but atmospheric in the clouds.",
  },

  'my-borneo-sarawak': {
    1: "January sits in the heart of the northeast monsoon — 600mm+ of rain in some areas, which sounds biblical but actually means dramatic downpours between steamy sunshine at 32°C. Mulu's show caves are spectacular with water features at full force, and the longhouse stays along the Batang Ai are intimate and uncrowded.",
    2: "The monsoon continues its drenching but Sarawak barely blinks — Kuching's waterfront stays lively, the Semenggoh orangutan centre operates rain or shine, and the jungle trails of Bako National Park are alive with proboscis monkeys and bearded pigs. Expect muddy boots and empty trails.",
    3: "Rain starts easing and the jungle transitions — trails dry out at Bako, river levels on the Rejang and Batang Ai become more navigable, and the diving off Miri's coast improves noticeably. Kuching's laksa vendors don't care about the weather, and neither should you.",
    4: "April brings drier conditions and the Rainforest World Music Festival is on the horizon — Sarawak starts buzzing. Mulu's pinnacles trek becomes more feasible as trails firm up, the orangutans at Semenggoh are active in the drier canopy, and the birdwatching in Kubah National Park is exceptional.",
    5: "May is comfortable and relatively dry — the perfect window for Mulu Cave exploration, river journeys into Iban territory, and hiking the Kelabit Highlands. Kuching's food scene (arguably Malaysia's best) is in full swing with laksa, kolo mee, and jungle ferns at every hawker centre.",
    6: "June typically hosts the Rainforest World Music Festival in Kuching — a globally renowned event set in the jungle that alone justifies the trip. Weather cooperates with moderate rainfall, and the caves, longhouses, and national parks are all accessible. Book accommodation early; this month fills fast.",
    7: "July is Sarawak's driest month — trails are firm, rivers are navigable, and the humidity drops to its most bearable levels. The Mulu pinnacles hike is at its best, Bako's wildlife is easy to spot on parched trails, and a longboat journey to a remote Iban longhouse feels like proper adventure.",
    8: "August extends the dry season's gift — excellent trekking in the Kelabit Highlands, reliable cave exploration at Mulu, and river trips without the drama of flood-stage rapids. International visitors peak but Sarawak never feels crowded; even busy Kuching retains its languid, eat-everything charm.",
    9: "September is the transitional month — rain starts returning but trails stay manageable and the jungle explodes with new fruit, drawing orangutans and hornbills into visible feeding frenzies. Kuching's low-key cafe culture is at its best in the slightly cooler evenings, and you'll find shoulder-season pricing across most lodges.",
    10: "October signals the monsoon's return with increasing rain and humidity. Mulu's caves become more dramatic with water flows, Bako's trails get muddier (and more atmospheric), and the Rajang River swells for adventurous longboat journeys. Crowds vanish and prices drop — welcome to the real Borneo.",
    11: "Heavy rain returns — 400mm+ in some areas — and the jungle drinks it up spectacularly. River levels rise, making some longhouse visits more accessible by boat, while Mulu's show caves put on their most dramatic water displays. Pack rain gear and a sense of humour; Sarawak rewards both.",
    12: "Peak monsoon season with serious rainfall, but Kuching's covered waterfront hawker stalls and Sarawak's magnificent cave systems are rain-proof adventures. Christmas brings a unique multicultural celebration to this diverse state, and the orangutans at Semenggoh are reliably active, rain or shine.",
  },

  'my-cameron-highlands': {
    1: "A cool 22°C oasis in tropical Malaysia — January's dry-season clarity means misty mornings over the tea plantations followed by crisp sunshine perfect for hiking Mossy Forest's cloud-draped trails. Strawberry farms are ripe for picking, and the Saturday night market in Brinchang serves the best steamboat you'll eat above 1,500m.",
    2: "February continues the dry spell with pleasant 22°C days and cool nights dipping to 14°C — bring a light jacket, which feels absurd in equatorial Southeast Asia. BOH Tea Estate walks are at their most photogenic, the butterfly gardens are active, and weekend crowds from KL are manageable midweek.",
    3: "The inter-monsoon transition brings afternoon showers but mornings stay clear and cool — ideal for early hikes to the summit of Gunung Brinchang, the peninsula's highest road-accessible peak. Tea plantation tours don't need sunshine to be magical, and the Cameron Highlands' famous scones and cream taste better in the mist.",
    4: "April's rainfall picks up as the southwest monsoon approaches, adding drama to the tea-terraced hillsides. The Rafflesia (world's largest flower) sometimes blooms in the surrounding jungle — ask local guides about recent sightings. Cool temperatures and occasional fog make this feel more Scottish Highlands than Southeast Asia.",
    5: "The southwest monsoon brings regular afternoon storms, but the cool 20-23°C climate never stops being a relief from lowland Malaysia. The tea plantations glow an impossibly vivid green in the rain-washed light, and the hiking trails through mossy cloud forest are atmospheric even (especially) in drizzle.",
    6: "Monsoon rains continue but the Highlands' elevation keeps things cool and lush at 22°C — a world away from the sweltering coast. Weekend visitors from KL thin out on rainy weekdays, making this a peaceful retreat for tea plantation walks, strawberry picking, and that distinctive Cameron Highlands steamboat dinner.",
    7: "July is the driest month of the southwest monsoon period — relative to the rest of the year, expect clearer mornings and manageable afternoon showers. The lavender gardens and rose farms are in bloom, Mossy Forest trails are less waterlogged, and the highland vegetable markets overflow with produce you won't find at sea level.",
    8: "August mirrors July's relatively drier conditions with pleasant trekking weather and clear morning views across the tea valleys. The Cameron Highlands is a popular domestic escape during school holidays, so midweek visits are smarter. The night market's clay pot chicken and herbal tea hit differently at 1,500m elevation.",
    9: "September brings the inter-monsoon shift and unpredictable weather — sunny mornings can turn to heavy downpours by noon. The upside: the jungle is at peak lushness, waterfalls around Tanah Rata thunder with runoff, and the mist-shrouded tea estates look like something from a period drama.",
    10: "October kicks off the northeast monsoon with heavier, more sustained rainfall. The trails get muddy but the scenery is breathtaking — layers of mist roll through the tea valleys and the jungle canopy drips with orchids and ferns. A good book and a pot of BOH Sungei Palas tea make rainy afternoons a feature, not a bug.",
    11: "Peak monsoon season — expect heavy rain and cool nights down to 13°C, which is practically winter by Malaysian standards. The tea factories and indoor attractions become essential, and there's something deeply cozy about eating steamboat in the highlands while rain hammers the tin roof. Crowds are thin and prices gentle.",
    12: "December's monsoon rains persist but the Christmas-holiday crowd brings a festive energy to Tanah Rata and Brinchang. The cool 20°C climate, strawberry farms, and tea plantation walks make this a uniquely Malaysian holiday destination — just pack waterproofs and embrace the mist.",
  },

  'my-kl-west-coast': {
    1: "KL in January is the tail end of the monsoon — afternoon thunderstorms are dramatic but brief, and the 33°C heat makes the air-conditioned malls (KLCC, Pavilion) feel like survival shelters. Thaipusam falls in late January, and the Batu Caves festival is a spectacle of devotion, colour, and kavadi bearers you won't forget.",
    2: "February dries out slightly with the monsoon retreating, and Chinese New Year transforms KL's Chinatown into a riot of red lanterns, lion dances, and open-air feasting. Temperatures hover at 33°C — embrace the hawker stall culture at Jalan Alor, then cool off with cendol and teh tarik.",
    3: "The inter-monsoon period brings unpredictable weather — blazing mornings followed by afternoon deluges — but KL thrives regardless. The Petronas Towers gleam against dramatic storm clouds, Batu Caves are comfortably uncrowded midweek, and the Malacca day trip is at its most pleasant before peak heat arrives.",
    4: "April is warm and increasingly wet as the southwest monsoon approaches, but KL's covered hawker centres and air-conditioned cultural attractions (Islamic Arts Museum, National Museum) make rain irrelevant. The food scene peaks during Ramadan's bazaar season — pasar Ramadan stalls across the city serve extraordinary iftar spreads.",
    5: "The southwest monsoon settles in with regular afternoon storms, but mornings are bright and sticky at 33°C. Hari Raya Aidilfitri celebrations bring a festive energy, open houses serve ketupat rendang across the city, and Malacca's Jonker Street weekend market buzzes with Nyonya cuisine and antiques.",
    6: "June is hot, humid, and rainy — classic KL. School holidays bring domestic tourists but the city never feels overcrowded thanks to its sheer sprawl. The Petronas Towers' skybridge visit is best booked early morning before the haze builds, and Ipoh's old town (2 hours north) makes a cooler, quieter food-focused day trip.",
    7: "July is relatively drier by KL standards — the southwest monsoon takes a breather and the city gets more sunshine than surrounding months. This is peak international tourist season, so book Batu Caves visits for early morning and secure your KL Tower dinner reservation ahead of time.",
    8: "August brings National Day celebrations (Merdeka, August 31) with parades down Dataran Merdeka and a patriotic energy throughout the city. The weather is hot but manageable with occasional storms, and the George Town Festival in Penang makes for an excellent combined trip up the west coast.",
    9: "September is KL's haziest month — regional agricultural burning can reduce air quality and blur the skyline. When the air clears, the city is pleasant at 32°C with manageable crowds. The Mooncake Festival adds colour to Chinatown, and Cameron Highlands makes a welcome cool-weather escape.",
    10: "October marks the inter-monsoon transition — heavier rain returns, sometimes as all-day affairs rather than quick bursts. Deepavali celebrations light up Little India with spectacular displays, and the food festivals that follow make this one of the tastiest months to eat your way through KL's hawker stalls.",
    11: "November brings the northeast monsoon's first heavy rains — flooding can occasionally disrupt low-lying areas, so stay alert. The upside: Kuala Lumpur's rooftop bars, covered food courts, and world-class malls become your playground, and the rain cools the city to a relatively pleasant 31°C.",
    12: "December rain is persistent but the Christmas and year-end sales transform KL's malls into glittering consumer temples. The diverse city celebrates enthusiastically — from Bukit Bintang's light displays to Chinatown's year-end markets — and the food scene is at its most festive and indulgent.",
  },

  'my-langkawi': {
    1: "Dry season is in full swing — January delivers 30°C sunshine, calm Andaman Sea waters perfect for island-hopping by boat, and excellent snorkeling at Pulau Payar Marine Park. The sky bridge and cable car views over Mat Cincang are crystal-clear, and the duty-free shopping keeps evenings lively in Pantai Cenang.",
    2: "February is arguably Langkawi's best month — minimal rain, warm calm seas at 29°C, and visibility for diving and snorkeling that makes the marine park feel like an aquarium. Eagle-feeding boat tours on the mangroves are reliable, and the island's pace is unhurried despite moderate tourist numbers.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot at 33°C with the Andaman Sea at its calmest — ideal for jet-skiing, parasailing, and that languid beach-bar lifestyle Langkawi was built for. The mangrove kayaking tours through the geopark are magical in the still morning air, and sunset cocktails at Pantai Cenang cost almost nothing duty-free.",
    4: "April is the transition month — heat peaks at 34°C and the first afternoon thunderstorms announce the approaching monsoon. The seas remain calm enough for island hopping and the underwater world at Pulau Payar is vibrant. Crowds thin as Europeans head home, making this a smart shoulder-season play.",
    5: "The southwest monsoon arrives with gusto — 200mm+ of rain, higher seas, and that thick tropical humidity. But Langkawi's west coast stays sheltered, the jungle waterfalls (Telaga Tujuh) are thundering, and the eagle-feeding tours carry on between squalls. Duty-free beer tastes the same in the rain.",
    6: "Monsoon season means regular downpours and some rough seas on the exposed side, but Langkawi's geopark caves and mangroves are rain-proof adventures. Accommodation prices drop significantly, the island's languid character emerges without the tourist polish, and the seafood at Pantai Cenang's beachfront restaurants is as good as ever.",
    7: "July brings heavy rainfall and the roughest seas of the year — some boat tours may cancel and beach days require flexibility. The jungle, however, is at its most spectacular, and the waterfalls are roaring. This is when locals reclaim the island and you'll eat the best laksa of your life at a stall nobody photographs.",
    8: "August stays wet but school holidays bring domestic visitors who enliven Pantai Cenang's strip. The rain tends toward dramatic afternoon bursts, leaving mornings viable for geopark exploration and mangrove tours. Sea conditions are improving toward month's end, and the duty-free chocolate shops don't need sunshine.",
    9: "September marks the monsoon's peak — 300mm+ of rain and occasional flooding, but the island's infrastructure handles it well. If you can tolerate uncertainty, the empty beaches between storms are hauntingly beautiful, and the jungle trails are alive with birds and monitor lizards.",
    10: "The monsoon starts retreating in October's second half — seas calm, visibility improves, and the island starts prepping for high season. Early-month rain can still be heavy, but the deals are excellent and the sunset views through clearing storm clouds are cinematic. A gambler's month that often pays off.",
    11: "November is transitional — the last monsoon rains peter out, the seas settle, and the dry-season energy begins returning. Snorkeling conditions at Pulau Payar improve weekly, the mangroves are lush from months of rain, and you'll catch pre-season pricing with increasingly reliable weather.",
    12: "Dry season clicks back on — December brings clear skies, calm seas, and the return of peak-season visitors for the holidays. The cable car views are sharp, island-hopping tours run daily, and the duty-free Pantai Cenang strip buzzes with year-end energy. Book ahead for Christmas week.",
  },

  'my-penang': {
    1: "January is the tail end of the northeast monsoon — expect occasional heavy showers and 31°C heat, but George Town's covered hawker courts (Gurney Drive, New Lane) laugh at rain. Thaipusam preparations begin at the Waterfall Hilltop Temple, and the street art scene in the UNESCO zone is best explored in cooler morning hours.",
    2: "Chinese New Year electrifies George Town — Clan jetties explode with firecrackers, Kek Lok Si Temple is draped in thousands of lights, and the food scene goes into overdrive with reunion dinner specials at every kopitiam. Rain eases compared to January, and the 31°C heat is standard Penang fare.",
    3: "The inter-monsoon lull means drier conditions and the best beach weather on Penang's north coast — Batu Ferringhi's waters are calmer and clearer. George Town's street art walking tours are comfortable in the morning warmth, and the legendary char kway teow at Lorong Selamat needs no weather excuse.",
    4: "April heats up to 33°C with increasing humidity as the southwest monsoon looms. Ramadan brings spectacular pasar Ramadan food stalls across the island — the iftar spreads are extraordinary and open to everyone. The Penang Hill funicular ride offers panoramic views above the haze.",
    5: "Hari Raya celebrations bring festive energy and open-house hospitality across Penang. The monsoon delivers regular afternoon storms but mornings stay hot and bright — perfect for temple-hopping between Kek Lok Si and the Dharmikarama Burmese Temple before retreating to air-conditioned cendol paradise.",
    6: "June is hot, humid, and intermittently rainy — vintage Penang. The George Town Heritage Festival often falls this month, celebrating the UNESCO zone with cultural performances and heritage walks. Penang's hawker food is the best in Malaysia (fight me), and rain just means longer lunches.",
    7: "July brings the Georgetown Festival — an arts and culture extravaganza that fills the heritage zone with performances, installations, and creative energy. The southwest monsoon means rain but Penang's east-facing coast stays relatively sheltered. The Penang laksa at Jalan Penang doesn't need sunshine to be transcendent.",
    8: "August is National Day season with patriotic celebrations, and the west coast monsoon eases slightly. The street food scene peaks during school holidays with night markets bustling across the island. Penang Hill's temperatures are a blessed 5°C cooler than sea level — escape upward when the heat overwhelms.",
    9: "September can be hazy from regional burning — check air quality before planning outdoor adventures. When clear, the Penang National Park coastal trail is excellent, and the food scene (as always) operates regardless of atmospheric conditions. The Mooncake Festival adds lantern-lit charm to George Town's streets.",
    10: "October's inter-monsoon shift brings heavier rain and Deepavali celebrations that light up Little India with extraordinary displays. The covered hawker centres become essential infrastructure, and the Penang Heritage Trail walks are best done in early morning before the humidity becomes oppressive.",
    11: "The northeast monsoon returns with heavy rainfall and the roughest seas of the year — beach days are largely off the table, but George Town's indoor attractions (Pinang Peranakan Mansion, clan temples, the Camera Museum) and legendary food scene are completely rain-proof.",
    12: "December rain persists but festive energy transforms George Town — the Clan jetties host year-end celebrations, Christmas lights brighten the heritage zone, and the food courts are packed with holiday visitors. Penang proves that a great food city transcends weather entirely.",
  },

  'my-perhentian-east': {
    1: "The northeast monsoon has shut the islands down — ferries don't run, resorts are closed, and the seas are too rough for anything except dramatic shore-watching from the mainland. Kota Bharu's vibrant Siti Khadijah market and Kelantan cultural scene are your best bets, with excellent local food and zero tourists.",
    2: "Still firmly monsoon season — the Perhentians remain closed and the east coast is battered by rain and surf. Use this month for mainland Terengganu: visit the Noor Arfa batik factory, explore crystal mosques, and eat the best nasi dagang of your life without another tourist in sight.",
    3: "March is the monsoon's last act — seas begin calming in the second half and the first brave resorts start reopening on the islands. Visibility underwater is improving but not yet reliable, and accommodation options are limited. The adventurous are rewarded with deserted beaches and pioneer-season pricing.",
    4: "The Perhentians officially reopen — ferries resume, dive shops set up, and the coral reefs emerge from monsoon hibernation in surprisingly good shape. Visibility improves weekly, sea turtles are reliably spotted, and you'll share the white-sand beaches with a handful of early-season backpackers at their most blissful.",
    5: "May is the sweet spot — clear warm seas at 29°C, excellent diving visibility, and the islands are open but not yet packed. Reef sharks patrol the deeper sites, sea turtles nest on quiet beaches, and the jungle trails across Perhentian Besar are lush from the monsoon rains. Book a simple beach hut and disconnect.",
    6: "June brings school holidays and the islands wake up — snorkeling trips are busy, beach bars pump music, and the coral gardens off Perhentian Kecil are teeming with tropical fish. Sea conditions are calm and warm, visibility is excellent, and the sunsets from Long Beach are non-negotiable viewing.",
    7: "Peak season on the Perhentians — every beach hut and dive resort is full, the coral reefs are at their most vibrant, and the seas are warm, calm, and crystal clear. Sea turtles nest regularly, whale sharks occasionally pass through, and the nightlife on Perhentian Kecil buzzes until the generator dies.",
    8: "August matches July for crowds and conditions — the water is bathwater-warm, visibility is outstanding for both diving and snorkeling, and Hari Raya Haji brings a cultural dimension to the mainland. The Redang and Lang Tengah islands nearby offer overflow options if the Perhentians feel too busy.",
    9: "September is the smart play — diving conditions remain excellent, sea turtles are still active, but the summer crowds have thinned considerably. Prices drop, beach space opens up, and the late-afternoon light on those white-sand shores turns everything golden. This is the month photographers come.",
    10: "October is the last call — resorts begin closing mid-month as the northeast monsoon approaches, seas get choppier, and ferry schedules become unreliable. Early October still offers decent snorkeling and that end-of-season melancholy that makes tropical islands feel extra poignant. Don't wait until the 20th.",
    11: "The monsoon reclaims the coast — islands close, ferries stop, and the east coast shifts to mainland mode. Heavy rain and rough seas make this purely a cultural-exploration month: Terengganu's heritage, Kelantan's shadow puppet traditions, and the extraordinary local cuisine take center stage.",
    12: "Deep monsoon — the Perhentians are completely shuttered and the coast is storm-battered. Kota Bharu's Siti Khadijah market is at its most authentic without tourists, and the year-end cultural festivals in Kelantan offer a window into Malaysia's most traditional Malay state. The islands will wait for March.",
  },

  'mz-north': {
    1: "Peak summer in southern Mozambique — Bazaruto's waters hit 29°C and the snorkeling over coral reefs is spectacular, but January brings the heaviest rains (200mm+) and cyclone risk. Humpback whale season has ended, but dugong sightings in the archipelago are year-round and magical. Expect heat, humidity, and dramatically empty beaches between storms.",
    2: "February continues the hot, wet pattern at 32°C with the highest cyclone probability — travel insurance and flexibility are essential. Between storms, the diving off Bazaruto is world-class with manta rays and whale sharks, and the dhow sailing is atmospheric. The rain keeps tourist numbers low and resorts offer their best deals.",
    3: "March is the tail end of the wet season — rain eases to 150mm and the cyclone window starts closing. The ocean remains bathwater-warm at 28°C, diving visibility improves, and the Bazaruto dunes are lush and green. This is budget-friendly Mozambique with improving conditions week by week.",
    4: "April marks the welcome transition to dry season — rainfall drops sharply, skies clear, and the Bazaruto Archipelago reveals its full turquoise glory. Water temperatures are still warm at 27°C, the snorkeling is pristine, and humpback whales begin their northward migration past the coast. Crowds remain pleasantly thin.",
    5: "Dry season settles in with clear skies, calm seas, and comfortable 27°C days — this is when northern Mozambique starts to shine. The diving around Bazaruto and the Quirimbas is outstanding, traditional dhow trips operate smoothly, and the cashew harvest brings local markets to life.",
    6: "June is the dry season's cool heart — daytime highs drop to a pleasant 25°C, the ocean is calm at 25°C, and visibility underwater is at its best. Humpback whales begin arriving in the Bazaruto channel, making this the start of whale-watching season. Tourist numbers build but the coastline is so vast it never feels crowded.",
    7: "Peak dry season and peak whale season collide — humpback mothers and calves are regular sights from Bazaruto's shores, the diving is superlative, and the 24°C days are the most comfortable of the year. This is Mozambique's high season with premium pricing, but the combination of whales, reefs, and empty white sand earns every metical.",
    8: "August is the crown jewel — humpback whale encounters are at their most reliable, the seas are glass-calm, and Bazaruto's sandbanks glow against the Indian Ocean blue. Cool nights (18°C) and warm days make everything comfortable, though water temps dip to 23°C so bring a rash guard for longer dives.",
    9: "September extends the magic — whales are still present, the dry season holds, and the shoulder-season pricing starts to appear as summer approaches. Diving conditions remain excellent, the Quirimbas islands to the north are pristine and uncrowded, and the dhow culture along the coast is endlessly photogenic.",
    10: "October is the transition — heat builds to 30°C, the first rain showers appear, and humpback whales begin their southern departure. The ocean warms back up for swimming, and early-month diving is still excellent before visibility drops. It's a smart time to visit before the wet season's uncertainty arrives.",
    11: "The wet season creeps in with increasing rain and humidity at 32°C, but the ocean is warm and the reefs are alive with tropical fish. Whale shark season begins as plankton blooms attract these gentle giants to the coast. Expect afternoon thunderstorms, reduced tourist infrastructure, and that raw, uncurated Mozambique experience.",
    12: "December brings heat, rain, and the full wet-season atmosphere — 33°C with daily storms, but the whale sharks are feeding close to shore, the diving is adventurous, and the mango season makes every meal better. Christmas on a Bazaruto sandbank has a Robinson Crusoe magic that no resort can manufacture.",
  },

  'mz-south': {
    1: "Maputo in January is hot and humid at 31°C with heavy tropical downpours that turn the jacaranda-lined avenues into rivers. The seafood at the fish market (Mercado do Peixe) is transcendent regardless of weather, and the beaches at Ponta do Ouro to the south are warm but stormy. Cyclone risk exists — check forecasts.",
    2: "February peaks the heat at 32°C with the most rainfall of the year — Maputo's colonial architecture looks dramatic in storm light, and the city's jazz and marrabenta music scene provides excellent indoor entertainment. The Inhambane coast (5 hours north) offers whale shark snorkeling in warm but unpredictable seas.",
    3: "The wet season starts winding down — rain decreases and Maputo's energy shifts as the city dries out. The prawns at Costa do Sol restaurant are legendarily good year-round, and the improving weather makes the day trip to Inhaca Island increasingly viable by ferry.",
    4: "April is the transition sweet spot — rain drops significantly, temps settle to a comfortable 27°C, and Maputo's outdoor cafe culture along the Marginal comes alive. The whale shark season at Tofo Beach near Inhambane is still running, and the cultural scene in the capital (jazz clubs, art galleries) is vibrant.",
    5: "Dry season arrives and southern Mozambique becomes genuinely pleasant — 25°C days, clear skies, and calm Indian Ocean waters ideal for diving at Tofo and Ponta do Ouro. Maputo's street food stalls on Avenida Julius Nyerere are at their most enjoyable in the cooler evening air.",
    6: "June brings the coolest weather of the year — 22°C days and nights dipping to 15°C, which Mozambicans treat as winter. The ocean calms to a diving paradise, humpback whales begin appearing off the southern coast, and Maputo's seafood restaurants serve the best prawns in Africa without debate.",
    7: "Peak dry season and the start of serious whale watching — humpback mothers and calves cruise the coast from Ponta do Ouro to Inhambane. The 23°C days are ideal for exploring Maputo's historic Baixa district, and the diving at Tofo delivers manta rays, whale sharks, and pristine visibility.",
    8: "August is prime time for southern Mozambique — whales are reliably spotted, the seas are calm, and the dry winter weather (22°C) makes everything from Maputo city walks to Inhambane beach days comfortable. Tourist numbers build but the coastline absorbs visitors gracefully.",
    9: "Spring arrives with warming temps (26°C) and the last of the dry-season clarity — humpback whales are still passing through, diving visibility is excellent, and the jacarandas in Maputo are about to explode into purple bloom. This is the savvy traveler's window: great conditions, moderate crowds.",
    10: "October heats up to 28°C with the first rain showers returning — Maputo's jacarandas bloom spectacularly, the whale season winds down, and the ocean warms back up for swimming. The transition means some afternoon storms but mornings are reliably bright and beautiful.",
    11: "The wet season returns with afternoon thunderstorms and 30°C humidity, but the ocean is warm and the whale sharks at Tofo are feeding actively. Maputo's cultural calendar picks up with music festivals and gallery openings, and the mangoes and tropical fruit hit peak season at every market stall.",
    12: "December is hot, wet, and festive — Maputo celebrates the holidays with beach parties, seafood feasts, and marrabenta music on every corner. The coast at Ponta do Ouro fills with South African holidaymakers, Tofo delivers whale shark encounters, and the tropical storms make every sunset a fireworks show.",
  },

  'na-etosha': {
    1: "Midsummer means 35°C heat, afternoon thunderstorms, and the Etosha pan filled with water — attracting flamingos by the thousands but dispersing the big game across the bush. The landscape is impossibly green, newborn springbok dot the plains, and the birding is spectacular. Crowds are low but the heat is oppressive; carry water obsessively.",
    2: "February is Etosha's wettest month — the pan can become a shallow lake, roads get muddy, and some camps close sections. The upside: flamingo flocks are extraordinary, the green savanna is dramatic against storm-lit skies, and the calving season means predators are active. Budget for a 4x4 and patience.",
    3: "The rains start easing and the pan begins its slow retreat, concentrating waterbirds and waders in shrinking pools. Temps are still hot at 33°C but the bush is lush, the roads are improving, and the park is nearly empty of other tourists. March rewards those who like their safari raw and uncurated.",
    4: "April marks the transition — the last rains fall, the bush starts drying, and animals gradually shift toward permanent waterholes. Temperatures drop to a comfortable 29°C, the light turns golden, and the birdlife is still excellent. This is one of the best-value months: good conditions, minimal crowds, and improving game viewing daily.",
    5: "Dry season begins in earnest — the bush thins, waterholes become the only show in town, and Etosha's famous game-viewing formula kicks in: park yourself at Okaukuejo or Halali waterhole at dusk and watch the parade. Cool nights (10°C), warm days (27°C), and increasingly reliable Big Five sightings.",
    6: "Winter in Etosha is crisp and clear — morning game drives start at a teeth-chattering 6°C but warm to a pleasant 24°C by midday. The waterholes are magnets now, with elephants, rhinos, lions, and gemsboks appearing like clockwork. Crowds build to moderate levels, the sky is vast and blue, and the photography is exceptional.",
    7: "Peak dry season and peak game viewing — the bush is stripped bare, every waterhole visit feels like a David Attenborough episode, and the cold nights (5°C) and dry air make for razor-sharp stargazing. This is Etosha's high season: book the rest camps months ahead, layer up for dawn drives, and bring your longest lens.",
    8: "August is Etosha at its most dramatic — bone-dry, cloudless, and the game concentrates at waterholes in densities that make your jaw drop. Black rhinos at Okaukuejo, lion prides at Salvadora, elephants everywhere. The cold pre-dawn drives (4°C) warm quickly, and by midday a pleasant 25°C invites lazy waterhole vigils. Peak pricing, peak wildlife.",
    9: "September cranks up the heat as spring arrives — daytime temps push toward 32°C and the bush is at maximum dryness, meaning wildlife viewing remains superb at waterholes. The crowds start thinning post-August, offering a slightly more relaxed safari experience. Mornings are warmer now, making those early game drives less brutal.",
    10: "October is the hot, tense month before the rains — temperatures soar past 35°C and the parched landscape shimmers with heat haze. Animals are desperate at waterholes, creating extraordinary (if sometimes difficult to watch) wildlife drama. The first thunderstorms of the season build spectacular cloud formations, and migratory birds begin returning.",
    11: "The first real rains arrive and Etosha transforms overnight — the pan floods, the bush greens, and animals disperse from the waterholes into the wider landscape. Calving season begins, attracting predators, and the birdlife explodes with migrants. Game viewing requires more patience as animals spread out, but the landscape photography is unbeatable.",
    12: "Full summer — hot (34°C), wet, and dramatically green. The Etosha pan hosts wading birds and flamingos, springbok lambs dot the plains, and the afternoon thunderstorms are theatrical. Most visitors avoid the wet season, so you'll have the waterholes to yourself and pay significantly less. Bring binoculars for the birds and patience for the mud.",
  },

  'na-skeleton': {
    1: "Midsummer in the Namib — Sossusvlei's dunes blaze at 36°C and you need to be in the park at dawn or not at all. The Skeleton Coast stays eerily cool due to the Benguela Current fog, creating a surreal contrast. Afternoon thunderstorms can briefly flood Deadvlei, creating those legendary reflection shots every photographer chases.",
    2: "February continues the scorching summer — Sossusvlei at sunrise is sublime but by 10am the sand can literally burn your feet. The ephemeral rivers occasionally flow through the Kuiseb Canyon, bringing brief life to the desert floor. Skeleton Coast seal colonies at Cape Cross are active and pungent, regardless of season.",
    3: "The heat begins to ease — temps drop from extreme to merely hot (32°C), and the desert starts its transition toward the kinder months. The dunes maintain their famous orange-against-blue contrast, and the Skeleton Coast fog creates haunting morning atmospheres around the shipwrecks. Tourist numbers remain low.",
    4: "April is when the Namib becomes genuinely pleasant — 28°C days, cool nights, and that extraordinary clear-sky light that makes Sossusvlei's dunes glow amber at sunrise and crimson at sunset. The Skeleton Coast's ghostly shipwrecks are best explored now, and the desert-adapted elephants along the Hoanib River are easier to track.",
    5: "May locks in ideal conditions — dry, cool nights (8°C), warm days (25°C), and zero rain. Climbing Big Daddy dune in the golden morning light is comfortable rather than punishing, and the Skeleton Coast's fur seal colony at Cape Cross is active with pups. The desert's silence at night, under those stars, is worth the trip alone.",
    6: "Winter in the Namib is magical — frosty dawns (4°C) give way to mild 22°C afternoons, and the Sossusvlei dunes are at their most photogenic in the raking winter light. The Skeleton Coast fog is at its thickest, feeding the lichen fields and creating a world that feels genuinely alien. Peak season pricing applies but crowds are modest by global standards.",
    7: "July is peak season — every sunrise at Sossusvlei is a congregation of photographers, every lodge near the dunes is booked solid, and the Skeleton Coast expeditions run at full capacity. The cold mornings (3°C) are bracing but the days are perfect at 20°C, and the cloudless skies make every landscape shot effortless. Book months ahead.",
    8: "August matches July for crowds and conditions — bone-dry, crystal-clear, and those dawn dune-walks at Sossusvlei remain the marquee experience. The desert-adapted wildlife (oryx, springbok, ostrich) is easier to spot against the stripped-back landscape, and hot-air balloon flights over the dunes are at their most reliable in the still morning air.",
    9: "Spring arrives and the Namib warms up — still comfortable at 27°C with crowds easing post-August. The light shifts toward warmer tones, Sossusvlei's dunes get that late-afternoon burnish, and the Skeleton Coast's seal pups at Cape Cross are growing. An excellent month that balances conditions, crowds, and value.",
    10: "October heats up toward 32°C and the first summer energy builds, but conditions remain dry and excellent for dune exploration if you start early. The Hoanib River's desert elephants are more active in the warming weather, and the Skeleton Coast's fog begins to thin, revealing stark coastal landscapes in sharp detail.",
    11: "Summer heat returns — 35°C in the interior means Sossusvlei visits require pre-dawn starts. The first rains can arrive late November, occasionally transforming Deadvlei's clay pan into a mirror. Crowds thin, prices soften, and the desert takes on a shimmering, mirage-heavy quality that feels hypnotic.",
    12: "Peak summer — Sossusvlei bakes past 37°C and only the earliest risers catch comfortable dune conditions. Occasional thunderstorms bring brief drama and the possibility of rare desert flooding. The Skeleton Coast remains cool and foggy in its own microclimate. This is off-peak pricing with on-peak intensity — bring sun protection and several litres of water per person.",
  },

  'ne-niger': {
    1: "January is the cool heart of the Sahel dry season — highs around 32°C with bone-dry air, cold desert nights dipping to 14°C, and the Saharan landscape at its most navigable. The Cure Salée salt cure festival near Agadez has passed, but camel caravans still cross the Ténéré, and Niamey's Grand Marché buzzes with dry-season commerce.",
    2: "February stays dry and warm at 35°C — the Saharan air is clear, the Aïr Mountains are hikeable, and the W National Park's wildlife concentrates around dwindling water sources, making game viewing surprisingly productive. Niamey's cultural scene is active, and the Gerewol preparations begin in Wodaabe camps to the north.",
    3: "Heat begins building aggressively — 38°C is typical and the harmattan dust haze can reduce visibility. The desert is vast and austere, W National Park remains good for wildlife, and the Niger River near Niamey is at its lowest, revealing sandbanks where hippos cluster. Carry more water than you think you need.",
    4: "April is brutally hot — 42°C+ is common, making this one of the hottest places on Earth. Only the most determined travelers venture out, but those who do find empty landscapes, dramatic heat shimmer over the Ténéré, and genuinely warm hospitality in Tuareg encampments. Air-conditioning is not a luxury; it's survival.",
    5: "May pushes heat to its absolute peak — 44°C days are not unusual, and the first tentative rain clouds appear on the southern horizon hinting at the approaching monsoon. The Niger River is at its lowest ebb, dust storms are common, and travel is for specialists only. Niamey slows to a heat-dazed crawl.",
    6: "The first rains arrive in the south — dramatic thunderstorms break the months-long heat and temperatures drop to a more manageable 38°C. The Sahel starts greening, farmers plant millet, and there's a palpable sense of relief across the country. W National Park becomes less accessible as tracks muddy, but the birdlife awakens.",
    7: "Rainy season builds — the south receives regular downpours, the Niger River begins rising, and the landscape transforms from brown to green with startling speed. Temperatures moderate to 34°C, and the agricultural energy across the Sahel is infectious. Northern desert areas remain dry but the Aïr Mountains catch occasional spectacular storms.",
    8: "August is peak rainy season — the south is lush, the Niger River floods its banks creating wetlands teeming with birdlife, and W National Park is largely inaccessible. Temperatures hover around 32°C with high humidity, and the Sahel is at maximum green. Road travel requires serious planning, but the cultural life in Niamey continues uninterrupted.",
    9: "September brings the last heavy rains and the Cure Salée festival near Ingall — Tuareg and Wodaabe nomads converge for one of West Africa's most extraordinary cultural gatherings, with camel races, the Gerewol beauty contest, and salt-cure rituals. The landscape is green and the Niger River runs high. This alone justifies a Niger trip.",
    10: "The rains retreat and the Sahel begins drying — temperatures climb back toward 38°C and the landscape holds its green for a few more weeks. The Niger River remains high, W National Park becomes accessible again, and the post-harvest energy in villages is celebratory. Migrating birds begin arriving from Europe.",
    11: "November locks in the dry season — clear skies, 36°C days, cool nights, and the harmattan dust starting to haze the horizon. The Aïr Mountains and Ténéré Desert are at their most accessible, camel treks from Agadez run smoothly, and the W National Park wildlife viewing improves as water sources shrink.",
    12: "December is the ideal Saharan adventure month — cool nights (15°C), warm days (33°C), clear skies, and the Ténéré Desert at its most navigable. Agadez's old town and famous mosque are best explored in the comfortable dry-season air, and the Tuareg silver markets are active. The stars over the Sahara are worth the journey alone.",
  },

  'ng-abuja': {
    1: "Harmattan season cloaks Abuja in a dry, dusty haze — 35°C days, cool nights, and that distinctive Saharan dust that makes sunsets spectacular and contacts lenses miserable. Zuma Rock looms dramatically through the haze, and the city's restaurants and cultural centres operate at full speed. The dryness keeps mosquitoes at bay.",
    2: "February is the hottest and driest month — 38°C heat shimmers off Abuja's modernist government buildings, and the surrounding hills are parched brown. The Abuja Carnival (if running) brings spectacular masquerades and cultural performances, and the Jabi Lake area offers evening relief. Hydration is a lifestyle, not a choice.",
    3: "The tail end of the dry season pushes temperatures past 37°C with occasional dust storms. The Gurara Falls near Abuja are at their lowest flow but the rocky landscape is dramatic. Weekends bring Abuja's middle class to outdoor restaurants and the growing craft beer scene — the city's modern energy is undeniable.",
    4: "April signals the transition — the first tentative rains bring blessed relief from months of dry heat, and the surrounding savanna starts greening. Temperatures ease to 34°C, Abuja's parks and gardens come alive, and the weekend markets (particularly the arts and crafts village) buzz with energy.",
    5: "The rains arrive properly — afternoon thunderstorms become a daily ritual, temperatures drop to a comfortable 31°C, and the landscape transforms from brown to green almost overnight. Abuja's garden city planning really shows now as the tree-lined boulevards flush with foliage. Mosquitoes return, so pack repellent.",
    6: "Full rainy season — regular heavy downpours, lush green hillsides, and Abuja at its most verdant and photogenic. The 30°C temperatures are the most comfortable of the year, and the cultural scene (Nollywood screenings, live music at Jabi) thrives despite — or perhaps because of — the evening showers.",
    7: "July is deep green and wet — the rains are heavy and consistent, surrounding waterfalls like Gurara are now thundering, and Abuja's parks are impossibly lush. Flooding can disrupt some areas, but the city centre handles the rain well. The cooler 28°C temperatures make this the most physically comfortable month.",
    8: "August matches July's wet intensity with a brief dry spell (the 'August break') mid-month that provides welcome relief. Temperatures stay around 28°C, the farmlands around Abuja are productive and green, and the cultural calendar picks up with independence-month preparations.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — torrential downpours, full rivers, and Abuja at its most dramatically green. Gurara Falls is at maximum power, the surrounding rock formations glisten, and the mosquitoes are relentless. Cultural life continues regardless, and there's a particular beauty to Abuja's clean modernist lines against storm-dark skies.",
    10: "October marks the transition back to dry — the last rains fall, the air clears, and the surrounding hills are still lush green. Independence Day (October 1) brings celebrations across the capital, temperatures are a comfortable 31°C, and this is arguably Abuja's most pleasant month overall. The haze hasn't returned and the mud is drying.",
    11: "November ushers in the dry season with clear skies, cooling nights, and that first hint of harmattan dust on the horizon. Temperatures are warm but not punishing (33°C), the landscape holds its green for a few more weeks, and the outdoor dining culture along Wuse II thrives in the pleasant evenings.",
    12: "December is dry, festive, and social — Abuja's population swells as diaspora Nigerians return for the holidays, restaurants are packed, and the city's nightlife hits peak energy. Cool harmattan evenings (18°C) make outdoor events comfortable, and the Christmas celebrations across this cosmopolitan capital are lively and warm.",
  },

  'ng-lagos': {
    1: "Lagos in January is dry, dusty, and relentless — harmattan haze blankets the skyline, 33°C heat pushes everyone toward the coast, and the energy on Victoria Island and Lekki never dims. The music scene (Afrobeats HQ, after all) is in full swing, Epe's fish markets are bustling, and the beaches at Tarkwa Bay offer gritty, authentic Lagos escapes.",
    2: "February stays hot and hazy at 34°C with the harmattan's last gasp — Lagos Fashion Week and Valentine's season give the city extra sparkle. Elegushi Beach buzzes on weekends, the New Afrika Shrine hosts legendary Afrobeats nights, and the street food (suya, jollof rice, puff puff) is a religion practised on every corner.",
    3: "March brings the first hint of humidity and occasional pre-rain showers — the harmattan lifts, the air clears, and Lagos's famous traffic somehow feels more tolerable. The bar and restaurant scene on Victoria Island is at its most dynamic, and a weekend boat trip to Ilashe Beach feels like a different country entirely.",
    4: "April marks the rainy season's arrival — afternoon thunderstorms roll in, humidity spikes, and Lagos's drainage infrastructure faces its annual test. The upside: temperatures ease to 31°C, the city's greenery explodes, and the cultural scene (art galleries in Ikoyi, live music on the mainland) uses the rain as an excuse to keep the party indoors.",
    5: "Full rainy season — heavy downpours, flooding in low-lying areas, and that particular Lagos humidity that makes air conditioning a human right. But the city doesn't slow down: the Afrobeats scene pulses through every weekend, the restaurant culture on VI evolves constantly, and the rain makes golden-hour photography over the lagoon extraordinary.",
    6: "June is wet and wild — the rains are intense, the Third Mainland Bridge looks dramatic against thunderheads, and Lagos's resilience is impressive to witness. Mid-year cultural festivals keep the energy high, and the seafood at Makoko floating market is freshest during the rains. Mosquito season is serious; malaria prophylaxis is wise.",
    7: "July brings a brief dry spell ('July break') that Lagosians celebrate with beach weekends and outdoor festivals. Temperatures moderate to 28°C — the coolest month — and the city's creative energy is at peak output. Art exhibitions, music festivals, and restaurant openings cluster here. A surprisingly great time to visit.",
    8: "August returns to heavy rain, but the cultural calendar compensates: the Lagos Theatre Festival and various Afrobeats showcases keep the city buzzing. The 28°C temperatures are Lagos's most comfortable, and the mainland markets — Balogun, Computer Village — operate their organised chaos rain or shine.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — serious flooding can occur, the lagoon swells, and getting across the city requires patience and waterproof shoes. But the live music scene doesn't miss a beat, the art galleries in Ikoyi are a perfect rain refuge, and there's something exhilarating about Lagos refusing to let weather dampen its energy.",
    10: "October brings the rainy season's exit — the last heavy showers fall, the city starts drying out, and Nigerian Independence Day (October 1) brings patriotic celebrations. Temperatures climb slightly to 30°C, the beaches reopen in earnest, and the start of the social season means every weekend has a party worth attending.",
    11: "November is dry, warm, and socially electric — Lagos's famous 'Detty December' season starts early, with concerts, weddings, and beach parties filling every weekend calendar. The harmattan hasn't fully arrived so conditions are clear and comfortable at 32°C. This is Lagos at its most magnetic and expensive.",
    12: "Detty December in full effect — Lagos becomes the most exciting city in Africa as the diaspora returns, Afrobeats concerts sell out nightly, beaches are packed, and the nightlife on VI runs until dawn. Cool harmattan evenings balance hot days, and the festive energy is genuinely intoxicating. Book everything ahead; the city operates at maximum capacity.",
  },

  'ni-nicaragua': {
    1: "Dry season delivers — 32°C sunshine, the Pacific coast at its most swimmable, and the colonial charm of Granada at its photogenic best without the muggy heat. Ometepe Island's twin volcanoes rise sharply against blue skies, the surf at San Juan del Sur is consistent, and the Masaya Volcano's lava lake glows spectacularly at night.",
    2: "February is peak dry season and arguably Nicaragua's best month — warm, sunny, minimal humidity, and the country's main attractions (León's cathedral, Corn Islands, Somoto Canyon) are all accessible and uncrowded. The Pacific surf is reliable, the coffee harvest is wrapping up in the highlands, and everything feels golden.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot — temperatures push past 34°C in the lowlands, making the cloud forests around Matagalpa and Jinotega welcome cool retreats. Semana Santa preparations begin, León's streets fill with sawdust carpets, and the Little Corn Island's Caribbean waters are crystal-clear for diving and snorkeling.",
    4: "Holy Week (Semana Santa) transforms Nicaragua — elaborate processions fill Granada and León, beaches are packed with local families, and the festive atmosphere is genuine and infectious. The heat is intense at 35°C, the dry landscape is at its most parched, and the surf at Popoyo breaks perfectly for experienced riders.",
    5: "May signals the rainy season's arrival — the first afternoon storms break months of heat, the countryside starts greening, and temperatures ease to 31°C. The transition period offers good value: tourist numbers are low, the surf remains strong on the Pacific, and the Corn Islands stay relatively dry thanks to Caribbean weather patterns.",
    6: "Rainy season proper — daily afternoon downpours, lush green landscapes, and the volcanoes often wreathed in dramatic clouds. The Pacific coast gets muddy but surfable, the cloud forests around Miraflor are at their most alive, and Granada's colonial architecture looks stunning wet. Mosquitoes are active; DEET is essential.",
    7: "July brings a brief dry spell (canícula) that locals treasure — the rains pause for a week or two, the countryside stays green, and the beaches get a welcome window of sunshine. Temperatures are comfortable at 30°C, the surf at San Juan del Sur is excellent, and the Little Corn Island delivers its turquoise promise.",
    8: "August returns to regular rain with heavy afternoon storms, but mornings are usually clear and bright. The highlands around Estelí are lush with coffee plants and wildflowers, Ometepe's jungle trails are atmospheric in the mist, and the rum distilleries around Managua don't care about the weather.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — serious rainfall can cause flooding and mudslides, and some rural roads become impassable. The upside: the landscape is spectacularly green, tourist prices are at their lowest, and the few visitors who come get an authentic Nicaragua experience that high-season travelers never see.",
    10: "October stays wet but the rains ease toward month's end, and the countryside is at maximum lushness. The Caribbean coast (Corn Islands, Pearl Lagoon) often gets better weather than the Pacific side this month. Surf swells on the Pacific are powerful for experienced riders.",
    11: "November is the transition month — rains taper off, the landscape is still lush green, and the dry-season energy starts building. Temperatures hover around 30°C, the Corn Islands' waters clear up beautifully, and the surf season along the Pacific winds down gracefully. An underrated month for value and variety.",
    12: "December clicks back to dry season — clear skies, warm days (32°C), and the Purísima celebrations (December 7-8) fill every Nicaraguan city with fireworks, singing, and treats thrown from doorways. Granada sparkles, the surf at Popoyo fires up, and the holiday atmosphere makes this a festive, uncrowded alternative to neighbouring Costa Rica.",
  },

  'nl-amsterdam': {
    1: "Amsterdam in January is cold, dark, and atmospheric — 5°C highs, short days ending by 4:30pm, and the canal houses reflected in rain-slicked cobblestones. Crowds are nonexistent, museum queues (Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh) are manageable, and the brown cafés feel their cosiest with jenever in hand. Skating on frozen canals happens if you're very lucky.",
    2: "February stays grey and cold (6°C) with occasional sleet, but the first hints of spring appear: crocuses in Vondelpark, longer evenings, and the anticipation of tulip season ahead. This is budget Amsterdam — hotels are cheap, restaurants don't require reservations, and the Anne Frank House is almost approachable without a months-ahead booking.",
    3: "Spring stirs — temperatures reach 9°C, the earliest tulips appear in the Bloemenmarkt, and the city shakes off its winter torpor. Keukenhof Gardens open mid-March and the first blooms draw crowds, but Amsterdam itself stays manageable. Rain is common but the cafés are ready, and the cycling starts feeling less masochistic.",
    4: "April is King's Day month (April 27) and the entire city turns into a massive street party dressed in orange — it's glorious, chaotic, and unmissable. Tulip season peaks at Keukenhof, temps hit a pleasant 13°C, and the canal-side terraces fill with the first al fresco drinkers of the season. Book ahead for King's Day weekend.",
    5: "May is Amsterdam's sweet spot — 17°C, long evenings, tulips still blooming, and the canals lined with locals drinking rosé in the fading light. The museums are manageable, cycling through the countryside to windmills at Zaanse Schans is idyllic, and the herring carts serve the freshest nieuwe haring of the season.",
    6: "June brings near-perfect Amsterdam — 20°C, 16+ hours of daylight, and the city's outdoor culture in full bloom. Canal boat tours are at their most enjoyable, the Jordaan neighbourhood buzzes with terrace life, and the Holland Festival fills the city with performing arts. Crowds build to peak but the energy is infectious.",
    7: "Peak summer: 22°C, long light evenings, and Amsterdam is packed — the Anne Frank House requires booking weeks ahead, the Red Light District tour groups are dense, and hotel prices peak. But cycling along the Amstel at 10pm in golden light, eating bitterballen on a canal terrace — the clichés exist because they're magnificent.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and crowds with the added bonus of the Grachtenfestival — classical music on floating stages along the canals is uniquely Dutch and wonderful. Vondelpark hosts free concerts, the Jordaan Festival fills the neighbourhood with live music, and the cheese markets at Alkmaar and Gouda are in full tourist mode.",
    9: "September is the smart play — summer warmth lingers at 19°C, the crowds thin after Labour Day, and the city settles into a golden-lit autumn rhythm. Museum season begins in earnest, the brown cafés get cosier, and the canal houses framed by yellowing trees are peak Amsterdam postcard material.",
    10: "October brings autumn properly — 14°C, falling leaves along the canals, and the ADE (Amsterdam Dance Event) turning the city into the world's electronic music capital for five days. The Rijksmuseum and Stedelijk are wonderfully uncrowded midweek, and the food scene shifts to stamppot, erwtensoep, and other hearty Dutch comfort.",
    11: "November is grey, rainy, and cosy — the quintessential Amsterdam atmosphere of lit windows, steamed café glass, and canals reflecting bare trees. Sinterklaas arrives mid-month by boat (a uniquely Dutch spectacle), the Christmas markets start setting up, and the city is refreshingly affordable with almost no tourist queues.",
    12: "December transforms Amsterdam with twinkling lights along every canal, Christmas markets at Museumplein and Dam Square, and Sinterklaas festivities through December 5th. It's cold (5°C) and often wet, but the festive atmosphere, oliebollen (Dutch doughnuts) from street carts, and hot chocolate in a candlelit brown café make it genuinely magical.",
  },

  'nl-countryside': {
    1: "The Dutch countryside in January is flat, grey, and windswept — 4°C highs, the polder landscape stripped bare, and the iconic windmills at Kinderdijk standing stoic against pewter skies. If the canals freeze (rare but possible), the skating culture that inspired the Elfstedentocht comes alive. Cheese markets are closed until spring, but the coastal dunes make for bracing walks.",
    2: "February is the bleakest month — short days, relentless North Sea wind, and the tulip fields still bare brown earth. But the Wadden Sea mudflats are hauntingly beautiful in winter light, the fishing villages of Volendam and Marken are tourist-free, and a bowl of erwtensoep (split pea soup) in a village café tastes like survival earned.",
    3: "Spring's first signals: crocuses push through, the earliest tulip shoots appear in the Bollenstreek, and the light starts improving. Keukenhof opens mid-March, and the Dutch countryside transitions from endurance to anticipation. The windmills of Kinderdijk and Zaanse Schans are uncrowded and photogenic against March's dramatic cloud formations.",
    4: "April explodes with colour — the tulip fields between Leiden and Haarlem become striped ribbons of red, yellow, pink, and purple that look fake but aren't. Keukenhof peaks, the cheese markets at Alkmaar and Gouda open for the season, and cycling through the Bollenstreek at 14°C with a tailwind is pure Dutch perfection.",
    5: "May is the countryside at its most charming — 17°C, late tulips giving way to wildflowers, and every village draped in its best spring greenery. The Wadden Sea islands (Texel, Terschelling) become accessible and beautiful, the cheese markets are in full swing, and the flat cycling landscape rewards with endless horizon views under big skies.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 20°C, endless light, and the Dutch countryside completely alive with outdoor festivals, village fairs, and agricultural energy. The North Sea coast (Scheveningen to Zandvoort) becomes beachable, the Frisian lake district is perfect for sailing, and the cheese wheels rolling at Alkmaar market are peak Instagrammable Netherlands.",
    7: "July is the warmest month — 22°C, long beach days along the North Sea coast, and the countryside buzzing with cycling families and sailing regattas on the Frisian lakes. The Wadden Sea islands are at their peak for wildlife (seals, seabirds), and the Hoge Veluwe National Park is a forested escape from the flat farmland.",
    8: "August continues summer with beach weather, outdoor swimming in the Dutch lakes, and the Sneekweek sailing regatta turning Friesland into a maritime festival. Temperatures hover around 22°C, the coastal dunes are golden, and the roadside farm stands sell the sweetest tomatoes and strawberries. The crowds are family-oriented and cheerful.",
    9: "September is the golden transition — summer warmth (19°C) lingers, the tourist crowds vanish, and the countryside takes on that particular Dutch autumnal glow. The Wadden Sea is quieter but still accessible, the cycling is perfect, and the Hoge Veluwe's heathland turns purple with heather. Cheese market season winds down gracefully.",
    10: "October brings autumn fog, falling leaves, and the Bollenstreek's tulip farmers planting next spring's bulbs — the cycle begins again. Temperatures drop to 13°C, the North Sea turns angry and spectacular for storm-watching, and the Veluwe's forests are aflame with autumn colour. The Wadden Sea's mussel season makes coastal village visits worthwhile.",
    11: "November is the Dutch countryside at its most introspective — grey skies, bare trees, and that distinctive North Sea light that painters have chased for centuries. Sinterklaas arrives by boat in various harbour towns, the indoor-season begins for farmers' markets and craft fairs, and the coastal storms are genuinely dramatic. Bring waterproofs and embrace it.",
    12: "December winter descends — 5°C, short days, and the countryside villages twinkle with Christmas lights. Dickensfest in Deventer, Christmas markets in cave systems of Valkenburg, and the hope of ice-skating on natural ice keep spirits high. The flat landscape under frost or occasional snow has a stark beauty that rewards the well-layered visitor.",
  },

  'no-bergen-fjords': {
    1: "January in Bergen means 4°C, 200mm+ of rain, and about five hours of grey daylight — but the fjords are hauntingly beautiful in winter, the funicular up Fløyen offers misty panoramas, and the fish market sells the freshest seafood you'll eat all year. Northern lights are possible on clear nights, and hotel prices are wonderfully gentle.",
    2: "February is Bergen's coldest month at 3°C with persistent rain and occasional snow, but the days are getting longer and the fjord cruises into Sognefjord or Hardangerfjord in winter are sublime — silent, fog-draped, and virtually private. The city's Bryggen wharf area is atmospheric without the summer crowds.",
    3: "March brings the first real signs of spring — daylight extends past 12 hours, the snow line starts retreating up the mountains, and the occasional sunny day transforms the fjords into mirrors. Skiing at Voss is still excellent, and Bergen's cultural scene (concerts, galleries) is an ideal antidote to any remaining grey.",
    4: "April awakens the fjords — waterfalls thunder with snowmelt, fruit orchards in Hardanger begin blossoming, and temps climb to 9°C. The rain eases slightly, the hiking trails at lower elevations open up, and the Fløibanen funicular ride rewards with increasingly green vistas. Tourist numbers are low and hotels offer real value.",
    5: "May is when Bergen becomes genuinely stunning — 14°C, waterfalls at maximum power from snowmelt, and the Hardanger fruit blossoms create a white-and-pink canopy over the fjords that rivals Japan's sakura. The National Day celebrations (May 17) fill the streets with traditional bunads, marching bands, and infectious patriotic joy.",
    6: "June delivers Bergen's best — 17°C, 19 hours of daylight, and the fjords in full emerald glory. The Trolltunga hike is now accessible, midnight-sun boat cruises on Sognefjord are magical, and the Bergen International Festival brings world-class music and theatre. Rain is still likely (it's Bergen), but the long light compensates beautifully.",
    7: "July is peak season — 19°C, the longest days, and tourists filling Bryggen's colourful wooden warehouses. The hiking is supreme (Trolltunga, Preikestolen is a day trip away), the fjord kayaking is warm enough to enjoy without a drysuit, and the seafood restaurants serve the freshest king crab and salmon. Book ahead for everything.",
    8: "August matches July's warmth and crowds with the added berry season — cloudberries, blueberries, and lingonberries line the mountain trails. The fjord cruises are at their busiest but the kayaking trips offer more intimate access. Bergen's rain reputation is honestly at its least deserved in summer, though an umbrella remains non-negotiable.",
    9: "September is the connoisseur's month — autumn colours paint the fjord walls in copper and gold, temps stay mild at 15°C, and the summer crowds dissolve. The hiking trails are still open, the Bergen Philharmonic season begins, and the seafood is exceptional as the autumn harvest fills the fish market. Rain returns in force, but you knew that.",
    10: "October brings proper autumn — 11°C, heavy rain, and the fjords wrapped in moody mist and flame-coloured foliage. The tourist infrastructure starts winding down, but Bergen itself stays vital with its indoor cultural life, and the Bryggen wharf under grey skies and rain is perhaps more atmospheric than in bright sunshine. Northern lights season begins.",
    11: "November is dark and wet — Bergen gets barely seven hours of daylight and 250mm+ of rain, but the city is beautifully lit with early Christmas preparations. The funicular offers dramatic moody views, the fish soup at the market warms you to the core, and northern lights are increasingly likely on the rare clear nights.",
    12: "December in Bergen is Christmas card material — twinkling lights on Bryggen, gingerbread house competitions (Bergen's iconic Christmas tradition), and the fish market selling holiday specialties. Expect 4°C, heavy rain, and short days, but the festive atmosphere, gløgg in hand, makes the darkness part of the charm.",
  },

  'no-lofoten': {
    1: "Polar night — the sun doesn't rise at all for the first two weeks, and the Lofoten sky is a canvas of deep blues, purples, and the northern lights dancing overhead. Temperatures hover around 1°C (mild for 68°N, thanks to the Gulf Stream), and the snow-draped fishing villages of Reine and Hamnøy are heartbreakingly beautiful. The cod fishing season (skrei) has just begun.",
    2: "The sun returns briefly in early February, painting the snow-covered peaks in pink alpenglow for a few precious hours each day — photographers call this the 'blue hour season.' Northern lights remain spectacular, the cod fishing is in full swing (join a local boat trip), and the frozen landscape is perfect for snowshoeing between villages.",
    3: "March brings meaningful daylight — 12+ hours by month's end — and the winter scenery becomes increasingly dramatic as sunlight hits the jagged peaks. The Lofoten cod drying racks fill with stockfish (a centuries-old tradition), northern lights are still visible, and the skiing from mountain to sea is unlike anywhere else on Earth.",
    4: "April is the magic transition — snow still caps the peaks but the beaches emerge, the Arctic light is extraordinary, and the midnight sun is just weeks away. The fishing villages thaw, the eagle safari boats resume in Trollfjord, and the hiking trails at lower elevations start opening. Lofoten at its most photogenic is a strong claim, but April makes it.",
    5: "The midnight sun arrives in late May and doesn't set again until July — the endless golden light makes the turquoise beaches at Haukland and Utakleiv look tropical (they're not; the water is 8°C). Hiking season opens properly, the birdlife on the outer islands explodes with nesting puffins, and the fishing villages buzz with pre-summer energy.",
    6: "June under the midnight sun is Lofoten's crown jewel — 15°C days that feel warmer in the endless light, hiking from Reinebringen summit to Kvalvika Beach, and the sea kayaking through the fjords at midnight. It's peak season with premium pricing, but standing on a white-sand beach at 11pm in full daylight is worth every krone.",
    7: "July is the warmest month at 16°C, the midnight sun continues, and Lofoten is at its busiest — the hiking trails are crowded, the rorbuer (fishermen's cabins) are booked months ahead, and the beaches are as busy as Arctic beaches get. The whale watching (sperm whales, orcas) is active, and the fishing for halibut and cod is excellent.",
    8: "August stays warm (15°C) with the midnight sun fading into spectacular golden-hour sunsets that last for hours. The hiking is still prime, the berry picking begins in the mountains, and the first hints of northern lights return late in the month. Crowds ease slightly, making this a sweet spot for those who want Lofoten without the July crush.",
    9: "September is the autumn transition — the northern lights return in earnest, the mountains turn rust and gold, and the temperatures drop to 11°C with increasing rain. The tourist crowds thin dramatically, the rorbuer cabins become available, and the combination of autumn colour with aurora borealis is exclusive Lofoten magic that few other places can match.",
    10: "October brings the full Arctic autumn — wild storms, the northern lights at their most active, and the Lofoten peaks dusted with the first snow. Temperatures hover around 7°C, the fishing villages hunker down, and the moody light makes every photograph look like a Nordic noir poster. This is raw, beautiful Lofoten for those who don't need sunshine.",
    11: "November plunges toward polar night — the sun barely crests the horizon, the northern lights dominate the sky, and the cod fishing season begins building toward its winter peak. Snow settles on the fishing villages, the temperature drops to 3°C, and the isolation is either deeply romantic or deeply challenging. There is no middle ground.",
    12: "Polar night returns — the sun disappears entirely by mid-December, but the Christmas lights in Svolvær and Kabelvåg create a warm glow against the Arctic darkness. The northern lights are magnificent, the cod fishing boats prepare for the January season, and a Christmas in a Lofoten rorbuer with snow, candles, and fresh fish is unforgettable.",
  },

  'no-oslo-east': {
    1: "Oslo in January is properly cold — minus 4°C average, the Oslofjord frozen at the edges, and the city draped in snow that makes the Vigeland sculptures look like ice art. Cross-country skiing in Nordmarka forest starts from the metro station (only in Norway), and the Munch Museum and National Gallery offer warm refuge. Days are short but the city is cosy and quiet.",
    2: "February is the coldest month but also the most fun for winter sports — the Holmenkollen ski jump towers over the city, cross-country trails in Nordmarka are in prime condition, and the Oslo Winter Festival brings ice bars and snow activities to the waterfront. The northern lights occasionally reach this far south on clear nights.",
    3: "March brings the first spring hints — daylight extends past 12 hours, the snow starts softening, and Oslo's café culture begins its migration toward outdoor tables. The skiing is still excellent (some of the best conditions, in fact, with longer days and corn snow), and the cultural season at the Opera House is in full swing.",
    4: "April is Oslo's awakening — temps climb to 10°C, the Oslofjord thaws, and the city's parks explode with crocuses and daffodils. The Bygdøy peninsula museums (Viking Ship, Kon-Tiki, Fram) are open and uncrowded, and the street food scene at Vippa and Mathallen starts buzzing. Pack layers — April in Oslo can deliver four seasons in a day.",
    5: "May is magnificent — Constitution Day (May 17) transforms Oslo into a city of Norwegian flags, children's parades, and russ (graduates) in red overalls celebrating everywhere. The temps hit 16°C, the Oslofjord islands become accessible by ferry for swimming and picnics, and the Aker Brygge waterfront dining scene comes alive.",
    6: "June delivers Oslo's best — 20°C, nearly 19 hours of light, and the city at its most vibrant. Swimming in the Oslofjord at Sørenga or Langøyene island is warm enough to enjoy, the rooftop bars along Aker Brygge are buzzing, and the Munch Museum's waterfront location is at its most impressive. Norwegian National Day energy lingers.",
    7: "Peak summer: 22°C, endless daylight, and Oslo empties slightly as Norwegians head to their hyttes (cabins). The Oslofjord islands are perfect for kayaking and swimming, the sculpture parks are sun-drenched, and the Tjuvholmen dining scene peaks. Prices are high but the long evenings make every restaurant bill feel justified.",
    8: "August is warm (21°C) and still bright, with the Øya Festival bringing Norway's best music to the city. The beaches along the fjord are lively, the forest swimming spots in Nordmarka are divine, and the cultural calendar is packed. Late August sees the first touch of autumn gold in the trees — fleeting and beautiful.",
    9: "September is Oslo's golden month — the city's trees turn amber and rust, temps hover around 15°C, and the cultural season (Oslo Philharmonic, National Theatre) hits full stride. The fjord is still swimmable for the brave, the hiking in Nordmarka is spectacular in autumn colour, and the city feels like it's exhaling after summer.",
    10: "October brings proper autumn — 8°C, falling leaves, and the cosy season taking hold in Oslo's coffee shops and restaurants. The food scene shifts to warming seasonal menus, the Munch Museum and National Gallery are uncrowded, and the first frosts in Nordmarka make morning hikes crisp and invigorating.",
    11: "November is the grey transition — temperatures hover around 2°C, the first snow can arrive, and the city starts its winter preparations. Christmas markets begin opening at Spikersuppa and the Fortress, the days are short (7 hours), and the city's indoor cultural life (opera, concerts, galleries) becomes essential. Oslo does hygge differently from Denmark, but just as well.",
    12: "December in Oslo is dark, cold, and festive — the Christmas markets at the Fortress and Karl Johans gate glow with candles, the city smells of gløgg and pepperkaker (gingerbread), and the ice rink at Spikersuppa becomes the city's living room. The days are just six hours long, but the Norwegian approach to winter — embrace it — is contagious.",
  },

  'no-tromso-arctic': {
    1: "Deep polar night — the sun stays below the horizon all month, but Tromsø doesn't sleep. The northern lights are at their most spectacular, dog-sledding across frozen landscapes under the aurora is life-changing, and the Arctic Cathedral's architecture glows against the blue darkness. At minus 4°C with snow everywhere, this is genuine Arctic winter at its most dramatic.",
    2: "The sun returns in late January/early February, and those first pink rays hitting the snow-covered peaks after months of darkness are genuinely emotional. Northern lights remain outstanding, the dog-sledding and reindeer-sleigh rides are in peak season, and the Tromsø International Film Festival brings warmth to the blue-lit streets.",
    3: "March is the sweet spot for Arctic winter activities — 12 hours of daylight, reliable snow cover, and the northern lights still dancing on clear nights. Cross-country skiing through the birch forests, snowmobiling across the tundra, and whale watching (late-season orcas) make this arguably the best winter-experience month.",
    4: "April brings real light — 16+ hours of daylight, the snow starts softening for excellent spring skiing, and the northern lights season winds down. The Arctic landscape takes on a luminous quality as the midnight sun approaches, and the Sámi cultural experiences near Tromsø are at their most accessible.",
    5: "The midnight sun arrives in mid-May and the Arctic world transforms — snow melts rapidly from the lowlands, the fjords thaw, and the landscape shifts from white to green with startling speed. Whale watching transitions to summer species, the hiking trails begin opening, and the 24-hour daylight is disorienting and exhilarating in equal measure.",
    6: "June under the midnight sun is extraordinary — the sun simply circles the sky for 24 hours, the Arctic landscape is bathed in perpetual golden light, and the hiking in the Lyngen Alps and along the coast is spectacular. Sea kayaking at midnight, fishing for Arctic char, and the Midnight Sun Marathon make this Tromsø's most magical month.",
    7: "July peaks at 15°C — warm for the Arctic — with endless daylight, the wildflowers carpeting every hillside, and the fjords at their most accessible for boat trips. This is peak tourist season with premium pricing, but midnight hikes to mountain summits under a sun that never sets create memories that outlast any budget concern.",
    8: "August is still light-filled but the first sunsets return — watching the sun dip below the horizon for the first time in months feels oddly nostalgic. The berry picking (cloudberries, blueberries) is extraordinary, the whale watching is active, and the hiking remains excellent as the autumn colours begin their first shy appearance.",
    9: "September brings the northern lights back and the autumn colours to the Arctic — the birch forests turn gold against snow-dusted peaks, creating a landscape that's almost aggressively photogenic. Temperatures drop to 7°C, the tourist crowds thin, and the combination of aurora, autumn foliage, and Arctic fjords is exclusive to this latitude.",
    10: "October is aurora prime — the long dark nights return, the northern lights are frequent and spectacular, and the first snow dusts the mountains. Temperatures hover around 2°C, the whale migration (orcas chasing herring) begins, and the polar night is approaching fast. This is the start of Tromsø's atmospheric dark season.",
    11: "November plunges into polar night — the sun disappears around November 21 and won't return for two months. Northern lights are at peak activity, the snow settles in, and the city's culture (concerts, the Arctic library, cosy restaurants) sustains life through the darkness. Dog-sledding season opens, and whale watching for orcas is building.",
    12: "Polar night reigns — total darkness at midday has a surreal beauty, and Tromsø counters it with Christmas markets, candle-lit restaurants, and the finest northern lights viewing of the year. The whale watching for orcas and humpbacks in the fjords is at its peak, dog-sledding through the Arctic darkness feels like another world entirely.",
  },

  'np-himalaya': {
    1: "January is cold and clear in the Himalayas — Annapurna and Everest Base Camp treks are technically possible but bitterly cold at altitude (minus 20°C+ at base camps), and many teahouses close above 4,000m. The Terai lowlands, however, are perfect for wildlife: Chitwan's jungle is dry, visibility is excellent, and rhinos and tigers are easier to spot.",
    2: "February starts thawing at lower elevations — rhododendrons begin budding, the Terai remains excellent for safaris, and the mountain views from Pokhara and Nagarkot are crystal-clear. High-altitude trekking is still cold and challenging, but the Poon Hill trek (lower elevation) offers spectacular dawn Himalayan panoramas in relative comfort.",
    3: "Spring arrives and the Himalayas ignite — rhododendrons explode into crimson, pink, and white along every trekking trail, and the Annapurna Circuit and Everest Base Camp routes open in earnest. The weather is warming (15°C at Pokhara) but stable, Chitwan's jungle is lush but still navigable, and this is the start of peak trekking season.",
    4: "April is peak trekking month — the weather window is ideal, the rhododendron forests are at full bloom, and the trails to Everest Base Camp and Annapurna are buzzing with trekkers from every nation. Temperatures are comfortable up to 3,500m, the mountain views are reliable, and the Terai starts getting hot. Book teahouses ahead on popular routes.",
    5: "May is the last trekking window before the monsoon — the trails are still open but haze builds, temperatures are warm, and the Everest region sees its final summit-season push. The lower hills get hot and humid, Chitwan becomes uncomfortable, but the high passes (Thorong La, Cho La) are at their most accessible. Thunderstorms can build in afternoons.",
    6: "The monsoon arrives — heavy rain blankets the Himalayas, trails become muddy and leech-infested, landslides close roads, and most trekkers stay away. But the landscape is staggeringly beautiful in the rain, the rice terraces are planted, and the Upper Mustang and Dolpo (rain-shadow regions) remain viable treks for the adventurous.",
    7: "Peak monsoon — the Himalayas are drenched, the rivers rage, and trekking is only for those who genuinely enjoy mud. The Terai floods, roads are unreliable, and Kathmandu's streets become rivers. Upper Mustang behind the Annapurna range stays relatively dry and offers one of Nepal's most extraordinary cultural landscapes. Leeches are a certainty below 3,000m.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon's grip with the heaviest rainfall — not recommended for most trekking. The rice paddies are emerald green, the Himalayas are hidden behind clouds, and the country waits for autumn. Rafting the Trisuli and Bhote Koshi rivers is excellent with the high water levels, and Kathmandu's indoor cultural attractions are rain-proof.",
    9: "The monsoon retreats and Nepal springs back to life — the skies clear, the Himalayas emerge spectacularly washed and sharp, and the autumn trekking season begins in earnest. Temperatures are perfect for hiking, the Dashain festival brings the country together in celebration, and the trails are emptier than October. A canny trekker's secret.",
    10: "October is Nepal's golden month — crystal-clear skies, the entire Himalayan range visible from Kathmandu's valley rim, and every trek route at its absolute best. The Annapurna Circuit, Everest Base Camp, and Langtang Valley are at peak capacity, Chitwan is comfortable again for safaris, and the Tihar festival of lights adds magic to every village.",
    11: "November extends the trekking window — the weather stays stable, the crowds thin slightly from October's peak, and the mountain views remain exceptional. Temperatures drop at altitude (layering is essential above 3,500m), but the dry air and clear skies make this an outstanding trekking month. Chitwan's wildlife viewing is at its best in the dry, cool conditions.",
    12: "December is cold but clear — the Himalayan views are sharp, the lower-elevation treks (Poon Hill, Langtang) are comfortable with proper gear, and the Terai's wildlife viewing remains excellent. High-altitude treks are bitterly cold (minus 15°C at EBC), and many teahouses close above 4,000m. The cities are festive and surprisingly warm in the December sun.",
  },

  'np-kathmandu': {
    1: "January mornings in the Kathmandu Valley are cold (2°C) and often foggy, but the afternoon sun warms to a pleasant 18°C and the mountain views from Nagarkot and Bhaktapur are crystalline. The temple complexes at Boudhanath and Pashupatinath are uncrowded and meditative, and the Thamel district is quieter without the trekking-season frenzy.",
    2: "February warms slightly and the first spring flowers appear in the valley — the Holi festival preparations begin, and the city's temples receive fresh marigold garlands daily. The mountain panorama from Swayambhunath (Monkey Temple) is exceptional in the clear winter air, and Newari cuisine in Bhaktapur's backstreets is comforting and uncrowded.",
    3: "Holi (Festival of Colours) often falls in March, turning Kathmandu's streets into a joyful paint fight — expect to be coloured head to toe. The weather warms to 24°C, the rhododendrons start blooming in the surrounding hills, and the trekking season begins, filling Thamel with excited hikers buying last-minute gear.",
    4: "April is festival season — Bisket Jatra in Bhaktapur is one of Nepal's most spectacular celebrations, with chariot processions and ancient rituals. The valley is warm (28°C), the Himalayan views are still reliable before monsoon haze builds, and the trekkers returning from Annapurna and Everest fill Thamel's restaurants with trail stories.",
    5: "May gets hot (30°C+) and hazy — the pre-monsoon heat makes the valley uncomfortable and obscures the mountain views. Buddha Jayanti (Buddha's birthday) celebrations at Lumbini and Boudhanath are moving, and this is the last window for clear temple visits before the rains. Thamel's rooftop bars are lively with returning trekkers.",
    6: "The monsoon arrives and Kathmandu transforms — the rain is heavy, the streets flood regularly, and the valley turns impossibly green. The temple rituals continue regardless, and there's something powerful about Pashupatinath's cremation ghats in the rain. Crowds vanish, prices drop, and the Newari restaurants in Patan serve the best dal bhat without the wait.",
    7: "Peak monsoon — Kathmandu is drenched, the rivers run muddy, and the Himalayan views are hidden behind curtains of cloud. But the valley's rice paddies are planted and luminous green, the indoor museums (Patan Museum, National Museum) come into their own, and the monsoon light gives the brick temples an amber glow.",
    8: "August continues the deluge but Gai Jatra (Cow Festival) brings colour and comedy to the streets — costumed processions satirise politicians and celebrate the dead. The Krishna Mandir in Patan hosts beautiful Janmashtami celebrations, and the vegetarian food during festival season is extraordinary. The rain is relentless but the culture never stops.",
    9: "The monsoon retreats and Kathmandu rejoices — Indra Jatra brings spectacular masked dances, the living goddess (Kumari) makes her chariot procession, and Dashain preparations fill the markets with energy. The mountains start reappearing through clearing skies, the air freshens, and the trekking season ramps up in Thamel.",
    10: "October is Kathmandu at its absolute best — Dashain and Tihar festivals transform the city with kite-flying, family feasting, and millions of oil lamps and marigold garlands. The sky is crystal-clear, the Himalayan panorama from Swayambhunath is breathtaking, and the valley's autumn light makes every temple photograph extraordinary.",
    11: "November keeps the magic — clear skies, comfortable 22°C days, and the post-festival calm settling over the valley. The temple complexes are at their most photogenic in the low autumn sun, Bhaktapur's pottery squares are active, and the trekking-season energy in Thamel is contagious even if you're not heading for the hills.",
    12: "December chills Kathmandu to winter mode — morning fog, 3°C nights, and locals bundled in shawls around charcoal fires. The temples are uncrowded and atmospheric, the mountain views from Nagarkot are razor-sharp when the fog lifts, and a plate of momo dumplings in a Thamel back-alley kitchen feels like the best meal on Earth.",
  },

  'nr-nauru': {
    1: "The world's smallest island republic sits at 32°C year-round with the wet season in full swing — 300mm+ of rain, but the tropical showers pass quickly. The phosphate pinnacles of Topside create an otherworldly moonscape, the reef snorkeling off Anibare Bay is excellent, and you'll likely be the only tourist on the entire 21-square-kilometre island.",
    2: "February continues the wet season with heavy tropical downpours and warm, humid conditions. The reef fish are abundant, the coconut crabs emerge after rains, and the circular road around the island (19km) makes for a sweaty but fascinating walk through one of the Pacific's most unusual stories. There are no hotels — you'll need local contacts.",
    3: "Peak wet season — the most rainfall of the year, but Nauru's equatorial position means sun between storms and consistently warm 32°C days. The phosphate mining history is sobering and fascinating in equal measure, and the few visitors who make it here find genuine warmth from locals surprised to see tourists at all.",
    4: "April begins the transition toward drier months — rain eases, the reef visibility improves, and the island's single road is less puddled. Fishing with locals off the reef edge is the main activity, and the sunsets from the western shore over the Pacific are quietly spectacular. Nauru is less a destination and more an experience in remoteness.",
    5: "May sees rainfall dropping and conditions improving for outdoor exploration of Nauru's peculiar landscape — the raised coral interior, the abandoned phosphate works, and the narrow coastal fringe where life concentrates. The snorkeling is good, the diving (if you can arrange it) reveals drop-offs teeming with pelagic fish.",
    6: "June is the driest month — clear skies, moderate 30°C heat, and the reef at its most visible. This is the best window for Nauru's limited attractions: Buada Lagoon (the island's only freshwater body), the Japanese WWII ruins, and Command Ridge's panoramic views. Flights connect through Brisbane; plan your logistics carefully.",
    7: "July continues dry conditions with pleasant trade winds keeping the humidity in check. The fishing is excellent — yellowfin tuna and mahi-mahi are caught from the reef edge — and the phosphate pinnacles at Topside take on an eerie beauty in the dry-season light. Nauru requires self-sufficiency; bring what you need.",
    8: "August is warm and dry — the most comfortable month, with trade winds and minimal rain. The reef snorkeling at Anibare Bay is at peak visibility, and the island's compact size means you can explore every corner in a day. The Nauruan people are generous hosts, and the Friday evening outdoor gatherings are a window into Pacific Island life.",
    9: "September stays dry but humidity starts building as the wet season approaches. The island's mood shifts with the weather, outdoor activities remain comfortable, and the deep-sea fishing from the reef drop-off is productive. Nauru's isolation is its defining feature — this is about as far from mass tourism as it's possible to get.",
    10: "October marks the wet season's return — afternoon thunderstorms resume, humidity climbs, and the island gets lush quickly. The coconut palms along the coast rustle with fruit, the reef remains fishable between storms, and the few expats and locals make up a social scene so small it becomes instantly familiar.",
    11: "November is solidly wet — heavy rain, high humidity, and the occasional tropical storm make outdoor plans flexible. The phosphate pinnacles collect rainwater in pools that attract birdlife, and the island's peculiar charm (if charm is the right word for a mined-out micro-nation) is most apparent when you're waiting out a storm with a Nauruan family.",
    12: "December is hot, wet, and quiet — Nauru celebrates Christmas with community gatherings, church services, and communal feasts. The reef stays diveable between storms, the sunsets remain extraordinary, and the island's radical isolation from the rest of the world feels especially poignant during the holiday season.",
  },

  'nz-auckland': {
    1: "Midsummer in Auckland — 24°C, long sunny evenings, and the Hauraki Gulf sparkling with sailboats (the City of Sails earns its name). Waiheke Island's vineyards are in full swing, the Coromandel Peninsula's beaches are warm enough for proper swimming, and the Polynesian cultural energy of the city is infectious. Peak holiday crowds, so book ahead.",
    2: "February is Auckland's hottest month — 25°C, low rainfall, and the waterfront buzzing with outdoor dining and the Laneway Festival. The surf beaches on the west coast (Piha, Muriwai) are at their best, Waiheke's cellar doors pour rosé on sun-drenched terraces, and the gannet colony at Muriwai is spectacular with chicks fledging.",
    3: "March brings the first autumn hints — still warm at 23°C, the summer crowds thin, and the Pasifika Festival celebrates Auckland's Pacific Island heritage with the largest Polynesian event in the world. The Coromandel's Hot Water Beach is less crowded, the wine harvest at Waiheke is underway, and the evenings develop a golden quality.",
    4: "Autumn settles in beautifully — 19°C, the pohutukawa and deciduous trees begin turning, and the Waitakere Ranges west of the city are stunning in autumn colour. The crowds vanish, the food and wine scene operates at full quality without the queues, and the Hauraki Gulf remains warm enough for sailing and fishing.",
    5: "May is the autumn coda — 16°C, occasional rain, and Auckland's cultural scene (theatre, galleries, live music) shifts indoors. The Matariki (Maori New Year) celebrations begin in some communities, the Hobbiton day trip from Auckland is atmospheric in the misty green farmland, and the local seafood (green-lipped mussels, crayfish) is at its best.",
    6: "Winter arrives — 14°C, frequent rain, and the shortest days, but Auckland doesn't hibernate. Matariki (Maori New Year) is celebrated city-wide with lantern festivals and cultural events, the Sky Tower pierces through the grey cloud dramatically, and the winter warmth of a bowl of Tongan or Samoan food in Otara market is deeply satisfying.",
    7: "July is Auckland's coldest month at 13°C — rain is frequent, the days are short, but the ski fields of Ruapehu (4 hours south) open for the season. In the city, the restaurant and bar scene thrives in winter mode, the Auckland Art Gallery is uncrowded, and the Devonport ferry across the harbour on a moody winter day has its own beauty.",
    8: "August is still winter but the days are lengthening — the first spring blossoms appear, the whale watching from the Hauraki Gulf occasionally delivers Bryde's whales, and the city starts shaking off the grey. The Auckland Arts Festival lights up the cultural calendar, and the volcanic cones (Mt Eden, One Tree Hill) are dramatically moody in the winter light.",
    9: "Spring arrives — 16°C, the cherry blossoms in Auckland Domain and Cornwall Park bloom spectacularly, and the city's energy lifts visibly. The Hauraki Gulf islands reopen for the season, the west coast surf is powerful with consistent autumn swells, and the garden shows and farmers' markets return to weekend life.",
    10: "October is Auckland's spring sweet spot — 18°C, increasing sunshine, and the pohutukawa trees starting their famous red bloom. Labour Weekend brings the first beach exodus to the Coromandel, the Pasifika cultural events pick up, and the city's outdoor dining scene re-emerges. Lamb season in the surrounding farmland is impossibly cute.",
    11: "November warms to 20°C with the longest days approaching — the beaches fill up, Waiheke's vineyards open for summer, and the Hauraki Gulf sailing season hits its stride. The Coromandel and Bay of Islands become viable weekend escapes, and the pohutukawa blooms paint every coastline red. Summer is arriving and Auckland knows it.",
    12: "December is summer — 23°C, long evenings, and the build-up to Christmas fills the waterfront with markets and celebrations. The Viaduct Harbour dining precinct buzzes, the ferry to Rangitoto Island's volcanic summit is a quintessential Auckland experience, and the New Year's Eve fireworks from the Sky Tower bring the whole city to the harbour. Book accommodation early for the holiday crush.",
  },

  'nz-fiordland': {
    1: "Midsummer in Fiordland — 20°C, the longest days, and Milford Sound at its most accessible (though 'accessible' here means sharing it with peak tourist buses). The Great Walks (Milford Track, Routeburn, Kepler) are booked months ahead, the beech forests hum with birdlife, and those prehistoric-looking fiords under summer light are genuinely humbling.",
    2: "February stays warm at 19°C with slightly fewer crowds than January — the hiking is still prime, Milford Sound boat cruises are reliable, and the sandflies are at their most enthusiastic (bring repellent, seriously). Doubtful Sound, the quieter alternative, rewards those willing to take the extra boat-and-bus journey with near-solitude and dolphins.",
    3: "March is autumn's arrival — the beech forests begin turning gold, temperatures drop to 16°C, and the crowds thin noticeably on the Great Walks. Milford Sound's waterfalls are still impressive, the Te Anau Glowworm Caves are atmospheric, and the reduced visitor numbers make Fiordland feel like the wilderness it actually is.",
    4: "April brings full autumn colour to Fiordland's beech forests — golds and russets against the dark water of the fiords create landscapes that make you stop walking and just stare. Temperatures drop to 12°C, rain is frequent (but that's year-round here), and the hiking shifts to shorter day walks as the Great Walks close for the season.",
    5: "May transitions to winter — 9°C, heavy rain (Milford Sound receives 7,000mm annually, remember), and the snowline dropping toward the fiord edges. The boat cruises still run and are arguably more dramatic with snow-capped peaks reflected in dark water and waterfalls multiplied by the rain. Fiordland in winter is raw, vast, and profoundly quiet.",
    6: "Winter proper — 7°C, snow on the peaks, and Milford Sound at its most atmospherically dramatic. The waterfalls multiply with the heavy rain, morning mist clings to the fiord walls, and the handful of visitors who brave the Homer Tunnel in winter conditions are rewarded with a Milford Sound that feels genuinely primordial.",
    7: "July is Fiordland's coldest month at 5°C — the Milford Road can close with avalanche risk, the Great Walks are firmly shut, but the overnight Milford Sound cruises (if accessible) are extraordinary in winter. Doubtful Sound's stillness in winter is meditative, and the Kepler Track's lower sections around Te Anau are still walkable.",
    8: "August stays cold with occasional snow at lake level — the fiords are breathtaking when the clouds lift, revealing snow-covered peaks plunging into dark water. The road to Milford is more reliably open than July's, and the Te Anau township is cosy with winter-priced accommodation and genuine kiwi hospitality.",
    9: "Spring stirs — 10°C, the snowline starts retreating, and the beech forests show the first green buds. Milford Sound's waterfalls are at their most spectacular (snowmelt plus spring rain), the kea parrots are active and cheeky, and the Kepler Track's lower sections offer stunning spring walking. Sandflies wake up with the warmth.",
    10: "October is spring in full force — 13°C, the Great Walks start reopening, and the birdlife (tui, bellbird, fantail) is extraordinary as the forest awakens. Milford Sound boat cruises combine snowmelt waterfalls with spring greenery, and the hiking trails are at their most dramatically beautiful before summer crowds arrive.",
    11: "November warms to 15°C with the Great Walks open and the summer rush still a month away — this is the hiking sweet spot for those who want the trails without the January madness. The beech forests are vivid green, the alpine flowers bloom above the treeline, and the fiords are at their most colourful with new growth.",
    12: "December brings summer — 18°C, the longest days, and the start of peak season for the Great Walks and Milford Sound. The hiking is spectacular, the weather is as reliable as Fiordland gets (which means bring rain gear regardless), and the combination of blue sky, emerald forest, and mirror-dark fiord water is New Zealand at its most mythic.",
  },

  'nz-queenstown': {
    1: "Peak summer in adventure capital — 22°C, lake swimming at Wanaka and Wakatipu, and every adrenaline activity from bungy jumping to jet boating running at full throttle. The Remarkables mountain range provides a dramatic backdrop for everything, and the Central Otago vineyards (world-class Pinot Noir) are at their most beautiful. Book ahead; January is mobbed.",
    2: "February stays warm and slightly calmer — the summer crowds ease after school returns, the lake water is at its warmest for swimming, and the hiking (Ben Lomond, Roys Peak) is at its best in the long evening light. The Gibbston Valley wine harvest begins, and Arrowtown's tree-lined streets are drowsily beautiful.",
    3: "Autumn arrives and Queenstown transitions — the willows and poplars around the lake start turning gold, temperatures drop to 17°C, and the tourist pace shifts from frenetic to enjoyable. The hiking is prime (Routeburn day walks, Bob's Peak), the wine harvest is underway, and the autumn colour reflected in Lake Hayes is genuinely world-class.",
    4: "April is Queenstown's showstopper — the Arrow River blazes with autumn gold, the Remarkables get their first snow dusting, and the landscape becomes a study in amber, rust, and emerald. Arrowtown's Autumn Festival celebrates the colours, the jet boating and bungy operate year-round, and the cooler 12°C temperatures are perfect for hiking.",
    5: "May brings winter's edge — 8°C, the first snow on Coronet Peak and The Remarkables, and the ski-season anticipation building. The autumn colours linger in sheltered valleys, Queenstown's restaurant scene is world-class and uncrowded, and the dark-sky stargazing from nearby viewpoints is extraordinary in the cold, clear air.",
    6: "Ski season opens — the Remarkables and Coronet Peak fire up their lifts, the snow builds, and Queenstown transforms into New Zealand's winter playground. Temperatures hover around 5°C, the après-ski scene in the village is lively, and the Onsen Hot Pools overlooking the Shotover Canyon are the perfect post-slope reward.",
    7: "Peak ski season — consistent snow cover, clear winter days at 4°C, and Queenstown packed with skiers and snowboarders. The Remarkables and Coronet Peak are in full operation, the Milford Sound day trip in winter is astonishing, and the Winter Festival (if running) brings street performers, fireworks, and competitive dog barking to the lake.",
    8: "August is arguably the best ski month — the snow base is deepest, the days are lengthening, and the spring skiing conditions start to appear by month's end. The winter energy is still high, the Gibbston Valley wineries serve warming Pinot Noir by roaring fires, and the heliskiing on the Harris Mountains is bucket-list stuff.",
    9: "Spring arrives at the lake while winter lingers on the peaks — the best of both worlds at 10°C, with skiing still viable, the daffodils blooming around the lakefront, and the hiking trails at lower elevations opening up. The tourist lull between ski season and summer means excellent deals and smaller crowds.",
    10: "October is Queenstown's spring sweet spot — 14°C, the mountains still snow-capped but the valley floors green and flowering. The jet boating on the Shotover and Kawarau resumes at full capacity, the cycle trails along the lake are glorious, and the last ski runs of the season happen on the high slopes. Lupin season begins in the Mackenzie Country.",
    11: "November warms to 16°C with the summer adventure season ramping up — bungy, skydiving, paragliding, and every conceivable way to throw yourself off something. The lupins along Lake Tekapo are in spectacular bloom (a side trip), the Remarkables are snow-free for hiking, and Queenstown's restaurant strip is gearing up for peak season.",
    12: "Summer takes hold — 20°C, long sunny evenings, and Queenstown at full festive throttle for the holidays. Lake Wakatipu is warm enough for swimming, the Skyline Gondola and Luge are packed, and the New Year's Eve celebrations with the Remarkables as backdrop are spectacular. Book everything months ahead; this is peak of peaks.",
  },

  'om-desert': {
    1: "January is Oman's desert paradise — 25°C in the interior, cool nights perfect for camping among the Wahiba Sands dunes, and the Jebel Akhdar rose gardens dormant but the mountain hiking at its most comfortable. The Empty Quarter's silence at night under a billion stars is a spiritual experience that no luxury tent can improve upon.",
    2: "February stays cool and ideal for desert exploration — the Wahiba Sands are comfortable for camelback excursions, the wadis (Wadi Shab, Wadi Bani Khalid) have water for swimming, and the Jebel Shams (Oman's Grand Canyon) hiking is at its prime. Daytime highs of 27°C feel luxurious without air conditioning.",
    3: "March is the last comfortable month before the heat builds — 30°C in the desert, the wadis are flowing with late-season water, and the rose harvest in Jebel Akhdar begins. The Wahiba Sands dunes shift colour from gold to amber in the intensifying sunlight, and Bedouin desert camps operate at full hospitality.",
    4: "April heats up noticeably — 34°C in the lowlands, but the mountains remain comfortable for hiking. The damask rose harvest peaks in Jebel Akhdar (the rosewater production is fascinating), and the desert camps start operating mainly at dawn and dusk to avoid the midday heat. The wadis are a blessed escape.",
    5: "May pushes to 40°C in the desert — this is serious heat, and outdoor activities shift to very early mornings and evenings. The Wahiba Sands campfires still feel magical at night as temperatures drop, and the mountain villages of Jebel Akhdar stay cooler at altitude. Only heat-tolerant travelers will enjoy this month.",
    6: "Summer arrives with a vengeance — 43°C+ in the desert interior, and the landscape shimmers with heat mirages. The Wahiba Sands are for hardy souls only, the wadis are drying up, and even the mountain highlands are warm. This is Oman's deep off-season: prices drop dramatically, but the heat is genuinely dangerous without precautions.",
    7: "July is the hottest month — the desert hits 45°C+ and even the mountains feel warm. The Dhofar region (far south) is the exception, where the Khareef monsoon brings miraculous green mists. If you're determined to visit interior Oman, pre-dawn dune bashing and nocturnal stargazing are the only sane activities.",
    8: "August matches July's extreme heat in the desert and mountains — this is survival territory, not tourism. The Khareef continues greening Dhofar in the south (Salalah becomes a domestic escape), but the rest of Oman's interior is essentially dormant. Air-conditioned museums in Nizwa and the mountain villages provide the only comfortable experiences.",
    9: "September starts cooling marginally — 40°C is still hot by any standard, but the desert evenings become more bearable. The Wahiba Sands camps begin stirring back to life, and the wadis see the first trickles of water. The shoulder-season pricing makes this appealing for budget travelers with heat tolerance.",
    10: "October is the transition — 35°C feels almost pleasant after summer, the desert camps fully reopen, and the wadi swimming returns as water levels build. Jebel Akhdar's pomegranate harvest adds agricultural charm, the Wahiba Sands sunrises are spectacular in the cooling air, and the tourism infrastructure awakens.",
    11: "November clicks into prime season — 30°C, the desert is comfortable again, the wadis are flowing, and the Wahiba Sands camps operate at full capacity. The mountain hiking on Jebel Shams and Jebel Akhdar is excellent, the stargazing from the desert is world-class, and the Bedouin hospitality is as warm as the sunset light on the dunes.",
    12: "December is peak desert season — 25°C days, cool nights ideal for dune camping, and every wadi and mountain trail at its best. National Day celebrations (November 18, but festivities linger) add cultural colour, the desert sky is crystal-clear for astronomy, and Oman delivers Arabian hospitality at its most refined and understated.",
  },

  'om-muscat': {
    1: "January in Muscat is as good as it gets — 25°C, zero rain, and the Indian Ocean at a comfortable 24°C for swimming and diving. The Sultan Qaboos Grand Mosque gleams under clear skies, the Muttrah Souq is atmospheric without the summer heat, and the dolphin-watching tours in the Gulf of Oman are reliable.",
    2: "February stays perfection — 26°C, calm seas ideal for dhow cruises and snorkeling at the Daymaniyat Islands, and the frankincense-scented air of the Muttrah Corniche is at its most enjoyable. Musandam Peninsula (a day trip or overnight) delivers fjord-like scenery with dolphins. This is Oman's peak tourism window.",
    3: "March warms to 29°C but remains excellent — the beaches at Qurum and Al Bustan are pristine, the diving at the Daymaniyat Islands hits peak visibility, and the waterfront dining along the Corniche is magical at sunset. The heat is building but manageable, and most tourist attractions remain comfortable.",
    4: "April marks the transition — 33°C, the last comfortable month for outdoor exploration. Turtle nesting season begins at Ras al Jinz (a spectacular experience), the sea stays warm and diveable, and the opera season at the Royal Opera House Muscat wraps up. Book that mountain escape to Jebel Akhdar before the summer shutdown.",
    5: "May ramps to 38°C and Muscat starts wilting — the seaside still has a breeze, but exploring the old town and souq in the midday heat is punishing. Turtle nesting at Ras al Jinz continues (a nighttime activity, conveniently), and the restaurant scene along Qurum Beach caters to the heat with evening-only outdoor dining.",
    6: "June brings full summer — 40°C+, the city empties of tourists, and the shopping malls become the social hub. The sea is warm (30°C) but the air above it is hotter, creating a steam-room beach experience. This is deep off-season Muscat: hotel deals are excellent if you can handle the furnace-blast heat.",
    7: "July is Muscat at its most extreme — 42°C with humidity creeping up as the distant Khareef monsoon affects atmospheric patterns. The city operates nocturnally: shopping, dining, and socialising happen after dark. The diving is still possible early morning, but this is fundamentally an indoor month. Omanis who can afford to leave, do.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 42°C, high humidity, and an outdoor environment that's genuinely hostile. The malls, museums (National Museum is excellent), and air-conditioned restaurants are your world. If you're transiting through, the Sultan Qaboos Mosque is stunning at dawn before the heat builds, and the Muttrah Souq is atmospheric even empty.",
    9: "September begins the long cool-down — still 38°C but the humidity drops and evenings become marginally more bearable. The turtle nesting at Ras al Jinz is active, the diving shows improved visibility, and the first brave tourists start returning. Shoulder-season pricing makes the few open attractions affordable.",
    10: "October finally feels like progress — 34°C, Muscat's outdoor life starts stirring, and the Corniche walking path becomes usable in the evening. Whale shark season begins in the Gulf of Oman (October through February), the Daymaniyat Islands reopen for diving, and the cultural calendar restarts with gallery openings and events.",
    11: "November is the grand reopening — 30°C, the National Day celebrations (November 18) fill Muscat with patriotic decorations and cultural events, and every restaurant, beach club, and diving operator is back at full capacity. The whale sharks are feeding close to shore, the Muttrah Souq is buzzing, and the sunset over the Gulf of Oman is pure copper.",
    12: "December is peak Muscat — 26°C, crystal-clear skies, and the city at its most polished and welcoming. The Sultan Qaboos Mosque is magnificent in the winter light, whale shark encounters are at their best, and the Muttrah Corniche evening promenade is a window into Omani social life. Holiday visitors push hotel prices up, but the weather earns every rial.",
  },

  'pa-bocas': {
    1: "January is Bocas del Toro's brief dry window — the rain drops to its lowest (though 'dry' in Caribbean Panama is relative), the turquoise waters around the archipelago are calm for snorkeling, and the reggae-inflected island pace sets the tone. Red Frog Beach and Starfish Beach are accessible and relatively uncrowded.",
    2: "February stays relatively dry and warm at 30°C — the Caribbean water is bathtub-warm, the coral reefs off Zapatilla Cays are at peak visibility, and the overwater bungalows that define Bocas are at their most enjoyable. San Blas Archipelago to the east is accessible and pristine for island-hopping among the Guna communities.",
    3: "March brings increasingly wet weather as the rainy season approaches, but the islands still deliver plenty of sunshine between showers. The sloth sanctuary on Isla Colón is active year-round, the seafood patacones are best eaten ocean-side, and the San Blas islands remain paradise-level for sailing and snorkeling.",
    4: "April kicks off the rainy season — afternoon downpours become daily events, but mornings are bright, warm, and perfect for reef snorkeling. The jungle canopy on Isla Bastimentos National Marine Park is at its most alive with red frogs, sloths, and howler monkeys. Prices drop as the wet season deters fair-weather visitors.",
    5: "May is wet and green — heavy tropical rain, the islands lush to bursting, and the Caribbean Sea still warm and diveable between storms. The Guna communities in San Blas maintain their traditional way of life regardless of weather, and visiting during the wet season feels more authentic and less performative.",
    6: "June surprises with a brief dry spell — the 'veranillo' (little summer) brings a welcome week or two of sunshine to Bocas, making it the best rainy-season month to visit. The ocean is warm, the reef fish are abundant, and the island nightlife in Bocas Town runs on island time and cold beer.",
    7: "July is solidly wet — heavy Caribbean rain, rough seas occasionally, and the archipelago at its quietest. But the jungle walks on Bastimentos are atmospheric in the rain, the sloths don't care about the weather, and a hammock under a thatched roof with the sound of rain on the Caribbean is surprisingly addictive.",
    8: "August continues the rain with occasional heavy storms, but the surfing at Bluff Beach on Isla Colón picks up with Caribbean swells. The overwater bungalows provide the perfect rain-proof retreat, and the local chocolate tours on the mainland (Bocas del Drago) are fascinating regardless of conditions.",
    9: "September and October are the wettest months — serious rainfall that can disrupt boat schedules and make some trails impassable. But the San Blas islands stay accessible, the reef snorkeling between storms is excellent, and the green season pricing makes Caribbean Panama accessible on a backpacker budget.",
    10: "October peaks the rainfall — rivers swell, the jungle canopy drips constantly, and Bocas del Toro feels like an aquatic world where the line between ocean and sky dissolves. The adventurous are rewarded with deserted beaches, dramatic sunsets through rain clouds, and locals who appreciate off-season visitors.",
    11: "November brings the last heavy rains before the dry season — the islands start drying out in the second half, the seas calm, and the reef visibility improves weekly. Thanksgiving week brings a small bump of American visitors, but Bocas remains laid-back and affordable. The frogs, sloths, and monkeys don't wait for sunshine.",
    12: "December clicks toward dry season — the Christmas crowd arrives as the rain retreats, the Caribbean waters settle to crystal clarity, and Bocas del Toro's beachfront bars and restaurants hit peak festive mode. New Year's Eve in Bocas Town is legendary — barefoot on the beach, reggaeton and fireworks over the water.",
  },

  'pa-city': {
    1: "Dry season in Panama City — 32°C, clear skies, and the Pacific side at its most sparkling. The Canal locks at Miraflores are best viewed in the morning light, Casco Viejo's restored colonial streets buzz with rooftop bars, and the Frank Gehry-designed BioMuseo gleams against blue sky. The causeway walk is pleasant before noon.",
    2: "February continues perfect dry-season conditions — Carnival weekend (if it falls here) transforms the city into a massive street party with water trucks, music, and dancing. The Panama Canal transit vessels are visible daily, the seafood ceviche at the fish market is impeccable, and Casco Viejo's nightlife peaks.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot — 33°C with the last weeks of reliable sunshine before the rains. The Canal's new Agua Clara locks on the Atlantic side make for an excellent day trip, Casco Viejo's jazz bars and restaurants are vibrant, and the indigenous Emberá communities on the Chagres River welcome dry-season visitors.",
    4: "April marks the transition — the first afternoon storms appear, humidity rises, and the city starts its green transformation. Semana Santa brings holiday energy and processions through Casco Viejo, the Canal operates rain or shine (obviously), and the rooftop bars add a dramatic storm-watching dimension to cocktail hour.",
    5: "The rainy season arrives — daily afternoon deluges that clear by evening, leaving the city steaming and fragrant. The Metropolitano Natural Park (a rainforest inside the city) comes alive with toucans and sloths, the Canal vessel traffic continues regardless, and Panama City's indoor scene (restaurants, casinos, museums) absorbs the rain effortlessly.",
    6: "Full rainy season at 31°C with heavy daily storms — the surrounding rainforest explodes with wildlife, the Canal's Gatun Lake fills to capacity, and the city's modern skyline looks dramatic against thunderheads. The food scene is year-round excellent, and a wet-season visit to Casco Viejo's restaurants means no wait for the best tables.",
    7: "July is wet but the city's energy doesn't dim — Panama's cosmopolitan character means air-conditioned malls, world-class restaurants, and cultural events regardless of weather. The Canal is fascinating in the rain, the BioMuseo is a perfect indoor destination, and prices are at their most reasonable for the quality on offer.",
    8: "August continues the rains with tropical intensity — the Chagres River runs high for adventurous kayaking, the Metropolitan Park trails are lush but muddy, and the city's economic hub (Panama's banking sector) keeps the restaurant and bar scene buzzing through any weather. Whale migration begins in the Gulf of Panama.",
    9: "September-October is the wettest period — 200mm+ monthly, but the humpback whale season in the Gulf of Panama and the Pearl Islands is spectacular (July through October). The Canal boats keep sliding through, Casco Viejo is atmospheric in the rain, and the low tourist numbers mean you'll get genuine interactions with proud Panamanians.",
    10: "October brings the heaviest rains and the tail end of whale season — the Gulf of Panama delivers humpback sightings, the city's jazz and arts festivals provide indoor entertainment, and the Canal's operations are endlessly fascinating to watch from the Miraflores visitor centre, rain or shine.",
    11: "November signals the rainy season's retreat — the skies clear, the air freshens, and Panama City starts its dry-season preening. Independence celebrations (November 3, 10, 28) fill the month with parades and patriotic energy, and the rooftop bars in Casco Viejo celebrate the return of sunset views.",
    12: "December brings dry season back with a bang — 31°C, clear skies, and the holiday energy of a city that knows how to celebrate. The Canal is pristine for visits, Casco Viejo's Christmas decorations are beautiful against the colonial architecture, and the cosmopolitan restaurant scene peaks with festive menus and visiting diaspora.",
  },

  'pe-amazon': {
    1: "January is the heart of the wet season in the Peruvian Amazon — the rivers are high, the jungle is at maximum lush, and the canoe trips through flooded forest near Iquitos reveal a world where trees grow from water. Pink river dolphins surface regularly, and the birdlife is extraordinary. Expect daily rain, 32°C heat, and mosquitoes that mean business.",
    2: "February continues the flood season — the Amazon and its tributaries swell to their peak, making canoe exploration through the flooded várzea forest the primary activity. The wildlife concentrates in the canopy (monkeys, macaws, toucans are everywhere), and the Pacaya-Samiria National Reserve is at its most accessible by water. Rain gear is your second skin.",
    3: "March is peak flood — the rivers are at their highest, entire forest floors are submerged, and the canoe journeys through this aquatic jungle world are unforgettable. Piranha fishing in the flooded tributaries is excellent (they're hungry), pink dolphins play near the lodge docks, and the humidity is tropical-extreme. Not for the faint of heart.",
    4: "April begins the slow recession — water levels start dropping, the rain eases slightly, and the jungle floor begins emerging from its annual bath. The transitional period means good fishing, active wildlife as animals adapt to changing water levels, and slightly fewer mosquitoes. Iquitos's market (Belén) is a sensory overload of jungle produce.",
    5: "May is the transition month — the dry season establishes itself, river levels drop revealing beaches and banks, and the jungle trails become walkable again. The wildlife is exceptional as animals that were dispersed through the flooded forest now concentrate along rivers. The heat stays at 31°C but humidity drops noticeably.",
    6: "June marks the dry season — lower rivers, exposed trails, and the Amazon at its most accessible for hiking and land-based wildlife spotting. Night walks reveal tarantulas, tree frogs, and the occasional caiman, while daytime canoe trips deliver macaw clay-lick sightings. Iquitos's vibrant nightlife scene helps process the jungle experiences.",
    7: "July is prime Amazon time — the driest month with minimal rain, comfortable 30°C days (by jungle standards), and the wildlife concentrated along shrinking waterways. The river dolphins are easier to spot in the lower water, caiman night-spotting is reliable, and the jungle lodges operate at full capacity. Book ahead for the best operations.",
    8: "August extends dry-season perfection — the rivers reach their lowest levels, the fishing is outstanding (peacock bass season), and the hiking trails through terra firme forest are at their most navigable. The Pacaya-Samiria reserve offers deep-jungle experiences, and the mosquitoes are at their least oppressive. Peak tourist season means premium lodge rates.",
    9: "September is the dry season's last act — the rivers are still low, the wildlife viewing remains excellent, and the first hints of returning rain green up the forest edges. The jungle sunset over the Amazon from a lodge hammock is a cliché because it's perfect. Crowds ease from August's peak, and the guides have more time for you.",
    10: "October signals the wet season's return — afternoon storms build, the rivers start rising, and the jungle shifts gears. The transitional period offers both trail hiking (still possible) and early canoe exploration as the water creeps back. The birdlife is spectacular with residents and migrants overlapping, and the heat intensifies with humidity.",
    11: "November brings the rains back properly — the jungle drinks deeply, the rivers swell, and the flooded forest begins its annual transformation. The canoeing is already excellent, the mosquitoes return with enthusiasm, and the pink dolphins are active in the rising waters. This is raw, uncurated Amazon — bring good rain gear and an appetite for adventure.",
    12: "December is full wet season — heavy daily rain, rising rivers, and the jungle at its most intense. The canoe trips through emerging flood forest are magical, the Christmas celebrations in Iquitos blend Catholic and indigenous traditions, and the wildlife (river dolphins, macaws, monkeys) is reliably spectacular. The humidity is relentless but the experience is unmatched.",
  },

  'pe-cusco': {
    1: "January in the Sacred Valley is wet season — daily afternoon storms drench the ancient stones, the hills are vivid green, and the Inca Trail is closed for annual maintenance. Cusco at 3,400m is cold (12°C) and rainy but hauntingly beautiful with fewer tourists, and the ruins of Sacsayhuamán are atmospheric in the mist. Altitude sickness is real — take your coca tea seriously.",
    2: "February is the wettest month — the Sacred Valley rivers run brown with runoff, landslides can disrupt road travel, and the Inca Trail remains closed. But Cusco's colonial churches and museums (Qorikancha, the Chocolate Museum) are perfect indoor escapes, the local food scene serves warming soups and stews, and the reduced crowds mean genuine interaction with Cusqueños.",
    3: "March is the tail end of the rainy season — showers continue but the sun breaks through more often, and the Inca Trail reopens mid-month. The Sacred Valley's Moray agricultural terraces and Maras salt mines are stunning against the green landscape, and the first trekking groups head toward Machu Picchu. Altitude acclimatization in Cusco takes 2-3 days — don't skip it.",
    4: "April marks the transition — rain drops sharply, the skies clear, and Cusco and the Sacred Valley reveal themselves in sharp Andean light. The Inca Trail is open and relatively uncrowded, Machu Picchu is accessible without the peak-season crush, and the hiking conditions are excellent with lush trails and clear mountain views. This is the savvy trekker's window.",
    5: "May locks in the dry season — clear blue skies, cold nights (minus 1°C in Cusco), and the Sacred Valley at its most photogenic. The Inca Trail and alternative treks (Salkantay, Lares) are in prime condition, Machu Picchu is busy but not overwhelming, and the hillside agricultural terraces glow golden in the harvest season. Layer for the temperature swings.",
    6: "June is Cusco's marquee month — Inti Raymi (Festival of the Sun, June 24) brings a massive Inca re-enactment to Sacsayhuamán, the dry season is in full effect, and the mountain views from every angle are razor-sharp. This is peak season: the Inca Trail books out months ahead, Machu Picchu hits its visitor cap daily, and prices are at their highest.",
    7: "July is peak-season Cusco — bone-dry, cold nights (minus 3°C), spectacular clear days, and tourists everywhere. Fiestas Patrias (Peruvian Independence Day, July 28) adds domestic crowds to the international ones. Machu Picchu is at maximum capacity — book permits months ahead. The alternative treks offer slightly more breathing room and equally stunning Andean scenery.",
    8: "August continues peak conditions — dry, cold, and clear. The Inca Trail is fully booked, the Sacred Valley is golden-brown between harvest and planting, and the night sky above Cusco's colonial rooftops is astronomically spectacular. The Pachamama celebrations and local festivals add cultural depth beyond the ruins. Bring your warmest layers for pre-dawn temple visits.",
    9: "September eases the crowds while keeping the dry-season weather — clear skies, warming temperatures (15°C), and the first spring flowers appearing in the Sacred Valley. The Inca Trail is more accessible without the July-August peak demand, and Machu Picchu in the morning mist without the summer hordes is genuinely transcendent. Smart timing.",
    10: "October is the transition back — the first rain showers appear, the hillsides start greening, and the trekking season begins its wind-down. The Sacred Valley's agricultural rhythm is visible as planting begins, the Machu Picchu crowds thin, and the combination of clearing storms and Andean light creates extraordinary photography conditions.",
    11: "November brings increasing rain — afternoon storms become daily events, some trails get muddy, and the crowds thin to low-season levels. But the Sacred Valley is turning green, Cusco's San Blas neighbourhood is cosy with artists and cafés, and the ruins at Pisac and Ollantaytambo are dramatic in storm light. Prices drop and availability opens up.",
    12: "December is wet season — daily rain, green valley floors, and Cusco's Christmas celebrations (Santuranticuy market on December 24) filling the Plaza de Armas with handcrafted nativity scenes. The Inca Trail is open but muddy, Machu Picchu visits require rain gear, and the cold-and-damp combination makes a warm alpaca sweater from the San Pedro Market the best souvenir in Peru.",
  },

  'pe-lima': {
    1: "Lima's summer is here — 28°C, sunny skies over the Pacific, and the garúa fog that defines the city in winter nowhere to be seen. The beaches at Miraflores and Barranco fill with surfers and sunbathers, the ceviche at La Mar is at its most refreshing, and the Malecón cliffside walk offers unobstructed ocean views. Peak domestic holiday season.",
    2: "February peaks the summer — 29°C, the warmest month, and Lima's coastal energy is at full volume. The surfing at Punta Hermosa is excellent, the Barranco neighbourhood's street art and bars buzz every evening, and Peru's gastronomic capital delivers its bounty: ceviche, lomo saltado, and pisco sours on every corner.",
    3: "March stays warm at 27°C as summer winds down — the beaches are still viable, the crowds ease after holiday season, and the food scene (arguably South America's best) operates without the February frenzy. The Museo Larco's pre-Columbian collection is magnificent any time, and the Pacific sunsets from Costa Verde are legendary.",
    4: "Autumn arrives and Lima's personality shifts — 24°C, the first morning mists appear, and the city settles into its intellectual, gastronomic mode. Mistura food festival season approaches, the Barranco galleries have new exhibitions, and the surfing stays consistent along the coast. A sophisticated month for a sophisticated city.",
    5: "May brings the garúa — Lima's famous coastal fog rolls in, dropping temps to 20°C and blanketing the city in grey. It sounds depressing, but the locals embrace it: the food scene pivots to warming dishes, the museums and cultural life intensify, and the city's bohemian Barranco district feels properly atmospheric and artistic.",
    6: "Winter fog dominates — 17°C, grey skies, and the garúa drizzle that never quite becomes rain but always threatens. Lima's indoor life flourishes: world-class restaurants (Central, Maido), colonial churches in the Historic Centre, the catacombs beneath San Francisco, and the literary cafés of Miraflores. Bring a jacket; the damp cold is deceptive.",
    7: "July is Lima's greyest month — the fog is thick, the Pacific waves are big for surfers (wetsuit required at 16°C water), and Fiestas Patrias (July 28-29) brings patriotic celebrations, military parades, and anticuchos on every street corner. The city is atmospheric in its winter mode, and the pisco sours taste better when it's cold outside.",
    8: "August continues winter's grey embrace — the garúa persists, the temperatures hover at 16°C, and Lima doubles down on its indoor strengths: gastronomy, galleries, and that particular coastal melancholy that inspires poets. The Mistura food festival (Latin America's largest) often falls this month, drawing chefs and food lovers from across the continent.",
    9: "September begins Lima's slow awakening — the fog starts thinning, the sun breaks through more often, and the temperature creeps toward 18°C. The city's spring energy builds: Barranco's street art gets new additions, the surfing conditions are excellent with powerful winter swells, and the anticipation of summer brightens the mood.",
    10: "Spring arrives — 20°C, the garúa retreats, and Lima's parks (El Olivar, Parque Kennedy) fill with flowers. The Pacific shows its blue again, the paragliders launch from the Miraflores cliffs, and the rooftop restaurants reopen their terraces. The food scene (it's always the food scene) serves seasonal ceviche with corvina at its freshest.",
    11: "November warms to 22°C with increasing sunshine — the beaches start filling on weekends, the Pacific warms enough for wetsuit-free surfing (barely), and the city's outdoor energy returns. The Malecón walkway is alive with joggers and couples, Barranco's oceanfront bars are open-air again, and the ceviche calls louder than ever.",
    12: "Summer begins — 25°C, clear skies, and Lima shaking off its winter grey with palpable relief. The beaches fill, the surfing is excellent, and the Christmas decorations in Miraflores and the Historic Centre are elegant. Lima's food scene doesn't have an off season, but eating fresh tiradito on a sunny Barranco terrace in December hits different.",
  },

  'pf-tahiti': {
    1: "Wet season in paradise — 30°C, afternoon tropical downpours, and Bora Bora's lagoon still that impossible shade of turquoise between storms. The overwater bungalows are slightly more affordable (slightly — this is Tahiti), the reef sharks and manta rays are active, and the humid air smells of tiare flowers and wet frangipani.",
    2: "February is the wettest month — heavy tropical rain and occasional cyclone risk, but the lagoons are warm (29°C), the diving is excellent with improved marine life activity, and the crowd levels are at their lowest. Tahiti's Heiva cultural rehearsals begin in preparation for July's festival, and the fresh poisson cru tastes extraordinary in any weather.",
    3: "March continues the wet season with moderating rainfall — the storms are less frequent, the lagoons clear between showers, and the surf season on Tahiti's reef breaks (Teahupo'o) is building toward its legendary peak. The islands are lush, the pace is unhurried, and the vanilla harvest in Taha'a begins scenting the entire island.",
    4: "April transitions toward the dry season — rain eases, the seas calm, and the lagoons of Bora Bora, Moorea, and Rangiroa return to postcard perfection. The whale sharks begin appearing at Tikehau atoll, the diving visibility improves weekly, and the warm 28°C water makes every snorkeling session feel like a nature documentary.",
    5: "May is shoulder season at its finest — the rain has largely stopped, 28°C sunshine prevails, and the tourist crowds haven't yet peaked. Moorea's pineapple and tropical fruit season is in full swing, the humpback whales begin arriving from Antarctica, and the Tuamotu atolls (Rangiroa, Fakarava) offer wall diving that rivals anywhere on Earth.",
    6: "Dry season proper — 27°C, clear skies, and the humpback whales now reliably in French Polynesian waters. The overwater bungalow experience at Bora Bora is at its most flawless, Teahupo'o surf break comes alive with massive swells, and the lagoon snorkeling across the Society Islands is crystal-clear. Prices climb with the weather.",
    7: "July is Heiva season — Tahiti's month-long festival of Polynesian dance, music, and culture is one of the Pacific's greatest celebrations, and the performances are electrifying. The weather is dry, the whales are everywhere, and the diving at Rangiroa's Tiputa Pass delivers dolphin encounters and shark wall dives. Peak season pricing, but culturally unmissable.",
    8: "August extends peak conditions — dry, the humpback whales performing breaches and spy-hops across every lagoon, and the surf at Teahupo'o reaching its terrifying maximum. The atolls are pristine for diving, Moorea's Cook's Bay is postcard-perfect, and the evening Polynesian dance shows at the resorts are a window into a living culture.",
    9: "September is the connoisseur's month — the whales are still present, the weather stays dry at 27°C, but the peak crowds ease and prices soften. The diving at Fakarava's south pass delivers grey reef shark walls by the hundreds, the lagoons are calm and clear, and the manta ray encounters at Tikehau are at their most reliable.",
    10: "October is the dry-to-wet transition — the last reliable dry month with whales making their final appearances before heading south. The surf at Teahupo'o winds down, the lagoons are warm and inviting, and the tourist density drops to manageable levels. An excellent value month with near-peak conditions.",
    11: "November brings the first wet-season showers — warm rain, building humidity, and the whale season officially ending. The lagoons remain beautiful between storms, the manta rays and reef sharks are active year-round, and the overwater bungalow prices start their descent toward wet-season rates. Bring a sense of flexibility.",
    12: "December is warm and wet — 30°C with daily tropical showers, but the holiday crowd arrives for Christmas in paradise. Bora Bora's resorts hit peak pricing despite the rain, Moorea offers a slightly more grounded alternative, and the New Year's Eve celebrations under palm trees with Polynesian drums beating are unforgettable. Cyclone awareness is prudent.",
  },

  'pg-png': {
    1: "January sits in the wet season — 30°C with heavy rain across much of Papua New Guinea, though the Highlands get a relative dry spell making festival visits feasible. The diving around Rabaul and Kimbe Bay is excellent year-round, the coral reefs are among the world's least-visited, and the cultural diversity (800+ languages) defies comprehension.",
    2: "February continues the wet season with the heaviest rainfall — rivers swell, some highland roads become impassable, and the lowland rainforest is at its most alive (and leech-infested). The WWII wreck diving at Rabaul is outstanding regardless of weather, and the reef systems off Milne Bay deliver some of the best macro diving on Earth.",
    3: "March rain begins easing in some regions — the Sepik River is high (great for longhouse village visits by canoe), the Highlands are transitioning, and the coastal diving continues to astound. PNG is not easy travel — infrastructure is minimal, safety requires awareness, and the rewards (uncontacted cultures, pristine reefs, volcanic landscapes) are proportional to the effort.",
    4: "April brings the dry season's first hints to the Highlands — the Wahgi Valley starts drying, trekking conditions improve, and the cultural sing-sings (ceremonial gatherings) begin appearing on the calendar. The Kokoda Track becomes more feasible, and the diving at Kimbe Bay is at peak clarity. This is adventure travel for the committed.",
    5: "May establishes drier conditions across much of PNG — the Highlands are accessible, the Kokoda Track is in its best shape, and the cultural encounters in the Sepik and Highlands regions are extraordinary. The diving remains world-class, the bird-of-paradise displays are active in the highland forests, and you'll be one of very few visitors.",
    6: "June is prime time for PNG — the dry season is established, the Highlands festivals are in full swing, and the trekking conditions on the Kokoda Track are optimal. The Mt. Hagen Show (if scheduled) is one of the world's greatest cultural spectacles, with hundreds of tribes in full ceremonial regalia. The diving never stops being incredible.",
    7: "July continues peak conditions — dry weather, cultural festivals, and the Goroka Show (one of PNG's signature events) bringing together dozens of highland tribes in spectacular bilas (body decoration). The trekking is excellent, the birdwatching for birds-of-paradise is productive, and the reef diving is at its clearest. Book guides well ahead.",
    8: "August extends the dry season's bounty — excellent trekking, diving, and cultural encounters across the country. The Sepik River is lower and navigable, the highland air is cool and pleasant (15°C at 2,000m), and the WWII memorial sites along the Kokoda Track are powerfully moving in the clear weather.",
    9: "September is the dry season's last reliable month — the Hiri Moale Festival in Port Moresby celebrates Papuan maritime culture with traditional lagatoi sailing canoes. The diving at Milne Bay and Kimbe Bay remains outstanding, and the final highland festivals of the season provide cultural experiences that are genuinely life-changing.",
    10: "October signals the wet season's return — rain builds, some highland tracks become muddy, and the diving conditions start shifting. The coral reefs are still spectacular, the lowland rainforest explodes with new growth, and the country's wild, untamed character is most apparent in the transition months when plans require constant flexibility.",
    11: "November brings heavier rain across most of PNG — the rivers swell, the jungle canopy drips, and the adventurous find that the reduced accessibility makes everything feel more remote and authentic. The diving never disappoints (Kimbe Bay's reefs are year-round wonders), and the birdlife is active in the wet forest canopy.",
    12: "December is deep wet season — heavy rain, challenging travel logistics, and the country's remotest regions becoming more isolated. But the coral reefs don't care about rain, the WWII wreck diving at Rabaul is atmospheric in any conditions, and a Christmas spent in a highland village witnessing the meeting of Melanesian and Christian traditions is profoundly moving.",
  },

  'ph-batanes': {
    1: "January in Batanes is the tail end of the amihan (northeast monsoon) — blustery winds, 24°C, and dramatic seas crashing against the island's volcanic cliffs. The rolling green hills of Batan Island look like a Southeast Asian Ireland, the stone houses of Ivatan villages are built to withstand typhoons, and the handful of visitors get these breathtaking landscapes to themselves.",
    2: "February stays windy and cool at 23°C — the driest month, with clear skies between gusts revealing views across the Bashi Channel toward Taiwan. The Ivatan fishing culture (vakul hats, stone houses, dried flying fish) is fascinating, and the hiking trails across Batan and Sabtang islands are at their most navigable.",
    3: "March brings calmer seas and warming temperatures to 25°C — the boat crossings to Sabtang Island become more reliable, the rolling hills are vivid green, and the lack of tourists means genuine encounters with Ivatan communities. The traditional stone boat shelters and cliff-edge villages feel like stepping back centuries.",
    4: "April is Batanes' transition to calmer weather — 27°C, reduced winds, and the most comfortable conditions for exploring. The iconic Marlboro Hills (Racuh a Payaman) are breathtaking, the lighthouse at Basco offers panoramic views, and the flying fish season delivers the freshest uvud (dried fish) at every family table.",
    5: "May brings summer heat (29°C) and the calmest seas of the year — island hopping between Batan, Sabtang, and Itbayat is most reliable now. The landscape is a rolling patchwork of green pastures and dramatic coastline, the honesty coffee shops (leave payment in a box) embody the Ivatan spirit, and the sunsets over the West Philippine Sea are legendary.",
    6: "June introduces the habagat (southwest monsoon) with increasing rain and the first whispers of typhoon season. The islands remain accessible and stunningly green at 28°C, but flight cancellations become possible. The dramatic weather adds atmosphere to the already cinematic landscapes — think moody clouds rolling over volcanic peaks.",
    7: "July is deep into typhoon season — flights are frequently disrupted, the seas are rough, and visiting requires serious flexibility. When the weather cooperates, the islands are spectacularly lush and nearly empty of tourists. The Ivatan people's typhoon resilience (those stone houses survive Category 5) is genuinely awe-inspiring.",
    8: "August matches July's typhoon risk — this is the peak danger month, and Batanes' extreme northern position makes it the first Philippine province hit by storms from the Pacific. Travel insurance and flexible dates are absolutely essential. Between storms, the islands are hauntingly beautiful in the storm-washed light.",
    9: "September continues typhoon season with heavy rain and rough seas — Batanes in the rain is dramatic and beautiful, but getting there (and leaving) can be challenging. The rolling hills are at maximum green, the waterfalls thunder, and the few travelers who make it experience an authentic, weather-tested Ivatan hospitality.",
    10: "October brings the last serious typhoon risk and the transition back to the amihan winds. The weather is unpredictable but the island's rugged beauty is undeniable — storm-cleared skies reveal razor-sharp views across the island chain. The flying fish season is active, and the stone villages are atmospheric in the autumn light.",
    11: "November eases into the amihan season — winds pick up, rains diminish, and the islands take on that windswept, Atlantic-feeling quality that makes Batanes so unique in the Philippines. The hiking trails are excellent, the seas remain choppy but crossings to Sabtang are feasible, and the cool 25°C air is a revelation after tropical Manila.",
    12: "December is windy but clear — 24°C, the amihan blowing steadily, and the Christmas celebrations in the Ivatan communities are intimate and genuine. The landscapes are green and dramatic, the tourist numbers are minimal, and a few days in Batanes at year's end feels like pressing reset on your entire concept of the Philippines.",
  },

  'ph-cebu-bohol': {
    1: "January is the tail end of the amihan dry season — 30°C, the waters around Moalboal and Oslob are calm and clear for diving with sardine balls and (controversially) whale sharks. Bohol's Chocolate Hills are brown and postcard-perfect, the tarsier sanctuary is active, and the Sinulog Festival in Cebu City (third Sunday) is one of the Philippines' most spectacular celebrations.",
    2: "February is peak dry season — blue skies, warm calm seas, and Cebu's dive sites at maximum visibility. The island hopping from Moalboal to Pescador Island delivers walls of sardines and sea turtles, Bohol's river cruises through the jungle are idyllic, and the Panglao Island beaches are pristine. Book ahead for the popular dive resorts.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot at 32°C — the seas are calm, the beaches are packed with domestic holiday crowds (summer break begins), and the diving is outstanding. Bohol's Hinagdanan Cave swimming hole is refreshing, the Chocolate Hills viewpoint is panoramic, and the ferry between Cebu and Bohol is reliable and scenic.",
    4: "April is the transition — the dry season holds but the humidity builds, and Semana Santa brings reflective processions through Cebu's colonial churches. The island hopping remains excellent, the Kawasan Falls canyoneering in Moalboal is at its most popular, and the tiny tarsiers at Bohol's sanctuary are wide-eyed and nocturnal as ever.",
    5: "May ushers in the wet season — the first afternoon showers arrive, but the mornings stay sunny and the seas remain diveable. Flores de Mayo celebrations drape churches in flowers, the waterfalls across both islands are gaining power, and the tourist numbers thin as the shoulder season offers better value on beachfront accommodation.",
    6: "June brings regular rain — the habagat monsoon delivers afternoon storms, but the diving around Moalboal and Panglao stays productive with warm 29°C water and active marine life. The Chocolate Hills turn green (hence the name's dry-season origin), and the Philippine school year means fewer domestic tourists and more local character.",
    7: "July is wet but warm at 31°C — the canyoneering at Kawasan Falls is more thrilling with higher water, the diving visibility varies but the marine life is abundant, and the island pace slows to something genuinely relaxing. The few tourists get better attention from guides and better deals from resorts.",
    8: "August brings the heaviest typhoon risk — while Cebu and Bohol's central Visayas position offers some protection, disruptions are possible. Between weather events, the reef diving is excellent, the Chocolate Hills are at their greenest, and the Aloguinsan River ecotourism experience is at its most lush.",
    9: "September continues the wet season with the highest rainfall — the waterfalls are spectacular, the jungle is dense and alive, and the diving operators run year-round for those willing to work around afternoon storms. The typhoon risk is real but the value is excellent, with empty resorts and deeply discounted rates.",
    10: "October is peak typhoon month for the Visayas — travel requires flexibility and insurance. On calm days, the diving around Pescador Island and Balicasag is world-class, and the rain-washed Chocolate Hills landscape is beautifully lush. The wet season's tail end brings some of the year's most dramatic sunset light.",
    11: "November transitions back toward the amihan — rains ease, seas calm, and the dive sites start clearing up beautifully. The tourist numbers begin building for the Christmas season, Sinulog Festival preparations start in Cebu City, and Bohol's Panglao beaches emerge from the wet season looking pristine and uncrowded.",
    12: "December brings the dry season back — clear skies, calm warm seas, and the Christmas celebrations that Filipinos do better than almost anyone. Cebu's malls and churches are elaborately decorated, Bohol's river cruises are scenic and reliable, and the diving conditions improve daily. Holiday crowds build, but the festive warmth is infectious.",
  },

  'ph-mindanao-highlands': {
    1: "January in the Mindanao Highlands is cool and pleasant — 24°C in the Bukidnon plateau, with the dry season keeping trails in excellent condition. Mt. Apo (the Philippines' highest peak at 2,954m) is climbable with permits, the rafting on the Cagayan de Oro River is exciting, and the pineapple plantations of Bukidnon stretch to the horizon.",
    2: "February stays dry and cool — ideal for trekking and highland exploration. The indigenous Lumad communities of the highlands maintain traditions that predate colonisation, the waterfalls around Iligan City (City of Majestic Waterfalls) are accessible, and the durian season in Davao begins its legendary aromatic assault.",
    3: "March is the driest month — clear skies, comfortable highland temperatures, and the best window for Mt. Apo's challenging but rewarding summit trek. The Kadayawan Festival preparations begin in Davao, the eagle centre (home to the critically endangered Philippine Eagle) is active, and the Mindanao chocolate scene is genuinely world-class.",
    4: "April heats up in the lowlands but the highlands stay pleasant at 25°C — the transition toward the wet season brings occasional afternoon storms. The Easter celebrations across Mindanao blend Catholic and indigenous traditions in ways that are unique to the region, and the durian stands in Davao are at their most fragrant.",
    5: "May brings the first serious rains — the highlands turn greener, the rivers swell for more adventurous white-water rafting, and the waterfalls around Iligan thunder with increased flow. The Philippine Eagle breeding season is active at the Davao centre, and the lush landscape makes every highland drive cinematically beautiful.",
    6: "June settles into the wet season — regular heavy rain, lush green highlands, and the Bukidnon pineapple fields at their most vivid. The trekking trails require careful planning around weather, the rivers are in full rafting mode, and the cultural richness of the Lumad and Moro communities provides depth beyond the natural beauty.",
    7: "July is solidly wet — highland trails can be slippery, waterfalls are at maximum power (Maria Cristina Falls near Iligan is thunderous), and the Mt. Apo trek is challenging but doable with experienced guides. The cooler highland temperatures (22°C) and misty mornings give the landscape a mystical quality.",
    8: "August brings the heaviest rains — flash floods are possible in the valleys, and some trails close temporarily. The highland communities continue their agricultural rhythms regardless, and the Kadayawan Festival in Davao (celebrating the harvest) is a spectacular display of indigenous culture, dance, and the fruit bounty of Mindanao.",
    9: "September continues heavy rain with some areas experiencing flooding — travel requires local knowledge and flexibility. The waterfalls are spectacular, the Philippine Eagle centre operates rain or shine, and the remote highland villages offer some of the most authentic cultural experiences in the Philippines.",
    10: "October stays wet but the rains ease slightly — the landscape is at maximum lushness, the rafting season on the Cagayan de Oro is thrilling with high water, and the durian season's second harvest brings Davao's most celebrated fruit back to the markets. The highland cool air is a welcome escape from the tropical lowlands.",
    11: "November transitions toward drier conditions — the highland trails start firming up, the skies clear more frequently, and the trekking season begins its return. The Mindanao International Marathon (if running) brings athletic energy to the highlands, and the waterfalls remain impressive with lingering wet-season flow.",
    12: "December brings improving weather and festive energy — the highlands cool further (20°C at elevation), the trails are increasingly accessible, and Mindanao's diverse communities celebrate Christmas in styles that range from Catholic mass to indigenous harvest thanksgiving. The durian and tropical fruit abundance makes every meal an event.",
  },

  'ph-palawan': {
    1: "January is Palawan at its best — 30°C, the amihan winds keeping humidity bearable, and the waters around El Nido's limestone karsts at their most turquoise and calm. The Underground River at Puerto Princesa is accessible, the island-hopping to Bacuit Archipelago's hidden lagoons is perfect, and the diving at Tubbataha Reef season has just opened.",
    2: "February is peak season perfection — dry, warm, crystal-clear waters, and the El Nido lagoons and Coron's WWII wreck dives at maximum visibility. Tubbataha Reef Natural Park is in full season (March-June access only by liveaboard), and the beaches of Port Barton offer a quieter alternative. Book well ahead; Palawan's secret is thoroughly out.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot at 32°C — the Tubbataha Reef liveaboard season is in prime form (whale sharks, manta rays, pristine coral), and El Nido and Coron are busy but spectacular. The heat is intense by midday, making the lagoon swimming and island-hopping tours that start early the smartest play.",
    4: "April is the dry season's last hurrah — 33°C, increasingly humid, but the waters remain calm and diveable. Tubbataha is still accessible, the Coron wreck dives are at their clearest, and the El Nido sunsets over the Bacuit Bay are the stuff of lifetime memories. The crowds peak around Semana Santa week.",
    5: "May signals the transition — the first afternoon storms appear, but El Nido's lagoons stay calm in the morning, Coron's lakes and wrecks are atmospheric in building weather, and Tubbataha wraps its final liveaboard departures. The shoulder season means better deals and slightly fewer kayaks in the Big Lagoon.",
    6: "The habagat monsoon arrives — rain becomes daily, the western coast (El Nido, Port Barton) takes the brunt, and some island-hopping tours modify their routes. The diving remains warm and marine-life-rich, the waterfalls across Palawan thunder to life, and the jungle interior is at its most vivid and alive.",
    7: "July is deep wet season — El Nido gets properly drenched, some boat tours cancel in rough seas, and the tourist numbers drop dramatically. But the snorkeling around Coron (more sheltered on the east) stays viable, the prices drop by half, and the Underground River without the crowds is a genuinely different experience.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon with heavy rain and occasional typhoon disruption — flexibility is essential. When the weather cooperates, the reefs are healthy and active, the jungle wildlife (including endemic Palawan species) is at its most visible, and the resorts offer rates that make paradise accessible on a real-world budget.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — serious rainfall, rough seas, and many operators running reduced schedules. The intrepid are rewarded with empty El Nido lagoons between storms, the jungle kayaking is adventurous, and the reduced footprint means Palawan's delicate ecosystem gets a breather. Travel insurance is non-negotiable.",
    10: "October stays wet but improves in the second half — the seas start calming, the reefs clear up, and the first dry days feel like gifts. Coron's Kayangan Lake and Twin Lagoon are spectacular even in the rain, and the diving operators who run year-round deliver excellent marine encounters with personal attention.",
    11: "November transitions back toward the amihan — rains ease, the seas calm, and El Nido's legendary beauty re-emerges from the wet-season clouds. Tourist numbers start building but the off-season pricing lingers, making this the value play of the year. The island-hopping tours resume their full routes with improving conditions.",
    12: "December brings the dry season back — clear skies, calm turquoise waters, and the Christmas crowd filling El Nido's beachfront restaurants. Coron's wreck dives are pristine, the Underground River runs smoothly, and the Filipino Christmas spirit (the longest Christmas season on Earth, starting in September) reaches its joyful peak.",
  },

  'ph-siargao': {
    1: "January in Siargao is the tail end of the amihan — breezy, 29°C, and the surf at Cloud 9 delivering the powerful right-hand barrels that put this island on the map. The island's palm-fringed lagoons, particularly Sugba, are calm and pristine for paddleboarding, and the post-New Year vibe is mellow and uncrowded.",
    2: "February is dry and warm — the surf at Cloud 9 stays consistent, the island-hopping trips to Naked, Daku, and Guyam islands are at their most reliable, and the coconut-palm jungle interior is lush from recent rains. The backpacker-to-boutique hotel ratio still tips toward authentic, though that's changing fast.",
    3: "March brings the driest conditions — perfect for exploring beyond the surf: the Magpupungko tidal pools reveal their rock formations at low tide, the Tayangban Cave Pool is crystal-clear for swimming, and the island's emerging food scene (Filipino-fusion restaurants in General Luna) is surprisingly good.",
    4: "April is hot (32°C) and still dry — the surf eases slightly but the offshore islands are at peak snorkeling conditions. The Siargao International Surfing Competition (if scheduled) brings the world's best to Cloud 9, and the transition toward the wet season hasn't yet dimmed the island's golden-hour magic.",
    5: "May introduces the habagat — the first rains arrive, the surf pattern shifts, and the island transitions to its green season. The waves at Pacifico (Siargao's north coast) start firing for intermediate surfers, the rivers swell for inland kayaking, and the tourist numbers thin as the party crowd departs.",
    6: "June is wet but Siargao's surf community doesn't sleep — the monsoon brings different wave patterns and the dedicated surfers adapt. The jungle is lush, the waterfalls are thundering, and the island takes on a rawer, more local character. The seafood from the daily market is exceptional year-round.",
    7: "July brings heavy rain and the habagat swell — the surf shifts to Siargao's west-facing breaks, the main Cloud 9 break gets unpredictable, and the island's laid-back vibe deepens. The few visitors get the lagoons, tidal pools, and island-hopping tours with minimal company, and the hostel-bar scene in General Luna stays social.",
    8: "August is Siargao's wettest month — serious rainfall, some road flooding, and the surfing reserved for experienced riders who know the monsoon breaks. The island's interior is at its most beautiful — dense palm jungle, overflowing rivers, and the misty-morning atmosphere that makes tropical islands feel ancient.",
    9: "September continues heavy rain with peak typhoon risk — Siargao's eastern exposure makes it vulnerable, and flexibility is essential. Between weather events, the surf is powerful and uncrowded, the rock pools at Magpupungko are dramatic in the monsoon light, and the island's resilient community carries on with characteristic Filipino cheerfulness.",
    10: "October stays wet but the surf season is building — the waves at Cloud 9 start returning to form as the amihan patterns reassert. The rain eases in the second half, the island-hopping tours resume, and the early-season visitors get improving conditions at off-season prices.",
    11: "November transitions to the amihan — the rains retreat, the surf at Cloud 9 builds toward its November-March peak, and the island's tourist infrastructure gears up for high season. The sunsets over the palm-fringed coastline are spectacular as the skies clear, and the island's energy shifts from sleepy to anticipatory.",
    12: "December is prime Siargao — the surf at Cloud 9 is pumping, the weather is dry and warm at 29°C, and the island-hopping and lagoon tours are back at full capacity. The Christmas and New Year's crowd transforms General Luna into a festive beach party, and the combination of world-class waves and palm-tree paradise is irresistible. Book ahead.",
  },

  'pk-karachi': {
    1: "January is Karachi's most pleasant month — 25°C, dry, and the sea breeze off the Arabian Sea making the city's famous Clifton Beach promenade genuinely enjoyable. The Mohatta Palace Museum and Quaid-e-Azam's Mausoleum are best visited in the mild winter sunshine, and the street food (biryani, nihari, bun kebab) is the city's beating heart year-round.",
    2: "February stays dry and comfortable at 26°C — the Sindh Festival (if running) celebrates the province's cultural heritage, and Karachi's literary and arts scene is at its most active. The Sindhi cuisine (sajji, sai bhaji) is outstanding, the Empress Market is a sensory overload in the best way, and the sunset from Do Darya seafood strip is unforgettable.",
    3: "March warms to 30°C — still dry and pleasant, though the heat is building. Holi celebrations add colour to Karachi's Hindu communities, the Defence Housing Authority food streets are buzzing, and the Churna Island day trip for snorkeling in the Arabian Sea is at its most reliable. Pakistan Day (March 23) brings celebrations city-wide.",
    4: "April ramps up to 34°C and the comfortable season's window starts closing. The sea is warm for swimming at Hawke's Bay and Sandspit beaches, the turtle nesting season at Sandspit begins (green and olive ridley turtles), and the Sindhi Ajrak and Topi artisans in the old city are worth seeking out before the heat becomes oppressive.",
    5: "May is the furnace ignition — 36°C with building humidity as the monsoon approaches from the south. The city slows down in the midday heat, but the evenings along the Sea View promenade are magical with the entire city outdoors. The pre-monsoon atmospheric drama (dust storms, orange skies) gives Karachi a cinematic quality.",
    6: "June brings the monsoon's first rains — a blessed relief from the heat, dropping temps to 34°C. Karachi's notorious flooding can disrupt transportation, but the rain transforms the dusty city into something greener and more alive. The seafood season peaks, and breaking fast during Ramadan (if it falls here) at the street stalls is a communal experience.",
    7: "July is the monsoon's main event — heavy rain, humidity above 80%, and Karachi's infrastructure tested by the deluge. The city is waterlogged but spirited — the chai stalls are packed, the biryani tastes better in the rain (this is not up for debate), and Independence Day preparations (August 14) begin building patriotic energy.",
    8: "August peaks monsoon intensity with Pakistan's Independence Day (August 14) bringing green-and-white flags to every corner of the city. The rain and humidity are at their most challenging, but the celebrations are genuine, the food scene is unstoppable, and Karachi's resilient, chaotic energy is on full display.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon retreating — the city starts drying out, temperatures ease to 33°C, and the sea clears up for Churna Island snorkeling trips. The post-monsoon light is beautiful over the Arabian Sea, and the cultural calendar picks up with exhibition openings and music events as the city emerges from its monsoon cocoon.",
    10: "October is Karachi's second spring — 33°C with the humidity dropping, clear skies, and the city at its most energetic. The Defence food festivals buzz with vendors from across Pakistan, the Mohenjodaro day trip (a flight away) is feasible in the comfortable weather, and the Clifton Beach sunset promenade peaks with families and friends.",
    11: "November cools to 28°C and the city hits its stride — perfect weather for exploring Karachi's colonial architecture, Saddar's bazaars, and the increasingly vibrant art gallery scene. The street food tours (Burns Garden to Boat Basin) are best enjoyed in the evening cool, and the cultural diversity of Pakistan's megacity is most apparent now.",
    12: "December is Karachi at its gentlest — 24°C, zero rain, and the winter sunshine making every outdoor activity enjoyable. The Quaid's birthday (December 25) is a national holiday, the year-end celebrations bring the city's food streets to peak activity, and the Arabian Sea at sunset from Seaview is the colour of molten copper.",
  },

  'pk-karakoram': {
    1: "January in the Karakoram is deep winter — the Karakoram Highway is often blocked by snow, Gilgit and Skardu are accessible mainly by (unreliable) flights, and temperatures plunge to minus 15°C at elevation. But the frozen waterfalls and snow-covered peaks are staggeringly beautiful, and the handful of adventurers who make it find a silence so complete it rings.",
    2: "February is the coldest month — the high passes are sealed shut, the rivers are frozen, and the northern areas feel genuinely isolated. The winter light on Nanga Parbat and Rakaposhi is extraordinary for those who can reach viewpoints, and the Hunza Valley's dry-stone architecture under snow is haunting.",
    3: "March begins the thaw — the first blossoms appear in Hunza Valley (cherry and apricot), creating pink-and-white carpets against the snow-capped Karakoram backdrop. The KKH opens on good years, temperatures climb to a manageable 10°C in Gilgit, and the trekking season is still weeks away but the anticipation builds.",
    4: "April is the blossom season — Hunza Valley explodes into cherry, apricot, and almond bloom against 7,000m peaks in one of the most photographed landscapes on Earth. The KKH is open, Karimabad is accessible, and the Baltit Fort and Altit Fort provide cultural depth between the jaw-dropping mountain views.",
    5: "May opens the trekking season — the snow melts from the mid-altitude trails, the Fairy Meadows trek (gateway to Nanga Parbat base camp) becomes feasible, and the Hunza Valley is warm (20°C) and green. K2 and Broad Peak expeditions launch from Skardu, the Deosai Plains are still snow-covered, and the mountain energy is electric.",
    6: "June is prime Karakoram — the high passes open (Khunjerab Pass to China at 4,693m), the Deosai Plains melt into a wildflower-carpeted plateau with Himalayan brown bears, and the trekking to Concordia (the throne room of the world's highest peaks) begins. The weather is warm (25°C in valleys) with some afternoon storms at altitude.",
    7: "July is peak mountaineering and trekking season — K2 summit attempts happen now, the Baltoro Glacier trek to Concordia is at its most accessible, and the Deosai Plains are at full wildflower-and-bear glory. The valleys are warm, the passes are clear, and the mountain views are reliably spectacular. Book guides and porters months ahead.",
    8: "August continues peak season — the Baltoro trek, the Hushe Valley, and the Snow Lake trek are all in prime condition. The fruit harvest in Hunza (apricots, mulberries, cherries) makes every meal a celebration, and the mountain hospitality of northern Pakistan is as warm as anywhere on Earth. Afternoon storms at altitude require planning.",
    9: "September brings autumn to the Karakoram — the poplar trees along the Hunza River turn gold, the peaks get their first new snow dustings, and the trekking conditions are excellent with clearer skies and thinner crowds. The fruit harvest continues, the passes remain open, and the autumn light on the mountains is photography perfection.",
    10: "October is the grand finale — the Karakoram's autumn colours peak with golden poplars against white peaks and blue sky, creating what many consider the most beautiful landscape on Earth. The KKH is still open, the weather is cooling (10°C in valleys), and the treks are winding down. The last trekkers share trails with falling leaves.",
    11: "November signals shutdown — the high passes close, snow returns to the valleys, and the northern areas begin their long winter isolation. The Hunza Valley holds out longest with the KKH still (usually) passable, and the bare poplars against snow peaks have an austere beauty. Warm Hunza hospitality and walnut cake by the fire define the month.",
    12: "December is full winter — the Karakoram is locked in snow, the KKH can close for days, and only Gilgit remains reliably connected by flight. The frozen landscape is beautiful in a brutal way, and the local culture (Ismaili communities, traditional music, winter festivals) provides warmth when the thermometer won't. Serious winter gear required.",
  },

  'pk-lahore': {
    1: "January is Lahore's cosiest month — 20°C days, cold nights (5°C), and the morning fog that gives the Mughal monuments a mysterious, dreamlike quality. The Lahore Fort and Badshahi Mosque emerge from the mist spectacularly, the food street in the old city serves the most restorative nihari, and the Basant kite festival preparations build excitement.",
    2: "February warms slightly with the fog lifting to reveal Lahore's Mughal grandeur in sharp winter light. Basant (kite festival, if celebrated) fills the sky with colour and the rooftops with celebration. The Shalimar Gardens are green and pleasant, the Lahore Museum's Gandhara collection is world-class, and the street food crawl from Anarkali to Gawalmandi is legendary.",
    3: "March brings Pakistan Day (March 23) with military parades and celebrations, and spring arrives with temperatures climbing to 28°C. The Lahore Literary Festival (if scheduled) is one of South Asia's premier cultural events, the canal road is lined with blooming trees, and the Walled City's labyrinthine bazaars are at their most navigable before the heat.",
    4: "April heats up to 34°C — the last comfortable month for extensive outdoor sightseeing. The Mughal gardens are at their most fragrant, the sunset from the Minar-e-Pakistan is spectacular in the lengthening evenings, and the lassi shops of the old city become essential survival stations. The Wagah border ceremony is dramatic year-round.",
    5: "May is punishing — 40°C+, the city shimmers in heat haze, and the Mughal monuments should only be visited at dawn or dusk. The mango season begins (the one consolation), and the evening food culture shifts entirely outdoors to escape the heat-soaked buildings. Only the most committed history buffs visit Lahore in May.",
    6: "June reaches 42°C before the monsoon — the hottest month, and the city holds its breath waiting for rain. The pre-monsoon dust storms are dramatic, the mangoes reach their peak, and the very idea of walking through the Walled City at midday is medically inadvisable. Indoor pursuits only.",
    7: "The monsoon arrives — blessed rain drops temperatures to 35°C and the city exhales. The Shalimar Gardens glisten, the old city's narrow lanes channel the rainwater dramatically, and the street food scene (now operating in the cooler, wetter evenings) is at its most vibrant. Flooding can disrupt traffic, but Lahori resilience is legendary.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon with Independence Day (August 14) celebrations bringing patriotic green-and-white to every corner. The rain keeps temperatures manageable, the mangoes are still available (just), and the Wagah border ceremony's sunset flag-lowering is even more atmospheric in the monsoon light.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon retreating — the air is fresher, the vegetation is lush, and Lahore's cultural season begins its autumn revival. The Lahore Fort looks its best against the post-monsoon clean sky, and the evening food street crawls resume in the cooling temperatures. The city is pleasant and forward-looking.",
    10: "October is Lahore's golden month — 30°C, clear skies, and the Mughal heritage at its most accessible and photogenic. The food festivals return, the literary and cultural calendar fills up, and the Walled City at sunset is genuinely one of South Asia's greatest urban experiences. The Wagah ceremony crowds are enthusiastic but manageable.",
    11: "November cools to a comfortable 25°C — the ideal month for Lahore. The Badshahi Mosque at sunrise, the Lahore Fort in afternoon light, and the Anarkali Bazaar at dusk create a perfect day. The food scene peaks with winter specialties (saag, makki di roti), and the cultural calendar is packed with exhibitions and performances.",
    12: "December is cold (18°C days, 4°C nights) but wonderful — the morning fog returns to shroud the Mughal monuments in mystery, the Walled City's tea stalls serve steaming cups to warming crowds, and the year-end cultural events bring Lahore's artistic community together. A plate of siri paye (trotters stew) in the old city is winter medicine.",
  },

  'pl-gdansk': {
    1: "Gdansk in January is Baltic winter at its most bracing — 1°C, grey skies, and the reconstructed Main Town eerily quiet under occasional snow. The European Solidarity Centre (documenting Solidarnosc) is a powerful indoor experience, the amber shops along Mariacka Street have no queues, and the pierogi in the old town are warming and cheap.",
    2: "February is Gdansk's coldest month — sub-zero temperatures, the frozen harbour looking dramatic, and the medieval crane on the Motlawa River standing sentinel over empty quays. The Gdansk Shakespeare Theatre offers winter performances, the Baltic Philharmonic is in full season, and the cosy milk bars (bar mleczny) serve traditional Polish comfort food.",
    3: "March brings the first hints of spring — 5°C, longer days, and the occasional sunny spell that transforms the colourful merchants' houses along Long Market into a photographer's dream. The tourist crowds are nonexistent, the museums (WWII Museum, Solidarity Centre) are uncrowded, and the coffee shops along the Motlawa are atmospheric.",
    4: "April awakens Gdansk — 11°C, the amber-coloured facades of the Main Town glowing in spring light, and the outdoor café tables appearing along Long Market and Mariacka Street. The Westerplatte memorial (where WWII began) is powerful in any weather, and the rebuilt Old Town reveals its remarkable details without summer crowds blocking the view.",
    5: "May is lovely — 16°C, the Baltic coast coming alive, and Gdansk's maritime heritage on full display. The Sopot Pier (Europe's longest wooden pier) is walkable without the summer crush, the beach at Gdynia starts attracting early sunbathers, and the amber jewellery shopping is a genuine pleasure. Polish May Day and Constitution Day add festive energy.",
    6: "June delivers Baltic summer — 20°C, long evenings, and the Tri-City (Gdansk, Sopot, Gdynia) buzzing with outdoor festivals, beach life, and sailing. St. Dominic's Fair preparations begin, the Motlawa River fills with excursion boats, and the Old Town restaurants serve excellent Baltic herring and pierogi on outdoor terraces. Tourist season is in full swing.",
    7: "July is peak season — 22°C, the Baltic beaches at Sopot packed with sunbathers, and St. Dominic's Fair (starting late July) transforming Gdansk into an enormous street market. The Main Town is at its most colourful and crowded, the Motlawa river cruises are lovely, and the beer gardens along the waterfront are the social hub.",
    8: "August continues summer's peak — St. Dominic's Fair runs through the first week, the beach scene is at its busiest, and the 22°C weather holds. The Solidarity Centre and WWII Museum are must-visits that transcend the season, and the evening light on the reconstructed Main Town's façades is genuinely golden. Book ahead for the popular Mariacka restaurants.",
    9: "September is Gdansk's golden month — the summer crowds thin, temperatures stay pleasant at 17°C, and the Main Town's amber-toned architecture matches the autumn light. The Baltic coast is still beach-viable for the hardy, the cultural season ramps up, and the pierogi at a quiet terrace table without the August madness taste even better.",
    10: "October brings Baltic autumn — 11°C, rain becoming more frequent, and the Main Town beautiful in its moody, grey-sky way. The museums are uncrowded, the amber markets quiet enough for proper browsing, and the seafood restaurants serve the freshest Baltic catch of the year. Pack layers and an umbrella.",
    11: "November is grey and cold — 5°C, the Baltic wind cutting through the streets, and the first Christmas preparations appearing in the old town. The covered Hala Targowa market is a warm refuge, the Solidarity Centre is particularly resonant in the grey November light, and the hotel prices are at their most generous.",
    12: "December transforms Gdansk — Christmas markets fill the Main Town with twinkling lights and mulled wine, the medieval buildings look like an advent calendar come to life, and the amber glows warm in the holiday displays. The cold (2°C) is real, but a cup of grzaniec (spiced hot beer) and pierogi by the Motlawa makes it all worthwhile.",
  },

  'pl-krakow': {
    1: "Krakow in January is a snow-dusted fairytale — 1°C, the Cloth Hall and St. Mary's Basilica framed in white, and the Planty gardens quiet under a blanket of frost. The Wieliczka Salt Mine is magnificent any time, the Jewish quarter (Kazimierz) bars are cosy and uncrowded, and the traditional zurek (sour rye soup) warms you from the inside out.",
    2: "February is the coldest month — sub-zero nights, the Wawel Castle dramatic against grey skies, and the Auschwitz-Birkenau memorial at its most sombre. The Tlusty Czwartek (Fat Thursday) tradition fills every bakery with paczki doughnuts, and the indoor cultural scene (jazz clubs in Kazimierz, gallery openings) provides shelter from the cold.",
    3: "March brings the first spring thaw — 7°C, snowdrops in the Planty gardens, and the Main Square beginning its seasonal awakening. The Schindler Factory Museum and Galicia Jewish Museum are powerful without the summer queues, and the restaurant scene in Kazimierz is at its most accessible. Krakow's student energy keeps the nights warm.",
    4: "April is Krakow at its most charming — 14°C, the Vistula River reflecting blue sky, and the flower market in Rynek Glowny (Main Square) bursting with colour. Easter traditions bring elaborate processions, painted eggs, and festive food. Wawel Castle's dragon sculpture breathes fire on the quarter-hour, and the terrace cafés are open.",
    5: "May is arguably Krakow's sweet spot — 19°C, the Planty gardens in full bloom, and the city alive with outdoor concerts and festivals. The Wawel Castle grounds are perfect for wandering, the Vistula riverbank fills with students and cyclists, and a sunset beer on the Main Square watching St. Mary's trumpet call is a near-religious experience.",
    6: "June brings warm summer — 22°C, the Jewish Culture Festival transforming Kazimierz with klezmer music and outdoor performances. The Wieliczka Salt Mine stays cool underground while the city basks in long evenings, the Zakopane mountain resort is a day trip away, and the outdoor dining scene reaches peak perfection. Crowds are building.",
    7: "July is peak season — 24°C, the Main Square packed with tourists, and Wawel Castle requiring timed-entry tickets. The Vistula River beaches (yes, river beaches) fill with sunbathers, the open-air cinema in the Kazimierz district runs nightly, and the street food (zapiekanki from Okragly) is best enjoyed at 11pm on a warm summer night.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and crowds with afternoon thunderstorms adding drama to the Gothic skyline. The Assumption of Mary (August 15) brings pilgrimages and celebrations, the Wieliczka Salt Mine is a cool refuge, and the Krakow nightlife (Kazimierz's endless bars) peaks with summer visitors and locals alike.",
    9: "September is the connoisseur's month — 19°C, the summer crowds thinning, and the Main Square settling into golden-hour glory. The university quarter is buzzing with returning students, the museums are accessible without queues, and the pierogi, oscypek cheese, and obwarzanki (pretzel rings) taste better when you're not competing for a table.",
    10: "October brings autumn to Krakow's parks — 12°C, the Planty gardens ablaze with colour, and the Tyniec Monastery perched above the Vistula in peak autumn beauty. The cultural season (theatre, opera, jazz) is in full swing, and the All Saints' Day preparations (November 1) bring candle-lit atmosphere to every cemetery.",
    11: "November is atmospheric and affordable — 5°C, the first fog rolling through the Main Square, and the All Saints' Day tradition of thousands of candles in Rakowicki Cemetery creating one of Europe's most moving sights. The Christmas market preparations begin mid-month, and the Schindler Factory Museum resonates deeply in the autumn darkness.",
    12: "December transforms Krakow into a Christmas wonderland — the Main Square market serves grzaniec and oscypek, carollers fill the Cloth Hall, and the szopka (nativity scene) competition showcases elaborate miniature architectural masterpieces. The cold (0°C) is real, but Krakow's festive spirit, medieval backdrop, and mulled-wine warmth are genuinely magical.",
  },

  'pl-warsaw': {
    1: "Warsaw in January is properly cold — minus 2°C average, the reconstructed Old Town under snow, and the Palace of Culture looming through winter fog. The Warsaw Uprising Museum and POLIN Museum of the History of Polish Jews are powerful indoor experiences, and the city's craft beer scene provides evening warmth in Praga district's creative bars.",
    2: "February stays frozen — the coldest month with nights hitting minus 8°C, but Warsaw's cultural life doesn't slow down. The Chopin concerts at the Fryderyk Chopin Museum are intimate, the Royal Castle is uncrowded, and the traditional Polish comfort food (bigos, golonka, pierogi) is at its most essential. Tlusty Czwartek brings the paczki frenzy.",
    3: "March brings tentative spring — 6°C, the Vistula River thawing, and the first outdoor tables appearing in the New Town. The Warsaw Theatre Meetings festival showcases Poland's vibrant performing arts, the Lazienki Park crocuses bloom around Chopin's monument, and the city starts shaking off its winter torpor.",
    4: "April is Warsaw's springtime — 13°C, the Royal Route from the Old Town to Lazienki Park lined with blooming trees, and the Sunday Chopin concerts in Lazienki Park beginning their outdoor season. The Easter markets and traditions are charming, the food scene in Mokotow and Srodmiescie buzzes, and the rebuilt Old Town is photogenic under blue spring skies.",
    5: "May delivers — 19°C, the Lazienki Park peacocks strutting, and Warsaw's rooftop bars opening for the season with skyline views. Museum Night brings free late-night access to dozens of cultural institutions, the Vistula beach bars (Poniatowka) set up for summer, and the pierogi are best eaten on a sunny Old Town terrace. Constitution Day (May 3) adds national pride.",
    6: "June is excellent — 22°C, the longest evenings, and Warsaw's dual identity (historic Old Town, modernist skyscrapers) most impressive in summer light. The Open'er Festival in Gdynia draws music fans north, but Warsaw's own cultural calendar is packed. The Vistula riverbank bars and the Praga district galleries are the city's contemporary soul.",
    7: "Peak summer at 24°C — Warsaw buzzes with outdoor cinema, river festivals, and the Vistula beaches packed with sunbathing locals. The Old Town terraces are tourist-heavy but the Praga district and Mokotow offer more authentic summer experiences. The POLIN Museum and Warsaw Uprising Museum are always worth the visit regardless of weather.",
    8: "August continues summer with the occasional dramatic thunderstorm — the Vistula river bars are at peak social mode, the Chopin concerts in Lazienki Park draw crowds on Sunday afternoons, and the food halls (Hala Koszyki, Hala Gwardii) are at their most vibrant. The Warsaw Uprising anniversary (August 1) is a deeply moving city-wide commemoration.",
    9: "September is Warsaw's golden month — 19°C, autumn colour in Lazienki Park, and the cultural season launching with film festivals, gallery openings, and the Warsaw Autumn contemporary music festival. The crowds thin, the restaurant scene shifts to seasonal Polish cuisine, and the city feels energised and forward-looking.",
    10: "October brings autumn properly — 12°C, the Royal Route spectacular with fall foliage, and the indoor-season cultural offerings (Warsaw Philharmonic, National Theatre) in full swing. The craft beer scene in Praga is lively on weekend evenings, and the All Saints' Day preparations add a contemplative energy to this history-heavy city.",
    11: "November is grey but culturally rich — 5°C, All Saints' Day (November 1) candles transforming Powazki Cemetery into a sea of light, and the Independence Day (November 11) celebrations adding historical weight. The first Christmas markets appear, the museums are uncrowded, and the hearty Polish food is at its most satisfying.",
    12: "December in Warsaw is cold (0°C) and festive — Christmas markets in the Old Town, the Royal Castle decorated for the holidays, and the city's remarkable story of destruction and reconstruction adding poignancy to every lit window. The pierogi are celebratory, the Chopin Museum offers holiday concerts, and New Year's Eve at the Palace of Culture plaza is exuberant.",
  },

  'pr-puerto-rico': {
    1: "January in Puerto Rico is peak perfection — 28°C, minimal rain, and the Atlantic trade winds keeping the humidity from overwhelming. Old San Juan's colonial streets are buzzing with post-holiday visitors, the bioluminescent bays at Vieques and Fajardo glow brightest in the dry season, and the surfing at Rincón is at its winter prime.",
    2: "February extends the magic — dry, warm, and the ocean at a comfortable 26°C for snorkeling at Culebra's Flamenco Beach (regularly rated among the world's best). The Ponce Carnival brings masked vejigantes dancing through the streets, coffee harvest season wraps up in the central mountains, and the forts of San Juan are tourist-busy but magnificent.",
    3: "March stays dry at 29°C — spring break brings American college crowds to the hotel zone, but Vieques and Culebra islands absorb the overflow gracefully. The El Yunque National Forest is at its least rainy and most hikeable, the bioluminescent bay kayaking is reliable, and the mofongo at a Luquillo kiosk is a taste of Puerto Rican soul.",
    4: "April warms and the rainy season teases its first drops — occasional afternoon showers that do nothing to diminish the 30°C beach days. The Fiestas de la Calle San Sebastián energy lingers, the surf at Rincón transitions to summer patterns, and the piña coladas (invented here, allegedly) taste better oceanside.",
    5: "May introduces the rainy season — afternoon tropical showers become daily events, the El Yunque rainforest lives up to its name, and the island turns lush green. Crowds thin, hotel prices drop, and the Puerto Rican food scene (lechón at Guavate, mofongo everywhere) doesn't have an off season. The bioluminescent bays still glow.",
    6: "June brings proper rain and the official start of hurricane season — the trade winds ease, humidity climbs, and the surf at Rincón quiets down. The San Juan Pride celebrations bring colour to the capital, the Luquillo Beach food kiosks are in summer mode, and the accommodation deals make this a smart value play.",
    7: "July is hot (32°C), humid, and rainy — the island is at its most tropical with daily storms and a lush, steamy energy. The beaches are still gorgeous between showers, the Fiestas de Santiago Apóstol in Loíza celebrate Afro-Puerto Rican heritage with bomba music and dance, and the piragua (shaved ice) vendors become essential.",
    8: "August is peak hurricane season — weather awareness is essential and travel insurance non-negotiable. The island is hot, wet, and genuinely beautiful between storms, the bioluminescent bays are active, and the local beaches are full of Puerto Rican families on summer holiday. The risks are real but the rewards are authentic Caribbean culture.",
    9: "September is the highest hurricane-risk month — prices are at their lowest and the island is at its emptiest. The fiestas patronales (patron saint festivals) still happen across every town regardless of weather, and the combination of reduced tourism and genuine Puerto Rican hospitality makes for memorable encounters if the storms stay away.",
    10: "October eases the hurricane risk while keeping the lush green landscape — the rain starts tapering off, the surfing at Rincón begins its winter season build-up, and the island transitions toward its best months. The Fiestas de la Calle Loíza (October) brings art, music, and food to San Juan's emerging creative corridor.",
    11: "November is the transition month — rain decreases, the seas calm, and the dry-season sunshine starts reasserting itself at 29°C. The Fiestas de la Calle San Sebastián spirit starts building (the actual festival is in January), the surf at Rincón fires up, and the accommodation between hurricane and holiday seasons is a genuine bargain.",
    12: "December brings the dry season back and the holiday crowd with it — 28°C, clear skies, and the parrandas (Puerto Rican Christmas carolling with instruments) filling every neighbourhood with music and rum. Old San Juan is festively lit, the lechón asado (roasted pig) season peaks, and the New Year's celebrations bring the entire island out to celebrate.",
  },

  'ps-palestine': {
    1: "January in Palestine is cold and rainy — 12°C in Bethlehem and Ramallah with 130mm of rain, occasional snow in the highlands, and the Judean Hills stark and beautiful. The Christmas season lingers in Bethlehem (Orthodox Christmas is January 7), the Old City of Hebron is uncrowded, and the olive oil fresh from the winter pressing is the best you'll ever taste.",
    2: "February stays cold at 12°C with the heaviest rain of the year — the West Bank landscape turns green, the almond trees begin blossoming spectacularly across the hillsides, and the markets of Nablus are aromatic with fresh knafeh (the city's legendary dessert). The Mar Saba Monastery overlooking the Kidron Valley is powerful in the winter light.",
    3: "March brings spring and the landscape transforms — wildflowers carpet the hills, temperatures climb to 16°C, and the olive groves turn silver-green. Easter preparations in Bethlehem build toward the city's other great pilgrimage season, the Jericho date palms are fruiting, and the hiking in Wadi Qelt (connecting Jerusalem to Jericho) is spectacular.",
    4: "April is Palestine at its most beautiful — 20°C, the hillsides blazing with red anemones and yellow mustard flowers, and Easter celebrations filling Bethlehem's churches with pilgrims and incense. The food is seasonal and superb (za'atar, fresh cheese, spring vegetables), and the hospitality in every village is genuine and humbling.",
    5: "May warms to 25°C with the last spring rains — the landscape starts drying but the olive orchards are lush, the Dead Sea (at minus 430m) is already hot, and the Nablus souq's knafeh and soap markets are vibrant. The Palestinian Heritage Festival (if running) showcases tatreez embroidery, dabke dance, and centuries of cultural resilience.",
    6: "June is dry and hot — 30°C, the landscape turning golden, and the Dead Sea resorts becoming the escape from highland heat. Ramallah's cafe culture buzzes in the evenings, the West Bank cities come alive after dark, and the ancient sites (Jericho's Tell es-Sultan, Sebastia's Roman ruins) are best visited in early morning light.",
    7: "July peaks the heat — 32°C, bone-dry, and the Palestinian cities shifting to nocturnal rhythms. The Dead Sea float is the coolest part of any day, the mountain breezes in Ramallah provide evening relief, and the summer cultural festivals bring music, poetry, and film to village squares across the territory.",
    8: "August continues the heat at 33°C — the fig and grape harvest begins, bringing sweetness to every market and family table. The evening culture of Palestinian cities is at its peak, with rooftop gatherings, fresh watermelon, and the Arab coffee ritual. The ancient sites are for dawn visits only; the midday heat is formidable.",
    9: "September brings the first hints of relief — 30°C but less intense, the olive harvest preparations begin, and the Palestinian cultural calendar is active with back-to-school energy and late-summer festivals. The Dead Sea is still warm, Jericho's date harvest is underway, and the evening light on Bethlehem's stone buildings is golden.",
    10: "October is the olive harvest — Palestine's most important agricultural and cultural event, when families gather in the groves and the stone mills press the season's first oil. Temperatures drop to a comfortable 24°C, the first rains hint at the approaching wet season, and participating in the harvest (many farms welcome visitors) is an unforgettable experience.",
    11: "November brings the first real rain and the landscape begins its green renewal — 18°C, the olive oil mills working at full capacity, and the winter vegetables appearing in the markets. Ramallah's restaurant scene shifts to warming Palestinian dishes (musakhan, maqluba), and the heritage sites are uncrowded and contemplative.",
    12: "December is cold (12°C) and rainy but profoundly special — Christmas in Bethlehem is a pilgrimage and a celebration, the Manger Square crowds on Christmas Eve are electric, and the Palestinian Christian communities' traditions are centuries deep. The Nablus knafeh is extra-warming in the winter chill, and the hospitality is undiminished by the cold.",
  },

  'pt-algarve': {
    1: "January on the Algarve is Europe's secret winter escape — 16°C, the dramatic limestone cliffs and sea caves bathed in low winter light, and the tourist hordes nowhere to be found. The almond blossoms begin appearing mid-month (the Algarve's answer to cherry blossom season), and the seafood cataplana at a quiet Lagos restaurant is restorative. The Atlantic at 16°C is for surfers in wetsuits only.",
    2: "February brings the almond blossom peak — every hillside is dusted white and pink, and the contrast with the golden cliffs and blue Atlantic is extraordinary. Temps stay around 16°C with less rain than January, the golf courses (Vilamoura, Vale do Lobo) are in perfect condition, and Carnival celebrations add unexpected liveliness to Loulé and Faro.",
    3: "March is the spring transition — 18°C, wildflowers spreading across the clifftops, and the hiking trails along the Seven Hanging Valleys at their most colourful. The surf at Sagres and Arrifana is powerful with late-winter swells, the seafood restaurants are open and uncrowded, and the coastal caves near Benagil are accessible by kayak without the summer queues.",
    4: "April delivers the Algarve's best-value experience — 20°C, increasingly sunny, and the Benagil sea cave accessible without battling 50 other kayaks. The beaches are swimmable for the hardy (17°C water), the golf is excellent, and the blooming coastal flowers make the clifftop walks between Carvoeiro and Algar Seco feel like a Mediterranean botanical garden.",
    5: "May is when the Algarve starts justifying its reputation — 23°C, the beaches filling with early summer visitors, and the Atlantic warming to a tolerable 18°C. The Ria Formosa lagoon system is alive with flamingos and wading birds, the seafood is fresh from the morning catch, and the sunset from Cape St. Vincent (Europe's southwestern tip) is epic.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 27°C, minimal rain, and the beaches from Albufeira to Tavira in full holiday mode. The Benagil cave tours run all day, the surfing at Sagres delivers summer swells, and the grilled sardines at every beachside restaurant are as good as Portugal gets. Crowds are building but the 155km coastline absorbs them.",
    7: "Peak season hits — 30°C, the Atlantic at a swimmable 21°C, and every beach, golf course, and restaurant at maximum capacity. The Algarve is unapologetically a summer playground: golden cliffs, turquoise grottos, sardine festivals, and waterparks. Albufeira's nightlife is not for the faint-hearted, but quieter Tavira and Olhão maintain their charm.",
    8: "August is the Algarve at maximum — 31°C, zero rain, and both Portuguese and international tourists competing for beach space. The sea is at its warmest (22°C), the boat tours to the sea caves run continuously, and the Banho 29 Festival in Silves brings medieval re-enactment and sardine grilling to the castle town. Book everything months ahead.",
    9: "September is the insider's month — still 27°C and sunny, but the families go home and the beaches clear. The Atlantic stays warm at 21°C (the best swimming of the year), the surf at Sagres builds with autumn swells, and the seafood restaurants operate at full quality without the queues. Wine harvest season adds another dimension to the food scene.",
    10: "October is the Algarve's beautiful wind-down — 23°C, the first autumn rains, and the tourist infrastructure still fully operational but far less busy. The clifftop walks are spectacular in autumn light, the golf courses are in post-summer condition, and the birdwatching in the Ria Formosa is excellent as migrants arrive from northern Europe.",
    11: "November brings the off-season — 18°C, increasing rain, and the resort towns quieting down significantly. But the seafood is at its freshest (percebes/barnacles season), the dramatic winter swells at Sagres attract hardcore surfers, and the Algarve's interior (Monchique mountains, Silves castle) reveals itself without the coastal crowds.",
    12: "December is quiet and mild — 16°C, the Christmas lights decorating Faro and Lagos, and the Algarve's golf courses busy with winter-escape Europeans. The Atlantic storms produce spectacular wave-watching at Cape St. Vincent, the cataplana stews are at their most warming, and the almond trees are already budding for January's show. New Year's Eve in Lagos is festive and fun.",
  },

  'pt-azores-flores': {
    1: "January on Flores is raw Atlantic drama — 15°C highs, relentless rain (around 180mm), and winds that rattle the hydrangea hedgerows. Crowds are essentially nonexistent, and the waterfalls at Poço da Alagoinha thunder with full force. Ferry connections are unreliable, so fly in and bring serious rain gear.",
    2: "February stays stormy with 14°C days and heavy rainfall, but between squalls the volcanic lakes glow an eerie emerald green under moody skies. You'll have the island's hiking trails entirely to yourself — the Fajã Grande coastal path is hauntingly beautiful in winter light. Whale-watching season is just around the corner.",
    3: "March sees the first hints of spring — temps nudge toward 15°C and rainfall eases slightly, though the Atlantic remains rough at 16°C. Early whale-watching trips begin spotting blue and sperm whales in the surrounding deep waters. The famous hydrangeas aren't blooming yet, but wildflowers start dotting the crater rims.",
    4: "April brings longer days, 16°C highs, and noticeably drier spells perfect for hiking the seven lakes of Sete Lagoas. Whale-watching season hits its stride with regular sightings of blues, sperms, and sei whales. Crowds are still minimal and guesthouse prices remain very reasonable — this is Flores at its most accessible without the summer squeeze.",
    5: "May is when Flores starts earning its name — wildflowers erupt everywhere, temps climb to 18°C, and rainfall drops to manageable levels. The hydrangeas begin budding along every road and stone wall, promising the blue explosion to come. Whale watching is excellent, hiking conditions are ideal, and you can still book accommodation without planning months ahead.",
    6: "June is arguably Flores at its peak — the legendary hydrangeas burst into bloom, lining every road in electric blue, and temperatures reach a pleasant 20°C under increasingly generous sunshine. The sea warms to 19°C, making coastal swimming pools (poças) viable. Crowds tick up but this is still one of the quietest islands in the Azores; book the Fajã Grande trail and have it nearly to yourself.",
    7: "July brings the best weather Flores can offer — 23°C highs, the least rain of the year, and hydrangeas at their absolute peak blanketing the island in blue and purple. The sea hits 21°C, warm enough for proper swimming at the natural rock pools. This is peak season by Flores standards, meaning you might actually see other tourists — book accommodation early but expect nothing like mainland resort crowds.",
    8: "August matches July's warmth at 24°C with long sunny days and the driest conditions of the year. The hydrangeas are fading but still photogenic, and the sea reaches its warmest at 22°C — perfect for snorkeling the crystal-clear volcanic coastline. This is the busiest month, though 'busy' on Flores still means peaceful trails and quiet restaurants. The Festa do Emigrante brings the diaspora home for lively village celebrations.",
    9: "September is the savvy choice — still 22°C and relatively dry, with the summer crowds departing and the sea clinging to a pleasant 21°C. Late hydrangeas still line the roads, the waterfalls run with renewed vigor from early autumn rain, and whale-watching delivers as migrating species pass through. Prices drop and availability opens up; pair a hike to Poço do Bacalhau with a local queijada and feel impossibly smug.",
    10: "October marks the return of serious Atlantic weather — rainfall climbs sharply, temps drop to 19°C, and the sea cools to 20°C. The island turns lush and dramatic, waterfalls reach full power, and the volcanic lakes reflect brooding skies. Crowds vanish, whale-watching winds down, and you'll want waterproofs for every hike. Moody, magnificent, and almost entirely yours.",
    11: "November is proper storm season — 17°C days, heavy rain, and Atlantic gales that can ground flights and cancel ferries. The upside is waterfalls at their most spectacular and a wild, windswept beauty that feels like the edge of the world (which, geographically, it nearly is). Come prepared for indoor days with local Azorean stew and vinho de cheiro, and you'll find a rugged charm that fair-weather visitors never see.",
    12: "December keeps the storms rolling with 16°C highs and some of the heaviest rainfall of the year. Christmas brings quiet village celebrations and traditional Azorean baking — massa sovada and bolo lêvedo fresh from local ovens. The island is at its emptiest and most atmospheric, with waterfalls roaring and volcanic craters shrouded in mist. Not for the faint-hearted, but deeply rewarding for the intrepid.",
  },

  'pt-azores-pico-faial': {
    1: "January across Pico and Faial is moody Atlantic winter — 15°C highs, frequent rain, and seas too rough for most boat crossings between the islands. The volcanic peak of Mount Pico often hides behind clouds, but clear breaks reveal snow-dusted summit views. Whale-watching hasn't started yet, so settle into Peter Café Sport in Horta with a gin and tonic and watch the storms roll in.",
    2: "February remains wet and windy with temps around 14°C, but the first whale-watching boats venture out from Lajes do Pico as sperm whales become more active. Faial's caldeira is dramatically misty, and the vineyards of Pico's UNESCO currais (stone-walled plots) are dormant but photogenic. Crowds are nonexistent and prices are at their lowest — perfect for a quiet food-and-wine deep dive into Azorean culture.",
    3: "March brings the earliest reliable whale-watching — sperm whales are regularly spotted from Pico's lookout towers, and the vigias (traditional whale spotters) come alive. Temps edge toward 15°C with improving sunshine, and the famous Pico wine vineyards start greening up between their basalt walls. Faial's hydrangeas are months away, but the capelinhos volcanic landscape is stark and stunning year-round.",
    4: "April sees whale-watching season hitting full stride with blues, fins, and sperms all passing through, and temperatures climbing to a pleasant 17°C. The sea is still brisk at 16°C but calmer, making the Pico-Faial channel crossing smooth. Hiking Mount Pico becomes viable on clear days — the 2,351m summit rewards with views across four islands. Crowds are light and accommodation is easy to find.",
    5: "May is prime time — 18°C days, reducing rainfall, and the best whale-watching of the year as migratory species peak in the surrounding deep waters. Pico's vineyards are lush green within their UNESCO black basalt walls, and Faial's hydrangeas begin showing their first blue buds. The inter-island ferries run reliable schedules, making two-island exploration effortless. Book a wine tasting at Cooperativa Vitivinícola and toast the Atlantic.",
    6: "June brings the hydrangeas to Faial in spectacular fashion — every hedgerow and roadside explodes in blue as temps reach 20°C and sunshine becomes generous. Whale watching remains excellent, the sea warms to 19°C for coastal swimming, and Pico's vineyards are in full leaf. Crowds build but stay manageable, and the Semana do Mar festival in Horta draws sailors and sea-lovers from across the Atlantic.",
    7: "July is peak Azores summer — 23°C, minimal rain, and the sea warming to 21°C for swimming, snorkeling, and diving the volcanic underwater formations. Climbing Mount Pico is at its most reliable with clearer skies and longer days, and the hydrangeas still blaze across Faial. Whale watching continues strong, and the yachting community fills Horta's marina with boats from around the world. Book early; this is as busy as these islands get.",
    8: "August is the warmest month at 24°C with long sunny days and the sea at a comfortable 22°C — prime time for diving Pico's underwater caves and swimming in Faial's natural pools. The Semana Cultural festival on Faial brings music and celebration, and Pico's wine harvest begins in the UNESCO vineyards. This is peak season with highest demand, but the laid-back Azorean pace keeps things from ever feeling overcrowded.",
    9: "September delivers summer weather (22°C) without summer crowds as visitors thin out and prices ease. The sea stays warm at 21°C, whale watching remains productive with autumn migrants, and the Pico wine harvest is in full swing — join a vindima and stomp grapes in the basalt-walled vineyards. Hydrangeas are fading but the landscape is lush, and hiking conditions are near-perfect. The smart traveler's month.",
    10: "October brings the autumn shift — temps drop to 19°C, rain picks up, and the Atlantic starts flexing its muscles again. Whale watching narrows but sperm whale sightings remain possible year-round off Pico. The wine harvest wraps up, leaving tasting rooms well-stocked, and Faial's caldeira takes on a moody beauty under October skies. Crowds are minimal and the pace slows to something deeply restorative.",
    11: "November signals winter's approach with 17°C days, heavy rain, and winds that test the inter-island ferries. Mount Pico often vanishes behind clouds for days at a time, and whale watching becomes weather-dependent. But Peter Café Sport stays open, Pico's wines are ready for tasting, and the volcanic landscapes take on a wild, storm-lit grandeur. Come for the solitude and the seafood stews — both are exceptional.",
    12: "December on Pico and Faial is Atlantic winter at its most honest — 16°C, persistent rain, and short days. Christmas brings quiet celebrations, traditional Azorean sweets like espécies, and the warmth of small-island hospitality. The volcanic landscapes are dramatically stark, whales occasionally pass through deep channels, and you'll find the kind of slow, contemplative travel that's increasingly hard to find anywhere else.",
  },

  'pt-azores-sao-miguel': {
    1: "January on São Miguel is mild by Atlantic standards — 16°C highs with frequent rain (around 120mm) and those signature Azorean four-seasons-in-one-day mood swings. The thermal pools at Furnas are steaming and glorious in the cool air, and the famous cozido stew slow-cooked underground by volcanic heat tastes even better when it's drizzling. Crowds are at their lowest; you'll have Sete Cidades crater lake views largely to yourself.",
    2: "February keeps the wet, mild pattern going at 15°C with the island at its greenest and most lush. Whale-watching season starts picking up with the first sperm whale sightings off the southern coast. Soak in the iron-rich thermal pools at Poça da Dona Beija after a rain-splashed hike, and enjoy restaurant prices that peak-season visitors would envy. Carnival brings modest festivities to Ponta Delgada.",
    3: "March marks a turning point — sunshine increases, temps reach 16°C, and whale-watching boats spot blues, sperms, and sometimes humpbacks in increasingly calm seas. The tea plantations at Gorreana are vivid green and offering tastings, and spring wildflowers begin brightening the volcanic hillsides. Tourist numbers are still low, making this ideal for unhurried exploration of the island's crater lakes and hot springs.",
    4: "April is a genuine sweet spot — 17°C, noticeably less rain, and the island exploding with hydrangea buds, azaleas, and the famous Azorean blue-green palette. Whale watching is at its best with multiple species passing through, and the hiking trails around Sete Cidades and Lagoa do Fogo are in prime condition. Crowds start building but accommodation remains available without advance-booking stress.",
    5: "May brings 19°C days, the driest conditions of spring, and hydrangeas beginning their iconic bloom along every road and stone wall. The tea plantations at Gorreana and Porto Formoso are harvesting the first flush, and whale watching delivers reliably. Surfing at Santa Bárbara beach picks up with clean Atlantic swells. This is when São Miguel starts feeling like summer without the summer prices — a genuine best-of-both-worlds month.",
    6: "June is glorious — 21°C, long sunny days, and the hydrangeas at full intensity turning the entire island into a blue-and-green postcard. The sea warms to 19°C for ocean swimming and the thermal pools offer a warm counterpoint. The Santo Cristo festival draws pilgrims and celebrations, and whale-watching tours run daily. Crowds are building toward summer levels but the island's size absorbs them well.",
    7: "July delivers São Miguel's best weather — 24°C, minimal rainfall, and nearly 8 hours of sunshine daily. The sea reaches 21°C, making the natural volcanic swimming pools at Mosteiros and Ferraria genuinely inviting. Hydrangeas are still blooming, whale watching continues strong, and canyoning in the island's lush ravines is at its most exhilarating. Peak season means higher prices and busier trails, but nowhere near Mediterranean-level chaos.",
    8: "August is the warmest month at 25°C with the driest skies and the sea at a comfortable 22°C — prime conditions for everything from diving and surfing to coasteering along the volcanic cliffs. The island buzzes with summer festivals and the diaspora returning for holidays. Book the volcanic cozido experience at Furnas well ahead, and grab a terrace table in Ponta Delgada for grilled limpets and Azorean pineapple. The busiest month, but the island handles it gracefully.",
    9: "September is arguably the smartest month to visit — still 23°C with warm seas at 22°C, but crowds drop noticeably and prices soften. Whale watching catches autumn migrants, the hydrangeas offer their last blooms, and the tea harvest continues at Gorreana. Swimming at natural pools and beaches remains perfect, and you'll find better availability at the island's best restaurants. The light turns golden and soft — photographers, take note.",
    10: "October sees temperatures easing to 20°C as the Atlantic reasserts itself with increasing rain. The island is spectacularly lush, thermal pools become even more appealing as the air cools, and whale watching remains possible though less reliable. Crowds thin to low levels, prices drop, and the cozido at Furnas steams up through volcanic earth with extra atmospheric drama. Pack a rain jacket and lean into the moody beauty.",
    11: "November is the return to proper Azorean winter — 18°C days, heavy rain, and skies that shift dramatically by the hour. The thermal pools at Furnas and Poça da Dona Beija become essential rather than optional, and the crater lakes take on a brooding intensity under low clouds. Tourist infrastructure stays open year-round on São Miguel, unlike the smaller islands, so you'll find restaurants and activities available at rock-bottom prices.",
    12: "December wraps São Miguel in Atlantic storms and quiet holiday charm — 16°C, significant rainfall, and short days brightened by Christmas lights in Ponta Delgada. The thermal pools steam invitingly against the cool air, volcanic stews bubble underground at Furnas, and you can hike the crater rims in dramatic solitude. New Year's Eve in Ponta Delgada brings fireworks over the marina. A wet, warm, and surprisingly festive end to the year.",
  },

  'pt-madeira': {
    1: "January in Madeira is the Atlantic's best-kept winter secret — 19°C highs, the levada trails are full and flowing, and the hillsides are carpeted in subtropical green. Rainfall is notable at around 100mm, mostly hitting the north coast while Funchal stays relatively dry. Crowds are low, hotel deals abound, and a poncha (Madeiran rum cocktail) after a levada hike through laurel forest feels downright medicinal. The sea sits at 18°C — brisk but swimmable if you're committed.",
    2: "February keeps the mild, lush formula going at 19°C with Carnival bringing an explosion of color to Funchal — the parade rivals Rio in enthusiasm if not quite in scale. The levada walks are at their most dramatic with waterfalls at full power, and the famous Mercado dos Lavradores overflows with exotic tropical fruits. Rain remains significant on the northern slopes, so plan hikes for the sunnier south side and always carry layers.",
    3: "March brings noticeably more sunshine and the first flush of spring flowers — Madeira's famous botanical diversity starts showing off with jacarandas, bird-of-paradise, and endemic orchids. Temperatures nudge to 19°C with drier spells, and the levada trails through the UNESCO laurisilva forest are at their most atmospheric. Crowds are still light and you can book top restaurants in Funchal without drama. The Pico do Arieiro sunrise hike is clearer now than in winter months.",
    4: "April is peak flower season — the Festa da Flor transforms Funchal into a wall-to-wall floral spectacle with parades, flower carpets, and displays that make Chelsea look understated. Temps reach 20°C with improving sunshine, and the levadas are still running strong. The sea warms to 18°C and whale-watching boats start spotting pilot whales and dolphins off the south coast. Shoulder-season pricing with near-peak-season beauty — this is the sweet spot.",
    5: "May delivers Madeira at its most balanced — 21°C, generous sunshine, and the tail end of the spring flower explosion still brightening every hillside. Levada hiking is sublime with comfortable temperatures and lush vegetation, and the sea warms enough (19°C) for natural lava-pool swimming at Porto Moniz. Crowds pick up but the island absorbs them across its dramatic vertical geography. Try espetada (beef on laurel skewers) at a mountain restaurant with views stretching to the horizon.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 23°C, long sunny days, and the sea warming to 21°C for comfortable swimming at Funchal's lido complex and the Porto Moniz natural pools. The Atlantic Festival lights up Funchal's harbor with spectacular Saturday-night fireworks all month. Levada walks are warm but manageable in the mornings, and dolphin-watching trips run daily. Peak season begins; prices rise and booking ahead becomes wise.",
    7: "July cranks up the heat to 25°C with virtually no rain and the longest days of the year — the sea hits 22°C, making beach time at Calheta's golden sand and Porto Moniz's rock pools irresistible. Levada hikes are best tackled early morning before the midday warmth, and the tropical fruit at the Mercado dos Lavradores peaks with passion fruit, custard apple, and tamarillo. Full peak season means higher prices, but Madeira never reaches Mediterranean-level overcrowding.",
    8: "August is the warmest month at 26°C with bone-dry conditions and the sea at its most inviting at 23°C. The island buzzes with summer visitors and returning diaspora, and the wine harvest begins in the steep terraced vineyards — join a vindima if you can. Canyoning in Madeira's dramatic ravines is at its most thrilling, and the sunset from Pico do Arieiro is reliably cloudless. Book everything well ahead; this is the island at maximum capacity.",
    9: "September is the insider's pick — still 25°C and dry, with the sea at a bathwater 23°C (the warmest of the year), but crowds thin and prices ease. The Madeira wine harvest continues in the terraced hillsides, and festival season winds down with the Colombo Festival in Porto Santo. Levada hiking is comfortable, the lava pools are warm, and you can snag a terrace table at Funchal's best seafood restaurants without a fight. Nearly perfect.",
    10: "October delivers warm autumn — 23°C days, the sea still a pleasant 22°C, and the first rains refreshing the levada trails without dampening plans too much. Crowds drop to moderate levels and prices soften noticeably. The subtropical gardens are spectacular with late-blooming flowers, and this is prime conditions for the challenging Pico do Arieiro to Pico Ruivo ridge hike. Poncha season never really ends, but it tastes better when you've earned it on a long trail.",
    11: "November marks the transition back to Atlantic weather — 21°C days, increasing rain (particularly on the north coast), and shorter afternoons. The levadas swell with fresh water and the waterfalls return to their dramatic best, especially the 25 Fontes and Risco trails. Crowds thin to low levels, deals appear on accommodation, and the warmth of a Funchal seafood restaurant after a misty forest hike is hard to beat. The Nature Festival often falls this month with organized hikes and trail events.",
    12: "December in Madeira is magical — Funchal goes all-in on Christmas and New Year's decorations, and the famous NYE fireworks display (Guinness-record-holding) draws visitors from across Europe. Temps hover at a pleasant 19°C, the levada trails are lush and waterfall-rich, and the traditional bolo de mel (honey cake) appears in every bakery. Rain is present but usually passes quickly, and the festive energy combined with subtropical warmth makes this one of Europe's most charming winter escapes.",
  },

  'pt-porto-douro': {
    1: "January in Porto is atmospheric and affordable — 14°C highs, frequent rain (around 160mm), and those moody skies that make the Ribeira waterfront look like a oil painting. Crowds are minimal, port wine cellars in Vila Nova de Gaia are uncrowded, and a francesinha (Porto's gloriously excessive cheese-and-meat sandwich) tastes even better when it's grey outside. The Douro Valley vineyards are bare and terraced in sculptural beauty.",
    2: "February stays cool and damp at 14°C, but carnival brings sporadic celebrations and the almond trees in the upper Douro Valley begin their early bloom — pink and white blossoms against terraced hillsides. Port cellars offer unhurried tastings, the Livraria Lello is actually visitable without a two-hour queue, and hotel prices remain very friendly. Pack an umbrella and a hearty appetite for caldo verde and rojões.",
    3: "March signals spring's arrival — temps reach 16°C, rainfall eases, and Porto's famous azulejo-clad churches gleam in increasing sunshine. The Douro Valley starts greening up, making river cruises more scenic, and the city's food scene buzzes with seasonal dishes. Tourist numbers pick up but nothing painful — you can still wander the Ribeira and climb the Clérigos Tower without queuing. A very pleasant shoulder-season window.",
    4: "April delivers Porto at its springtime best — 18°C, abundant sunshine, and the Douro Valley vineyards bursting into fresh green leaf against their schist terraces. River cruises through the valley are gorgeous, São João festival anticipation builds, and the city's craft beer and wine bar scene is thriving. Crowds are moderate and building; book the better restaurants and port lodges in advance. Pair a morning at Bolhão Market with bacalhau à brás and you're living right.",
    5: "May is outstanding — 20°C, the driest month of spring, and Porto glowing under generous sunshine. The Douro Valley is lush and vine-covered, perfect for a rabelo boat cruise or a drive along the N222 (one of the world's best roads). Beaches at Foz do Douro become viable for sunbathing if not quite swimming at 16°C. The city pulses with energy, outdoor terraces fill, and queues at Pastéis de Belém's Porto rivals are just starting to form.",
    6: "June brings São João — Porto's wildest night on June 23rd, when the entire city takes to the streets wielding plastic hammers, grilling sardines, and launching sky lanterns from every bridge and balcony. It's extraordinary and unmissable. Temps hit 23°C, sunshine is abundant, and the Douro Valley is photogenically vine-draped. Peak season begins and prices reflect it, but the festive energy of São João alone justifies the trip.",
    7: "July heats Porto up to 25°C with virtually no rain and long, luminous evenings perfect for sipping port on the Ribeira terraces. The Atlantic beaches at Matosinhos become the city's living room, though the water stays a bracing 17°C — refreshing after sunbathing. The Douro Valley bakes under clear skies, making morning vineyard visits wise. Full peak season: book everything ahead and expect busy streets and bridges, but the vibe is electric.",
    8: "August pushes temperatures to 26°C and keeps the rain away — Porto is at its sunniest and busiest, with beach culture at Foz and Matosinhos in full swing (sea: 18°C, still bracing). Many locals holiday elsewhere, giving the city an interesting mix of tourist buzz and quiet back-street calm. Douro Valley wine estates are gearing up for harvest, and a vineyard lunch with tasting overlooking the terraced river valley is pure summer perfection.",
    9: "September is Porto's golden month — still 24°C and sunny, but crowds ease and the Douro Valley grape harvest (vindima) begins, filling the terraces with workers and the air with the scent of crushed fruit. Many quintas welcome visitors to join the harvest and foot-tread the grapes — a once-in-a-lifetime experience. Beach days are still possible, port cellars are less frenetic, and the quality of light along the Douro is at its most painterly.",
    10: "October cools to 20°C as rain returns and Porto slips into its atmospheric autumn mode — think golden light on granite facades, fewer crowds, and the Douro Valley's vineyards turning amber and russet. Port wine harvest wraps up, tasting rooms are well-stocked, and the city's taverns serve hearty seasonal dishes. Livraria Lello queues shrink, Bolhão Market bustles with autumn produce, and a misty morning walk across the Dom Luís I Bridge is genuinely cinematic.",
    11: "November is honest Porto — 16°C, significant rain, and the kind of grey Atlantic skies that make the city's port cellars and cozy tascas feel like essential destinations rather than options. The Douro Valley is quiet and stark, with bare vines tracing geometric patterns up the hillsides. Crowds are minimal, prices are at their lowest, and this is prime time for a deep dive into Porto's food scene: roasted chestnuts, tripas à moda do Porto, and port by the fire.",
    12: "December dresses Porto in holiday lights and market stalls — the Avenida dos Aliados becomes a festive focal point with Christmas markets and a towering tree. Temps hover at 14°C with plenty of rain, but the warmth of a port lodge tasting in Gaia and a francesinha at a steamed-up taverna window more than compensate. New Year's Eve brings fireworks over the Douro. Crowds spike around Christmas but remain manageable compared to Lisbon.",
  },

  'pw-palau': {
    1: "January in Palau is tail-end wet season — 300mm+ of rain, 30°C heat, and humidity that'll have you living in your swimsuit. But here's the thing: diving is still world-class, with manta rays cruising German Channel and visibility hovering around 20-25m between downpours. Crowds are light and dive boats feel uncrowded, making this a solid budget play for serious underwater enthusiasts. Jellyfish Lake is open and mesmerizing year-round.",
    2: "February is the driest month of the wet season — rainfall drops noticeably, skies clear more often, and the sea at 29°C is a warm bath. Diving conditions improve at Blue Corner and Ulong Channel, with sharks, mantas, and Napoleon wrasse showing up reliably. Tourist numbers remain low, and the handful of resorts offer softer pricing. The coral is vibrant, the visibility is good, and you'll share the rock islands kayaking trails with almost nobody.",
    3: "March marks the transition to dry season — rain decreases, sunshine increases, and Palau starts looking like the brochure. Diving is excellent with 30m+ visibility at sites like Blue Hole and New Drop-Off, and the 30°C water temperature means a 3mm wetsuit is purely optional. This is a sweet shoulder month: prices haven't peaked, crowds are moderate, and conditions are outstanding for both above and below the waterline.",
    4: "April kicks off proper dry season — clear skies, calmer seas, and diving visibility stretching to 35m+. The water is a perfect 29°C, manta rays are reliable at German Channel, and the Rock Islands Southern Lagoon (a UNESCO site) is at its most photogenic. Tourist numbers start climbing, especially with dive groups, so book liveaboards and top resorts well ahead. Kayaking through the limestone mushroom islands is magical in the flat conditions.",
    5: "May delivers prime Palau — minimal rain, 31°C days, and the ocean like glass for diving and snorkeling. Blue Corner is electric with grey reef sharks, barracuda walls, and eagle rays, while Jellyfish Lake's golden jellies pulse in warm, stratified water. Peak season pricing is in effect and the best dive operators book out weeks ahead. If you've been dreaming about Palau, this is the month the dreams are based on.",
    6: "June continues the dry-season excellence with clear skies, calm seas, and outstanding 30m+ dive visibility. Temperatures hold at 31°C and the humidity is more bearable than the wet months. Shark diversity at Blue Corner peaks, and night dives reveal mandarin fish and nautilus in the shallows. Crowds are at their height for the year — serious divers from around the world converge, so book everything months in advance.",
    7: "July is the heart of dry season — expect reliable sunshine, 30°C, and pristine diving conditions across all major sites. Manta cleaning stations are active, the outer reef walls teem with pelagics, and snorkeling the Rock Islands reveals visibility you'll struggle to find anywhere else on earth. Prices remain at peak levels but the conditions justify every dollar. Non-divers can kayak, paddleboard, and explore WWII relics on Peleliu.",
    8: "August stays dry and warm at 30°C with excellent diving, though the first hints of the approaching wet season may bring occasional afternoon showers by month's end. The reefs are in magnificent condition, whale sharks make rare but thrilling appearances, and the Rock Islands glow turquoise under clear skies. This is the last of the prime dry-season months — catch it before the rains return.",
    9: "September signals the wet season's return — rainfall picks up, afternoon thunderstorms become regular, and the sea gets a touch choppier. But diving remains excellent between weather windows, the 29°C water stays bathwater-warm, and the reef life doesn't care about rain. Crowds thin noticeably, prices start easing, and you'll get more personalized attention from dive guides. Bring a rain jacket topside; underwater, it's still paradise.",
    10: "October is solidly wet season — 350mm+ of rain, high humidity, and grey mornings that clear to dramatic afternoon skies. Diving conditions are more variable but still good at sheltered sites like Blue Hole and German Channel, and the nutrient-rich runoff brings mantas and whale sharks closer. This is low season with the best prices of the year and empty dive boats. Embrace the rain and you'll be rewarded with uncrowded world-class reefs.",
    11: "November is peak wet season — heavy rain, high humidity, and the wettest month of the year. Seas can be rough, making outer reef dives weather-dependent, but inner lagoon sites and Jellyfish Lake remain accessible and beautiful. The upside: rock-bottom prices, virtually no crowds, and the lush green of the Rock Islands at maximum intensity. Serious divers who don't mind topside weather will find excellent conditions when the windows open.",
    12: "December keeps the rain coming but spirits are high — holiday visitors add a modest bump to otherwise quiet resorts, and the diving remains surprisingly good at sheltered sites. Water temperature stays at a toasty 29°C, visibility is 15-20m at inner sites, and the reef life is as abundant as ever. Christmas in a Palauan guesthouse with fresh seafood and warm rain pattering on the roof is more charming than it sounds.",
  },

  'py-paraguay': {
    1: "January is peak Paraguayan summer — sweltering 35°C+ days, high humidity, and the kind of heat that makes a tereré (cold mate) not just refreshing but essential to survival. The Paraguay River runs high, rainstorms are dramatic afternoon affairs, and Asunción's streets thin out as locals flee to countryside estancias. If you can handle the heat, catch a Cerro Porteño football match and eat empanadas in the Mercado 4 chaos.",
    2: "February continues the furnace — 34°C with thunderstorms rolling through most afternoons and humidity that feels like wearing a warm, wet blanket. Carnival celebrations bring color and music to Encarnación (Paraguay's 'Carnival Capital'), rivaling Brazilian festivities with samba, floats, and enthusiasm. The Chaco is best avoided unless you enjoy testing the limits of human perspiration. Stick to Asunción's air-conditioned museums and riverside restaurants.",
    3: "March starts easing the worst of summer — highs drop to 32°C but humidity stays oppressive, and the rainy season continues with 130mm+ of precipitation. The Pantanal wetlands in the northeast are flooding, creating excellent birdwatching as wading species concentrate. Asunción's Costanera riverside promenade is pleasant in the evenings, and the asado (grilled meat) culture is in full swing at every weekend gathering.",
    4: "April brings blessed relief — temps drop to a comfortable 27°C, rainfall decreases, and the humidity finally becomes bearable. This is when Paraguay starts feeling genuinely pleasant, with golden autumn light filtering through Asunción's jacaranda-lined streets. The Jesuit ruins at Trinidad and Jesús are comfortable to explore, and the Chaco becomes accessible for wildlife drives. A genuinely underrated month in an underrated country.",
    5: "May is Paraguayan autumn at its best — 23°C days, dry weather, and clear skies perfect for exploring the Jesuit missions or driving into the Chaco. Tereré gives way to hot mate as mornings cool, and the weekend asado gatherings shift to longer, lazier affairs in the mild sunshine. The Paraguay River drops to navigable levels, and the Pantanal dries enough for wildlife spotting along the Trans-Chaco Highway.",
    6: "June brings Paraguay's winter — which by most standards is still pleasant at 20°C, though nights can drop to 8°C and the occasional cold front from Patagonia (the 'surazo') can shock everyone into jacket territory. The Chaco is at its driest and best for wildlife encounters with jaguars, giant anteaters, and hundreds of bird species. Asunción's food markets serve warming sopá paraguaya (cornbread) and locro stew. Delightful if you pack layers.",
    7: "July is the coldest month — 19°C days with occasional frosts in southern Paraguay, though by global standards it's hardly Arctic. The dry weather makes this excellent for exploring the Chaco's wilderness, visiting the Jesuit ruins, and enjoying Asunción without sweating through your clothes. The Fiesta de San Blas brings traditional celebrations, and the city's small but growing craft beer scene thrives in the cooler weather.",
    8: "August stays cool and dry at 21°C — the tail end of winter before the heat starts building again. Controlled burns in the Chaco can create hazy skies but also concentrate wildlife around remaining water sources, making this a prime month for safari-style drives. The citrus harvest brings excellent oranges to the markets, and Asunción's cultural calendar picks up with theatre and music festivals. One of the most comfortable months to visit.",
    9: "September marks spring's arrival — jacaranda trees begin their purple bloom across Asunción, temps climb to 25°C, and the first heat shimmer appears on the Chaco horizon. Spring showers start but remain light, and the birdlife in the Pantanal wetlands becomes increasingly active with breeding season approaching. This is a sweet shoulder month: pleasant weather, minimal tourists (Paraguay never really has crowds), and the countryside in fresh green renewal.",
    10: "October heats up to 29°C with increasing humidity and afternoon thunderstorms returning to the forecast. The jacarandas are in full bloom, the Paraguay River starts rising, and the Chaco's dry landscapes begin greening up. This is a transition month — still comfortable enough for exploration but building toward the furnace-like summer ahead. Asunción's outdoor restaurants buzz on warm evenings, and the mango trees start fruiting.",
    11: "November cranks the dial — 32°C, high humidity, and serious thunderstorms that light up the sky over the Paraguay River. The wet season is fully underway, the Chaco roads start becoming difficult, and heat advisories are a real thing. But the lush green landscape, abundant fruit (mango season!), and the pre-holiday energy in Asunción have their own appeal. Hydrate with tereré and time outdoor activities for the cooler morning hours.",
    12: "December is full tropical summer — 34°C, torrential afternoon rains, and humidity that makes everything stick to everything else. Asunción winds down for the holidays with Christmas celebrations, nativity scenes, and family asados that stretch from noon to midnight. The Chaco is essentially impassable in parts, but the wetlands are dramatically flooded and alive with birdlife. Come for the cultural warmth and festive spirit, just not for the actual temperature.",
  },

  'qa-doha': {
    1: "January is Doha at its most pleasant — 22°C highs, zero rain, and sunshine that feels like a gift rather than an assault. The souqs of Souq Waqif bustle without the summer desperation for AC, and the Museum of Islamic Art gleams against cool blue skies. Desert camping at the Inland Sea is sublime with comfortable nights around 14°C. This is peak tourist season, so book ahead, but the weather justifies the premium entirely.",
    2: "February continues the golden stretch — 23°C, clear skies, and the desert in its most photogenic mood with occasional light cloud cover softening the harsh light. Kayaking through the mangroves at Al Thakira is perfect in the mild conditions, and the dune bashing at Khor Al Adaid is thrilling without heat exhaustion. Crowds are moderate-to-busy and Qatar's cultural calendar fills with festivals and exhibitions.",
    3: "March warms to 27°C — still comfortable but you can feel summer's approach in the afternoon sun. The water at Banana Island and Katara Beach reaches a pleasant 22°C, making morning beach sessions enjoyable. Spring brings occasional desert wildflowers after rare winter rains, and the Souq Waqif's outdoor dining terraces are buzzing in the evenings. This is your last comfortable window before the heat wall hits.",
    4: "April crosses the comfort threshold for many — 33°C highs with increasing humidity, and outdoor activities start requiring serious planning around cooler hours. The sea warms to 24°C for swimming, and early mornings in the desert are still beautiful. Indoor Doha excels: the National Museum of Qatar, Mathaf modern art museum, and the Pearl-Qatar's air-conditioned luxury all shine. Crowds thin as heat-averse visitors depart.",
    5: "May is when Qatar gets honest about being a desert — 39°C highs, blazing sunshine, and humidity starting its summer climb. Outdoor exploration becomes a dawn-or-dusk proposition, and the ultra-modern malls transform from shopping destinations to survival necessities. The sea at 27°C offers welcome relief, and dhow cruises at sunset are genuinely magical in the warm evenings. Hotel prices drop as the off-season begins.",
    6: "June enters the furnace — 42°C days, oppressive humidity, and an intensity that clears the streets by 10am. The upside: hotel prices crater, the indoor attractions are world-class and blissfully empty, and the sea at 30°C is like a warm bath. Desert excursions are genuinely dangerous in midday heat, so restrict outdoor time to brief sunset trips. Air-conditioned Doha — the restaurants, museums, malls — is actually brilliant if you accept the rhythm.",
    7: "July is Qatar's most extreme month — 43°C with humidity that makes the 'real feel' even worse, and stepping outside is like walking into a hairdryer aimed at a sauna. The sea at 32°C barely refreshes. This is deep off-season with the lowest prices and emptiest hotels; the city essentially turns inward. If you come, live like the locals: late dinners, mall culture, indoor sports complexes, and the extraordinary Aspire Zone facilities.",
    8: "August rivals July for sheer intensity — 42°C, peak humidity, and air so thick you can practically chew it. The Gulf waters hit their warmest at 33°C, which is surreal but not exactly refreshing. Virtually no tourists brave these conditions, so the few who do get VIP treatment at restaurants and hotels offering rock-bottom rates. Stick to indoor Doha: the food scene is exceptional, the museums are empty, and the people-watching at The Pearl is fascinating.",
    9: "September begins the long exhale — temps ease to 39°C but humidity peaks, creating a peculiarly sticky heat that requires strategy. The sea stays bath-warm at 31°C and sunset dhow cruises become slightly more bearable. This is still firmly off-season with low prices, but the cultural calendar starts stirring with early-season events. The promise of October's relief makes September feel more hopeful than it probably deserves.",
    10: "October is the turning point — temps drop to a manageable 35°C, humidity recedes, and Doha starts breathing again. Desert camping becomes viable in the cooling evenings, Souq Waqif's terraces reopen with gusto, and the Formula 1 (or other major sporting events) season often kicks off. Hotel prices start climbing as the good-weather tourists return. This is when outdoor Qatar reopens, and the relief is palpable across the entire city.",
    11: "November is magnificent — 29°C, low humidity, clear skies, and the kind of weather that makes you understand why people live here. Desert excursions to the Inland Sea and Film City are comfortable all day, the beaches are stunning, and the Corniche promenade fills with joggers and strollers at sunset. Qatar National Day (December 18) anticipation builds with cultural events. Peak season pricing kicks in, but the conditions are worth every riyal.",
    12: "December delivers Doha's finest — 24°C highs, cool desert nights, zero rain, and a festive energy boosted by Qatar National Day celebrations on the 18th with military parades, fireworks, and citywide festivities. The desert is perfect for overnight camping, the sea at 22°C is refreshing for winter swims, and the restaurant scene fires on all cylinders. Peak season means premium prices and advance booking is essential, but this is Qatar at its absolute best.",
  },

  're-reunion': {
    1: "January is peak Southern Hemisphere summer and deep cyclone season — 30°C, 300mm+ of rain, and humidity that envelops everything on this volcanic Indian Ocean island. The Piton de la Fournaise volcano is often off-limits during heavy rains, and some cirque trails close due to landslide risk. But the tropical fruits are extraordinary (lychees, mangoes), the Creole cuisine is at its richest, and the beaches at Saint-Gilles stay swimmable at 28°C.",
    2: "February continues cyclone season with the heaviest rainfall — Réunion holds the world record for most rain in 24 hours, and February regularly reminds everyone why. Temperatures stay at 30°C, trails can be treacherous, and the east coast gets drenched. But between storms the volcanic landscape is staggeringly lush, the waterfalls are at maximum power, and the local rhum arrangé tastes even better when you're watching a storm roll over the Cirque de Mafate.",
    3: "March starts easing the cyclone intensity — still hot at 29°C with significant rain, but the worst storms usually pass by mid-month. The Piton de la Fournaise may erupt (it's one of the world's most active volcanoes, and eruptions are spectacular rather than dangerous). Hiking the three cirques becomes more viable, and the sugarcane harvest begins, bringing cane juice and fresh rhum to roadside stalls. Crowds are low and prices reasonable.",
    4: "April marks the transition to the dry, cool season — temps ease to 27°C, rainfall drops sharply, and the hiking trails through the Cirque de Cilaos and Mafate start drying out. This is one of the best months for trekking the GR R2 trail across the island's volcanic spine. The sea stays warm at 27°C for snorkeling at L'Ermitage lagoon, and the Creole cuisine — cari poulet, rougail saucisse — sustains you through long trail days.",
    5: "May is dry-season bliss — 25°C, clear skies, and the volcanic landscapes in sharp, dramatic relief under crisp light. The Piton des Neiges (3,070m) summit hike is at its most reliable, and the cirques are spectacular with reduced cloud cover. Whale-watching season begins as humpbacks arrive from Antarctic waters. The sea cools to 25°C but remains comfortable, and the lack of crowds means trail huts and gîtes are easy to book.",
    6: "June brings the coolest, driest weather of the year — 23°C at the coast with mountain temperatures dropping into single digits at altitude. Humpback whale watching is in full swing off Saint-Gilles, and the hiking is superb in the clear, cool conditions. The annual whale festival celebrates the marine visitors with events across the west coast. Pack warm layers for mountain hikes and enjoy the most comfortable month to explore this dramatically vertical island.",
    7: "July is winter and school holidays — 22°C at the coast, potentially freezing at Piton des Neiges summit, and the driest conditions of the year. French families arrive for vacation, making it the busiest month, and hiking huts in the cirques book out fast. Whale watching peaks with mothers and calves visible from shore, and the cloudless mornings reveal the volcano in its full, stark glory. Book accommodation and hut reservations well in advance.",
    8: "August continues the dry-season peak — 22°C, crystal skies, and the humpback whale season at its most spectacular with breaching and nursing visible from the coast. Crowds match July as French school holidays continue, and the hiking trails are at their busiest but also their best condition. The Piton de la Fournaise is typically accessible, and the panoramic views from the Maïdo lookout over Mafate cirque at sunrise are absolutely worth the 4am alarm.",
    9: "September eases off the crowd pressure as holidays end — still dry and clear at 23°C with excellent hiking and whale-watching conditions. The cirque trails are in prime shape, accommodation opens up, and prices start softening. This is the savvy hiker's month: all the dry-season benefits with fewer people. The sea warms slightly to 23°C, and the vanilla plantations on the east coast are fragrant and open for visits.",
    10: "October warms to 25°C as the dry season transitions — rain starts returning with occasional afternoon showers, but the hiking remains excellent and whale watching catches the last departing humpbacks. The volcanic landscape starts showing fresh green after the first rains, and the Piton de la Fournaise often stirs with increased activity. Crowds are light, prices are moderate, and the tropical fruit season is just beginning.",
    11: "November is the transition into wet season — 27°C, increasing rain and humidity, and the first hints of cyclone-season energy building. The hiking trails are still passable but require more weather awareness, and the waterfalls start gaining power. Lychee season begins (Réunion's are legendary), tropical flowers bloom profusely, and the beaches at Saint-Gilles warm to 26°C. A good month for combining some hiking with beach days and culinary exploration.",
    12: "December brings summer heat (29°C), humidity, and the official start of cyclone season — rain builds to 200mm+ and the mountains often cloud over by midday. But the festive season brings lively Creole celebrations, the tropical fruits are extraordinary (lychees, mangoes, pineapple), and the Christmas reveillon dinner is a spectacular Creole feast. Beach time at the lagoon is warm and pleasant between showers, and rhum arrangé flows freely at every gathering.",
  },

  'ro-blacksea': {
    1: "January on Romania's Black Sea coast is bleak and beautiful in equal measure — 4°C highs, biting winds off the water, and the Danube Delta frozen into an otherworldly landscape. Constanța's seafood restaurants serve steaming fish soup (ciorbă de pește) to the few visitors brave enough to come. Birdwatching in the Delta drops off as most species migrate, though white-tailed eagles and other winter residents remain. Prices are at absolute rock-bottom.",
    2: "February keeps the chill at 5°C with occasional snow and the Delta still largely frozen or waterlogged. It's arguably the quietest month on the coast, but early signs of spring migration begin as some bird species start returning to the wetlands. The coastal resort town of Mamaia is a ghost town of shuttered hotels, lending it an eerie, post-apocalyptic charm. Warm up with mici (grilled meat rolls) and țuică (plum brandy) in Constanța.",
    3: "March brings the first thaw — temps edge toward 10°C and the Danube Delta starts its spring transformation as water levels rise and early migrant birds return. The coast remains quiet and wind-swept, but sunny days hint at the beach season ahead. Constanța's museums and the Roman mosaic building are pleasant without summer crowds. A transitional month best appreciated by birdwatchers with good patience and warm clothing.",
    4: "April is when the Danube Delta truly awakens — pelicans return in their thousands, water lilies start budding, and the wetlands teem with life at 16°C under increasingly sunny skies. The Black Sea is still too cold for swimming at 10°C, but the coast blooms with wildflowers and the resort infrastructure starts gearing up. Boat tours through the Delta's labyrinthine channels are magical in the spring light, with egrets and herons around every bend.",
    5: "May is arguably the best month for the Danube Delta — breeding colonies of white and Dalmatian pelicans are in full swing, the water lilies carpet the channels, and temperatures reach a comfortable 22°C. The Black Sea warms to 15°C (still bracing), but the coastal bluffs are gorgeous for hiking. Crowds are light, boat tour operators are available without booking weeks ahead, and the Delta's biodiversity — over 300 bird species — is peaking.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 27°C, long sunny days, and the Black Sea finally reaching a swimmable 21°C. Mamaia's beach clubs and resort strips come alive, and the Delta's water lilies reach their spectacular peak, turning entire channels white and yellow. Bird colonies are active with chicks, and kayaking through the quieter channels is unforgettable. Crowds build along the coast but the Delta absorbs visitors easily. Fresh sturgeon and Delta fish dishes are seasonal highlights.",
    7: "July is peak beach season — 30°C, blazing sunshine, and the Black Sea at 24°C drawing Romanian and Bulgarian holidaymakers to Mamaia, Vama Veche, and the resort strip in force. The Danube Delta is lush and alive but the heat and mosquitoes make boat tours best scheduled for early morning. Vama Veche's bohemian beach party vibe is in full swing. Expect crowded beaches, higher prices, and a festive energy along the entire coast.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 30°C, peak crowds, and the sea at its warmest at 25°C. Mamaia is shoulder-to-shoulder, Vama Veche hosts music festivals, and the entire coast buzzes with summer energy. The Delta is at maximum lushness but also maximum mosquito activity — dawn boat tours with repellent are the strategy. This is Romania's summer playground at full volume: loud, fun, and utterly packed. Book everything months ahead.",
    9: "September is the coast's redemption month — still 24°C and sunny, the sea holds at 22°C, but crowds thin dramatically after the first week as Romanian schools restart. The Danube Delta is spectacular with autumn migrations beginning, pelicans preparing to depart, and the wetlands glowing gold in the softer light. Mamaia's beach clubs quiet down to manageable levels, and the freshwater fish at Delta restaurants is at its flavorful peak.",
    10: "October brings autumn to the Delta in golden fashion — 17°C, migratory birds passing through in enormous flocks, and the wetland reeds turning amber under moody skies. The Black Sea cools to 16°C, ending the swimming season, and coastal resorts start closing for winter. But boat tours through the Delta's autumn landscape, with pelicans gathering for departure and raptors overhead, are hauntingly beautiful. Bring binoculars and warm layers.",
    11: "November signals winter's approach — 10°C, grey skies, and the last migratory birds departing the Danube Delta. The coast is windswept and melancholy, with most resort infrastructure shuttered until May. Constanța itself remains lively with its university population and working-port energy, and the seafood is excellent year-round. A raw, atmospheric month for those who prefer their coastal towns without the polish — just you, the gulls, and the Black Sea.",
    12: "December chills the coast to 5°C with rain, occasional snow, and the Danube Delta entering its winter dormancy. Christmas markets in Constanța bring modest festive cheer, and the coastal towns have a quiet, reflective beauty under winter skies. Winter birdwatching in the Delta can still reward with eagles and wintering waterfowl for the dedicated. This is strictly off-season — moody, empty, and perfect for misanthropic romantics.",
  },

  'ro-bucharest': {
    1: "January in Bucharest is proper continental winter — -1°C highs, occasional snow blanketing the grand boulevards, and a grey sky that makes the heated terraces of the Old Town feel essential. The Palace of Parliament (second-largest building in the world) is uncrowded and imposing, and the food scene thrives with hearty sarmale (cabbage rolls) and warming ciorbă soups. Crowds are minimal and hotel prices are at their lowest. Pack thermals and drink țuică to stay warm.",
    2: "February keeps the freeze going at 2°C with the most snowfall of the year — Bucharest under fresh snow is genuinely pretty, especially the Herăstrău Park lakeside and the grand Art Deco facades. Mărțișor celebrations begin at month's end, with red-and-white spring tokens exchanged everywhere. The city's museums and galleries are uncrowded and excellent, particularly the National Art Museum. Warm up with a covrigi (pretzel) and hot chocolate at a café in the Lipscani district.",
    3: "March signals spring's approach — temps climb to 10°C, the Mărțișor tradition fills the streets with vendors selling spring charms, and the first outdoor terraces start testing the waters. The parks begin greening up and magnolias bloom in the botanical garden. Tourist numbers remain low, making this a great time for the big cultural sites without queues. A jacket is still necessary, but the days are noticeably longer and brighter.",
    4: "April is Bucharest's spring bloom — 17°C, cherry blossoms in Cișmigiu Gardens, and the city shaking off winter with a visible energy. Outdoor terraces reopen across the Old Town, the craft beer scene (surprisingly excellent) spills onto sidewalks, and Herăstrău Park fills with joggers and families. Easter (Orthodox timing, often later than Western) brings painted eggs, lamb dishes, and church celebrations. A lovely month with manageable crowds and fair prices.",
    5: "May is outstanding — 23°C, long sunny days, and Bucharest at its most vibrant. The Old Town pulses with nightlife, Herăstrău Park is in full green glory, and the street food scene — mici, covrigi, kürtőskalács — hits its stride. Day-trip to the Comana Natural Park for spring birdwatching, or explore the Bărăgan Plain wildflowers. Crowds are moderate and building; this is the sweet spot between spring freshness and summer heat.",
    6: "June brings summer — 28°C, generous sunshine, and Bucharest's famous outdoor terrace culture in full swing. The city's parks host open-air concerts and cinema, and the food scene extends well past midnight. Thunderstorms can be dramatic but pass quickly. Crowds are busy but not overwhelming, and the Village Museum's open-air exhibits are at their best in the warm light. This is when Bucharest feels most cosmopolitan and alive.",
    7: "July pushes to 31°C with occasional fierce thunderstorms that break the heat. Bucharest can feel emptied as locals flee to the mountains or coast, leaving the city's Old Town bars and restaurants in a curious tourist-and-expat bubble. The parks provide shade, the public pools and Therme Bucharest spa complex offer relief, and evening dining on the terraces stretches deliciously late. Not the most atmospheric month, but the summer energy is undeniable.",
    8: "August is Bucharest's hottest — 32°C with humidity and afternoon storms, and a ghost-town quality as the city empties for summer holidays. If you stay, you'll find easy restaurant reservations, uncrowded museums, and a laid-back vibe in the normally hectic Old Town. Therme Bucharest's pools are a lifesaver, and evening concerts in the parks make the heat bearable. It's an acquired taste, but budget travelers will find excellent value.",
    9: "September is Bucharest reborn — 25°C, golden light, and the city snapping back to life as everyone returns from holiday. The cultural season kicks off with theatre, concerts, and gallery openings, and the Old Town terraces enjoy their last warm hurrah. George Enescu Festival (biennial, September) transforms the city into a world-class classical music destination. The food markets brim with autumn grapes, plums, and peppers. A genuinely excellent month.",
    10: "October dresses Bucharest in autumn color — 17°C, golden leaves in Herăstrău and Cișmigiu parks, and a crisp energy in the air. Wine harvest season means excellent new vintages appearing in wine bars across the city, and the food scene pivots to hearty stews and sarmale. Crowds are light, prices are moderate, and the grand Belle Époque architecture looks stunning against autumn foliage. Bring a light jacket and an appetite.",
    11: "November signals winter's return — 9°C, grey skies, and the first frost dusting the parks. Christmas markets start appearing toward month's end, and the city hunkers down into its indoor pleasures: museums, restaurants, and the increasingly excellent wine bar scene. The Old Town stays lively on weekends, and the warming effect of a proper mămăligă cu brânză (polenta with cheese) at a traditional restaurant shouldn't be underestimated.",
    12: "December transforms Bucharest with Christmas markets, twinkling lights along the boulevards, and holiday energy that softens the -1°C chill. The market in Constitution Square is the biggest, with mulled wine, cozonac (sweet bread), and holiday crafts. New Year's Eve brings large public celebrations and fireworks. The Palace of Parliament looks almost magical under snow, and the city's hospitality — warm, generous, slightly chaotic — is at its most endearing.",
  },

  'ro-transylvania': {
    1: "January in Transylvania is a snow-globe fantasy — -2°C highs, heavy snow blanketing the Carpathian Mountains, and medieval towns like Brașov and Sibiu looking like they've been waiting all year for this moment. Skiing at Poiana Brașov is in full swing, and the fortified churches of the Saxon villages are hauntingly beautiful under winter snow. Crowds are low outside the ski resorts, and warming up with a sarmale and țuică at a traditional guesthouse is practically mandatory.",
    2: "February keeps Transylvania deep in winter — -1°C, reliable snow cover, and the best skiing conditions of the year at Poiana Brașov and Sinaia. The medieval citadel of Sighișoara (Dracula's supposed birthplace) is atmospheric beyond belief under grey winter skies, and bear-watching tours in the forests can spot tracks in fresh snow. Costs are reasonable, crowds are thin outside ski weekends, and the Carpathian wilderness has a silent, fairy-tale quality.",
    3: "March brings the first spring thaw — snow starts melting at lower elevations while the mountains stay white, creating dramatic contrasts around the fortified churches and castle ruins. Temps climb to 8°C and wildflowers push through in sheltered valleys. Skiing remains viable at higher resorts, but the hiking season begins tentatively on lower trails. Brașov's Council Square starts setting up outdoor terraces on warmer days.",
    4: "April is Transylvania in bloom — 15°C, wildflower meadows carpeting the rolling hills between fortified villages, and the Carpathian foothills at their most photographically lush. Brown bears emerge from hibernation, making bear-watching hides near Brașov increasingly productive. The medieval towns are pleasantly uncrowded, Easter celebrations in the Saxon and Szekler communities are deeply traditional, and a hike to Bran Castle through spring forest is enchanting.",
    5: "May is arguably peak Transylvania — 20°C, endless wildflower meadows (some of Europe's last untouched hay meadows), and the Carpathians in full green splendor. Brown bear activity is high, hiking trails are in excellent condition, and the medieval towns of Sibiu, Brașov, and Sighișoara are lively but not overrun. The food scene showcases spring lamb and fresh herbs, and horse-drawn carts still outnumber cars on some village roads. Magical and still affordable.",
    6: "June brings warm summer weather — 25°C with afternoon thunderstorms that keep things green and dramatic. Transylvania's festivals kick off: Sibiu International Theatre Festival is world-class, and village fairs across the region celebrate with folk music and traditional food. Hiking in the Făgăraș Mountains is superb, bear watching is reliable, and the long evenings in Brașov's beer gardens are perfect. Crowds are moderate and the vibe is electric.",
    7: "July heats up to 28°C with occasional heavy thunderstorms in the mountains. Hiking the Făgăraș Ridge — the highest section of the Romanian Carpathians — is at its best with mountain huts open and trails clear. The Carpathian forests buzz with wildlife, and the medieval festival circuit continues with events in Sighișoara and beyond. Peak season brings higher prices at popular guesthouses, so book ahead. Fresh berries appear at every market stall.",
    8: "August matches July's warmth at 27°C and brings Sighișoara's Medieval Festival — a three-day extravaganza of jousting, crafts, and feasting in the citadel that feels like actual time travel. The Făgăraș Ridge hiking is superb, wild mushroom foraging begins in the forests, and the Szekler communities host traditional harvest-prep festivals. This is peak season with the highest visitor numbers, but Transylvania's vastness absorbs them gracefully.",
    9: "September is Transylvania's golden month — 22°C, misty mornings over the valleys, and the forests beginning their slow turn from green to gold and copper. The grape and plum harvests fill village kitchens with the scent of must and jam-making, and fresh țuică distillation begins in every other courtyard. Hiking remains excellent with comfortable temperatures, crowds thin after the first week, and the medieval towns are bathed in that honeyed autumn light. Simply gorgeous.",
    10: "October is peak autumn — 14°C, the Carpathian forests blazing with color, and morning mists wreathing the fortified churches and castle ruins in atmospheric gauze. Bear watching remains productive as the animals feed heavily before winter, and the hay meadows are golden and stubbled. The fortified churches of Viscri, Biertan, and Prejmer are stunning against autumn foliage. Tourist numbers drop, prices soften, and Transylvania feels like a place that time genuinely forgot.",
    11: "November brings winter's first bite — 6°C, bare trees, and the first snow on the Carpathian peaks. The medieval towns take on a stark, Gothic beauty that feels appropriate for Dracula country, and the food turns hearty: stews, cabbage rolls, and roasted meats. The first Christmas market stalls appear in Sibiu and Brașov by month's end, and the countryside goes quiet in a way that's either peaceful or eerie depending on your disposition.",
    12: "December in Transylvania is storybook winter — snow on the medieval rooftops, Christmas markets in Sibiu and Brașov glowing with lights and mulled wine, and the kind of festive atmosphere that makes you believe in Father Christmas (or at least Dracula in a Santa hat). Temps hover around 1°C, skiing opens at Poiana Brașov, and traditional Christmas Eve celebrations in the Saxon churches are profoundly moving. Cold, magical, and worth every frozen breath.",
  },

  'rs-belgrade': {
    1: "January in Belgrade is grey, cold, and defiantly alive — 4°C highs, occasional snow, and a nightlife scene that couldn't care less about the temperature. The kafanas (traditional taverns) along Skadarlija are steamy and loud with live music, and a plate of ćevapi with kajmak (grilled meat with cream cheese) is the ultimate winter warmer. Kalemegdan Fortress under snow is moody and magnificent, and hotel prices are at their lowest. Pack thermals and a sense of adventure.",
    2: "February keeps Belgrade cold at 6°C but the city's unstoppable energy burns through any winter blues. Valentine's Day is taken seriously at the riverside restaurants, and the kafana scene stays raucous on weekends. The Danube and Sava rivers run grey and swollen, and fresh snow on the fortress walls creates dramatic photo opportunities. This is budget Belgrade at its best — great food, great nightlife, almost no tourists.",
    3: "March signals spring — temps reach 12°C, the first outdoor café terraces cautiously open on Knez Mihailova street, and Ada Ciganlija island starts waking up from winter dormancy. The city's cultural calendar picks up with gallery openings and early festivals. Kalemegdan Park's trees begin budding, and the riverside splavovi (floating bars and clubs) start their seasonal preparations. A transitional month with growing energy and shrinking prices.",
    4: "April is Belgrade in bloom — 18°C, cherry blossoms along the Kalemegdan promenades, and the city's legendary outdoor lifestyle kicking into gear. The splavovi on the Sava and Danube begin their season, turning the riverbanks into a floating party strip. Orthodox Easter (often in April) brings special celebrations and feasting. The food markets at Zeleni Venac overflow with spring produce, and a beer at a newly opened terrace with fortress views is pure Belgrade.",
    5: "May is when Belgrade hits its stride — 23°C, long sunny days, and the city fully committed to outdoor living. Ada Ciganlija's artificial beach fills with swimmers and sunbathers, the splavovi are in full swing, and the restaurant terraces along the Danube buzz until late. The Belgrade Fortress grounds are stunning in fresh green, and this is prime people-watching season. Crowds are moderate and the energy is infectious without being overwhelming.",
    6: "June cranks up the summer — 27°C, occasional thunderstorms, and Belgrade's famous nightlife scene operating at full volume across the splavovi, rooftop bars, and open-air clubs. The sea-like Ada Ciganlija beach is packed, street musicians fill Skadarlija, and the city stays up later than any other European capital. Belgrade Beer Fest or various music festivals often land in June. Peak season means booking ahead, but the buzz is absolutely worth it.",
    7: "July is hot — 30°C with intense sunshine and the occasional fierce thunderstorm. Belgrade empties slightly as locals head to the coast, but the splavovi and Ada Ciganlija keep the party going. The Danube and Sava are warm enough for swimming, and evening dining in Skadarlija or on a river terrace stretches past midnight. The heat can be intense midday, so siesta like a local and come alive after dark. Summer festivals keep the cultural calendar full.",
    8: "August pushes past 30°C and the city takes on a languid, heat-soaked quality — many locals are on holiday, but tourists and remaining Belgradians keep the splavovi and terraces alive. The river swimming is at its warmest, the watermelon sellers line every corner, and the preparation for EXIT Festival (in nearby Novi Sad, but Belgrade feels the pre-party energy) adds excitement. Evening thunder clears the air for long, warm nights of Serbian barbecue and rakija.",
    9: "September is Belgrade's sweet spot — 24°C, golden light along the confluence of the Danube and Sava, and the city snapping back to full energy as everyone returns. Cultural season opens with theatre, film festivals, and gallery exhibitions. The splavovi enjoy their last warm month, Ada Ciganlija is still swimmable, and the food scene pivots to autumn flavors — roasted peppers, ajvar-making season, and fresh Serbian wines. Arguably the best month to visit.",
    10: "October dresses Belgrade in autumn color — 17°C, golden leaves along Knez Mihailova, and Kalemegdan Park at its most photogenic. The kafana season reignites as outdoor living shifts indoors, and the city's cultural calendar is in full swing. Wine harvest celebrations bring new vintages to the bars, and a long lunch of Serbian comfort food — prebranac (baked beans), sarma, roasted meats — feels like a civic duty. Crowds thin, prices ease, and the mood turns cozy.",
    11: "November is Belgrade going inward — 9°C, grey skies, and the city's indoor personality taking over. The kafanas are packed and loud, the live music scene thrives, and the warmth of a rakija-fueled evening in Skadarlija is the best central heating money can buy. Early Christmas decorations appear, the street food vendors pivot to roasted chestnuts and kurtosh, and the city's gritty, defiant charm feels most authentic in the gloom.",
    12: "December transforms Belgrade with holiday markets, lights, and a festive energy that builds toward both Christmas (January 7 for Orthodox) and New Year's Eve — one of Europe's wildest street celebrations on Knez Mihailova. Temperatures hover at 4°C with occasional snow, mulled wine and ćevapi warm every corner, and the shopping streets buzz with holiday spirit. The kafanas and restaurants are at their most atmospheric. NYE in Belgrade is genuinely legendary.",
  },

  'rs-novisad': {
    1: "January in Novi Sad is deep Vojvodina winter — 3°C highs, grey skies, and the Danube running cold and fast past the Petrovaradin Fortress. The city's cafés and restaurants serve warming čobanac (shepherd's stew) and rakija, and the Matica Srpska gallery is wonderfully uncrowded. Snow occasionally dusts the fortress battlements, creating a scene straight from a Serbian fairy tale. Rock-bottom prices and genuine local warmth make this an authentic, if chilly, experience.",
    2: "February stays cold at 5°C with occasional snow, but Novi Sad's cultural scene keeps things lively with theatre and gallery exhibitions in advance of the spring season. The fortress looms dramatically above the frozen riverside promenades, and the traditional restaurants in the old town serve the heartiest food of the year. Crowds are nonexistent — you'll share the museums and churches with locals only. A good month for slow, affordable cultural exploration.",
    3: "March brings the thaw — 12°C, the first sunny terraces opening along Zmaj Jovina street, and the Danube shaking off its winter gloom. Fruška Gora National Park's forests start greening up, and the monasteries dotting the hills become pleasant day-trip destinations. The city feels like it's stretching after a long sleep, with spring energy building. A transitional month best suited to culture-focused travelers who appreciate being ahead of the season.",
    4: "April blooms across Vojvodina — 18°C, wildflowers in Fruška Gora, and the Petrovaradin Fortress looking magnificent under spring skies. Orthodox Easter celebrations (when they fall here) bring special church services and festive meals, and the Danube promenades fill with strollers. The wine cellars of Sremski Karlovci, just 10km away, offer tastings of excellent local bermet wine. Crowds are light and the city's charm is fully accessible.",
    5: "May is Novi Sad at its best — 23°C, long sunny days, and the Danube sparkling below the fortress. The outdoor café culture is in full swing, Fruška Gora hiking is superb with wildflowers and monastery visits, and the Strand beach on the Danube opens for the season. Day-trips to the Sremski Karlovci wineries are idyllic. The pre-EXIT Festival energy starts building, and the city feels vibrant but not yet overrun.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 27°C with afternoon thunderstorms and long, warm evenings on the Danube promenades. The Strand beach is buzzing, Fruška Gora offers shaded hiking, and the city's food scene (try the fish paprikash at a riverside restaurant) is at its most spirited. Tourist numbers tick up as EXIT Festival preparations transform the Petrovaradin Fortress into a massive concert venue. The energy shift is palpable and exciting.",
    7: "July means EXIT Festival — one of Europe's premier music festivals, held inside the Petrovaradin Fortress walls, and it absolutely defines the month. Even beyond the festival, July brings 30°C heat, packed Strand beaches, and peak summer energy. The Danube is warm enough for swimming, the restaurants stay open late, and the fortress views at sunset are extraordinary. Book everything well ahead if you're coming for EXIT; otherwise enjoy peak summer Vojvodina.",
    8: "August stays hot at 30°C with the post-EXIT glow and peak summer beach culture at the Strand. The Danube runs warm and inviting, Fruška Gora's forests offer cool shade for hikes, and the Sremski Karlovci vineyards start thinking about harvest. Weekend traffic to the beaches is heavy, but weekday Novi Sad remains pleasantly manageable. Evening dining along the river, with fresh carp and a cold beer, is the quintessential Vojvodina summer experience.",
    9: "September is golden Vojvodina — 24°C, the grape harvest in Sremski Karlovci filling the air with the scent of must, and the fortress bathed in honeyed autumn light. Tourist numbers ease after summer, the Strand stays open for warm-weather swimmers, and cultural season kicks off with film and theatre festivals. This is prime wine-tasting season, and the combination of comfortable weather and thinning crowds makes it arguably the smartest month to visit.",
    10: "October brings autumn color to Fruška Gora — 16°C, golden-leafed forests framing the hilltop monasteries, and the Danube turning steel-grey under dramatic skies. Wine harvest wraps up and the new vintage appears in Karlovci cellars, and the city's cafés shift to cozy indoor mode. The cultural calendar stays active with exhibitions and concerts. A contemplative, beautiful month that rewards visitors who prefer atmosphere over sunshine.",
    11: "November is grey Vojvodina — 8°C, bare trees, and the Danube at its most melancholy. The first frost arrives, the fortress takes on a stark beauty, and the city's indoor life — kafanas, galleries, warm restaurants — becomes the main attraction. Early holiday preparations begin, and the traditional food scene pivots to hearty winter dishes. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, and the genuine warmth of Novi Sad's hospitality shines brightest when the weather doesn't.",
    12: "December brings Christmas markets, twinkling lights on the fortress, and Vojvodina's holiday traditions — think warm medenjaci (honey cookies) and hot rakija. Temperatures hover at 3°C with occasional snow, giving the baroque city center a festive glow. New Year's Eve celebrations on the Trg Slobode (Freedom Square) are lively and local. The museums and galleries are uncrowded and welcoming. A quiet, affordable, and genuinely charming winter destination.",
  },

  'ru-blacksea': {
    1: "January on Russia's Black Sea coast is mild by Russian standards — 8°C in Sochi, with the mountains behind covered in excellent ski-season snow. The Krasnaya Polyana ski resorts, built for the 2014 Olympics, offer surprisingly world-class runs with far fewer crowds than the Alps. The coast itself is grey and quiet, good for bracing seaside walks and sampling khachapuri (cheese bread) in the Caucasian restaurants that dot every street.",
    2: "February is peak ski season at Krasnaya Polyana — consistent snow, 6°C coastal temps, and the surreal experience of skiing in the morning and walking the mild seaside promenade by afternoon. The subtropical parks in Sochi stay green year-round, creating a bizarre contrast with the alpine peaks above. Crowds are moderate at the resorts and thin on the coast. Georgian and Caucasian cuisine keeps you fueled with hearty stews and khinkali dumplings.",
    3: "March brings spring to the coast while the mountains hold their snow — 11°C by the sea with magnolias and camellias blooming in Sochi's arboretum, while Krasnaya Polyana offers spring skiing in softening snow. The combination of coastal warmth and mountain winter is genuinely unique. Crowds are light, prices reasonable, and the Caucasian foothills start their wildflower season. A transitional month with the best of both worlds.",
    4: "April is when the Black Sea coast shakes off winter — 16°C, blossom-covered hillsides, and the sea still cool at 12°C but the promenades buzzing with returning energy. The ski season wraps up at Krasnaya Polyana, and hiking in the western Caucasus foothills becomes the draw. The tea plantations near Sochi are harvesting first flush, and the local honey from mountain apiaries is exceptional. A pleasant, uncrowded shoulder month.",
    5: "May delivers genuine warmth — 21°C, sunshine, and the coast coming alive with beach preparation and outdoor dining. The Black Sea reaches 16°C (bearable for a quick dip), and the mountain trails through rhododendron forests are spectacular. Victory Day (May 9) brings major celebrations, and the food scene peaks with fresh herbs, vegetables, and Caucasian feasts. A sweet spot before the summer rush, with comfortable weather and fair prices.",
    6: "June opens the beach season — 25°C, the Black Sea warming to 21°C, and Sochi's waterfront filling with sunbathers and swimmers. The mountain trails at altitude are clear and the alpine meadows are in bloom. Summer crowds begin building, particularly on weekends, and the resort hotels fill up. This is when the coast's subtropical character — palm trees, humid air, lush greenery — feels most pronounced. Evening dining on seaside terraces stretches past midnight.",
    7: "July is full summer — 28°C, the Black Sea at a comfortable 24°C, and the entire coast packed with Russian holidaymakers escaping northern winters (or rather, enjoying their brief summer). Sochi's beaches are shoulder-to-shoulder, the waterparks are heaving, and the mountain hiking offers a cool escape. This is peak season with peak prices, but the energy is festive and the combination of beach and mountain is hard to match.",
    8: "August matches July's heat at 28°C and maintains the peak-season intensity — the Black Sea stays warm at 25°C, the beaches overflow, and the subtropical humidity makes air conditioning essential. The mountain trails offer relief, and rafting on the Mzymta River is thrilling in the late-summer flows. Prices remain at their highest, advance booking is essential, and the crowds are as much part of the experience as the scenery. Russian summer at full volume.",
    9: "September is the coast's velvet season — still 24°C, the sea at its warmest at 25°C, but the summer hordes depart and the beaches become genuinely pleasant. The mountains turn gold and copper, hiking is superb in the cooler air, and the wine harvest begins at local vineyards. Prices drop, availability opens up, and the long warm evenings feel earned rather than fought over. Arguably the best month for the Black Sea coast.",
    10: "October cools to 19°C but the sea clings to a swimmable 20°C — the last viable beach month. Autumn color in the Caucasus foothills is stunning, the hiking is comfortable, and the chestnut and persimmon harvest fills the markets. Crowds thin to pleasant levels, and the resort towns reveal a more local, relaxed character. This is when the coast's natural beauty — not its resort infrastructure — takes center stage.",
    11: "November marks winter's return — 13°C, increasing rain, and the coast retreating into its off-season rhythm. The mountains above receive their first snow, hinting at the ski season ahead. Sochi's year-round subtropical gardens remain green and atmospheric, and the Caucasian restaurants are warm and welcoming. Prices are at their lowest, and a spa-and-food-focused visit is deeply restorative. The first ski runs at Krasnaya Polyana may open late in the month.",
    12: "December splits between coast and mountain — 10°C and mild-but-grey on the seafront, but increasingly snowy and exciting at Krasnaya Polyana as ski season begins in earnest. New Year's celebrations are enormous in Russia, and Sochi does it with particular flair — fireworks, parties, and festive markets. The subtropical coast dressed in holiday lights is a surreal and charming experience. Book ski accommodation early for the holiday period.",
  },

  'ru-kamchatka': {
    1: "January in Kamchatka is hardcore winter — -10°C, deep snow, and a volcanic landscape buried under white that feels like another planet entirely. Dog sledding through the frozen valleys is the marquee activity, and the hot springs at Paratunka and Malki steam invitingly against the bitter air. The northern lights occasionally shimmer above the volcanoes, and the isolation is total. This is expedition-grade travel requiring proper cold-weather gear and a guide.",
    2: "February is Kamchatka's coldest — hovering around -12°C with the deepest snowpack and the most reliable winter conditions. Backcountry skiing and ski-mountaineering on the volcanic slopes are world-class for those with the skills and guide support. The hot springs become essential recovery stations, and the frozen rivers create pathways into otherwise inaccessible valleys. Clear days reveal Koryaksky Volcano in staggering detail. Genuinely remote and unforgettable.",
    3: "March brings longer days and slightly warmer temps (-6°C) while maintaining excellent snow conditions — this is prime heliskiing season, with operators offering descents down volcanic slopes into steaming fumarole fields. The combination of deep powder, volcanic terrain, and total wilderness is unlike anything in the Alps or Rockies. Hot spring soaks under starry skies and fresh king crab dinners in Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky make the evenings as memorable as the days.",
    4: "April extends the ski season with softening snow and increasing sunshine — temps climb to 0°C and the days grow noticeably longer. Spring skiing on the volcanoes is superb, and the coastal areas start thawing, revealing dramatic cliff scenery. Brown bears begin emerging from hibernation toward month's end, and the early salmon have not yet arrived. The hot springs are particularly magical as snowmelt increases their flow.",
    5: "May is Kamchatka's awakening — 7°C, snowmelt flooding the rivers, and the volcanic tundra starting its brief, intense green season. Brown bears are active and hungry after hibernation, and the first guided wildlife tours begin. Skiing is still possible at higher elevations, creating a unique overlap of winter and spring activities. The days are long, the wildflowers start appearing, and Kamchatka's famous remoteness feels most poignant during the transition.",
    6: "June brings genuine warmth — 12°C, long subarctic days with up to 18 hours of light, and the salmon just beginning their epic spawning runs. Brown bear viewing starts in earnest as the bears gather at river mouths, and hiking through the Valley of Geysers (one of the world's largest geyser fields) becomes viable. Summer tourism infrastructure activates, with helicopter tours reaching otherwise inaccessible volcanic calderas. Mosquitoes arrive with enthusiasm.",
    7: "July is peak Kamchatka — 15°C, salmon running thick in every river, and brown bears gorging themselves in one of the planet's greatest wildlife spectacles. Helicopter tours to the Valley of Geysers and Kurilskoye Lake are at their best, and hiking the volcanic landscapes is superb in the brief, intense summer. This is the busiest (and most expensive) month, with guided tours booking out months ahead. Mosquitoes are relentless — industrial-strength repellent is not optional.",
    8: "August continues the salmon spectacle with bears, eagles, and seabirds all feeding at peak intensity. Temps hover at 14°C with increasing fog and rain, but the wildlife viewing remains outstanding. Volcanic hiking is still excellent, and the berry season (wild blueberries and crowberries carpet the tundra) adds another dimension. Late August sees the first autumn color, and the crowds ease slightly from July's peak. Still very much prime season with premium pricing.",
    9: "September transforms Kamchatka — 9°C, the volcanic tundra exploding in crimson, orange, and gold, and the last salmon runs drawing lingering bears. The autumn color against snow-capped volcanoes is genuinely one of the most dramatic landscapes on Earth. Crowds thin significantly, some operators offer reduced rates, and the mosquitoes mercifully disappear. Clear days are increasingly rare but spectacular. This is photographer's Kamchatka — every frame is a masterpiece.",
    10: "October brings winter's first grip — 3°C, the first snow dusting the volcanic peaks, and the bears retreating to their dens. The autumn color fades to brown and the landscape takes on a stark, pre-winter beauty. Most guided tours wind down, and the tourism infrastructure starts closing. The hot springs become particularly appealing as the air chills, and a soak at Paratunka under early snow feels like the edge of civilization. Genuinely rugged.",
    11: "November is winter's arrival — -3°C, heavy snow, and Kamchatka closing up for the season. Tourist access becomes extremely limited, roads close, and the peninsula enters its long hibernation. Dog sledding operations begin preparing for winter season, and the hot springs steam dramatically in the freezing air. This is not a month for casual visitors — only those living locally or with expedition-level support venture into the volcanic interior.",
    12: "December is deep Kamchatka winter — -8°C, short days (around 7 hours of dim light), and the volcanic landscape buried under fresh snow. The northern lights become more visible, dog sledding tours operate for the hardy, and the hot springs offer steaming contrast to the frozen world. Christmas and New Year celebrations in Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky are intimate and warm. This is the most remote, most extreme version of Kamchatka — and some travelers wouldn't have it any other way.",
  },

  'ru-moscow': {
    1: "January in Moscow is Russian winter at its most iconic — -8°C, snow blanketing Red Square, and the onion domes of St. Basil's looking like they were designed for exactly this moment. The GUM ice skating rink beside the Kremlin is magical, and the city's world-class museums (Tretyakov Gallery, Pushkin Museum) are blissfully uncrowded. Russian Orthodox Christmas on January 7 brings midnight liturgies and festive atmosphere. Bundle up in proper winter gear and let the pelmeni and borscht warm you from within.",
    2: "February is Moscow's coldest — -10°C on average, with bitter winds and short, grey days. But the city's extraordinary metro stations (essentially underground palaces) are warm and stunning, Maslenitsa (Pancake Week) brings blini-filled celebrations heralding spring, and the Bolshoi Theatre season is in full swing. The Golden Ring towns — Suzdal, Vladimir, Sergiev Posad — are spectacular under snow. This is when Moscow feels most authentically Russian, and the resilient beauty is unforgettable.",
    3: "March begins the long thaw — -2°C but warming, with the famous Moscow slush making good boots essential. International Women's Day (March 8) is a major holiday, with flowers flooding every market and metro station. The museums remain excellent winter refugoirs, and the city's café culture keeps you warm between attractions. The Kremlin churches are atmospheric under late-winter light. A transitional month that rewards patience with improving days.",
    4: "April breaks through — 10°C, the ice on the Moscow River cracking apart, and the city's parks erupting in early bloom. Gorky Park comes alive with joggers and cyclists, the Golden Ring's monasteries shed their winter austerity, and the café terraces start cautiously opening. Easter (Orthodox timing) often falls in April with midnight celebrations and beautifully painted eggs. Tourist numbers are still low, making the Kremlin and Tretyakov genuinely pleasant to explore.",
    5: "May is Moscow in celebration mode — 18°C, Victory Day on May 9 featuring massive parades on Red Square, and the city bursting into full spring green. The parks are gorgeous, the outdoor dining scene awakens, and river cruises along the Moskva offer stunning views of the Kremlin and Christ the Savior Cathedral. Crowds build but remain manageable, and the long days (17+ hours of light) make for incredible sightseeing. Arguably Moscow's most energetic month.",
    6: "June delivers white nights (nearly) — 22°C, incredibly long days, and the city's parks and boulevards at their lushest. The outdoor concert and festival season begins, Gorky Park hosts events nightly, and the Golden Ring towns are perfect for day trips in the warm sunshine. Moscow's food scene is excellent, from high-end Russian restaurants to street shashlik. Peak season starts with higher prices, but the weather and energy more than justify it.",
    7: "July is Moscow's warmest — 25°C with afternoon thunderstorms and the kind of humid warmth that makes the river cruises and park shade essential. The city's fountains are all running (VDNKH's golden fountains are spectacular), the Tretyakov's new galleries draw art lovers, and the Golden Ring is at its most accessible. Peak tourism means busy attractions, but early mornings at the Kremlin still feel special. Evening walks along the illuminated Moscow River are unforgettable.",
    8: "August stays warm at 24°C with frequent summer storms — Moscow in August has a slightly languid quality as many locals holiday in the countryside. The parks remain lush, the museums are excellent in the air conditioning, and the outdoor food markets at Danilovsky and Depo showcase the best of Russian and international cuisine. Late August brings the first hints of autumn color in the birch trees. Good value as the peak season starts winding down.",
    9: "September is golden Moscow — 16°C, the birch and maple trees turning the boulevards into tunnels of amber and gold, and the cultural season opening with theatre, opera, and ballet premieres. The Bolshoi and Mariinsky (via telecast) are in peak form. Moscow City Day (first weekend) brings citywide festivals and fireworks. The Golden Ring towns are spectacular in autumn color. Crowds are moderate, the weather is crisp, and the cultural energy is at its yearly height.",
    10: "October is Moscow's moody masterpiece — 8°C, rain and falling leaves, and the city pivoting to its indoor magnificence. The Tretyakov and Pushkin museums are at their most appealing, the metro stations glow warmly against the chill outside, and Russian comfort food — solyanka soup, beef stroganoff, medovik cake — reaches peak appeal. Crowds thin, prices ease, and the grey skies somehow make the golden domes shine brighter.",
    11: "November is the descent into winter — 1°C, the first snow often arriving mid-month, and the city's Christmas preparations beginning in earnest. The markets and lights start transforming Red Square into a winter wonderland, and the warm glow of the metro stations and museums becomes a genuine refuge. The Bolshoi Theatre season is excellent, and a performance followed by a late dinner is peak Moscow sophistication. Pack for cold and embrace the early darkness.",
    12: "December is Moscow at its most magical — -5°C, snow on Red Square, and the holiday decorations turning the city into a frost-covered fairy tale. The GUM Christmas market and ice rink are enchanting, the Kremlin gleams under winter lights, and New Year's Eve (Russia's biggest holiday) brings massive celebrations, fireworks, and a citywide party atmosphere. The museums are festive, the restaurants are decked out, and Russian hospitality reaches its warm, generous peak. Dress for the cold — it's absolutely worth it.",
  },

  'ru-siberia': {
    1: "January in Siberia is the real thing — -20°C or colder, with Lake Baikal frozen solid under meters of ice and the taiga forest buried in snow. The famous Baikal ice, with its deep cracks and impossibly clear blue formations, starts reaching its photogenic peak. Cross the frozen lake by hovercraft, try ice fishing, and warm up in a banya (Russian sauna) steaming beside the shore. This is extreme-cold travel that demands serious preparation and rewards with otherworldly beauty.",
    2: "February is the sweet spot for frozen Baikal — the ice is at its thickest and most spectacular, with methane bubbles frozen in surreal patterns and pressure ridges creating natural ice sculptures. Temps hover around -18°C, but the clear skies and increasing daylight make this the best month for ice photography and exploration. Dog sledding across the frozen lake and visiting Olkhon Island (reachable by ice road) are bucket-list experiences. Brutally cold but absolutely magnificent.",
    3: "March brings more light — -10°C with longer days and the famous Baikal ice still in excellent condition. The spring sun creates dramatic contrasts on the ice surface, and the clarity is at its most intense. Ice driving tours on the lake are popular, and the frozen shore caves near Olkhon Island glitter with ice stalactites. The worst of the cold is easing, making this a slightly more accessible entry point to the Baikal winter experience.",
    4: "April begins the thaw — 2°C, the Baikal ice starting to weaken (though still safe in early April), and the first hints of spring appearing in the forests. The Trans-Siberian Railway passes through increasingly dramatic scenery as the snow retreats. Late April sees ice breakup on the lake — a dramatic, cracking spectacle. Irkutsk's wooden architecture and museums are pleasant in the warming weather. A transition month between winter spectacle and spring mud.",
    5: "May is Siberia's spring explosion — 12°C, the taiga forest turning green almost overnight, and Lake Baikal finally breaking free of its ice cover. The endemic Baikal seals (nerpa) appear on rocky shores, and the wildflowers on the lake's western shore are surprisingly delicate. Irkutsk comes alive with outdoor markets and café terraces. Hiking trails open but can be muddy; patience is rewarded with empty landscapes and the first warm sunshine in months.",
    6: "June brings summer to Siberia — 20°C, long days with 18+ hours of light, and Lake Baikal's astonishingly clear water reaching a still-bracing 10°C at the surface. The Great Baikal Trail offers superb hiking along the lake's western shore, and the taiga is alive with wildflowers, butterflies, and birdlife. Tourist season begins, particularly along the Circum-Baikal Railway. The combination of warmth and emptiness is intoxicating — this is genuine wilderness.",
    7: "July is Siberia's peak — 24°C, the warmest water temps of the year on Baikal (reaching 15°C in shallow bays — brave swimmers only), and the surrounding mountains and forests at their most lush and accessible. Hiking the Great Baikal Trail, kayaking along the shore, and visiting the Baikal Limnological Museum are all at their best. Mosquitoes can be fierce in the forest, so pack repellent. This is when the impossible scale of Siberia feels most approachable.",
    8: "August stays warm at 22°C with the berries ripening across the taiga — wild blueberries, pine nuts, and sea buckthorn fill the forests and markets. Lake Baikal's water reaches its warmest, and the swimming beaches at Listvyanka and Olkhon Island are at their most appealing. The tourist season continues but the vast landscapes absorb visitors effortlessly. Storm clouds over the lake create dramatic photography, and the Trans-Siberian journey through late-summer countryside is sublime.",
    9: "September transforms Siberia — 12°C, the larch forests turning gold against the deep blue of Baikal, and the landscape entering its brief, spectacular autumn. The tourists thin out, the Great Baikal Trail is gorgeous in fall color, and the water clarity improves as summer plankton fades. Clear days offer stunning views across the lake to the eastern shore mountains. The first frosts arrive at altitude, and the sense of approaching winter adds urgency to every golden moment.",
    10: "October is the last gasp before winter — 3°C, the last golden larches dropping their needles, and Baikal's waters turning steely grey under increasingly dramatic skies. Most tourism infrastructure closes, and the region takes on a quiet, pre-winter intensity. The Trans-Siberian Railway is one of the few reliable ways to experience the landscape, passing through frosted birch forests and empty villages. Irkutsk's museums and restaurants provide warm refuge.",
    11: "November brings winter's first serious punch — -8°C, the first snow blanketing the taiga, and Baikal's surface beginning its slow freeze-over. Tourism is essentially on hold as the landscape transitions between seasons — too cold for summer activities, too early for the famous ice. Irkutsk is pleasant enough with its museums and banya culture, but the real show is the dramatic weather itself: storms, early ice, and skies that cycle from grey to brilliant blue.",
    12: "December is deepening winter — -15°C, heavy snow, and Baikal's freeze-up progressing from the shallows inward. The ice isn't yet thick enough for walking, so this is a between-seasons month best spent in Irkutsk enjoying the holiday atmosphere, visiting the Decembrist Museum, and eating pelmeni and borscht in warm restaurants. Russian New Year celebrations bring parties and fireworks. The coldest is yet to come — but the beauty of Siberian winter is already fully operational.",
  },

  'ru-stpetersburg': {
    1: "January in St. Petersburg is uncompromising — -7°C, snow-covered canals, and roughly six hours of dim winter light. But the Hermitage is magnificently uncrowded, the Mariinsky Theatre's ballet season is in full flight, and the frozen Neva River framed by baroque palaces is hauntingly beautiful. Russian Orthodox Christmas (January 7) brings candlelit midnight liturgies in the city's cathedrals. Bundle up for the cold and let the museums and culture warm your soul.",
    2: "February is the coldest month — -8°C with heavy snow and the shortest days still clinging on. Maslenitsa (Pancake Week) fills the city with blini, festivities, and the promise of spring. The Hermitage, Russian Museum, and Peterhof (closed gardens, open palace) are virtually empty, and the Mariinsky delivers world-class performances nightly. The city's art cafés and literary haunts — Pushkin-era atmospherics, essentially — are at their coziest. For culture vultures, February is actually perfect.",
    3: "March begins the slow thaw — -1°C, but the ice on the Neva starts cracking, and the extra daylight (12+ hours by month's end) lifts the city's spirits noticeably. The museums remain uncrowded, the cultural calendar heats up with International Women's Day (March 8) celebrations, and the first café terraces along Nevsky Prospekt start testing the waters on warmer afternoons. Galoshes are essential for the spectacular slush.",
    4: "April sees the Neva's ice break up — 8°C, the city's parks suddenly flooded with snowdrops and crocuses, and the famous bridges beginning their nightly openings (one of St. Petersburg's most romantic sights). The Hermitage and the Peterhof palace grounds start opening fully, and tourist numbers are still manageable. Easter celebrations in the Orthodox cathedrals are deeply moving. The city sheds its winter layers with palpable relief and growing energy.",
    5: "May is St. Petersburg reborn — 15°C, the Summer Garden and Peterhof's fountains launching their season (the grand cascade inauguration is a spectacle), and the White Nights beginning their magical approach. Victory Day (May 9) brings massive parades and genuine emotion. The Hermitage is busier now but not yet overrun, canal boat tours resume, and the late-evening light stretching past 10pm creates an intoxicating atmosphere. The city's best month for balance.",
    6: "June is the White Nights — 20°C, the sun barely dipping below the horizon, and St. Petersburg glowing in an endless twilight that makes the baroque facades and canal bridges look like a Romantic painting come to life. The Scarlet Sails festival (late June) with its giant ship and fireworks is extraordinary. The Mariinsky's Stars of the White Nights festival brings world-class performances. Peak season means peak prices and crowds, but this is genuinely unmissable.",
    7: "July continues the White Nights magic with 23°C warmth, long golden evenings, and the Peterhof fountains in full glory. The bridges open at 1am (still in light!), canal cruises are enchanting, and the Summer Garden is lush and photogenic. Peak tourism means the Hermitage queues are serious — book timed tickets online. The food scene buzzes with summer terraces and the city's increasingly excellent restaurant scene. Not cheap, not quiet, but absolutely magnificent.",
    8: "August is St. Petersburg's last summer hurrah — 21°C, the White Nights fading but evenings still long and luminous. The Hermitage and Peterhof remain busy but slightly less frantic than July, and the canal boat cruises continue in pleasant weather. Late August brings the first hints of autumn gold in the parks. The food markets are filled with late-summer berries, mushrooms, and fresh produce. A slightly gentler version of peak season with the same cultural richness.",
    9: "September is golden St. Petersburg — 14°C, the parks and palaces framed by autumn foliage, and the cultural season opening with fresh ballet and opera premieres at the Mariinsky. The Summer Garden turns amber, Pavlovsk and Tsarskoye Selo are spectacular in fall color, and the crowds thin noticeably after the first week. The Hermitage is genuinely pleasant to visit, and the canal reflections of golden trees are extraordinary. The savvy visitor's month, without question.",
    10: "October is atmospheric St. Petersburg — 7°C, rain and fog wreathing the canals in Dostoevsky-grade mood, and the autumn color reaching its peak before the leaves fall. The Mariinsky and cultural venues are in peak season, the museums are uncrowded and magnificent, and the city's literary cafés feel most alive when the weather outside is grey and dramatic. Pack a good jacket and an umbrella, and prepare for the most photographically moody version of Russia's cultural capital.",
    11: "November brings the first darkness — 1°C, the first snow, and daylight shrinking toward its winter minimum. The Neva River starts forming ice crystals, the palace facades are lit against early-evening darkness, and the museums and theatres become essential warm havens. The first holiday decorations appear on Nevsky Prospekt, and the warming power of Russian comfort food — shchi, pirozhki, hot tea — reaches its peak importance. Gloomy, beautiful, and deeply Russian.",
    12: "December is winter wonderland St. Petersburg — -4°C, snow on the baroque facades, and the holiday decorations turning Nevsky Prospekt into a frost-lit corridor of light. The Mariinsky's Nutcracker performances are legendary, Christmas markets sell crafts and warm drinks, and New Year's Eve (Russia's biggest celebration) brings fireworks over the frozen Neva. The Hermitage under winter light, with snow falling outside the windows, is one of Europe's most magical museum experiences.",
  },

  'rw-rwanda': {
    1: "January is dry season in Rwanda — 27°C, clear skies, and prime conditions for gorilla trekking in the Volcanoes National Park. The bamboo forests on the Virunga slopes are relatively dry, making the trek to habituated gorilla families less muddy (though still challenging). Golden monkeys are active, Nyungwe Forest offers excellent primate-watching, and Lake Kivu is perfect for kayaking. This is peak season with premium permit prices ($1,500+) and booking months ahead is essential.",
    2: "February continues the dry season with warm days (27°C) and excellent gorilla trekking conditions — visibility is good, trails are drier, and the volcanoes reveal their peaks more frequently. Kigali, one of Africa's cleanest and most progressive capitals, is pleasant for exploring with its Genocide Memorial and vibrant food scene. The coffee plantations along Lake Kivu are harvesting, offering excellent tasting tours. Book gorilla permits well in advance; this is still peak demand.",
    3: "March brings the transition to the long rains — showers start mid-month, humidity rises, and the Virunga slopes get muddier. Gorilla trekking is still possible and some argue the lush vegetation and fewer trekkers make it more intimate (permits may be slightly easier to secure). Nyungwe Forest drips with orchids and birdlife as the wet season energizes the ecosystem. Temps stay warm at 26°C, and a rain jacket is your most important gear item.",
    4: "April is the wettest month — heavy rains (150mm+), muddy trails, and the gorilla trek becoming a genuine physical challenge through slippery bamboo forests. But there's a reason some veterans prefer it: smaller groups, more active gorillas foraging at lower elevations, and lower permit prices. Nyungwe's chimpanzee tracking continues rain or shine, and the waterfalls across the country are spectacular. Rwanda's famous thousand hills are at their most impossibly green.",
    5: "May sees the long rains winding down — still wet (120mm) but with increasing dry spells and temperatures around 25°C. Gorilla trekking remains challenging but rewarding, and the lush vegetation means closer encounters as groups stay at lower altitudes. The birdwatching in Akagera National Park is outstanding with migratory species still present, and Lake Kivu's shores are beautifully green. Budget-friendly season with more permit availability.",
    6: "June kicks off the long dry season — 25°C, clear mornings, and the absolute prime window for gorilla trekking. Trails are drying out, visibility improves, and the mountain gorillas are active and photogenic in the clearing forests. Golden monkey tracking is excellent, Nyungwe Forest's canopy walkway offers stunning views, and Akagera's savanna wildlife (lions, elephants, giraffes) concentrates around shrinking water sources. Peak season pricing and demand return.",
    7: "July is one of Rwanda's best months — 24°C, dry skies, and optimal conditions across all national parks. Gorilla trekking in Volcanoes NP is at its most accessible, Akagera's Big Five viewing is reliable, and Nyungwe's primate tracking is superb. Kigali buzzes with cultural events and its excellent restaurant scene. This is the busiest month with the highest demand for gorilla permits — book 6+ months ahead. The combination of wildlife, culture, and climate is genuinely world-class.",
    8: "August continues July's dry-season excellence at 25°C — gorilla trekking conditions are superb, and the Virunga volcanoes often reveal their peaks in full, dramatic clarity. This is Rwanda's second-busiest month, so advance planning is critical for permits and lodges. Akagera National Park's concentrated wildlife makes for excellent game drives, and the coffee plantations around Lake Kivu are in full production. Clear nights offer spectacular stargazing over the volcanoes.",
    9: "September brings the transition — the short rains begin tentatively, with afternoon showers starting mid-month. Temps hover at 26°C and gorilla trekking remains excellent in the first half, with conditions gradually getting muddier. The vegetation starts its lush renewal, wildflowers bloom on the volcano slopes, and the birdwatching in Nyungwe and Akagera intensifies. Slightly fewer tourists and marginally easier permit access make this a strategic shoulder month.",
    10: "October is short-rain season — 100mm+ of precipitation, warm at 26°C, and the landscape at its most vivid green. Gorilla trekking continues (it never stops), with the wet conditions adding challenge but also intimacy to the experience. Chimpanzee tracking in Nyungwe is fascinating as the chimps respond to the fruiting season, and Akagera's birdlife peaks. This is a good value month with slightly lower demand and the lush scenery at its most photogenic.",
    11: "November sees the heaviest short rains — 120mm, muddy trails, and the gorilla trek at its most physically demanding. But the rewards are there: smaller groups, active gorillas, and a jungle atmosphere that feels primordial and raw. Kigali's restaurant scene and cultural attractions offer excellent rainy-day alternatives, and the countryside's thousand hills are so green they almost hurt your eyes. Bring waterproofs for everything and embrace the wild, wet beauty.",
    12: "December eases back into dry season — rainfall drops, sunshine returns, and gorilla trekking conditions improve steadily through the month. Holiday visitors arrive, pushing demand for permits back toward peak levels, and the festive atmosphere in Kigali is warm and celebratory. The volcanoes start clearing after the rains, Lake Kivu sparkles in the returning sun, and the year ends with some of the most dramatic landscapes in East Africa. Book early for the holiday period.",
  },

  'sa-alula': {
    1: "January in AlUla is peak season perfection — 22°C days, cool desert nights around 8°C, and the Nabataean tombs of Hegra (Saudi Arabia's first UNESCO site) glowing golden in the clear winter light. The Tantora Festival (or its successors) brings world-class concerts and cultural events to the ancient oasis. Crowds are at their highest but the vast landscape absorbs them. The sandstone canyons and rock art of the Hejaz Railway corridor are spectacular under blue skies.",
    2: "February continues the ideal weather — 24°C, zero rain, and crystal-clear skies that make the carved facades of Hegra look like they were designed for photography. The desert wildflowers can appear after rare winter rains, carpeting the wadis in brief, surprising color. Hot air balloon rides over the sandstone formations at dawn are extraordinary. Tourism is busy but the site management keeps the experience refined. One of the best months to visit.",
    3: "March warms to 28°C — still very pleasant for exploring the outdoor archaeological sites and hiking through the sandstone canyons. The date palm oasis in AlUla's old town is greening up beautifully, and the Elephant Rock formation catches the light dramatically. Stargazing in the desert is world-class with minimal light pollution. Tourist numbers start easing from peak winter, and the evenings are warm enough for outdoor dining in the heritage district.",
    4: "April pushes to 33°C and the first real heat waves signal summer's approach — morning and late afternoon are still comfortable for Hegra exploration, but midday requires shade and hydration. The desert is stark and beautiful in the harsh light, and fewer visitors mean more intimate experiences at the carved tombs. Desert camping becomes less comfortable as night temps rise. A transitional month that rewards early risers and sunset chasers.",
    5: "May crosses into genuine heat — 38°C, relentless sunshine, and the desert landscape shimmering in the haze. Outdoor sightseeing is strictly a dawn-or-dusk activity, and the midday hours belong to air-conditioned museums and restaurants. The mirrored Maraya concert hall offers temperature-controlled cultural experiences. Tourist numbers drop significantly and prices may soften. Committed desert lovers will find an intense, stark beauty, but casual visitors should come in winter.",
    6: "June hits 42°C and AlUla enters its furnace phase — the sandstone radiates stored heat well into the evening, and outdoor exploration is limited to brief pre-dawn windows. The oasis palms provide some shade, but this is essentially off-season. Hotel prices reflect the extreme conditions, and the region takes on a quiet, almost mystical emptiness. Only come if you have a high heat tolerance and a fascination with the desert in its most uncompromising form.",
    7: "July is AlUla at maximum intensity — 44°C, the hottest month, with daytime conditions that are genuinely dangerous without proper preparation. The desert is breathtaking in its severity: empty, vast, and beautiful in a way that demands respect rather than casual tourism. Virtually all visitors have departed, and the region is at its most private and affordable. If you come, stay hydrated, stay indoors midday, and let the evening stargazing justify the endurance.",
    8: "August matches July's extreme heat at 43°C — still too hot for comfortable outdoor tourism, though the dedicated few find the empty archaeological sites and solitary desert landscapes deeply rewarding at dawn and dusk. The Hejaz Railway ruins shimmer in the heat haze, and the isolation is total. Prices are at their annual low. A month for the truly heat-tolerant and those who want to experience the Arabian desert's raw, unmediated power.",
    9: "September begins the long cool-down — 40°C, still scorching but the worst is past and the days start shortening noticeably. The archaeological sites become viable for morning visits again, and the evening temperature drops enough for desert walks. Tourism infrastructure starts gearing up for the coming season, and early-bird visitors find excellent availability. The sandstone canyons take on warm sunset colors that somehow look different from winter — richer, deeper.",
    10: "October is the shoulder season return — 34°C, increasingly comfortable, and the tourism season cautiously reopening. Hegra's tombs are pleasant to visit in the morning and late afternoon, and the desert camping season begins again with cool nights. The old town oasis is atmospheric under the transitioning light, and the lack of crowds gives you room to explore at your own pace. A smart month for those who want the experience without the winter-season premium.",
    11: "November is when AlUla gets genuinely pleasant again — 28°C days, cool nights perfect for desert camping, and the main tourism season kicking into gear. The Nabataean tombs of Hegra are comfortable to explore all day, the rock formations glow in the softer autumn light, and the cultural programming ramps up with exhibitions and events. Stargazing in the clear desert air is spectacular. Book ahead as the popular season builds momentum.",
    12: "December is prime AlUla — 23°C, crisp desert nights, and the full tourism season in swing with cultural festivals, concerts at Maraya, and the Hegra archaeological site at its most accessible and beautifully lit. The sandstone canyons catch the low winter sun at dramatic angles, desert camping under the stars is magical, and the restored old town oasis buzzes with restaurants and galleries. Peak pricing applies, but the experience — ancient history meets modern cultural ambition — is worth every riyal.",
  },

  'sa-jeddah': {
    1: "January is Jeddah at its most comfortable — 29°C, low humidity, and clear skies over the Red Sea. Al-Balad, the historic coral-stone old town (UNESCO-listed), is pleasant to explore without the summer sweat, and the diving and snorkeling along the Red Sea's pristine reefs is superb in 24°C water. The Corniche promenade fills with families and joggers in the cooler evenings. This is peak tourist season, so book dive trips and restaurants ahead.",
    2: "February continues the sweet spot — 29°C, minimal rain, and the Red Sea at its clearest for diving. The coral reefs teem with tropical fish, manta rays, and occasionally whale sharks in the deeper waters. Al-Balad's carved wooden mashrabiya windows and coral architecture look stunning in the gentle winter light. Saudi National Day energy still lingers, and the city's rapidly evolving food scene — traditional Hejazi dishes meet modern Saudi cuisine — is thriving.",
    3: "March warms to 31°C with the first hints of the approaching humidity. The Red Sea is still excellent for diving (25°C water, outstanding visibility), and the last comfortable window for all-day exploration of Al-Balad and the floating mosque of Al-Rahma. The art and culture scene, centered around the Jeddah Season events, keeps the city vibrant. Early risers get the best outdoor experiences; afternoons start feeling warm.",
    4: "April pushes to 34°C and humidity starts climbing — outdoor sightseeing becomes a morning-and-evening affair, but the Red Sea compensates beautifully with warm, clear waters perfect for diving and snorkeling. The King Fahd Fountain (tallest in the world) is spectacular against clear skies. The seafood restaurants along the Corniche serve grilled hammour and samak mashwi that rival anything in the Gulf. Tourist numbers ease as the heat builds.",
    5: "May crosses into serious heat — 37°C with rising humidity that makes the 'real feel' punishing. The Red Sea is a warm 28°C bath, and diving becomes the most comfortable activity by far. Al-Balad exploration requires dawn starts and plenty of water. The city's malls — massive, air-conditioned, and surprisingly entertaining — become daytime survival stations. Prices drop as off-season begins, and the dive operators offer better availability.",
    6: "June heats to 39°C with humidity creating a stifling blanket over the city. The Red Sea, paradoxically, is at its most vibrant with coral spawning events and excellent fish activity in 29°C water. Outdoor Jeddah is a dawn-and-dusk proposition, but the dive sites are world-class and uncrowded. Ramadan (timing varies by Islamic calendar) can fall in summer months, affecting restaurant hours and creating a unique cultural atmosphere after sunset.",
    7: "July is Jeddah's most intense — 40°C with high humidity that makes even the shade feel oppressive. The Red Sea stays warm (30°C) and diving continues for the dedicated, but topside Jeddah is essentially an indoor city. The malls, the contemporary art galleries, and the restaurants operate fully in AC-cooled comfort. Off-season pricing applies, and the empty streets at midday have a surreal, cinematic quality. Come for the diving; endure the rest.",
    8: "August matches July's oppressive formula — 40°C, peak humidity, and a city that functions primarily after dark. The Corniche comes alive late evening when temperatures drop to a merely warm 32°C, and the seafood restaurants along the coast serve some of the year's best catches. The Red Sea diving remains good, though visibility can drop slightly in the warm water. Budget travelers benefit from the lowest hotel rates of the year.",
    9: "September begins the slow retreat from peak heat — 38°C, still humid but the worst is past. The Red Sea calms and clears, making this a solid month for diving and snorkeling at the famous Farasan Banks reefs. The city starts anticipating the coming cooler season, and the first whispers of cultural programming for the season ahead appear. Prices remain low and crowds minimal — a good value window for heat-tolerant travelers.",
    10: "October is the turning point — 35°C, humidity dropping, and Jeddah starting to feel livable outdoors again. The Red Sea is warm and inviting at 28°C, and the diving season enters its second peak with excellent visibility and fish activity. Al-Balad becomes comfortable for morning exploration, the Corniche fills with evening strollers, and the restaurant scene ramps up for the coming season. A smart shoulder month with improving conditions and fair prices.",
    11: "November delivers relief — 31°C, dry air, and a city exhaling after the summer heat. The Red Sea diving is outstanding in 26°C water with superb visibility, and Al-Balad's coral-stone architecture is a joy to explore in the comfortable conditions. The Jeddah Season events (if running) bring concerts, shows, and cultural programming. Tourist numbers build, the food scene peaks with fresh catches and Hejazi specialties, and evenings on the Corniche are genuinely pleasant.",
    12: "December is Jeddah at its finest — 28°C, low humidity, and the Red Sea sparkling in perfect conditions for diving and coastal exploration. The historic Al-Balad district is comfortable all day, the floating mosque glows in the winter light, and the city's increasingly cosmopolitan dining scene caters to holiday visitors with style. Peak season pricing applies, and the energy of Saudi Arabia's cultural opening is palpable. A surprisingly sophisticated Red Sea winter escape.",
  },

  'sa-riyadh': {
    1: "January in Riyadh is genuinely pleasant — 21°C days, cool nights around 9°C, and the desert air crisp and clear. The Edge of the World (Jebel Fihrayn) hike is spectacular in the mild conditions, and the Diriyah UNESCO site gleams in the winter sun. Saudi Season entertainment events bring concerts and cultural programming, and the rapid development of the dining scene means world-class restaurants alongside traditional Saudi fare. Peak tourist season with advance booking recommended.",
    2: "February continues the ideal weather — 23°C, zero rain, and perfect conditions for exploring Riyadh's ambitious new cultural offerings alongside its historic sites. The Masmak Fortress and National Museum are comfortably accessible, and the desert outside the city rewards 4x4 excursions with red sand dunes and clear skies. Riyadh's coffee scene (from traditional Arabic qahwa to specialty third-wave) is excellent. Still peak season, still worth it.",
    3: "March warms to 28°C — still comfortable but the afternoons start hinting at the furnace ahead. The Edge of the World is at its most photogenic with wildflowers possible after winter rains, and the Wadi Hanifa park system offers green walks through the city. The date markets are stocked with fresh varieties, and the Diriyah district's restaurants and galleries buzz with weekend energy. The last truly all-day-outdoor month before summer narrows the window.",
    4: "April pushes past 33°C and the heat becomes a factor — morning excursions to the desert and late-afternoon souq visits work well, but midday is for air conditioning. The King Abdullah Financial District's skyline is impressive against the hazy sky, and the traditional restaurants in Thumairi District serve excellent kabsa and jareesh. Tourist numbers ease, prices soften slightly, and the city's malls (some of the most extravagant on Earth) earn their keep as climate refuges.",
    5: "May is hot — 39°C, dry heat that hits you like opening an oven door, and outdoor Riyadh becomes a dawn-and-dusk city. The modern attractions — the National Museum, Kingdom Tower's sky bridge, the Boulevard entertainment district — all thrive in AC. Desert excursions are only viable at first light. Off-season pricing kicks in, and the city takes on a quieter, more local character that some travelers actually prefer to the peak-season buzz.",
    6: "June enters the furnace — 43°C, relentless sunshine, and the Saudi capital at its most extreme. The malls, museums, and indoor entertainment complexes become the city's true public spaces. Desert excursions are dangerous in the midday heat and not recommended. The city functions on a nocturnal schedule, with restaurants, souqs, and social life peaking well after dark. Ramadan (if falling here) adds a unique cultural dimension with elaborate iftar feasts at sunset.",
    7: "July is Riyadh's peak heat — 44°C, the kind of temperature where car door handles blister fingers and outdoor photography requires gloves for your equipment. The city essentially hibernates from 10am to 5pm, coming alive after dark when the temperature 'drops' to the mid-30s. Hotel prices are at their lowest, the indoor attractions are empty, and if you're heat-tolerant enough, the surreal emptiness of the desert on the city's edge at dusk has a stark, alien beauty.",
    8: "August stays brutal at 43°C with the dry heat making every outdoor moment a calculated risk. But late August brings a subtle shift — the first hints of the approaching cooler season appear in slightly less extreme evenings. The city's nocturnal food scene is outstanding, from traditional Saudi lamb mandi cooked in underground pits to contemporary restaurants pushing boundaries. Budget month with excellent value on accommodation.",
    9: "September begins the descent — 40°C, still extremely hot but the direction is right. Saudi National Day (September 23) brings massive celebrations, fireworks, and a patriotic energy that transforms the capital. The evening temperatures become more bearable, and outdoor events start tentatively returning. The city's cultural calendar ramps up, and the anticipation of the coming comfortable season is palpable. A month of transition and national pride.",
    10: "October is when Riyadh remembers it can be enjoyable — 34°C, dry air, and the desert cooling enough for sunset excursions and early-morning hikes. The Edge of the World becomes viable again, Diriyah's outdoor restaurants reopen, and the Riyadh Season entertainment festival launches with concerts, immersive experiences, and cultural events. Tourist numbers build, prices rise, and the city's incredible pace of development is on full display.",
    11: "November is outstanding — 27°C, clear skies, and Riyadh at its most energetic. The Riyadh Season is in full swing, the desert excursions are comfortable all day, and the dining scene is firing on all cylinders. The Edge of the World hike is magnificent in the cool, clear air, and the Diriyah heritage district feels like a living museum. Peak season begins with higher demand for hotels and experiences. The transformation of Saudi Arabia's capital is genuinely impressive to witness.",
    12: "December is Riyadh's sweet spot — 22°C days, cool desert nights, and the year's cultural calendar culminating in festivals, events, and holiday energy. The Masmak Fortress and At-Turaif UNESCO district are comfortable to explore all day, the desert camping is sublime under star-filled skies, and the food scene — from traditional qursan to cutting-edge fine dining — has never been better. Riyadh in December is the confident, ambitious version of the new Saudi Arabia, and it's hard not to be impressed.",
  },

  'sb-solomons': {
    1: "January in the Solomon Islands is peak wet season — 32°C, daily tropical downpours, and humidity that wraps around you like a warm, damp towel. But the diving is still excellent at sheltered sites like Marovo Lagoon (the world's largest saltwater lagoon), with warm 29°C water and vibrant coral. WWII wreck diving at Iron Bottom Sound near Honiara continues year-round. Crowds are minimal, prices are low, and the lush jungle is at maximum intensity. Malaria prophylaxis is essential.",
    2: "February continues the wet-season pattern — heavy rain (250mm+), 32°C, and rivers running high across the jungle-clad islands. The diving remains surprisingly good between storms, and the WWII relics (wrecked planes, sunken ships) are atmospheric in the rain-filtered light. The Melanesian culture is vibrant and accessible, with village visits possible when weather cooperates. Tourist numbers are at their lowest. Bring waterproof everything and take malaria prevention seriously.",
    3: "March is still solidly wet — 300mm of rain in some areas, though the eastern islands tend to be slightly drier. The diving at Uepi and Munda is world-class in warm, nutrient-rich water, and the pelagic activity (reef sharks, barracuda) is excellent. The jungle trails are slippery but spectacular with waterfalls at full force. This is real adventure travel — infrastructure is basic, planning is essential, and the rewards are proportional to the effort.",
    4: "April begins the transition — rainfall starts easing, sunny spells become more frequent, and the sea calms for better diving conditions. The 29°C water harbors incredible biodiversity, and the WWII wreck sites near Guadalcanal are accessible in improving visibility. Accommodation is basic but welcoming, and the traditional Melanesian hospitality is genuine and warm. Malaria risk remains high, so prophylaxis and insect repellent are non-negotiable. A sweet early shoulder month.",
    5: "May is the transition to dry season — rainfall drops noticeably, sunshine increases, and the diving conditions become outstanding with 25m+ visibility. The Solomons' incredible soft coral diversity (among the richest on the planet) is at its most photogenic. WWII history buffs can explore Honiara's battle sites and memorials comfortably, and village cultural visits are easier with drier trails. A genuine hidden gem month for intrepid divers willing to travel far off the beaten path.",
    6: "June kicks off the dry season — 30°C, lower humidity, and the best overall conditions for diving and island exploration. The trade winds keep things comfortable, Marovo Lagoon is crystal-clear, and the reef life is staggering for those who make the journey. The Skull Island shrines and traditional kastom villages are accessible via dugout canoe. This is as close to peak season as the Solomons get, though 'peak' here means you might see a dozen other tourists.",
    7: "July is prime Solomons — 29°C, dry and breezy, with diving visibility stretching to 30m+ at the best sites. The WWII wrecks are spectacular in the clear water, and the reef biodiversity rivals Raja Ampat without the crowds. The Malaita Province offers authentic cultural experiences with shell-money markets and man-made islands. This is the busiest month, but the Solomons remain one of the Pacific's least-visited nations — solitude is still easy to find.",
    8: "August continues the dry-season excellence — 29°C, consistent trade winds, and the sea at its calmest for diving, snorkeling, and inter-island travel. The Battle of Guadalcanal anniversary (August 7) brings commemorative events. The reef systems are pristine and the mangroves teem with juvenile fish and birdlife. Extended liveaboard dive trips reach the most remote atolls. Tourism remains minimal, making this a pure wilderness diving destination for the committed.",
    9: "September is still dry and comfortable — 30°C, clear skies, and the reefs in peak condition. Whale migrations pass through the deeper channels, and manta ray encounters increase at certain sites. The kastom villages welcome respectful visitors, and the island-hopping by small boat reveals deserted beaches and untouched jungle coastlines. Late September may see the first hints of returning rain. One of the best months for the complete Solomons experience.",
    10: "October begins the wet-season transition — afternoon showers return, humidity climbs to 31°C, and the jungle starts its lush wet-season growth. Diving remains good at most sites, though visibility may decrease near river mouths. The WWII wrecks take on a moodier character in the changing light. Tourist numbers drop from their already-low dry-season levels, and the prices reflect it. A solid shoulder month for heat-tolerant, rain-accepting travelers.",
    11: "November is the wet season's return — regular heavy rain (200mm+), 32°C, and the humidity climbing steadily. Diving is still possible at sheltered sites, and the nutrient-rich runoff can actually improve fish activity on the reefs. The jungle is dramatically lush, waterfalls thunder, and the rivers fill for spectacular kayaking. This is off-season territory requiring flexibility and a sense of adventure. Malaria prophylaxis remains critical through the wet months.",
    12: "December is deep wet season — heavy tropical rain, 32°C, and the islands at their most raw and primordial. Diving continues for the dedicated at sheltered lagoon sites, and the WWII wrecks are atmospheric in the rain-filtered visibility. Christmas brings warm community celebrations in the villages, and the hospitality is genuine and generous. Infrastructure challenges are real, but the Solomons in December offer something increasingly rare in the Pacific: genuine, uncommercialized adventure.",
  },

  'sc-seychelles': {
    1: "January is the Seychelles at their wettest — 350mm+ of rain, 30°C, and a tropical lushness that turns every granite boulder and palm-fringed beach into a saturated paradise. The northwest monsoon brings calm seas on the northwest-facing beaches (Beau Vallon, Anse Lazio), making swimming and snorkeling surprisingly good between downpours. Green sea turtles nest on the beaches, and the Vallée de Mai's coco de mer palms drip dramatically. Crowds are moderate and prices dip below peak-season levels.",
    2: "February is still rainy (250mm) but tends toward shorter, more intense bursts with sunny intervals — 30°C with high humidity. The northwest beaches remain calm and swimmable, and the snorkeling at Sainte Anne Marine National Park is excellent in the warm, plankton-rich water. Birdwatching is outstanding as seabirds nest on the outer islands. The Creole cuisine — grilled fish, octopus curry, ladob dessert — is exceptional year-round but the tropical fruits peak now.",
    3: "March sees the rains easing — still 200mm but with longer dry spells and the sea at a bathtub-warm 29°C. This is one of the calmest ocean months, making inter-island boat trips and diving at the granite formations of North Island and Silhouette supremely comfortable. The giant Aldabra tortoises at the various island sanctuaries are active in the warm conditions. A shoulder month with good value, improving weather, and increasingly reliable beach days.",
    4: "April is the transition sweet spot — rainfall drops to under 150mm, the trade winds haven't kicked in, and the ocean is at its flattest and most transparent. Diving and snorkeling conditions are arguably the best of the year, with 30m visibility at the outer island sites. Temps hold at 30°C, the beaches are stunning, and the crowds are lighter than peak season. Whale sharks occasionally appear in the deeper waters. If you want the postcard Seychelles without peak pricing, April delivers.",
    5: "May brings the southeast trade winds and the dry season — 28°C, decreasing rain (130mm), and a fresh, breezy quality to the air. The southeast-facing beaches (Anse Source d'Argent, Grand Anse on La Digue) get choppy and some accumulate seaweed, while the sheltered northwest beaches remain pristine. Diving is excellent, the endemic birds of Praslin and La Digue are active, and the hiking on Mahé's Morne Seychellois is magnificent. Crowds are moderate and manageable.",
    6: "June is dry-season proper — 27°C, the lowest rainfall of the year at just 60mm, and a pleasant breeze keeping humidity in check. The southeast trades make some beaches unsuitable for swimming, but the sheltered bays remain beautiful. Diving visibility is excellent, whale sharks are more frequently spotted, and the Creole culture of the islands — music, food, dance — is accessible through village visits and local festivals. Peak season pricing begins.",
    7: "July is the Seychelles' coolest, driest month — 26°C, under 70mm of rain, and the trade winds creating excellent conditions for sailing between the inner islands. The southeast-facing beaches are wind-swept and dramatic (beautiful to photograph, less ideal for swimming), while the northwest bays offer calm, clear water. Endemic birds including the black parrot on Praslin are active and vocal. This is the busiest month — book well ahead for the best lodges.",
    8: "August continues the dry, breezy pattern — 26°C, low rainfall, and the windiest month of the year, which makes for excellent sailing and windswept beach walks. The ocean churns on the southeast coast but the diving at sheltered sites remains excellent with spectacular coral formations. Whale shark season peaks, with encounters possible on dedicated boat trips. Peak season means premium prices at the exclusive island resorts, but the weather and marine life are at their most reliable.",
    9: "September is the tail end of the dry season — 27°C, still under 100mm of rain, and the trade winds starting to ease. The beaches gradually calm on both coasts, and the diving conditions are excellent. The endemic giant tortoises are active and photogenic, and the birdwatching on Cousin and Aride islands is outstanding. Crowds thin slightly from peak season while conditions remain excellent — a smart choice for those who want prime weather without maximum pricing.",
    10: "October is the inter-monsoon calm — 28°C, light winds, and the ocean reaching its most glasslike state of the year. This is prime diving and snorkeling season with visibility at its best, and both coastlines offering calm swimming. The rains start returning (150mm) but usually come as brief afternoon showers. Sea turtles begin nesting on some beaches, and the bird colonies on the outer islands are active. A beautiful transition month with moderate crowds and fair pricing.",
    11: "November signals the wet season's return — 200mm of rain, 29°C, and the northwest monsoon bringing calmer conditions to the northern beaches. Diving remains excellent, and the marine life is energized by the nutrient-rich seasonal shift. The giant tortoises and endemic birds are active, and the tropical vegetation starts its lush wet-season growth. Crowds thin as the weather becomes less reliable, and prices drop from peak-season levels. Still gorgeous, just wetter.",
    12: "December is full wet season — 300mm+ of rain, 30°C, and the highest humidity of the year. But the northwest monsoon brings calm seas to the best-known beaches, and between spectacular tropical downpours the sunshine is intense and the landscape vivid. Christmas and New Year bring festive Creole celebrations with music, food, and the warmest island hospitality. Green turtle nesting continues, and the snorkeling in the warm, calm bays is lovely. Holiday pricing applies at the top resorts.",
  },

  'sd-sudan': {
    1: "January is Sudan at its most accessible — 30°C in Khartoum, dry air, and the Nile confluence (where the White and Blue Nile meet) at its most clearly defined and photogenic. The ancient pyramids of Meroë rise from the desert without a single other tourist in sight — one of the world's most remarkable archaeological experiences. The Red Sea coast near Port Sudan offers world-class diving in 25°C water. Security concerns require careful research and likely a guide, but the cultural rewards are extraordinary.",
    2: "February continues the dry, warm pattern at 32°C — ideal for exploring the Nubian archaeological sites and the royal pyramids at Jebel Barkal. The desert heat is manageable in the dry air, and the Nile Valley reveals layers of ancient civilization with every site. Red Sea diving at Sanganeb and Sha'ab Rumi (Jacques Cousteau's former underwater base) is pristine and virtually unvisited. Dust storms (haboobs) are possible but infrequent this month.",
    3: "March heats up to 36°C and the first haboobs of the season may roll across the desert — dramatic walls of dust that transform the sky. The pyramids and temples of the Kushite kingdoms remain fascinating and uncrowded, and the dry conditions make desert travel reliable. Port Sudan's diving stays excellent with hammerhead sharks at the deeper sites. Travel here requires flexibility, self-sufficiency, and respect for a country in transition.",
    4: "April pushes past 40°C and Sudan becomes seriously hot — outdoor exploration is a dawn-and-dusk affair, and the desert radiates stored heat well into the evening. The ancient sites are dramatic in the harsh light but physically challenging to visit at midday. Red Sea diving provides cool relief in the 27°C water with outstanding reef biodiversity. Haboob season continues with occasional dust storms. Only heat-hardened travelers should attempt this month.",
    5: "May is Sudan's furnace prelude — 42°C in Khartoum, intense dust, and the approach of the rainy season in the south. Archaeological sites are best visited at first light, and the heat makes extended outdoor activities inadvisable. The Red Sea coast, while still hot, offers slightly more bearable conditions with ocean breezes and excellent diving. Tourist infrastructure is minimal throughout the country, making advance planning with a reputable operator essential.",
    6: "June brings the first rains to southern Sudan while the north stays dry and sweltering at 40°C. The Nile begins its annual rise, and the desert landscape shows the first hints of green in wadi channels. Khartoum's evening culture — tea stalls, riverside gatherings, warm hospitality — provides the best way to experience the city. Red Sea diving continues in good conditions. This is deep off-season requiring genuine commitment and adventurous spirit.",
    7: "July brings the khareef rains to central and southern regions — 30mm+ in Khartoum, 38°C, and a humidity spike that changes the desert's character entirely. The Nile swells, some desert roads become difficult, and the ancient sites can be harder to reach. But the rain greens the landscape in surprising ways, and the cultural life — music, markets, Sufi ceremonies — continues regardless of weather. Red Sea diving remains reliable on the coast.",
    8: "August is peak rainy season — the heaviest rainfall (80mm+ in Khartoum), flooding along the Nile, and some roads becoming impassable. The desert blooms briefly where rain falls, creating surreal landscapes around the ancient pyramids. Travel is genuinely challenging and requires significant flexibility. The Red Sea coast stays drier and the diving is excellent, making Port Sudan a viable base. The warmth of Sudanese hospitality compensates for the logistical challenges.",
    9: "September sees the rains begin retreating — still wet in the south (60mm in Khartoum), but the worst flooding eases and roads start drying. The Nile is at its highest and most dramatic, and the desert retains some green from the recent rains. The ancient sites become more accessible, and the Red Sea diving is outstanding with clear water and abundant marine life. The combination of recently-watered desert and ancient ruins is unexpectedly photogenic.",
    10: "October marks the dry season's return — rainfall drops sharply, temps settle at 37°C, and Sudan's archaeological wonders become fully accessible again. The pyramids of Meroë against the freshly-dry desert have a stark beauty that intensifies as the green fades. Red Sea diving is at its seasonal peak with excellent visibility and hammerhead encounters. Tourism (such as it is) starts its modest uptick as conditions improve. A good month for the committed explorer.",
    11: "November is excellent for Sudan — 33°C, dry and clear, and the desert archaeological sites at their most visitable. Meroë, Naga, and Musawwarat es-Sufra are accessible and uncrowded (you'll likely be the only visitor), and the Nile Valley's Nubian villages offer warm cultural encounters. Red Sea diving is superb with 25m+ visibility. The relative 'cool' makes day-long desert excursions viable. Still requires careful planning, but the rewards are immense.",
    12: "December is arguably Sudan's best month — 30°C, bone-dry, and the desert at its most photogenic under clear winter skies. The pyramids of Meroë at dawn, with the sun rising over the Saharan horizon, is one of the world's most underrated travel experiences. The Sufi whirling dervish ceremony in Omdurman on Friday evenings is mesmerizing. Red Sea diving is excellent, the cultural hospitality is warm, and the near-total absence of other tourists makes this feel like discovery rather than tourism.",
  },

  'tl-timor': {
    1: "January is peak wet season in Timor-Leste — expect 200mm+ of rain, sweltering 32°C days, and humidity that clings like a second skin. The upside? Almost zero tourists, the mountains around Maubisse are impossibly green, and you can haggle for tais textiles at Dili's Tais Market without competition. Roads to remote districts get dicey, so stick to the coast and enjoy fresh grilled fish on Cristo Rei beach with the statue looming above.",
    2: "February keeps the monsoon going with heavy afternoon downpours and warm 31°C days, but the diving off Atauro Island remains surprisingly good with 20m+ visibility between storms. Crowds are nonexistent — you might be the only foreigner at Baucau's old Portuguese pousada. The coral reefs here are among the most biodiverse on Earth, and February's warm 29°C seas make snorkeling effortless. Bring reef-safe sunscreen and a rain jacket; you'll need both daily.",
    3: "March is the monsoon's last hurrah — still 180mm of rain but the storms start spacing out, and the countryside is at maximum lushness. The road to Jaco Island becomes passable again, revealing one of Southeast Asia's most pristine beaches. Dili's waterfront cafes serve excellent Portuguese-influenced coffee, and with virtually no tourists (busyness 1/5), every interaction feels genuine. Temperatures hold at 31°C; the humidity is relentless but the sunsets compensate.",
    4: "April marks the transition to dry season and Timor-Leste starts to shine — rainfall drops to around 100mm, skies clear, and the diving off Atauro enters its best window with visibility pushing 30 meters. Anzac Day (April 25) is observed with genuine emotion here, reflecting the deep Australia-Timor bond. Temperatures stay at a toasty 31°C but the dropping humidity makes exploring Dili's resistance museums and beachfront far more comfortable.",
    5: "May is when the dry season locks in properly — barely 50mm of rain, clear skies, and 30°C days that feel pleasant rather than punishing. The whale migration begins offshore, with blue whales, sperm whales, and dolphins cruising the Wetar Strait in one of the world's great marine spectacles. Atauro Island diving is world-class right now. Crowds are still virtually nonexistent; this tiny nation hasn't hit most travelers' radars yet, and that's part of its magic.",
    6: "June delivers peak dry-season conditions: almost no rain, comfortable 29°C days, and the whale watching reaches its zenith as humpbacks join the parade through the strait. The mountains around Maubisse and Hatobuilico offer cool retreats at altitude with stunning coffee plantations to explore. This is arguably the best month to visit — perfect weather, whale season, pristine diving, and a country that feels like Southeast Asia did thirty years ago.",
    7: "July is dry, clear, and the coolest month — highs around 28°C with refreshingly low humidity and zero rain. The whales are still passing through, Atauro's reefs are at peak visibility, and the trekking to Mount Ramelau (Timor's highest peak) is at its most accessible. A handful of adventurous tourists appear but crowds remain negligible. The morning coffee ritual with locally grown beans in Dili's cafes is a small perfection worth savoring.",
    8: "August continues the dry-season dream — 28°C, bone-dry conditions, and arguably the clearest waters of the year around Atauro and Jaco islands. Independence Day celebrations on August 30th bring Dili alive with parades, traditional dancing, and a palpable national pride that's genuinely moving to witness. The whale migration winds down but sightings are still possible. This is peak season by Timor standards, meaning you might actually see other tourists at Cristo Rei.",
    9: "September stays dry and warm at 30°C with the landscape turning golden-brown after months without rain. The diving remains excellent though whale sightings taper off. This is a sweet month for cultural immersion — the pace of life in smaller towns like Baucau and Ainaro is unhurried and welcoming. Trekking conditions are ideal with firm trails and clear mountain views. Tourist numbers remain tiny; Timor-Leste is still one of Asia's least-visited nations.",
    10: "October sees the first tentative rains return — maybe 50mm — and temperatures climb back to 32°C as humidity creeps in. The landscape begins greening up and the transitional weather creates dramatic skies for photography. Diving is still very good, and the beaches remain empty and gorgeous. If you want dry-season conditions with a hint of the lush greenery to come, October threads that needle. Stock up on that excellent Timorese coffee before the wet roads complicate supply chains.",
    11: "November brings the wet season's opening act — 150mm of rain, building humidity, and 33°C days that test your tolerance. The diving visibility starts to drop but the marine life remains extraordinary, and the countryside begins its transformation back to vivid green. Crowds are nonexistent, prices are rock-bottom, and the local markets in Dili overflow with tropical fruit. Pack light, breathable clothing and serious mosquito repellent — dengue and malaria are real concerns here.",
    12: "December is full monsoon territory: heavy daily rains, 32°C heat, and roads that challenge even the most optimistic 4WD driver. But Dili's Christmas celebrations are surprisingly vibrant — this deeply Catholic nation throws a proper festive season with midnight masses, street processions, and family gatherings that visitors are warmly welcomed into. The reefs are still there, the coffee is still excellent, and there's something humbling about experiencing one of the world's youngest nations in its most unvarnished season.",
  },

  'tm-turkmenistan': {
    1: "January in Turkmenistan is brutally cold — Ashgabat shivers at 5°C highs with occasional frost, and the Karakum Desert, which covers 70% of the country, is a windswept, monochrome expanse. The marble-clad capital is eerily quiet (even by its usual empty-boulevard standards), and the Darvaza Gas Crater burns even more dramatically against the frigid night sky. Virtually no tourists brave the cold, so transit visa holders get the surreal white-marble cityscape entirely to themselves.",
    2: "February stays cold at around 7°C with biting winds sweeping across the desert plains, but the days start lengthening and Ashgabat's golden-domed monuments gleam in the low winter light. Nowruz preparations begin, lending a quiet buzz to the bazaars where vendors stock dried fruits and nuts. The Gas Crater visits are at their most atmospheric — pitch-black desert nights, zero light pollution, and that flaming pit feels genuinely otherworldly. Tourism is at absolute minimum; visa logistics remain the biggest hurdle.",
    3: "March brings the thaw and Turkmenistan's brief spring window opens — temperatures climb to a pleasant 16°C and the desert fringes erupt in short-lived wildflowers. Nowruz celebrations (March 21) transform the country with horse races, traditional music, and communal feasting on pilaf. This is arguably the best month to visit: comfortable weather, cultural festivities, and the Karakum hasn't yet turned into a furnace. The ancient ruins at Merv are stunning in the soft spring light.",
    4: "April is gorgeous — 24°C days, minimal rain, and the last of the spring green before the desert reasserts itself. The Silk Road ruins at Merv, Konye-Urgench, and Nisa are comfortable to explore without the summer heat haze, and Ashgabat's bizarre marble architecture photographs beautifully in the clear air. Tourist numbers tick up slightly as organized tours arrive for the spring window. The Darvaza Crater camping remains excellent with mild nights perfect for stargazing beside the flames.",
    5: "May is the tipping point — temperatures hit 30°C and the desert starts reminding you who's boss. The spring flowers are gone, replaced by that vast beige Karakum palette, but the longer days mean more time at archaeological sites before the midday heat forces retreat. Turkmenbashi's coastal strip on the Caspian offers a quirky beach alternative. This is your last comfortable month before summer turns Turkmenistan into one of Central Asia's hottest destinations.",
    6: "June crosses into seriously hot territory — 37°C highs in Ashgabat and 40°C+ in the desert interior. The Darvaza Crater visit becomes a dawn-or-dusk-only affair, and midday sightseeing at Merv is genuinely inadvisable without serious sun protection. The Caspian coast around Awaza offers a slightly cooler escape with its bizarre resort complex. Tourist numbers drop as the heat deters all but the most determined. Hydrate obsessively and plan around the brutal midday hours.",
    7: "July is Turkmenistan at its most extreme — 40°C+ in the shade, relentless sun, and the Karakum Desert becomes one of the hottest places on Earth. Even Ashgabat's air-conditioned marble palaces can't fully mask the furnace outside. Tourism essentially pauses outside of organized transit tours. If you must come, confine activities to early morning and late evening, swim in the Caspian at Awaza, and respect the heat the way locals do — slowly and with copious amounts of green tea.",
    8: "August matches July's punishing heat — expect 39°C in Ashgabat and worse in the desert. The upside, if you can call it that, is the complete absence of other tourists, meaning guides and drivers are very available and negotiable on price. The Darvaza Crater at night remains spectacular (the fire doesn't care about seasons), and the Tolkuchka Bazaar near Ashgabat is quieter but still stocked with Turkmen carpets and silver jewelry. Carry water everywhere, and we mean everywhere.",
    9: "September brings the first relief — temperatures ease to 32°C and the worst of the furnace relents, though it's still properly hot by any reasonable standard. The autumn touring season begins cautiously, with organized groups returning for the more manageable conditions. Merv and Konye-Urgench become explorable again without risking heatstroke, and the Darvaza Crater camping improves as desert nights cool down. This is the start of the second-best travel window after spring.",
    10: "October is Turkmenistan's other sweet spot — 22°C in Ashgabat, comfortable desert temperatures, and that golden Central Asian light that makes ancient ruins look like they're posing for you. The Karakum turns bronze and copper, and Darvaza camping is near-perfect with cool nights and clear skies. Turkmen carpet bazaars are bustling, the melon harvest brings some of the sweetest fruit you'll ever taste, and the organized tour groups are back in force. Book ahead for the limited quality accommodation.",
    11: "November cools rapidly to around 14°C and the short autumn window starts closing — but it's still a viable visiting month with manageable weather and thinning crowds. The ruins at Nisa and Merv are peaceful without tour groups, and Ashgabat's marble boulevards take on a moody, overcast grandeur. The first rains arrive, greening up patches of desert scrub. The Darvaza Crater is still accessible but nights are cold — bring proper camping gear. Visa logistics remain the primary barrier to entry.",
    12: "December brings proper winter — 8°C highs, cold desert winds, and the occasional frost that glazes Ashgabat's marble facades. Tourism flatlines and the country retreats indoors, though the bazaars stay active with winter provisions and those magnificent Turkmen carpets. The Gas Crater burns on defiantly against the cold, dark desert — seeing it in winter has a stark, almost apocalyptic beauty. New Year's Eve is celebrated with surprising enthusiasm in Ashgabat, complete with one of Central Asia's tallest Christmas trees.",
  },

  'tn-coast': {
    1: "Tunis in January is refreshingly cool at 15°C with about 60mm of rain — think Mediterranean winter without the tourist hordes. The medina's souks are quiet enough for genuine haggling, and Carthage's ancient ruins stand in dramatic solitude against grey skies. Warm up with a bowl of lablabi (chickpea soup) from a street vendor and explore the Bardo Museum's world-class mosaic collection without a single tour bus in sight. The sea is a chilly 14°C, firmly off-limits for swimming.",
    2: "February is Tunis at its most underestimated — temperatures nudge up to 16°C, almond blossoms start appearing in Sidi Bou Said's blue-and-white lanes, and the rain eases slightly. Crowds remain minimal, making it perfect for exploring Carthage's Antonine Baths and the atmospheric Byrsa Hill without jostling. The food is magnificent year-round here — try a steaming brik a l'oeuf at a medina cafe. The coast remains cold and wind-swept but beautifully moody.",
    3: "March brings genuine spring warmth to the coast — 18°C days, noticeably more sunshine, and wildflowers creeping across the Cap Bon peninsula. Sidi Bou Said's cascading bougainvillea starts its annual show, and the terrace cafes reopen with mint tea and sea views. Tourist numbers are low-to-moderate, prices remain reasonable, and the Carthage archaeological park is comfortable to explore all day. The sea is still brisk at 15°C but beach walks are glorious.",
    4: "April is when Tunisia's coast gets genuinely lovely — 21°C under clear skies, the jasmine is blooming, and the Mediterranean warms to a tolerable 16°C (the brave take a dip). The Tunis International Festival of the Medina begins, filling ancient courtyards with music and performance. Day trips to the cliff-top village of Kerkouane, a Punic ruin found nowhere else, are pure magic in spring light. Crowds are building but still comfortable, and hotel prices haven't spiked yet.",
    5: "May is the sweet spot — 25°C, long sunny days, and the sea reaching a swimmable 19°C for the first time. The beaches at Hammamet and La Marsa come alive without the summer crush, and the medina's souks buzz with energy. Couscous with spring vegetables hits different when eaten on a terrace overlooking the Gulf of Tunis. This is savvy-traveler season: peak-quality weather at shoulder-season prices, with enough warmth for the beach and enough cool for the ruins.",
    6: "June turns up the heat to 30°C with virtually no rain and the Mediterranean hitting a proper 22°C — beach season is fully on. The coast fills up as Tunisian families and European tourists arrive, especially around Hammamet and Sousse. Carthage's ruins shimmer in the heat haze, so hit them early morning. The Tunisian summer diet of grilled fish, mechouia salad, and cold almond milk is perfect fuel for long beach days. Book seaside restaurants ahead on weekends.",
    7: "July is peak everything — 34°C, relentless sunshine, and the sea at a bathwater 25°C that keeps you in the water for hours. The Carthage International Festival brings world-class music and performance to the ancient amphitheatre, and it's genuinely spectacular under the stars. Crowds hit maximum along the coast, prices peak, and Hammamet's beaches are packed towel-to-towel. The heat makes midday ruins visits brutal, so adopt the local rhythm: beach morning, siesta, culture evening.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 35°C, packed beaches, and that gorgeous 27°C sea that's warmer than most swimming pools. The entire Tunisian coast is on holiday mode, meaning loud, joyful, and very busy. Sidi Bou Said's clifftop cafes are elbow-to-elbow but the sunset views remain transcendent. Night markets and beachfront restaurants buzz until late, and the smell of grilling merguez fills every seaside town. Budget for peak prices and embrace the Mediterranean chaos.",
    9: "September is the coast's golden month — temperatures ease to 29°C, the sea holds at a glorious 26°C, and the crowds evaporate after the first week like they were never there. This is hands-down the best swimming month: warm, calm, uncrowded water along the entire coast. Hammamet and La Marsa feel like private beaches, Carthage is blissfully quiet for exploring, and the olive harvest begins inland. Prices drop noticeably and the light turns that honeyed Mediterranean gold that flatters everything.",
    10: "October stays surprisingly warm at 24°C with the sea still a comfortable 22°C — late-season beach days are very much on the table. Rain starts returning (40mm) but in brief, dramatic bursts that clear quickly. The medina shopping is at its most relaxed with vendors happy to chat without the hard sell, and the olive oil nouveau starts appearing in markets. Sidi Bou Said's blue doors and white walls glow in the autumn light. A genuinely underrated month.",
    11: "November brings the Mediterranean autumn in earnest — 18°C, increasing rain at 55mm, and the sea cooling to 18°C (hardy swimmers only). Tourist infrastructure starts winding down in resort towns, but Tunis city itself remains vibrant with its cafes, markets, and cultural institutions. The Bardo Museum is perfect rainy-day territory with its jaw-dropping Roman mosaics. Lablabi soup season returns, and the medina smells of warming spices and fresh bread. Prices are rock-bottom.",
    12: "December in Tunis is quiet and cool at 16°C with about 65mm of rain and short days — a world away from the summer beach chaos. The medina takes on a cozy, almost Parisian feel with cafe culture and indoor markets dominating. Year-end brings a gentle festive atmosphere and some of the best restaurant deals of the year. The ruins at Carthage are hauntingly empty, and Sidi Bou Said in winter rain is moodily photogenic. Not a beach month, but a culture-and-food month of the highest order.",
  },

  'tn-sahara': {
    1: "January in Tunisia's Saharan south is the coolest month — daytime highs around 16°C in Tozeur and Douz, with nights plummeting near freezing in the open desert. This is prime camel-trekking season: comfortable days, spectacular stargazing, and the Chott el Jerid salt lake shimmering under pale winter sun. The Mos Espa Star Wars set near Tozeur is hauntingly photogenic in the low light. Pack serious layers for dawn excursions — the desert cold catches people off guard.",
    2: "February keeps the desert comfortable at 18°C highs, and the Douz Festival of the Sahara (if running) transforms this gateway town into a spectacle of camel racing, traditional music, and sand-wrestling. The Chott el Jerid's mirages are at their most convincing in the winter light, and the oasis towns of Tozeur and Nefta are lush with date palms against the arid backdrop. Nights remain cold in the erg, so camping requires proper gear. Tourist numbers are low and guides are readily available.",
    3: "March warms to a pleasant 22°C and the desert's brief spring window opens — wildflowers appear in the wadis and the oasis gardens are green and fragrant. This is one of the best months for trekking into the Grand Erg Oriental: warm days, cool nights, and exceptional visibility. Matmata's underground Berber houses are fascinating to explore without the summer heat pushing you back to the car. Sand-boarding the dunes near Douz is excellent in the firmer, cooler sand.",
    4: "April nudges toward 26°C and the desert starts asserting its personality — long, clear days perfect for exploring Ksar Ouled Soltane and the hilltop Berber villages of the Dahar region. The Chott el Jerid dries further, revealing its crystalline salt patterns. This is the last truly comfortable month before summer heat makes midday travel inadvisable. Dates from last season are still available in Tozeur's markets, and the palm-shaded oasis walks are sublime in the spring warmth.",
    5: "May crosses into hot territory — 32°C highs and the sirocco winds start carrying Saharan dust that turns the sky hazy orange. The desert is beautiful but demanding, and midday excursions require serious sun protection and hydration. Tourist numbers thin as the heat builds, meaning better prices and private guide experiences at sites like Tamerza canyon and the mountain oases. Morning and evening are golden hours — literally and figuratively — for desert photography.",
    6: "June is when the Sahara reminds you it's the Sahara — 38°C highs, merciless sun, and sand too hot to walk on barefoot past mid-morning. Only the most heat-adapted travelers attempt the deep desert now; stick to the oasis towns and time any excursion for dawn or dusk. Tozeur's old town offers shaded medina walks and ice-cold citronade as survival tactics. The upside is complete solitude and rock-bottom prices, but the heat genuinely limits what you can do between 10am and 4pm.",
    7: "July peaks at 42°C and the Saharan south essentially shuts down for tourism — the sand dunes are untouchable, the salt flats blaze white, and even Douz feels like standing inside an oven. If you're here, you're probably passing through en route somewhere. The oasis pools at Tamerza offer a bizarre respite: cool water surrounded by moonscape. Night provides the only relief, with desert temperatures dropping to a manageable 25°C and a sky full of stars worth losing sleep over.",
    8: "August matches July's furnace at 41°C and the landscape is baked to its most extreme — stark, beautiful, and utterly inhospitable during daylight hours. The occasional flash storm can sweep through a wadi with dramatic, photogenic violence, though they're rare. Tourism is effectively zero, which means if you've always wanted to stand alone in front of the Star Wars sets at Ong Jmel, this is your moment. Hydrate as if your life depends on it, because it rather does.",
    9: "September begins the long cool-down at 35°C — still hot but manageable with early starts and late finishes. The desert light turns golden and the first hint of touring season returns as a few hardy travelers arrive. Tozeur's date harvest begins, filling the oasis with activity and the markets with fresh deglet noor dates that taste nothing like their exported cousins. The Chott el Jerid at sunset is pure visual poetry. A month for those who like their destinations raw and uncrowded.",
    10: "October drops to a comfortable 28°C and the Saharan touring season reopens properly — camel treks resume, desert camps light their fires, and the dunes near Douz are walkable again without burning your feet. The date harvest is in full swing, making Tozeur a wonderfully fragrant and flavourful stop. Star Wars set visits, canyon hikes at Tamerza, and Berber village explorations are all back on the menu. Tourist numbers are moderate and the evening desert light is extraordinary.",
    11: "November cools to a pleasant 20°C and this is prime Sahara season — perfect trekking weather, clear night skies for stargazing, and the oasis towns humming with harvest energy. The Grand Erg Oriental's dunes are at their most inviting for overnight camping with cool but not cold nights. Ksar Ghilane's hot spring oasis, surrounded by palm trees and sand, feels like a mirage that turns out to be real. Book desert camps in advance — this and December are the most popular months.",
    12: "December brings the coolest weather at 16°C highs and near-freezing desert nights, but the daytime sunshine is reliable and the crowds are manageable. This is exceptional trekking and camel-riding season — the desert is comfortable, the light is low and golden, and the dunes cast shadows that photographers dream about. The oasis towns feel festive with year-end energy, and a night camping under the Saharan sky with a Berber dinner of couscous and tagine is one of Tunisia's most unforgettable experiences.",
  },

  'to-tonga': {
    1: "January is deep in Tonga's wet season — expect 33°C days, heavy tropical rain (200mm+), and humidity that turns everything slightly damp. Cyclone risk is at its highest, so keep an eye on forecasts. The islands are lushly green and almost tourist-free, meaning you'll have those limestone beaches on Vava'u entirely to yourself. The sea is a warm 28°C and snorkeling is fine between downpours, but whale season is months away. Feast on 'ota ika (raw fish in coconut) at a waterfront fale.",
    2: "February continues the steamy pattern — 33°C, heavy rain, and cyclone season still very much active. The 'Eua island rainforest is at its most dramatic with waterfalls running full force, and the diving off Tongatapu's reef is warm and uncrowded if not optimally clear. Sunday in Tonga means everything stops — attend a Tongan church service for the most magnificent choral singing you'll ever hear. Prices are at their lowest and the warmth is genuine, both temperature-wise and from the locals.",
    3: "March starts easing out of the wet season — rain decreases slightly, temperatures hold at 31°C, and the cyclone risk begins to diminish. The islands remain gloriously quiet and green, and the reef snorkeling improves as visibility picks up. Tonga is one of the few places where you can still swim with humpback whales, but that's a July-October affair — for now, enjoy the lobster, the empty beaches, and the slow Pacific rhythm. The 'umu (underground oven) feasts on Sunday are not to be missed.",
    4: "April marks the transition — rain drops noticeably, temperatures ease to a comfortable 28°C, and the humidity becomes less suffocating. The ocean calms and visibility improves across Vava'u's stunning island group, making it excellent for kayaking and snorkeling. Tourist numbers start building from their wet-season low but remain very manageable. The coral gardens off 'Eua are spectacular year-round, and the hiking through the island's raised limestone terrain is now comfortable without the summer heat.",
    5: "May settles into the dry season with 26°C days, light trade winds, and dramatically less rain — the islands sparkle under clearer skies. This is shoulder-season perfection: warm enough for the beach, clear enough for diving, and quiet enough to feel like a genuine discovery. The first humpback whale scouts sometimes appear late in the month, causing excitement among the boat operators. Tongan vanilla is harvested around now, and the markets smell incredible.",
    6: "June is dry, comfortable at 24°C, and the calm before the whale storm — tourist numbers are low, prices reasonable, and the snorkeling off Vava'u's islands is crystal-clear. The trade winds keep things pleasant, and this is excellent sailing weather for exploring the Vava'u island group by chartered yacht. The first humpback whales begin arriving from Antarctica, and anticipation builds in the whale-watching community. Tongan feasts feature the season's best root vegetables and fresh seafood.",
    7: "July is when the magic happens — humpback whales arrive in force to breed and calve in Tonga's warm waters, and you can swim alongside these gentle giants in one of the world's most extraordinary wildlife encounters. Temperatures are a pleasant 23°C, rain is minimal, and the ocean is clear and calm. This is peak season now (busyness 4/5), so book whale-swim permits and accommodation months ahead. Vava'u is the epicenter, and every boat operator is buzzing. Worth every dollar and every mile.",
    8: "August is peak whale season and peak Tonga — the humpbacks are everywhere, breaching, singing, nursing calves, and allowing snorkelers close enough to feel the vibration of their songs. At 23°C with dry, clear conditions, this is the best overall month to visit. Crowds are at their highest (5/5 for Tonga, which still means nothing like Bali) and prices reflect the demand. The Heilala Festival celebrates Tongan culture with dance competitions, beauty pageants, and lavish feasting.",
    9: "September keeps the whale encounters going strong while crowds start thinning slightly — smart timing if you want the magic without fighting for boat spots. Temperatures nudge up to 25°C, the weather stays dry and clear, and the sea is a comfortable 24°C. Late-season whales are often mothers with young calves, making for incredibly tender encounters. The diving on Tongatapu's outer reefs is world-class with exceptional visibility. One of the best months for the full Tongan experience.",
    10: "October is the whale season's farewell — the last humpbacks linger before their Antarctic journey south, offering final chances for those extraordinary swim encounters. Temperatures climb to 27°C and the first hints of wet-season rain appear, but conditions remain predominantly dry and sunny. Tourist numbers drop and prices soften, making this a smart value play. The ocean is warm, the reefs are vibrant, and the 'ota ika is as good in October as any other month. Savor the dry-season window.",
    11: "November brings the wet season's return — rain picks up to 120mm+, humidity climbs, and temperatures reach 30°C. The whales have departed for cooler waters, taking the peak tourists with them. What remains is authentic island Tonga: quieter, greener, and deeply welcoming. The reef snorkeling is warm if not crystal-clear, and the fishing is excellent. Cyclone season officially begins, though November storms are rare. Fresh tropical fruit — papaya, mango, coconut — is abundant and extraordinary.",
    12: "December is wet and warm at 32°C with regular tropical downpours and the highest cyclone risk approaching. Christmas in Tonga is a major cultural event — church services are elaborate and joyful, community feasts are massive, and the gift-giving tradition of koloa (woven mats) reflects deep Polynesian values. Tourist numbers tick up slightly for the holidays but remain modest. The islands are lush and green, the sea is bathtub-warm, and the pace of life makes you question every life choice that keeps you on a schedule.",
  },

  'tr-antalya': {
    1: "January on the Turquoise Coast is surprisingly mild — 15°C days in Antalya, occasional rain (235mm is significant), and snow dusting the Taurus Mountains behind the city, creating a dramatic backdrop. The ancient ruins at Perge, Aspendos, and Termessos are yours alone, and the old town (Kaleici) is atmospheric without the summer stampede. Fresh-squeezed pomegranate juice from street vendors and a steaming bowl of iskender kebab warm you from the inside. Beach season is firmly off, but the hiking along the Lycian Way is superb.",
    2: "February stays cool at 15°C with decreasing rainfall and the first almond blossoms appearing along the coast — a hint of the Mediterranean spring to come. The Lycian Way long-distance trail is in prime condition for trekking without the heat, and the Roman theatre at Aspendos is hauntingly empty. Antalya's bazaar is excellent for leather goods and spice shopping without the tourist markup. The sea is a chilly 16°C (no swimming), but the coastal cliffs and ruins make for spectacular winter walking.",
    3: "March warms to 18°C and the Turquoise Coast shakes off winter — wildflowers carpet the hillsides, the Duden Waterfalls run at full power, and the ancient cities along the coast start getting comfortable to explore all day. Crowds are minimal, hotel prices are a fraction of summer, and the seafood restaurants in Kaleici serve the same fresh catch without the wait. The sea is still brisk at 16°C but warming, and the first brave swimmers appear at Konyaalti Beach by month's end.",
    4: "April is the Turquoise Coast's first sweet spot — 21°C, long sunny days, and the Mediterranean warming to 18°C (tolerable for a dip). The Lycian ruins from Olympos to Phaselis are draped in wildflowers and pine-scented air, making this peak hiking season. The eternal flames of Chimaera on the hillside are atmospheric at dusk, and the bazaars are lively but not overwhelming. Shoulder-season pricing means boutique hotel rooms in Kaleici that would cost triple in July.",
    5: "May delivers near-perfect conditions — 26°C, the sea hitting 21°C (properly swimmable), and barely any rain. The beaches at Kaputas, Patara, and Olympos are gorgeous without the summer sardine-packing, and the ancient theatre at Aspendos hosts its first open-air events. Boat trips along the coast to sunken cities and hidden coves are running without the peak-season crowds. The food scene peaks with fresh artichokes, strawberries, and grilled sea bream that would cost three times as much in August.",
    6: "June cranks up the heat to 31°C with the Mediterranean reaching a lovely 24°C — beach season is fully operational. The Turquoise Coast earns its name as the water turns that impossible shade of blue-green, and every beach along the Kaputas-to-Kas stretch is postcard-perfect. Crowds build to busy levels as European summer holidays begin, and all-inclusive resorts hit their stride. The ancient sites are hot by midday, so go early. Evening dining along Antalya's harbour, with meze and raki, is summer living at its finest.",
    7: "July is peak season without apology — 34°C, zero rain, and the sea at a blissful 27°C. Every beach from Kemer to Side is packed, hotel prices peak, and Antalya becomes Turkey's summer capital. The water is so warm and clear that snorkeling from any rocky cove delivers. Blue Voyage gulet cruises along the coast are in full swing, though you'll share the anchorages. Pro tip: escape the coast crowds with a day trip to the cool pine forests and ancient ruins at Termessos, high in the Taurus Mountains.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity — 35°C highs, packed beaches, and that bathwater-warm 28°C sea that refuses to let you leave the water. Turkish families are on holiday alongside international tourists, creating maximum energy and maximum crowds (5/5). The waterfall restaurants at Duden are a must but book ahead, and the boat trips to Kekova's sunken city are running constantly. Budget for premium everything, but know that a sunset over the Taurus Mountains from a Kaleici rooftop, cold Efes in hand, remains absolutely free.",
    9: "September is the smart traveler's pick — 31°C, the sea still at 27°C, and the crowds thinning noticeably after the first week. Prices drop, beach space opens up, and the ancient sites become pleasant again for extended exploration. This is arguably the best swimming month: warm, calm, uncrowded water along the entire coast. The pomegranate harvest begins and the markets overflow with figs, grapes, and fresh almonds. Aspendos occasionally hosts evening concerts in the Roman theatre — check the schedule.",
    10: "October keeps the party going longer than you'd expect — 25°C days, the sea holding at a comfortable 24°C, and the first autumn rains barely noticeable. Beach season extends well into the month, and the Lycian Way returns to prime hiking condition as temperatures moderate. Crowds are moderate and dropping, meaning better restaurant tables and more responsive guides at ruins. The food scene shifts to autumn with chestnuts, quince, and heavier Ottoman dishes. A genuinely underrated month on this coast.",
    11: "November brings the Mediterranean autumn — 19°C, increasing rain (135mm), and the sea cooling to 20°C (still swimmable for the hardy). Tourist infrastructure starts winding down at beach resorts, but Antalya city remains vibrant and the ruins are wonderfully atmospheric in the softer light. The Lycian Way is excellent for trekking with cooler temperatures and dramatic coastal scenery. This is budget-season territory with serious hotel deals and restaurants happy to see you. The citrus harvest begins, filling the air with orange-blossom perfume.",
    12: "December on the Turquoise Coast is a mild Mediterranean winter — 16°C, regular rain, and short days, but still considerably warmer than most of Europe. Antalya's old town dresses up for New Year's celebrations with lights and markets, and the ruins at Perge and Aspendos are eerily beautiful in the low winter sun. The mountains behind the coast catch snow, creating that classic Riviera contrast of palms against white peaks. Hotel prices are at their lowest and a long lunch of fresh fish in Kaleici, unhurried and unshared, is a luxury the summer crowds never know.",
  },

  'tr-cappadocia': {
    1: "January in Cappadocia is a winter wonderland — snow blankets the fairy chimneys, temperatures hover around 2°C, and the landscape looks like a scene from a fantasy novel. Hot air balloon flights run when weather permits (roughly half the mornings), and a balloon over snow-capped chimneys is genuinely once-in-a-lifetime. The underground cities of Kaymakli and Derinkuyu maintain a constant cool temperature, making them year-round attractions. Crowds are minimal, cave hotel prices drop significantly, and a warm pottery-baked testi kebab after a cold day of exploring feels earned.",
    2: "February keeps Cappadocia frozen and photogenic — average highs around 4°C with frequent snowfall that transforms the valleys into a monochrome dreamscape. Balloon flights are weather-dependent and more likely to be cancelled than in summer, so build in extra days. The Goreme Open Air Museum's rock churches are atmospheric in winter quiet, and Urgup's cave restaurants serve hearty Central Anatolian fare without the summer queues. Valentine's Day has become a thing here, with cave hotels marketing the fairy-chimney romance hard.",
    3: "March begins the thaw — temperatures reach 10°C and the snow starts retreating from the valleys while clinging to the peaks. Balloon reliability improves and the hiking trails in Rose Valley and Love Valley become passable again, though muddy patches require decent boots. The apricot orchards start budding, hinting at the blossom spectacle to come. Crowds are still low, giving you breathing room at the Goreme churches and Uchisar castle. A transitional month that rewards flexible travelers.",
    4: "April is Cappadocia's spring awakening — 17°C days, apricot and cherry blossoms softening the volcanic landscape, and balloon flights running most mornings with reliable conditions. The hiking is superb in Ihlara Valley and Pigeon Valley with wildflowers and mild temperatures, and the underground cities are comfortable to explore. Crowds build to moderate but nothing overwhelming, and the cave hotels offer shoulder-season rates. The pottery workshops in Avanos are a great rainy-day fallback, and the local wine scene is surprisingly good.",
    5: "May is arguably Cappadocia's best month — 22°C under clear skies, balloon flights launching reliably at dawn, and the volcanic valleys carpeted in spring green. The hiking is at its peak: Rose Valley in the afternoon light, Ihlara Valley's riverside trail, and the fairy chimneys of Devrent Valley all shine without the summer heat. Crowds are moderate and building, so book balloon flights a few days ahead. The local cuisine — manti (Turkish ravioli), pottery kebab, and Cappadocian wines — is world-class and still uncrowded at the best restaurants.",
    6: "June brings proper summer heat to Cappadocia — 27°C and climbing, with long days and zero rain. Balloon flights are at their most reliable and the early-morning light over the valleys is liquid gold. Crowds arrive in force (busyness 4/5), with tour buses filling the Goreme parking lots by mid-morning. Beat the masses by hiking at dawn or dusk when the temperatures and light are both perfect. The pottery town of Avanos, the wine cellars of Urgup, and sunset from Uchisar castle are all summer essentials.",
    7: "July hits 30°C+ and Cappadocia is in full peak-season mode — every balloon company is flying at capacity, every cave hotel is booked, and the fairy chimneys host a parade of selfie sticks. The heat makes midday hiking uncomfortable, so adopt an early-morning-or-evening strategy. The upside is cloudless balloon mornings and spectacular sunset light. Air-conditioned underground cities provide midday refuge, and evening dining in cave restaurants with Cappadocian wine is a genuine pleasure. Book everything well in advance.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and crowds — 31°C, packed accommodation, and that relentless Anatolian sun that demands early starts and long siestas. The balloon flights at dawn are magical precisely because the air cools enough to make floating over the landscape comfortable before the heat builds. The Nevsehir Grape Harvest Festival brings wine-related celebrations and the vineyards are heavy with fruit. Hotel prices are at their peak, but a night in a well-chosen cave hotel — naturally cool and atmospherically lit — is worth the premium.",
    9: "September is the golden month — temperatures ease to 25°C, the crowds thin significantly, and that Central Anatolian light turns the tuff formations into sculptures of amber and rose. Balloon flights are reliable, the hiking returns to all-day comfort, and the grape harvest means fresh wine and seasonal produce in every restaurant. Prices start softening and availability improves at the best cave hotels. The valleys turn golden-brown, creating a warm palette that photographs beautifully. If you can only pick one month, September rarely disappoints.",
    10: "October brings autumn to the highlands — 18°C days with occasional rain, the vineyards turning gold and crimson, and the tourist crowds dropping to comfortable levels. Balloon flights still run most mornings, and the fall colors add a dimension to the landscape that summer visitors never see. The underground cities feel especially atmospheric in the cooling weather, and Urgup's restaurants pivot to heartier autumn menus. Bring layers for cold mornings and enjoy what may be Cappadocia's most photogenic season.",
    11: "November is the quiet transition to winter — 10°C, increasing overcast skies, and the first possibility of snow dusting the fairy chimneys. Balloon flights become less reliable as weather windows narrow, so build in contingency days. The tourist infrastructure is still running but quieter, and prices drop to low-season levels. The Goreme churches and Zelve ghost town feel appropriately medieval in the grey autumn light. Hot testi kebab and Cappadocian red wine by a cave-hotel fireplace is November done right.",
    12: "December wraps Cappadocia in early winter — 5°C highs, occasional snow, and that magical moment when the fairy chimneys get their first proper white dusting. Balloon flights are weather-dependent (maybe 40% of mornings), making them feel like a genuine gift when they happen. Christmas and New Year bring a small spike in visitors seeking the snow-and-caves aesthetic, but it's nothing like summer. The underground cities maintain their constant 13°C regardless of surface conditions. A steaming sahlep from a street vendor while watching snow fall on the chimneys is pure Cappadocian winter magic.",
  },

  'tr-east': {
    1: "Eastern Turkey in January is no joke — temperatures in cities like Kars and Erzurum regularly hit -15°C, and the Armenian ruins of Ani stand stark against a landscape of deep snow. Lake Van freezes at its edges, and the Ishak Pasha Palace near Dogubayazit looks like it belongs in a fairy tale with its snow-capped backdrop of Mount Ararat. This is for the adventurous only: roads can close, heating is variable, and you'll need serious cold-weather gear. But the Kars goose and honey are world-class warming fuel.",
    2: "February is the coldest month — think -10°C to -20°C with heavy snowfall that transforms the landscape into a silent, white vastness. The Kars Frozen Lake Festival (Cildir Lake) brings ice fishing, horse-drawn sleigh rides across the frozen surface, and a raw beauty that summer visitors can't imagine. Ani's medieval ruins in the snow are hauntingly beautiful but require genuine cold-weather endurance. Warm up in Erzurum's historic hamams and fill up on the region's famous cag kebab.",
    3: "March starts the slow thaw in the east — temperatures climb to around 5°C in lower elevations but mountain passes remain snowy and sometimes impassable. The ice on Lake Cildir begins cracking, creating photogenic patterns, and Ani becomes slightly more accessible. Van's famous breakfast culture (dozens of small plates of cheese, honey, kaymak, and herbs) is worth the trip alone. Spring is still weeks away at these altitudes, but the increasing daylight lifts the mood noticeably.",
    4: "April brings genuine spring to the lower valleys — 14°C in Van, wildflowers erupting across the plateaus, and Mount Ararat emerging from winter clouds in all its 5,137-meter glory. The roads to Ani, Ishak Pasha, and the Georgian churches of the Kackar Mountains reopen fully. Lake Van's famous cats (with one blue eye and one green) sun themselves in Akdamar Island's monastery gardens, and the island church is a masterpiece worth the ferry ride. Crowds are virtually nonexistent.",
    5: "May is glorious in eastern Turkey — 20°C, wildflower meadows stretching to every horizon, and the snowcapped peaks providing constant drama. The trekking in the Kackar Mountains is superb as alpine meadows bloom, and Mount Ararat expeditions launch for the season. Akdamar Island on Lake Van is at its most beautiful, and the Kurdish hospitality in Diyarbakir and the southeast is legendary — expect endless tea invitations. This is prime season: comfortable, uncrowded, and deeply rewarding for adventurous travelers.",
    6: "June is peak season for Eastern Turkey — 26°C in Van, long days, and the landscape at its most lush before the summer dry-out. The Kackar Mountains are perfect for trekking with snowmelt waterfalls and yayla (highland pasture) culture in full swing. Mount Ararat climbing season is open, and the ancient cities of Hasankeyf (what remains above the reservoir) and the Nemrut summit with its colossal stone heads are comfortable to visit. Fresh herbs, cheese, and honey at Van's famous breakfast tables are at their seasonal best.",
    7: "July pushes to 32°C in the lowlands and the eastern Turkish steppe turns golden-brown — but the mountains remain cool and the Kackar trekking is at its best with clear trails and wildflower meadows. Mount Ararat's summit attempts peak this month with the best snow conditions. Nemrut's sunrise is magnificent in the warm, clear air. Tourist numbers reach their (still modest) peak, especially around Van and the Kackar. Lake Van's alkaline waters are surprisingly pleasant for a swim at 22°C, and the local Van otlu peynir (herbed cheese) is addictive.",
    8: "August stays hot at 33°C in the lowlands but the mountains and Lake Van's 1,650-meter altitude provide relief. The Kackar range continues to deliver excellent trekking, and the yayla festivals bring highland villages alive with folk music, wrestling, and communal feasting. Nemrut's colossal heads at dawn remain the region's iconic experience. Late August sees the first cooling hints, and the landscape takes on amber tones. Eastern Turkey rewards patience — the distances are long, the infrastructure basic, but the experiences are among Turkey's most authentic.",
    9: "September brings the perfect balance — 25°C, clear skies, and the landscape turning golden without the July heat. The Kackar Mountains begin their autumn color show, and the crowds (such as they were) depart. Ani's ruins are spectacular in the warm September light, and Van's breakfast scene is less crowded but equally magnificent. This is the last comfortable month for Nemrut sunrise visits and Mount Ararat approaches. The pomegranate and walnut harvest fills every market, and the cag kebab tastes even better with cool evenings.",
    10: "October brings brisk autumn to the east — 15°C in Van with the first mountain snows appearing and the forests of the Kackar turning spectacular shades of copper and gold. Ani is atmospheric in the autumn light, and the border landscape between Turkey, Armenia, and Georgia has a melancholic beauty. Roads remain open but mountain passes start getting risky. The food pivots to hearty stews and fresh walnuts, and the historic hamams in Erzurum become genuinely appealing as the cold creeps in.",
    11: "November announces winter's arrival — temperatures drop to 5°C in Van and below freezing in Kars, with the first serious snowfall transforming the landscape. Most mountain activities wind down and the high passes close. The cities remain accessible and the covered bazaars of Diyarbakir and Van are excellent for winter shopping. Ani in early snow is photogenic but bitterly cold. This is the month for Turkish hamams, hearty kebabs, and the deep hospitality that makes eastern Turkey unforgettable — hosts won't let you leave without three cups of tea.",
    12: "December is full winter — -10°C in Kars, heavy snow, and the haunting beauty of Ani's medieval skyline against a white landscape. Lake Van's eastern shore gets atmospheric fog and early ice. The region's famous honey and kaymak breakfasts are the best start to a cold day you'll find anywhere in Turkey. Tourist numbers are near zero, but the Kars-Tbilisi railway offers a legendary winter train journey. If you pack for the Arctic and expect adventure over comfort, December rewards with a raw, powerful beauty that summer travelers never see.",
  },

  'tr-istanbul': {
    1: "Istanbul in January is grey, damp, and thoroughly atmospheric — 8°C highs, 110mm of rain, and a moody Bosphorus that makes the skyline of minarets look like a watercolour. The Grand Bazaar is uncrowded enough for genuine engagement with artisans, and Hagia Sophia (now a mosque again) can be experienced without the summer stampede. Warm up with a simit and sahlep from a street vendor, then duck into a historic hamam for the full Ottoman spa experience. This is the cheapest month, and the city's depth rewards winter visitors.",
    2: "February is Istanbul's coldest month at 7°C average, with occasional snow dusting the domes of the Blue Mosque — a genuinely magical sight. Crowds remain at their lowest, making it possible to linger in the Basilica Cistern and Topkapi Palace without being herded. The food is at its winter best: hearty Ottoman stews, fresh lahmacun, and balik ekmek (fish sandwiches) on the Galata Bridge with steam rising into the cold air. Valentine's Day brings a romantic buzz to Beyoglu's rooftop bars. Dress warm — the Bosphorus wind cuts through.",
    3: "March brings spring's first stirrings — temperatures climb to 11°C, the tulips start appearing in Sultanahmet parks (Istanbul's official flower), and the rain eases. The Spice Bazaar fills with fresh spring herbs, and the ferry rides across the Bosphorus are brisk but beautiful. Crowds start building from their winter low but remain comfortable. The Asian side — Kadikoy's food market, Moda's cafes — is especially rewarding in the mild weather without summer's sweaty chaos.",
    4: "April is Istanbul at its finest — the International Tulip Festival fills every park and boulevard with millions of blooms, temperatures hit a pleasant 16°C, and the city buzzes with spring energy. The rooftop bars of Beyoglu and Karakoy throw open their doors, and the Bosphorus turns from grey to blue. Crowds are moderate and manageable, making this prime time for Hagia Sophia, the Blue Mosque, and a long Bosphorus cruise. Turkish breakfast on a sunny terrace — menemen, simit, and endless tea — is the proper April ritual.",
    5: "May is when Istanbul hits its stride — 21°C, long sunny days, and the city's outdoor culture in full swing. The rooftop bars along Istiklal Caddesi are packed at sunset, the Bosphorus sparkles, and evening strolls through Sultanahmet are warm and pleasant. Crowds are building toward peak (busyness 4/5) but the queues haven't reached absurd levels yet. The Princes' Islands are perfect for a day trip — take the ferry, rent a bike, and eat fresh fish by the water. This is pragmatist's peak Istanbul.",
    6: "June brings proper summer — 26°C, long evenings, and the first waves of peak-season tourism. The open-air restaurants along the Bosphorus are at their best, and sunset from Uskudar looking back at the Old City skyline is one of the world's great views. Crowds at Hagia Sophia and the Grand Bazaar are heavy; consider early mornings or the lesser-known Chora Church (Kariye Museum) instead. The Istanbul Music Festival brings world-class classical performances. Fish sandwiches on the Galata Bridge taste better when you're not shivering.",
    7: "July is hot and busy — 29°C with high humidity, packed tourist sites, and prices at their peak. The Bosphorus provides the only real relief: evening ferry rides catch the breeze and the sunset views are spectacular. Rooftop bars in Beyoglu and Karakoy are in full swing, the Asian side's Kadikoy market is a foodie paradise, and the city's energy is undeniable if sweaty. Beat the heat with the underground Basilica Cistern's cool air. Booking ahead is essential for everything from restaurants to hamams.",
    8: "August is Istanbul's hottest month — 30°C with stifling humidity and crowds that fill every mosque courtyard and market lane. Many locals flee to the coast, creating an interesting dynamic where tourist hotspots overflow while neighborhood restaurants suddenly have tables free. The Bosphorus swimming race is a unique event, and the evening culture scene — open-air cinema, rooftop concerts — thrives. The key is embracing the pace: move slowly, eat ice cream (dondurma), take ferry rides for the breeze, and save the Grand Bazaar for early morning.",
    9: "September is the clever month — temperatures ease to 25°C, the summer crowds begin their retreat, and Istanbul's light turns golden and generous. The Bosphorus is still warm enough for waterfront dining, the Grand Bazaar thins to manageable levels, and the food markets overflow with autumn produce. The Istanbul Biennial (in odd years) and the film festival bring cultural depth. Prices start softening and hotel availability improves at the better boutique properties in Sultanahmet and Galata. A top-three month for Istanbul.",
    10: "October is moody and magnificent — 19°C, the first autumn rains arriving (65mm), and the Bosphorus taking on that steel-grey glamour that photographers chase. The tourist crush eases to comfortable levels, and the covered markets and hamams feel especially welcoming as the chill sets in. Kadikoy's food hall and the Spice Bazaar are prime territory for seasonal treats: chestnuts, pomegranates, and fresh-pressed pomegranate juice. The city's cafe culture shifts indoors, and a rainy afternoon in a Beyoglu bookshop-cafe is pure Istanbul.",
    11: "November is Istanbul stripped down to its essentials — 13°C, increasing rain, and crowds at their lowest since February. This is the month for museum-hopping (the Archaeological Museum, the Istanbul Modern), hamam sessions, and eating your way through Beyoglu without fighting for a table. The autumn leaves along the Bosphorus shores are surprisingly beautiful, and the ferries run nearly empty. Prices are low, experiences are intimate, and the handful of tourists you meet tend to be the interesting kind. Pack an umbrella and an appetite.",
    12: "December wraps Istanbul in festive winter atmosphere — 9°C, rain and occasional snow, and a New Year's Eve countdown along the Bosphorus that draws big crowds to the waterfront. The Grand Bazaar is lively with holiday shopping, the hamams steam invitingly, and the food scene pivots to warming salep, roasted chestnuts, and rich Ottoman-style dishes in candlelit restaurants. The city's Christian, Muslim, and secular New Year traditions overlap in a way that's uniquely Istanbul. One of Europe's best-value winter city breaks.",
  },

  'tt-trinidad': {
    1: "January in Trinidad is dry-season gold — 31°C, manageable humidity, and the entire nation building toward Carnival fever. The steelpan yards of Port of Spain are rehearsing nightly, costume camps are putting finishing touches on elaborate mas designs, and the energy is infectious. Tobago's beaches at Pigeon Point and Englishman's Bay are gorgeous with calm seas and good visibility. The birding at Asa Wright Nature Centre is excellent with dry conditions drawing wildlife to water sources. Carnival is coming, and you can feel it in every rumshop.",
    2: "February is Carnival month — and nothing in the world quite compares to Trinidad Carnival. The two-day explosion of soca music, mas bands, and jab jab celebrations is a sensory overload of joy, colour, and rhythm that makes Rio look restrained. Temperatures hit 32°C, the streets of Port of Spain become a river of feathered costumes and pulsing sound systems, and sleep is optional. Book accommodation a year ahead and bring earplugs you won't use. Outside Carnival, the dry season keeps Tobago's beaches perfect and the hiking in the Northern Range comfortable.",
    3: "March stays dry and hot at 32°C — the post-Carnival calm settles over Trinidad with a collective hangover and a return to normal life. This is excellent beach weather on Tobago, with the Nylon Pool sandbar and Buccoo Reef snorkeling at their clearest. The Caroni Bird Sanctuary's scarlet ibis evening flyover is stunning against dry-season skies. Crowds thin after the Carnival departure, prices drop, and you get both islands at their most relaxed. The roti shops and doubles vendors never take a holiday.",
    4: "April straddles the seasons — rain starts building but the dry-season sunshine still dominates, with temperatures around 32°C. Easter is celebrated enthusiastically with beach limes (picnics), crab and callaloo, and Tobago goat races that are as fun as they sound. The leatherback sea turtles begin nesting on Trinidad's northeast beaches at Grande Riviere — watching a half-ton turtle emerge from the surf at midnight is genuinely humbling. Humidity builds but the payoff in wildlife is immense.",
    5: "May tips into the wet season — expect afternoon thunderstorms, 33°C heat, and a lushness that transforms both islands. The leatherback turtle nesting hits its peak at Grande Riviere, with dozens of turtles hauling themselves up the beach nightly in one of nature's great spectacles. The Tobago Jazz Festival brings international acts. The rainforest canopy in the Northern Range explodes with green, and the birding remains world-class with over 450 species across both islands. Bring waterproof layers and insect repellent.",
    6: "June is full wet season — heavy tropical downpours, 32°C, and lush jungle everywhere you look. The turtle nesting continues at Grande Riviere, and the rivers in Tobago run full for excellent waterfall hikes to Argyle Falls. Crowds are at their lowest outside Carnival season, making Tobago's beaches feel private even in the rain. The street food never suffers: doubles for breakfast, shark and bake at Maracas Bay, and pepper roti for dinner. Just plan around the afternoon showers and you'll be fine.",
    7: "July brings a brief mid-wet-season dry spell called the Petit Careme — a few weeks of clearer skies and reduced rainfall that feels like nature throwing you a bone. Temperatures hold at 31°C and the islands remain green and lush. Tobago Heritage Festival runs through the month with folk traditions, storytelling, and communal feasting that reveals the island's cultural depth. The diving at Speyside on Tobago's windward coast offers giant manta rays and brain coral the size of cars. Tourist numbers are low and the vibes are unhurried.",
    8: "August is back to full wet season — heavy rains, 32°C humidity, and everything dialled to maximum tropical. But the ocean is warm at 28°C, the diving remains excellent, and Tobago's south coast beaches are sheltered enough for swimming between showers. Trinidad's Emancipation Day celebrations (August 1) bring cultural events and reflection. The Caroni Swamp's scarlet ibis are nesting, creating clouds of crimson against the green mangroves. Budget travelers take note: this is rock-bottom pricing season for some of the Caribbean's most authentic experiences.",
    9: "September sits in the heart of the wet season and the edge of hurricane territory — though Trinidad and Tobago's southern position means direct hits are rare. Temperatures stay at 32°C with heavy afternoon rains and high humidity. The islands are at peak lushness, waterfalls are thundering, and the forest trails are alive with toucans, howler monkeys, and hummingbirds. Tourist numbers are minimal. The local Tobago food scene — curried crab and dumplings, provisions, and fresh coconut water — is excellent year-round but particularly appreciated when you have the restaurants to yourself.",
    10: "October starts the slow turn — still rainy (170mm+) and warm at 32°C, but the rains begin spacing out and the sun makes more frequent appearances. Divali (Festival of Lights) is celebrated beautifully in Trinidad, with thousands of clay lamps illuminating homes and temples across the island. The Hindu and Christian traditions side by side make for fascinating cultural exploration. Tobago's diving visibility starts improving, and the beach scene picks up. Late October feels like the wet season losing its grip.",
    11: "November eases toward dry season — rainfall drops noticeably, skies clear more often, and the 31°C temperatures come with less oppressive humidity. The Tobago beaches return to their calendar-photo glory, and the diving off Speyside is excellent with improving visibility. Pan Trinbago events start building toward Carnival season, and the rumshops start buzzing with soca previews for the coming season. This is a smart shoulder-season pick: good weather, low prices, and the first whisper of Carnival energy.",
    12: "December is dry-season lovely — 30°C with minimal rain, gorgeous beaches, and the Christmas Parang music tradition filling every lime and party with Spanish-influenced folk songs. Tobago's beaches are perfect, the diving is excellent, and the vibe is festive without the Carnival intensity. Old Year's Night (New Year's Eve) in Port of Spain is legendary with street parties, fireworks, and enough rum punch to float a ferry. Doubles for breakfast on New Year's Day is the only known cure. The tourist season starts building, so book ahead for the holidays.",
  },

  'tv-tuvalu': {
    1: "January in Tuvalu is peak wet season — 33°C, heavy tropical rain, and the kind of humidity that makes you reconsider all life choices involving movement. This tiny atoll nation (the world's fourth-smallest country) sees virtually no tourists ever, let alone in January. The lagoon on Funafuti is warm and calm for swimming, and the local culture — communal fishing, church singing, and shared meals — is welcoming in a way that larger destinations can't replicate. Rising seas are an existential threat here, adding poignancy to every visit.",
    2: "February continues the wet season with 300mm+ of rain and 32°C heat, but between downpours the turquoise lagoon and coconut-palm islets are as postcard-perfect as any Pacific atoll. Funafuti's conservation area protects pristine reef and marine life, and snorkeling in the warm 30°C water reveals surprising biodiversity. There are no resorts here — accommodation is guesthouse-basic — and that's precisely the point. The communal te ano (ball game) played on the airstrip is uniquely Tuvaluan and genuinely entertaining.",
    3: "March is still wet but the season begins to ease — rainfall drops slightly and the trade winds pick up, providing some relief from the humidity. Tuvalu's nine atolls are impossibly remote and impossibly beautiful, with the outer islands accessible only by infrequent inter-island ferries. Fishing is the national pastime and obsession, and joining a local fishing trip on the lagoon is the best cultural exchange you'll find. The pace here is measured in tides and church bells, not tourist itineraries.",
    4: "April marks the transition toward drier conditions — still warm at 31°C but the intense rain starts spacing out. The lagoon clarity improves and the reef snorkeling in Funafuti Marine Conservation Area becomes excellent. Tuvalu is one of the world's most climate-vulnerable nations, and visiting now feels both privileged and urgent — these atolls may not exist in their current form by century's end. The food is simple — fish, taro, coconut, breadfruit — and shared generously. Expect to be invited to meals by strangers.",
    5: "May settles into the drier season — 30°C with noticeably less rain and pleasant trade winds. The lagoon is crystal-clear and the outer motus (small islets) around Funafuti are pristine for beach days and snorkeling. Getting here requires a flight from Fiji (three times a week), which filters visitors down to the genuinely curious. The total annual tourist count rarely exceeds a few hundred people — you're not just off the beaten path, you're on a different map entirely. The community warmth makes up for the limited infrastructure.",
    6: "June is prime dry season — 30°C, clear skies, and the trade winds keeping things comfortable on these low-lying atolls. This is arguably the best time to visit, with calm seas for lagoon exploration and the driest conditions of the year. The outer islands like Nanumea and Vaitupu are accessible with good weather, offering an even more remote experience than Funafuti. Traditional dance and music are integral to community life, and visitors are always invited to participate. Bring everything you need — shops here stock the basics only.",
    7: "July continues the dry-season window — comfortable 29°C days, reliable sunshine, and seas calm enough for exploring the reef passages. Tuvalu's marine environment is remarkably healthy, with large schools of reef fish, sea turtles, and occasional dolphins in the channels. The lack of tourist infrastructure means no dive shops — bring your own snorkel gear. The airstrip doubles as a community gathering space, sports field, and evening promenade, which tells you everything about Tuvaluan priorities. Life moves slowly here, and that's the whole point.",
    8: "August is the coolest month at 29°C with persistent trade winds and minimal rain — as comfortable as it gets on a Pacific atoll. The Independence Day celebrations (October 1 preparations begin) bring extra energy to Funafuti, and the communal spirit is palpable. Fishing and reef snorkeling are excellent in the clear, calm conditions. Tuvalu is one of the few places where climate change isn't an abstract concept — high tides already flood parts of Funafuti — making every visit a lesson in urgency and resilience.",
    9: "September stays dry and pleasant at 30°C with the driest conditions of the year — perfect for lagoon exploration and outer-island visits. The community prepares for Independence Day (October 1) with boat races, traditional games, and communal feasting. The reef life is vibrant and the water visibility outstanding. Accommodation options remain extremely limited (one small hotel, a few guesthouses), so book whatever's available well ahead of your Fiji connection. The sunsets over the lagoon, with nothing between you and the horizon, are staggering.",
    10: "October brings Tuvalu's Independence Day celebrations on the 1st — a week of festivities including canoe races, traditional dancing, feasting, and inter-island competitions that showcase Polynesian culture at its most genuine. Temperatures climb to 31°C and the first wet-season rains start appearing, though October remains mostly dry. The lagoon is warm and inviting, and the celebratory atmosphere makes this the most culturally rich time to visit. Just getting here — two flights a week from Fiji — remains the biggest logistical challenge.",
    11: "November signals the wet season's return — rain picks up noticeably, humidity climbs, and temperatures sit at 31°C. The lagoon stays warm and swimmable, but some outdoor activities become less reliable as afternoon downpours intensify. Tuvalu sees so few tourists that there's no real 'off-season' drop in welcome — you'll be treated as a curiosity and a guest regardless of when you arrive. The coconut toddy (sour palm sap) is worth trying, and the communal evening gatherings on the maneapa (meeting house) are open to visitors.",
    12: "December is full wet season — heavy rain, 32°C, and high humidity, but the Christmas celebrations across this deeply Christian nation are joyful and community-centered. Church choirs are magnificent, and the communal feasting features the best of what the atoll provides: fresh tuna, taro, and coconut in every form. The lagoon remains warm for swimming between showers. Tuvalu at Christmas feels like stepping into a world where community and faith genuinely outweigh commerce — because here, they do. Getting here is the hard part; leaving is harder.",
  },

  'tw-taipei': {
    1: "Taipei in January is cool and damp — 16°C highs, frequent drizzle, and the kind of overcast grey that makes the neon signs of Ximending glow brighter. Chinese New Year preparations fill the city with red lanterns and excitement, and the night markets — Shilin, Raohe, Ningxia — are steamy havens of stinky tofu, beef noodle soup, and pepper buns that warm you from the inside. Crowds are low until the Lunar New Year rush, when the entire country migrates home. Yangmingshan's hot springs are at their most appealing in the cold drizzle.",
    2: "February brings Lunar New Year celebrations that transform Taipei — temples overflow with incense and prayers, Dihua Street market explodes with holiday treats, and fireworks light up the skyline. Temperatures hover around 17°C with persistent dampness, but the festive energy is electric. If you time it right, the Pingxi Sky Lantern Festival sends thousands of glowing lanterns into the night sky over the old railway town — genuinely otherworldly. After the holiday, crowds drop and the city settles into a pleasant early-spring rhythm. Hot pot season is still gloriously on.",
    3: "March starts Taipei's slow warm-up — 19°C, less rain than the winter months, and the cherry blossoms blooming in Yangmingshan National Park adding pink splashes to the volcanic landscape. The hiking is excellent: Elephant Mountain for the iconic Taipei 101 skyline shot, and the trails around Maokong for tea plantation walks. The night markets are in fine form without summer's crushing humidity, and a bowl of beef noodle soup from Lin Dong Fang still hits like a masterpiece. Crowds are moderate and manageable.",
    4: "April is one of Taipei's best months — 23°C, the plum rains (meiyu) haven't arrived yet, and the city is pleasant for exploring on foot. The Bao'an Temple's arts festival brings traditional opera and puppet shows, and the hiking trails across the city are lush without being steam-bath humid. Maokong's oolong tea is being harvested, making gondola rides and tea tastings especially rewarding. Night market season is in full swing, and the mango shaved ice starts appearing at the first hint of warmth. A sweet spot before the humidity hammer falls.",
    5: "May signals the arrival of the plum rain season (meiyu) — expect 200mm+ of rain, rising humidity, and 27°C temperatures that hint at the summer ahead. The city gets properly damp, but Taipei is built for rain: covered night markets, MRT-connected malls, and museum-hopping (the National Palace Museum's collection rivals the Louvre). The mango season begins in earnest, and the first shaved ice shops start their seasonal frenzy. Bring an umbrella everywhere and embrace the wet — the city's energy doesn't slow down for drizzle.",
    6: "June is when Taipei gets tropical — 30°C, 80%+ humidity, and 300mm+ of rain from the tail end of meiyu season blending into summer thunderstorms. The Dragon Boat Festival brings exciting races on the Keelung River and sticky rice zongzi wrapped in bamboo leaves. Taipei's air conditioning becomes a survival tool, and the hot springs at Beitou pivot to cooling outdoor pools. The night markets are steamier but no less delicious — try the pepper buns at Raohe when they're fresh from the barrel oven. Hydrate aggressively.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 34°C, intense humidity, and afternoon thunderstorms that are dramatic but usually brief. Typhoon season is in full swing, so watch the forecasts and have flexible plans. The upside: mango shaved ice is at its absolute peak, the beer gardens along the riverside park are lively, and the rooftop bars near Taipei 101 offer spectacular storm-watching. If a typhoon misses, the post-storm skies are the clearest of the year. Night markets actually improve in summer heat — the outdoor cooking matches the air temperature perfectly.",
    8: "August matches July's furnace — 34°C, relentless humidity, and typhoon risk that can cancel plans with 24 hours' notice. But the Ghost Month festivities (Zhongyuan Festival) bring lantern releases, temple ceremonies, and a fascinating cultural atmosphere as the city honors its spirits. The Shilin Night Market is at maximum energy, and the shaved ice vendors are the most important people in Taipei. Summer fruit — lychee, dragon fruit, passion fruit — is extraordinary. If you can handle the heat, August's cultural depth is genuine. Taipei 101's observation deck on a clear day after rain shows the city at its most dramatic.",
    9: "September starts the cool-down — 30°C feels almost pleasant after August, typhoon risk begins easing, and the light turns warmer and more photogenic. The Mid-Autumn Festival brings mooncakes and barbecues to every park and rooftop (Taipei's unique spin involves grilling meat alongside the mooncakes). The hiking at Elephant Mountain and Yangmingshan becomes enjoyable again without the peak summer swelter. Night market culture shifts subtly with autumn ingredients appearing — taro, sweet potato, and mushroom dishes. One of Taipei's most underrated months.",
    10: "October is glorious — 25°C, decreasing rain, and the kind of crisp autumn air that makes Taipei's urban hiking trails genuinely enjoyable. The views from Elephant Mountain are sharp and clear, Maokong's fall oolong harvest produces exceptional tea, and the night markets feel energetic without being oppressive. Crowds are moderate, and the city's cafe culture — some of Asia's best specialty coffee — is at its most appealing for lingering over a pour-over. The National Palace Museum on a quiet October Tuesday is one of the world's great cultural experiences.",
    11: "November turns cool and occasionally damp — 21°C with the northeast monsoon bringing grey skies and intermittent rain. But Taipei handles autumn beautifully: the hot springs at Beitou and Wulai are at their most inviting, the night markets shift to warming soups and stews, and the city's world-class tea culture is perfect for contemplative, rainy afternoons. Yangmingshan's fall foliage is subtle but lovely by Japanese standards, and the hiking is comfortable. A good month for those who prefer culture over beach weather.",
    12: "December wraps Taipei in cool, festive energy — 17°C with the northeast monsoon keeping things grey and damp, but the Christmas lights, night market bustle, and hot spring culture create genuine warmth. The New Year's Eve fireworks from Taipei 101 are one of Asia's most spectacular shows, drawing huge crowds and global TV audiences. Hot pot season reaches its peak — shabu-shabu restaurants steam with convivial energy on every block. The Dihua Street area dresses up beautifully, and the beef noodle soup is all you need to face a drizzly December day.",
  },

  'tw-taroko': {
    1: "Taroko Gorge in January is cool and relatively dry — 18°C along the coast at Hualien, dropping sharply in the marble canyon itself. The gorge trails are at their most accessible with lower water levels, and the towering marble walls of Swallow Grotto and Tunnel of Nine Turns are dramatic under winter light. Crowds are thin outside Chinese New Year, and the indigenous Truku village visits offer cultural depth beyond the scenery. The Hualien night market serves superb Truku-influenced dishes and fresh Pacific seafood. Pack layers for the canyon shade.",
    2: "February sees Lunar New Year bring a domestic tourism surge to Taroko — the gorge trails can get crowded during the holiday week, but the marble canyon is no less spectacular. Temperatures hover around 18°C in Hualien with occasional rain, and the cherry blossoms begin appearing along the gorge roads. The Shakadang Trail follows a crystal-clear river through marble boulders and is manageable even in damp conditions. Outside the holiday period, you'll have the trails mostly to yourself. Fresh tuna sashimi in Hualien is world-class and criminally affordable.",
    3: "March brings spring to Taroko — temperatures climb to 21°C, wildflowers dot the gorge trails, and the marble cliffs take on warmer tones in the strengthening sun. The hiking is superb: the Zhuilu Old Trail (permit required) is one of Asia's most dramatic cliff walks, carved into the marble face 500 meters above the river. Crowds are light and the weather is generally cooperative, making this one of the best months for serious gorge exploration. The east coast surf breaks near Hualien start picking up.",
    4: "April is prime Taroko season — 24°C, comfortable hiking weather, and the gorge at its most lush with spring growth softening the stark marble walls. Trail conditions are generally excellent before the summer rains, and the Baiyang Waterfall Trail leads to a stunning water curtain cave. The indigenous Truku communities celebrate their culture with seasonal festivals worth attending. Hualien's restaurants are in fine form with spring seafood and fresh mountain vegetables. Book the Zhuilu Old Trail permit well ahead — it's limited to 96 hikers per day.",
    5: "May brings the plum rains to the east coast — expect 200mm+ of rain, trail closures at Taroko due to rockfall risk, and 27°C temperatures with climbing humidity. When the gorge trails are open, the waterfalls are thundering and the marble is slicked to a photogenic sheen. Check trail status daily as landslides can close paths without notice. The coast around Hualien offers whale-watching excursions as dolphins and sperm whales migrate along the continental shelf. Bring rain gear and flexibility — the gorge rewards patience.",
    6: "June is wet and dramatic — heavy rain, 30°C heat, and the gorge rivers running high through the marble canyon. Some trails close during heavy rain, but the spectacle of waterfalls cascading down the marble walls is extraordinary when accessible. Typhoon season begins, adding an element of unpredictability. The east coast beaches at Qixingtan (Seven Star Beach) are gorgeous on clear days, and the Hualien night market serves cooling shaved ice alongside the usual excellent dumplings and seafood. Always check conditions before heading into the gorge.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 33°C on the coast, afternoon thunderstorms in the mountains, and the highest typhoon risk of the year. When the weather cooperates, Taroko's marble gorge is steamy and spectacular, with the rivers running jade-green through impossibly narrow passages. The Shakadang Trail is most manageable in dry spells. Whale watching off Hualien is excellent, and the east coast's dramatic shoreline offers stunning drives. Domestic tourists arrive in force (summer holidays), so expect crowds at trail entrances and popular viewpoints.",
    8: "August stays hot and typhoon-prone — 33°C with the constant possibility that a storm will close the gorge entirely. But between weather events, the gorge is at its most dramatic: swollen rivers, thundering waterfalls, and an almost primeval atmosphere in the narrow marble passages. The indigenous Truku Harvest Festival (if it falls in August) is a genuine cultural highlight with traditional dancing, singing, and feasting. Always have a backup plan — a typhoon day is a perfect excuse for Hualien's excellent hot springs and seafood restaurants.",
    9: "September begins the slow cool-down — 30°C with decreasing typhoon frequency and the gorge trails gradually reopening after summer closures. The marble canyon's autumn light is warmer and more photogenic, and the crowds start thinning after the summer holiday rush. This is when serious hikers return to the Zhuilu Old Trail with comfortable temperatures and improving conditions. The Pacific coast east of Hualien offers excellent surf, and the indigenous cultural sites are peacefully uncrowded. A transitional month that rewards optimistic planning.",
    10: "October is excellent for Taroko — 26°C, diminishing rain, and the gorge trails in their most reliable condition since April. The marble walls glow warm in the autumn light, the Liwu River runs clear enough to see the polished stone beneath, and the crowds have thinned to comfortable levels. The Zhuilu Old Trail is spectacular with clear views across the gorge to distant peaks. Hualien's food scene features seasonal specialties, and the coastal bike path along the Pacific offers world-class riding. One of the top months to visit.",
    11: "November brings cool, clear weather to the east coast — 22°C in Hualien with the northeast monsoon bringing occasional rain but many fine days. The gorge is atmospheric in the autumn light, and hiking conditions remain good on maintained trails. Crowds are minimal, making this an intimate time to explore the marble canyon without jostling at viewpoints. The hot springs at Wenshan (inside the gorge) are especially inviting in the cooler air. Hualien's seafood stalls serve fresh bonito and flying fish at their seasonal best.",
    12: "December cools to 18°C with the northeast monsoon bringing grey skies and intermittent rain to the coast, but the gorge itself is sheltered enough for rewarding visits on dry days. The marble canyon in winter light has a stark, austere beauty that summer visitors never see. Crowds are at their lowest, accommodation is affordable, and the hot springs dotted along the gorge road are perfect post-hike recovery. Hualien's night market steams with warming noodle soups and scallion pancakes, and the pace of life on Taiwan's quieter east coast is a welcome contrast to Taipei.",
  },

  'tz-kilimanjaro': {
    1: "January is one of the best months to summit Kilimanjaro — it's the short dry season between the rains, with clear skies, 28°C at the base in Moshi, and the mountain's glaciers gleaming against blue sky. The Marangu and Machame routes are busy with climbers (busyness 4/5), so book your operator early. The surrounding coffee plantations are lush, and a pre-climb day exploring Materuni Waterfalls with Chagga coffee is the perfect warm-up. Altitude sickness doesn't care about the season — acclimatize properly regardless.",
    2: "February continues the dry window with clear summit views and comfortable 27°C base temperatures — excellent climbing conditions that draw steady crowds. The mountain's five climate zones, from tropical rainforest to arctic summit, are all accessible without rain delays, and the Lemosho route offers the best balance of scenery and acclimatization. The Chagga villages around Moshi serve farm-fresh banana beer and grilled goat that fuel pre-climb carb-loading. Valentine's Day proposals at Uhuru Peak are apparently a thing — the altitude makes everyone emotional.",
    3: "March brings the long rains — expect heavy downpours on the mountain, slippery trails, reduced visibility, and a significantly tougher climb. Most operators still run expeditions but success rates drop, and the mountain can be genuinely dangerous in poor conditions. The upside: far fewer climbers (busyness 2/5), lower permit costs, and the rainforest zone is at its most lush and biodiverse. The Moshi area is beautifully green, and the coffee cherry harvest adds activity to plantation tours. Only attempt the summit if you're experienced and well-equipped.",
    4: "April is the wettest month on Kilimanjaro — 300mm+ of rain turns trails to rivers and summit bids become a serious undertaking. Many trekking companies scale back operations, and only the most determined (or foolish) attempt the peak. The compensation is dramatic solitude, vivid green rainforest bands teeming with colobus monkeys and exotic birds, and significantly discounted pricing. Moshi town is quiet and welcoming, and the surrounding Kilimanjaro coffee region is lush. Consider the foothills and cultural experiences over a summit bid this month.",
    5: "May is the tail end of the long rains — still wet (200mm) but conditions improve through the month, especially at higher elevations where the air dries out faster. Late May offers a gambler's window: fewer climbers, improving weather, and the mountain starting to reveal its snow-capped glory between cloud breaks. The Machame route's Shira Plateau can be spectacular when the clouds part. Moshi's restaurants and cultural tours are uncrowded and excellent — the Chagga people's history and coffee culture deserve more than a pre-climb footnote.",
    6: "June marks the start of the main dry season and prime climbing — clear skies, 26°C at the base, and the mountain in its full glory with fresh snow on the summit glaciers. The Machame, Lemosho, and Rongai routes are all in excellent condition, and the night skies from high camps are staggering. Crowds build quickly (busyness 4/5) as this is peak climbing season, so book your expedition months ahead. The surrounding Arusha National Park offers excellent day walks and wildlife viewing as a pre- or post-climb complement.",
    7: "July is peak Kilimanjaro season — the driest conditions, clearest views, and highest success rates draw climbers from around the world. Expect 25°C at the base and brutally cold (-20°C) summit nights, with the famous glaciers providing that iconic backdrop. Routes are busy (5/5) and the best operators book out well in advance. The full moon summit pushes are popular for Uhuru Peak sunrise views. Post-climb, the hot springs near Moshi are the reward your legs have earned, and a Kilimanjaro lager at the bottom tastes better than any beer in history.",
    8: "August rivals July for climbing conditions — bone-dry, crystal-clear, and the mountain at its most photogenic. The crowds match (5/5), making camps lively and trail encounters frequent. The Lemosho route's eight-day itinerary offers the best acclimatization profile, and the Western Breach approach (for the experienced) provides a less-trafficked alternative to the standard routes. Summit night is frigid but the sunrise from Uhuru Peak, Africa's highest point at 5,895m, is genuinely life-altering. The coffee estates around Moshi are in harvest season — reward yourself.",
    9: "September extends the dry season beautifully — excellent climbing conditions with slightly thinning crowds (4/5) as the European summer ends. The summit views are clear, the trails are firm, and the temperatures are marginally warmer than July-August, making the high camps slightly less brutal. This is arguably the sweet spot: nearly peak conditions at slightly reduced demand. The surrounding Kilimanjaro region offers excellent cycling, coffee tours, and waterfall hikes for non-climbers. The jacaranda trees in Moshi start blooming purple, framing the mountain perfectly.",
    10: "October brings the first hints of the short rains — afternoon clouds build and occasional showers hit the lower slopes, but summits remain achievable with around 50mm total rainfall. The mountain's rainforest zone turns vivid green and the wildlife (colobus monkeys, duikers) becomes more active. Crowds thin to moderate levels, offering a more intimate climbing experience. The Rongai route from the north remains drier than southern approaches. Temperatures at the base are warm at 27°C, and the evening thunderstorms over the plains below are spectacular from high camp.",
    11: "November is the short rainy season — 100mm+ of rain makes climbing trickier with slippery trails and reduced visibility, though summit success is still possible with good gear and determination. Fewer climbers (busyness 2/5) mean quieter camps and trails, and the pricing reflects the off-peak conditions. The mountain's lower slopes are lush and the birdlife is exceptional in the rainforest band. Moshi's cultural scene — Chagga markets, coffee cooperatives, and local restaurants — deserves more attention than most climbers give it. The rains usually come in afternoon bursts, leaving mornings clear.",
    12: "December splits in two: early December is still rainy, but by mid-month the short rains typically end, creating a window of clear weather and fresh snow that makes the mountain look stunning. Christmas and New Year climbers fill the routes (busyness 4/5), bringing festive energy to the high camps. Summit night temperatures drop to -15°C, so pack your warmest gear. The Marangu route's hut system offers slightly more comfort than tent-based routes. A Christmas Day summit or New Year's sunrise from Uhuru Peak is the kind of memory that redefines your relationship with alarm clocks.",
  },

  'tz-zanzibar': {
    1: "January in Zanzibar is hot and humid — 32°C with manageable rainfall (65mm) between the monsoon seasons. The beaches along the east coast at Nungwi and Kendwa are gorgeous with warm 28°C seas perfect for swimming, and the diving off Mnemba Atoll is excellent with good visibility. Stone Town's labyrinthine streets are less crowded than peak season, and the spice tours through the island's plantations are fragrant and fascinating. The night food market at Forodhani Gardens serves fresh grilled seafood and Zanzibari pizza as the sun sets over the Indian Ocean.",
    2: "February is one of Zanzibar's best months — the hottest of the year at 33°C, minimal rain (50mm), and the sea at its clearest and calmest. The beaches are postcard-perfect, the kite surfing at Paje is in full swing with steady trade winds, and the reef snorkeling at Mnemba is outstanding. The Sauti za Busara music festival transforms Stone Town with East African music, dance, and arts — it's the island's cultural highlight. Crowds are moderate and the vibe is perfect: hot, beautiful, and buzzing without the March-April rain anxiety.",
    3: "March brings the long rains — and they mean business, with 150mm+ of rainfall, high humidity, and the lush interior turning almost jungle-like. The sea gets rougher on the east coast but the west side around Stone Town stays calmer. Many beach resorts offer dramatic discounts, and if you don't mind afternoon downpours (mornings are often clear), the island is beautiful in its most verdant state. The spice plantations are at peak fragrance, and Stone Town's UNESCO-listed architecture is atmospheric in the rain. Diving visibility drops but the marine life stays abundant.",
    4: "April is the wettest month — 300mm+ of rain turns roads to mud, some beach resorts close entirely, and the humidity is relentless. But here's the contrarian case: rock-bottom prices, empty beaches between storms, and the island at maximum tropical intensity. The rain usually comes in heavy afternoon bursts, leaving mornings for beach time and Stone Town exploration. The Jozani Forest's red colobus monkeys are active and easier to spot. Not for the sun-seeking majority, but adventurous budget travelers find April rewarding.",
    5: "May wraps up the long rains — still 200mm of rainfall but it's easing, and by late May the skies start clearing and the island exhales. Temperatures are a comfortable 28°C and the seas begin calming. This is deep shoulder season with few tourists and excellent value, though some smaller resorts remain closed. Stone Town's restaurants and cultural sites are fully operational and refreshingly uncrowded. The deep-sea fishing picks up, and the sunset dhow cruises start running again. Pack rain gear for early May; by the 20th you might not need it.",
    6: "June kicks off the dry season — 27°C, cool kaskazi trade winds, and the beaches drying out and returning to their white-sand glory. The east coast at Nungwi and Paje is excellent for kite surfing, and the diving at Mnemba Atoll sharpens with improving visibility. Crowds build from the wet-season low but are still moderate. This is the smart shoulder-season play: dry weather, reasonable prices, and the island hitting its stride without peak-season congestion. Fresh seafood, tropical fruit, and sundowners on a dhow — June delivers.",
    7: "July brings peak dry season — clear skies, 26°C with pleasant trade winds, and the sea at its most inviting for diving and snorkeling. The Zanzibar International Film Festival (ZIFF) transforms Stone Town with screenings, concerts, and cultural events that bring genuine creative energy. Tourist numbers hit their high (busyness 4/5) and beach-resort prices peak, but the conditions justify the premium. The spice tours are excellent in the dry weather, and a sunset dinner on a rooftop in Stone Town with the call to prayer echoing below is unforgettable.",
    8: "August is peak everything — dry, comfortable at 27°C, and busy with international and Kenyan/Tanzanian visitors. The beaches are at their most pristine, the diving is excellent, and the trade winds make the east coast a world-class kite-surfing destination. Stone Town's cultural weight — centuries of Omani, Indian, and African fusion — comes alive during evening walks through its carved-door corridors. Prices are at their highest, especially at the upmarket beach lodges, but a Forodhani seafood platter at sunset costs almost nothing. Book well ahead for August stays.",
    9: "September extends the dry season beautifully — 28°C, still minimal rain, and the crowds starting to thin as European summers end. The diving at Mnemba remains stellar, the beaches are glorious, and Stone Town's cultural attractions are less pressured. This is arguably the best value-for-conditions month: summer weather at post-peak prices. The dhow-building yards near Stone Town are fascinating to visit, and the island's clove and nutmeg plantations are preparing for harvest. A September week in Zanzibar is the cheat code seasoned travelers won't share.",
    10: "October marks the transition — the short rains begin tentatively with occasional afternoon showers (60mm), but most days are sunny and warm at 30°C. The sea stays warm and swimmable, and the crowds thin further. Early October is essentially still dry season; late October gets more unpredictable. The fishing is excellent, the reef dives are still good, and the east coast kite surfers get some of the season's last consistent winds. Stone Town's spice markets are fragrant with the approaching harvest season.",
    11: "November brings the short rains properly — 150mm of rain, humidity climbing, and the island turning lush and green again. The eastern beaches get some rough surf, but the western coast stays calmer. Prices drop noticeably and the tourist crowds thin to low-season levels. The rain typically comes in intense afternoon bursts, leaving mornings clear for beach time and diving (visibility is still acceptable). Forodhani's food market operates rain or shine, and the grilled lobster and sugarcane juice are seasonal-proof pleasures.",
    12: "December splits the difference — the short rains taper off mid-month, giving way to the festive season with sunshine, 32°C heat, and a rush of holiday visitors. Christmas and New Year push resort prices to near-peak levels, and the beaches are busy with a jubilant mix of families and honeymooners. The sea is warm and calm, the snorkeling is good, and Stone Town dresses up for the holidays with its unique blend of Islamic, Christian, and secular celebrations. A dhow sunset cruise on New Year's Eve, with Stone Town glowing behind you, is a genuinely special way to turn the calendar.",
  },

  'ua-kyiv': {
    1: "January in Kyiv is deep winter — temperatures average -4°C with regular snowfall that transforms the golden domes of the Pechersk Lavra monastery into a scene from a Slavic fairy tale. The Dnipro River freezes at its edges, and the city's cafe culture shifts entirely indoors with warming borscht and varenyky (dumplings) at every turn. Orthodox Christmas (January 7) brings beautiful church services and carolers. Crowds are minimal and the cultural institutions — museums, opera, ballet — are in full season. Layer up seriously; the wind off the river cuts through.",
    2: "February is Kyiv's coldest month — think -6°C to -8°C with biting winds and heavy snow that makes the city feel like a frozen postcard. But the Ukrainians don't hibernate: the Kyiv Opera and Ballet performs nightly, the contemporary art scene in Podil is thriving, and Maslenitsa (Pancake Week) fills the streets with blini stalls and folk celebrations before Lent. The golden domes against grey snow-clouds are hauntingly beautiful, and the city's resilience and spirit are palpable. Warm up in a traditional pich (wood-fired oven) restaurant.",
    3: "March brings the thaw — temperatures climb above freezing to around 4°C, the snow turns to slush, and Kyiv enters its least photogenic but most hopeful phase. Shevchenko Day (March 9) celebrates Ukraine's national poet, and the first hints of spring appear in the parks along Khreshchatyk. The cafe scene is lively, the Pinchuk Art Centre and other galleries worth visiting, and the city's famous golden domes peek through clearing skies. Dress for mud and unpredictable weather — March can serve snow and sunshine in the same afternoon.",
    4: "April is Kyiv's spring awakening — 14°C, cherry and chestnut trees blooming across the city, and the parks bursting back to life. Easter is the cultural highlight, with elaborate pysanky (decorated eggs) and midnight church services that are genuinely moving. The Botanical Garden is gorgeous, the river promenades reopen, and outdoor dining begins tentatively. Crowds are light and the city's energy is optimistic and warm. Kyiv's craft beer and specialty coffee scenes are excellent and still finding their international audience.",
    5: "May is arguably Kyiv's best month — 20°C, chestnuts in full bloom (the city's symbol), and the parks and riverfront cafes alive with locals celebrating the end of winter. Victory Day (May 9) carries complex significance, and the Embroidery Day celebration showcases stunning vyshyvanka (traditional embroidered shirts). The Dnipro's beaches start seeing early swimmers, and the cycling along the riverbank is superb. Crowds are moderate, prices reasonable, and the food scene — from high-end Ukrainian cuisine to street-vendor pampushky — is firing on all cylinders.",
    6: "June brings summer proper — 24°C, long days, and Kyiv at its most vibrant. The riverfront beaches fill up, the outdoor festivals begin, and the nightlife in Podil and Pechersk runs late. The food markets overflow with Ukrainian cherries, strawberries, and fresh herbs. Constitution Day (June 28) adds civic celebration. The city's Soviet architecture, brutalist and imposing, somehow looks its best against summer greenery and blue skies. Tourist numbers are growing as the world discovers Kyiv's cultural depth — come before it becomes the next Prague.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 26°C with occasional thunderstorms and the city in full outdoor mode. The Dnipro beaches (Hydropark island especially) are packed with sunbathers, and the rooftop bar scene along Podil is excellent. Kyiv's music festivals bring international and Ukrainian acts, and the cafe culture migrates entirely outdoors. The heat can be intense in the city center, but the river always offers relief. Traditional Ukrainian watermelon and cold borscht (yes, cold) are summer staples. Tourist numbers peak but Kyiv never feels overwhelmed.",
    8: "August holds the summer heat at 25°C with the best swimming conditions on the Dnipro — the river beaches are lively and the evening strolls along the waterfront are pure pleasure. Independence Day (August 24) is celebrated with ceremonies, concerts, and genuine patriotic emotion. The food markets are at peak harvest with tomatoes, corn, and peaches at their best. Late August starts hinting at autumn with cooler evenings perfect for outdoor dining. The city's resilience and cultural pride are impossible to miss.",
    9: "September is golden Kyiv — 18°C, the chestnut trees turning amber, and a cultural season that rivals any European capital. The opera and ballet restart their programs, the galleries launch new exhibitions, and the city's cafe scene shifts to cozy mode. The Dnipro is still swimmable through early September, and the parks are stunning in their autumn dress. Tourist crowds thin, hotel prices drop, and the food scene features autumn mushrooms, apples, and the first warming stews. One of the most underrated European city-break months.",
    10: "October brings brisk autumn — 10°C with golden leaves carpeting the parks and a distinctly cozy atmosphere settling over the city. The Pechersk Lavra in autumn foliage is one of Eastern Europe's great sights, and the indoor market halls (Bessarabsky Market especially) overflow with seasonal produce. Rain increases but Kyiv handles it with cafe culture and umbrella nonchalance. The ballet and opera seasons are in full swing, and Halloween has been adopted by the city's younger creative scene with genuine enthusiasm.",
    11: "November is the grey transition — 3°C, frequent rain turning to the first snow, and daylight shrinking fast. But Kyiv's indoor cultural life compensates: world-class ballet at the National Opera, the contemporary art scene in former industrial spaces, and restaurant culture at its most inventive. The Holodomor Remembrance Day (fourth Saturday) is a solemn and important commemoration. Warm up with banosh (Carpathian cornmeal with cheese) and honey-laced uzvar. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, making this a genuine locals' month.",
    12: "December wraps Kyiv in festive magic — temperatures hover around -2°C, snow is likely, and the Christmas markets on Sophia Square and Kontraktova Square fill with wooden stalls selling mulled wine, handmade ornaments, and grilled sausages. The New Year celebrations are enormous — Kyiv goes bigger for New Year's than Christmas (which is January 7 on the Orthodox calendar). St. Sophia Cathedral's golden domes against fresh snow and twinkling lights is one of Eastern Europe's most enchanting winter scenes. Bundle up and bring your appetite for celebration.",
  },

  'ua-lviv': {
    1: "Lviv in January is winter perfection if you like your cities cold, caffeinated, and culturally rich — think -3°C, snow-dusted Habsburg architecture, and over 1,500 cafes vying for your patronage. The Rynok Square Christmas decorations linger into early January, and Orthodox Christmas (January 7) brings carolers and candlelit church services through the cobblestone old town. The city's famous coffee culture is at its most essential — Lviv literally runs on kava — and the warm interiors of Lviv Handmade Chocolate and Masoch Cafe are perfect cold-weather refuges.",
    2: "February is Lviv at its coldest — -5°C to -8°C with proper Ukrainian winter, but the city's defiant cosiness makes it bearable and even charming. The coffee houses steam, the theatres perform nightly, and Maslenitsa brings pancake stalls and folk celebrations to the squares. Lviv's beer scene (the city claims to have brewed Ukraine's first beer) is excellent for pub-crawling through the medieval cellars of the old town. The High Castle hill offers views of snow-covered rooftops and church spires that justify the frozen climb.",
    3: "March begins the thaw in Lviv — temperatures nudge above freezing to 5°C, the snow melts into atmospheric slush, and the first outdoor tables appear optimistically in Rynok Square. International Women's Day (March 8) is celebrated with flowers and warmth, and the city's gallery scene launches spring exhibitions. Lviv's food culture — heavy, hearty, and magnificent — starts lightening with the first spring vegetables. The opera house rivals Vienna's in beauty and the tickets are a fraction of the price.",
    4: "April brings proper spring to Lviv — 13°C, blooming magnolias and cherry trees framing the Austro-Hungarian facades, and the old town buzzing with renewed energy. Easter celebrations are elaborate and beautiful, with hand-painted pysanky eggs and midnight church processions that feel centuries old. The cafe terraces fill up, the craft beer flows, and the cobblestoned streets dry out enough for comfortable wandering. Crowds are light, prices reasonable, and the city's UNESCO-listed old town is a joy to explore without summer congestion.",
    5: "May is glorious — 19°C, the city draped in chestnut and lilac blossoms, and the cultural calendar in full swing with Embroidery Day celebrations and spring festivals. The Lychakiv Cemetery, one of Europe's most beautiful, is especially moving among the spring flowers. Lviv's restaurant scene — from modern Ukrainian to traditional Galician — is among the best value fine dining in Europe. The High Castle park offers panoramic views of a city that looks like it belongs in a period film. A genuinely perfect month to visit.",
    6: "June brings warm summer to Lviv — 22°C, long days, and the cultural festivals reaching peak density. The Leopolis Jazz Fest fills the city center with world-class music, and the outdoor dining scene is in full swing across Rynok Square and the Armenian Quarter. Crowds build to their highest but Lviv never feels overwhelmed — it's still wonderfully affordable and genuinely friendly. The coffee culture extends to outdoor terraces, and the evening light on the Habsburg architecture is liquid gold. One of Europe's great undiscovered city-break destinations.",
    7: "July is peak summer — 24°C with occasional thunderstorms and the city at maximum energy. The outdoor festivals continue, the beer gardens in the old town cellars are packed, and day trips to the Carpathian foothills offer hiking and traditional highland culture (hutsul villages, wooden churches). Tourist numbers are at their peak but prices remain remarkably reasonable by European standards. A pint of craft beer and a plate of varenyky on a Rynok Square terrace costs what a coffee alone would in Prague. That's Lviv's superpower.",
    8: "August stays warm at 23°C with the best weather for combining city culture with Carpathian day trips — the mountain trails are dry and the highland pastures are gorgeous. Lviv's food scene features summer produce: fresh berries, forest mushrooms, and seasonal salads alongside the heavier Galician classics. The city's craft chocolate and coffee scenes are year-round attractions but somehow taste better in summer. Late August sees the first autumn hints as universities prepare to resume, lending a pleasant intellectual buzz to the cafe culture.",
    9: "September is Lviv's golden month — 18°C, autumn light warming the stone facades, and the cultural season reopening with opera, ballet, and new gallery exhibitions. The grape and apple harvests bring seasonal produce to Dobrobut market, and the city's wine scene (yes, Ukrainian wine) is worth exploring. Crowds thin from summer peaks, cafe terraces make their final stand before winter, and a walking tour through the old town in September light is genuinely one of Europe's great urban experiences. Book the opera — the Lviv National Opera House is stunning.",
    10: "October brings crisp autumn — 10°C, golden leaves in Stryisky Park, and that cozy Lviv atmosphere that makes you want to drink coffee and read books in candlelit cafes indefinitely. The Lviv Coffee Festival (if running) celebrates the city's obsession with a thoroughness that borders on religious. The food pivots to mushroom dishes, pumpkin, and hearty Galician stews. Tourist numbers drop to comfortable levels, and the city's best restaurants are walkable without reservations. The Lychakiv Cemetery in autumn colour is hauntingly beautiful.",
    11: "November is moody and magnificent — 4°C, grey skies, and the first snow sometimes appearing on the Carpathian peaks visible from the High Castle. Lviv retreats indoors to its natural habitat: coffee houses, book-filled cellars, and candlelit restaurants serving borscht and banosh. The cultural calendar is rich with theatre and music, and the crowds are at their lowest. This is the month Lviv was designed for — warm interiors, cold streets, and the kind of intellectual cafe culture that Central Europe used to be famous for.",
    12: "December is Lviv at its most magical — the Christmas market fills Rynok Square with wooden stalls, mulled wine (glintvein), and handmade crafts, all framed by snow-dusted Renaissance and Baroque facades. Temperatures sit around -2°C, the cobblestones gleam with frost, and the city's churches prepare for both Catholic (December 25) and Orthodox (January 7) celebrations. The chocolate shops and coffee houses are at maximum cosiness, and New Year's Eve in the old town is a joyful, affordable celebration. Lviv in December is everything Prague charges triple for.",
  },

  'ua-odesa': {
    1: "Odesa in January is cold and windswept — 2°C, the Black Sea grey and uninviting, and the famous Potemkin Steps looking suitably dramatic against winter skies. The city's legendary humour doesn't hibernate: the opera season is in full swing at the magnificent Odesa Opera House, and the restaurants along Derybasivska Street serve warming Odessan cuisine — their take on forshmak (herring pate) is the city's signature dish. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, but the indoor cultural scene and cafe culture make January surprisingly rewarding for those who pack warm.",
    2: "February is Odesa's coldest month — hovering around 0°C with occasional snow and biting wind off the Black Sea. But the city's indoor world is rich: the Odesa Fine Arts Museum, the Philharmonic concerts, and the theatre scene that's historically been among Ukraine's most vibrant. Maslenitsa brings pancake celebrations and pre-Lenten festivity. The Privoz Market is a covered wonderland of fish, cheese, and Odessan banter regardless of weather. Hot mulled wine in a Derybasivska cafe while watching snow fall on 19th-century facades is peak Odessan winter.",
    3: "March starts the thaw — temperatures climb to 7°C, the snow retreats, and Odesa begins shaking off winter with increasing energy. The famous Odessan humour festival (Humorina, April 1) preparations begin, and the city's parks show the first crocuses. The beach promenades are windswept but walkable, and the Potemkin Steps offer views of a Black Sea gradually transitioning from steel grey to blue. The restaurant scene pivots to spring menus with fresh herbs and the first local vegetables. A transitional month with genuine charm.",
    4: "April opens with Humorina (April Fool's Day) — Odesa's beloved humour festival turns the city into a street party of parades, costumes, and the sharp Odessan wit that's been famous across the Russian-speaking world for centuries. Temperatures reach 14°C, the parks bloom, and the cafe terraces along Derybasivska burst back to life. The Black Sea is still too cold for swimming (10°C) but the coastal walks along Arcadia are beautiful. Crowds are moderate, prices are gentle, and the cultural energy post-Humorina carries through the month.",
    5: "May is Odesa at its most charming — 20°C, the acacia trees blooming (the city's signature scent), and the beach season tantalizingly close with the Black Sea warming to 15°C (the brave wade in). Victory Day (May 9) carries deep significance in this hero-city. The outdoor restaurants are fully operational, the Privoz Market overflows with spring produce, and the evening promenades along the coast feel like scenes from an Odessan novel. Affordable, uncrowded, and genuinely beautiful — May is the insider's month.",
    6: "June brings summer to Odesa — 24°C, the Black Sea reaching a swimmable 20°C, and the city's famous beach culture beginning its annual takeover. Arcadia Beach and Lanzheron fill with umbrellas, music, and that uniquely Odessan mix of sophistication and irreverence. The Odesa International Film Festival brings cinematic energy, and the nightlife along Arcadia kicks into high gear. Crowds build but the city handles them with characteristic style. Fresh Black Sea mussels and cold Odessan beer on a beach terrace — June done right.",
    7: "July is peak Odesa — 28°C, the Black Sea at a lovely 24°C, and every beach packed with sunbathers. The city's legendary nightlife runs until dawn, the beach clubs compete for attention, and the cultural programming includes outdoor concerts and theatre. Arcadia transforms into a 24-hour party zone. The food is outstanding: fresh fish, Odessan-style aubergine caviar, and watermelon sold from every corner. Prices peak and booking ahead is wise for the better restaurants and hotels. The Potemkin Steps at sunset with the harbour below is timeless.",
    8: "August matches July's summer energy — 28°C, warm seas, packed beaches, and the city in full holiday mode. The Black Sea holds at 25°C (its warmest), making this the prime swimming month. Odessan families are in full beach-picnic mode, and the waterfront restaurants serve the freshest seafood of the year. The atmosphere is joyful, slightly chaotic, and deeply Odessan — equal parts European elegance and Black Sea swagger. Late August sees the first gentle cooling, and the grape harvest begins in the nearby wine region around Shabo.",
    9: "September is Odesa's golden month — 23°C, the Black Sea still warm at 22°C for late-season swimming, and the summer crowds departing like a tide going out. The light turns amber, the beach clubs thin to pleasant levels, and the city's cultural season reopens with opera, ballet, and exhibitions. The wine season is in full swing, with day trips to Black Sea vineyards rewarding. Privoz Market overflows with autumn produce. This is when Odesa feels most like itself: witty, warm, and slightly melancholic as summer ends.",
    10: "October brings crisp autumn — 14°C, the parks turning gold, and the Black Sea cooling to 16°C (last-swim-of-the-year territory). The cafe culture shifts indoors, the theatre and concert seasons are in full swing, and the Privoz Market is at its most atmospheric with seasonal mushrooms, chestnuts, and new wine. Crowds are light and the city's beauty — its 19th-century courtyards, ironwork balconies, and tree-lined boulevards — feels intimate and accessible. The famous catacombs (world's largest tunnel network) are fascinating year-round but especially atmospheric in autumn.",
    11: "November is grey and honest — 7°C, increasing wind, and the Black Sea turning hostile. But Odesa's indoor culture more than compensates: the Opera House programmes are excellent, the restaurants cosy with autumn menus, and the café culture is at its most philosophical. Tourist numbers are minimal, making this a genuine locals' experience. The Privoz Market vendors are at their most engaging without summer crowds, and a rainy afternoon browsing the literary museum or the Roerich Museum is deeply satisfying. Pack warm and embrace the Odessan melancholy.",
    12: "December wraps Odesa in modest festive atmosphere — 3°C, occasional snow, and the main streets twinkling with lights. The Opera House is magnificent during the holiday season, and the restaurants serve celebratory menus featuring Odessan specialties at year-end. New Year's Eve on Derybasivska Street is Odesa's biggest celebration — the city parties with champagne, fireworks, and that irrepressible Odessan spirit that no amount of cold weather can dampen. Winter markets, glintvein, and stuffed pike at a candlelit table — December Odesa has a rough-edged charm that polished European cities can't match.",
  },

  'ug-bwindi': {
    1: "January is one of the best months for gorilla trekking in Bwindi — it falls in the short dry season, meaning firmer trails, 25°C days, and the mountain gorillas feeding lower on the slopes where they're easier to reach. The dense montane forest is still dripping and atmospheric, and the encounter itself — sitting meters from a silverback in the wild — is among Earth's most profound wildlife experiences. Permits are expensive ($700+) and limited, so book months ahead. The surrounding Batwa communities offer cultural experiences that provide important context.",
    2: "February continues the dry window with excellent trekking conditions — manageable trails, warm mornings, and the gorillas in accessible locations. The Impenetrable Forest (yes, that's its real name) is at its least impenetrable, and the birding is outstanding with over 350 species in the park. Permits remain the main bottleneck (busyness 4/5), and the drive from Kampala is long but scenic through terraced hillsides. The altitude (1,400-2,600m) keeps things cool — pack layers and a rain jacket because the forest generates its own weather.",
    3: "March brings the long rains to Bwindi — trails become muddy and slippery, the forest is genuinely challenging to navigate, and your porters earn every shilling. Gorilla tracking still operates daily (the gorillas don't cancel for weather), but expect a tougher, muddier, and ultimately more adventurous experience. The upside: the forest is spectacularly lush, the waterfalls run strong, and permits may be slightly easier to secure. Leeches appear, so tuck your trousers into your socks and consider it a badge of honour.",
    4: "April is the wettest month — 200mm+ of rain turns Bwindi into a steaming, dripping wonderland that fully earns its 'Impenetrable' title. The gorilla families are harder to reach (they move to feed on fresh growth), and treks can extend to 6+ hours in thick mud. But the birding is extraordinary with migrants present, and the forest's raw, primal atmosphere is unforgettable. Permit availability is better and some lodges offer wet-season discounts. Waterproof everything — boots, camera, spirit — and embrace the adventure.",
    5: "May sits at the transition — rain eases toward month's end, the forest begins drying, and the gorilla trekking gradually improves. The undergrowth is thick from the rains, which can make visibility in the forest challenging, but the guides are expert trackers who've spent lifetimes here. Tourist numbers are low (busyness 2/5) and the lodges surrounding Bwindi are more available and negotiable on pricing. The mountain scenery is at peak green, and the drive through southwest Uganda's terraced hills is stunning. A month for patient, adventurous travelers.",
    6: "June marks the return of dry season and prime trekking — trails firm up, the gorillas settle into predictable patterns, and the forest opens up enough for better photography during encounters. Temperatures are comfortable at 23°C (cool at altitude), and the clear mornings mean earlier tracking starts with better light. Permits sell faster now (busyness 4/5), so book well ahead. The community tourism projects around Bwindi — Batwa cultural visits, coffee cooperatives, village walks — are excellent and ensure tourism benefits reach beyond the park gates.",
    7: "July is peak season at Bwindi — dry trails, reliable tracking conditions, and the highest demand for gorilla permits. The encounters themselves are weather-independent magic: an hour with a habituated gorilla family, watching juveniles play and the silverback maintain his dignified surveillance, is worth every penny and every muddy step. The forest is alive with primates — golden monkeys, L'Hoest's monkeys, and chimpanzees in the northern sector. Book permits 3-6 months ahead; this month sells out earliest. Post-trek sundowners at a forest-edge lodge are the proper celebration.",
    8: "August continues peak dry-season conditions — excellent trekking, the most reliable weather of the year, and permit demand at maximum. The gorilla families are well-habituated and frequently found at lower elevations, making treks shorter and more accessible. The birding remains exceptional, and the butterfly diversity in the forest clearings is remarkable. This is the most popular month alongside July, so expect to share the trails with other groups and pay premium lodge rates. But the encounter — that primal, silent communion with our closest relatives — never gets routine.",
    9: "September extends the dry season beautifully — slightly thinning crowds (4/5), continued excellent conditions, and the forest at its most accessible. This is arguably the sweet spot: near-peak conditions with marginally better permit availability and lodge pricing. The golden monkeys in Mgahinga (nearby) are an excellent add-on activity, and the dramatic volcanic landscape of the Virungas frames the experience perfectly. The coffee harvest in the surrounding communities produces excellent beans — buy some for a meaningful souvenir.",
    10: "October straddles the seasons — the short rains begin tentatively, with afternoon showers becoming more frequent but mornings staying clear for early tracking starts. The forest begins greening up and the gorillas feed actively on fresh growth. Permit demand eases slightly, and the shoulder-season pricing at lodges can save meaningful money without sacrificing the experience. The trails get their first slippery patches but nothing compared to the long-rain months. The Impenetrable Forest in early rain has a mysterious, cinematic quality.",
    11: "November brings the short rains — wetter trails, muddier conditions, but the gorilla tracking continues without pause. The forest is dramatically lush and the atmosphere almost primordial with mist, rain, and dense green canopy. Permit availability is easier and prices at surrounding lodges drop — this is budget gorilla season for those willing to get muddy. The birding actually improves as migratory species arrive, and the forest floor comes alive with fungi and fresh growth. Pack waterproofs, gaiters, and a sense of humour about mud.",
    12: "December falls in a relatively dry pocket between the rains — trails improve, the gorillas are accessible, and the festive-season visitors create a brief high-season bump (busyness 3/5). The mornings are often clear and beautiful, and the tracking conditions are surprisingly good for what many assume is rainy season. Christmas in the Bwindi area is quiet but warm, with the local communities celebrating enthusiastically. A gorilla encounter followed by a mountain-view lodge dinner might be the most extraordinary Christmas Day activity on offer anywhere.",
  },

  'ug-kampala': {
    1: "January is one of Kampala's driest months — 30°C, manageable humidity, and the seven hills of Uganda's capital at their most walkable. The city's chaotic energy, matatu-taxi madness, and rolex (not the watch — it's a rolled chapati with egg and vegetables) culture are best experienced when you're not being rained on. The Kasubi Tombs, Namugongo Martyrs Shrine, and the bustling Owino Market are must-visits. The nightlife in Kololo and Bugolobi is vibrant, and the Nile breweries keep things social. This is also prime time for day trips to the source of the Nile in Jinja.",
    2: "February stays dry and warm at 31°C — arguably Kampala's most pleasant month with lower humidity and clear skies that let you see the surrounding green hills. The craft markets in the city center sell excellent Ugandan textiles and jewelry. Jinja's Nile rafting is at its most exciting with optimal water levels, and the Ssese Islands in Lake Victoria are a short ferry ride for a beach break. The Ugandan food scene revolves around the beloved rolex, luwombo (steamed banana-leaf parcels), and some of the world's best fresh tropical fruit.",
    3: "March brings the long rains — afternoon storms dump 130mm+ on the red-clay hills, turning the city's unpaved roads into rivers and the green spaces into jungles. The upside: the Botanical Gardens at Entebbe are spectacular, and the birdlife across the Kampala area is exceptional as migrants arrive. The music and nightlife scene doesn't pause for rain. The rain is usually a dramatic two-hour affair followed by cool, clear evenings perfect for outdoor dining. Bring waterproof shoes and plan around the afternoon window.",
    4: "April is the wettest month — 175mm of rain and humidity that makes the equatorial heat feel personal. The city slows slightly but the culture never stops: live music at Ndere Cultural Centre, the theatre scene, and Kampala's growing food scene all thrive indoors. Lake Victoria's northern shore is moodily beautiful in the rain, and the nearby Mabira Forest offers stunning (if muddy) rainforest walks. The matoke (steamed banana) and groundnut sauce is comfort food perfected, and you'll need it between downpours.",
    5: "May sees the rains easing — still 120mm but the storms become less frequent and more predictable, and Kampala starts shaking off the wet season. The hills are impossibly green, the birdlife is outstanding, and the equatorial sun returns with increasing confidence. The waragi (local gin) and Nile beer flow freely at the city's growing craft bar scene. The white-water rafting at Jinja is excellent as the Nile runs high, and the chimpanzee tracking at nearby Kibale Forest is in good form. Kampala rewards those who don't need everything to be polished.",
    6: "June opens the dry season — 27°C with comfortable humidity and reliable sunshine. This is Kampala at its most accessible: the roads firm up, the outdoor markets buzz, and day-trip destinations like Jinja (bungee jumping and rafting), Entebbe (zoo and botanical gardens), and the Ssese Islands are all in prime condition. The cultural scene is vibrant, with music festivals and the growing film industry adding creative energy. Kampala's street food — rolex, samosa, and fresh sugarcane juice — is a meal plan in itself.",
    7: "July is dry-season prime — 26°C, minimal rain, and the city humming with activity. The Kampala nightlife in Kisementi and Industrial Area is legendary and runs until dawn. Day trips to Jinja for rafting, Entebbe for lake-shore relaxation, or the Ngamba Island Chimpanzee Sanctuary are all excellent. The Ugandan coffee scene is emerging with excellent single-origin beans from the Rwenzori and Elgon regions. Tourist numbers are moderate — Uganda flies under the safari radar compared to Kenya and Tanzania, which is part of its appeal.",
    8: "August stays dry and comfortable at 27°C — the best conditions for exploring Kampala's sprawling, energetic, wonderfully chaotic landscape of markets, churches, mosques, and matatu madness. The independence celebrations (approaching October 9) begin percolating, and the city's arts scene is active with exhibitions and performances. The boda-boda (motorcycle taxi) is the quintessential Kampala transport experience — terrifying and efficient in equal measure. The food is magnificent: freshwater tilapia from Lake Victoria, roasted chicken and chips, and the ever-present rolex.",
    9: "September sits between the dry seasons — 29°C with the first hints of rain returning, though conditions remain predominantly dry and pleasant. The Bayimba International Festival of Arts brings music, dance, and performance to Kampala, and the cultural energy is high. The surrounding countryside is starting to green up, and the day-trip options expand as both weather and roads cooperate. Kampala's Indian food scene (reflecting the significant South Asian diaspora) is excellent and surprisingly affordable. A sweet spot of good weather and building cultural momentum.",
    10: "October brings the short rains — afternoon showers return, temperatures hover at 28°C, and the city's vegetation explodes back to full tropical density. Independence Day (October 9) is celebrated with parades and cultural events, and the national pride is infectious. The rain keeps things cool and the evening dining scene is excellent. This is a good month for combining Kampala with gorilla trekking in Bwindi, as the shoulder-season pricing kicks in for both. The matoke and groundnut stew taste even better when it's raining outside.",
    11: "November is the heart of the short rains — 140mm of afternoon downpours, 28°C humidity, and the vivid green of equatorial Africa at full throttle. The city adapts rather than stops, with covered markets and indoor venues keeping things moving. The birdlife around Kampala and the surrounding wetlands is exceptional during the rainy season. The Buganda Kingdom's cultural sites — palaces, tombs, and traditional court ceremonies — offer fascinating insights into one of Africa's most sophisticated pre-colonial cultures.",
    12: "December bridges the short rains and the dry season — rain eases mid-month and the festive season brings energy to Kampala's streets. Christmas is celebrated with genuine gusto, and the outdoor dining scene ramps up for the holiday crowds. Temperatures sit at 29°C and the evenings are warm and social. This is a popular time for diaspora Ugandans to return, creating a reunion atmosphere in restaurants and bars. The drive to Jinja for New Year's rafting is a tradition, and a cold Bell beer on the banks of the Nile is the proper way to close the year.",
  },

  'us-california': {
    1: "January in California splits in two: the coast from San Francisco to LA sits around 15°C with winter rains greening the hills, while the deserts offer clear skies and a comfortable 20°C — perfect Joshua Tree and Death Valley weather. The ski season at Tahoe and Mammoth is in full swing with fresh powder. The wine country (Napa, Sonoma) is quiet and atmospheric for tastings without the crowds. Whale watching peaks along the coast as grey whales migrate south. In-N-Out tastes the same regardless of season, which is to say: perfect.",
    2: "February continues the pattern — rain on the coast (this is when California actually gets green, contrary to the golden stereotype), excellent skiing in the Sierra, and desert wildflower season starting to tease in Anza-Borrego. The Monterey coast is moody and dramatic, and the Big Sur drive is at its most theatrical with waterfalls running at full force. Valentine's Day in wine country is predictably popular but genuinely lovely. San Diego sits at a sunny 18°C, reminding the rest of the state that Southern California exists in a different weather system entirely.",
    3: "March is California's spring unveiling — 18°C on the coast, the hills blazing emerald green, and the desert super bloom (in good rain years) carpeting Death Valley and Anza-Borrego in wildflowers that make national news. The hiking in Yosemite's lower elevations opens up, and the waterfalls are thundering from snowmelt. Wine country starts its gorgeous spring phase with mustard flowers between the vines. Crowds are moderate everywhere except during spring break weeks. The taco trucks of LA operate at peak efficiency year-round, but March light flatters everything.",
    4: "April is arguably California's sweet spot — 20°C coastal days, Yosemite's waterfalls at peak flow, and the golden poppies blanketing the Antelope Valley in orange carpets visible from space. The beaches from Santa Barbara to San Diego are gorgeous without the summer crowds, and the Pacific warms just enough for wetsuit surfing. Napa's vineyards are lush green and uncrowded, Big Sur is spectacular, and the skiing season wraps up at Mammoth with spring corn snow. The farmers' markets overflow with artichokes, strawberries, and citrus.",
    5: "May brings the marine layer — that famous coastal fog that keeps LA and SF mornings grey while the inland valleys bake at 28°C. But by afternoon the coast clears to glorious sunshine, and the beaches are warm enough to enjoy without summer's parking nightmares. Yosemite is at its most spectacular with full waterfalls and accessible trails (Tioga Pass opens late May in good years). The wine country is verdant and uncrowded, and the Central Coast — Paso Robles, San Luis Obispo — is California's best-kept wine secret.",
    6: "June marks California's famous 'June Gloom' — persistent coastal fog that disappointingly cloaks LA and San Francisco in grey mornings, though it usually burns off by noon. Head inland: Yosemite is magnificent with long days and flowing waterfalls, Lake Tahoe's crystal waters are accessible, and the Sierra backcountry opens for hiking season. Crowds build at Disneyland and the major beaches but the state is so vast that solitude is always a canyon away. The farmers' market stone fruit — peaches, cherries, apricots — is outstanding. Summer pricing kicks in at coastal hotels.",
    7: "July is peak California summer — 30°C+ inland, 24°C on the coast (fog-free now), and every beach from Malibu to La Jolla packed with sun-seekers. Yosemite is crowded (book campsites months ahead), Tahoe is full summer lake mode, and the Pacific coast highway is as iconic as ever. The Central Valley hits 40°C, which is why nobody vacations there. The state fair, Fourth of July celebrations, and outdoor concert season all hit simultaneously. Budget for premium everything, but remember: a beach sunset in Big Sur costs nothing.",
    8: "August continues July's heat — the hottest month inland at 35°C+, though the coast stays comfortable at 24°C with reliable sunshine. The beaches are packed, Yosemite is at maximum capacity, and Tahoe's lake temperature peaks at its most swimmable. This is when California's fire season can disrupt plans with smoke — check conditions before heading to the Sierra or north coast. The tomato harvest produces the best produce of the year at farmers' markets, and the outdoor dining scene from LA to SF is in full swing. Late August hints at autumn with slightly shorter days.",
    9: "September is California's real summer — the marine layer is gone, the coast is warm and clear at 25°C, and the crowds vanish after Labor Day weekend. Napa and Sonoma's grape harvest (crush season) is the wine world's most exciting time, and the tasting rooms buzz with fresh-pressed juice turning to wine. Yosemite clears out and the park feels almost intimate. The beaches are at their warmest, the hiking is superb, and the light turns golden in a way that explains why Hollywood chose this place. The insiders' month, no contest.",
    10: "October extends September's magic — warm days (23°C coast, 28°C inland), fire-season concerns (check conditions), and the wine country in its most photogenic harvest phase. The Eastern Sierra fall colors around June Lake and Bishop Creek rival New England. Halloween in West Hollywood and San Francisco's Castro is an event unto itself. Whale watching resumes as humpbacks linger along the coast, and the surfing conditions are excellent with south swells. The farmers' markets feature pomegranates, persimmons, and late-season figs.",
    11: "November is quiet and gorgeous — 18°C on the coast, the first rains greening the hills after summer's golden-brown, and the crowds at a fraction of summer levels. Wine country wraps up harvest with cozy tasting rooms and reduced pricing. Thanksgiving in Napa is a foodie's pilgrimage. Death Valley returns to perfect hiking weather at 22°C, and Joshua Tree's climbing season is in full swing. The early winter surf picks up on the north coast. California after the tourists leave is, ironically, when the living is easiest.",
    12: "December splits: SoCal stays mild at 18°C with beach walks and outdoor dining still viable in LA and San Diego, while NorCal gets grey, rainy, and properly atmospheric. Tahoe and Mammoth's ski season opens (snow permitting), and the holiday lights in cities from SF's Union Square to LA's Griffith Observatory are festive without East Coast misery. Wine country is cozy and uncrowded for tastings, Death Valley is perfect for hiking, and a Christmas morning surf session in Malibu followed by fish tacos is peak California living.",
  },

  'us-hawaii': {
    1: "January is Hawaii's wettest and coolest month — 'coolest' meaning 26°C, because Hawaii doesn't really do cold. The North Shore of Oahu gets massive 10-meter swells that draw the world's best surfers to Pipeline and Sunset Beach, making it the spectator sport of the winter. Whale watching peaks as humpbacks fill the channels between Maui and Lanai. The rain mostly hits the windward sides, leaving the leeward beaches sunny. Crowds are moderate post-holidays, and a plate lunch of kalua pork and macaroni salad tastes like home no matter where you're from.",
    2: "February keeps the winter surf pumping on the North Shore and the humpback whales breaching offshore — the Maui Whale Festival celebrates their arrival in style. Temperatures hold at a perfect 26°C with the Kona (leeward) coasts staying dry and sunny while the windward sides get their tropical showers. The hiking on Kauai's Na Pali Coast is lush but muddy, and the Big Island's Volcanoes National Park steams dramatically in the cooler air. Valentine's Day in Maui is predictably popular — book that beachfront dinner early.",
    3: "March starts the transition — winter swells begin easing (North Shore surf is still good but less epic), whale season continues strong, and the wildflowers on Maui's Haleakala slopes add splashes of color. Temperatures push toward 27°C and the rain decreases noticeably. Spring break brings a crowd spike mid-month, especially on Oahu and Maui, so book ahead. The shave ice season is technically year-round but hits different as the sun gets stronger. Snorkeling at Molokini crater and Hanauma Bay is excellent with calmer winter swells.",
    4: "April is a sweet spot — the whales make their final appearances before heading to Alaska, the surf transitions to calmer summer patterns, and temperatures settle at 27°C with decreasing rain. The Merrie Monarch Festival on the Big Island is the world's premier hula competition and a genuine cultural treasure. Crowds ease after spring break, prices moderate, and the underwater visibility improves as winter swells fade. Every island shines in April, from Kauai's emerald valleys to the Big Island's lava fields.",
    5: "May ushers in Hawaiian summer — 28°C, calm seas on the north shores (perfect for swimming at Waimea Bay), and the south shores picking up their summer swells for surfers. Lei Day (May 1) celebrates Hawaiian culture with flower-lei-making festivals across the islands. The hiking conditions are excellent on all islands with drier weather and manageable temperatures. Crowds are moderate, and the luau experience — kalua pig, poi, hula — is at its most enjoyable outdoors. Maui's Road to Hana is spectacular with waterfalls still running from winter rains.",
    6: "June brings full summer — 29°C, calm north shores for swimming and snorkeling, and reliable south-shore surf. The beaches at Lanikai, Ka'anapali, and Poipu are at their best: warm water, clear visibility, and enough sun to justify that fourth application of reef-safe sunscreen. The Kamehameha Day celebrations (June 11) honour Hawaii's unifying king with parades and lei draping. Crowds build as mainland schools release, especially on Oahu and Maui. A sunset catamaran cruise off Waikiki with dolphins alongside is peak Hawaiian living.",
    7: "July is peak season — 30°C, packed beaches, and fireworks over Waikiki for the Fourth of July that rival any mainland show. Every island is at maximum occupancy, prices peak, and that famous aloha spirit gets tested by resort pool territorial disputes. But the conditions are undeniably gorgeous: calm, warm seas for snorkeling (manta ray night dives on the Big Island are extraordinary), and 13 hours of daylight. The Big Island's Kilauea may or may not be erupting — check the USGS updates for the latest volcanic drama.",
    8: "August matches July's heat and crowds — 30°C, packed resorts, and the south-shore surf running consistently. The humidity ticks up and brief tropical showers become more frequent, though they're usually over in minutes. The underwater visibility is excellent, making this prime snorkeling and diving season. Duke's OceanFest on Waikiki celebrates surf culture and ocean sports. Late August sees the first crowd relief, and the sunset from Haleakala (10,000 feet above it all) remains one of the Pacific's most spectacular regardless of the season.",
    9: "September is Hawaii's secret best month — the summer crowds vanish, temperatures hold at 29°C, and the ocean is at its warmest and calmest. Prices drop noticeably (the post-Labor Day effect), and every beach, trail, and restaurant has breathing room. The Aloha Festivals celebrate Hawaiian culture with events across the islands. Snorkeling is at its annual best with peak visibility, and the south-shore surf provides consistent fun waves. The light turns golden earlier, making sunset chasing even more rewarding. The locals breathe easier too.",
    10: "October starts the slow transition — temperatures ease to 28°C, the first winter swells tease the North Shore (drawing early surf pilgrims), and the humpback whale scouts sometimes appear by month's end. Rain begins picking up on the windward sides, but the leeward coasts stay reliably sunny. Halloween in Lahaina, Maui (if the town has rebuilt) was legendarily over-the-top, and the autumn shoulder season delivers excellent value. The hiking on the Big Island — from Kilauea crater to Pololu Valley — is comfortable and uncrowded.",
    11: "November brings the winter transformation — North Shore surf builds to serious size, the humpback whales begin arriving from Alaska, and the rain increases on windward slopes. Temperatures stay warm at 27°C and the leeward beaches remain sunny beach days. Thanksgiving in Hawaii is a unique fusion of mainland tradition and local ohana culture, with kalua turkey alongside the traditional spread. The Ironman World Championship (if in November) turns Kona into endurance-sport central. Surfing spectators should post up at Pipeline — the season is opening.",
    12: "December is Hawaii at its most festive — 26°C, holiday lights draped over palm trees, and the world's best surfers battling 15-meter waves on the North Shore during the Triple Crown and Pipe Masters. Whale watching heats up as more humpbacks arrive daily. Christmas and New Year bring peak crowds and peak prices to every island (book months ahead), but the spirit is genuinely warm and the beachfront luau with a holiday twist is special. The Eddie Aikau big-wave invitational is always 'on hold' waiting for 12m+ surf — when it goes, it's the greatest show in surfing.",
  },

  'us-mountain': {
    1: "January in the Mountain West is winter's domain — ski season peaks with fresh powder at Park City, Jackson Hole, and Telluride, while the deserts of Arizona and New Mexico bask in a pleasant 15°C under vast blue skies. The Grand Canyon dusted in snow is one of America's most dramatic winter sights, and Sedona's red rocks against blue sky never disappoint. Las Vegas is at its cheapest and most manageable. The contrast between skiing in Utah at 2°C and hiking in Scottsdale at 20°C — both on the same day — is peak Mountain West versatility.",
    2: "February keeps the ski season strong — Sundance Film Festival vibes linger in Park City, and the powder at Alta, Snowbird, and Big Sky is often at its deepest. The desert Southwest is gorgeous: Monument Valley in winter light, White Sands under crisp blue skies, and the Sonoran Desert's first wildflowers hinting at the spectacular spring to come. Temperatures range from -5°C in the mountains to 22°C in the Arizona desert. Valentine's Day in Santa Fe's adobe warmth — with green chile on everything — is underratedly romantic.",
    3: "March is the great divide: spring skiing with corn snow and sunshine at 5°C in the Rockies, while the desert Southwest hits a perfect 25°C for hiking season. The Arizona desert wildflower bloom starts building toward its March-April peak, and the Grand Canyon's South Rim is comfortable for rim-to-rim hiking without summer's brutal heat. Moab's red rock country — Arches and Canyonlands — is at its most hiker-friendly. The mountain towns start thawing, and the mud season between ski and summer creates some deals for the flexible.",
    4: "April is when the Mountain West gets complicated: ski resorts close one by one (Mammoth and A-Basin hold out), the desert heats up to 30°C (still pleasant), and the national parks start their spring awakening. Zion's Narrows are running high with snowmelt (check conditions), and the Grand Canyon's inner canyon turns genuinely warm. The Sonoran Desert's saguaro cactus bloom is spectacular, and Santa Fe's art galleries are uncrowded and exceptional. Between the mud and the bloom, April rewards flexible planning.",
    5: "May opens the hiking season across the Mountain West — Zion, Bryce, and Capitol Reef are perfect at 25°C, the wildflowers in the Colorado Rockies start appearing at lower elevations, and the desert transitions from pleasant to increasingly hot. Memorial Day marks the unofficial summer start with crowds arriving at the national parks (book campsites early). The rim trails at Grand Canyon are in prime condition, and Mountain biking in Moab is world-class. The chile verde in New Mexico is exceptional year-round, but it tastes better after a desert hike.",
    6: "June is Mountain West summer — the Rockies shed their snow (mostly), opening alpine trails in Rocky Mountain National Park, Grand Teton, and Glacier. The desert Southwest crosses into hot territory: Phoenix hits 40°C (avoid unless you enjoy suffering), but the higher elevations of Sedona (32°C) and Santa Fe (28°C) remain livable. National park crowds are heavy, especially at Yellowstone and Grand Canyon. The Telluride Bluegrass Festival is one of America's great outdoor music events. Early morning hikes beat the heat everywhere.",
    7: "July is peak everything — the Rocky Mountain high country is at its most accessible with wildflower meadows, clear trails, and 25°C mountain days. Yellowstone's geysers, wildlife, and crowds are all at maximum. The desert is brutally hot (45°C in Phoenix, 50°C in Death Valley), so stick to the mountains and the Four Corners high country. Monsoon season begins in the Southwest, bringing dramatic afternoon thunderstorms that create waterfalls in slot canyons. The Fourth of July in a mountain town — Park City, Aspen, Jackson — is quintessentially American.",
    8: "August stays warm in the mountains (24°C) with the best backpacking conditions of the year in the Rockies and Sierra. The Southwest monsoon is in full force: spectacular lightning storms, flash flood risk in slot canyons, and a lushness in the desert that surprises everyone. Yellowstone and Glacier are busy but the backcountry offers solitude. The Perseid meteor shower from a dark-sky location (Chaco Canyon, Bryce Canyon) is unforgettable. Late August sees the first autumn hints in the aspen groves, and the crowds start their slow retreat.",
    9: "September is the Mountain West's golden month — the aspens turn gold across Colorado, Utah, and New Mexico, the hiking is sublime at 20°C, and the national park crowds thin dramatically after Labor Day. The Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta (early October) preparations buzz, and the high country is at its most photogenic. The desert returns to comfortable temperatures (32°C in Sedona), and the monsoon eases. A drive over the Million Dollar Highway in Colorado with golden aspens is one of America's great road trips.",
    10: "October extends the magic — fall colors peak in the Rockies and work their way down to the canyon country, temperatures in the desert are a perfect 25°C, and the national parks are blissfully uncrowded. The Albuquerque Balloon Fiesta fills the sky with 500+ hot air balloons at dawn — genuinely one of the world's great spectacles. Hiking in Zion, Bryce, and Grand Canyon is at its annual best: perfect weather, fall light, no crowds. The first dustings of snow appear on the highest peaks, signaling ski season ahead.",
    11: "November is the quiet transition — the ski resorts open (Arapahoe Basin, Keystone lead the charge), the desert cools to a glorious 20°C for hiking, and the shoulder-season pricing across the region is excellent. The Grand Canyon in November light, without the summer hordes, is a revelation. Thanksgiving in Santa Fe — green chile turkey, anyone? — is a uniquely Southwestern experience. The national parks shift to winter hours but the landscapes are stunning under the lower sun angle. Pack for everything; the Mountain West does all four seasons in a day.",
    12: "December means ski season is on — fresh snow blankets the Rockies, and resorts from Vail to Taos fire up their lifts. The desert Southwest is perfect for hiking at 15°C with crystal-clear air and dramatic shadows. The Pueblo cultural celebrations in New Mexico blend Catholic and indigenous traditions in ways found nowhere else. Las Vegas goes full festive, and the Grand Canyon under a dusting of snow is postcard material. Christmas in a log cabin in Jackson Hole or a ski chalet in Telluride is the Mountain West doing winter exactly right.",
  },

  'us-northeast': {
    1: "January in New York is brutally cold — 3°C highs, biting wind off the Hudson, and the occasional nor'easter dumping 30cm of snow on Manhattan. But the city is magnificent: Broadway shows are in full season, the museums (Met, MoMA, Guggenheim) are uncrowded, and the restaurant scene is at its coziest with winter menus featuring everything from Chinatown dumplings to Brooklyn ramen. Central Park under snow is genuinely magical. Post-holiday prices drop across hotels and flights. A hot pretzel from a street vendor has never been more essential.",
    2: "February is New York's cheapest month — still freezing at 4°C but Valentine's Day brings romantic energy, Fashion Week electrifies the industry crowd, and the Lunar New Year celebrations in Chinatown and Flushing are spectacular. The rest of the Northeast is in full winter mode: skiing in Vermont (Stowe, Killington) is excellent, and the coastal towns of New England are hauntingly beautiful in their off-season solitude. Bundle up for a walk across the Brooklyn Bridge at sunset — the cold is real but the views are life-altering.",
    3: "March is mud season in New England and the Northeast's least glamorous month — 8°C with slushy grey everything in New York, the ski season winding down (spring skiing in Vermont still delivers), and that 'will winter ever end' vibe. But the St. Patrick's Day parade down Fifth Avenue is enormous, the restaurant week deals are excellent, and the first crocuses in Central Park feel like a personal victory. Boston's South End restaurant scene is one of America's best and doesn't care about the weather.",
    4: "April is the Northeast's spring revelation — 16°C in New York, cherry blossoms erupting in Central Park and the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, and the entire region shaking off winter with palpable relief. The Boston Marathon electrifies Massachusetts, and the coastal towns of Cape Cod and Maine start their cautious seasonal awakening. Baseball's Opening Day adds a ceremonial energy. The restaurant patios open, the farmers' markets return, and the city's energy shifts from endurance to celebration. Rain is frequent but brief.",
    5: "May is glorious — 22°C, Central Park in full bloom, and the Northeast delivering the spring it's been promising since March. The rooftop bars open across Manhattan and Brooklyn, the High Line is lush with plantings, and the Hamptons season begins its buildup. New England's coastal towns open for business with lobster shacks and harbor walks. The hiking in the Hudson Valley, Catskills, and Green Mountains is superb with fresh foliage and wildflowers. Memorial Day weekend signals summer's arrival with beach openings from the Jersey Shore to Cape Cod.",
    6: "June brings warm, perfect days — 27°C in New York, long evenings in the parks, and the cultural calendar stacked with Shakespeare in the Park, outdoor concerts, and gallery openings. The Jersey Shore and Long Island beaches hit their stride, and the lobster in Maine starts its legendary summer run. Pride Month transforms NYC with the world's most famous parade. New England's coastal towns — Portland, Newport, Provincetown — are in fine form. The food from street carts to starred restaurants is at its most ambitious. Summer has arrived and it's magnificent.",
    7: "July is peak Northeast summer — 30°C in New York with humidity that'll flatten your hair, packed parks and beaches, and the Fourth of July fireworks over the East River drawing millions. Cape Cod, Martha's Vineyard, and Nantucket are in full season (book months ahead). The Berkshires host Tanglewood music festivals, and Maine's coast delivers the lobster-boat-to-table experience that dreams are made of. Central Park's Shakespeare performances, if you can snag tickets, are summer magic. Hydrate, ride the Staten Island Ferry for free views, and embrace the sweat.",
    8: "August is hot, humid, and the last hurrah — 29°C with the city's energy somehow intensifying even as many locals flee to the beaches. The US Open tennis tournament arrives late month, and the outdoor dining scene from Williamsburg to the West Village is at maximum buzz. New England's beaches are at their warmest (still bracing by global standards), and the Maine lobster is at peak season and quality. Late August carries a bittersweet quality — summer's fading but the city squeezes every last drop of rooftop cocktails and park picnics from it.",
    9: "September is the Northeast's golden month — 24°C in New York, the summer crowds departing, and that particular September light that makes the city look like a Woody Allen film. Fashion Week returns, the cultural season reopens with symphony, ballet, and theatre premieres, and Central Park's first hints of autumn color appear. New England's fall foliage begins in northern Vermont and Maine, starting one of nature's great color shows. The apple cider, pumpkin patches, and hiking in the Catskills and White Mountains — September starts the Northeast's most beautiful season.",
    10: "October is peak fall and the Northeast delivers — New England's foliage peaks in a blaze of crimson, amber, and gold that draws leaf-peepers from around the world. New York settles into a perfect 17°C with the Halloween buildup transforming the Village and Brooklyn into creative spectacles. The hiking in the Adirondacks, Green Mountains, and Acadia National Park is at its annual best. Apple picking, cider donuts, and pumpkin everything are seasonal requirements. The only downside: New England's country roads get genuinely crowded on peak foliage weekends.",
    11: "November is the Northeast's cozy pivot — 10°C in New York, the trees bare, and the city gearing up for the holidays. The Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade is an American institution (arrive obscenely early for a viewing spot), and the food scene reaches its most indulgent with Thanksgiving menus everywhere. Black Friday shopping on Fifth Avenue is either thrilling or horrifying depending on your constitution. The Rockefeller Center tree goes up, ice skating opens in Central Park, and the city begins its transformation into a holiday postcard.",
    12: "December is New York at its most iconic — the Rockefeller Center tree, the Saks Fifth Avenue light show, the window displays on Fifth Avenue, and the energy of a city that takes the holidays personally. Temperatures hover around 5°C with the possibility of a white Christmas (though it's rarer than the movies suggest). Broadway is in peak season, the restaurants compete with elaborate holiday menus, and New Year's Eve in Times Square — if you have the stamina and the bladder for it — is a bucket-list spectacle. Bundle up and let the city dazzle you.",
  },

  'us-pnw': {
    1: "January in the Pacific Northwest is peak grey — Seattle sits at 7°C under a blanket of cloud with 140mm of rain, and Portland matches it puddle for puddle. But the coffee culture is at its coziest, Powell's Books is the world's largest bookstore for a reason, and the skiing at Crystal Mountain, Mt. Baker, and Mt. Hood is in full swing with fresh Pacific powder. The Olympic Peninsula's rainforests are at their most primordially lush. This is when PNW residents prove their mettle: flannel, Gore-Tex, and a flat white in hand. No umbrellas — that's how you spot a tourist.",
    2: "February continues the grey — still 8°C and drizzly, but the days are getting noticeably longer and the first crocuses appear. The skiing remains excellent, and the Oregon coast is dramatically storm-swept (bring waterproofs and a camera for those crashing waves). Seattle's restaurant scene is among America's best, with Pacific Northwest cuisine — Dungeness crab, foraged mushrooms, and local oysters — at its winter peak. Portland's craft beer scene provides essential warmth. The San Juan Islands are quiet and atmospheric for a ferry adventure.",
    3: "March brings the first real spring hints — 11°C, scattered sunny days that make the entire region collectively gasp with gratitude, and the cherry blossoms at UW's Quad in Seattle creating a viral sensation. The tulip fields of Skagit Valley start blooming late month, and the skiing transitions to spring conditions. Portland's food cart pods are excellent rain or shine, and the Oregon coast begins its transition from dramatic winter to moody spring. The hiking in the Columbia River Gorge shows the first waterfall-season glory.",
    4: "April is when the PNW earns its reputation — 14°C, the Skagit Valley tulip festival in full blaze, and the Columbia Gorge waterfalls at peak flow from snowmelt. Sunny days increase and the hiking season opens in the lowlands. The cherry blossoms give way to dogwoods and rhododendrons, and the farmers' markets reopen with spring greens and morel mushrooms. Crowds are light outside the tulip fields, and Seattle's Pike Place Market is lively without summer's gridlock. The rainforests of Olympic National Park are impossibly green.",
    5: "May is the PNW's spring sweet spot — 17°C, increasingly sunny, and the mountains still snowcapped while the valleys burst with wildflowers. The hiking in Mt. Rainier's lower trails opens up, and the Oregon coast transitions to pleasant beach-walk weather. Portland's food scene is in full bloom with outdoor dining and the famous food carts operating at peak efficiency. Seattle's Ballard neighborhood hosts the best farmers' market in the region. The craft beer flows freely from hundreds of local breweries. This is the month PNW residents wait all winter for.",
    6: "June brings the start of PNW summer — 20°C, longer dry spells, and the first hints that the region might actually be the paradise the residents claim (then deny to outsiders). Mt. Rainier's wildflower meadows begin blooming, the San Juan Islands are gorgeous for kayaking and orca watching, and the Oregon coast finally feels comfortable for extended beach days. The craft brewery patios fill up, the farmers' markets overflow, and the outdoor concert season begins. Still cheaper than July-August, and the locals are in an aggressively good mood.",
    7: "July is PNW perfection — 24°C, virtually no rain, and the region reveals why people put up with nine months of grey. Mt. Rainier's wildflower season peaks, the San Juan Islands offer orca sightings and stunning kayaking, and the Oregon coast is warm and magnificent. Every patio, beer garden, and rooftop bar is packed with sun-worshipping Seattleites. The lavender harvest on Whidbey Island and the berries at every farmers' market are summer highlights. Book everything ahead — this is when the secret gets out.",
    8: "August continues July's paradise — 25°C, the driest month of the year, and the entire region operating at maximum outdoor intensity. Crater Lake in Oregon is fully accessible and impossibly blue, the backcountry in the Cascades offers spectacular multi-day hikes, and the Hood River wind and kite surfing is world-class. The peach and berry harvest fills every farmers' market, and Seattle's seafood (salmon run!) is at its peak. Wildfire smoke can occasionally drift in, checking what should be clear skies — monitor air quality. Late August's subtle cooling signals summer's denouement.",
    9: "September is the PNW's golden month — still warm at 20°C, reliably dry, and the crowds thinning as schools resume. The apple and grape harvests are in full swing, the Cascade fall colors begin at higher elevations, and the hiking is superb with clear air and fewer people. Portland's food and beer scenes are at their creative peak during the fall festival season. The San Juan Islands are calm and uncrowded, and the Oregon coast enters its most photogenic phase with warm light and dramatic skies. The insiders' summer extends through September.",
    10: "October brings the rain back — but slowly, with 80mm and plenty of sunny breaks between the returning grey. Temperatures ease to 14°C, the fall colors in the Cascades and Columbia Gorge are stunning, and the mushroom foraging season begins in earnest (chanterelles!). Portland's cozy season returns with rain-splattered food cart visits and brewery taproom culture. Halloween in Seattle's Capitol Hill and Portland's Alberta Arts District is creatively intense. The ski resorts start making snow, and the locals resign themselves to nine months of flannel.",
    11: "November is when the PNW retreats indoors — 9°C, steady rain, and the region settling into its familiar grey cocoon. But the coffee shops are extraordinary, the bookstores beckon, and the food scene pivots to hearty mushroom dishes, Dungeness crab season (opener!), and warming stews. Portland's craft beer scene releases its imperial stouts and barrel-aged specialties. The Oregon coast in November storms is dramatically beautiful from a warm, dry viewpoint. Ski season begins at Baker, Stevens Pass, and Mt. Hood. Embrace the hygge.",
    12: "December wraps the PNW in festive drizzle — 6°C, dark by 4pm, and the holiday lights reflecting off wet streets in a way that's actually beautiful. Portland's ZooLights and Seattle's Westlake holiday market add cheer, and the Nutcracker performances at Pacific Northwest Ballet are a tradition. Skiing ramps up with early-season snow, the oyster bars and crab houses are in full winter mode, and a rainy evening pub crawl through Seattle's Pioneer Square or Portland's Pearl District is cozy perfection. New Year's at the Space Needle, with fireworks over the grey skyline, is quintessentially PNW.",
  },

  'us-southeast': {
    1: "January in Florida and the Southeast is snowbird season — 22°C in Miami, 18°C in Savannah, and every Midwesterner with a passport to warmth claiming their beach chair. The Everglades are at their absolute best: dry season concentrates wildlife around water sources, making gator and bird sightings practically guaranteed. The Keys are gorgeous with calm seas and excellent diving. Orlando's theme parks have post-holiday lulls that mean shorter queues. The Art Deco District in Miami Beach is at peak people-watching season, and the stone crab claws are in full season.",
    2: "February keeps the Southeast mild and dry — Miami at 24°C, the Keys crystal-clear for snorkeling, and the Everglades wildlife viewing still excellent. The Daytona 500 kicks off NASCAR season, and the Miami International Boat Show turns the waterfront into a floating luxury showroom. Mardi Gras in New Orleans (timing varies) is the Southeast's biggest party — a hurricane of brass bands, king cake, and theatrical excess that makes Carnival look restrained. Savannah's squares are blooming with camellias, and the shrimp and grits are magnificent.",
    3: "March is spring break chaos at the Florida beaches — 26°C in Miami, packed pools, and the particular energy of college students temporarily freed from responsibility. The Keys and Dry Tortugas are perfect for diving with peak visibility and calm seas. Savannah's azaleas explode in pink and purple, framing the historic squares in living watercolour. St. Augustine, America's oldest city, is lovely in spring without summer's crush. The food across the Southeast — from Tampa's Cuban sandwiches to Charleston's she-crab soup — never has an off-season.",
    4: "April brings perfect Southeast weather — 28°C in Florida, low humidity, and the crowds thinning after spring break. The Masters at Augusta (if you can get in) is golf's most prestigious event. Charleston and Savannah are in full bloom with festivals, garden tours, and evening strolls along tree-canopied streets. The Everglades start heating up and drying out, concentrating the wildlife even further. The Gulf Coast beaches from Pensacola to Naples are gorgeous with warm, calm water. April is the Southeast before the summer humidity hammer falls.",
    5: "May signals the transition — temperatures push to 30°C, humidity builds, and Florida's summer thunderstorm pattern begins its daily 3pm curtain call. The beaches are warm and less crowded than spring break, and the sea temperature hits a lovely 27°C. The Outer Banks of North Carolina start their summer season with manageable crowds. New Orleans' Jazz Fest (if it falls in May) is a world-class celebration of music and Louisiana cuisine. The key lime pie in the Keys is mandatory, and the Cuban coffee in Miami is strong enough to alter your perception of time.",
    6: "June kicks off Southeast summer — 33°C, high humidity, and afternoon thunderstorms that are dramatic but predictable (they usually clear by 5pm). The beaches from Miami to Destin are packed with summer families, and Orlando's theme parks hit maximum intensity. But the water is 29°C and perfect for all-day swimming. The Outer Banks and Gulf Islands offer slightly less crowded alternatives. The Lowcountry cuisine of Charleston — shrimp and grits, Frogmore stew, pecan pie — is at its most essential when you need fuel for the heat.",
    7: "July is peak Southeast heat — 34°C with stifling humidity and those daily thunderstorms that keep things dramatic. The Fourth of July celebrations across the region are massive, from Miami's beach fireworks to Savannah's waterfront spectacle. The Gulf waters are bathtub-warm at 30°C, and the Florida Keys offer excellent diving and snorkeling. Theme park crowds are at absolute maximum — budget for express passes. The fresh peaches, watermelon, and corn at every roadside stand make summer in the South a produce paradise. Stay hydrated and embrace the slow pace.",
    8: "August is the Southeast's hottest month — 35°C in Florida with humidity that makes breathing feel optional. Hurricane season is at its most active, so keep an eye on forecasts and have flexible plans. But the beaches are warm, the seafood is excellent, and the locals adopt a slower rhythm that tourists would be wise to follow. The Everglades are in their wet season — flooded and spectacular but less accessible. Back-to-school sales mean theme park crowd drops late in the month. A cold glass of sweet tea has never been more important.",
    9: "September is the Southeast's most underrated month — still warm at 32°C, but the summer crowds vanish, prices plummet, and the beaches remain gorgeous. Hurricane risk continues (the peak is actually mid-September), requiring flexible planning, but the odds are in your favor and the rewards are enormous: empty beaches, available restaurants, and hotel rates that are genuinely shocking compared to March. The Outer Banks and Gulf Coast are particularly excellent in September's golden light. The food never suffers — the shrimp are still fresh, the barbecue still smokes, and the craft cocktail scene keeps innovating.",
    10: "October brings relief — 27°C, dropping humidity, and the first hints of autumn color in the northern reaches (Smoky Mountains and Blue Ridge are spectacular by mid-month). Florida stays warm and swimmable, the Keys are entering their best season, and the Halloween celebrations from Savannah's ghost tours to Orlando's Horror Nights are elaborate. Stone crab season opens October 15 in Florida — mark your calendar. New Orleans cools enough for comfortable walking, and the food festivals begin. Arguably the Southeast's best overall month.",
    11: "November is the Southeast at its most comfortable — 22°C in Florida, crisp autumn in the Carolinas and Georgia, and the tourist crowds at manageable levels before the holiday rush. The Everglades dry season begins and the wildlife viewing improves weekly. Savannah and Charleston are at their most atmospheric with cool evenings and Spanish moss draped over quiet squares. Thanksgiving in the Southeast is a magnificent fusion of Southern and American traditions — deep-fried turkey, cornbread dressing, and pecan pie make a strong case for relocating permanently.",
    12: "December brings festive warmth — 20°C in Miami (beach Santa is a real thing), holiday lights draped over palm trees, and the Art Basel scene turning Miami Beach into the contemporary art world's biggest party (early December). The Keys are in peak season with excellent diving and fishing. Savannah and Charleston dress up beautifully for the holidays with candlelight tours of historic homes. New Year's Eve in Miami's South Beach is a glittering, international affair. The snowbirds return in force, pushing prices up but bringing energy to every coastal town.",
  },

  'uy-uruguay': {
    1: "January is peak summer in Uruguay — 28°C, the beaches of Punta del Este packed with Argentine and Brazilian holidaymakers, and Jose Ignacio operating as South America's most glamorous coastal village. The Atlantic water reaches a swimmable 23°C, and the nightlife runs until dawn. Montevideo empties as everyone heads to the coast, but the capital's Ciudad Vieja neighborhood rewards the few who stay with excellent parrillas and empty museums. Prices are at their highest and accommodation in Punta del Este books out — this is La Plata society's Hamptons, and they take summer seriously.",
    2: "February keeps the summer party rolling — still 27°C, busy beaches, and the start of Carnival season turning Montevideo into a street-party spectacle of candombe drumming and murga theatre that's less famous than Rio but arguably more authentic. The Las Llamadas parade through Barrio Sur features Afro-Uruguayan candombe drum groups that will rearrange your understanding of rhythm. Punta del Este starts its slow retreat from peak intensity, and the beach town of Cabo Polonio — accessible only by 4WD or foot through sand dunes — feels like the end of the world.",
    3: "March is autumn's gentle arrival — 24°C, the beaches calming down, and Uruguay's wine harvest (tannat grapes are the star) beginning in the Canelones and Maldonado regions. The Punta del Este crowds thin dramatically, revealing a more relaxed coastal vibe. Montevideo's restaurant scene is in fine form with asado (grilled meat) that rivals Argentina's and craft beer that doesn't get nearly enough international attention. The gaucho culture in the interior is authentic and accessible — estancia (ranch) stays are genuinely memorable.",
    4: "April brings proper autumn — 19°C, golden light across the Montevideo waterfront, and the first mate-sipping-on-the-rambla days that define Uruguayan culture. The beaches are quiet and beautiful, the wine country is in harvest mode with cellar-door tastings, and the Punta del Este surf picks up with autumn swells. Uruguay's famous progressive culture — legal marijuana, wind-powered electricity, a social safety net that works — feels tangible in the laid-back daily rhythm. A chivito (the national sandwich) on the Montevideo rambla is autumn done right.",
    5: "May cools to 15°C with increasing rain and shorter days — autumn is firmly established, and the beach towns along the coast settle into off-season quiet. Montevideo comes alive as the cultural capital it truly is: excellent theatre, live music in Ciudad Vieja, and the feria de Tristan Narvaja Sunday market sprawling across the Cordón neighborhood. The asado culture moves indoors to wood-fired parrillas, and the tannat wine pairs perfectly with the cooling weather. Uruguay in the shoulder season is affordable, uncrowded, and deeply authentic.",
    6: "June is winter in Uruguay — 12°C, grey skies, and the kind of damp cold that gets into your bones despite the mild temperatures. The beaches are deserted and atmospheric, the surf at La Paloma and Punta del Diablo is excellent for those with wetsuits, and Montevideo's indoor culture — museums, theatre, wine bars — is at its most appealing. The gaucho heritage celebrations begin, and the estancias in the interior offer winter-rate stays with roaring fires and hearty lamb asado. Uruguay in winter is Europe's budget alternative for those who like melancholy with their meat.",
    7: "July is the coldest month — 11°C with occasional frosts and a raw dampness that makes the rambla walks bracing rather than pleasant. School holidays bring some domestic tourism to the mountains (Minas and its surroundings), and the thermal hot springs at Salto and Paysandu are at their most appealing. Montevideo's cafe culture thrives, and the city's remarkable bookshops and vinyl record stores deserve a rainy afternoon. The food is magnificent and hearty: thick stews, grilled provoleta cheese, and medialunas (croissants) that rival any in Buenos Aires.",
    8: "August is the tail end of winter — still 12°C and damp, but the days lengthen and the first wildflowers appear in Montevideo's parks. Nostalgia Week in late August celebrates vintage cars, music, and culture with citywide events. The surf at eastern beaches remains good, and the thermal springs continue to draw weekend visitors. Uruguay's craft beer scene keeps growing impressively, and a brewery tour through Montevideo's emerging beer district is a worthy rainy-day activity. Accommodation prices are at their lowest — this is budget Uruguay.",
    9: "September brings spring — 16°C, blooming jacarandas turning Montevideo's streets purple, and the optimism of warming days after a long, damp winter. The rambla becomes walkable again with mate in hand, and the beach towns start their slow reawakening. Semana Criolla (Creole Week, timing varies) celebrates gaucho culture with rodeos, folk music, and enough grilled meat to threaten the ozone layer. The wine regions begin their spring flush, and the migrating southern right whales appear off the Atlantic coast, visible from shore.",
    10: "October is gorgeous — 19°C, the wildflowers in full bloom, and the coast warming up for summer. Punta del Este begins its seasonal preparations (restaurants reopen, hotels dust off), and the beaches are perfect for uncrowded walks. The whale watching continues off the Rocha coast, and the surf conditions are consistent. Montevideo's outdoor culture returns to the rambla and parks. The tannat vines are flowering and the pastoral interior — rolling green hills dotted with cattle and gauchos — is at its most photogenic. Spring in Uruguay is quietly special.",
    11: "November warms to 22°C and summer is imminent — the beaches start seeing their first swimmers, the Atlantic reaches 18°C (hardy types only), and the outdoor dining scene across Montevideo shifts into gear. Punta del Este's restaurants and clubs begin opening, and the social season builds. The interior's estancias offer spring riding and lamb roasts. The sunsets from Montevideo's rambla get longer and more spectacular, and the evening mate ritual with friends becomes an extended affair. Uruguay's understated charm is most noticeable when you're not competing with peak-season crowds.",
    12: "December is early summer — 25°C, the beaches filling up, and the social calendar heating up alongside the temperatures. Christmas in Montevideo is a family affair with outdoor asados, and New Year's Eve on the Punta del Este waterfront is South America's most stylish countdown. The sea reaches 21°C, comfortable for swimming, and Cabo Polonio's wild beaches and sea lion colonies are accessible and magical. Prices start climbing and accommodation in the beach towns requires advance booking. The dulce de leche in everything — facturas, helado, alfajores — never gets old.",
  },

  'uz-samarkand': {
    1: "January in Samarkand is Central Asian winter at its sharpest — 5°C days, occasional snow dusting the turquoise domes of the Registan, and a stillness that makes the medieval architecture feel genuinely timeless. The bazaars sell steaming samsa (meat pastries) and plov (the national pilaf dish) that are essential cold-weather fuel. Tourist numbers are at their lowest, and you might have the Shah-i-Zinda necropolis entirely to yourself — its tilework is mesmerizing in any season. Bukhara and Khiva are similarly quiet and atmospheric.",
    2: "February stays cold at 7°C with occasional snow, but the days lengthen and the Silk Road cities begin their slow thaw. Nowruz preparations add energy to the bazaars, where dried fruits, nuts, and sumalak (wheat sprout pudding) start appearing. The Registan in winter light — low sun catching the blue and gold mosaics — is genuinely stunning and crowd-free. This is budget Silk Road travel: cheap flights, available guesthouses, and local restaurants serving massive portions of lagman (hand-pulled noodle soup) for almost nothing.",
    3: "March brings spring and Nowruz — the Persian New Year on March 21 transforms Samarkand with music, dancing, plov feasts, and an infectious joy that's the highlight of the Uzbek cultural calendar. Temperatures climb to 14°C, the almond blossoms appear, and the outdoor eating season begins. The Registan, Bibi-Khanym Mosque, and Shah-i-Zinda are comfortable to explore all day. Tourist numbers pick up but remain manageable. The hand-pulled plov prepared in enormous cauldrons for Nowruz gatherings is one of Central Asia's great communal food experiences.",
    4: "April is Samarkand's sweet spot — 20°C, wildflowers in the surrounding hills, and the Silk Road architecture glowing under clear spring skies. The madrasas and mausoleums are in perfect photography light, and the crowds are moderate enough that you can linger. The Siab Bazaar overflows with fresh spring herbs, warm bread baked in tandoor ovens, and the dried fruits that are Samarkand's signature souvenirs. Day trips to the ancient observatory of Ulugh Beg add astronomical wonder. The Silk Road feels most alive in spring.",
    5: "May is excellent — 26°C, long days, and the landscape green and lush from spring rains. The walking between Samarkand's major monuments is pleasant, and the outdoor chaikhanas (teahouses) are the best places to linger over green tea and conversation. The tourist season is building (busyness 4/5) but the sites never feel overwhelmed. The route between Samarkand, Bukhara, and Khiva — the classic Silk Road circuit — is in prime condition. The cherries and apricots start appearing in the bazaars, hinting at the fruit bonanza to come.",
    6: "June crosses into hot territory — 33°C and climbing, with the dry Central Asian heat making midday sightseeing uncomfortable. But the mornings and evenings are glorious: the Registan at sunset is life-altering, and the Bibi-Khanym Mosque in golden hour light is worth sweating for. The bazaars are heavy with apricots, cherries, and melons that rival any fruit you've ever tasted. Tourist numbers peak, so book accommodation ahead. The plov at Samarkand's famous restaurant row is served in quantities that suggest Uzbeks don't believe in portion control.",
    7: "July is furnace season — 36°C+ in Samarkand with relentless sun and air that feels like opening an oven. But the Silk Road doesn't close for heat: the early-morning and late-evening light on the tilework is extraordinary, and the bazaars are loaded with the sweetest melons and grapes in Central Asia. Midday requires shade, cold drinks, and the strategic use of the many tree-lined parks. Tourist numbers remain high but the heat thins the casual crowds. The underground workshop visits (silk weaving, ceramics) offer essential cool refuge.",
    8: "August matches July's heat at 35°C — Samarkand bakes, and the landscape turns brown and dry. But the fruit season peaks with watermelons, grapes, and figs that justify the sweating, and the Silk Road monuments are no less magnificent in the summer haze. The Uzbek Independence Day (September 1) preparations begin, adding energy. The trick is timing: explore from dawn to 10am, retreat to a chaikhana or pool until 5pm, then enjoy the extended golden evening. Silk workshops, ceramic studios, and the cool interiors of the madrasas become essential midday stops.",
    9: "September is the golden month — temperatures ease to 28°C, Independence Day celebrations (September 1) bring festivals and cultural performances, and the grape and pomegranate harvest fills every bazaar stall. The light turns warm and generous, making the Registan's tilework glow in ways that justify every hour of every previous hot month. Crowds thin from summer's peak, and the drive between cities passes through cotton fields and orchards at their most productive. This is arguably the best month for the full Silk Road circuit.",
    10: "October brings autumn perfection — 20°C, golden light, and the Silk Road cities in their most comfortable visiting conditions since April. The fall foliage around Samarkand adds warm tones to the turquoise domes, and the bazaars are stocked with the last of the harvest: pomegranates, quinces, and dried fruits. Tourist numbers ease to moderate, accommodation is available, and the evening plov-and-tea ritual at outdoor chaikhanas is pure Central Asian bliss. The ceramics of Rishtan and Gijduvan are perfect souvenirs — buy more than you think you need.",
    11: "November cools quickly to 12°C with the first grey skies and occasional rain — the Silk Road cities take on a moody, atmospheric quality that winter visitors find addictive. Crowds thin to minimal, prices drop, and the bazaars shift to winter provisions: dried fruits, nuts, and warming spices for plov and lagman. The Registan in fog or light rain has a melancholic beauty that contrasts beautifully with its summer brilliance. The guesthouses light their bukhara (wood stoves), and the warmth of Uzbek hospitality — always generous — becomes genuinely essential.",
    12: "December is quiet and cold — 6°C with occasional snow dusting the turquoise domes in a scene straight from a Silk Road miniature painting. The tourist season is effectively over, meaning prices bottom out and the monuments are yours. The bazaars steam with hot samsa, manty (steamed dumplings), and the kind of hearty lagman that makes cold weather feel purposeful. New Year's Eve is celebrated enthusiastically (a Soviet legacy), and Samarkand under snow, with the Registan's blue tiles against white powder, is a sight few travelers ever witness.",
  },

  'uz-tashkent': {
    1: "January in Tashkent is properly cold — 4°C with occasional snow and a biting wind that sweeps across the Central Asian steppe. The Soviet-era metro stations (genuinely beautiful, with chandeliers and marble) offer warm underground art tours. The Chorsu Bazaar is covered and steaming with fresh nan bread, samsa pastries, and mountains of dried fruits. Tourist numbers are near zero, but the museums (Applied Arts, Amir Timur) are excellent, and the Uzbek hospitality — a cup of tea is offered before you can say 'please' — is at its most warming.",
    2: "February keeps Tashkent cold at 6°C but the days start lengthening and the city's energy picks up with Nowruz preparations in the bazaars. The food is at its most essential and hearty: plov ceremonies where massive cauldrons of rice, meat, and carrots serve hundreds, lagman with hand-pulled noodles, and hot green tea in every chaikhana. The Fergana Valley side-trip (silk workshops, ceramic studios in Rishtan and Margilan) is worth the effort in any season. The cold keeps crowds away, meaning lower prices and personal attention at guesthouses.",
    3: "March brings spring and Nowruz — Tashkent transforms with the Persian New Year celebration on March 21, filling Navruz Park with plov cooking competitions, traditional music, and genuine communal joy. Temperatures climb to 14°C, the parks burst into blossom, and the city feels reborn after winter. The Fergana Valley's spring is beautiful for silk factory visits and ceramic workshops. Tourist numbers start building from zero, meaning early March still offers winter pricing with spring weather. The sumalak-making tradition (communal wheat-sprout pudding, stirred all night) is deeply hospitable.",
    4: "April is Tashkent at its best — 20°C, blooming trees lining the wide Soviet-era boulevards, and a city that feels surprisingly modern and livable. The parks are gorgeous, the outdoor dining begins, and the bazaars overflow with spring herbs and the first strawberries. The modernist architecture — Tashkent was rebuilt after the 1966 earthquake — is fascinating and underappreciated. Day trips to Chimgan Mountains for spring hiking offer mountain scenery just two hours from the city. The plov at the Central Asian Plov Centre is a mandatory experience.",
    5: "May warms to 27°C and Tashkent's outdoor culture hits its stride — the parks fill with families, the chaikhanas set up outdoor platforms, and the evening promenade along Amir Timur Square is lively. The Fergana Valley is gorgeous with green cotton fields and fruit orchards. Tourist season is building (moderate crowds) but the city never feels overwhelmed. The cherries and apricots appear in the bazaars, and the shashlik (kebab) grills fire up at every street corner. May is Tashkent with all the best qualities on display.",
    6: "June gets hot — 33°C and climbing, with the dry steppe heat making midday uncomfortable but mornings and evenings divine. The bazaars pile up with apricots and melons that Central Asians insist are the world's best (they might be right). The Chorsu dome market is magnificent for photography and eating. Tourist numbers are at their summer peak, and the Tashkent Metro's air-conditioned stations are both art galleries and survival tools. The evening dining culture extends late, with outdoor platforms serving plov under the stars.",
    7: "July is full furnace — 37°C in the shade, and the city moves to a morning/evening rhythm that's been refined over millennia. The fruit season peaks with watermelons so sweet they should be classified as dessert, and the dried fruit stalls prepare their winter stocks. Tourist numbers thin as the heat deters casual visitors. The Chimgan Mountains offer a cooler escape with swimming holes and hiking. The evening teahouse culture is at its most essential — the green tea literally keeps you alive — and the cold lagman (yes, cold noodle soup) finally makes sense.",
    8: "August stays brutal at 36°C — but the Uzbek Independence Day preparations (September 1) begin adding cultural energy. The bazaars are at maximum abundance with every fruit imaginable, and the dried-fruit sellers are doing their busiest trade. The cotton fields of the Fergana Valley are tall and green (with complicated social history worth understanding). Morning visits to mosques, museums, and markets before the heat sets in are the smart strategy. The underground metro is your air-conditioned transport and art gallery combined.",
    9: "September is the turnaround — 28°C and cooling, Independence Day festivities (September 1) bring parades and cultural celebrations, and the city begins its most pleasant season. The grape and pomegranate harvest fills the bazaars with extraordinary produce, and the outdoor dining is glorious in the warm evenings. Tourist numbers are moderate and well-served by Tashkent's improving hotel scene. The Fergana Valley is in full harvest beauty, and the Silk Road craft workshops (Margilan silk, Rishtan ceramics) are at their most active.",
    10: "October is lovely — 19°C, golden autumn light, and the chaikhanas operating at perfect outdoor temperature. The bazaars shift to autumn provisions — pomegranates, quinces, dried fruits, and nuts — and the plov tastes richer in the cooling weather. Tourist crowds ease, prices soften, and the city's tree-lined boulevards turn amber and gold. The Fergana Valley side trip is excellent: Rishtan's ceramics, Margilan's silk, and Kokand's palace are all comfortable to explore. This is Tashkent at its most livable and visitor-friendly.",
    11: "November cools to 11°C with increasing grey skies and the first real hints of winter returning. The outdoor dining retreats indoors, but the restaurant and chaikhana culture is built for this transition. The bazaars are stocked with winter provisions: mountains of dried apricots, nuts, and the sumalak ingredients for future Nowruz celebrations. Tourist numbers drop to minimal, and the city's cultural institutions (opera, ballet, museums) are in full season. A hot bowl of lagman in a steaming Chorsu market stall is November at its most honest and satisfying.",
    12: "December brings winter back — 5°C, occasional snow, and Tashkent settling into its cold-season routine. The New Year's celebrations are enthusiastic and communal (the biggest holiday in the secular calendar), with families gathering for massive plov ceremonies and gift-giving. The Chorsu Bazaar steams with hot bread and samsa, and the metro's underground warmth makes station-hopping a viable activity. The city's modernist architecture looks unexpectedly dramatic under snow and grey skies. Tashkent in December is raw, cold, and entirely authentic.",
  },

  'va-vatican': {
    1: "January at the Vatican is blessedly uncrowded — 12°C, winter drizzle, and the Sistine Chapel nearly empty enough to actually contemplate Michelangelo's genius without a tour guide's microphone in your ear. The Vatican Museums are at their most intimate, and St. Peter's Basilica is magnificently atmospheric in the low winter light. The Papal New Year's Mass draws devoted crowds but the museum spaces are blissfully manageable. A hot supplì (fried rice ball) from a nearby stand and a cappuccino at a Roman bar make the cold entirely worthwhile.",
    2: "February continues the sweet low-season window — 13°C, minimal queues at the museums, and the chance to stand beneath the Sistine Chapel ceiling with breathing room. The Vatican Gardens (book ahead) are still green despite the season, and the February calendar sometimes brings significant papal audiences that add spiritual weight to the visit. The food in the surrounding Prati neighborhood is excellent Roman cuisine without the Trastevere tourist markup. Lent preparations begin, lending the entire Vatican a contemplative atmosphere.",
    3: "March brings the first spring warmth — 16°C and the Vatican starts waking up with increasing visitors as Easter approaches. If Easter falls in March, expect maximum crowds for Holy Week services, Papal Mass in St. Peter's Square, and emotional Palm Sunday and Good Friday processions. The museums get noticeably busier, so book timed entries well ahead. The Vatican Gardens begin blooming, and the light through the basilica's windows turns golden. A powerful month for the faithful and the art-curious alike.",
    4: "April is peak Vatican — either Easter's massive crowds or the post-Easter rush brings busyness to 5/5, with 20°C days drawing tourists who queue around the block for the museums. The Sistine Chapel is packed, and the experience requires patience and early-morning strategy (book the first entry slot). That said, the basilica at sunrise, the Papal Wednesday audience, and the sheer density of Renaissance masterpieces make it worth the hassle. The wisteria on nearby streets is blooming, and a gelato from Prati makes the queue recovery instant.",
    5: "May hits the sweet spot for many visitors — 24°C, long sunny days, and crowds that are heavy but slightly more manageable than April's Easter chaos. The Vatican Gardens are in full spring bloom, and the light inside St. Peter's Basilica in May is arguably the best of the year. Papal audiences on Wednesdays are well-attended but accessible with early arrival. The surrounding Prati neighborhood's restaurant terraces are open for lingering lunches. Book museum entry at least a week ahead — skip-the-line tickets are essential. The Friday evening museum openings are a lesser-known gem.",
    6: "June brings Roman summer heat — 29°C, full tourist intensity, and the Vatican Museums requiring timed entry booked well in advance. The Sistine Chapel is warm, crowded, and still astonishing. St. Peter's Square bakes in the afternoon, so morning visits are strategic. The Feast of Saints Peter and Paul (June 29) is a significant celebration with papal celebrations and the blessing of the pallium. Evening visits to St. Peter's Basilica (free entry) are atmospheric and less crowded. A granita across the Tiber in Trastevere is the proper afternoon recovery.",
    7: "July is hot and busy — 32°C, lines that snake through the Piazza, and the Sistine Chapel feeling like a warm, artistically transcendent sauna. The Pope's summer schedule may include retreats to Castel Gandolfo, so check the papal audience calendar. The museum's air conditioning is a genuine draw, and the art is obviously season-proof. Beat the heat with strategic timing: arrive at opening (7:30am ticket) or try the evening opening on Fridays. The surrounding neighborhood's trattorie serve excellent cacio e pepe that you've earned after those queues.",
    8: "August sees many Roman businesses close for Ferragosto (August 15), but the Vatican Museums stay open — and the irony is that the mid-August crowds can actually be lighter than July as Italian tourists flee to the coast. The heat is intense at 32°C, and St. Peter's Square at midday is not for the faint-hearted. Morning visits remain essential, and the basilica's cool marble interior is a genuine refuge. The Assumption of Mary (August 15) is a major feast day with special observances. Carry water like your life depends on it.",
    9: "September is the Vatican's return to grace — 27°C, crowds easing after the summer peak, and the light turning that particular Roman gold that makes every dome and column glow. The museums are still busy but manageable with advance booking, and the Papal Wednesday audiences resume their regular rhythm. The weather is ideal for the walk through the Vatican Gardens, and the nearby Castel Sant'Angelo adds a perfect complement. September combines excellent conditions with post-summer pricing — the smart pilgrim's choice.",
    10: "October brings gentle autumn — 22°C, the crowds thinning to moderate levels, and the Vatican taking on a contemplative quality that suits its purpose. The museums are comfortable to explore at leisure, and the basilica in autumn light is genuinely moving. The Synod of Bishops (if in session) adds ecclesiastical energy. The food in Prati pivots to autumn with carciofi (artichokes), mushrooms, and cacio e pepe that tastes better in cool weather. The queue times shorten noticeably, making this a top-three month for the museum experience.",
    11: "November is Vatican off-season done right — 16°C, occasional rain, and the Sistine Chapel quiet enough to hear your own thoughts (and the guards' 'no photos' whispers). The museums are uncrowded, the basilica is atmospheric, and the All Saints' Day (November 1) and All Souls' Day ceremonies carry genuine spiritual weight. The Vatican Necropolis tour (the excavations beneath St. Peter's) is fascinating and available with less advance booking than peak months. A rainy afternoon in the Vatican Library reading room, if you can arrange access, is scholar heaven.",
    12: "December is the Vatican at Christmas — and it's genuinely magical. The enormous nativity scene in St. Peter's Square, the Christmas tree, and the midnight Mass on Christmas Eve (tickets required, apply months ahead) create an atmosphere of joy and reverence. Temperatures hover at 13°C with occasional rain, and the museums are quiet outside the holiday week. The Pope's Urbi et Orbi blessing on Christmas Day draws tens of thousands to the Square. New Year's Eve Mass and the Te Deum close the year with appropriate solemnity. Even for the non-religious, Christmas at St. Peter's is unforgettable.",
  },

  'ad-andorra': {
    1: "Andorra in January is a skier's paradise — average highs around 3°C in the valleys, with Grandvalira and Vallnord buried under reliable snowpack. The principality buzzes with duty-free shoppers and slope enthusiasts from Barcelona and Toulouse, so book early. Après-ski means hot chocolate with a splash of something local in a stone-walled bar.",
    2: "February brings Andorra's best snow conditions and carnival season, with temperatures hovering between -3°C and 4°C. Expect peak crowds on the slopes during school holidays, but the powder is worth the lift queues. Caldea spa is the perfect antidote to a hard day on the mountain.",
    3: "March delivers long sunny days on the slopes with temps creeping toward 8°C — spring skiing at its finest. Crowds thin out after mid-month as European school breaks end, leaving groomers gloriously empty. The snow lingers up high while the valleys start to thaw.",
    4: "April is shoulder season in the truest sense — ski resorts wind down by mid-month while hiking trails begin to open. Temperatures reach 12°C and wildflowers start dotting the Pyrenean meadows. It's the cheapest time to visit, with hotel rates dropping and restaurants happy to see you.",
    5: "May transforms Andorra into a hiking and mountain-biking wonderland, with highs around 15°C and the high passes finally clearing. Crowds are minimal and the valleys are lush green against lingering snow caps. The Andorra Ultra Trail draws runners, but everyone else has the paths to themselves.",
    6: "June is glorious — 20°C days, wildflower meadows in full bloom, and near-empty trails through the Madriu-Perafita-Claror Valley. This is prime time for serious hikers before the summer rush. Evenings are cool enough for a wool layer and a plate of trinxat on a terrace.",
    7: "July heats up to 24°C and the hiking season hits full stride, with every refuge and mountain restaurant open for business. Tour de France fever spills over the border and cyclists tackle the same legendary climbs. It's peak season, so the tiny capital Andorra la Vella gets genuinely crowded with shoppers.",
    8: "August is Andorra's busiest month — 25°C highs, Spanish and French holidaymakers everywhere, and duty-free shops heaving. The mountains offer escape, with alpine lakes warm enough for a bracing dip. Thunderstorms roll in most afternoons, so start hikes early.",
    9: "September is arguably Andorra's sweetest month — 20°C, golden light on the peaks, and summer crowds vanished overnight. Hiking conditions are perfect and the mountain refuges are still open but blissfully quiet. The Festes de Meritxell on September 8 brings Andorran culture to life.",
    10: "October brings autumn colour to the Pyrenean slopes, with temperatures around 13°C and crisp clear days. It's dead quiet between summer and ski season, making it ideal for peaceful walks and exploring Romanesque churches. Early snow can dust the highest peaks, adding drama to every vista.",
    11: "November is Andorra's quietest month — grey skies, 7°C temps, and a collective holding of breath waiting for ski season to start. Resorts typically open late in the month if the snow gods cooperate. Prices are rock-bottom and the duty-free shopping is hassle-free.",
    12: "December kicks off ski season proper, with temperatures around 2°C and fresh snow drawing the first wave of visitors. Christmas markets fill Andorra la Vella's narrow streets with mulled wine and artisan goods. The holiday period is pricey but festive, and the slopes are in good early-season form.",
  },
  'ae-dubai': {
    1: "January is Dubai's golden month — 24°C days, zero rain, and a packed calendar from the Dubai Shopping Festival to world-class golf tournaments. Beach weather is superb without the scorching heat, and the desert is perfect for overnight glamping. This is peak season, so expect premium pricing and book brunches early.",
    2: "February holds steady at 25°C with clear skies and the Dubai Jazz Festival livening up the cultural scene. Crowds remain high but slightly thinner than January, and hotel rates begin to soften. It's the last truly comfortable month before the mercury starts its relentless climb.",
    3: "March sees temperatures push to 28°C — still pleasant but a hint of what's coming. Art Dubai takes over and the horse racing season peaks at Meydan with the Dubai World Cup. Beach days are lovely, though you'll start seeking shade by early afternoon.",
    4: "April hits 33°C and the first beads of sweat signal shoulder season — tourists thin out and hotel deals emerge. Sandstorms can roll through, turning the skyline sepia-toned. It's still manageable for sightseeing if you time outdoor activities for morning and evening.",
    5: "May crosses into genuinely hot territory at 38°C, and the city pivots indoors to its air-conditioned malls, aquariums, and indoor ski slopes. Ramadan may fall in this period, which means daytime dining gets discreet and nighttime iftar feasts are a cultural highlight. Hotel prices drop significantly.",
    6: "June is brutally hot — 41°C and humidity climbing — but Dubai Summer Surprises brings massive retail discounts and hotel rates plummet. The beaches are for dawn walkers only, and pool time revolves around the nearest ice bucket. It's an insider move for budget travelers who can handle the heat.",
    7: "July averages 43°C with oppressive humidity, making outdoor activity genuinely inadvisable between 10am and 5pm. The city functions on AC and determination, with malls, indoor theme parks, and hotel pools as the social hubs. Flights and hotels are at their cheapest all year.",
    8: "August rivals July for misery outdoors — 43°C and saturating humidity — but the city's indoor infrastructure is unmatched. Water parks, indoor skydiving, and restaurant deals make it bearable for families on a budget. Even the desert safari operators shift to cooler evening-only schedules.",
    9: "September starts to hint at relief with temps easing to 39°C, though humidity stays punishing. The city begins gearing up for the winter season with new restaurant openings and hotel renovations wrapping up. Late-month deals are excellent if you can tolerate lingering heat.",
    10: "October finally breaks the fever — 35°C and dropping, with outdoor dining returning to life. Dubai Fitness Challenge kicks off and the city literally runs back outside. It's a smart shoulder-season play with decent prices and improving weather daily.",
    11: "November is beautiful — 30°C, dry, and the social calendar explodes with the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix, art fairs, and outdoor concerts. Beach season is back in full swing and desert camping becomes magical under cool starlit skies. Prices start climbing toward peak season.",
    12: "December is peak Dubai — 26°C perfection, National Day celebrations, and a New Year's Eve spectacle that competes with Sydney and London. Every rooftop bar and beach club is at capacity, and hotel rates hit their zenith. Book three months ahead or prepare to pay through the nose.",
  },
  'ae-northern': {
    1: "January in the Northern Emirates averages a pleasant 23°C — perfect for exploring Ras Al Khaimah's Jebel Jais mountain trails or Fujairah's rocky coastline without Dubai's crowds. Desert safaris in Sharjah's interior are magical with cool evenings and clear skies. Accommodation is a fraction of Dubai pricing, making this the budget-savvy base.",
    2: "February stays mild at 24°C with the wadis flowing from winter rains — Wadi Shawka and Wadi Al Bih are at their most photogenic. The hiking up Jebel Jais is comfortable and Fujairah's beaches are uncrowded. It's peak season for the region but still feels like a well-kept secret.",
    3: "March warms to 27°C and the desert wildflowers make their brief annual appearance after any rain. Snorkeling off Fujairah's Snoopy Island is excellent with calm seas and good visibility. Al Ain's oasis and fort complex is worth the inland detour before heat takes over.",
    4: "April pushes to 32°C and the window for comfortable outdoor exploration starts narrowing. Hajar Mountain hikes need an early start but reward with dramatic geology. The Northern Emirates empty out as visitors head to cooler pastures.",
    5: "May hits 37°C and the desert landscape turns monochromatic under a bleached sky. Fujairah's east coast catches occasional breezes, making it marginally more bearable than the interior. Hotel rates drop sharply — it's bargain territory if you're heat-tolerant.",
    6: "June bakes at 40°C with humidity rising, pushing all activity to dawn, dusk, or air-conditioned interiors. The Al Ain Oasis offers shaded walks through date palms, and mountain resorts like Jebel Jais offer slightly cooler escapes. Don't underestimate the desert heat — carry water like your life depends on it.",
    7: "July averages 42°C and the Northern Emirates enter survival mode — even the camels look unimpressed. This is strictly indoor season: Sharjah's excellent museums and Ajman's souks provide refuge. Rock-bottom hotel prices make luxury stays surprisingly affordable.",
    8: "August matches July's intensity at 42°C, with occasional coastal humidity making Fujairah feel like a steam room. Night diving off the east coast is popular with the die-hard expat community. The upside is empty roads, no queues, and five-star resorts at two-star prices.",
    9: "September begins the slow cool-down to 39°C, though it still feels plenty hot. Turtle nesting season starts along Fujairah's beaches — a remarkable sight for patient visitors. The first hints of approaching pleasant weather draw cautious optimism.",
    10: "October drops to 34°C and the outdoors beckon again — Jebel Jais reopens its adventure activities and desert camping becomes viable. Wadi pools retain summer warmth for swimming, and the light turns golden for photographers. Shoulder-season pricing remains attractive.",
    11: "November at 29°C is when the Northern Emirates shine — perfect hiking weather in the Hajar Mountains and warm seas for snorkeling. Sharjah's cultural festivals kick off and the desert comes alive with cooler camping conditions. It's the sweet spot of great weather and moderate prices.",
    12: "December drops to 24°C and the region fills with winter sunseekers looking for an alternative to Dubai's premium pricing. Ras Al Khaimah's adventure tourism — zip lines, via ferrata, mountain trails — is at peak season. Clear desert skies make for spectacular stargazing away from coastal light pollution.",
  },
  'af-afghanistan': {
    1: "January in Kabul averages a bitter -2°C with snow covering the Hindu Kush and passes regularly blocked by avalanches. This is Afghanistan at its most isolated — travel is extremely limited and security concerns dominate any itinerary. Only essential travel should be considered under current conditions.",
    2: "February remains frozen with temperatures around 0°C, though Jalalabad in the east is markedly milder at 12°C. The Bamiyan Valley sits under heavy snow, its empty Buddha niches stark against the white cliffs. Travel infrastructure is minimal and security assessments are mandatory.",
    3: "March brings the first thaw to Kabul at 10°C, and the almond blossoms in Istalif offer a fleeting moment of beauty. Nowruz (Persian New Year) on March 21 is celebrated across the country with buzkashi matches and feasting. Road conditions remain unpredictable and professional security guidance is essential.",
    4: "April warms to 18°C and the valleys turn vivid green — Afghanistan is strikingly beautiful when spring arrives. The Band-e-Amir lakes begin to thaw into their famous turquoise. Current security conditions severely restrict travel; independent tourism is not advisable.",
    5: "May is pleasant in Kabul at 24°C with clear skies and the Hindu Kush still snow-capped on the horizon. The poppy fields bloom across southern provinces, a visually stunning but complicated reality. Security constraints make travel extremely challenging for all but the most experienced operators.",
    6: "June hits 32°C in Kabul and the lowlands bake — Kandahar and Helmand regularly exceed 40°C. Dust storms are common and the dry heat is relentless. Afghanistan's tourism potential remains locked behind ongoing security concerns.",
    7: "July peaks at 34°C in Kabul with the Wakhan Corridor offering dramatic high-altitude trekking for the rare adventurer with appropriate security arrangements. The Panjshir Valley provides some respite from lowland heat. Travel requires specialized operators and thorough security planning.",
    8: "August stays hot at 33°C with occasional monsoon moisture reaching eastern provinces from Pakistan. The fruit markets overflow with Afghan melons, grapes, and pomegranates — the country's agricultural bounty is remarkable. Security conditions continue to dominate travel planning.",
    9: "September cools to 27°C and the light turns golden over Kabul's sprawling cityscape. The grape harvest in the Shomali Plain north of Kabul is a centuries-old tradition. Any travel requires comprehensive security assessment and professional guidance.",
    10: "October drops to 19°C with autumn colour appearing in the valleys and the first dustings of snow on high peaks. The weather is arguably Afghanistan's best, with clear skies and comfortable temperatures. Security remains the primary constraint on any travel.",
    11: "November chills to 10°C and the mountains begin closing for winter — the Salang Pass can become impassable without warning. Kabul's bazaars are at their most atmospheric as merchants stock winter supplies. Travel is increasingly difficult and security concerns persist.",
    12: "December brings genuine cold to Kabul at 2°C, with the Hindu Kush locked under snow and much of the country isolated. Heating relies on bukhari stoves burning wood or diesel, filling neighborhoods with smoky haze. Travel is extremely limited and not recommended under current conditions.",
  },
  'ag-antigua': {
    1: "January in Antigua averages a glorious 27°C with trade winds keeping humidity in check and virtually zero rain. It's peak season — Jolly Beach and Dickenson Bay fill with sun worshippers, and catamaran cruises to uninhabited islands run daily. Book well ahead and expect premium Caribbean pricing.",
    2: "February continues the dry-season perfection at 27°C, with the Antigua Sailing Week buildup adding nautical energy to English Harbour. Valentine's Week is unsurprisingly popular, and Nelson's Dockyard buzzes with yacht crews and cocktail bars. The snorkeling is crystal-clear with calm seas.",
    3: "March is arguably the island's finest month — 28°C, bone-dry, and the famous 365 beaches at their most inviting. Kite surfing takes off on the east coast as trade winds strengthen. Carnival prep begins, and the steel pan rhythms start leaking out of practice halls.",
    4: "April warms to 29°C and Antigua Sailing Week (late April) transforms English Harbour into the Caribbean's greatest nautical party. Hotel rates start softening outside of race week, making it a strategic booking window. The first hints of humidity appear but the trade winds compensate.",
    5: "May marks the start of shoulder season — 30°C, occasional brief showers, and hotel prices dropping 30-40% from peak. The island empties of winter snowbirds but the water is bath-warm and the beaches are yours. Mango season kicks off, turning every roadside into a fruit stand.",
    6: "June brings warmer, more humid conditions at 31°C with afternoon rain showers becoming routine. It's the start of hurricane season on paper, though June storms are rare. The pace slows to properly Caribbean — long lunches, afternoon naps, and sunset rum punches.",
    7: "July heats to 31°C with increasing humidity and the island's famous Carnival erupting in a riot of costumes, soca music, and street parties. It's the one time the off-season crowds rival winter — book accommodation for Carnival months in advance. Trade winds provide some relief from the sticky air.",
    8: "August stays at 31°C and marks the statistical peak of hurricane season, though direct hits on Antigua are relatively rare. The island is quiet and deeply affordable, with many smaller hotels and restaurants taking their own vacations. Those who come find empty beaches and authentic local life.",
    9: "September is the heart of hurricane season — 31°C, humid, and the month most likely to see tropical weather disruptions. Some resorts close entirely, and those that stay open offer deep discounts. It's a gamble, but calm weeks deliver extraordinary solitude on world-class beaches.",
    10: "October transitions back with diminishing hurricane risk, 30°C temps, and the island shaking off its summer quiet. Rain showers green up the landscape and the bougainvillea explodes with colour. Prices remain low and the smart money books now for excellent value.",
    11: "November signals the return of dry season — 29°C, decreasing rainfall, and the first wave of winter visitors arriving. The seas calm, diving visibility improves, and the sunset bar scene picks up. It's the sweet spot of good weather and pre-peak pricing.",
    12: "December is magic on Antigua — 27°C, dry, festive, and the harbours fill with gleaming yachts for the holiday season. Christmas and New Year's bring premium everything, from hotel rates to restaurant reservations. The Old Year's Night celebrations in St. John's are joyously raucous.",
  },
  'al-riviera': {
    1: "January on the Albanian Riviera means 12°C, grey skies, and a coast that's gone into hibernation — most beachfront hotels and restaurants are shuttered. Saranda has some life year-round, and the ruins of Butrint are hauntingly empty. It's an atmospheric time if you enjoy solitude and don't mind drizzle.",
    2: "February is similar — 13°C, intermittent rain, and the coast still asleep. The upside is Butrint and Gjirokastër practically to yourself, plus rock-bottom prices on the few accommodations that stay open. Citrus trees are heavy with fruit and the mountain backdrop is often snow-dusted.",
    3: "March brings the first whispers of spring at 15°C, with wildflowers starting to carpet the coastal hillsides. Ksamil's beaches are deserted but stunning, and the water is still too cold for swimming. Gjirokastër's stone houses look magnificent under clearing skies.",
    4: "April is the Riviera's secret season — 19°C, everything blooming, and the first brave swimmers testing Ksamil's turquoise water. Accommodation opens up but prices haven't spiked yet, and the Llogara Pass drive is jaw-dropping in spring light. Easter celebrations in the villages are heartfelt and welcoming.",
    5: "May is superb — 23°C, seas warming to swimmable, and the entire coastline coming alive without the summer madness. Dhërmi and Himara beaches are pristine and uncrowded, and the seafood is fresh and absurdly cheap. This is arguably the best month to experience the Riviera.",
    6: "June brings summer proper at 28°C with warm seas and long golden days. The coast is busy but not yet overwhelmed — Ksamil can still feel peaceful on weekday mornings. Beach bars crank up, boats run to hidden coves, and the grilled fish is exceptional.",
    7: "July hits 32°C and the Albanian Riviera reaches peak intensity — Dhërmi and Ksamil pack out with Albanian and Kosovar holidaymakers blasting music from beach towels. The vibe is lively and unapologetically Balkan. Accommodation books up fast and prices triple from spring.",
    8: "August is the Riviera's crescendo — 33°C, every beach claimed by umbrella, and the coast road clogged with cars from Tirana. It's chaotic, fun, and exhausting in equal measure. If you want peace, take a boat to the more remote beaches south of Himara.",
    9: "September is the Riviera's redemption — 28°C, warm seas, thinning crowds, and that gorgeous late-summer Adriatic light. Prices drop significantly and the beach bars mellow from party to chill. Swimming is at its best with sea temperatures peaking from summer accumulation.",
    10: "October cools to 22°C and the coast enters its golden shoulder season — excellent for hiking the coastal trails and exploring without competition. Rain returns occasionally but the warm days outnumber the wet ones. Olive harvest begins in the groves above the beaches.",
    11: "November brings 17°C and increasing rain as the Riviera winds down for winter. Most beachfront operations close, though Saranda keeps its year-round restaurants and cafes going. It's a fine time for Butrint and the Blue Eye spring without any crowds.",
    12: "December is quiet and cool at 13°C, with the coast essentially closed for the season. Saranda's promenade still has enough going on for a pleasant off-season visit, and the mountain towns of Gjirokastër and Përmet are cosy. Prices are at their absolute lowest.",
  },
  'al-tirana': {
    1: "Tirana in January averages 7°C with grey skies and frequent rain — the city's colourful Edi Rama-painted buildings are needed more than ever. Museums and the Bunk'Art bunker galleries are the move, plus warming up with byrek and macchiato in the city's obsessive cafe culture. Berat and Gjirokastër day trips are feasible but chilly.",
    2: "February is Tirana's dreariest month — 8°C, damp, and the Dajti mountain backdrop often shrouded in cloud. But the city pulses on regardless, with bustling cafes and a nightlife scene that punches well above its weight. Hotel rates are laughably cheap and you'll have the National History Museum to yourself.",
    3: "March brings 12°C and the first spring warmth, with outdoor cafe terraces reopening on Blloku's fashionable streets. The Tirana Half Marathon draws runners and the parks fill with families enjoying longer days. Day trips to the Dajti Express cable car offer mountain views over a greening landscape.",
    4: "April is lovely — 17°C, blossoming trees along the Lana River, and the city at its most photogenic. It's perfect for exploring the Ottoman quarter and Skanderbeg Square without melting or shivering. Shoulder-season calm means easy bookings and genuine hospitality everywhere.",
    5: "May warms to 22°C with long sunny days ideal for the Dajti Mountain trails and the scenic drive to Berat's white Ottoman houses. Outdoor dining season is in full swing and the city buzzes with energy. Prices remain reasonable — Albania is still Europe's best-value destination.",
    6: "June hits 27°C and Tirana shifts into summer mode — Blloku's rooftop bars stay open late and the Lake Tirana park fills with joggers and strollers. The heat is manageable and the long evenings are magical. Many Tiranans start heading to the coast, thinning the city crowd.",
    7: "July bakes at 31°C and the city empties as Albanians migrate to the coast — Tirana in summer is oddly quiet and very hot. Air conditioning is inconsistent outside modern hotels, so plan accordingly. The upside is a city laid bare for exploration without the usual Balkan bustle.",
    8: "August peaks at 32°C and Tirana is at its quietest — this is a beach country in summer and the capital is an afterthought. Those who stay find a handful of dedicated restaurants and bars still operating at full tilt. The nearby Dajti mountain offers some elevation relief.",
    9: "September brings Tirana back to life — 27°C, everyone returning from the coast, and the cafe scene buzzing again. The city's cultural calendar restarts with gallery openings and music events. It's an ideal month for combining Tirana with day trips to Berat and Kruja.",
    10: "October cools to 20°C with occasional rain but still plenty of pleasant days for exploring. The foliage around Lake Bovilla turns golden, making for an excellent half-day hike. Tirana International Film Festival adds cultural weight to the social calendar.",
    11: "November drops to 14°C with increasing rain and shorter days, but the cafe culture and indoor dining scene are at their atmospheric best. Warm tavë kosi (baked lamb with yoghurt) and a glass of local Shesh i Zi wine is the perfect grey-day antidote. Prices hit off-season lows.",
    12: "December brings 9°C and festive energy to Skanderbeg Square, where a Christmas market and ice rink appear. New Year's Eve is celebrated with more enthusiasm than Christmas in this historically secular country, with fireworks and packed restaurants. It's cold and occasionally rainy but genuinely charming.",
  },
  'am-yerevan': {
    1: "Yerevan in January is bitterly cold — averaging -3°C with snow and Mount Ararat floating above the city in crystalline winter light. The city's cafe culture thrives regardless, with lavash, khorovats, and potent Armenian brandy keeping spirits high. Crowds are nonexistent and the Matenadaran manuscript museum is a world-class indoor refuge.",
    2: "February stays frozen at -1°C but Yerevan celebrates Trndez (the fire-jumping festival) on February 13, a pagan-Christian hybrid that's unforgettable to witness. The Cascade complex is atmospheric under winter skies and Vernissage flea market still operates on weekends. Pack serious layers — the wind cuts through everything.",
    3: "March begins the thaw at 8°C with apricot orchards hinting at bloom below Ararat's snow-heavy flanks. Mud season is real — the Garni Gorge basalt columns are spectacular but the trails are soggy. Spring energy builds in the city's restaurants and bars.",
    4: "April is Armenia's awakening — 16°C, apricot blossoms erupting everywhere, and Ararat framed in pink and white. The Genocide Remembrance Day on April 24 is somber and deeply moving to attend. Temple of Garni and Geghard Monastery are magnificent in spring light with manageable visitor numbers.",
    5: "May is arguably Yerevan's best month — 22°C, wildflowers blanketing the Armenian Highlands, and every outdoor cafe packed until midnight. Wine country in Areni is green and gorgeous, and the hiking in Dilijan National Park is superb. The city buzzes with an infectious warmth that matches the weather.",
    6: "June warms to 28°C with dry heat and endless blue skies over the Hrazdan Gorge that cuts through the city. Lake Sevan is warming up for swimming and the southern wine region is in full swing. It's peak season but Armenia is still uncrowded by European standards — enjoy it before the world catches on.",
    7: "July hits 33°C and the dry Continental heat settles over the Ararat Plain — mornings and evenings are divine, midday requires shade. Vardavar (the water festival) turns the entire country into a joyous water fight — tourists are fair game. Lake Sevan is the national escape, its shores lined with grilled fish vendors.",
    8: "August holds at 33°C with harvest season beginning across the vineyards and orchards. The Areni Wine Festival draws oenophiles to the cradle of winemaking (the world's oldest winery is here). Tatev Monastery, reached by the world's longest reversible cable car, is spectacular in summer heat-haze.",
    9: "September cools to 26°C and Armenia enters its golden age — literally, with the landscapes turning amber and the grape harvest in full swing. Yerevan's Jazz Festival adds cultural spice and the city feels perfectly calibrated between summer buzz and autumn calm. This is the insider's pick for visiting.",
    10: "October drops to 17°C with spectacular autumn colour in Dilijan's forests and the pomegranate harvest turning roadsides ruby red. Mount Ararat gets its first fresh snow, creating iconic photo opportunities from Yerevan. The city's restaurant scene is peaking with seasonal menus.",
    11: "November chills to 7°C with grey skies descending and the last leaves falling in the Cascade gardens. It's a reflective, atmospheric time — warm up with Armenian coffee and gata pastry in the countless cafes. Prices drop and the city reveals its everyday rhythm without tourism's varnish.",
    12: "December brings 0°C and occasional snow to Yerevan, with New Year's preparations overshadowing Christmas (celebrated January 6 in the Armenian church). Republic Square lights up and the city's festive spirit is genuine and warm despite the cold. Tsakhkadzor ski resort opens nearby for modest but affordable skiing.",
  },
  'ao-angola': {
    1: "January in Luanda is hot and humid at 30°C, right in the middle of the cacimbo wet season — expect tropical downpours most afternoons. The Ilha de Luanda waterfront bars stay lively regardless, and the city's Portuguese-Angolan fusion cuisine is worth the sweat. Angola remains expensive and logistically challenging for visitors.",
    2: "February continues the wet-season pattern at 30°C with heavy rains greening the landscape but making dirt roads outside Luanda treacherous. Carnival celebrations bring Brazilian-influenced parades and semba music to the streets. The Kwanza River swells dramatically and the waterfalls inland are at their most powerful.",
    3: "March stays hot and wet at 30°C, with the Kalandula Falls (one of Africa's largest) at peak flow and genuinely thunderous. Luanda's traffic and infrastructure challenges are real — this is not an easy country to navigate. The warm Atlantic waters along the coast are inviting if you can reach the cleaner beaches.",
    4: "April sees the rains begin to ease around 29°C, with lush vegetation everywhere and the interior plateau cooling slightly. The Kissama National Park has improving wildlife viewing as animals congregate near remaining water sources. Travel infrastructure remains basic outside the capital.",
    5: "May brings the dry season's arrival — 27°C, decreasing humidity, and Luanda exhaling with relief. The beaches south toward Cabo Ledo become more accessible and the surf breaks are world-class. This is when Angola starts becoming more navigable for intrepid visitors.",
    6: "June is Luanda's most pleasant month — 24°C, dry, with the cacimbo mist rolling off the Atlantic in the mornings. It's the coolest time of year and the city functions more smoothly. The Namib Desert's northern edge in Namibe province is hauntingly beautiful under clear skies.",
    7: "July stays cool and dry at 22°C — unusual for a tropical African capital and genuinely pleasant. The Tundavala Gap near Lubango offers staggering escarpment views in crystal-clear conditions. Pack a light jacket for Luanda evenings — locals break out winter coats.",
    8: "August holds at 23°C with dry conditions perfect for exploring the colonial architecture of Benguela and the surreal landscapes of Namibe's desert meeting the ocean. Whale watching off the coast begins as humpbacks migrate north. The dry season makes overland travel to Kissama feasible.",
    9: "September warms to 25°C as the dry season reaches its peak — dust replaces mud as the main travel challenge. The Palanca Negra (giant sable antelope) is Angola's national symbol, and Cangandala National Park is the place to seek this critically endangered creature. Prices remain stubbornly high by African standards.",
    10: "October transitions at 27°C with the first rains returning and temperatures climbing. The landscape begins its green transformation and birding improves dramatically across the interior. Angola's complex visa requirements and limited tourist infrastructure mean planning well ahead is essential.",
    11: "November brings heavier rains at 28°C and increasing humidity — roads deteriorate and travel times stretch. Luanda's nightlife scene is relentless year-round, with kizomba and kuduro beats soundtracking the city. The mango and avocado season begins, flooding markets with tropical abundance.",
    12: "December is hot and wet at 30°C, with festive season energy overcoming the rain. Angolans celebrate Christmas with gusto — expect street parties, grilled fish, and the sound of semba everywhere. New Year's on the Ilha de Luanda marginal is a spectacle worth braving the humidity for.",
  },
  'ar-buenos-aires': {
    1: "January is Buenos Aires at its hottest — 30°C and steamy, with porteños fleeing to the coast and the city wonderfully emptied out. Tango milongas are quieter, restaurants offer summer menus on candlelit patios, and San Telmo's Sunday market still draws die-hards. Hit the city's beautiful parks early before the afternoon heat pins you to a cafe chair.",
    2: "February stays sweltering at 29°C with Carnival energy (more restrained than Rio but still festive) and tango festivals filling the cultural gaps. The jacaranda-lined streets of Palermo are stunning, and the ice cream culture kicks into overdrive. Accommodation deals are excellent as tourism hits its annual low.",
    3: "March cools slightly to 26°C and the city starts waking from its summer siesta — universities reopen, cultural programming resumes, and the restaurants get serious again. Autumn light makes the grand Beaux-Arts buildings along Avenida de Mayo glow. It's an excellent time to visit with manageable weather and prices.",
    4: "April drops to 21°C with golden autumn light and leaves turning in Palermo's parks — Buenos Aires at its most romantic. The cultural season is in full swing with theatre, live jazz, and world-class dining at prices that still embarrass European capitals. Pack a light jacket for evening milongas.",
    5: "May cools to 16°C with occasional rain and the city settling into its atmospheric autumn groove. Buenos Aires' cafe culture hits its stride — lingering over cortados and medialunas in historic confiterías feels mandatory. The neighbourhood of San Telmo is at its misty, mysterious best.",
    6: "June is winter — 12°C, grey skies, and the kind of cold that makes a parilla steak with a Malbec feel medicinal. Day of the Flag festivities animate the city, and the opera season at Teatro Colón is in full magnificent swing. Crowds are minimal and hotel rates are rock-bottom.",
    7: "July averages 11°C and is the coldest month — Buenos Aires doesn't do winter charmingly, it does it with determination and many layers. School holidays bring some domestic tourist activity, and Tango Day (July 11) gives you an excuse to take a class. The indoor food markets of San Telmo are perfect for cold-day grazing.",
    8: "August stays chilly at 13°C but spring anticipation is building — the magnolia trees start budding and cafe terraces tentatively reopen. This is bargain season for flights and hotels, and the cultural calendar is stacked. The bookshop El Ateneo Grand Splendid deserves an entire afternoon of your cold winter day.",
    9: "September brings spring at 17°C with jacarandas beginning their legendary purple bloom across the city's avenues. Buenos Aires Fashion Week and the start of the polo season add glamour. The city shakes off winter with visible joy — expect packed bars and spontaneous street celebrations.",
    10: "October is Buenos Aires in bloom — 20°C, jacarandas at peak purple, and the city operating at full cultural throttle. It's one of the best months to visit, with perfect weather for walking the grand boulevards and exploring La Boca without overheating. Restaurant reservations on Friday nights become essential.",
    11: "November warms to 24°C with long sunny days and the city's outdoor terraces packed from lunch through late-night drinks. Polo season climaxes at the Argentine Open in Palermo, drawing a glamorous crowd. The Feria de Mataderos folk fair on Sundays is a riot of gaucho culture.",
    12: "December hits 27°C and the holiday buzz is palpable — Christmas Eve asado gatherings, fireworks over the Río de la Plata, and Récoleta Cemetery eerily beautiful in summer twilight. The city empties after New Year's as the coastal exodus begins, but the weeks before Christmas are festive and fabulous.",
  },
  'ar-mendoza': {
    1: "January in Mendoza wine country averages 33°C — hot, dry, and glorious for poolside winery visits with the snow-free Andes shimmering in the background. The grape harvest is approaching and the vineyards are at their most lush. Summer crowds and prices are high, so book bodegas and boutique hotels early.",
    2: "February is Mendoza's star turn — the Vendimia grape harvest festival builds to its spectacular March climax, and the weather holds at 31°C with warm evenings perfect for outdoor dining. Malbec flows freely and the region operates at peak capacity. This is harvest time — winery tours have an electric energy.",
    3: "March brings the Vendimia festival's Grand Finale — a massive open-air celebration of wine, music, and gaucho culture. Temperatures ease to 27°C and early autumn colour tinges the vineyard rows. It's the single best month to be in Mendoza if you can score tickets to the show.",
    4: "April cools to 21°C and the vineyards turn spectacular shades of gold and crimson — this is Mendoza's most photogenic moment. Tourist crowds thin out and winery visits become leisurely and personal. The Andes get their first fresh snow, creating stunning backdrops for wine-soaked lunches.",
    5: "May drops to 15°C with crisp mornings and clear mountain views as the vines go dormant and autumn reaches its golden peak. It's quiet but the wineries are open and happy to see you without reservation hassles. The olive oil harvest adds another tasting dimension.",
    6: "June is winter at 10°C — the vineyards are bare, the Andes are heavy with snow, and Mendoza pivots to its ski-adjacent identity with Las Leñas and Los Penitentes drawing skiers. The cold makes the region's hearty cuisine — locro stew, empanadas, and robust reds — even more appealing.",
    7: "July averages 9°C and is peak ski season in the nearby Andes — combine a few days on the slopes with wine tasting in the valley. Mendoza city is quiet and inexpensive, with cosy restaurants offering winter menus. Clear winter days offer the sharpest Aconcagua views of the year.",
    8: "August stays cold at 11°C with snow still reliable in the mountains and the almond trees starting to blossom in the lower valleys. The vineyard pruning season is underway — a fascinating time for wine nerds to visit and talk to winemakers with time on their hands. Hotel rates are at their annual low.",
    9: "September brings spring at 16°C with cherry and almond blossoms carpeting the Valle de Uco. Bud break in the vineyards signals a new vintage beginning, and winemakers are cautiously optimistic and chatty. It's a gorgeous shoulder season with climbing temperatures and minimal crowds.",
    10: "October warms to 22°C and the vineyards are green with new growth — spring in wine country is energizing. Rafting on the Mendoza River picks up with snowmelt, and outdoor activities along the Andes foothills are at their best. The bodega tasting rooms start extending their hours.",
    11: "November hits 27°C with dry heat and long days — the vines are flowering and the region hums with pre-harvest anticipation. Adventure tourism peaks with hiking, horseback riding through the pre-cordillera, and white-water rafting. Wine country lunches under pergolas with mountain views are transcendent.",
    12: "December brings 31°C and full summer — poolside wineries become essential, and evening asados under starlit Andean skies are the ultimate Mendoza experience. The holiday season draws Argentine families and international visitors, pushing prices up. Book well ahead for Christmas and New Year's at the top bodegas.",
  },
  'ar-patagonia': {
    1: "January is Patagonia's warmest month — a relative 18°C in El Calafate and 20°C in Bariloche, with 17 hours of daylight for hiking Torres del Paine and Perito Moreno Glacier. This is peak season: trails are crowded, refugios are booked months ahead, and prices rival Western Europe. The trade-off is the best weather you'll get in this wind-battered land.",
    2: "February holds at 17°C with long days and the summer hiking season still in full swing, though crowds begin thinning after mid-month. The Perito Moreno Glacier calving is spectacular, and the steppe wildflowers are in final bloom. Wind is a constant companion — bring layers for everything.",
    3: "March brings autumn to Patagonia — 14°C, the lenga forests igniting in red and gold, and hiking crowds evaporating. It's arguably the most beautiful month, with warm light and calm conditions. Refugios start closing late in the month, so plan accordingly.",
    4: "April drops to 9°C with stunning autumn colour persisting and the first snow dusting the peaks. Many lodges and services close for winter, and the Carretera Austral is at its most atmospheric. Wildlife watching improves as guanacos and rheas are easier to spot against the thinning landscape.",
    5: "May brings winter's advance — 5°C, short days, and snow closing higher trails and passes. El Calafate and Ushuaia stay accessible but feel end-of-the-world remote. The upside is empty landscapes of staggering beauty and hotel rates that are half of summer's.",
    6: "June is deep winter — 2°C in El Calafate, snow on the ground, and Cerro Catedral near Bariloche opening for ski season. Ushuaia, the world's southernmost city, has barely seven hours of pale daylight but offers cross-country skiing and husky sledding. King crab season is in full swing.",
    7: "July is Patagonia's coldest at 1°C, with ski season peaking at Cerro Catedral and Cerro Castor near Ushuaia. The landscape is stark and beautiful under winter light, and the glaciers are dramatically framed by snow-covered peaks. Argentine school holidays bring domestic skiers but the region is still far quieter than summer.",
    8: "August averages 3°C with reliable snow for skiing and the first hints of longer days. Whale watching season begins in Peninsula Valdés as southern right whales arrive for calving. The Patagonian steppe under winter light has a raw, monochrome beauty that rewards photographers.",
    9: "September brings early spring at 7°C with snowmelt feeding roaring rivers and waterfalls at their most powerful. Peninsula Valdés whale watching is in full swing, with calves breaching alongside their mothers. Hiking trails remain snowy at altitude but lower routes begin opening.",
    10: "October warms to 11°C and spring arrives tentatively — wildflowers appear on the steppe and the hiking season begins to awaken. Penguin colonies at Punta Tombo welcome returning Magellanic penguins by the hundred thousand. The weather is volatile — four seasons in one day is standard.",
    11: "November hits 14°C and the hiking season opens properly, with trails clearing and refugios staffing up. Crowds haven't arrived yet, making this a sweet spot for Torres del Paine and Los Glaciares. Orca season at Peninsula Valdés provides one of nature's most dramatic spectacles.",
    12: "December averages 17°C with long days and the summer season in full momentum — book everything months in advance. The wildflowers are extraordinary, the glaciers are calving dramatically, and the Patagonian wind is doing its best to test your resolve. It's expensive but unforgettable.",
  },
  'ar-salta-northwest': {
    1: "January in Salta is hot and wet — 28°C with daily afternoon thunderstorms that turn the Quebrada de Humahuaca into a green paradise streaked with waterfalls. The Ruta 40 can flood, making some routes impassable, so check conditions before heading north. The city's peñas (folk music clubs) are lively with zambas and chacareras.",
    2: "February continues the wet season at 27°C with the same pattern of morning sun and afternoon deluges. The salt flats around Salinas Grandes are less photogenic with standing water, but the landscapes are dramatically green. Carnival in Quebrada de Humahuaca is an Andean explosion of colour and dancing.",
    3: "March cools to 24°C with rains easing and the landscapes at peak lushness — the contrast of red rock, green valleys, and blue sky is extraordinary. The grape harvest in Cafayate's high-altitude vineyards brings Torrontés wine festivals. It's a shoulder-season gem with falling prices and improving roads.",
    4: "April drops to 20°C with dry weather settling in and autumn colour appearing in the quebrada valleys. The Tren a las Nubes (Train to the Clouds) runs its spectacular route, and the clear skies make the Andean vistas razor-sharp. This is one of the best months for the region.",
    5: "May brings 16°C and bone-dry conditions — perfect for driving the high-altitude routes without weather worries. The Puna landscapes turn austere and beautiful, with flamingos on high-altitude lagoons and vicuñas on the hillsides. Pack warm layers for the altitude — nights can drop to freezing above 3,000m.",
    6: "June cools to 12°C with frost in the valleys and the highest passes occasionally snow-dusted. Salta city is pleasant and uncrowded, with excellent street food and colonial architecture best appreciated in mild temperatures. The dry air makes the star-gazing in the Puna world-class.",
    7: "July averages 11°C — dry, clear, and ideal for the dramatic landscapes despite chilly mornings. Argentine school holidays bring domestic tourists to the region's highlights. The Quebrada de las Flechas and Cachi loop are at their most accessible and photogenic.",
    8: "August stays dry and cool at 14°C with the clearest skies of the year — the Andes are razor-sharp on the horizon and the pre-Columbian ruins at Quilmes are best visited now. Pachamama (Earth Mother) celebrations on August 1 connect visitors to the region's indigenous Andean culture.",
    9: "September warms to 18°C as spring arrives in the Argentine northwest. The jacarandas begin blooming in Salta city and the countryside starts greening from the first spring rains. Cafayate's high-altitude vineyards are budding and the wine bars are happy to pour their latest vintage.",
    10: "October reaches 23°C with increasing warmth and the occasional spring shower greening the valleys. The region is uncrowded and the driving conditions are excellent — this is prime road-trip territory. Hummingbirds return to the cloud forests of Calilegua National Park.",
    11: "November heats to 26°C with afternoon thunderstorms becoming more regular as the wet season approaches. The landscapes are transitioning from dry ochre to vibrant green, creating dramatic photographic contrasts. Salta's outdoor dining scene peaks before the summer rains get serious.",
    12: "December is hot and increasingly wet at 28°C, with the wet season establishing its afternoon thunderstorm rhythm. Christmas in Salta is celebrated with empanadas, locro, and fireworks over the colonial plaza. The roads start getting tricky toward month's end — plan routes with flood awareness.",
  },
  'at-salzburg': {
    1: "Salzburg in January is a winter postcard — 1°C, snow on the fortress, and Mozart's birthplace glowing golden against grey skies. The ski areas of Flachau and the Salzburg Sportwelt are in full swing, a short drive from the city. Crowds are manageable and the Augustiner Bräustübl brewery is the ultimate warming refuge.",
    2: "February brings Salzburg's coldest temperatures around -1°C, with reliable snow for skiing and the lakes frozen around their edges. Fasching (carnival) adds playful energy to the city before Lent settles in. The Salzkammergut lake district is hauntingly beautiful under winter light.",
    3: "March sees the first thaw at 6°C, with crocuses pushing through in the Mirabell Gardens and the Easter Festival preparations beginning. Skiing is still viable at higher resorts, and the shoulder-season pricing is attractive. The city shakes off winter with a palpable sense of relief.",
    4: "April warms to 11°C with unpredictable weather — sunshine and snow showers can alternate within hours. The Easter Festival at the Festspielhaus is world-class, drawing classical music devotees. The Untersberg cable car reopens and the hiking season tentatively begins.",
    5: "May is glorious at 17°C with the Mirabell Gardens in full bloom and the sound of music literally everywhere (the tour buses are back). The lake district warms up and the first brave swimmers test the Wolfgangsee. It's peak spring with manageable crowds and excellent weather.",
    6: "June brings 21°C and long sunny days — the Salzkammergut lakes turn swimmable and the mountain meadows are carpeted in wildflowers. Outdoor concerts and beer gardens define the social scene. Book ahead if your dates overlap with any Festspielhaus performances.",
    7: "July hits 24°C and the legendary Salzburg Festival begins its five-week reign — the city fills with culture vultures and ticket prices for prime performances are staggering. The lakes are at their warmest and hiking in the Hohe Tauern is superb. This is peak everything: season, prices, and crowds.",
    8: "August continues the Festival at 23°C with the city operating at maximum cultural and tourist capacity. The Sound of Music tour buses are relentless but the alpine lakes provide serene escape. Book months ahead for accommodation — Salzburg in August is serious business.",
    9: "September cools to 18°C as the Festival wraps and the city takes a collective breath. The hiking is exceptional with stable weather and autumn colours beginning in the higher valleys. It's a sophisticated shoulder season with great dining and none of July's frenzy.",
    10: "October drops to 12°C with the Salzkammergut forests turning amber and gold — the drive around Hallstätter See is outrageously beautiful. Hallstatt itself is fighting overtourism, but early morning visits reward with mist-on-lake perfection. The city's wine bars pivot to Sturm (partially fermented new wine).",
    11: "November chills to 5°C with fog settling over the lakes and the city transitioning to Christmas market mode. The Christkindlmarkt opens mid-month, filling the Domplatz and Residenzplatz with Glühwein, handicrafts, and stollen. It's atmospheric and increasingly popular — weekday visits are calmer.",
    12: "December is peak Christmas — 1°C, snow likely, and Salzburg's Advent markets among Europe's most magical. Krampus runs on December 5 are thrillingly terrifying, and Silent Night was composed near here (Oberndorf, 1818). Hotel rates climb steeply for the holiday period but the atmosphere justifies every euro.",
  },
  'at-tyrol': {
    1: "January in Tyrol is peak ski season — average -4°C in the valleys and metres of snow blanketing St. Anton, Kitzbühel, and the Stubai Glacier. The Hahnenkamm downhill race in Kitzbühel (late January) is the social event of the season, equal parts sports and spectacle. Après-ski culture is religion here — schnapps and Kaiserschmarrn are the sacraments.",
    2: "February stays cold at -3°C with the best snow conditions of the year and Fasching carnival adding colour to the white landscape. Ski resorts are packed during school holidays but the grooming is immaculate and the off-piste is extraordinary. Innsbruck's old town, framed by snow-covered peaks, is outrageously photogenic.",
    3: "March brings spring skiing at its finest — -1°C but strong sunshine means you can ski in a t-shirt by afternoon. The snow is still deep at altitude while the valley floors begin to thaw. Longer days and deck-chair sundowners at mountain huts make this many locals' favourite month.",
    4: "April is the transition — ski resorts close one by one as temperatures hit 10°C, while hiking trails remain snowy above 2,000m. It's the quietest month in Tyrol, with a brief lull between winter and summer seasons. Innsbruck's cafes fill with locals celebrating the return of outdoor terrace culture.",
    5: "May bursts with colour at 15°C — alpine meadows erupt in wildflowers and the hiking season opens properly. The valleys are green while peaks remain snow-capped, creating classic Tyrolean postcards at every turn. Cable cars reopen and mountain huts start serving their famous Tiroler Gröstl.",
    6: "June is alpine perfection — 20°C, wildflower meadows at peak bloom, and hiking trails in prime condition. The Inntal Valley is lush and the higher hut-to-hut trails become passable. It's busy but not yet peak, making it the cognoscenti's choice for serious mountain walking.",
    7: "July hits 23°C and Tyrol enters full summer mode — every cable car runs, every hut is open, and the mountain biking is world-class. Thunderstorms roll through most afternoons, so start hikes early. The Innsbruck Festival of Early Music adds cultural depth to the outdoor adventures.",
    8: "August matches July at 22°C with the most reliable hiking weather and peak tourist numbers. The Almabtrieb (cattle drive) preparations begin and the alps ring with cowbells. It's the busiest month but the mountains are vast enough to absorb the crowds.",
    9: "September cools to 17°C with golden light, stable weather, and the legendary Almabtrieb — flower-crowned cows descend from summer pastures in festive processions. Hiking conditions are ideal with thinner crowds and the first autumn colours appearing at altitude. Tyrolean wine harvest (yes, they make wine) adds a local flavour.",
    10: "October drops to 10°C with spectacular larch forests turning gold against granite peaks. It's the quietest shoulder season — trails empty, huts close one by one, and the mountains feel properly wild again. Innsbruck's restaurants pivot to game and pumpkin menus.",
    11: "November chills to 3°C with the first serious snowfall at altitude and ski resorts performing their annual snow dances. Early-season skiing opens on glaciers like Stubai and Sölden. Innsbruck's Christmas markets begin mid-month, and the city has a cosy pre-winter charm.",
    12: "December brings full winter at -2°C with Innsbruck's Altstadt markets among Austria's most atmospheric. Ski season is in full swing by mid-month, and the holiday period in the Alps is a bucket-list experience — think candlelit mountain dinners, horse-drawn sleigh rides, and champagne-quality snowfall. Prices peak but the magic is real.",
  },
  'at-vienna': {
    1: "Vienna in January averages a bracing 1°C, with grey skies and the occasional snow flurry dusting the Ringstrasse's imperial facades. The opera and concert season is in full magnificent swing — this is when the Musikverein and Staatsoper justify their legendary reputations. Warm up with Sachertorte and a mélange in a wood-panelled Kaffeehaus.",
    2: "February is Vienna's ball season apex — 0°C outside but the Hofburg glitters with waltzing at the Opernball and dozens of other formal dances. It's the most Viennese month imaginable: classical music, elaborate pastries, and an entire culture built around ignoring the cold with extraordinary style. Hotel prices spike around ball dates.",
    3: "March brings the first hints of spring at 7°C, with crocuses in the Volksgarten and the Naschmarkt's outdoor stalls buzzing with life again. The Prater's giant Ferris wheel starts getting scenic views of a greening city. Easter markets add charm to the squares in front of the great churches.",
    4: "April warms to 14°C and Vienna shifts outdoors — the Schönbrunn gardens are magnificent, the Heurigen wine taverns in Grinzing reopen their patios, and the bike paths along the Danube Canal fill up. It's an excellent time to visit, with moderate crowds and blooming chestnut trees lining every boulevard.",
    5: "May is arguably Vienna's finest month — 19°C, the city ablaze with flowers, and outdoor life in full bloom. The Danube Island opens for swimming and sunbathing, and every Schanigarten (pavement terrace) is packed by 5pm. The Life Ball (if running) and the Vienna Festival add cultural firepower.",
    6: "June brings 23°C and long golden evenings — open-air cinema on the Rathausplatz, wine spritzers at sunset Heurigen, and the Danube warm enough for swimming. The tourist crowds build but Vienna's grand scale absorbs them. The Donauinselfest (free open-air music festival) draws millions.",
    7: "July hits 26°C and Vienna's museums provide air-conditioned refuge from the heat — the Kunsthistorisches Museum alone deserves a full day. The Museumsquartier's courtyard becomes the city's living room, and the Alte Donau lake is the local beach. Many Viennese flee to the Salzkammergut, leaving some restaurants closed.",
    8: "August holds at 25°C with a distinctly quieter feel — Parliament is in recess, the opera takes a break, and the city belongs to tourists and the locals who stayed. The outdoor Film Festival on Rathausplatz screens free movies with international food stalls. It's hot but manageable.",
    9: "September cools to 20°C and the cultural season explodes back to life — the Vienna Philharmonic returns, new exhibitions open, and the wine harvest in the surrounding vineyards kicks off. It's the insider's month: perfect weather, post-summer energy, and the Heurigen pouring Sturm (new wine). Peak sophistication.",
    10: "October drops to 13°C with autumn colour in the Wienerwald and the Viennale film festival adding intellectual edge. The coffee house culture hits its atmospheric peak — imagine reading the Neue Zürcher Zeitung under a chandelier while rain streaks the windows. Long Night of Museums is worth planning around.",
    11: "November chills to 6°C and Vienna transitions to Advent — the Christmas markets open mid-month, and the Rathausplatz Christkindlmarkt is genuinely magical. Fog and early darkness make the illuminated buildings extra dramatic. The opera and concert programs are in full, glorious swing.",
    12: "December is Vienna at its most enchanting — 2°C, mulled wine steaming at every corner, and the New Year's Concert tickets the world's most coveted (or watch the rehearsal for a fraction). Christmas Eve is quiet and familial, while Silvesternacht (New Year's Eve) brings a city-wide waltz. Accommodation books out months ahead for the holiday period.",
  },
  'au-melbourne': {
    1: "January is Melbourne at its peak — 26°C on average but notorious for 40°C scorchers that send the city running for the beach or the pub. The Australian Open transforms Melbourne Park into a sporting cathedral, and the city's laneway bars and rooftop terraces are in full summer mode. Four seasons in one day? Entirely possible.",
    2: "February holds at 26°C and is arguably Melbourne's best event month — the Melbourne Food & Wine Festival, St Kilda Festival, and the White Night arts festival pack the calendar. The Yarra Valley wineries are lush and harvest-ready. Keep a jacket handy; Melbourne's weather mood swings are legendary.",
    3: "March cools to 24°C with early autumn warmth and the Melbourne Comedy Festival getting underway. The Great Ocean Road is perfect — warm enough for swimming at Lorne but not searingly hot. Formula 1 roars around Albert Park, bringing international glamour to an already cosmopolitan city.",
    4: "April drops to 20°C with reliably pleasant weather and autumn foliage appearing in the Dandenong Ranges. The Melbourne International Comedy Festival is in full swing and the cafe culture is at its cosiest. It's shoulder season with excellent prices and comfortable exploring weather.",
    5: "May brings 16°C and Melbourne's coffee-and-culture personality shines brightest — ducking between laneway espresso bars, galleries, and bookshops as the rain intermittently patters. AFL football season is heating up and the city's sporting tribalism is infectious. Layer up and lean into Melbourne's moody autumn charm.",
    6: "June is winter at 14°C — grey, occasionally drizzly, and utterly perfect for Melbourne's indoor strengths: world-class dining, live music, and the NGV's winter exhibitions. The Yarra Valley's cellar doors are cosy and uncrowded, with bold shiraz the appropriate seasonal choice. Rising film festival season adds cultural weight.",
    7: "July averages 13°C and is Melbourne's coldest month — the kind of weather that justifies hot chocolate at Koko Black and slow-cooked lamb at a Southbank restaurant. The Melbourne International Film Festival is the major cultural draw. Weekend drives to the Mornington Peninsula's hot springs are genuinely therapeutic.",
    8: "August stays cool at 14°C with the city still in winter mode but the first daffodils hinting at spring. Melbourne Writers Festival draws the literary crowd, and the AFL finals race intensifies. Phillip Island's penguin parade is running year-round but winter's smaller crowds make it more intimate.",
    9: "September brings spring at 16°C with a buzz of anticipation — the AFL Grand Final (late September) is the city's Super Bowl, Melbourne Cup carnival prep begins, and the Royal Botanic Gardens burst with spring blooms. Wildflower season on the Great Ocean Road is stunning.",
    10: "October warms to 19°C with spring in full effect and the Melbourne Festival (arts and culture) running through the month. The Yarra Valley is blooming and the Dandenongs are thick with rhododendrons and fern gullies. Weather remains unpredictable — the four-seasons-in-a-day cliché exists for good reason.",
    11: "November hits 22°C and the Melbourne Cup on the first Tuesday stops the nation — it's a public holiday in Melbourne and the fashion at Flemington is as competitive as the horses. Spring racing carnival aside, the city's outdoor dining scene explodes and beach weather returns to St Kilda. Jacarandas add purple drama to every streetscape.",
    12: "December brings 25°C and full summer — Boxing Day Test cricket at the MCG is a national institution, and the city buzzes with holiday energy. The laneways are packed, the rooftop bars are humming, and the coastal villages of the Mornington Peninsula draw weekending Melburnians. New Year's Eve fireworks over the Yarra are worth staking out a spot for.",
  },
  'au-outback': {
    1: "January in the Top End is monsoonal madness — Darwin hits 32°C with 90% humidity and spectacular afternoon thunderstorms that turn waterfalls into roaring cataracts. Kakadu's Jim Jim Falls are at their most powerful but many roads are impassable. Crocodile activity is at its peak — stay well back from waterways.",
    2: "February is the wettest month in the Top End — 33°C with constant humidity and cyclone risk along the coast. Litchfield National Park's waterfalls are thunderous but some trails close. In central Australia, Alice Springs bakes at 36°C with the occasional dramatic desert thunderstorm transforming red landscapes to green.",
    3: "March stays wet and hot in the north at 32°C, with the monsoon season winding down and floodwaters still covering outback tracks. Uluru is brutally hot at 35°C — sunrise and sunset visits only. The Outback's harsh beauty demands respect and preparation in any season.",
    4: "April brings the magical transition in the Top End — rains ease, humidity drops, and the 'green season' reveals a lush landscape at 33°C. Kakadu's wetlands are spectacularly full of birdlife and barramundi. Central Australia cools to 27°C and becomes genuinely pleasant for hiking around the MacDonnell Ranges.",
    5: "May is when the Outback opens for business — Darwin cools to 31°C with dry days and cool evenings, and central Australia hits a perfect 22°C. The dry season transforms Kakadu's roads from impassable to accessible, and Uluru and Kata Tjuta are magnificent in mild conditions. Tourist season begins in earnest.",
    6: "June brings the Top End's best weather — 30°C, zero humidity, and electric-blue skies over Katherine Gorge and Litchfield. Alice Springs drops to a crisp 19°C with cold desert nights perfect for campfire storytelling under the clearest skies on Earth. This is prime Outback season — book ahead.",
    7: "July is the Outback's peak month — 30°C in Darwin, 20°C in Alice Springs, and every tour, campsite, and scenic flight at capacity. The Camel Cup in Alice Springs and the Beer Can Regatta in Darwin showcase the Outback's irreverent humour. Desert nights can drop near freezing — bring a proper sleeping bag.",
    8: "August holds peak-season form — dry, sunny, and busy across the Top End and Red Centre. Darwin's Mindil Beach sunset markets are at their vibrant best, and the Henley-on-Todd dry riverbed regatta in Alice Springs is gloriously absurd. Uluru's golden-hour light shows are at their most reliable.",
    9: "September marks shoulder season's start — still excellent conditions at 33°C in Darwin, but heat begins building in the Red Centre at 27°C. The build-up (pre-monsoon) hasn't started yet and the landscapes retain their dry-season beauty. Crowds thin slightly and prices ease from peak levels.",
    10: "October brings the infamous 'build-up' to the Top End — 34°C with climbing humidity and gathering thunderheads that turn sunsets apocalyptic. Swimming holes warm to bath temperature and the locals get a bit twitchy. Central Australia is heating up fast — Uluru visits need early morning starts.",
    11: "November is build-up at full intensity in the north — 34°C, 80% humidity, and spectacular lightning storms every afternoon. It's dramatic and beautiful but exhausting. Alice Springs hits 33°C and the tourist season winds down. Accommodation prices drop and you'll share Kakadu with almost nobody.",
    12: "December in the Top End is wet season foreplay — 33°C, monsoonal rains beginning, and waterfalls starting to flow. Darwin's Christmas is celebrated with cold beer and prawns in the humid heat. The Red Centre bakes at 35°C — only the truly hardy visit Uluru in December, but sunrise has the rock almost to yourself.",
  },
  'au-queensland': {
    1: "January on the Great Barrier Reef means 30°C air, 28°C water, and stinger season in full swing — you'll need a lycra suit for snorkeling but the coral is spectacular. It's wet season in tropical North Queensland, with afternoon downpours in Cairns and the Daintree rainforest earning its name. Crowds thin in the heat, creating dive-boat intimacy.",
    2: "February is the wettest month in tropical Queensland — 31°C with cyclone risk and sometimes impressive flooding. The reef is quiet and prices drop, but dive operations run unless conditions are genuinely dangerous. The Daintree is at its most primordially lush, with cassowaries active and crocs well-fed.",
    3: "March stays hot and wet at 30°C, with the tail end of cyclone season keeping cautious travelers away. The Whitsundays are still beautiful between storms, and the reef's coral spawning (if you hit the timing) is a once-in-a-lifetime underwater snowstorm. Stinger season continues — respect the box jellyfish.",
    4: "April brings the transition — 28°C, rains easing, and stinger season winding down. The reef's visibility starts improving and the Daintree's rivers calm. It's an excellent shoulder-season play with good weather, reduced prices, and the Gold Coast's Broadbeach strip gleaming in autumn sunshine.",
    5: "May is when tropical Queensland hits its stride — 26°C, dry, clear skies, and the reef sparkling with excellent visibility. Port Douglas and Cairns are busy but not insane, and the Atherton Tablelands offer cooler highland exploring. Humpback whale migration north begins off the coast.",
    6: "June brings Queensland's winter — a laughable 24°C in Cairns and 21°C on the Gold Coast, which locals consider freezing. Reef conditions are superb with calm seas and crystal visibility. Whale watching from Hervey Bay kicks off as humpbacks pause in the sheltered waters. Peak season begins.",
    7: "July is prime reef season — 25°C, dry, zero stingers, and dive conditions at their annual best. The Whitsundays are postcard-perfect and Whitehaven Beach justifies every superlative thrown at it. Book well ahead — this is when Australian school holidays and international visitors converge on the tropics.",
    8: "August continues the dry-season perfection at 25°C with the Great Barrier Reef in its absolute prime. Whale watching peaks off Hervey Bay and the Gold Coast, and the Daintree is accessible and comfortable. Airlie Beach and Port Douglas are humming with visitors but the reef is big enough for everyone.",
    9: "September holds ideal conditions at 26°C — the last of the peak dry season with reef visibility still excellent and the weather warming nicely. Cairns Festival brings cultural energy to the tropics and the first spring warmth hits the Gold Coast. Stinger-free waters mean worry-free swimming.",
    10: "October warms to 28°C with the dry season's dying days delivering reliable sunshine. Stinger season technically returns late in the month, but the first half is perfect for unrestricted ocean swimming. The Whitsundays enter shoulder season with softer pricing and fewer sailing boats on the horizon.",
    11: "November transitions to wet season — 29°C with humidity climbing and afternoon storms returning to the tropics. Stinger nets go up on major beaches and reef trips include stinger suits. It's shoulder season with decent prices and the landscapes beginning their green transformation.",
    12: "December heats to 30°C with wet season establishing itself in the tropics — dramatic storms, oppressive humidity, and the reef under its annual deluge. The Gold Coast is in full summer party mode and Schoolies Week (late November/early December) is a particular kind of chaos. Christmas on the reef is festive if you embrace the tropical weather.",
  },
  'au-sydney': {
    1: "January is peak Sydney — 27°C, the harbour sparkling, and the aftermath of New Year's fireworks still glittering in the conversation. Bondi to Bronte walk is packed with sun-seekers, and the Sydney Festival brings outdoor performances to every park. Book Bondi beachside brunch weeks ahead or accept a 9am queue.",
    2: "February stays at 27°C and feels like Sydney's most livable month — still hot, still beachy, but the January tourist crush softens. The Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras builds to its spectacular Oxford Street parade, and the harbour ferries to Manly are running on summer schedules. Late-afternoon thunderstorms provide dramatic harbour photography.",
    3: "March cools to 25°C with autumn edging in and the Royal Easter Show drawing suburban families to Olympic Park. The beaches are still swimmable and the Blue Mountains offer cooler day-trip relief. Sydney's food scene gears up for autumn menus — look for new-season produce at the fish markets.",
    4: "April drops to 22°C with Sydney's best weather — stable, sunny, and comfortable for harbour walks, coastal hikes, and long lunches in Surry Hills. The crowds have thinned and hotel rates ease from summer peaks. The Royal National Park's coastal track is spectacular in autumn light.",
    5: "May brings 19°C and a cosier Sydney — the outdoor obsession retreats slightly and the city's indoor dining, theatre, and gallery scene steps forward. Vivid Sydney (light festival) begins late May, transforming the Opera House and harbour into a luminous wonderland. Whale migration starts — watch from the coastal cliffs.",
    6: "June is Sydney's winter — 17°C, short days, and the harbour under moody grey skies. Vivid Sydney continues into early June and is genuinely spectacular. The Blue Mountains get genuinely cold with occasional frost, and the city's fireplaced restaurants come into their own.",
    7: "July averages 16°C with clear, crisp days and the most reliable dry weather of the year — winter sun in Sydney is still pleasant enough for harbour walks in a jumper. Whale watching peaks along the coast, and the city's cultural calendar is stacked. Hotel rates are at their annual low.",
    8: "August stays at 17°C with spring teasing at the edges — the cherry blossoms at Auburn Botanic Garden draw Instagram pilgrims. The Sydney Film Festival and Good Food Month fill the cultural and culinary calendars. Early wildflower displays begin in the Royal National Park.",
    9: "September brings spring at 20°C with whale watching still going strong and the city's parks erupting in colour. The Sydney Running Festival takes over the Harbour Bridge, and jacaranda season begins to purple-up the Inner West. Beach water temperatures are still brisk but the brave are back in.",
    10: "October warms to 22°C with perfect spring weather and the Sculpture by the Sea exhibition transforming the Bondi to Tamarama coastline into an open-air gallery. The harbour is blue, the bougainvillea is electric, and Sydney is reminding everyone why it's one of the world's great cities. Whale season winds down.",
    11: "November hits 24°C and summer energy returns — the beaches fill, the rooftop bars open, and the ocean temperature finally invites swimming. Jacarandas peak in Kirribilli and Paddington, creating canopies of purple over heritage terrace houses. The social calendar builds toward the festive season.",
    12: "December is Sydney gearing up for the greatest New Year's Eve party in the Southern Hemisphere — 26°C, golden beaches, and the harbour in party mode. Christmas Day is typically spent at the beach with cold prawns and champagne, a deeply Australian tradition. NYE harbour-view spots require arriving before dawn — commitment is everything.",
  },
  'au-tasmania': {
    1: "January is Tasmania's warmest month at 21°C — balmy by Tassie standards — with the longest days for hiking the Overland Track and exploring the Freycinet Peninsula's Wineglass Bay. MONA's Festival of Music and Art (MONA FOMA) brings cutting-edge culture to Hobart. The produce is extraordinary: cherries, berries, and oysters fresh from the source.",
    2: "February holds at 21°C with stable weather and the tail end of summer providing excellent conditions for the Three Capes Track and Cradle Mountain day hikes. Hobart's Salamanca Market is at its bustling best with local artisans and food producers. The lavender fields at Bridestowe are still in bloom for early visitors.",
    3: "March cools to 19°C with autumn approaching and Tasmania's produce season at full throttle — Agrarian Kitchen cooking classes book out months ahead. The Tarkine wilderness is magnificent, and the east coast beaches are still warm enough for swimming if you're hardy. Tourist crowds thin noticeably.",
    4: "April drops to 15°C with the fagus (Australia's only deciduous tree) turning the highlands golden — it's a uniquely Tasmanian autumn phenomenon. The dark skies make for exceptional stargazing, and the seafood is running: salmon, abalone, and rock lobster. Shoulder-season pricing makes luxury lodges more accessible.",
    5: "May brings 12°C and moody skies that make Tasmania feel properly atmospheric — think fireside whiskies at Lark Distillery and slow drives through misty forests. Dark Mofo festival preparations begin and the arts scene intensifies. Oyster season is peaking and the truffle hunt begins.",
    6: "June is Dark Mofo month — Hobart's extraordinary winter arts festival transforms the city with provocative installations, feasting, and the nude solstice swim. At 10°C, it's cold but the cultural heat is intense. The Overland Track is closed for winter, but shorter walks remain accessible.",
    7: "July averages 9°C and is Tasmania's coldest month — kunanyi/Mount Wellington gets regular snow dustings visible from Hobart's waterfront. Truffle season peaks in the north and the winter food scene is remarkably sophisticated for such a small island. The Central Highlands feel wonderfully remote and wild.",
    8: "August stays chilly at 10°C with winter still gripping the highlands but the first signs of spring appearing in northern valleys. The Tasmanian devil breeding season makes Cradle Mountain's wildlife park particularly active. Short days and wild weather make this a season for whisky tastings and gallery hopping.",
    9: "September brings spring at 13°C with wattle (acacia) blooming yellow across the bush and platypus becoming more active in the rivers. Whale watching begins off the east coast and the hiking trails start opening up. Tasmania's isolation feels most rewarding when the bush is coming alive.",
    10: "October warms to 15°C with spring wildflowers and green landscapes making the Cradle Mountain area spectacular. Tulip festivals bloom at Table Cape and the Tamar Valley wine region springs to life. Tourist numbers are low and the island feels like a well-kept secret.",
    11: "November hits 17°C with long days and the promise of summer drawing hikers to book their Overland Track spots. The Freycinet Peninsula is uncrowded and beautiful, and the oyster and seafood season continues year-round. Tassie's craft beer scene — among Australia's best — provides its own touring itinerary.",
    12: "December warms to 20°C and the summer season launches — the Taste of Tasmania food festival on Hobart's waterfront between Christmas and New Year's is a gourmet pilgrimage. Cradle Mountain huts book out for the walking season, and Maria Island's car-free wilderness is pristine. Long twilight evenings at MONA are unforgettable.",
  },
  'au-wa': {
    1: "January in the Kimberley and Broome is wet season — 34°C with tropical downpours, flooded gorges, and the outback tracks often impassable. Broome's Cable Beach is stunning despite the humidity, and staircase-to-the-moon events draw crowds to the mudflats. The waterfalls at Mitchell Falls are at their most powerful but access is limited.",
    2: "February is the peak of the Kimberley wet — 34°C, cyclone risk, and roads closed across the region. It's the cheapest time to visit Broome, with pearl farm tours and dinosaur footprint walks still running. The northwest's dramatic weather creates apocalyptic sunsets that justify the sweat.",
    3: "March stays hot and wet at 34°C in the Kimberley, with the monsoon beginning its retreat. Ningaloo Reef's whale shark season kicks off on the central coast — swimming with the world's largest fish is a life-altering experience. Perth hits 29°C with late-summer warmth and the Perth Festival wrapping up.",
    4: "April brings the transition in the north at 33°C — rains end, the Gibb River Road begins to open, and the Kimberley's impossible gorges emerge gleaming. Whale shark season is in full swing at Ningaloo, and Perth cools to a pleasant 25°C. It's shoulder season with excellent value across the state.",
    5: "May opens the Kimberley season proper — 31°C, dry, and the iconic red-rock gorges of El Questro and Purnululu (Bungle Bungles) fully accessible. Ningaloo whale sharks continue and humpback migration begins. Perth hits 21°C with autumn crispness and the Margaret River wine region at its cosy best.",
    6: "June brings the Kimberley's peak season — 30°C with zero rain and every gorge, waterfall, and creek crossing at its most photogenic. Perth's winter is a mild 18°C with increasing rain but the Margaret River truffle season and cosy cellar doors compensate. Wildflower season begins in the northern heathlands.",
    7: "July is prime Kimberley at 30°C — Horizontal Falls, Tunnel Creek, and the Mitchell Plateau are all running at capacity. Ningaloo transitions from whale sharks to humpback whales. Perth gets its most rain at 17°C, making it a Margaret River and Pemberton wine-country month.",
    8: "August continues peak northern conditions at 31°C with the Kimberley at its absolute best — clear skies, accessible tracks, and Indigenous cultural tours at their most active. The famous Western Australian wildflower season explodes across the midwest and south. Perth improves to 18°C with spring approaching.",
    9: "September brings spring to Perth at 20°C and the wildflower bloom reaches its spectacular peak — carpets of everlastings, banksias, and orchids cover the bush from Kalbarri to Esperance. The Kimberley starts heating up and drying out as the season winds down. Ningaloo humpback season runs strong.",
    10: "October warms Perth to 23°C with the wildflower season continuing in southern regions and the beaches calling again. The Kimberley enters its hot build-up and the tourist operators start closing for wet season. Margaret River is gorgeous in spring with cellar door gardens in full bloom.",
    11: "November hits 26°C in Perth with summer approaching and the Indian Ocean warming for swimming season. Rottnest Island's quokkas are camera-ready year-round, and the island's snorkeling improves with warming waters. The northwest heats up toward wet-season temperatures and the last Kimberley stragglers head south.",
    12: "December brings 30°C to Perth and full summer — Cottesloe Beach fills up, Margaret River's restaurants are booked out, and the wine region hums with cellar-door visitors. The Kimberley and Broome enter wet season with the first big storms rolling in. Christmas in the sun is a West Australian institution.",
  },
  'aw-aruba': {
    1: "January in Aruba is dry-season perfection — 29°C, constant trade winds, and Eagle Beach consistently ranked among the world's best. It's peak season with North American snowbirds filling the high-rise hotels along Palm Beach. The wind makes it a windsurfing and kiteboarding paradise — Fisherman's Huts is the epicenter.",
    2: "February holds at 29°C with carnival season exploding in a riot of floats, costumes, and tumba music that rivals Trinidad's. The trade winds are strong and reliable, keeping the heat comfortable and the divi-divi trees permanently bent. Hotel rates are at their peak — book months ahead.",
    3: "March is the end of peak dry season at 29°C with clear skies and the island winding down from carnival energy. Spring breakers arrive mid-month, but Aruba's family-friendly vibe keeps things from getting too wild. Arikok National Park's desert landscapes are stark and beautiful.",
    4: "April transitions with 30°C temps and the trade winds easing slightly as the wet season approaches. The island is quieter and cheaper, with beach conditions still excellent. The Hooiberg (Aruba's volcanic haystack hill) is worth the 587-step climb for 360-degree island views.",
    5: "May brings 31°C and occasional brief showers, though Aruba is the driest island in the Caribbean and barely notices. Hotel rates drop 30-40% from peak and the beaches are gloriously uncrowded. The calm-wind days make snorkeling off Baby Beach in the south particularly crystal-clear.",
    6: "June hits 31°C with the off-season in full effect — great hotel deals, empty beaches, and the locals reclaiming their island. The water is bath-warm and the sunsets are legendary. Hurricane season starts elsewhere in the Caribbean, but Aruba sits safely below the storm belt.",
    7: "July warms to 32°C with Aruba's unique position outside the hurricane belt making it a safe bet when other Caribbean islands watch the weather anxiously. The trade winds return strong, and Hadicurari Beach hosts kite and windsurf competitions. Local festivals and food fairs pop up across the island.",
    8: "August stays at 32°C and feels like Aruba's most authentically local month — the tourists are sparse but the Bon Bini Festival showcases Aruban culture every Tuesday in Oranjestad. The Arikok National Park's natural pool (Conchi) is worth the rugged hike. Prices remain friendly.",
    9: "September is the wettest month — a relative term in Aruba, where 'wet' means brief showers between long sunny stretches at 32°C. Hotel prices hit their annual low and you'll feel like you own Eagle Beach. The water visibility remains excellent for diving the Antilla shipwreck.",
    10: "October brings 31°C with the last of the wet-season showers and the island beginning to gear up for high season. It's a savvy traveler's sweet spot — great weather, low prices, and the restaurants haven't gone into peak-season overdrive. The flamingos on Renaissance Island are photogenic year-round.",
    11: "November signals the return of dry season at 30°C with trade winds picking up and the first wave of winter visitors arriving. Hotel prices start climbing and the beachfront restaurants extend their hours. The sunsets turn increasingly spectacular as the atmosphere clears.",
    12: "December is full festive season — 29°C, holiday decorations mixing with palm trees, and Aruba's Dande (New Year's) traditions adding local flavour to the celebrations. Peak pricing returns with a vengeance and the high-rise strip buzzes with holiday energy. New Year's Eve features island-wide fireworks visible from every beach.",
  },
  'az-baku': {
    1: "Baku in January averages a chilly 4°C with the Caspian wind cutting through the old city's medieval lanes. The futuristic Flame Towers and Heydar Aliyev Center look dramatic against winter skies, and the indoor warmth of a chaikhana (tea house) with plov and black tea is essential survival. Crowds are nonexistent and hotel prices bottom out.",
    2: "February stays cold at 4°C with occasional rain and the notorious Baku wind (khazri) at its fiercest. The Old City (Icherisheher) is atmospheric when empty, and the carpet museum and Maiden Tower deserve unhurried visits. Novruz (Persian New Year) preparations begin, with bonfires and festive energy building through the month.",
    3: "March brings Novruz celebrations around the equinox — fires are jumped, wheat grass (samani) sprouts on windowsills, and Baku erupts in a week of feasting on shekerbura pastries and pakhlava. Temperatures climb to 8°C and the first tentative spring warmth appears. It's the single most culturally rewarding time to visit Azerbaijan.",
    4: "April warms to 14°C with blossoms appearing in the parks and the Caspian waterfront boulevard (bulvar) becoming walkable again. The wind eases and the city feels optimistic and energized. Day trips to the fire temple Ateshgah and the mud volcanoes of Gobustan are comfortable.",
    5: "May hits a pleasant 20°C and Baku is genuinely lovely — the waterfront parks are green, the Old City's narrow lanes are perfect for exploring, and the Formula 1 Azerbaijan Grand Prix brings an international circus to town. The Absheron Peninsula's beaches start to beckon, though the Caspian water is still brisk.",
    6: "June brings summer at 26°C with the Caspian breezes keeping humidity in check. Baku's rooftop restaurants come alive, and the nightlife along Nizami Street buzzes until late. The Caspian beaches at Bilgah and Zagulba are warm enough for swimming and the locals start their summer routines.",
    7: "July hits 30°C and Baku enters full summer mode — the bulvar is packed with evening strollers and the Caspian is bath-warm. The heat is dry and manageable compared to the Gulf, and the city's modernist architecture gleams under endless blue skies. Fruit season brings watermelons the size of small children to every market.",
    8: "August holds at 31°C — the hottest month, but the persistent Caspian breeze saves Baku from Gulf-state misery. Evenings on the waterfront are magical, and the rooftop bar scene rivals anything in the Caucasus. It's peak domestic tourism season with Azerbaijanis from the regions flooding the capital.",
    9: "September cools to 25°C and is arguably Baku's best month — warm, dry, and the summer crowds dissolving. The Caspian is still swimmable and the pomegranate harvest begins across the country. Cultural programming restarts after the summer break with music and theatre festivals.",
    10: "October drops to 18°C with golden autumn light making the Old City's sandstone glow. The surrounding countryside is beautiful — Lahij's copper workshops and Sheki's caravanserai are perfect day-trip or overnight destinations. Wine from the Shamakhi region accompanies every meal.",
    11: "November chills to 11°C with grey skies and increasing wind returning to the Absheron Peninsula. The tea houses become essential infrastructure again, and the indoor markets overflow with autumn pomegranates and persimmons. It's quiet, cheap, and genuinely interesting for culturally curious visitors.",
    12: "December brings 6°C and a festive atmosphere to Baku — the city decorates enthusiastically and New Year's (bigger than Christmas in post-Soviet tradition) brings spectacular celebrations. The Flame Towers shimmer with holiday light shows and the Old City's restaurants serve warming dolma and piti. Hotel prices remain reasonable for the holiday period.",
  },
  'az-caucasus': {
    1: "January in Azerbaijan's countryside averages -2°C in the Caucasus highlands, with snow blanketing the villages of Lahij and Xinaliq — the latter claiming to be one of the world's highest continuously inhabited settlements. The skiing at Shahdag is modest but uncrowded. Warming up with piti (slow-cooked lamb soup) in a village guesthouse is the quintessential winter experience.",
    2: "February holds at -1°C in the mountains with deep snow making highland villages feel genuinely isolated. The Sheki region's forests are beautiful under frost, and the ancient caravanserai is wonderfully atmospheric when empty. Road conditions to remote villages can be challenging — 4WD is essential.",
    3: "March sees the thaw begin at 6°C in the lower valleys, with spring wildflowers erupting across the steppe. The fire festival of Novruz is celebrated with particular enthusiasm in rural Azerbaijan — village bonfires and communal feasting are deeply welcoming to visitors. Sheki's famous stained-glass Khan's Palace glows in spring light.",
    4: "April warms to 13°C with the Caucasus foothills turning emerald green and the shepherd migrations beginning to high summer pastures. The Gobustan rock art site and mud volcanoes are comfortable to explore without summer heat. Highland villages are emerging from winter isolation and guest houses are reopening.",
    5: "May is the Caucasus at its finest — 19°C, wildflower meadows stretching to snow-capped peaks, and the hospitality of rural Azerbaijan at full warmth. The Tufandag and Shahdag mountain areas offer excellent hiking with few other visitors. Village life revolves around tea, cheese, and extraordinary generosity.",
    6: "June hits 24°C and the mountain pastures are in prime condition — semi-nomadic shepherds are settled in their summer camps and the highland landscapes are spectacular. Gabala, the country's outdoor recreation hub, offers forest zip-lines and mountain trails. The warmth draws Baku residents to the countryside.",
    7: "July reaches 28°C in the lowlands but the highlands stay pleasant around 20°C, making the Caucasus villages ideal escapes from Baku's heat. The Ismailli wine region is lush and the roadside watermelon stands are irresistible. Book highland guesthouses ahead as domestic tourism peaks.",
    8: "August matches July's heat pattern with the lowlands baking and the mountains providing relief. The pomegranate orchards of Goychay are setting fruit and the walnut harvest begins in Sheki. Mountain rivers run clean and cold for swimming in natural pools.",
    9: "September cools to 22°C with the harvest season transforming the countryside into a cornucopia of pomegranates, grapes, and walnuts. The hiking is superb with stable weather and the first hints of autumn colour in the beech forests. Sheki's bazaar overflows with preserves and dried fruits.",
    10: "October drops to 15°C with stunning autumn foliage in the Caucasus forests — the drive from Sheki to Zagatala is a corridor of gold and crimson. The pomegranate festival in Goychay is a wonderful rural celebration. Highland villages start preparing for winter closure.",
    11: "November chills to 8°C with rain increasing and the highland roads getting muddy. The countryside is beautiful in its muted autumn palette, and the warm hospitality of village guesthouses compensates for the grey skies. It's quiet, authentic, and deeply rewarding for the patient traveler.",
    12: "December brings 2°C and the first serious snow to the Caucasus villages, with Shahdag ski resort opening for the season. Sheki's caravanserai under snow is fairy-tale atmospheric, and the rural New Year's preparations are fascinating to witness. Access to remote villages becomes weather-dependent.",
  },
  'ba-mostar': {
    1: "Mostar in January averages 5°C with occasional rain and the famous Stari Most bridge reflecting in the emerald Neretva without a tourist in sight. The old town's coppersmiths and leather workers carry on regardless, and the warmth of a Bosnian coffee and ćevapi lunch is deeply satisfying. Herzegovina's mild Mediterranean influence keeps it warmer than Sarajevo.",
    2: "February stays at 7°C with almond blossoms appearing early in the Herzegovina valleys — spring comes sooner here than anywhere else in Bosnia. The Kravice Waterfalls are flowing strong from winter rain. Mostar's Ottoman quarter is empty enough to feel like a private discovery.",
    3: "March brings 11°C and proper spring — the hillsides around Blagaj's Dervish monastery turn green and the outdoor cafes along the Neretva tentatively reopen. Počitelj's medieval fortress is stunning without crowds, and the wine country around Čitluk starts pouring its žilavka whites.",
    4: "April warms to 16°C and Herzegovina is arguably at its best — wildflowers, warm sunshine, and tourist infrastructure opening without the summer hordes. The Stari Most bridge jumpers start their season, and the Kravice Waterfalls are spectacular with spring meltwater. Wine tasting in Blatina country is a delight.",
    5: "May hits 21°C and Mostar enters its sweet spot — warm enough for swimming in the Neretva's aquamarine pools, cool enough for exploring the cobblestone old town without melting. The surrounding countryside is gorgeous for day trips to Blagaj, Počitelj, and the Župa wine region. Crowds are building but manageable.",
    6: "June brings summer at 26°C and the Stari Most bridge divers are performing daily for gathered crowds. The old town is busy but not yet overwhelmed, and the Neretva is irresistibly inviting for a swim. Herzegovina's stone-walled restaurants serve lamb under a peka (iron bell) that justifies the entire trip.",
    7: "July hits 31°C and Mostar gets properly hot — the limestone amplifies the heat and the old town becomes a midday furnace. Morning and evening are magical, and the bridge diving competitions draw impressive crowds. The Kravice Waterfalls are a popular swimming escape from the city heat.",
    8: "August is Mostar's hottest month at 32°C and the most crowded, with day-trippers from the Dalmatian coast flooding the narrow lanes. The heat is intense but the early morning light on the bridge is extraordinary. Evening dining along the Neretva, with the bridge illuminated above, is unforgettable.",
    9: "September cools to 26°C and Mostar breathes again — crowds thin, the light turns golden, and the swimming in the Neretva is at its warmest. The wine harvest in Herzegovina is underway, and the roadside pomegranate sellers set up shop. This is the insider's month for the region.",
    10: "October drops to 18°C with autumn colour creeping into the surrounding hills and the old town returning to its peaceful rhythm. The cafes are unhurried, the ćevapi taste better without a queue, and the Herzegovina wine country is at harvest peak. Rain increases but the mild days outnumber the wet ones.",
    11: "November chills to 11°C with increasing rain and the tourist season definitively over. Mostar has a melancholic beauty in the rain — the bridge and minarets against grey skies are hauntingly photogenic. The war history museums and galleries deserve more time than summer visitors typically give them.",
    12: "December brings 6°C and a quiet festive season — Mostar's multi-faith heritage means modest celebrations across traditions. The old town is empty enough to hear your footsteps echo on the cobblestones, and the warmth of a Bosnian kafana (tavern) with rakija and grilled meats is the season's great comfort. Prices are at their lowest.",
  },
  'ba-sarajevo': {
    1: "Sarajevo in January averages -1°C with snow covering the Ottoman quarter's minarets and the surrounding mountains — the city hosted the 1984 Winter Olympics for good reason. Skiing at Jahorina and Bjelašnica is excellent and absurdly affordable by Alpine standards. The Baščaršija bazaar steams with ćevapi, burek, and Bosnian coffee in tiny copper džezvas.",
    2: "February is the coldest month at -2°C with reliable snow and the ski resorts in peak condition. MESS Theatre Festival adds cultural weight to the indoor season, and the city's cafe culture — arguably the Balkans' finest — is at its most atmospheric. The bobsled track on Trebević mountain is a haunting Winter Olympics relic.",
    3: "March brings the thaw at 5°C with spring tentatively arriving and the Miljacka River running high with snowmelt. Nowruz celebrations in the Bosniak community add colour, and the city's complex history is best absorbed on walking tours as the weather improves. The first outdoor terraces open, defended by blankets and heaters.",
    4: "April warms to 12°C and Sarajevo's parks bloom — the city is beautiful in spring with magnolias and cherry blossoms softening the war-scarred facades. The Sarajevo Film Festival planning is underway and the cultural calendar picks up. Tunnel of Hope and the siege history museums are essential, uncomfortable visits.",
    5: "May hits 17°C and Sarajevo is at its most inviting — warm enough for long walks through the old town, cool enough for hiking up to the Yellow Fortress for panoramic views. The Vrelo Bosne spring park just outside the city is magical with its emerald pools. Cafe terraces along Ferhadija are packed from noon to midnight.",
    6: "June brings 21°C and long sunny days — the call to prayer echoing between mountains and church bells creates Sarajevo's unique soundtrack. Outdoor dining along the Miljacka is excellent, and the surrounding mountains offer accessible hiking. It's increasingly popular but still feels undiscovered compared to Croatian neighbours.",
    7: "July is warm at 24°C and the Sarajevo Film Festival (mid-August) anticipation builds. The city is at its liveliest, with outdoor events, concerts, and the Baščaršija buzzing until late. Day trips to Lukomir, Bosnia's highest and most isolated village, are spectacular in summer conditions.",
    8: "August peaks at 24°C with the Sarajevo Film Festival turning the city into a Balkan Sundance — outdoor screenings in the old town are atmospheric and accessible. The mountains offer escape from city heat, and the Sutjeska National Park's primeval forest is magnificent. Book ahead for festival weeks.",
    9: "September cools to 19°C and the post-festival calm descends — a lovely time to explore without crowds. The surrounding hills turn golden and the evening light on the Ottoman quarter is extraordinary. Bosnian plum season means šljivovica (plum brandy) production begins in earnest.",
    10: "October drops to 13°C with stunning autumn foliage on the surrounding mountains and the city's cultural season resuming after summer. The Baščaršija feels most local now, with university students and office workers reclaiming the cafes. Rain increases but the warm-toned city looks beautiful when wet.",
    11: "November chills to 6°C with fog settling in the valley and the first snow dusting the Olympic mountains. It's atmospheric and deeply affordable, with the kafana culture at its most authentic. Remembrance of the 1990s siege weighs heavier in the grey months — visit the museums with respect and time.",
    12: "December brings 1°C and snow to Sarajevo — the Ottoman quarter under white is genuinely enchanting, and the city's multi-faith identity means both Christmas and New Year's are celebrated. The ski resorts open and the slopes are often empty on weekdays. Warming up with a proper Bosnian coffee ceremony is non-negotiable.",
  },

  'bb-barbados': {
    1: "January is peak season — trade winds keep temps around 26–29°C while the rest of the Caribbean sweats. Beaches are pristine, rum punch flows freely, and the west coast is calm enough to snorkel right off the sand. Book early; this is when half of London relocates here.",
    2: "February stays dry and breezy at 26–29°C, and the island hits its social stride with the Holetown Festival celebrating Bajan heritage. Whale watching picks up as humpbacks pass through, and the surf on the east coast at Bathsheba starts pumping. Still peak season pricing, but worth every dollar.",
    3: "March closes out dry season beautifully — 27–30°C with minimal rain and the Oistins Fish Fry in full weekend swing. The east coast delivers world-class surfing at Soup Bowl while the west coast stays glassy for swimming. Spring breakers arrive but Barbados stays classier than Cancún.",
    4: "April straddles dry and wet with occasional brief showers and temps around 27–30°C. Crop Over rehearsals begin buzzing through the parishes, and hotel rates start their seasonal dip. The water visibility remains excellent for diving the Stavronikita wreck.",
    5: "May marks the official start of wet season, but showers are mostly brief afternoon affairs with 28–31°C temps. Crowds thin dramatically and rates drop — savvy travelers take note. The flying fish are running and you'll find them fried to perfection at every rum shop.",
    6: "June brings warmer 28–31°C days with increasing humidity and afternoon rain showers that clear quickly. Crop Over festival season kicks into gear with calypso tents and fêtes across the island. Green season rates make luxury properties suddenly accessible.",
    7: "July heats up to 28–31°C with regular afternoon showers, but Crop Over is now in full carnival mode and the energy is electric. Kadooment Day preparations dominate the social calendar. Hurricane season is technically on but Barbados sits far enough south to dodge most storms.",
    8: "August opens with Kadooment Day — the Grand Kadooment parade is one of the Caribbean's great spectacles, rivaling Trinidad Carnival. Temps hold at 28–31°C with periodic rain. If you're here for the party, book months ahead; if not, enjoy discounted rates the rest of the month.",
    9: "September is the wettest month with frequent heavy showers and 28–31°C heat, plus peak hurricane season anxiety. Hotel rates hit rock bottom and beaches are nearly empty. It's actually a great time for authentic Bajan experiences without the tourist veneer.",
    10: "October remains wet and warm at 27–31°C, with the tail end of hurricane season keeping some visitors away. The upside: you'll have Carlisle Bay's turtle swimming spots practically to yourself. Restaurant reservations are unnecessary and locals are at their most welcoming.",
    11: "November transitions back toward dry season with decreasing rainfall and pleasant 27–30°C temps. The food scene shines with Barbados Food & Rum Festival typically landing this month. Rates begin climbing as the snowbird migration starts.",
    12: "December brings dry, breezy perfection at 26–29°C and the island sparkles for the holidays. Bajans go all out for Christmas with elaborate home decorations and jug-jug on every table. Prime season pricing returns with a vengeance — book by summer or pay the premium.",
  },

  'bd-coxs': {
    1: "January is ideal for Cox's Bazar — dry, sunny, and around 20–26°C with calm seas perfect for the world's longest natural beach. The Sundarbans are accessible by boat with excellent wildlife spotting as water levels recede. Spotted deer and if you're extraordinarily lucky, Bengal tigers emerge near the riverbanks.",
    2: "February continues the dry season sweet spot at 21–28°C with low humidity and clear skies over the Bay of Bengal. The Sundarbans mangrove channels are at their most navigable, and migratory birds fill the canopy. Cox's Bazar is busy with domestic tourists but the 120km beach absorbs crowds easily.",
    3: "March warms to 24–31°C and remains dry, making it the last comfortable window before the heat ramps up. Fishermen bring in massive hauls and the seafood in Cox's Bazar is at its freshest and cheapest. Sundarbans trips become hotter but wildlife concentrates around shrinking water sources.",
    4: "April is brutally hot at 27–34°C with rising humidity foreshadowing the monsoon. Nor'westers — sudden violent thunderstorms — can roll in without warning. The Sundarbans get steamy and mosquito-heavy; only the committed venture in.",
    5: "May cranks the heat to 28–34°C as pre-monsoon humidity makes everything feel ten degrees hotter. Cyclone risk increases in the Bay of Bengal and the sea gets rough. Most tour operators wind down Sundarbans excursions. Not recommended unless you enjoy being perpetually damp.",
    6: "June unleashes the monsoon with torrential rain, 27–32°C temps, and seriously rough seas at Cox's Bazar. The Sundarbans flood and boat access becomes unpredictable. On the bright side, the landscape turns impossibly green and you'll have hotels at a fraction of peak rates.",
    7: "July is monsoon at its most dramatic — 26–31°C with relentless rain and swollen rivers making the Sundarbans largely inaccessible. Cox's Bazar beach is atmospheric but swimming is dangerous due to strong currents. Budget travelers who don't mind getting soaked find absurdly cheap accommodation.",
    8: "August continues the deluge with 26–32°C temps and flooding common across low-lying areas. The Sundarbans are waterlogged and boat tours are suspended by most operators. Cox's Bazar sees dramatic waves that attract a handful of adventurous surfers.",
    9: "September remains solidly monsoon with heavy rainfall and 27–32°C temps, though frequency begins tapering toward month's end. The seas remain rough and the Sundarbans are still largely off-limits. Patience — the payoff is coming.",
    10: "October sees the monsoon retreating with decreasing rainfall and 26–31°C temps, though the occasional cyclone can still form. The Sundarbans begin draining and early-season visitors get lush, uncrowded forests. Cox's Bazar beach starts looking inviting again.",
    11: "November is gorgeous — dry, mild 22–29°C weather returns and the tourist season kicks off. Cox's Bazar fills with domestic holidaymakers and the beach comes alive with seafood stalls and horse rides. The Sundarbans reopen properly with good wildlife spotting as vegetation thins.",
    12: "December delivers the best conditions of the year — 19–26°C, bone-dry, and pleasantly cool by Bengali standards. The Sundarbans are prime for multi-day boat trips with excellent visibility into the mangrove forest. Cox's Bazar is at peak buzz; arrive midweek to dodge the weekend crowds.",
  },

  'bd-dhaka': {
    1: "January is Dhaka at its most bearable — cool, dry mornings around 12–25°C and smog levels at their lowest. Old Dhaka's chaotic Buriganga riverfront is actually enjoyable, and the street food scene from Shakhari Bazar to Chawk Bazar is magnificent. This is when you tackle the city.",
    2: "February warms slightly to 15–28°C while staying dry and pleasant, making it ideal for exploring Lalbagh Fort and Ahsan Manzil. Spring brings jacaranda and shimul flowers to the city's few green spaces. The Bengali New Year preparations start buzzing through the old quarters.",
    3: "March sees temperatures climbing to 20–33°C with increasing humidity as summer approaches. Pohela Falgun spring festival adds color to the streets. Still manageable for sightseeing but afternoons get sweaty — schedule rickshaw rides for mornings.",
    4: "April is Pohela Boishakh territory — Bengali New Year on April 14 transforms Dhaka into a riotous celebration of color, music, and street food. But at 25–35°C with building humidity and sudden nor'wester storms, the heat is relentless. Come for the festival, retreat to AC between events.",
    5: "May is pre-monsoon purgatory — 26–35°C with stifling humidity and frequent thunderstorms that turn Dhaka's already chaotic streets into rivers. Power outages are common. Unless you have specific business here, this is not the month.",
    6: "June inaugurates the monsoon proper with 26–33°C temps and near-daily torrential downpours. Dhaka floods regularly and traffic — already legendarily bad — becomes apocalyptic. The mangoes, however, are extraordinary and worth the suffering.",
    7: "July is peak monsoon with 27–33°C heat and relentless rain making the city a challenging proposition. Waterlogging in low-lying neighborhoods is severe. The hilsa fish season peaks and every restaurant serves this beloved Bengali staple — the one genuine silver lining.",
    8: "August continues the monsoon drumbeat at 27–33°C with the city functioning in a state of organized chaos through the flooding. The national Mourning Day on August 15 is somber but culturally significant. Budget hotels drop rates but you get what you pay for in drainage.",
    9: "September starts easing the monsoon — rain decreases and temps hold at 27–33°C, though humidity remains punishing. Durga Puja preparations begin, adding energy to Hindu neighborhoods. The city starts to breathe again.",
    10: "October brings Durga Puja — Dhaka's Hindu community puts on a spectacular show with elaborate pandals and five days of celebration. Temps sit at 24–32°C with decreasing rain. This is when Dhaka starts becoming visitable again and the cultural calendar heats up.",
    11: "November is lovely — 19–29°C, dry, and the smog hasn't fully settled in yet. The winter wedding season begins, turning every weekend into a feast of Bengali cuisine and celebration. Sightseeing is comfortable and rickshaw rides through Old Dhaka are actually pleasant.",
    12: "December is prime Dhaka — cool, dry, 14–25°C, with short-sleeve days and light-jacket evenings. Victory Day on December 16 brings patriotic fervor. The street food is at its most enjoyable when you're not dripping sweat into your fuchka.",
  },

  'be-brussels': {
    1: "January in Brussels is grey, damp, and 1–6°C — but the post-holiday sales on Rue Neuve are spectacular and the museums are blissfully empty. Warm up with a bowl of waterzooi in a Grand Place bistro while rain drums the medieval windows. Belgian beer tastes better when it's miserable outside.",
    2: "February remains cold at 1–7°C with occasional snow dustings that make the Art Nouveau facades look magical. The Belgian carnival season hits with Binche's UNESCO-listed carnival featuring its iconic Gilles in their wax masks. Restaurant week deals make this the month to eat above your budget.",
    3: "March begins the thaw — 3–10°C with lengthening days and the first outdoor terraces opening optimistically. Daffodils carpet the Bois de la Cambre and the chocolate shops prep for Easter with window displays that are basically edible art. Hotel rates are still reasonable before spring tourism kicks in.",
    4: "April brings the Royal Greenhouses of Laeken opening for their brief annual window — a must-see Art Nouveau wonderland. Temps climb to 5–14°C with a mix of sun and spring showers. The city's many parks burst into bloom and terrace culture begins in earnest.",
    5: "May is Brussels at its best — 9–18°C, longer evenings, and the Iris Festival opens up normally closed heritage buildings. The EU Quarter empties on long weekends while the Marolles flea market thrives. Sidewalk frites and a gueuze in the sun: peak Belgian contentment.",
    6: "June delivers warm 12–21°C days perfect for cycling along the canal to the Atomium. Brussels Summer Festival begins loading the calendar with free concerts. The Grand Place flower carpet happens in even-numbered years and is worth planning around if the timing aligns.",
    7: "July peaks at 14–23°C with the longest days and Ommegang — the magnificent historical pageant in the Grand Place. Belgian National Day on July 21 brings fireworks and festivities. Summer terraces are packed and booking restaurant tables becomes actually necessary.",
    8: "August holds at 14–23°C and every other year the Grand Place Flower Carpet draws enormous crowds to see 600,000 begonias arranged in intricate patterns. Many locals flee to the coast, leaving the city pleasantly navigable. This is when Brussels feels like a secret.",
    9: "September is gorgeous — 11–20°C with golden light on the Grand Place and Brussels Design September taking over galleries and warehouses. The comic book festival celebrates Belgium's greatest cultural export after beer. Hotel rates dip as summer crowds disperse.",
    10: "October cools to 7–15°C with autumn colors transforming the Sonian Forest on the city's doorstep into a fairytale. Restaurant season returns with game menus featuring wild boar and venison from the Ardennes. The Belgian film festival adds cultural heft.",
    11: "November descends into grey at 4–10°C with rain becoming a daily companion. But the Christmas markets begin setting up around the Bourse, and the first speculoos and glühwein vendors appear. Museums launch their winter exhibitions and become welcome refuges.",
    12: "December transforms Brussels into a winter wonderland — Plaisirs d'Hiver stretches from the Grand Place to Place Sainte-Catherine with Christmas markets, an ice rink, and a ferris wheel. Temps hover at 2–7°C. The chocolate shops reach peak excellence for gift-giving season.",
  },

  'be-wallonia': {
    1: "January in the Ardennes means proper winter — temps around -2 to 4°C with snow cover in the higher elevations around Spa and the Hautes Fagnes moorland. Cross-country skiing and snowshoeing are on, and the region's abbey beers taste even better by a roaring fire. Quiet, atmospheric, and affordable.",
    2: "February stays cold at -1 to 5°C with the most reliable snow conditions in the Ardennes for winter sports. Carnival season erupts across Wallonia with each town having its own gloriously weird traditions. The Carnival of Binche on the border with Flanders is a UNESCO treasure.",
    3: "March sees the slow thaw at 1–9°C with snowdrops and crocuses pushing through in the river valleys. The Meuse Valley towns start opening their terraces and the first kayaking operators test the waters. Bastogne's WWII history sites are uncrowded and deeply moving.",
    4: "April warms to 4–13°C with wildflowers carpeting the Ardennes forests and the Amblève and Lesse rivers reaching ideal levels for kayaking. The region's many châteaux open their gardens and the hiking trails dry out enough for comfortable walking. Spring in Wallonia is criminally underrated.",
    5: "May is stunning — 8–17°C with the Ardennes at peak green and the famous Caves of Han fully operational. The Dinant citadel overlooking the Meuse is spectacular in spring light. Festival season begins in Namur and Liège with concerts in medieval courtyards.",
    6: "June brings long, warm days at 11–20°C ideal for the Ardennes' extensive hiking and mountain biking networks. The Lesse River is perfect for multi-hour kayaking trips past cliff faces and castles. Trappist beer pilgrimages to Orval and Chimay are best now when the drive is gorgeous.",
    7: "July peaks at 13–23°C and the Ardennes becomes Belgium's outdoor playground — kayaking, rock climbing, caving, and hiking through ancient beech forests. The Francofolies music festival rocks Spa. This is when Wallonia earns its keep as one of Europe's most underrated summer destinations.",
    8: "August holds at 13–22°C with river levels still good for water activities and the forests providing cool canopy for hiking. The Namur International Festival of Folklore brings global culture to the Meuse Valley. Belgian families flood the region so book gîtes well ahead.",
    9: "September is magical — 10–19°C with the first autumn colors touching the Ardennes canopy and summer crowds vanishing overnight. The hunting season opens and restaurant menus fill with game, wild mushrooms, and local cheeses. This might be Wallonia's best-kept secret month.",
    10: "October delivers peak autumn at 7–14°C with the Ardennes forests blazing in copper and gold. The Hautes Fagnes moorland turns russet and atmospheric. It's truffle season in some areas and the regional food festivals celebrate the harvest with Walloon enthusiasm.",
    11: "November turns cold and misty at 3–9°C with bare branches and the first frost on the Ardennes plateaus. Spa town wellness retreats come into their own — this is when you want thermal baths and a good book. The quietest month, but hauntingly beautiful.",
    12: "December brings Christmas magic to Wallonia's medieval towns — Durbuy, Bouillon, and Namur all host atmospheric markets. Temps drop to 0–5°C with snow possible in the Ardennes highlands. The abbey breweries release their Christmas ales and the entire region smells of pine and spice.",
  },

  'bf-burkinafaso': {
    1: "January is Burkina's sweet spot — dry season at its finest with 18–33°C temps, harmattan haze, and cool evenings perfect for outdoor concerts. FESPACO, Africa's biggest film festival, runs every odd year in Ouagadougou and is electrifying. The Sahel landscapes are golden and atmospheric.",
    2: "February stays dry and warms to 20–36°C as the harmattan winds begin fading. The Nazinga Game Ranch in the south offers good elephant and warthog sightings with dry conditions concentrating wildlife around water holes. Cultural festivals dot the calendar across ethnic communities.",
    3: "March cranks up the heat to 24–39°C as the long dry season peaks. The landscapes are parched but photogenic, and the traditional mask ceremonies of the Bobo and Mossi peoples are extraordinary. Hydrate aggressively and pack sun protection that means business.",
    4: "April is scorching — 27–41°C with the hottest temps of the year and landscapes baked dry. The first tentative rains may arrive in the south by month's end. This is survival mode for travelers, though early mangoes start appearing in markets.",
    5: "May brings the first real rains to southern Burkina with 26–39°C temps and dramatic thunderstorms that feel like divine intervention after the heat. The landscapes begin their remarkable green transformation. Roads to rural areas can become challenging.",
    6: "June marks proper wet season onset with 24–34°C temps and regular heavy downpours, especially in the southwest. The countryside turns lush but unpaved roads become problematic. Fewer tourists mean more authentic interactions in Ouagadougou's lively neighborhoods.",
    7: "July is full monsoon — 23–31°C with heavy, sustained rainfall and flooding risk on rural roads. The Sahel greens up dramatically and farming communities are at their busiest. Travel is challenging but the transformed landscape is genuinely stunning.",
    8: "August delivers peak rainfall with 23–30°C temps and the most consistent downpours. Many rural areas become inaccessible and even Ouagadougou can flood. The mangoes and papayas are extraordinary. Stick to cities if you visit.",
    9: "September remains very wet at 23–31°C though rainfall begins tapering in the north. The countryside is impossibly green — a completely different landscape from dry season. International Crafts Fair (SIAO) runs in even years and showcases stunning West African artisanry.",
    10: "October sees the rains retreating northward with 24–34°C temps and a patchwork of wet and dry conditions. The landscape transitions from green to gold in real-time. Cultural season begins ramping up with traditional harvest festivals.",
    11: "November is excellent — dry, warm at 21–36°C, and the harmattan hasn't yet turned the sky hazy. The Safari-style wildlife viewing at reserves like Nazinga improves as water sources shrink. Ouagadougou's nightlife scene, centered on live music, is among West Africa's best.",
    12: "December cools to 18–33°C with dry harmattan winds bringing Saharan dust and spectacular sunsets. The tourism season peaks around Christmas with international visitors joining locals at maquis restaurants and outdoor concerts. Cool evenings make sleeping without AC actually possible.",
  },

  'bg-blacksea': {
    1: "January on the Bulgarian Black Sea coast is cold and windswept — 0–6°C with grey skies and ghost-town resort vibes. Varna and Burgas have enough urban life to sustain a visit with excellent cheap seafood and museums. Hotel rates are rock bottom if atmosphere isn't your priority.",
    2: "February is similarly bleak at 0–7°C with the coast feeling like a different country from the summer party zone. The Varna archaeological museum is world-class and nearly empty. Trifon Zarezan wine festival celebrates the vine-pruning season with tastings across the region.",
    3: "March begins a slow thaw to 3–10°C with the first hints of spring in Varna's Sea Garden. The coast remains quiet but restaurants start opening terraces on warmer days. It's an excellent time for the region's many ancient Thracian sites without summer crowds.",
    4: "April warms to 8–16°C with wildflowers carpeting the coastal cliffs and the first brave swimmers testing the 10°C water. Nessebar's UNESCO old town is gorgeous without summer congestion. Birdwatching along the Via Pontica migration route is spectacular with thousands of raptors and storks.",
    5: "May is lovely — 13–22°C with the sea warming to 15–17°C for the bold, and the coastal towns coming alive without July's crush. The archaeological sites at Sozopol and Nessebar are at their most pleasant. Beach bars begin opening and the vibe shifts from sleepy to anticipatory.",
    6: "June kicks off proper beach season with 18–27°C air and 20–22°C sea temperatures that are genuinely swimmable. The coast buzzes with early-season energy at a fraction of August's prices. Varna's summer festival program begins with concerts and theater along the waterfront.",
    7: "July is peak season — 21–30°C, sea at 23–25°C, and the coast is in full party mode from Golden Sands to Sunny Beach. Sozopol hosts the Apollonia Arts Festival in one of Bulgaria's most charming old towns. Book ahead; domestic and international tourists pack the coast.",
    8: "August maxes out at 21–31°C with the warmest sea temps around 25–26°C and crowds to match. Sunny Beach is a nonstop party while Sozopol and the smaller coves offer slightly more refined beach experiences. Morning sessions on the sand, afternoon naps, evening seafood — that's the rhythm.",
    9: "September is the savvy traveler's pick — still warm at 17–26°C with 22–24°C seas, dramatically fewer crowds, and lower prices. The light turns golden on Nessebar's medieval churches. Wine harvest season begins inland and the coastal restaurants serve the year's best produce.",
    10: "October cools to 12–19°C with the sea dropping to 17–19°C — swimmable on warm days. The coast quiets dramatically but the wine regions just inland are at their harvest peak. Autumn colors around the Strandzha Nature Park are unexpectedly beautiful.",
    11: "November settles into off-season at 6–13°C with grey skies and choppy seas. The coastal resorts shutter but Varna maintains year-round cultural life with its opera house and gallery scene. Fresh Black Sea turbot and bluefish are in season and absurdly cheap.",
    12: "December is cold at 2–8°C with occasional snow and a melancholic beauty to the empty beaches. Varna's Christmas market adds warmth to the Sea Garden. This is when you appreciate the Black Sea coast for its Ottoman-era architecture and cheap winter dining rather than its sand.",
  },

  'bg-sofia': {
    1: "January is Sofia's coldest month — -4 to 3°C with snow on Vitosha Mountain creating a ski resort literally on the city limits. The thermal mineral baths downtown steam in the freezing air and the city's buzzing restaurant scene focuses on hearty Bulgarian comfort food. Budget-friendly and atmospheric.",
    2: "February stays cold at -3 to 5°C with Vitosha still offering solid skiing and snowboarding just 30 minutes from the center. Kukeri festival brings elaborate costumed processions to villages near Sofia — one of Europe's most visually striking winter traditions. Hot wine and banitsa are your best friends.",
    3: "March thaws slowly to 0–11°C with snowdrops in Borisova Gradina park and the first café terraces testing the waters. Baba Marta on March 1 sees everyone exchanging red-and-white martenitsi bracelets for luck. Vitosha transitions from ski to early hiking season.",
    4: "April springs to life at 5–16°C with cherry blossoms around the Alexander Nevsky Cathedral and the hiking trails on Vitosha drying out. The Rila Monastery day trip is spectacular with wildflowers lining the mountain road. Sofia's craft beer scene is booming and bars multiply.",
    5: "May is ideal — 10–22°C with long evenings, outdoor dining in full swing, and the entire city feeling energized. The Seven Rila Lakes hike opens up and is absolutely magnificent. Sofia's parks fill with picnickers and the street art scene in Kapana adds new installations.",
    6: "June delivers warm 14–26°C days perfect for combining urban culture with mountain escapes. The Sofia Film Fest brings international cinema and Vitosha's alpine meadows burst with wildflowers. The city's communist architecture becomes oddly photogenic in golden summer light.",
    7: "July peaks at 16–29°C with afternoon thunderstorms rolling off the mountains. Vitosha offers excellent high-altitude hiking with panoramic views of the Thracian Plain. Sofia's nightlife extends into outdoor clubs and rooftop bars. The city empties somewhat as Bulgarians head to the coast.",
    8: "August holds at 16–30°C and Sofia is at its quietest as locals vacation on the Black Sea coast. This means easier restaurant bookings and the city's museums to yourself. The mineral springs park downtown is perfect for cooling off between gallery visits.",
    9: "September is gorgeous — 12–25°C with golden light and the grape harvest in full swing at wineries within an hour of the city. The cultural season opens with a packed schedule at the National Palace of Culture. The Rila Mountains are spectacular with early autumn colors.",
    10: "October brings peak autumn to Sofia at 7–18°C with Borisova Gradina park ablaze in yellows and reds. The Vitosha ridgeline gets its first dustings of snow while the city below enjoys mild days. Wine festivals celebrate the Bulgarian vintage across the region.",
    11: "November turns grey and cold at 2–10°C with the first proper snow possible on Vitosha. The city turns inward to its excellent café culture, wine bars, and hearty tavern (mehana) dining. Cultural programming intensifies with theater and music filling the National Palace.",
    12: "December brings Christmas markets to Sofia's center with 0–5°C temps and festive illuminations around the Serdica ruins. Vitosha ski season opens with snow typically reliable by mid-month. Bulgarian Christmas traditions blend Orthodox customs with pagan Kukeri energy.",
  },

  'bh-bahrain': {
    1: "January is Bahrain's coolest month at 14–20°C — practically sweater weather by Gulf standards — with clear skies and comfortable humidity. The Bahrain Grand Prix circuit hosts winter events and the old Muharraq quarter is perfect for walking without melting. Pearl diving heritage sites and the national museum are must-visits.",
    2: "February warms slightly to 14–22°C and remains dry and pleasant for exploring the ancient Dilmun burial mounds and Bahrain Fort. The Spring of Culture festival launches weeks of music, art, and theater. This is arguably Bahrain's most comfortable month.",
    3: "March approaches 16–26°C with the last truly comfortable weeks before the summer furnace ignites. The Bahrain International Garden Show celebrates the brief window when things actually grow outside. Manama's suq district is lively and the café culture is thriving.",
    4: "April heats up to 20–32°C as summer announces itself with authority. The Formula 1 Bahrain Grand Prix typically roars through the desert circuit under lights — one of the sport's most atmospheric races. Evening dining on the Adliya strip is still pleasant.",
    5: "May crosses into properly hot territory at 25–38°C with humidity climbing and outdoor activities shifting firmly to evenings and air-conditioned malls. The famous Tree of Life, standing alone in the desert for 400+ years, is best visited at dawn. Hotel rates drop as the summer exodus begins.",
    6: "June is serious heat — 27–40°C with high humidity making it feel even worse. This is indoor Bahrain: galleries, the national museum, and the excellent dining scene in Adliya and Juffair. The island's liberal attitude by Gulf standards means you can pair sightseeing with a cold beer.",
    7: "July hits 29–42°C with humidity that could poach an egg. Even locals limit outdoor time to dawn and dusk. The water parks and indoor attractions earn their keep. Pearl diving demonstration trips still run at dawn for the hardy.",
    8: "August matches July's ferocity at 29–42°C and is the least touristic month. Hotel rates are at their lowest and the dining scene doesn't take summer off. Bahrain's position as the Gulf's most laid-back destination shines when you're mostly indoors anyway.",
    9: "September remains brutal at 27–39°C with humidity still oppressive, but the very late month starts hinting at relief. Bahrain National Day preparations begin. The souq shopping for pearls and gold is year-round but you'll negotiate better in the quiet months.",
    10: "October gradually cools to 24–35°C with humidity dropping and outdoor dining becoming possible again by evening. The cultural calendar begins filling up and the waterfront corniche becomes walkable. This is when Bahrain wakes up from its summer hibernation.",
    11: "November is delightful at 20–29°C with low humidity and clear skies returning. The Bahrain International Airshow (odd years) is a massive regional draw. The ancient Dilmun sites, dhow harbor, and Muharraq's pearl trail are all comfortable to explore again.",
    12: "December is peak season — 16–23°C with perfect weather for the Bahrain National Day celebrations on December 16-17 and the festive season. The island's compact size means you can do ancient ruins, modern art, traditional suqs, and beachfront dining in a single day.",
  },

  'bi-burundi': {
    1: "January sits in the heart of the wet season with 20–28°C temps and regular heavy afternoon downpours. Lake Tanganyika — the world's second-deepest — stays warm for swimming near Bujumbura. The lush green hillsides are stunning but muddy roads make reaching the Kibira National Park chimpanzee habitat challenging.",
    2: "February continues the rains at 20–28°C with the countryside at maximum green intensity. The drumming traditions of the Royal Drummers of Burundi can be experienced year-round but feel especially powerful echoing through rain-washed hills. Travel requires patience and 4WD.",
    3: "March remains wet at 19–28°C though brief dry spells become more frequent. The Rusizi National Park near Bujumbura offers hippo and crocodile watching without venturing far from the capital. Bujumbura's lakeside restaurants serve excellent tilapia and Primus beer.",
    4: "April is the wettest month with 19–27°C temps and near-daily heavy rain. Road conditions deteriorate significantly outside major routes. This is when Burundi's famously terraced hillsides look most dramatic — every shade of green imaginable against red laterite soil.",
    5: "May transitions toward dry season with 19–28°C and decreasing rainfall, though showers persist. The tea plantations around Teza are brilliantly green and the source of the Nile at Rutovu becomes more accessible. Tourism infrastructure is minimal but improving.",
    6: "June ushers in the long dry season with 18–28°C, dropping humidity, and increasingly clear skies. Lake Tanganyika is perfect for swimming and sunset watching from Bujumbura's beach. Chimpanzee tracking in Kibira becomes more feasible as trails dry out.",
    7: "July is peak dry season — 17–27°C with virtually no rain and cool, pleasant evenings. The Karera Waterfalls are accessible and magnificent, and the drive through the mountainous interior reveals Burundi's jaw-dropping landscape of terraced hills. The best month to visit, period.",
    8: "August continues dry and pleasant at 18–28°C with excellent conditions across the country. The source of the southernmost headwater of the Nile near Rutovu is a worthwhile pilgrimage. Bujumbura's cultural scene is modest but genuine — live drumming performances are unforgettable.",
    9: "September starts warming to 19–29°C as the dry season nears its end. The landscapes take on a golden, dry-season hue and wildlife viewing improves as animals concentrate near water. Lake Tanganyika sunsets remain spectacular.",
    10: "October brings the short rains — 19–28°C with afternoon showers returning but not yet dominating. The transition creates dramatic skies and the first green shoots appear on the hillsides. Still very manageable for travel.",
    11: "November ramps up the wet season with 19–27°C temps and frequent heavy downpours. The Rusizi delta floods, attracting waterbirds in enormous numbers. Roads become slippery but the dramatic weather adds atmosphere to Bujumbura's lakeside scene.",
    12: "December is solidly wet at 19–27°C with regular rain but typically some dry windows each day. Lake Tanganyika rises and the surrounding hills are impossibly lush. The Christmas period sees Burundi's strong drumming tradition featured in special cultural performances.",
  },

  'bj-benin': {
    1: "January brings the harmattan to Benin — dry, dusty, and 22–34°C with hazy Saharan air filtering the sun. The Ganvié stilt village on Lake Nokoué is best visited now when water levels are stable and navigable. Voodoo Day on January 10 in Ouidah is one of West Africa's most extraordinary cultural events.",
    2: "February stays dry and hot at 24–35°C with the harmattan fading and clearer skies returning. The Abomey royal palaces — a UNESCO site — are comfortable to explore without the furnace-blast heat of later months. Cotonou's Dantokpa market is one of West Africa's largest and most vibrant.",
    3: "March heats up to 25–35°C as the humid air begins building before the rains. The Pendjari National Park in the north offers West Africa's best wildlife viewing with elephants, lions, and hippos concentrating around waterholes. Book a guide and go — this is Africa's most underrated safari.",
    4: "April brings the first rains to southern Benin with 25–33°C temps and building humidity. Pendjari remains excellent for wildlife as the north stays drier longer. The Vodoun festival circuit continues with ceremonies across the coast that few Western travelers ever witness.",
    5: "May kicks off the major wet season in the south at 24–32°C with heavy, frequent downpours. The north stays drier and Pendjari National Park has its last good wildlife month before access roads deteriorate. Grand-Popo's beaches remain swimmable between storms.",
    6: "June brings full wet season to the coast with 23–30°C and daily rain. Porto-Novo, the official capital, is lush and atmospheric in the rain. Road conditions between cities remain manageable on paved routes but village access gets difficult.",
    7: "July eases slightly — a short dry spell hits the southern coast at 23–28°C while the north gets its rainy season. This coastal break makes beach visits to Grand-Popo viable. The Gèlèdé masked dances of the Yoruba community are UNESCO-listed and mesmerizing.",
    8: "August continues the southern coast's relative dry spell at 23–28°C while the north is soaked. This quirk of Benin's climate makes it a surprisingly good beach month in the south. Cotonou's live music scene pumps with Afrobeat and traditional rhythms.",
    9: "September sees the rains return to the south with 24–30°C while the north begins drying. The entire country is brilliantly green. This transitional month can go either way — pack for both sun and deluge.",
    10: "October is the last wet month with 24–32°C temps and the heaviest rains of the second rainy season in the south. Pendjari access remains difficult. The upside: Benin's renowned bronze-casting artisans in Abomey are always working and welcome visitors.",
    11: "November dries out nicely at 24–34°C with the rains departing and the landscapes still lush from the wet season. Pendjari National Park reopens for wildlife viewing as roads dry. The Vodoun culture circuit along the coast becomes comfortable to explore.",
    12: "December is prime Benin — dry, 22–33°C, with harmattan coolness in the evenings and the tourism season in full swing. The Route des Esclaves in Ouidah is haunting and essential. The lead-up to January's Voodoo Day begins building energy across the animist communities.",
  },

  'bm-bermuda': {
    1: "January is Bermuda's coolest month at 15–20°C with water temps around 18°C — swimmable for the brave but better for coastal walks along the Railway Trail. The pink sand beaches are hauntingly beautiful without summer crowds. Hotel rates drop significantly and the local vibe takes over from the tourist polish.",
    2: "February holds at 15–20°C with occasional rain and the island settling into its quietest rhythm. The Bermuda Festival of the Performing Arts brings world-class theater and music to this tiny mid-Atlantic speck. A Dark 'n' Stormy at a harbor pub is the correct move.",
    3: "March begins warming to 16–21°C with spring flowers erupting across the island's manicured gardens. The Bermuda Goodwill Tournament brings international golf stars. Whale watching starts as humpbacks migrate north past the island — boat tours depart from Hamilton.",
    4: "April is gorgeous — 17–23°C with azaleas and Easter lilies in full bloom and the Ag Show celebrating Bermuda's agricultural heritage. The water warms to 19–20°C and the first snorkelers appear at Church Bay. Peppercorn Ceremony in St. George's is delightfully quirky.",
    5: "May sees temperatures climb to 20–26°C with Bermuda Day on the 24th bringing a marathon, parade, and the unofficial start of swimming season. The water hits 21–22°C and the island's stunning coves start earning their keep. Shoulder season rates apply for another few weeks.",
    6: "June kicks off peak season proper — 22–29°C with 24°C water and the reefs buzzing with tropical fish. The Newport-Bermuda yacht race brings sailing culture to the Royal Naval Dockyard. The crystal caves and snorkeling at Tobacco Bay are at their best.",
    7: "July peaks at 24–31°C with the warmest water temps around 27°C and the island in full summer mode. Cup Match cricket holiday is Bermuda's biggest party — two days of cricket, crown-and-anchor gambling, and serious festivity. Book far ahead for this one.",
    8: "August holds at 25–31°C with the warmest, calmest seas perfect for diving the many shipwrecks that line Bermuda's treacherous reef. Hurricane season is the caveat — late August through October carries real risk. The pink beaches are at their most photogenic.",
    9: "September stays warm at 24–30°C with 27°C water but hurricane season is at its peak. The island can take direct hits, so travel insurance is mandatory. On calm days, the diving and snorkeling are extraordinary with summer-warm water and slightly fewer crowds.",
    10: "October cools to 21–27°C with hurricane risk persisting through mid-month before tapering. The Bermuda International Film Festival often lands this month. Fall colors aren't really a thing on a subtropical island but the quality of light becomes magical.",
    11: "November transitions at 19–24°C with the storm season ending and a sense of relief settling over the island. The World Rugby Classic brings international teams for a week of rugby and socializing. Water drops to 22°C but remains swimmable.",
    12: "December cools to 17–22°C with festive lights adorning Hamilton's Front Street and the iconic Bermuda Christmas Boat Parade lighting up the harbor. Santa arrives by boat, naturally. Low-season rates return and the island's genuine charm comes through without the summer hustle.",
  },

  'bn-brunei': {
    1: "January is wet season in Brunei — 24–31°C with heavy tropical downpours, often dramatic afternoon thunderstorms that clear by evening. The Kampong Ayer water village, the world's largest, is best explored by water taxi between storms. Ulu Temburong National Park's canopy walkway is atmospheric in the mist.",
    2: "February continues the wet pattern at 24–31°C, the peak of the northeast monsoon. The rain feeds Brunei's spectacular primary rainforest — some of Borneo's most pristine. The Omar Ali Saifuddien Mosque gleams against grey skies. Brunei's National Day on February 23 brings rare public festivity.",
    3: "March sees rainfall beginning to ease at 24–32°C while humidity remains high. The Ulu Temburong rainforest is magnificent with swollen rivers and waterfalls at full force. Brunei's curious oil wealth is on display at the Royal Regalia Museum — gold, diamonds, and excess.",
    4: "April transitions toward drier weather at 24–33°C though showers remain frequent. Ramadan often falls around this period, adding cultural depth to any visit — the nightly pasar malam night markets are extraordinary. The Brunei River proboscis monkey tours are excellent.",
    5: "May dries somewhat at 24–33°C with decreasing rainfall and comfortable morning hours for exploring the capital's gilded mosques. The Temburong district's longhouse communities welcome visitors for authentic Iban cultural experiences. Brunei's food scene punches above its tiny weight class.",
    6: "June marks the start of the driest period at 24–33°C with lower humidity and clearer skies. This is prime time for Ulu Temburong — the canopy walkway 60 meters above the forest floor offers views across unbroken Borneo rainforest. Proboscis monkeys are active in the cooler mornings.",
    7: "July continues the relatively dry stretch at 24–33°C, making it ideal for jungle trekking and river cruises to spot crocodiles and proboscis monkeys. The Empire Hotel's beach — Brunei's most luxurious — is at its best. The sultanate's quiet, conservative pace is its own attraction.",
    8: "August holds at 24–33°C with the driest conditions of the year and excellent visibility in the rainforest. The Tasek Merimbun black-water lake is perfect for kayaking. Brunei's zero-alcohol law means you'll appreciate the elaborate mocktail and tea culture.",
    9: "September stays relatively dry at 24–33°C before the wet season returns. The Belait district's oil wells and Seria's bizarre oil-field-meets-mosque landscape is uniquely Brunei. Night markets in Gadong serve some of Southeast Asia's best and cheapest satay.",
    10: "October sees rain returning at 24–32°C as the northeast monsoon builds. The countryside greens up rapidly and the rivers swell, making boat access to Temburong's interior easier. Hari Raya celebrations, if timed right, open private homes to visitors.",
    11: "November brings heavier rain at 24–31°C with the wet season establishing itself. The rainforest is at its most alive — leeches included. Brunei's remarkable Jame' Asr Hassanil Bolkiah Mosque's 29 golden domes are stunning against storm clouds.",
    12: "December is wet at 24–31°C with heavy rainfall and high humidity. The royal family's birthday celebrations on December 15 add spectacle to the capital. The water village takes on a special atmosphere in the rain, and the Brunei Museum offers refuge from the downpours.",
  },

  'bo-lapaz': {
    1: "January is wet season in La Paz — 3–14°C at 3,640m elevation with afternoon downpours and dramatic cloud formations over the bowl-shaped city. The Witches' Market on Calle Sagárnaga is mystical in the rain. Altitude hits hard; coca tea and slow pacing are non-negotiable for the first 48 hours.",
    2: "February continues wet at 3–13°C with the heaviest rainfall of the year turning La Paz's steep streets into rivers. Carnaval de Oruro — a UNESCO Masterpiece 3 hours south — is one of the continent's most spectacular festivals with elaborate diablada dancing. Worth the muddy roads.",
    3: "March sees the rains beginning to ease at 3–14°C with clearer days emerging. The Altiplano around Tiwanaku shows its ancient ruins against brooding skies. La Paz's Mercado Lanza is heaving with fresh highland produce and the street food is extraordinary.",
    4: "April transitions to dry season at 2–15°C with rapidly decreasing rainfall and crisp, clear mornings revealing the Illimani glacier towering over the city. The Death Road mountain bike descent is in prime condition. Trekking the Choro trail to the Yungas becomes feasible.",
    5: "May is excellent — cold at -1 to 15°C but dry with brilliant blue skies and the thinnest air you've ever breathed. The cholets — neo-Andean architecture in El Alto — are extraordinary to tour. The Altiplano sunsets paint Illimani in impossible pinks.",
    6: "June brings dry, cold conditions with -3 to 14°C and Aymara New Year (Willkakuti) on June 21 drawing thousands to Tiwanaku for the winter solstice sunrise. The cold is biting at altitude but the skies are crystalline. Layer up like you mean it.",
    7: "July is the coldest month at -5 to 14°C with frost on the Altiplano but bone-dry skies and brilliant sunshine. The views from the teleferico cable car system across La Paz are at their most spectacular. The Yungas road trips are in perfect condition.",
    8: "August stays dry and cold at -4 to 15°C with zero rain and the Festival of the Virgin of Urkupiña in Cochabamba (4 hours away) providing one of Bolivia's most colorful celebrations. Independence Day on August 6 brings festivities to every plaza.",
    9: "September warms slightly to -1 to 17°C with dry conditions holding and the first hints of warmth returning. The Altiplano begins its transition and the jacarandas in the Yungas start blooming. El Alto's Thursday and Sunday markets are among Latin America's largest.",
    10: "October is the last reliable dry month at 1–18°C before the rains return. The Choro Trek and Takesi Trek are in excellent condition. La Paz's cultural calendar picks up with contemporary art festivals and live music in Sopocachi bars.",
    11: "November sees the first rains returning at 2–17°C, typically as afternoon showers that build through the month. The Gran Poder festival rehearsals energize the city's Indigenous neighborhoods. The countryside greens up and Copacabana on Lake Titicaca is still accessible.",
    12: "December brings proper wet season at 3–15°C with regular downpours and slippery cobblestone streets. The Christmas Alasitas fair and Ekeko figurine market is uniquely Bolivian. Lake Titicaca is at its most moody and dramatic. Budget extra time for every journey.",
  },

  'bo-uyuni': {
    1: "January floods the Salar de Uyuni with 5–15cm of water, creating the world's largest mirror at 5–18°C. The reflection photos are otherworldly — Uyuni's wet season is actually its most photogenic. Tours run but stick to the edges; accessing Incahuasi Island may be impossible.",
    2: "February continues the mirror effect at 5–17°C with the most reliable reflections of the year. The shallow water perfectly mirrors clouds and sky, creating that impossible horizon-melting effect plastered on every travel Instagram. Roads to Uyuni from Potosí can flood — fly from La Paz if possible.",
    3: "March still delivers mirror reflections at 4–17°C though water levels begin receding. The flamingo populations at Laguna Colorada and Laguna Verde in the Eduardo Avaroa Reserve are at their most spectacular. The 3-day jeep tour through the Southwest is rough but unforgettable.",
    4: "April transitions as water evaporates at 0–17°C, creating a patchwork of mirror and dry sections. The hexagonal salt patterns begin emerging from receding water. This shoulder season offers both experiences — reflection shots and the classic cracked-white-desert aesthetic.",
    5: "May is dry season onset at -5 to 16°C with the salt flat fully exposed and blazing white under intense high-altitude sun. The hexagonal patterns are razor-sharp and the perspective-trick photos (dinosaur toys, etc.) are at their best. Nights are brutally cold.",
    6: "June brings the coldest, driest conditions at -10 to 15°C with the salt flat a blinding white expanse under cobalt skies. The 3-day tour to the colored lagoons of the Southwest is in prime condition. Pack thermal everything — desert nights at 4,500m are no joke.",
    7: "July is peak dry season at -12 to 14°C with the coldest overnight temps but the clearest skies and most dramatic stargazing you'll ever experience. The salt flat is bone-dry and surreal. Tour 4x4s can cross the entire flat to Incahuasi Island's giant cacti.",
    8: "August holds dry at -10 to 16°C with conditions identical to July — perfect salt flats, freezing nights, dazzling days. The Train Cemetery outside Uyuni town is atmospheric at sunrise. Bolivian winter holidays bring domestic visitors but the salt flat absorbs crowds effortlessly.",
    9: "September warms slightly to -5 to 18°C while staying dry and clear. The salt flat is still perfectly white and tours are less crowded than July-August. The colored lagoons of the Reserva Eduardo Avaroa are at their most vivid against dry-season browns.",
    10: "October begins warming at -2 to 19°C with the first distant storm clouds hinting at the coming wet season. The salt flat remains dry and excellent for photography. Flamingo numbers start building at the altiplano lagoons as breeding season approaches.",
    11: "November is transition time — 0–20°C with occasional rain starting to pool on the salt flat. You might get the mirror, you might get the dry flat, or you might get an atmospheric hybrid. The unpredictability is part of the adventure.",
    12: "December brings the rains back at 3–18°C with water returning to the salar in earnest. The mirror effect starts building and by late December, early reflection shots are possible. Christmas in Uyuni town is modest but the locals are warm and the stargazing is still incredible.",
  },

  'br-amazon': {
    1: "January is peak wet season in the Amazon — 24–31°C with daily torrential rain swelling the rivers to their maximum. The flooded forest (igapó and várzea) opens up for canoe exploration through the treetops, and pink river dolphins are everywhere. Manaus is hot, humid, and buzzing.",
    2: "February continues the flood season at 24–31°C with the highest water levels of the year. This is actually spectacular — you'll canoe through the canopy, spot sloths at eye level, and the Meeting of the Waters where the Rio Negro and Solimões merge is at its most dramatic.",
    3: "March sees peak flooding at 24–31°C with the forest floor meters underwater. Jungle lodge experiences are water-based: piranha fishing, caiman spotting at night, and paddling through submerged forest. The humidity is relentless but so is the biodiversity.",
    4: "April begins the transition at 24–31°C with water levels peaking then slowly starting to recede. The aquatic Amazon is still in full effect with excellent dolphin watching. The Parintins Boi-Bumbá festival preparations begin in earnest for June.",
    5: "May sees waters receding at 24–31°C, revealing muddy riverbanks and concentrating wildlife along shrinking waterways. Fishing improves dramatically as fish are funneled into smaller channels. The bird life is extraordinary as wading species work the exposed shorelines.",
    6: "June begins the dry season at 24–32°C with water levels dropping and the famous Parintins Festival — the Amazon's answer to Carnival — drawing massive crowds. The forest floor becomes walkable for hiking and wildlife trails. This is transition territory at its most dynamic.",
    7: "July deepens the dry season at 24–33°C with rivers at their lowest and some tributaries becoming impassable. The beaches emerge along the Rio Negro — yes, freshwater Amazon beaches — and the Anavilhanas Archipelago reveals stunning sandbars. Prime hiking month.",
    8: "August is peak dry season at 24–34°C with the lowest water levels and the warmest temperatures. The caiman population concentrates in shrinking pools making for dramatic wildlife viewing. Smoke from agricultural burning can haze the skies. Trails are at their most accessible.",
    9: "September stays dry at 25–35°C and is the hottest month with some fire-season haze. The rivers are at their lowest revealing maximum beach area. The transition back to wet season begins late in the month with the first tentative showers.",
    10: "October sees the rains returning at 25–34°C with the forest beginning its cyclical transformation. Water levels start rising and the aquatic Amazon begins reasserting itself. The birding remains excellent with migratory species arriving from North America.",
    11: "November brings increasing rain at 25–33°C with the river levels rising noticeably. The forest transitions from walkable to water-based exploration. Pink dolphin activity increases as the flooding opens new territory for them to patrol.",
    12: "December is solidly wet at 24–32°C with daily downpours and rapidly rising rivers. The flooded forest canoe experience begins in earnest. Manaus celebrates a lively Christmas with the opera house hosting performances in the middle of the jungle.",
  },

  'br-iguazu': {
    1: "January is southern summer — hot and humid at 22–33°C with the falls at their most thunderous from seasonal rains. The spray from the Devil's Throat creates permanent rainbows and soaks you to the bone. The subtropical forest surrounding the falls is alive with toucans and coatis. Pack rain gear and embrace the drenching.",
    2: "February stays hot at 22–33°C with peak water flow making Iguazú Falls an absolute spectacle of raw power. The boat rides into the falls' base are operating and are exactly as insane as they sound. The Argentinian side's walkways offer better immersion while Brazil gives the panorama.",
    3: "March remains warm at 20–31°C with heavy water flow and fewer crowds than January as the school holidays end. The full moon walks on the Argentine side are magical and worth planning around. The Triple Frontier region — Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay — adds geopolitical intrigue.",
    4: "April cools to 16–27°C with autumn bringing perfect hiking temperatures and the subtropical forest displaying subtle color changes. Water flow remains strong and the falls are powerful without the extreme drenching of peak summer. One of the best months to visit.",
    5: "May is autumn at 13–23°C with comfortable temperatures, lower humidity, and the falls still flowing strongly. The reduced water volume actually reveals geological features hidden in summer's deluge. Crowds thin significantly and hotel rates drop.",
    6: "June cools to 11–21°C — Iguazú's driest month with reduced water flow but dramatically clearer views of the falls' incredible structure. The cool, dry air makes the extensive walkway system on both sides a pleasure. Budget travelers rejoice: this is off-season pricing.",
    7: "July is the coolest month at 10–21°C with the lowest rainfall but the falls remain impressive — there's no such thing as underwhelming at Iguazú. Winter school holidays bring Brazilian and Argentine families. The bird park on the Brazilian side is excellent year-round.",
    8: "August stays cool and dry at 11–23°C with water levels at their annual minimum. The falls are at their most photogenic with defined water curtains against dark basalt rather than a wall of white spray. Full moon walks continue on clear winter nights.",
    9: "September warms to 14–25°C with spring arriving and water levels beginning to rise from upstream rainfall. The subtropical forest erupts with wildflowers and the birdlife becomes extremely active. A sweet spot of good weather and building water flow.",
    10: "October hits 16–28°C with the falls regaining serious power as spring rains upstream feed the Iguazú River. The ipê trees bloom yellow and purple across the forest canopy. This is arguably the best month — strong falls, good weather, manageable crowds.",
    11: "November warms to 19–31°C with increasing rainfall and the falls roaring back to full power. The humidity returns but the spectacle intensifies. The Argentine side's San Martín Island hike reopens as water levels permit. Book walkway timeslots on busy weekends.",
    12: "December is peak summer at 21–33°C with school holidays driving up prices and crowds on both sides of the falls. The water volume is massive and the experience is absolutely thunderous. Go early morning on the Brazilian side for the best light and fewest tour groups.",
  },

  'br-noronha': {
    1: "January on Fernando de Noronha is warm and wet at 26–30°C with occasional tropical showers that pass quickly. The water visibility drops slightly but the sea is warm at 28°C and the spinner dolphins are performing their morning shows in the Baía dos Golfinhos. The visitor cap keeps crowds manageable regardless of season.",
    2: "February brings the most rain at 26–31°C but between showers the island is paradise — volcanic peaks, emerald water, and beaches regularly ranked among the world's best. The surf at Cacimba do Padre starts building. The environmental tax keeps backpackers at bay and conservation real.",
    3: "March sees heavy rainfall at 26–31°C but the swells arrive, making Cacimba do Padre one of the best surf breaks in the Atlantic. The lush vegetation peaks in intensity and the waterfalls on the main island actually flow. Diving visibility is lower but marine life is abundant.",
    4: "April transitions toward dry season at 26–31°C with decreasing rain and improving visibility. The humpback whale migration begins offshore. The Morro Dois Irmãos twin peaks reflect in calming seas and the snorkeling at Sueste Bay with sea turtles is outstanding.",
    5: "May dries significantly at 26–30°C with clearer skies and water visibility improving to 30m+. The sea calms on the interior (mar de dentro) side, opening up beaches that were pummeled by surf. Snorkeling at Porto de Santo Antônio reveals an underwater wonderland.",
    6: "June is dry season perfection — 25–29°C with minimal rain and water visibility hitting 40–50m. The diving around the islands is among the best in the Atlantic with reef sharks, turtles, and rays in crystalline water. The spinner dolphin bay viewpoint at dawn is pure magic.",
    7: "July continues dry season excellence at 24–28°C with the calmest seas and best visibility of the year. The trail to Atalaia Beach — limited to a handful of visitors per day — reveals tidal pools with nurse sharks and octopuses. Reserve your slot weeks ahead.",
    8: "August stays dry at 24–28°C with consistently excellent diving and snorkeling conditions. The water temperature drops to 26°C but visibility is staggering. Sea turtle nesting season begins on Leão Beach — one of the most moving wildlife spectacles in Brazil.",
    9: "September is gorgeous — 25–29°C, dry, and uncrowded with some of the year's best conditions for underwater activities. The plateau trail hikes offer dramatic volcanic landscape views. Sea turtles continue nesting and early hatchlings may emerge by month's end.",
    10: "October marks shoulder season at 26–30°C with the first light showers returning but conditions remaining excellent. Whale shark sightings peak during this period. The combination of improving surf and still-good visibility makes this a versatile month.",
    11: "November warms to 27–31°C with increasing rainfall but the surf season at Cacimba do Padre begins building again. Turtle hatchlings make their dramatic beach-to-sea runs. The island maintains its exclusive feel year-round — that visitor cap is a beautiful thing.",
    12: "December is warm and increasingly wet at 27–31°C with tropical showers becoming more frequent. Brazilian holiday season brings domestic tourists but the daily visitor limit prevents overcrowding. The spinner dolphins perform regardless of season, and the sunsets over Mar de Fora are end-of-year perfect.",
  },

  'br-rio': {
    1: "January is peak Rio summer — 25–35°C with pre-Carnival energy electrifying the city and beach culture at maximum intensity. Copacabana and Ipanema are packed from dawn till late, the caipirinhas flow freely, and the blocos (street parties) start building toward February's main event. Hot, humid, and gloriously alive.",
    2: "February is Carnival — nothing else matters. Rio at 25–35°C with the Sambadrome parades, hundreds of street blocos, and the entire city surrendering to samba. Book a year ahead and prepare for controlled chaos. It's expensive, sweaty, and utterly unforgettable.",
    3: "March cools slightly to 24–33°C with post-Carnival calm settling over the city. The beaches are less frenzied, hotel rates drop, and the carioca rhythm returns to its naturally laid-back state. This is excellent Rio without the Carnival premium.",
    4: "April brings pleasant 22–30°C weather with decreasing humidity and gorgeous golden light on Sugarloaf and Corcovado. The water is still warm enough for swimming and the Zona Sul neighborhood bar scene is at its most authentic without summer crowds. One of the best months.",
    5: "May cools to 20–27°C — Rio's autumn with crisp mornings and clear skies that make the Christ the Redeemer views spectacular. The cultural season opens with film festivals and gallery exhibitions. Beach culture shifts to afternoon-only but the seafood restaurants are year-round.",
    6: "June is Rio's winter — 18–25°C, which means locals wear parkas while tourists from cold climates swim happily. The Festa Junina celebrations bring forró dancing, bonfire parties, and mulled wine to neighborhoods across the city. Hotel rates are at their most reasonable.",
    7: "July hits 17–25°C with the driest conditions and clearest skies of the year. Sugarloaf, Corcovado, and Pedra da Gávea hiking offer unobstructed views across the city and coast. Winter school holidays bring Brazilian families to the attractions. Cool evening jazz in Lapa is perfect.",
    8: "August stays dry and mild at 18–26°C with Rio's cultural calendar in full swing. The international film festival brings global cinema to Cinelândia. Hang gliding from Pedra Bonita over São Conrado beach is at its best in the stable winter air.",
    9: "September warms to 19–26°C with spring arriving and the jacarandás preparing to bloom. Rio Marathon typically runs this month. The buildup to summer begins and the beach bar scene gets livelier on weekends.",
    10: "October delivers spring at 20–28°C with the jacarandá trees exploding in purple across the city — particularly stunning in Laranjeiras and Gávea. The warmth returns to the beaches and Carnival samba school rehearsals begin in the favela quadras. Get an early taste of what's coming.",
    11: "November heats up to 22–30°C with summer energy building. Black Consciousness Day on November 20 adds cultural depth. The beaches fill with pre-summer anticipation and the first Carnival blocos rehearsals spill into the streets.",
    12: "December is summer at 23–32°C, building toward the legendary New Year's Eve on Copacabana Beach — two million people in white, fireworks over the Atlantic, and offerings to Iemanjá at the water's edge. Book months ahead for Réveillon; it's one of the planet's greatest parties.",
  },

  'br-salvador': {
    1: "January is peak Salvador summer — 25–31°C with afternoon tropical showers and the Pelourinho historic center buzzing with live music every night. The beaches of Itapuã and Stella Maris are warm, the acarajé vendors are out in force, and the Afro-Brazilian drumming echoes through cobblestone streets.",
    2: "February brings Salvador's Carnival — the world's largest street party with over 2 million people dancing behind trios elétricos (massive sound trucks) through the streets. At 25–31°C, it's hot, crowded, and completely intoxicating. Blocks in Campo Grande and Barra are legendary.",
    3: "March sees the last of the summer heat at 25–31°C with Carnival energy fading into a more relaxed vibe. The Recôncavo region surrounding the Bay of All Saints is perfect for exploring Afro-Brazilian culture, quilombo communities, and colonial churches.",
    4: "April begins the rainier season at 24–30°C with tropical downpours becoming more frequent. The Pelourinho's pastel-colored colonial buildings gleam wet against dramatic skies. Candomblé temple ceremonies — the Afro-Brazilian spiritual tradition — continue year-round and are deeply moving.",
    5: "May is solidly rainy at 24–28°C with frequent heavy showers, though they rarely last all day. The indoor markets like Mercado Modelo are excellent for browsing local crafts. The moqueca de peixe (fish stew with dendê oil and coconut milk) tastes even better on a rainy day.",
    6: "June marks the wettest month at 23–27°C, but São João festivities light up the entire state with forró dancing, bonfires, and fireworks. The Festa Junina celebrations rival Carnival in local enthusiasm. Despite the rain, the cultural energy is electric.",
    7: "July sees rainfall decreasing at 22–27°C with winter bringing milder weather. The Festa de Santa Bárbara and Festa da Ribeira bring Candomblé-Catholic syncretism to spectacular public display. Salvador's unique religious culture is most visible during these winter festivals.",
    8: "August dries further at 22–27°C with pleasant conditions for exploring the Pelourinho without melting. The Festa de Iemanjá preparations begin building toward February. The Lower City (Cidade Baixa) elevator ride and Mercado Modelo are comfortable to explore.",
    9: "September is spring in Salvador — 23–28°C with decreasing rain and the Bahian coast heating up. The historic center's live music scene — pagode, axé, MPB — is world-class and accessible nightly. Whale watching for humpbacks is excellent off Praia do Forte, 80km north.",
    10: "October warms to 23–29°C with the beaches reclaiming their place as the center of social life. Chapada Diamantina National Park, 6 hours inland, is in prime hiking condition with waterfalls and tabletop mountains. Salvador's contemporary art scene is increasingly vibrant.",
    11: "November heats up to 24–30°C with the build toward summer palpable. The Lavagem do Bonfim preparations begin — the January procession is Salvador's most sacred event after Carnival. Beach culture intensifies and the acarajé ladies reclaim their corner stations.",
    12: "December is summer at 25–31°C with Reveillon (New Year's Eve) celebrations along the beaches turning Salvador white — the traditional color for the holiday. The year-end festas de largo circuit of public celebrations begins, running through February. It's one long party from here.",
  },

  'br-saopaulo': {
    1: "January is peak summer — 19–28°C with afternoon thunderstorms that are as dramatic as the city itself. The cultural institutions are open while half the city vacations on the coast. São Paulo's restaurant scene — the best in Latin America — operates at full tilt. The Villa-Lobos and Ibirapuera parks offer green relief.",
    2: "February brings Carnival, though São Paulo's version is more street-based and democratic than Rio's spectacle. At 20–29°C with rain, the blocos in Vila Madalena and Pinheiros are raucous and authentic. The Sambadrome exists here too — cheaper and less touristy than Rio's.",
    3: "March cools to 19–28°C with the rains easing and the city returning to its workaholic rhythm. The São Paulo Biennial (even years) preparations fill the Oscar Niemeyer pavilion in Ibirapuera Park. The Japanese neighborhood of Liberdade is atmospheric year-round.",
    4: "April arrives at 17–25°C with autumn bringing cooler evenings perfect for São Paulo's legendary bar culture. Restaurant Week deals make Michelin-starred dining accessible. The Pinacoteca and MASP art museums warrant full days. This is the city at its most civilized.",
    5: "May cools to 14–23°C with dry, crisp weather ideal for exploring the city's 15,000+ restaurants, 300+ theaters, and countless galleries. The Virada Cultural — a 24-hour citywide arts festival — is one of the world's great cultural events. Evenings call for a light jacket.",
    6: "June is winter approaching at 12–22°C with the driest conditions and clearest air, revealing skyline views normally hidden by haze. Festa Junina celebrations bring forró, quentão (spiced cachaça), and pamonha to squares across the city. São Paulo does cozy better than anyone expects.",
    7: "July is the coldest month at 11–21°C — cold by Brazilian standards, sending paulistanos into dramatic overcoat mode. The winter cultural season is packed with theater and music. The Mercado Municipal's mortadella sandwiches and tropical fruit tasting are essential regardless of weather.",
    8: "August stays dry and cool at 12–23°C with the city's cultural calendar in overdrive. The São Paulo International Film Festival is one of Latin America's most important. The Japanese, Italian, and Lebanese immigrant neighborhoods each offer culinary universes to explore.",
    9: "September begins warming to 14–25°C with jacarandás hinting at purple and the outdoor dining scene stirring back to life. The Formula 1 buzz builds toward the Brazilian Grand Prix at Interlagos (typically November). The Beco do Batman street art in Vila Madalena refreshes constantly.",
    10: "October is spring proper at 16–26°C with the first thunderstorms of the wet season and the city's parks bursting with subtropical flowers. São Paulo Fashion Week typically lands this month. The rooftop bar scene in Jardins comes alive as evenings warm up.",
    11: "November brings the Brazilian Grand Prix at Interlagos — the most passionate F1 crowd on the calendar. Temps hit 17–27°C with increasing afternoon rain. Consciência Negra Day adds cultural significance and the city's Afro-Brazilian communities celebrate with music and food.",
    12: "December heats to 19–28°C with summer energy and holiday fever. The Avenida Paulista Christmas lights draw millions, and the city's countless year-end confraternizações (office parties) fill every restaurant. New Year's Eve along Paulista Avenue is São Paulo's biggest street party.",
  },

  'bs-bahamas': {
    1: "January is peak Bahamas season — dry, sunny, and 18–25°C with crystal-clear water at 24°C. Nassau buzzes with cruise ships while the Out Islands (Exumas, Eleuthera, Harbour Island) offer serene pink and white sand perfection. The swimming pigs of Big Major Cay are best visited midweek.",
    2: "February continues peak conditions at 18–26°C with the Junkanoo parades still echoing and the deep-sea fishing heating up. The Exumas' Thunderball Grotto is sublime for snorkeling in the dry season calm. Hotel rates are at their highest but the weather justifies it.",
    3: "March brings spring break energy to Nassau and Paradise Island at 19–27°C, while the Out Islands remain blissfully tranquil. The Andros Barrier Reef — the third-largest in the world — is in perfect diving condition. The bone fishing flats of Andros are legendary.",
    4: "April warms to 21–28°C with spring break crowds thinning and the water temperature climbing to 26°C. The Eleuthera Pineapple Festival celebrates the island's heritage crop. This is shoulder season: great weather, lower rates, and the Bahamian pace at its most authentic.",
    5: "May transitions at 23–30°C with the first tropical showers arriving and the summer season approaching. Rates drop as the weather shifts. The blue holes of Andros and Dean's Blue Hole on Long Island are spectacular year-round but especially vivid in the softening spring light.",
    6: "June begins hurricane season but early June is typically calm at 24–31°C with the warmest, calmest waters. Goombay Summer festival kicks off in Nassau with Junkanoo-style celebrations every weekend. The diving visibility is excellent and the stingrays at Compass Cay are friendly.",
    7: "July is peak summer at 25–33°C with Junkanoo Summer adding weekly cultural celebrations. The Out Islands are quiet and magnificent, with pink sand beaches and bonefish flats mostly to yourself. Hurricane awareness is essential but statistically, July storms are rare.",
    8: "August is the hottest month at 25–34°C with the highest hurricane risk beginning to build. The Emancipation Day celebrations on the first Monday are culturally significant. If you're lucky with weather, this is the most affordable time for a genuine Bahamian experience.",
    9: "September is peak hurricane season at 25–33°C — travel insurance is absolutely mandatory. The upside: hotel rates crater and the few visitors who come get an authentic, uncrowded experience. The reef systems are thriving in the warm water.",
    10: "October maintains hurricane risk at 24–31°C though the threat diminishes through the month. The annual McLaren's Harbour Hermit Crab Races on Great Exuma are charmingly local. Water temps remain a balmy 28°C for snorkeling and diving.",
    11: "November sees hurricane season ending at 22–28°C with dry conditions returning and the winter tourism season beginning. The Bahamas International Film Festival in Nassau adds cultural depth. Water clarity improves as storm season passes.",
    12: "December is magical — 19–26°C, dry, festive, and the Junkanoo Boxing Day parade (December 26) is one of the Caribbean's most spectacular cultural celebrations. The Out Islands are peaceful holiday retreats and the water is crystalline. Peak rates return but Junkanoo is priceless.",
  },

  'bt-bhutan': {
    1: "January is Bhutan's coldest month — -3 to 12°C in the Paro Valley with snow dusting the high passes and the dzongs looking like medieval fantasies against white mountains. The skies are clear and the Himalayan panoramas are breathtaking. Few tourists means genuine interaction with Bhutanese culture.",
    2: "February remains cold at -2 to 13°C but the Punakha Tshechu festival brings masked dancers and the Black-Necked Crane Festival in Gangtey Valley celebrates the endangered cranes wintering in Bhutan. The ancient monasteries are atmospheric in the winter silence.",
    3: "March brings the first warmth at 2–16°C with rhododendrons beginning their legendary bloom across the hillsides. The Paro Tshechu — Bhutan's most famous festival with masked dances at the spectacular Paro Dzong — typically falls in March or April. Essential to witness.",
    4: "April is spring perfection — 5–20°C with rhododendrons blazing red and pink across the mountainsides and crystal-clear Himalayan views. The trekking season opens with routes to Tiger's Nest monastery at their most photogenic. This is Bhutan's postcard month.",
    5: "May warms to 10–23°C with lush green landscapes and the last reliable weeks before monsoon rains arrive. The rice paddies begin flooding and terracing creates hypnotic geometric patterns across the valleys. Pre-monsoon clouds add drama to the already dramatic terrain.",
    6: "June brings the monsoon at 15–25°C with heavy rainfall making trekking challenging but transforming Bhutan into an impossibly green jewel. The leeches come out in force on forest trails. Dzongs and monasteries make excellent rainy-day refuges. Visitor numbers plummet and rates drop.",
    7: "July is peak monsoon at 15–26°C with near-daily rain, mudslides occasionally closing mountain roads, and the full force of Himalayan weather on display. Mushroom season begins and the matsutake harvest is culturally significant. Only committed Bhutanophiles visit now.",
    8: "August continues the deluge at 15–26°C with the heaviest rainfall and the countryside at maximum lushness. The Haa Summer Festival celebrates highland nomadic culture with yak herders and traditional sports. Roads can be challenging but the landscapes are otherworldly.",
    9: "September sees the monsoon retreating at 12–24°C with improving conditions and the valleys turning golden with ripening rice. The Thimphu Tshechu — the capital's biggest festival — typically falls in September or October with elaborate masked dances. The crowds return but so does the sun.",
    10: "October is prime season — 5–20°C with clear skies, harvested rice terraces in golden tones, and the best trekking conditions. The Jambay Lhakhang Drup festival in Bumthang features the famous naked fire dance. Tiger's Nest is spectacular against autumn-blue skies.",
    11: "November brings crisp, cold conditions at 1–16°C with crystalline Himalayan views and the Black-Necked Cranes arriving in the Phobjikha Valley. The trekking season's final window offers uncrowded trails. Festival season winds down but Bhutanese hospitality doesn't.",
    12: "December is cold and quiet at -2 to 13°C with snow on the high passes and the shortest days. The Trongsa Tshechu and winter festivals keep the cultural calendar active. The clear winter sky makes for extraordinary mountain photography. Bhutan in winter is Bhutan at its most intimate.",
  },

  'bw-kalahari': {
    1: "January is peak summer in the Kalahari — 20–36°C with afternoon thunderstorms that transform the red desert into a sea of green grass and wildflowers. The Central Kalahari Game Reserve comes alive with calving season bringing zebra, wildebeest, and springbok foals — plus the predators they attract.",
    2: "February continues the green season at 20–35°C with the Kalahari at its most lush and photogenic. The salt pans of Makgadikgadi flood, attracting flamingos by the thousand. Chobe's elephants are dispersed across the floodplains. Game drive photography is spectacular with dramatic storm skies.",
    3: "March sees the rains beginning to taper at 18–34°C with the Kalahari still green but the wildlife starting to concentrate as water sources shrink. The Makgadikgadi zebra migration — one of Africa's least-known great migrations — is in motion. Nxai Pan is superb.",
    4: "April marks the transition to dry season at 14–32°C with rapidly greening giving way to golden grasslands. Game viewing improves daily as water holes become focal points. The Kalahari meerkats are at their most photogenic in the soft autumn light.",
    5: "May cools dramatically to 7–28°C with frost possible at night and perfect sunny days. The Central Kalahari's famous black-maned lions are easier to spot as vegetation dries. Chobe's riverfront starts concentrating elephant herds. This is when the Kalahari gets serious about safari.",
    6: "June brings winter — 3–25°C with cold nights and warm days under cloudless skies. The Makgadikgadi pans dry to blinding white expanses perfect for quad biking and surreal photography. Bushmen (San) cultural experiences in the Kalahari are among Africa's most authentic encounters.",
    7: "July is the coldest month at 2–24°C with frost on the Kalahari dunes at dawn and bone-dry conditions concentrating wildlife around permanent water. Chobe River game viewing is at its finest with hundreds of elephants drinking at sunset. Wrap up for dawn game drives.",
    8: "August stays dry at 4–27°C with the Kalahari at peak game-viewing as the last water sources draw massive herds. Chobe sees its most dramatic elephant concentrations — up to 100,000 along the river. The Makgadikgadi salt pans are surreal lunar landscapes.",
    9: "September warms to 9–32°C with the heat building and wildlife clinging to remaining water. Game viewing is outstanding but the afternoon heat can be brutal. Chobe's predator activity increases as prey concentrates. The Kalahari's leopard population becomes more visible.",
    10: "October is the hottest dry month at 14–36°C with scorching midday heat and desperate wildlife activity around water. The first thunderstorms tease late in the month. The Makgadikgadi begins its miraculous greening. Spring game viewing can be extraordinary if you handle the heat.",
    11: "November brings the first real rains at 16–34°C with the Kalahari beginning its annual transformation from brown to green. The zebra migration starts moving toward the pans. Calving season for impala and other antelope begins, drawing predators into action.",
    12: "December is hot and increasingly wet at 19–35°C with the Kalahari greening rapidly and summer bird migrants arriving from Europe and Central Asia. The breeding season for raptors and ground-nesting birds makes for dramatic birding. Christmas in a bush camp is pure magic.",
  },

  'bw-okavango': {
    1: "January is green season in the Okavango at 20–33°C with afternoon thunderstorms and the delta at its lowest water levels. Surprisingly, the game viewing is excellent as animals concentrate around remaining channels. Calving season brings baby impala, tsessebe, and wildebeest — plus hungry predators.",
    2: "February continues the green season at 19–33°C with lush landscapes and dramatic storm skies that make for extraordinary photography. The delta's resident wildlife is supplemented by migratory species. Rates drop significantly and the experience is intimate — you'll have the mokoro channels to yourself.",
    3: "March sees the Okavango at its driest paradox — 18–32°C with local rains but the annual flood from Angola hasn't arrived yet. The channels are low and game drives dominate over water activities. Birdlife is spectacular with breeding plumage on full display.",
    4: "April brings the first signs of the annual flood at 14–31°C — water from Angolan highlands starts trickling into the delta. The game viewing transitions as animals shift their patterns. Wild dog packs are denning and sightings improve dramatically.",
    5: "May sees the flood arriving in earnest at 8–28°C with water levels rising visibly day by day, transforming the landscape from dry savanna to water wonderland. The mokoro (dugout canoe) excursions begin and the delta starts becoming the Okavango. Spectacular transition month.",
    6: "June is the flood at its most dynamic — 5–25°C with the water spreading across the delta and the bush transforming into a watery maze of channels and islands. Mokoro trips through papyrus-lined waterways are peak Okavango. The cold mornings on boat cruises require serious layering.",
    7: "July is peak season — 4–25°C with the flood at or near maximum and the delta at its most spectacular. Water-based safari activities combine with excellent game drives on the islands. Elephant, buffalo, and predator sightings are daily occurrences. Book six months ahead minimum.",
    8: "August continues peak season at 6–27°C with the flood holding and the dry winter air providing crystal-clear visibility for game viewing. This is National Geographic Okavango — vast herds, hunting predators, and aquatic wilderness as far as you can see. Premium pricing applies.",
    9: "September warms to 11–32°C with the flood beginning to recede and wildlife concentrating along shrinking channels. The birding is extraordinary as wading species feast on stranded fish. Game drives improve as more land becomes accessible. Still peak season.",
    10: "October is hot at 15–36°C with the delta drying and game viewing at its most intense as animals crowd remaining water sources. The heat is significant but the wildlife encounters are unmatched. Spring migrants arrive and the birdlife reaches its annual peak.",
    11: "November brings the first rains at 18–34°C with dramatic thunderstorms and the delta beginning its dry-to-green transition. The resident herds are joined by newborn calves. Rates drop from peak season but the experience is superb. Lightning storms at sunset are unforgettable.",
    12: "December is green season proper at 19–33°C with regular rain greening the islands and the delta at its lowest water levels. The Christmas period sees a brief spike in visitors but the green season rates and lush landscapes make this a surprisingly good value month.",
  },

  'ci-ivorycoast': {
    1: "January is dry season in Abidjan — 25–33°C with harmattan haze from the Sahara giving the sky a milky quality. The Plateau business district and Treichville market are buzzing, and the lagoon-side restaurants of Cocody serve extraordinary attieké and grilled fish. A surprising cosmopolitan energy.",
    2: "February stays dry and hot at 26–34°C with the harmattan clearing to reveal blue skies. Abidjan's contemporary art scene — anchored by the Fondation Donwahi — is West Africa's most dynamic. The Basilica of Our Lady of Peace in Yamoussoukro is worth the 3-hour drive.",
    3: "March begins heating up at 26–34°C with humidity building before the rains. The Carnival of Bouaké brings elaborate floats and masked dancers from across the country. Abidjan's maquis (open-air restaurants) serve the best garba and alloco you'll ever taste.",
    4: "April brings the first heavy rains to southern Côte d'Ivoire at 25–33°C with dramatic thunderstorms announcing the wet season. The rainforest around Taï National Park — home to rare pygmy hippos and chimpanzees — is magnificent in the first rains. Roads become challenging.",
    5: "May is wet at 24–31°C with heavy, frequent rain transforming Abidjan's landscape. The Fête du Dipri in Gomon features one of West Africa's most extraordinary nocturnal rituals. The lagoon system around Grand-Bassam offers boat rides through mangrove forests.",
    6: "June brings the heaviest rains at 23–29°C with southern Côte d'Ivoire thoroughly soaked. Abidjan functions but flooding is common in low-lying areas. The Comoé National Park in the north remains drier and offers decent wildlife viewing.",
    7: "July sees a brief dry interlude in the south at 23–28°C — a quirk of equatorial weather that makes Abidjan suddenly pleasant. Grand-Bassam's colonial beach town, a UNESCO site, is perfect for weekend escapes. The cacao-growing regions in the interior are lush.",
    8: "August continues the short dry spell at 23–28°C in the south while the north gets its rainy season. Abidjan's cultural calendar picks up with the Anoumabo Arts Festival. The seafood at Assinie beach is extraordinary and the surf is reliable.",
    9: "September brings the second rainy season to the south at 24–30°C with renewed downpours. The country is at maximum green. Man's traditional stilt-dancing region in the west offers extraordinary cultural experiences when roads permit.",
    10: "October is the wettest month of the second rainy season at 24–31°C with heavy, persistent rain. Travel outside major routes requires serious planning. Abidjan's indoor cultural life — galleries, live music venues, restaurants — carries the month brilliantly.",
    11: "November sees the rains retreating at 25–32°C with the dry season approaching and a sense of relief. The Festival des Masques in Man showcases the sacred mask traditions of western Côte d'Ivoire. Road conditions improve and national parks begin reopening.",
    12: "December brings dry season back at 25–33°C with festive energy in Abidjan and harmattan coolness in the evenings. The Fêtes des Masques continue across different ethnic regions. Christmas celebrations blend French colonial tradition with Ivorian exuberance — réveillon dinners go all night.",
  },

  'ck-cook-islands': {
    1: "January is cyclone season on the Cook Islands — 25–30°C with heavy tropical humidity and the risk of serious storms, though direct hits are rare. Rarotonga's lagoon is warm at 28°C and the snorkeling is good between rain showers. The local vibe is distinctly Polynesian — unhurried, warm, and utterly charming.",
    2: "February continues the wet, humid pattern at 25–30°C with the highest rainfall and cyclone risk of the year. Aitutaki — the lagoon that makes postcards feel inadequate — is stunning even in the rain. Rates are at their lowest and the resorts are peaceful. Travel insurance covering cyclones is essential.",
    3: "March begins transitioning at 25–30°C with cyclone risk diminishing and rainfall starting to ease. The Te Maeva Nui constitution celebrations on Rarotonga bring traditional dance competitions that showcase Polynesian culture at its most vibrant. The interior cross-island trek is lush and muddy.",
    4: "April cools slightly to 24–29°C with drier conditions settling in and the lagoons reaching perfect clarity. The Vaka Eiva outrigger canoe festival celebrates the island's seafaring heritage. Aitutaki's One Foot Island is exactly as impossibly beautiful as the photos suggest.",
    5: "May enters the dry season at 23–28°C with comfortable humidity and excellent snorkeling conditions across the lagoon. The Saturday morning Punanga Nui market on Rarotonga is the social hub — coconut bread, fresh fish, and local crafts. Muri Beach lagoon is at its best.",
    6: "June is dry and pleasant at 22–27°C with the coolest, most comfortable conditions of the year. The coral reefs are teeming and visibility is outstanding for diving the outer reef passages. The lack of crowds means genuine interaction with Cook Islanders — among the Pacific's friendliest people.",
    7: "July is peak dry season — 21–26°C with minimal rain and the most pleasant weather. Humpback whale migration passes through and whale watching from Rarotonga and Aitutaki is increasingly popular. The island night cultural shows at resorts are a surprisingly authentic experience.",
    8: "August stays dry and mild at 21–26°C with whale watching at its peak and the lagoons in pristine condition. The round-Rarotonga road trip takes about 45 minutes but you should spend days stopping at every beach. Scooter rental is the way.",
    9: "September warms to 22–27°C with the dry season holding strong and spring energy building. The Tiare Flower Festival celebrates the Cook Islands' national flower with parades and competitions. The traditional medicine and healing practices of the islands are fascinating to explore.",
    10: "October begins the transition at 23–28°C with the first scattered showers returning but conditions still excellent. The water temperature rises to 25°C and the marine life responds. Aitutaki's lagoon is at its most vivid turquoise against the white sand motus.",
    11: "November warms to 24–29°C with humidity building and occasional tropical showers. The gardens and jungle interiors are lush and the waterfalls on Rarotonga flow properly. Pre-Christmas rates offer good value before the holiday rush.",
    12: "December brings festive warmth at 25–30°C with increasing rain and humidity. Christmas on the Cook Islands blends Polynesian tradition with colonial influences — the singing in village churches is extraordinary. The lagoon water hits 27°C and the snorkeling is warm and wonderful.",
  },
  'cl-atacama': {
    1: "January is peak summer in the driest desert on Earth — days hit 30°C but nights plunge below 10°C, so layer up for stargazing. The salt flats shimmer, flamingos crowd the altiplano lagoons, and this is prime time for the Valle de la Luna at sunset.",
    2: "February brings the rare 'invierno boliviano' — brief afternoon thunderstorms can paint the desert with wildflowers if you're lucky. Temps stay around 28°C by day, and the Tatio Geysers at dawn are worth every 4am alarm.",
    3: "March starts to cool slightly to 26°C days, and the last of the altiplanic storms may linger. Crowds thin after Carnival, making it a sweet spot for solitude among the salt flats and ancient petroglyphs.",
    4: "April ushers in autumn with crisp 22°C days and near-freezing nights that sharpen the already surreal stargazing. The ALMA observatory area is at its clearest, and tourist numbers drop noticeably.",
    5: "May is dry, clear, and cold — days around 18°C, nights well below zero. This is arguably the best month for astrophotography, with bone-dry skies and minimal light pollution.",
    6: "June means winter solstice and the coldest nights, dipping to -10°C, but daytime highs of 16°C under endless blue skies make exploring comfortable. San Pedro de Atacama is quiet and prices dip accordingly.",
    7: "July is frigid after dark but brilliantly sunny — expect 15°C days and the Milky Way in staggering detail overhead. Chilean school holidays bring a modest bump in domestic visitors, but nothing overwhelming.",
    8: "August remains cold and crystal-clear, with temps creeping back toward 18°C. The desert silence is profound, and this is a photographer's dream month for the surreal landscapes of the Salar de Atacama.",
    9: "September warms to 22°C and spring energy returns — wildflowers may appear in the foothills if winter rains cooperated. The shoulder season pricing is kind, and the geysers steam more dramatically in the still-cold mornings.",
    10: "October is a sweet spot: 25°C days, cool nights, and manageable crowds before the summer rush. The lagoons are full of birdlife and the Valle de la Muerte begs for a sandboarding session.",
    11: "November heats up to 28°C and the high season begins its slow ramp. Book Tatio Geyser tours early, and don't skip the lesser-known Piedras Rojas — the red rocks against turquoise water are absurd.",
    12: "December is full summer — 30°C days, blazing sun, and peak tourist season in full swing. Reservations at San Pedro's better restaurants fill fast, but the long daylight hours mean more time at the salt flats.",
  },
  'cl-easter': {
    1: "January is warm and humid at 27°C, peak summer on Rapa Nui with the longest daylight for exploring moai. The Tapati festival (late Jan–Feb) electrifies the island with traditional Polynesian competitions — book flights months ahead.",
    2: "February stays hot at 27°C and Tapati celebrations may spill into the month. Occasional tropical showers keep the volcanic slopes green, and the beaches at Anakena are genuinely swimmable.",
    3: "March begins the slow cool-down to 25°C with lighter crowds after summer. The ocean is still warm enough for diving around the moai underwater, and the sunset from Ahu Tahai is peak magic.",
    4: "April drops to 23°C with increasing chance of rain, but the island takes on a moody, photogenic quality. Fewer tourists mean you might have Rano Raraku's moai quarry entirely to yourself.",
    5: "May is shoulder season at 21°C — pack a rain jacket and enjoy rock-bottom prices for the handful of guesthouses. The rugged coastline is dramatic under stormy skies, and local fish stews hit differently in cooler weather.",
    6: "June is winter on Rapa Nui: 19°C, breezy, and the quietest month on the island. Some tours reduce schedules, but the moai don't close, and the solitude at Ahu Tongariki at sunrise is hauntingly beautiful.",
    7: "July stays cool at 18°C with reliable wind and occasional rain. The island's wild horses roam freely against grey-green landscapes, and this is the cheapest time to visit — if you can handle the isolation.",
    8: "August holds at 18°C and winter's grip keeps crowds minimal. The stars are remarkable from this mid-Pacific speck, and the local Polynesian cuisine — ceviche and umu earth-oven feasts — warms you from the inside.",
    9: "September marks the turn toward spring at 19°C, with wildflowers beginning to dot the volcanic craters. Visitor numbers tick up slightly and the diving visibility starts improving.",
    10: "October warms to 21°C and the island shakes off winter nicely. The restored moai at Ahu Akivi — the only ones facing the ocean — look particularly striking against spring skies.",
    11: "November is pleasant at 23°C with moderate crowds and warm enough seas for snorkeling. The birdlife around Motu Nui picks up, echoing the ancient Birdman competition.",
    12: "December brings 25°C heat and the start of high season as Southern Hemisphere summer arrives. Flights from Santiago fill up fast, and the island buzzes with an energy that contrasts beautifully with its ancient stillness.",
  },
  'cl-patagonia': {
    1: "January is peak Patagonia — temps reach a balmy 15°C (balmy for here), the W Trek is packed, and daylight stretches past 10pm. Book refugios six months ahead or bring a tent and a tolerance for legendary wind.",
    2: "February holds similar conditions at 14°C with marginally thinner crowds toward month's end. The wildflowers are at their best in Torres del Paine, and guanaco sightings are practically guaranteed.",
    3: "March is the secret weapon — autumn colours ignite the lenga forests in crimson and gold, temps sit around 11°C, and the summer hordes have departed. Puma tracking season heats up as prey moves to lower ground.",
    4: "April is a gamble: 8°C, first snows dusting the peaks, and many refugios shutting down. But the Torres bathed in autumn light with no one around? That's the Patagonia you came for.",
    5: "May shuts most trekking operations as winter arrives — temps drop to 4°C and snow blankets the trails. The town of Puerto Natales goes quiet, but hardcore photographers chase dramatic storm light.",
    6: "June is deep winter at 2°C with short days and heavy snow. Torres del Paine is technically accessible but services are skeletal. This is for the committed few who want raw, empty wilderness.",
    7: "July stays frozen around 1°C, and the peaks look like something from a fantasy novel under fresh snow. If you're here, you're likely combining with a ski trip further north.",
    8: "August begins the very slow thaw at 3°C, with occasional bluebird days that make the snow-capped Torres glow. Some early-bird operators begin opening, but conditions remain firmly wintry.",
    9: "September is early spring — 6°C, snow melting, trails soggy but passable for the adventurous. Baby guanacos appear and the park has an awakening quality that rewards patience.",
    10: "October sees 9°C and the trekking season creaking back to life. Wildflowers emerge, the wind returns with enthusiasm, and you'll want waterproof everything from head to toe.",
    11: "November is the underrated opener — 12°C, long days, decent weather windows, and far fewer trekkers than the Dec–Feb crush. The Grey Glacier calves dramatically and condor sightings peak.",
    12: "December launches full high season at 14°C with near-endless daylight and all services running. The W Trek fills up and the wind can be ferocious, but the Torres at golden hour make everything worth it.",
  },
  'cl-santiago': {
    1: "January is Santiago's hottest month at 30°C+ with bone-dry air and locals fleeing to the coast. The city empties beautifully — explore Barrio Lastarria without crowds, and the Maipo Valley vineyards are lush and harvest-ready.",
    2: "February stays scorching near 30°C but the wine harvest kicks into high gear in the surrounding valleys. Hit a vendimia festival for grape-stomping and Carménère straight from the barrel.",
    3: "March cools to a perfect 27°C and the city snaps back to life after summer holidays. Autumn light gilds the Andes backdrop, and the seafood at Mercado Central is at its freshest.",
    4: "April brings 22°C and the first hints of smog season as temperature inversions settle over the valley. The fall foliage in Parque Bicentenario is lovely, and Cajón del Maipo's hot springs beckon.",
    5: "May drops to 16°C with the first rains greening the surrounding hills. The ski resorts in the Andes above start prepping, and Santiago's cozy wine bars come into their own.",
    6: "June is proper winter — 13°C, rain, and the Andes dusted in snow visible from every rooftop. Ski season opens at Valle Nevado and Portillo, just 90 minutes from downtown.",
    7: "July is the coldest at 11°C with the most rainfall, but the ski conditions are prime. Santiago's restaurant scene is world-class and underpriced — perfect weather for a multi-course Chilean tasting menu.",
    8: "August stays chilly at 13°C with good skiing still available above the city. The jasmine trees start blooming early, hinting at the spring to come.",
    9: "September brings spring and Chilean independence celebrations — expect 17°C, fondas (traditional food stalls), cueca dancing, and enthusiastic consumption of chicha and empanadas during Fiestas Patrias.",
    10: "October warms to 20°C with jacarandas beginning their purple explosion across the city. The Andes snowmelt feeds the rivers, and white-water rafting in the Cajón del Maipo is at its best.",
    11: "November hits 25°C and the city is gorgeous — long evenings on Barrio Italia's terraces, weekend trips to Valparaíso, and the Andes still snow-capped against blue skies.",
    12: "December ramps to 28°C as summer takes hold. Santiago buzzes with end-of-year energy, outdoor concerts fill Parque O'Higgins, and the swimming pools of Providencia become essential survival tools.",
  },
  'cm-cameroon': {
    1: "January is deep dry season in the north — Waza National Park is prime for wildlife spotting at 35°C as animals cluster around shrinking waterholes. The south stays humid at 28°C, and Douala is its typical sticky self.",
    2: "February remains hot and dry in the north at 37°C, ideal for trekking the Mandara Mountains and visiting Rhumsiki's volcanic landscapes. The coast offers whale-watching possibilities as the season begins.",
    3: "March heats up to 38°C in the north and the dry season starts winding down. The Ring Road in the northwest highlands is passable and the Bamenda region's craft markets are vibrant.",
    4: "April brings the first rains to the south at 29°C, greening the landscape rapidly. The north holds dry a bit longer, and Cameroon's famous biodiversity starts its annual awakening.",
    5: "May is transitional — rain arrives in earnest across the south and the cloud forests of Mount Cameroon get lush and misty. The dry north at 35°C offers a last window for Waza safaris.",
    6: "June launches the wet season across most of the country, with Douala getting absolutely drenched. The highlands around Bamenda at 22°C are the pleasant exception, cool and relatively dry.",
    7: "July is peak rainy season — expect daily downpours in the south and challenging road conditions. The Mount Cameroon Race of Hope happens this month, a grueling volcanic ascent that draws international runners.",
    8: "August dumps the heaviest rainfall, especially around Mount Cameroon — the wettest place in Africa. Travel is challenging but the forests are impossibly green and alive with primates and birds.",
    9: "September remains wet but the rains begin easing, especially in the north. Korup National Park's ancient rainforest is spectacular if muddy, and river levels make pirogue journeys feasible.",
    10: "October sees the rains retreating northward, and the savannas begin drying out for better wildlife access. Temperatures in Yaoundé settle at a pleasant 25°C and the cultural festivals pick up.",
    11: "November is dry season's return — the north at 32°C reopens for safari and the Waza elephants become reliable again. The Ngaoundéré-to-Douala train ride showcases the country's wild geographic diversity.",
    12: "December is hot and dry in the north at 33°C, warm and sunny in the south, and the whole country buzzes with festive season energy. Limbé's black-sand beaches are popular with domestic holidaymakers.",
  },
  'cn-beijing-north': {
    1: "January is Beijing's coldest — highs barely reach -1°C and the Forbidden City is dusted with snow that few tourists witness. The Great Wall under fresh powder is otherworldly, and hotpot season is in full, glorious swing.",
    2: "February stays frigid at 2°C but Chinese New Year (date varies) transforms the city with temple fairs, fireworks, and dumplings. Book ahead if the holiday falls here — hotels fill fast and half the country is traveling.",
    3: "March thaws to 10°C and the willows along the moat start budding. The infamous spring dust storms from the Gobi can blow through, turning skies yellow, but crowds are thin and the hutongs are peaceful.",
    4: "April is gorgeous at 19°C with cherry blossoms in Yuyuantan Park rivaling Tokyo's. The air is relatively clear, the Summer Palace lake is open, and this is arguably Beijing's best month for sightseeing.",
    5: "May warms to 26°C and the city is lush before summer's heaviest heat. The International Labour Day holiday (early May) brings crowds, but the Temple of Heaven's morning tai chi sessions remain timelessly serene.",
    6: "June hits 30°C with increasing humidity and the first hints of the summer monsoon. The hutong bars set up outdoor seating, Peking duck tastes just as good with a cold Yanjing beer, and the long evenings are lovely.",
    7: "July is sweltering at 31°C with heavy monsoon rains and thunderstorms. It's peak domestic tourism season, so the Great Wall is packed — go to Jinshanling instead of Badaling for breathing room.",
    8: "August mirrors July's heat and humidity at 30°C, with occasional flooding from downpours. The Summer Palace boat rides offer some breeze, and Beijing's craft beer scene provides excellent indoor refuge.",
    9: "September is spectacular — 26°C, clear skies, and the city wrapped in early autumn gold. This is universally considered the best time to visit, with National Day crowds not hitting until the last few days.",
    10: "October opens with Golden Week (Oct 1–7), when 800 million Chinese travel simultaneously — expect maximum crowds and prices. After the holiday, the 20°C weather and fall colours are superb and the crowds vanish.",
    11: "November chills to 10°C and autumn's last amber light filters through the ginkgo-lined streets near Ditan Park. Winter is coming but hasn't arrived, making this a solid shoulder season play.",
    12: "December drops to 2°C with occasional snow and crystal-clear winter skies. The Forbidden City without crowds is genuinely magical, and the lamb spine hotpot at local joints will rewire your understanding of comfort food.",
  },
  'cn-guilin-guangxi': {
    1: "January is Guilin's coldest month at 8°C — the karst peaks fade into romantic mist, and the Li River runs low but the bamboo rafts still operate. Tourist numbers hit rock bottom, and a steaming bowl of Guilin rice noodles has never tasted better.",
    2: "February holds at 10°C with Chinese New Year potentially bringing crowds and festive atmosphere. The terraced fields of Longji are bare but dramatic, and the region's minority villages celebrate with their own colourful traditions.",
    3: "March warms to 15°C and spring rains begin to fill the rivers. The canola flowers bloom bright yellow in the countryside around Yangshuo, creating a photographer's paradise against the limestone karst backdrop.",
    4: "April is lush and misty at 21°C — the Li River cruise from Guilin to Yangshuo is at its most atmospheric with karst peaks emerging from low clouds. Pack a rain jacket and embrace the dreamscape.",
    5: "May heats to 26°C with serious humidity and the start of the rainy season. The Longji rice terraces begin flooding for planting, creating mirror-like reflections that justify every step of the hike up.",
    6: "June is hot and wet at 29°C, with dramatic thunderstorms rolling through the karst valleys. The Dragon Boat Festival brings zongzi dumplings and racing, and the rivers run high and fast.",
    7: "July peaks at 32°C with intense humidity and frequent downpours. Yangshuo's rock climbing scene thrives despite the heat, and the cormorant fishermen on the Li River put on their lantern-lit shows at dusk.",
    8: "August stays steamy at 32°C — this is peak domestic tourism and the caves around Guilin offer blessed 18°C relief. The Silver Cave and Reed Flute Cave are touristy but genuinely spectacular.",
    9: "September dials back to 28°C and the rains ease. The Longji terraces turn golden as the rice ripens — this is the iconic postcard shot of tiered amber fields against green peaks.",
    10: "October brings 23°C and the harvest — the Longji terraces are at their golden peak in early October, and the Li River clears to jade green. Golden Week crowds are intense but the scenery compensates.",
    11: "November cools to 17°C with clear skies and excellent visibility for photographing the karst landscape. Crowds thin dramatically and Yangshuo's West Street returns to its backpacker-village charm.",
    12: "December drops to 10°C and the mist returns, softening the karst scenery into traditional Chinese ink-painting territory. It's quiet, cool, and the perfect time for slow cycling through the Yulong River valley.",
  },
  'cn-hainan': {
    1: "January is Hainan's dry season sweet spot — 22°C in Haikou, warmer in Sanya at 26°C, with blue skies and minimal rain. The beaches are busy with Chinese escaping northern winters, but the surf at Riyue Bay is reliably good.",
    2: "February stays warm at 23°C and Chinese New Year turns Sanya into China's unofficial winter capital. Hotel prices spike dramatically, but the tropical fruits — coconut, mango, papaya — are outstanding and cheap at roadside stalls.",
    3: "March warms to 26°C with lingering dry season clarity. The diving at Wuzhizhou Island hits peak visibility, and the crowds from New Year have dispersed. This is Hainan at its most balanced.",
    4: "April heats to 29°C as spring transitions toward the humid season. The surfing community at Houhai village is in full swing, and the rainforest interior around Yanoda Park is lush without being sweltering.",
    5: "May hits 31°C with rising humidity and the first pre-monsoon showers. The Li and Miao minority villages in the central highlands offer cultural depth beyond the beach resorts, with spring festivals in full color.",
    6: "June launches typhoon season — 32°C, humid, with potential for tropical storms. The duty-free shopping in Haikou's malls becomes the main attraction on rainy days, and seafood prices drop at the markets.",
    7: "July is peak summer at 33°C, blazing and humid with occasional typhoon threats. Chinese families flood the resorts, and the night markets in Haikou sizzle with grilled seafood and coconut chicken.",
    8: "August mirrors July's intensity at 33°C — the highest typhoon risk month, but also thrilling surf conditions for experienced riders. Keep an eye on weather forecasts and stay flexible.",
    9: "September starts cooling fractionally to 31°C but typhoon season continues. The crowds thin after school starts, and the Wenchang chicken — Hainan's signature dish — tastes just as good in the quieter restaurants.",
    10: "October eases to 28°C with typhoon risk diminishing. The autumn light on Sanya's beaches is gorgeous, and this shoulder season month offers good value before the winter rush returns.",
    11: "November drops to 25°C and the dry season reasserts itself. Russian and domestic tourists start arriving in numbers, but the newly clear skies and warm seas make this excellent timing for diving and sailing.",
    12: "December is prime season at 23°C — dry, sunny, and packed with northerners chasing warmth. Sanya's Yalong Bay feels like a different country from wintry Beijing, and the tropical sunsets don't disappoint.",
  },
  'cn-sichuan': {
    1: "January is Sichuan's coldest at 6°C in Chengdu, with grey skies and the basin trapped under its characteristic winter fog. The giant pandas at the Chengdu Research Base are frisky in the cool air, and the mapo tofu hits with extra fury.",
    2: "February stays chilly at 8°C but Chinese New Year lights up Chengdu's Jinli Ancient Street with lanterns and street food. The Sichuan Opera's fire-spitting face-changing shows are a must-see during festival season.",
    3: "March warms to 13°C and the fog lifts occasionally to reveal green hills. Leshan's Giant Buddha is less crowded than summer, and the teahouses of People's Park settle into their languorous rhythm.",
    4: "April is lovely at 19°C — the mountains around Jiuzhaigou begin thawing and the valleys fill with wildflowers. Chengdu's restaurant patios open up, and the numbing-spicy hotpot somehow tastes even better outdoors.",
    5: "May hits 24°C with increasing humidity and the start of the rainy season. Emei Shan is lush and occasionally misty, the monkeys are bold, and the tea plantations in Ya'an produce their finest spring harvest.",
    6: "June brings serious rain and 26°C heat — Jiuzhaigou's waterfalls roar at full power and the turquoise pools overflow. Roads to western Sichuan can be challenging, but the Tibetan grasslands of Tagong are magnificent.",
    7: "July is hot and wet at 28°C in the basin, but the western highlands at 3,500m+ offer cool relief. The Litang Horse Festival (if timing aligns) is one of China's most spectacular cultural events.",
    8: "August stays at 28°C with heavy monsoon rains, particularly in the mountains. The pandas are less active in the heat, preferring air-conditioned indoor enclosures — visit early morning for the best sightings.",
    9: "September cools to 23°C and the rains begin easing. Jiuzhaigou enters its legendary autumn colour season, with forests turning every shade from amber to crimson against turquoise lakes.",
    10: "October is Sichuan's crown jewel — 19°C, clear skies, and Jiuzhaigou's autumn colours at absolute peak. Golden Week (early Oct) brings crushing crowds, but mid-to-late October is pure gold.",
    11: "November chills to 13°C and the autumn palette fades, but the first snows dust the peaks of Siguniang Mountain. The hot springs around Hailuogou Glacier become irresistible, and Chengdu's fog rolls back in.",
    12: "December drops to 7°C with persistent grey skies over Chengdu — but the food scene is at its most comforting. Dan dan noodles, rabbit heads, and hotpot provide more warmth than any radiator could manage.",
  },
  'cn-xinjiang': {
    1: "January is brutally cold — Urumqi averages -12°C and the Taklamakan Desert gets snow dusting its dunes in surreal fashion. The Kazakh herders have settled into winter camps, and the lamb pilaf (polo) is peak comfort food.",
    2: "February stays frozen at -10°C but the Uyghur communities celebrate with traditional music and gatherings. Kashgar's old town is atmospheric under winter haze, and the naan bread comes hot from underground tandoor ovens.",
    3: "March begins a slow thaw at -1°C, with the Tian Shan mountains still buried in snow. The Sunday livestock market in Kashgar resumes its ancient, chaotic energy — one of Central Asia's great spectacles.",
    4: "April warms to 14°C and the apricot blossoms explode across the Ili Valley in a display that rivals Japan's cherry season. Turpan's grape trellises start greening, and the Silk Road trading towns shake off winter.",
    5: "May is gorgeous at 21°C — the Ili Valley is carpeted in wildflowers and the Sayram Lake reflects snow-capped peaks. This is the best month for the northern grasslands, with Kazakh herders moving to summer pastures.",
    6: "June hits 28°C and the long days illuminate Xinjiang's staggering scale. The Karakoram Highway to Pakistan is fully open, and the lavender fields around Ili rival Provence at a fraction of the tourist density.",
    7: "July peaks at 32°C (and 40°C+ in Turpan's Flaming Mountains, where even the raisins sweat). The Heavenly Lake near Urumqi is a cool mountain escape, and the night markets burst with grilled lamb and cold beer.",
    8: "August holds at 30°C with the fruit harvest in full swing — Hami melons, Turpan grapes, and figs are at their sugar-saturated best. The Karakul Lake near Kashgar mirrors Muztagh Ata peak in perfect stillness.",
    9: "September cools to 22°C and the poplars along the desert highways turn brilliant gold. The grape harvest festival in Turpan is a sweet farewell to summer, and the Silk Road sites are blissfully uncrowded.",
    10: "October drops to 12°C with the golden poplar forests of Luntai creating some of China's most dramatic autumn scenery. The desert landscapes turn amber, and Kashgar's bazaar operates at a wonderfully unhurried pace.",
    11: "November chills to 2°C and winter comes fast — snow closes mountain passes and the tourist season ends definitively. The old cities of Kashgar and Turpan are quiet and genuine, with few outsiders around.",
    12: "December plunges to -8°C with heavy snow in the mountains and short, cold days. The international bazaar in Urumqi's Grand Bazaar stays warm inside, and the lamb skewers seasoned with cumin are winter survival essentials.",
  },
  'cn-yunnan': {
    1: "January is dry and mild in Kunming at 15°C — the 'Spring City' earns its nickname while the rest of China shivers. Dali and Lijiang are crisp at 10°C with clear mountain views, and the Hani rice terraces catch the low winter light beautifully.",
    2: "February stays pleasant at 16°C and Chinese New Year brings Bai and Naxi ethnic minority festivals across the province. The red-billed gulls at Kunming's Green Lake are in their winter residence, and the temple fairs are spectacular.",
    3: "March warms to 19°C and the canola fields around Luoping bloom in a sea of gold that stretches to every horizon. This is peak flower season, and the minority market days in the villages are full of colour and trade.",
    4: "April is Yunnan's sweet spot at 22°C — the Water Splashing Festival in Xishuangbanna celebrates Dai New Year with epic water fights and dancing. The tea mountains produce their prized spring pu'er harvest.",
    5: "May hits 24°C and the first monsoon rains start greening the landscape. Tiger Leaping Gorge trekking is excellent before the heavy rains, and the wild mushroom season begins its delicious annual run.",
    6: "June brings the wet season at 23°C with afternoon thunderstorms becoming routine. The mushroom markets of Kunming go berserk with dozens of wild species, and the rice terraces of Yuanyang begin flooding.",
    7: "July is warm and wet at 24°C — the monsoon feeds Yunnan's legendary biodiversity and the jungles of Xishuangbanna are at their most alive. Wild elephants in Pu'er are easier to spot as they move through lush habitat.",
    8: "August stays damp at 24°C with the heaviest rainfall of the year. The Shangri-La meadows (Zhongdian) at 3,200m are a cool, flower-strewn escape, and the yak butter tea starts making sense.",
    9: "September begins drying at 22°C with the monsoon retreating. The rice terraces of Yuanyang turn golden before harvest, creating the staircase-to-heaven postcard shot the region is famous for — catch them before mid-month or you'll arrive to stubble.",
    10: "October cools to 19°C with clear skies returning, but the rice paddies are brown and harvested through November — terraces look bare and dry rather than photogenic. Lijiang's old town is busy during Golden Week but settles into charm afterward.",
    11: "November drops to 15°C and the dry season locks in with brilliant blue skies. The Hani terraces are still brown from harvest in early November, but by late month the winter flooding begins, creating the mirror-surface reflections that grace every photography book about China.",
    12: "December is crisp at 12°C with frost at elevation but warm sunshine in Kunming. The Black Dragon Pool in Lijiang frames Jade Dragon Snow Mountain perfectly, and the province's famous crossing-the-bridge noodles warm you right through.",
  },
  'co-bogota': {
    1: "January is one of Bogotá's driest months — 18°C and pleasantly sunny at 2,640m elevation, perfect for exploring La Candelaria's colonial streets without an umbrella. The ajiaco soup still hits though — it's a constant craving at altitude.",
    2: "February stays dry and mild at 18°C with blue skies over the Andes. Carnaval energy buzzes even this far from the coast, and the Monserrate cable car offers crystal-clear views over the sprawling city.",
    3: "March brings the first rains at 18°C — afternoon showers become routine, but mornings are bright. The Paloquemao market is bursting with exotic fruit, and the craft beer scene in Chapinero is genuinely world-class.",
    4: "April is the wettest month with daily rain at 18°C. Bogotá's museum scene — Botero, Gold Museum, contemporary galleries — is among South America's best, making rainy days a non-issue.",
    5: "May stays rainy at 18°C but the city's green hills are impossibly lush. The ciclovía on Sundays shuts down major roads for cyclists and runners — over a million bogotanos participate weekly.",
    6: "June sees rain easing slightly at 17°C as a brief drier spell settles in. The altitude takes newcomers by surprise — take it easy, drink agua de panela, and let the city reveal itself slowly.",
    7: "July is the driest mid-year month at 17°C with clear, cool days. Colombian independence celebrations on July 20th fill the streets, and the nightlife in Zona T and Chapinero runs until dawn.",
    8: "August holds at 17°C with dry weather and the famous Bogotá Book Fair — one of the largest in Latin America. The city's intellectual and cultural energy is palpable, and the cafés overflow with conversation.",
    9: "September starts the second rainy season at 18°C with afternoon storms returning. Rock al Parque and other free festivals make this a great cultural month despite the weather.",
    10: "October is wet at 18°C with the heaviest second-season rains. The Usaquén flea market on Sundays powers through regardless, and the empanadas from street vendors provide essential rain-walking fuel.",
    11: "November stays rainy at 18°C but the Christmas lights go up mid-month, and Bogotá's display rivals any in the Americas. The entire city transforms into a warm-hued wonderland despite the drizzle.",
    12: "December is festive and increasingly dry at 18°C — the Christmas light displays are genuinely spectacular, and the aguardiente flows freely at year-end celebrations. The city radiates warmth that defies its cool mountain air.",
  },
  'co-cartagena-caribbean': {
    1: "January is peak season on Colombia's Caribbean — 31°C, bone-dry, and trade winds keeping Cartagena's humidity just bearable. The walled city hums with tourists but the ceviche at the portal vendors is worth every elbow.",
    2: "February stays hot and dry at 31°C with Cartagena's pre-Lent Carnival atmosphere building. Day trips to the Rosario Islands offer turquoise water and fresh fish lunch, and this is prime time for the coast.",
    3: "March holds at 32°C and dry — the last gasp of the perfect season. Semana Santa (if it falls here) brings processions through the colonial streets, and the palenqueras with their fruit bowls are everywhere.",
    4: "April marks the transition at 32°C as the first rains arrive. The Hay Festival Cartagena brings literary heavyweights to the colonial city, and the afternoon thunderstorms are spectacular but brief.",
    5: "May heats to 32°C with proper rain arriving — afternoon downpours cool things off and the crowds thin. Hotel prices drop and the old city's bougainvillea explodes in colour against the colonial facades.",
    6: "June stays at 32°C with regular rain but plenty of sunshine between showers. The Tayrona coast is lusher and greener, and the quieter beaches near Santa Marta are at their most appealing.",
    7: "July brings a brief dry spell at 32°C — the 'veranillo de San Juan' offers a summer pocket within the wet season. Cartagena's restaurant scene is outstanding and less frantic than peak season.",
    8: "August stays at 31°C with light rain and a cultural calendar that includes the Barranquilla Atlantic Music Festival. The seafood is reliably excellent and the Caribbean sunsets put on a nightly show.",
    9: "September is the wettest month at 31°C with heavy afternoon storms and elevated humidity. Prices are at their lowest and the colonial city, slick with rain, photographs beautifully.",
    10: "October remains rainy at 31°C — the tail end of the wet season, with lush green surrounding the city walls. The Halloween celebration at the walled city is surprisingly festive and spooky.",
    11: "November sees rain tapering off at 31°C as the dry season approaches. The Cartagena International Film Festival fills the colonial courtyards with screenings, and the transition month offers good value.",
    12: "December kicks off high season at 31°C — dry, festive, and packed with Colombian holidaymakers. New Year's Eve in the walled city is legendary, with champagne, salsa, and fireworks over the bay.",
  },
  'co-coffee-region': {
    1: "January is relatively dry in the Coffee Triangle at 22°C — the fincas around Salento and Filandia are emerald green and the wax palms of Valle de Cocora pierce misty skies. Coffee harvest season means you can pick cherries alongside the recolectores.",
    2: "February stays mild at 22°C with occasional showers keeping the hillsides impossibly verdant. The coffee processing demonstrations at local fincas are fascinating, and a tinto on any mirador terrace is a ritual.",
    3: "March brings more rain at 22°C and the landscape is at peak lushness. The jeeps to Cocora Valley splash through mud with cheerful recklessness, and the trout from mountain streams is always on the menu.",
    4: "April is one of the wetter months at 21°C with daily afternoon rain. The cloud forests around Manizales are atmospheric and alive with hummingbirds, and the thermal pools at Santa Rosa de Cabal beckon.",
    5: "May stays wet at 21°C but the coffee flowers bloom in fragrant white waves across the hillsides — brief and beautiful. The region's fincas are quieter and more intimate, perfect for slow travel.",
    6: "June dries out slightly at 22°C as a mid-year dry spell settles in. The second coffee harvest begins, and the small-town plazas of Filandia and Jardín are at their most charming and unhurried.",
    7: "July is the driest month at 22°C with clear mornings revealing the snow-capped Nevado del Ruiz. This is peak domestic tourism season, so book the best finca stays early.",
    8: "August holds at 22°C and dry, with the Feria de Manizales bringing bullfighting controversy and incredible street parties. The coffee tours run at full capacity, and sunset from Salento's viewpoint is reliably spectacular.",
    9: "September starts the second wet season at 21°C with rains returning. The birdwatching is exceptional as migrant species arrive, and the cloud forests drip with orchids and bromeliads.",
    10: "October is rainy and lush at 21°C — the main coffee harvest begins and the hillsides buzz with activity. Don't miss the chance to see the full bean-to-cup process on a working finca.",
    11: "November is the wettest month at 21°C with muddy trails and dramatic cloud formations. The coffee harvest continues, prices are low, and the arepa-and-chorizo breakfasts fuel long rainy-day reading sessions.",
    12: "December sees rain easing at 22°C as the holiday season brings Colombian families to the region's charming towns. The Christmas lights in Salento are modest but genuine, and the aguardiente warms the cool mountain evenings.",
  },
  'co-medellin-antioquia': {
    1: "January is dry and spring-like at 24°C — Medellín's eternal spring reputation holds up perfectly. The Feria de las Flores may be months away, but the city's innovation district and street art scene keep things vibrant year-round.",
    2: "February stays pleasant at 24°C with minimal rain and clear views from the Metrocable over the green valley. The food scene in Laureles is booming, and the bandeja paisa is the mountain of a meal you didn't know you needed.",
    3: "March brings the first rains at 24°C — afternoon showers are brief and the city barely pauses. Guatapé's Piedra del Peñol is best visited on a clear morning before clouds roll in.",
    4: "April is wetter at 23°C with lush green hills framing the valley. The Botero sculptures in the plaza look handsome wet, and Medellín's craft cocktail bars make rainy evenings dangerously enjoyable.",
    5: "May stays rainy at 23°C but the city's transformation story is best experienced rain or shine — the commuting libraries, escalators, and parks in formerly tough neighborhoods are genuinely inspiring.",
    6: "June brings a brief dry spell at 24°C and a second wind of good weather. The city buzzes with cultural events, and the paragliding over the Aburrá Valley from San Félix offers heart-stopping views.",
    7: "July is relatively dry at 24°C and the Colombiatex fashion fair brings style to an already stylish city. The nightlife in Parque Lleras runs late, and the climate makes outdoor dining a year-round pleasure.",
    8: "August is Medellín's flagship month — the Feria de las Flores fills the city with spectacular flower displays, silletero parades, and concerts. Book well ahead; at 24°C and dry, the city is irresistible.",
    9: "September starts the second rainy season at 23°C with afternoon storms returning. The Jazz Festival brings international acts to outdoor stages, and the empanadas at every corner kiosk remain essential eating.",
    10: "October is the wettest month at 23°C with daily downpours greening the mountainsides. The covered Mercado del Río food hall is the perfect rain refuge, with dozens of restaurants under one roof.",
    11: "November stays wet at 23°C but the Christmas lights display — one of the most elaborate in the world — begins mid-month along the Medellín River. The alumbrados are genuinely jaw-dropping.",
    12: "December is festive and increasingly dry at 24°C, with the Christmas lights in full glory and the city alive with year-end parties. The warmth, both climatic and cultural, makes Medellín a December revelation.",
  },
  'cr-caribbean': {
    1: "January is technically the dry season on Costa Rica's Caribbean side, though 'dry' here means only occasional rain at 28°C. The cloud forests of Monteverde are clear and magical, with resplendent quetzals easier to spot.",
    2: "February to early March is the Caribbean coast's driest window at 28°C — Cahuita and Puerto Viejo's beaches are at their best and the coral reefs offer prime snorkeling visibility. The Afro-Caribbean culture and coconut rice-and-beans are unmissable.",
    3: "March stays warm at 29°C with the dry spell holding on the Caribbean slope. The cloud forest canopy tours are running at full capacity, and the poison dart frogs are neon bright against the forest floor.",
    4: "April begins the green season transition at 29°C — rains start on the Caribbean side while the cloud forests get mistier. Semana Santa brings Costa Ricans to the coast, so book beach lodges early.",
    5: "May launches proper rainy season at 28°C with daily afternoon downpours. Tortuguero's sea turtle nesting season begins (green turtles), and the canals of this roadless national park are at their lushest.",
    6: "June is wet and wild at 27°C — the Caribbean coast gets drenched but the rainforest comes alive with frogs, sloths, and toucans. Tortuguero turtle nesting ramps up, offering extraordinary nighttime beach experiences.",
    7: "July sees a brief 'veranillo' dry spell on the Pacific side, but the Caribbean stays wet at 27°C. The cloud forests are dripping and mystical, and howler monkeys provide the soundtrack.",
    8: "August stays rainy at 27°C with peak green season in the cloud forests. The Monteverde orchid garden is in bloom, and the birding is exceptional as resident species are joined by early migrants.",
    9: "September is one of the wettest months at 27°C — rivers run high and waterfalls thunder. The leatherback turtles may still nest at Tortuguero, and the reduced tourism means wildlife encounters feel more intimate.",
    10: "October is drenched at 27°C with the heaviest rains of the year. Prices drop significantly and the hardiest travelers are rewarded with explosive biodiversity and empty trails through pristine cloud forest.",
    11: "November starts transitioning at 27°C — rains begin easing on the Caribbean side. The bird migration is in full swing, and the chocolate tours in Puerto Viejo showcase cacao from bean to bar.",
    12: "December sees rain tapering dramatically at 28°C as the dry season approaches. The Caribbean coast's laid-back calypso vibe, coral-reef snorkeling, and palm-fringed beaches make for an un-resort-like tropical holiday.",
  },
  'cr-pacific': {
    1: "January is prime dry season on Costa Rica's Pacific — 33°C, cloudless skies, and the Guanacaste beaches at their golden best. Humpback whales are in the waters off the Osa Peninsula, and surf at Tamarindo is consistently clean.",
    2: "February stays hot and dry at 34°C with the landscape turning from green to tawny gold. The Nicoya Peninsula's beaches are postcard-perfect, and the howler monkeys at Manuel Antonio are reliably entertaining.",
    3: "March is the hottest month at 35°C — the dry forest of Guanacaste crackles and the beaches are packed with surfers and sunworshippers. It's the last full dry month, so the urgency is real.",
    4: "April begins the green season transition at 33°C with the first evening showers. Semana Santa (Easter week) is the busiest travel week in Costa Rica — expect full hotels and festive beach parties.",
    5: "May starts the rainy season in earnest at 31°C — lush green returns overnight and prices drop sharply. The olive ridley sea turtles begin arriving at Ostional, and the surfing at Pavones gets serious swells.",
    6: "June is properly wet at 30°C with daily afternoon storms, but mornings are typically sunny and gorgeous. The smaller Pacific beaches empty out, and the zip-lining through rain-soaked canopy is exhilarating.",
    7: "July brings a surprise dry spell — the 'veranillo' — at 31°C, giving a summer pocket on the Pacific coast. This brief window is popular with families, and the whale sharks appear off the Osa Peninsula.",
    8: "August stays at 30°C with the veranillo fading and rains resuming. The olive ridley turtle arrivals at Ostional can reach hundreds of thousands in a single 'arribada' — one of nature's great spectacles.",
    9: "September is seriously wet at 29°C with the heaviest Pacific-side rains and some road flooding. It's the quietest tourism month and the cheapest, with lodges offering deep discounts.",
    10: "October is the wettest month at 29°C, but the rains feed Costa Rica's superlative biodiversity. The last big olive ridley arribadas occur, and the rivers are at their most dramatic for white-water rafting.",
    11: "November sees rains easing at 30°C as the Pacific coast begins its transformation back to blue skies. Humpback whales from the Southern Hemisphere arrive, creating a second whale-watching season.",
    12: "December is the glorious return to dry at 32°C — the Pacific coast sparkles, holiday crowds arrive, and the sunsets over the ocean are absurdly beautiful. Book Nosara and Santa Teresa well ahead.",
  },
  'cu-havana': {
    1: "January is Havana's coolest month at 25°C with low humidity and virtually no rain — the crumbling pastel facades of the Malecón glow in clean winter light. Classic cars cruise without the sweaty shimmer, and the mojitos go down easy.",
    2: "February stays at 26°C and the Havana International Jazz Festival (date varies) fills the city's clubs and plazas with extraordinary music. The cigar factories are in full production, and the vintage-car taxis run all day long.",
    3: "March warms to 27°C and the dry season holds strong. The Vinales Valley tobacco fields in Pinar del Río are at their most photogenic, with mogotes (limestone hills) rising from emerald green plots.",
    4: "April hits 29°C with humidity creeping up and the first rain showers. The Biennial de La Habana (if scheduled) transforms the city into an open-air contemporary art gallery, and the nightlife is relentless.",
    5: "May brings the wet season at 30°C — afternoon thunderstorms roll in dramatically off the Florida Straits. The wet streets reflecting neon signs and colonial architecture create a noir atmosphere Hemingway would have loved.",
    6: "June is hot and humid at 31°C with regular rain and the start of hurricane season. The music scene doesn't pause — live son, rumba, and salsa pour from every open doorway in Centro Habana.",
    7: "July peaks at 32°C with serious humidity and tropical downpours. The Carnival celebrations in late July bring congas, comparsas, and dancing through the streets — it's sweaty and joyous in equal measure.",
    8: "August stays at 32°C and is the highest hurricane risk month. The streets steam after afternoon rains, and the coppelia ice cream queues are the one place no Cuban minds waiting.",
    9: "September is peak hurricane season at 31°C — travel insurance is essential. The city is at its quietest, but the cultural scene never sleeps, and intimate finds (a house concert, a backyard rumba) are more likely.",
    10: "October sees hurricane risk waning at 29°C but rain still frequent. The Festival de La Habana de Cine Latinoamericano preparations begin, and the tobacco-curing season starts in Pinar del Río.",
    11: "November cools to 27°C and the dry season returns, bringing relief and tourist numbers. The Latin American Film Festival draws cinephiles, and the rooftop bars along the Malecón reopen for sunset sessions.",
    12: "December is festive at 26°C with dry weather, holiday energy, and New Year's Eve celebrations that blend revolutionary history with rum and roast pork. Hotel prices spike, but the atmosphere is worth every convertible peso.",
  },
  'cu-trinidad': {
    1: "January is idyllic in Trinidad at 25°C — dry, clear, and the colonial cobblestone streets are gorgeous under blue skies. The live music scene in the Casa de la Música steps is in full swing every night, and the nearby Playa Ancón is quiet and warm.",
    2: "February holds at 26°C with dry weather and excellent conditions for hiking in the nearby Sierra del Escambray. The waterfalls are accessible without the wet-season mud, and the casas particulares offer genuine Cuban hospitality.",
    3: "March warms to 28°C with the dry season at its peak. The sugar mill ruins at Valle de los Ingenios are best explored in the cooler morning light, and the UNESCO-listed old town practically hums with history.",
    4: "April transitions at 29°C as humidity builds and the first rains threaten. The snorkeling at Cayo Blanco is excellent, and the street food — churros, tamales, and fresh guarapo — keeps you fueled for exploring.",
    5: "May starts the wet season at 30°C with afternoon storms becoming routine. The tobacco and agricultural landscapes around Trinidad are at their greenest, and the fewer tourists mean more authentic local encounters.",
    6: "June is hot and wet at 31°C but the Valle de los Ingenios is lush and dramatic. Live music sessions in Trinidad's intimate venues are an every-night occurrence, and the rum cocktails keep pace with the heat.",
    7: "July hits 32°C with tropical humidity and occasional heavy rain. The Carnival spirit reaches even this colonial gem, and the casa particular hosts pull out all the stops with home-cooked lobster (when available).",
    8: "August stays hot at 32°C with the highest hurricane awareness — Camagüey and the eastern provinces are more exposed, but Trinidad's inland position offers some shelter. The pace slows to a tropical crawl.",
    9: "September is the wettest month at 31°C with storm risk at its highest. The old town's drainage channels — originally Spanish colonial engineering — get a serious workout, and you'll have the museums largely to yourself.",
    10: "October sees rain easing at 29°C and the landscape transitioning back toward the dry season. The horseback rides through the surrounding valley are back in action, and the sunsets from the bell tower are extraordinary.",
    11: "November cools to 27°C and tourist season begins ramping up. The colonial architecture looks magnificent in the softer autumn light, and the live salsa at La Escalinata is justifiably famous.",
    12: "December is dry and festive at 26°C — the holiday season brings both tourists and local celebrations. New Year's Eve in Trinidad's main plaza, surrounded by 500-year-old buildings and live music, is unforgettably intimate.",
  },
  'cv-caboverde': {
    1: "January is warm and dry at 24°C with the trade winds providing natural air conditioning across the islands. Sal and Boa Vista's beaches are windswept and gorgeous, and the kitesurfing conditions are world-class.",
    2: "February stays dry at 24°C with peak wind season driving kitesurfers and windsurfers to absolute euphoria. The Carnival celebrations across the islands, especially on São Vicente, rival Brazil's for energy if not scale.",
    3: "March remains at 24°C and dry, with the last month of optimal wind conditions. The lunar landscapes of Santo Antão's interior are best hiked now, before the heat intensifies, and the grogue (local rum) fuels the trail.",
    4: "April warms slightly to 25°C as winds begin easing. The hiking on Santo Antão's ribeiras (valleys) is spectacular, with terraced agriculture clinging to impossible slopes, and the fresh tuna is outstanding.",
    5: "May is transitional at 25°C — the wind dies down, the sea calms, and the diving visibility around Sal improves dramatically. The beaches shift from kitesurfer playgrounds to swimming and snorkeling territory.",
    6: "June warms to 26°C with calm seas and the driest conditions. The underwater world around Boa Vista reveals sharks, rays, and sea turtles, and the laid-back Cape Verdean pace of life is infectious.",
    7: "July hits 27°C and the humpback whale migration passes through the channels between islands. São Vicente's music scene — the birthplace of morna and Cesária Évora's legacy — is best experienced in its intimate bars.",
    8: "August is the warmest at 28°C with the first hints of the brief rainy season. The loggerhead sea turtles begin nesting on Boa Vista's beaches, and the cultural festivals across the islands celebrate creole heritage.",
    9: "September brings sporadic rain at 28°C, briefly greening the volcanic slopes. The turtle nesting peaks, and guided night walks to watch loggerheads lay eggs on Ervatão beach are profoundly moving.",
    10: "October is the wettest month at 27°C, though 'wet' in Cabo Verde is relative — expect brief showers. The hillsides of Santiago show rare green, and the local cachupa stew is the national dish you'll crave afterward.",
    11: "November dries out at 26°C as the trade winds begin returning. The Baía das Gatas music festival (if scheduled) on São Vicente draws crowds, and the volcanic peak of Fogo is climbable in comfortable conditions.",
    12: "December returns to dry at 25°C with festive energy and rising winds. The Christmas celebrations blend Portuguese and African traditions, and the Mindelo harbor on São Vicente is postcard-perfect under clear skies.",
  },
  'cw-curacao': {
    1: "January is dry and breezy at 29°C with the trade winds keeping the heat manageable. Willemstad's candy-colored Dutch colonial waterfront is at its photogenic best, and the snorkeling at Playa Lagun is crystal clear.",
    2: "February stays at 29°C and the Carnival season explodes — weeks of parades, music, and elaborate costumes culminating in Grand Parade. It's the island's biggest cultural event, and the energy is absolutely electric.",
    3: "March holds at 30°C and dry as Carnival winds down. The underwater visibility is exceptional for diving the Mushroom Forest and the Superior Producer wreck, and the quiet beaches on the west coast are divine.",
    4: "April warms to 30°C with the trade winds easing slightly. The Curaçao North Sea Jazz Festival (date varies) has drawn major international acts, and the island's diverse food scene blends Dutch, Caribbean, and Indonesian flavors.",
    5: "May is transitional at 31°C with the first possibility of brief showers. The flamingos at Jan Kok salt flats are reliably pink and photogenic, and the Hato Caves offer cool limestone refuge.",
    6: "June stays at 31°C and sits outside the hurricane belt — one of Curaçao's great advantages. The diving is excellent year-round, and the Pietermaai district's bars and restaurants buzz every evening.",
    7: "July is warm at 31°C with dry conditions and steady breezes. The beaches on the sheltered west coast — Cas Abao, Grote Knip — are among the Caribbean's most beautiful and surprisingly uncrowded.",
    8: "August peaks at 32°C and it's the hottest month, but the constant trade wind and ocean proximity make it tolerable. The island's liqueur distillery (Curaçao of Curaçao) is worth a tour and tasting.",
    9: "September is the driest month at 32°C, sitting firmly outside the hurricane zone while other Caribbean islands worry. The snorkeling at Director's Bay reveals turtles, and the sunsets from Playa Forti are legendary.",
    10: "October brings the first real rain at 31°C — brief afternoon showers that barely interrupt beach days. The island greens up beautifully, and the street food scene around Marshe Bieu (the old market) is outstanding.",
    11: "November is the wettest month at 31°C, though downpours are short and the sun returns quickly. The diving remains excellent, and Willemstad's UNESCO-listed pontoon bridge (the Queen Emma) swings open for ships in a uniquely charming spectacle.",
    12: "December dries out at 30°C and the holiday season lights up Willemstad's waterfront. The NYE fireworks over the harbor bridge are a Caribbean highlight, and the island's pastechi (savory pastries) fuel every celebration.",
  },
  'cy-cyprus': {
    1: "January is Cyprus's coolest month at 15°C, with rain in the Troodos Mountains and occasional snow on Mount Olympus for skiing. The coastal cities stay mild, and the archaeological sites — Paphos mosaics, Kourion amphitheatre — are blissfully empty.",
    2: "February warms slightly to 16°C with almond blossoms decorating the hillsides around Paphos. Limassol's Carnival is a raucous multi-week affair, and the Troodos ski season is still going strong at 1,952m.",
    3: "March brings 18°C and wildflowers carpeting the Akamas Peninsula in a display that rivals any Mediterranean island. The citrus orchards are fragrant, and the Easter preparations (Orthodox date varies) add cultural depth.",
    4: "April is gorgeous at 21°C with the island in full bloom and Orthodox Easter celebrations filling the churches and villages with tradition. The hiking trails are at their best, and swimming season begins for the brave.",
    5: "May warms to 25°C and the beaches come alive — Nissi Beach and Fig Tree Bay start filling up without yet reaching peak chaos. The Kataklysmos (Festival of the Flood) in Larnaca combines water fights with seaside feasting.",
    6: "June hits 29°C and summer mode is fully engaged. The ancient sites bake in the heat, so visit early morning, then spend the afternoon in the turquoise waters off the Karpaz Peninsula.",
    7: "July is hot at 32°C with zero rain and relentless sunshine. The beach clubs and resort pools are essential, and the mountain villages of Troodos — Kakopetria, Platres — offer cool altitude refuge at 20°C.",
    8: "August peaks at 33°C and is the busiest tourist month. The Commandaria wine region is harvesting, and the Aphrodite Festival in Paphos stages opera against the medieval castle backdrop — culture with a sea breeze.",
    9: "September eases to 30°C with the sea still bath-warm and the crowds thinning noticeably. The Limassol Wine Festival celebrates the island's 5,000-year winemaking heritage, and the sunsets from Petra tou Romiou are epic.",
    10: "October cools to 25°C with the first autumn rain freshening the air. The swimming is still excellent, the halloumi is always squeaky-fresh, and the carob trees are being harvested in the countryside.",
    11: "November drops to 20°C with increasing rain and the tourist season winding down. The olive harvest is in full swing in the villages, and the meze at traditional tavernas is a multi-course masterpiece.",
    12: "December is mild at 16°C with festive lights in Nicosia and Limassol, and the Troodos getting its first proper snow. The mulled commandaria wine is a uniquely Cypriot winter warmer.",
  },
  'cz-moravia': {
    1: "January is cold and often snowy at -1°C — Moravia's rolling vineyards sleep under frost and the Beskydy Mountains offer cross-country skiing. The wine cellars of Mikulov stay a constant 12°C, making a tasting tour the smartest winter plan.",
    2: "February holds at 0°C with Carnival celebrations (Masopust) in rural villages featuring elaborate costumes and the butchering of a symbolic pig. The Moravian wine region is quiet but the cellars are open and generous.",
    3: "March thaws to 6°C with the landscape shaking off winter's grey. The UNESCO-listed Lednice-Valtice cultural landscape begins greening, and the Easter markets in Brno start setting up.",
    4: "April warms to 12°C and the vineyards start budding along the Moravian Wine Trail. Easter in the villages brings the 'pomlázka' tradition (decorated whips — don't ask, just observe), and Brno's café scene is lively.",
    5: "May is lovely at 17°C with the countryside in full bloom and the cycling trails through the wine country in perfect condition. The Znojmo wine festival kicks off the season, and the asparagus is fresh from local fields.",
    6: "June hits 21°C and the open-air wine cellars of Valtice and Velké Bílovice come alive with summer tastings. The Moravian folk festivals begin, with traditional costumes, cimbalom music, and slivovitz flowing freely.",
    7: "July is warm at 23°C and the folk festival season peaks — the Strážnice International Folklore Festival is one of Central Europe's finest, with music, dance, and crafts from across the region.",
    8: "August stays at 23°C with the grape harvest approaching and the Pálava Hills hiking trails offering panoramic views over the Austrian border. The sunflower fields make for absurdly photogenic backdrops.",
    9: "September is harvest time at 18°C — the wine cellars buzz with activity and 'burčák' (partially fermented young wine) appears at every stand. The Znojmo Grape Harvest Festival is a medieval-themed spectacular.",
    10: "October cools to 12°C with autumn colour sweeping through the vineyards. The new wine releases arrive and the thermal spa town of Luhačovice offers warm refuge as the days shorten.",
    11: "November drops to 5°C and the first Christmas markets appear in Brno. The Moravian wine region slows to its contemplative winter pace, and the game stew season begins in the countryside restaurants.",
    12: "December is cold at 1°C with Brno's Christmas markets glowing with mulled wine, trdelník pastries, and handcrafted ornaments. The candlelit wine cellars are magical, and the snow-dusted Lednice château is fairy-tale material.",
  },
  'cz-prague': {
    1: "January is Prague at its quietest — -1°C, occasional snow dusting the Charles Bridge, and the crowds that suffocate the Old Town Square are mercifully absent. The beer halls provide warmth both literal and spiritual, and goulash costs half the summer price.",
    2: "February stays cold at 1°C with Masopust (Czech Carnival) bringing masked parades and pork-heavy feasts to the streets. The castle complex is almost navigable without elbows, and the views from Petřín Hill are crisp and clear.",
    3: "March thaws to 7°C and early spring energy returns — the first outdoor café tables appear optimistically, and the Prague Spring music preparations begin. The daffodils in Letná Park are a welcome sight.",
    4: "April warms to 12°C with cherry blossoms on Petřín Hill and Easter markets filling Old Town Square. The tourist season is awakening but hasn't hit full force, making this the sweet spot for sightseeing and synagogue visits.",
    5: "May is gorgeous at 17°C — the Prague Spring International Music Festival fills churches and concert halls with world-class performances. The beer gardens open en masse, and the Vltava sparkles under long evening light.",
    6: "June hits 21°C and the city is firmly in high season — the Astronomical Clock draws dense crowds hourly, but the Vinohrady and Žižkov neighborhoods remain delightfully local. Czech craft beer is having a serious moment.",
    7: "July peaks at 23°C with occasional thunderstorms and maximum tourist density. Escape to Stromovka Park for green space, or take the train to Kutná Hora's bone church for a day trip with fewer selfie sticks.",
    8: "August holds at 23°C and the Old Town is elbow-to-elbow. The Signal Light Festival (if scheduled) transforms buildings into light-art canvases, and the summer cinema screenings in parks are a local ritual.",
    9: "September cools to 18°C and the tourist tide recedes beautifully. The Vinobraní (grape harvest) festival at Prague Castle celebrates Czech wine, and the early autumn light on the Vltava is painterly.",
    10: "October drops to 12°C with golden leaves lining the riverbanks and the Signal Festival lighting up the streets. The food scene shifts to hearty — svíčková (marinated sirloin) and knedlíky (dumplings) hit different in autumn.",
    11: "November chills to 5°C and the Christmas markets begin their setup in late month. The city turns moody and atmospheric, the jazz clubs are intimate, and Prague's literary café culture comes into its cozy own.",
    12: "December is magical at 1°C — the Christmas markets on Old Town Square and Wenceslas Square are among Europe's best, with trdelník, svařák (mulled wine), and hand-blown glass ornaments. The crowds return, but the festive glow is genuine.",
  },
  'de-berlin': {
    1: "January is Berlin's darkest month — 1°C, grey skies, and short days, but the city's museum collections (Museum Island alone could take a week) and legendary club scene don't need sunlight. Currywurst tastes better when you're freezing.",
    2: "February stays cold at 2°C with the Berlin International Film Festival (Berlinale) bringing global cinema glamour to Potsdamer Platz. The art galleries in Kreuzberg are heated and thriving, and the city feels bracingly alive.",
    3: "March thaws to 7°C and the first signs of spring appear in Tiergarten. The café culture along the canal in Kreuzberg stirs to life, and the flea markets at Mauerpark resume their Sunday spectacle.",
    4: "April warms to 13°C with cherry blossoms along the former Wall trail and outdoor events returning. The Gallery Weekend transforms the city's art scene, and the beer gardens in Prater start pouring.",
    5: "May is Berlin at its best — 18°C, long evenings, and the Karneval der Kulturen street parade celebrating the city's extraordinary diversity. The Spree River banks are lined with people, and the techno floats to the parks.",
    6: "June hits 22°C with the longest days and an outdoor-everything mentality. The Fête de la Musique fills every street corner with live music, and the lake swimming at Schlachtensee and Wannsee begins in earnest.",
    7: "July peaks at 24°C and Berlin lives entirely outside — rooftop bars, canal-side grills, and open-air cinema in parks. The occasional thunderstorm clears the air, and the clubbing extends to daytime garden parties.",
    8: "August holds at 23°C with a lazy, end-of-summer vibe. The Lollapalooza Berlin festival brings major international acts, and the Turkish market on the Landwehr Canal is essential for street food exploration.",
    9: "September cools to 18°C and the cultural season explodes — Berlin Art Week, the Marathon, and the Tag der offenen Tür (open-door day at government buildings). The early autumn light on the Spree is gorgeous.",
    10: "October drops to 12°C with golden leaves in Tiergarten and the Festival of Lights illuminating landmarks. The city's cozy Kneipe (pub) culture comes into its own, and the döner kebabs hit harder in cooler weather.",
    11: "November is grey and 6°C, but Berlin doesn't apologize for its melancholy — this is when the city's intellectual depth, its bookshops, and its kaffeehäuser feel most essential. The Christmas markets begin late in the month.",
    12: "December is cold at 3°C but the Christmas markets — Gendarmenmarkt, Charlottenburg Palace, Kulturbrauerei — are among Germany's finest. The mulled wine (Glühwein) is mandatory, and the reunification-era history resonates deeply in the winter quiet.",
  },
  'de-hamburg': {
    1: "January is Hamburg's coldest at 2°C with biting North Sea winds and grey skies over the Elbe. The Elbphilharmonie concert hall is the warm, acoustically perfect refuge you need, and the fish market runs rain or shine on Sunday mornings.",
    2: "February stays chilly at 3°C with occasional snow flurries. The harbor is atmospheric in winter light, and the Speicherstadt warehouse district — all red brick and canals — looks like a steampunk postcard.",
    3: "March brings 7°C and cautious optimism — the first crocuses appear in Planten un Blomen park, and the maritime energy of the port district starts its spring acceleration.",
    4: "April warms to 11°C and Hamburg shakes off winter properly. The Hamburg Ballet season is in full swing, and the Alster Lake's sailing boats return. The Reeperbahn's live music venues are always busy, regardless of season.",
    5: "May is lovely at 15°C with the Hafengeburtstag (harbor birthday) — the world's largest port festival — bringing tall ships, fireworks, and enormous crowds to the waterfront. The outdoor café terraces along the Alster are blissful.",
    6: "June hits 19°C with long days and a Scandinavian-light quality that suits this maritime city perfectly. The Dockville music festival and the open-air cinema season kick off, and cycling the HafenCity is wonderful.",
    7: "July warms to 21°C with Hamburg at its sunniest — the Alster Lake is ringed with sunbathers, and the Schanzenviertel neighborhood's street art and cafés are at their most vibrant. Summer storms can be dramatic.",
    8: "August holds at 21°C and the laid-back northern summer continues. The MS Dockville festival brings art and music to Wilhelmsburg, and a boat tour through the container port reveals Europe's logistics in awe-inspiring scale.",
    9: "September cools to 17°C with the Reeperbahn Festival turning Hamburg into a showcase for emerging music acts across dozens of venues. The autumn colours begin, and the fresh North Sea fish at the market is outstanding.",
    10: "October drops to 12°C and the maritime weather reasserts itself — rain, wind, and moody skies. The Hamburg Film Festival screens international cinema, and the cozy Portugiesenviertel restaurants serve warming stews.",
    11: "November is dark and 6°C with persistent drizzle that makes the city's covered passages and museum collections essential. The Christmas markets begin appearing, and the Speicherstadt's Miniatur Wunderland is indoor perfection.",
    12: "December brings 3°C and Hamburg's Christmas markets — especially the historic Rathausmarkt market — glow with warmth. The harbor fog, mulled wine, and Hanseatic dignity make for a distinctly northern German holiday season.",
  },
  'de-munich': {
    1: "January is Munich's coldest at -1°C with snow on the ground and the Alps gleaming white on the horizon. The ski resorts of Garmisch-Partenkirchen are 90 minutes away, and the beer halls — Hofbräuhaus, Augustiner — provide Alpine warmth.",
    2: "February stays cold at 1°C and Fasching (Carnival) brings costumed parades and balls to the Bavarian capital. The Viktualienmarkt's outdoor stalls sell roasted chestnuts and Glühwein, and the residenz museum is mercifully heated.",
    3: "March thaws to 7°C with Starkbier (strong beer) season — Munich's monasteries and breweries release powerful, dark lagers that were originally brewed for Lenten fasting. Nockherberg's Salvator tapping is a local institution.",
    4: "April warms to 12°C with the first beer garden days at the Englischer Garten's Chinese Tower. The Alps are still snow-capped and visible from the city on clear days, creating a backdrop no other major city can match.",
    5: "May is beer garden perfection at 17°C — the chestnuts are in bloom, the Isar River fills with sunbathers, and the Auer Dult flea market takes over Mariahilfplatz. Munich is at its most joyfully Bavarian.",
    6: "June hits 21°C with long Alpine evenings and Tollwood festival bringing music, food, and culture to Olympiapark. The river surfing on the Eisbach wave is a constant spectacle, and the Biergärten are packed.",
    7: "July peaks at 23°C with occasional dramatic thunderstorms rolling off the Alps. Munich's parks are alive with picnics and impromptu football, and a day trip to Neuschwanstein Castle is de rigueur.",
    8: "August holds at 22°C with lazy Bavarian summer energy. The lakes south of Munich — Starnberger See, Ammersee, Tegernsee — are swimming destinations, and the Augustiner Keller beer garden is the locals' true temple.",
    9: "September starts the legendary run — Oktoberfest opens in late September at 17°C, transforming Munich into the world's largest beer party. Book accommodation months ahead, wear lederhosen without irony, and pace yourself.",
    10: "October sees Oktoberfest ending in the first week at 11°C, after which the city exhales. The autumn foliage in the Englischer Garten is stunning, and the quieter beer halls welcome you like an old friend.",
    11: "November cools to 5°C and the Christmas market season begins. The Tollwood Winter Festival and the Christkindlmarkt on Marienplatz set up their stalls, and the smell of Lebkuchen and pine fills the cold air.",
    12: "December is magical at 1°C — Munich's Christmas markets are among Germany's most charming, with wooden toy stalls, roasted almonds, and Krampus sightings. The Alpine backdrop dusted in snow makes it feel like a living Advent calendar.",
  },

  'de-rhine': {
    1: "The Rhine Valley shivers under grey skies at 1-3°C, but empty castles and steaming Glühwein make for a moody, crowd-free escape. Cologne's carnival season kicks off mid-month with costumed revelry that rivals anything south of the Alps.",
    2: "Carnival reaches full tilt in Düsseldorf and Cologne—expect Rose Monday parades, face paint, and zero personal space. Temps hover around 2-5°C, so layer up beneath your costume and embrace the beautiful chaos.",
    3: "Spring teases the Rhineland with 6-10°C days and the first crocuses pushing through castle gardens. River cruise season begins to stir, and Bonn's cherry blossoms along the Altstadt start their famous pink corridor.",
    4: "The Rhine comes alive as temps climb to 10-15°C and vineyards green up along the Mittelrhein. Easter markets dot the smaller towns, and you can hike between hilltop castles without bumping into a single tour group.",
    5: "Warm days of 15-20°C turn the Rhine Gorge into postcard material—terraced vineyards, blooming wildflowers, castle ruins catching golden light. Wine festivals begin in earnest across the Mosel and Rheingau.",
    6: "Summer settles in at 18-24°C with long golden evenings perfect for Biergarten sessions along the river. Rhine in Flames fireworks festivals light up the gorge, and cycling the riverside paths is peak bliss.",
    7: "The warmest month at 20-26°C brings peak tourist season to the Rhine castles and river cruises. Book ahead for Rüdesheim and Bacharach, but escape crowds by hiking the Rheinsteig trail through shaded forest.",
    8: "High summer continues at 19-25°C with occasional thunderstorms that roll dramatically through the valley. Wine harvest prep begins in the vineyards, and outdoor concerts fill every available castle courtyard.",
    9: "Grape harvest season transforms the Rhine into a celebration of Riesling, with Weinfeste in every village and temps of 14-20°C. The tourist crush eases while the scenery peaks—golden vines against slate-grey castles.",
    10: "Autumn fog drifts through the gorge as temps drop to 9-14°C, creating atmospheric conditions photographers dream about. The last wine festivals wind down and Christmas market construction quietly begins.",
    11: "Grey skies and 4-8°C signal the arrival of Germany's beloved Christmas market season by month's end. Cologne's massive Weihnachtsmarkt opens, filling the cathedral square with the scent of Lebkuchen and roasted almonds.",
    12: "Christmas markets dominate the Rhine cities at 1-5°C, with Cologne, Düsseldorf, and Aachen running some of Germany's finest. Mulled wine flows freely, and the moody winter light gives every half-timbered town a storybook quality.",
  },
  'dj-djibouti': {
    1: "One of the cooler months at 25-29°C, making it prime time for whale shark encounters in the Gulf of Tadjoura. The water is a balmy 25°C, visibility is excellent, and the diving is world-class without the crowds.",
    2: "Still comfortable at 25-30°C with calm seas ideal for snorkeling at Moucha Island and the Day Forest. Whale shark season continues, and the lack of rain means crystal-clear underwater visibility.",
    3: "Temperatures start climbing to 28-32°C as the brief cool season winds down. Last chance for comfortable whale shark dives before the heat ramps up—the sea remains cooperatively calm.",
    4: "The heat arrives with authority at 30-35°C, and outdoor activities shift to early mornings and late afternoons. Lake Assal, the lowest point in Africa, shimmers with surreal salt formations best visited at dawn.",
    5: "Properly scorching now at 33-39°C—this is Djibouti earning its reputation as one of Earth's hottest places. Only the most heat-hardened travelers venture to Lac Abbé's otherworldly chimney formations.",
    6: "The Khamsin wind and 36-42°C temperatures make June genuinely brutal for anything beyond air-conditioned hotels. If you're here, stick to predawn excursions and the relatively cooler coast.",
    7: "Peak inferno season hits 38-44°C, and the country essentially hibernates through the afternoon hours. The landscape has a stark, Martian beauty if you can appreciate it through the heat shimmer.",
    8: "Still blazing at 36-42°C, though occasional sea breezes on the coast offer momentary relief. Tourist infrastructure is minimal and largely empty—this is Djibouti at its most raw and unfiltered.",
    9: "Heat begins its slow retreat to 33-38°C, and the sea starts cooling enough for diving to resume. The French military presence keeps restaurants open year-round, so you won't starve for decent cuisine.",
    10: "A transitional month at 30-35°C as conditions become more bearable for exploration. The first whale sharks of the new season may appear, and hotel rates are at their lowest.",
    11: "The pleasant season returns at 27-32°C, and whale shark tours fire up in earnest around the Gulf of Tadjoura. The desert light turns golden, perfect for photographing the alien landscapes around Lac Abbé.",
    12: "Ideal conditions at 25-30°C make December the start of peak season for this tiny, overlooked Horn of Africa nation. Whale sharks, pristine reefs, and empty beaches reward those adventurous enough to visit.",
  },
  'dk-copenhagen': {
    1: "Copenhagen in January is dark, cold (around 0-2°C), and utterly hygge. Candlelit cafés, steaming bowls of smørrebrød, and near-empty museums make this a cozy urban retreat for those who embrace the Scandinavian winter.",
    2: "Still frigid at 0-3°C with only eight hours of daylight, but Copenhagen Fashion Week brings glamour to the grey streets. The harbour baths stay open for the hardiest swimmers, and bakeries peak with fastelavnsboller pastries.",
    3: "Light returns noticeably as days stretch past 11 hours, though temps linger at 2-6°C. Tivoli Gardens reopens for the season, and the first outdoor café chairs appear on Nyhavn—optimism is a Danish specialty.",
    4: "Spring arrives properly at 6-12°C with cherry blossoms in Langelinie Park and daffodils in the King's Garden. Cycling becomes pleasant again, and the city shakes off winter with outdoor markets and harbour-side drinks.",
    5: "Gorgeous at 11-17°C with 16+ hours of daylight turning Copenhagen into a sun-worshipping city of cyclists and canal-side picnics. Distortion festival brings street parties to different neighbourhoods each day.",
    6: "Long, luminous days at 14-20°C make this one of the best months to visit. Midsummer celebrations on June 23rd involve bonfires, singing, and a collective Nordic joy that's infectious. Book Noma well in advance.",
    7: "Peak summer at 17-22°C with near-endless daylight and every Copenhagener decamped to the harbour baths or Amager Beach. Roskilde Festival draws rock fans, and Tivoli's evening concerts are magical.",
    8: "Warm and lively at 17-21°C, with the Copenhagen Cooking festival showcasing New Nordic cuisine at its finest. Crowds thin slightly from July's peak, and the canal tours catch perfect evening light.",
    9: "The golden shoulder season at 13-17°C offers warm enough days for cycling and fewer tourists clogging the Little Mermaid selfie spot. Culture Night in October is worth planning around if you're flexible.",
    10: "Autumn colours and 8-12°C temps bring a cozy transition as cafés switch to candlelight mode. Cultural season ramps up with opera, ballet, and jazz, while Tivoli's Halloween decorations are surprisingly spectacular.",
    11: "Dark and damp at 3-7°C, but Tivoli's Christmas market opens mid-month, transforming the park into a twinkling wonderland. This is peak hygge season—embrace the blankets, candles, and bottomless hot chocolate.",
    12: "Full Scandinavian winter at 1-4°C with just seven hours of daylight, but Copenhagen glows with Christmas markets and illuminated streets. Tivoli at Christmas is genuinely magical, and the Danes know how to make darkness beautiful.",
  },
  'dk-jutland': {
    1: "Jutland's January brings raw North Sea winds and 0-3°C temperatures across the peninsula's windswept heaths. The west coast surf scene stays active for the wetsuit-clad faithful, and Aarhus offers warm cultural refuge in its museums.",
    2: "Still biting at 0-3°C with short days, but Aalborg and Aarhus serve up cozy café culture and Viking history without a tourist in sight. The Wadden Sea's winter birdlife draws dedicated twitchers to the marshes.",
    3: "Spring creeps in at 2-7°C as migratory birds return to the Wadden Sea mudflats in staggering numbers. Skagen's famous light begins to intensify, and the fishing harbours shake off their winter quiet.",
    4: "Jutland brightens at 6-12°C with rapeseed fields turning the rolling farmland electric yellow. Legoland in Billund reopens, and the beaches of the west coast offer dramatic walks without summer crowds.",
    5: "Lovely at 10-16°C with wildflowers carpeting the heathlands and 17 hours of daylight stretching the evenings beautifully. The Limfjord oyster season runs strong, and Aarhus buzzes with outdoor festivals.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 14-19°C with the famously long Scandinavian evenings perfect for beach bonfires on the North Sea coast. Skagen's duelling seas and artistic heritage draw the first big wave of visitors.",
    7: "Peak season at 16-21°C brings Danish holidaymakers to the west coast's endless sandy beaches and iconic summer houses. Aarhus Festival fills the city with music, food, and street performances.",
    8: "Warm at 16-20°C with the North Sea reaching a swimmable 17-18°C for the brave. Ribe, Denmark's oldest town, glows in the late summer light, and the Wadden Sea offers unforgettable mudflat walks.",
    9: "The crowds vanish at 12-17°C, leaving Jutland's beaches and heaths peaceful and golden. Oyster season begins on the Limfjord, and Aarhus's food scene heats up with harvest menus and new restaurant openings.",
    10: "Autumn storms make the west coast dramatically wild at 7-12°C—perfect for moody coastal walks and photographing Rubjerg Knude lighthouse. The Viking museums in Jelling and Ribe are crowd-free and atmospheric.",
    11: "Dark and wind-battered at 3-7°C, but Jutland's Christmas markets begin opening in Aarhus and Aalborg with genuine small-town warmth. The heathlands take on a brooding beauty under heavy skies.",
    12: "Winter takes hold at 1-4°C with Christmas markets, candlelit churches, and the Danish tradition of julefrokost (Christmas lunch) in full swing across the peninsula. Hygge isn't just a word here—it's a survival strategy.",
  },
  'dm-dominica': {
    1: "The Nature Isle emerges from hurricane season into dry-season glory at 24-29°C. Hiking the Waitukubuli Trail through rainforest is spectacular, and the diving at Champagne Reef—where volcanic bubbles rise from the seafloor—is pristine.",
    2: "Peak dry season brings 24-29°C days with lower humidity and clear skies ideal for tackling the Boiling Lake hike. Whale-watching season is in full swing with sperm whales resident just offshore year-round.",
    3: "Dry and gorgeous at 24-30°C—this is Dominica at its most accessible, with waterfalls still flowing strong and trails in prime condition. Carnival celebrations add Caribbean colour to the lush green backdrop.",
    4: "The transition month hovers at 25-30°C with occasional showers greening up the already impossibly verdant landscape. Fewer visitors than the winter peak mean you might have Titou Gorge's emerald pools to yourself.",
    5: "Wet season begins announcing itself with afternoon showers at 26-31°C, supercharging the waterfalls and river swimming holes. The rainforest canopy erupts with new growth, and birding is exceptional.",
    6: "Properly rainy at 26-31°C, with lush conditions that earned Dominica its Nature Isle nickname. Hiking trails can be muddy but the waterfalls are thundering and magnificent—pack waterproof everything.",
    7: "Hot and humid at 26-32°C with regular tropical downpours that keep the island magnificently green. Dive sites remain accessible, and the lack of cruise-ship crowds means authentic encounters with local culture.",
    8: "Deep wet season at 26-32°C with the highest rainfall and the start of hurricane risk. The adventurous are rewarded with dramatic skies, roaring rivers, and some of the lowest prices of the year.",
    9: "Peak hurricane season keeps most tourists away at 26-32°C, but Dominica's mountainous terrain and resilient spirit mean the island functions normally most days. Creole heritage celebrations begin building toward October's festival.",
    10: "World Creole Music Festival electrifies the island at 26-31°C despite the tail end of hurricane season. The cultural celebration draws visitors from across the Caribbean for three nights of bouyon, zouk, and calypso.",
    11: "Wet season winds down at 25-30°C with showers becoming less frequent and the forest in peak lushness. Hot springs like Wotten Waven feel especially magical in the cooler evening air.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 24-29°C with Christmas festivities blending Caribbean warmth and Creole tradition. The hiking is superb, the diving is clear, and Dominica remains blissfully uncommercialized.",
  },
  'do-puntacana': {
    1: "Peak season delivers 25-29°C perfection with minimal rain and steady trade winds that keep the heat comfortable. The all-inclusive resorts are fully loaded with snowbirds, so book well ahead for Bávaro Beach's powdery white sand.",
    2: "Gorgeous at 25-29°C with the driest month of the year and whale-watching excursions running to Samaná Bay. Valentine's season fills the resorts, and the golf courses along the coast are in immaculate condition.",
    3: "Still prime time at 25-30°C with dry skies and warm Caribbean water perfect for snorkeling at Isla Saona. Spring breakers start appearing but Punta Cana's scale absorbs them without overwhelming the vibe.",
    4: "The shoulder season begins at 26-31°C as brief afternoon showers appear without ruining beach days. Semana Santa brings Dominican families to the coast in festive force, and hotel rates start dipping.",
    5: "Rainy season starts softly at 27-31°C with short tropical downpours that actually cool things down nicely. Prices drop significantly, and the lush interior around Anamuya makes for striking zip-line adventures.",
    6: "Warm and humid at 27-32°C with regular afternoon rain that rarely lasts more than an hour. The east coast catches consistent trade winds, making this surprisingly good for kiteboarding and windsurfing.",
    7: "Hot at 27-33°C with a mix of sunshine and tropical showers keeping the palm-fringed beaches lively. Dominican summer vibes mean merengue on every corner, and the resorts offer deep discounts.",
    8: "Peak hurricane awareness month at 27-33°C, though Punta Cana's eastern position often spares it the worst. The bold are rewarded with empty beaches, rock-bottom rates, and genuinely warm Dominican hospitality.",
    9: "The wettest month at 26-32°C with the highest hurricane risk, but most days still deliver usable beach time between dramatic cloud formations. Off-season pricing makes luxury resorts surprisingly accessible.",
    10: "Rain begins tapering at 26-31°C as the season transitions toward the dry winter ahead. The landscape is at peak tropical lushness, and the diving at the underwater museum near Bayahibe is spectacular.",
    11: "Shoulder season sweet spot at 26-30°C with decreasing rain, thinning crowds, and rates that haven't yet climbed to peak pricing. The water visibility improves weekly, and excursions to indigenous caves are uncrowded.",
    12: "High season launches at 25-29°C with Christmas and New Year filling the resorts to capacity. The weather is reliable, the water is warm, and the beachfront New Year's Eve parties are legendary across the Caribbean.",
  },
  'do-santodomingo': {
    1: "The colonial Zona kicks off the year at 24-29°C with dry trade winds and manageable humidity. Santo Domingo's 500-year-old streets are blissfully walkable, and the north coast's surf scene at Cabarete is pumping.",
    2: "Carnival explodes across the country at 24-29°C, with La Vega's elaborate devil masks and Santo Domingo's Malecón parade rivaling anything in Brazil. The north coast stays dry and perfect for kiteboarding.",
    3: "Dry season glory at 25-30°C makes this ideal for exploring the Zona Colonial's UNESCO sites and the Cibao Valley's tobacco country. Dominican baseball season is in full playoff swing—catch a game at Quisqueya Stadium.",
    4: "Semana Santa transforms the country at 26-31°C as Dominicans pour onto northern beaches and mountain towns. Brief afternoon showers begin, and the Jarabacoa highlands offer waterfall-chasing at pleasant elevations.",
    5: "Rainy season arrives at 27-31°C with lush greenery overtaking the mountain roads to Constanza. Santo Domingo's restaurant scene—one of the Caribbean's most underrated—thrives without the tourist markup.",
    6: "Hot and humid at 27-32°C with daily downpours that make the interior waterfalls thunder impressively. Merengue festival season kicks into gear, and the north coast surf remains consistent at Playa Encuentro.",
    7: "Summer heat peaks at 27-33°C, but Santo Domingo's cultural calendar doesn't slow down. The Merengue Festival on the Malecón is a massive street party, and Puerto Plata's cable car offers breezy mountain escapes.",
    8: "Hurricane season's peak brings 27-33°C temps and dramatic tropical weather, but most days still deliver sunshine between showers. The adventurous score incredible hotel deals across the north coast.",
    9: "The wettest stretch at 26-32°C keeps the mountains spectacularly green while Santo Domingo's indoor attractions—museums, galleries, restaurants—shine without crowds. Off-season is when you eat best here.",
    10: "Rain eases at 26-31°C as the landscape remains impossibly lush and the tourist infrastructure catches its breath before winter season. The 27 Waterfalls of Damajagua are at their most dramatic flow.",
    11: "Transition month at 26-30°C with drier days returning and the north coast beaches clearing up beautifully. Santo Domingo's jazz festival and gallery nights signal the cultural season's return.",
    12: "Holiday season ignites at 25-29°C with the whole country celebrating through music, food, and family gatherings. The Zona Colonial is festively lit, northern beaches fill with Dominican vacationers, and the energy is electric.",
  },
  'dz-algiers': {
    1: "Mediterranean winter brings 9-15°C and frequent rain to Algiers, but the Casbah's layered Ottoman architecture looks magnificent under moody skies. Couscous Fridays take on extra warmth in the city's traditional restaurants.",
    2: "Similar to January at 9-16°C with rainy spells, but the coastal cliffs of Tipaza's Roman ruins are dramatically beautiful in winter light. Few tourists means the National Museum of Fine Arts is yours alone.",
    3: "Spring emerges at 11-18°C with wildflowers blooming along the coastal hillsides and the first warm days drawing Algerois to the corniche. The transition season offers the best balance of mild weather and empty sites.",
    4: "Lovely at 13-20°C with orange blossoms perfuming the Jardin d'Essai and the Mediterranean turning from grey to turquoise. Djemila and Timgad—Algeria's staggering Roman ruins—are comfortable to explore without summer's blaze.",
    5: "Warm and sunny at 16-24°C, this is arguably the best month for the Algerian coast. The beaches begin to fill, the seaside restaurants open their terraces, and the light over the white city is luminous.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 20-28°C with dry heat and long evenings along the Bay of Algiers. Ramadan timing varies yearly but can affect restaurant hours—plan accordingly and respect the rhythm.",
    7: "Hot and dry at 23-32°C as Algiers bakes and locals decamp to the cooler Kabyle mountains or the beaches east of the city. The Casbah's narrow streets provide merciful shade for determined explorers.",
    8: "Peak heat at 24-33°C makes coastal swimming the main activity, with beaches from Zeralda to Tigzirt packed with Algerian families. Evening promenades along the waterfront are the social event of the day.",
    9: "Heat eases to 21-29°C as the Mediterranean cools enough for comfortable sightseeing. The light turns golden over the Casbah, and the cultural season begins to stir in Algiers's underrated gallery scene.",
    10: "Autumn brings 17-25°C and the first rains, refreshing the dusty city and greening the surrounding hills. Olive harvest begins in Kabylie, and the coastal Roman sites are uncrowded and atmospheric.",
    11: "Cooling to 13-19°C with increasing rainfall, but the quieter pace suits deep exploration of Algiers's layered history from Phoenician to French colonial. Traditional hammams are at their most inviting.",
    12: "Winter settles in at 10-16°C with rain and grey skies, but Algiers's café culture—strong coffee, heated debates, and pastries—thrives indoors. New Year's celebrations along the waterfront can surprise with their energy.",
  },
  'dz-sahara': {
    1: "Desert winter brings cool nights near 5°C and pleasant days around 18-22°C—ideal for exploring the Tassili n'Ajjer rock art and the M'zab Valley's UNESCO-listed towns. The Sahara is at its most comfortable and photogenic.",
    2: "Still excellent at 7-23°C with clear skies and comfortable trekking temperatures across the Grand Erg Oriental. Tuareg guides run camel expeditions from Djanet and Tamanrasset through landscapes that defy imagination.",
    3: "Warming to 10-26°C as the window for comfortable desert exploration begins to narrow. The Hoggar Mountains around Tamanrasset offer cooler elevations and volcanic landscapes unlike anywhere else in North Africa.",
    4: "Sand-storm season begins as temps climb to 15-30°C, with the sirocco wind whipping through the ergs. Dawn and dusk remain magical at the oasis towns of Ghardaia and Timimoun, but midday is punishing.",
    5: "Seriously hot at 20-36°C—only experienced desert travelers should venture into the deep Sahara now. The oasis town of In Salah regularly records some of Africa's highest temperatures this month.",
    6: "Extreme heat of 25-42°C makes the Sahara a no-go zone for all but the most hardened adventurers. Even the M'zab Valley towns slow to a crawl, and travel infrastructure essentially shuts down.",
    7: "Peak furnace conditions at 28-45°C—the deep Sahara is genuinely dangerous and effectively closed to tourism. The Hoggar Mountains at elevation offer the only marginally tolerable conditions.",
    8: "Still brutally hot at 27-44°C, though rare summer rains can briefly transform patches of desert into surreal temporary meadows. This is a month for armchair travel planning, not execution.",
    9: "Heat begins retreating to 23-38°C, but comfortable conditions haven't returned yet. Late September evenings in the oasis towns start hinting at the coming cool season's relief.",
    10: "The Sahara reopens at 17-32°C as tour operators in Djanet and Tamanrasset fire up their Land Cruisers and camel trains. The Tassili's prehistoric rock art glows in the autumn light, and desert camping becomes magical again.",
    11: "Excellent conditions at 10-26°C for deep desert exploration—stargazing, dune trekking, and Tuareg tea ceremonies under vast skies. The Sebkha Festival in Timimoun celebrates oasis culture with music and horse racing.",
    12: "Prime Sahara season at 6-22°C with cold clear nights perfect for stargazing and warm days ideal for exploring. The annual Festival of the Sahara in Douz (across the Tunisian border) draws regional attention to desert culture.",
  },
  'ec-coast': {
    1: "The wet season is in full swing on the coast at 25-31°C with heavy tropical downpours and lush conditions in the Amazon basin. Whale-watching isn't running yet, but the rainforest biodiversity is at its most active and vocal.",
    2: "Peak rainy season brings 25-31°C and daily downpours to the coast, swelling Amazon tributaries for deep-jungle canoe adventures. Carnival hits Guayaquil and coastal towns with Afro-Ecuadorian rhythms and water fights.",
    3: "Still wet and hot at 25-31°C, but the Amazon lodges around Tena and Coca offer prime wildlife encounters as animals concentrate near waterways. Coastal beaches are less popular, meaning lower prices and fewer crowds.",
    4: "Rain begins easing on the coast at 25-30°C while the Amazon remains lush and wildlife-rich. Semana Santa celebrations bring the country to festive life, and Montañita's surf scene stays consistent through the transition.",
    5: "The coastal dry season begins at 23-28°C with the garúa mist rolling in but rainfall dropping sharply. Humpback whale season starts off Puerto López—one of South America's most accessible whale-watching experiences.",
    6: "Cool and misty on the coast at 22-26°C as the Humboldt Current chills the Pacific. Whale watching peaks, and the Amazon experiences drier conditions with better trail access and concentrated wildlife around shrinking pools.",
    7: "The garúa keeps the coast overcast at 21-25°C, but humpback whales are breaching spectacularly off Isla de la Plata, the 'poor man's Galápagos.' Amazon dry season makes for excellent jungle trekking.",
    8: "Coastal dry season continues at 21-25°C with peak whale-watching conditions and the best visibility for snorkeling off Machalilla National Park. The Amazon forest floor is walkable, and indigenous communities welcome visitors.",
    9: "Whale season winds down at 22-26°C as the coast begins warming again. The Amazon transitions with occasional showers, and the cloud forests around Mindo offer spectacular birding with 500+ species.",
    10: "The wet season returns to the coast at 23-28°C with sporadic showers and warming seas. Last chance for whale sightings, and the Amazon's rising waters begin opening new canoe routes through flooded forest.",
    11: "Rain increases at 24-29°C as the coast greens up and the Amazon basin starts its seasonal flood cycle. Fewer tourists overall mean better prices and more personal attention at jungle lodges.",
    12: "Full wet season at 25-30°C with heavy tropical downpours on the coast and rising Amazon waters. Christmas celebrations bring unique coastal Afro-Ecuadorian traditions, and the warm rains make everything explosively verdant.",
  },
  'fr-paris': {
    1: "Paris in January is quietly magnificent at 3-7°C—the Louvre without queues, bistros glowing with warmth, and the winter sales (soldes) offering genuine bargains. The grey skies and bare chestnut trees have their own austere beauty.",
    2: "Still chilly at 3-8°C but Paris Fashion Week electrifies the Marais and Saint-Germain with style and spectacle. Crêpes are everywhere for La Chandeleur, and the museums remain blissfully uncrowded.",
    3: "Spring arrives tentatively at 6-12°C with magnolias blooming in the Tuileries and the first café terrasses opening along the Seine. The light shifts from winter grey to that luminous quality that inspired the Impressionists.",
    4: "Gorgeous at 8-16°C with cherry blossoms framing Notre-Dame and chestnut trees leafing out along the boulevards. This is arguably Paris at its most romantic—warm enough for long walks, cool enough for comfort.",
    5: "Magnificent at 12-19°C with the Luxembourg Gardens in full bloom and every Parisian outdoors along the Canal Saint-Martin. The French Open begins at Roland-Garros, and the golden hour stretches past 9 PM.",
    6: "Summer in Paris at 15-23°C is a dream of long evenings, rosé on rooftop terraces, and the Fête de la Musique flooding every street with live music on June 21st. Crowds build but the magic is undeniable.",
    7: "Peak tourist season at 17-25°C means the Eiffel Tower queue is brutal, but Paris Plages transforms the Seine's banks into urban beaches. Bastille Day fireworks on July 14th are spectacular from Trocadéro.",
    8: "Hot at 17-25°C and curiously emptier as Parisians flee to the coast, leaving the city to tourists and a languid August charm. Many neighbourhood shops close, but the major attractions run full tilt.",
    9: "The rentrée brings Paris back to life at 14-21°C as Parisians return, galleries launch new exhibitions, and the fashion calendar revs up. Golden light, manageable crowds, and harvest menus make this a perfect visit.",
    10: "Autumn paints the Jardin du Luxembourg in amber at 10-16°C, and the Nuit Blanche arts festival turns the city into an all-night gallery. The cultural season is in full swing, and the bistro menus turn hearty.",
    11: "Grey and moody at 6-11°C, but Beaujolais Nouveau launches on the third Thursday with nationwide celebration. Christmas illuminations begin on the Champs-Élysées, and the first vin chaud stalls appear at emerging markets.",
    12: "Christmas transforms Paris at 4-8°C with markets at Trocadéro and the Tuileries, sparkling lights on every grand boulevard, and shop windows turned into theatrical displays. Cold but absolutely magical.",
  },
  'fr-provence': {
    1: "The Mistral wind slices through Provence at 3-11°C, but the low winter sun paints Aix-en-Provence's honey-coloured stone in gorgeous light. Truffle markets in Richerenches and Carpentras make January a gourmet pilgrimage.",
    2: "Almond blossoms begin appearing at 4-12°C as the earliest signs of Provençal spring emerge. The Côte d'Azur's Nice Carnival fills the Promenade des Anglais with flower battles and costumed parades.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 7-15°C with mimosa blazing yellow across the hillsides and the first rosé of the season appearing on café tables. The Camargue's flamingos and wild horses are spectacular against greening marshes.",
    4: "Lovely at 10-18°C with wildflowers carpeting the Luberon and the hilltop villages of Gordes and Roussillon basking in clear Mediterranean light. Easter brings provençal traditions and the first outdoor antique markets.",
    5: "Stunning at 14-22°C as the Mediterranean warms up and the Cannes Film Festival brings glamour to the Riviera. The lavender isn't blooming yet, but the countryside is lush and the markets overflow with spring produce.",
    6: "The lavender begins its purple reign at 18-27°C across the Valensole plateau and Sénanque Abbey. Long golden evenings are made for rosé in Cassis, bouillabaisse in Marseille, and the scent of wild herbs on every breeze.",
    7: "Peak Provence at 21-30°C with lavender fields in full, intoxicating bloom and every hilltop village packed with admirers. The Festival d'Avignon transforms the papal city into the world's greatest open-air theatre.",
    8: "Hot and dry at 21-30°C as the Mediterranean beach towns fill with French vacationers and the inland heat shimmers over harvested lavender fields. Evening is everything—the Provençal dinner hour starts at 9 PM.",
    9: "The magical shoulder season at 17-26°C as crowds vanish, the sea remains warm for swimming, and the vendange (grape harvest) fills the countryside with activity. This might be the single best month for Provence.",
    10: "Autumn golds arrive at 12-20°C with mushroom foraging in the Luberon, olive harvest beginning, and the Côte d'Azur still warm enough for seaside lunches. Prices drop significantly from summer peaks.",
    11: "Quiet and atmospheric at 7-14°C as Provence retreats into its local rhythms. New olive oil flows at the mills, truffles return to the markets, and the Mistral clears the skies to an impossible blue.",
    12: "Cool but sunny at 4-11°C with Provençal Christmas traditions—thirteen desserts, santons figurines, and midnight mass at ancient churches. The Foire aux Santons in Marseille and Aix captures centuries of tradition in miniature.",
  },
  'ga-gabon': {
    1: "Deep in the rainy season at 25-30°C, Gabon's rainforests are at their most primordial and atmospheric. Lopé National Park's gorillas and forest elephants are harder to track in dense vegetation, but the jungle experience is unmatched.",
    2: "Still rainy and humid at 25-30°C, but the lowland gorilla habituation programs at Lopé continue year-round. The Ogooué River runs high and brown, and Libreville's waterfront buzzes despite the downpours.",
    3: "Wet season continues at 25-30°C with heavy afternoon storms that feed the equatorial forest's extraordinary biodiversity. Surfing hippos at Loango National Park are a genuine phenomenon best witnessed with a specialist guide.",
    4: "Rain begins easing slightly at 25-30°C as the forest canopy reaches maximum lushness. Loango's beach-forest wildlife corridor—elephants, buffalo, and hippos on pristine Atlantic beaches—is one of Africa's most surreal sights.",
    5: "The brief dry season begins at 24-29°C, making this the start of prime wildlife-viewing in Gabon's national parks. Forest elephants gather at Langoué Bai clearing in Ivindo National Park in remarkable concentrations.",
    6: "Dry season proper at 23-28°C with the best conditions for gorilla trekking, forest elephant encounters, and exploring the spectacular Kongou Falls in Ivindo. This is peak season for Gabon's emerging ecotourism.",
    7: "The driest month at 22-27°C offers the best wildlife visibility and most comfortable trekking conditions. Humpback whales arrive offshore, and Loango's combination of beach, lagoon, and forest makes for extraordinary safari days.",
    8: "Cool and dry at 22-27°C with humpback whales breaching off Mayumba and Loango while forest elephants roam the beaches below. This is Gabon at its most accessible—dry trails, clear skies, and active wildlife.",
    9: "The dry season fades at 23-28°C as the first rains return. Whale watching remains excellent, and the transition period keeps the forest trails passable while the landscape starts greening up dramatically.",
    10: "Rains return in earnest at 24-30°C, swelling rivers and transforming the forest floor into a carpet of mushrooms and new growth. The birding is exceptional as migratory species arrive to join the resident 700+ species.",
    11: "Full wet season at 24-30°C with heavy tropical downpours and spectacular thunder. Leatherback turtle nesting begins on Pongara and Mayumba beaches—watching a prehistoric giant haul itself ashore is a lifetime experience.",
    12: "Rainy and warm at 25-30°C with leatherback turtle nesting in full swing on the Atlantic beaches. The forest is challenging but magical, and Libreville's festive season brings Gabonese music and cuisine to the foreground.",
  },
  'gb-london': {
    1: "London is grey, damp, and 4-8°C, but the January sales, nearly empty museums, and cozy pub fires make for a rewarding visit. West End theatre tickets are plentiful, and the Tube is blessedly uncrowded.",
    2: "Still chilly at 4-9°C with occasional frost, but Chinese New Year in Soho brings spectacular celebrations, and the Six Nations rugby fills every pub with roaring fans. London Fashion Week adds glamour to the grey.",
    3: "Spring begins to stir at 5-11°C with daffodils in Hyde Park and the first outdoor café seating appearing on the South Bank. The boat race between Oxford and Cambridge draws crowds to the Thames in late March.",
    4: "London at 7-14°C is genuinely lovely—cherry blossoms in Greenwich Park, the London Marathon cheering through the streets, and the first hint that this city actually gets sunshine. Book early for Easter weekend.",
    5: "The Chelsea Flower Show signals summer's approach at 10-17°C with the city's parks in full bloom and the Thames-side terraces finally earning their keep. Long evenings and Borough Market at its seasonal best.",
    6: "Summer at 13-20°C brings Trooping the Colour, Wimbledon fever, and the impossibility of getting a rooftop bar reservation. The days stretch to 9:30 PM, and every park becomes an unofficial picnic venue.",
    7: "Peak season at 15-23°C with the Proms at the Royal Albert Hall, outdoor cinemas in every park, and tourists thronging the Tower of London. The heat can surprise—London rarely does air conditioning well.",
    8: "Notting Hill Carnival electrifies the August Bank Holiday weekend at 15-22°C with Caribbean culture, sound systems, and jerk chicken. Many Londoners escape to the coast, leaving certain neighbourhoods pleasantly quiet.",
    9: "The crowds thin at 13-19°C as the cultural season opens with new exhibitions, theatre premieres, and the London Design Festival. Golden afternoon light on the Thames is photographer's gold.",
    10: "Autumn colour transforms the royal parks at 9-15°C, and the Frieze Art Fair brings the international art world to Regent's Park. Cozy pub season begins in earnest—this is London at its most atmospheric.",
    11: "Bonfire Night on November 5th lights up the sky at 6-11°C, followed by Christmas lights switching on across Oxford Street and Regent Street. The city pivots to its winter personality—darker, cozier, theatrically lit.",
    12: "Christmas London at 4-8°C is a glittering affair of markets at the South Bank, ice rinks at Somerset House, and Boxing Day sales that Londoners treat as competitive sport. Wrap up warm and soak in the festive energy.",
  },
  'gb-north': {
    1: "Edinburgh and northern England hunker down at 1-6°C with short days and the possibility of snow dusting Arthur's Seat. Burns Night on January 25th fills Scottish pubs with haggis, whisky, and heartfelt recitations.",
    2: "Still raw at 1-7°C, but the Six Nations rugby turns Edinburgh's pubs into cauldrons of noise on match days. The Yorkshire Dales offer stark winter beauty, and Durham Cathedral is atmospheric in the grey light.",
    3: "Spring teases at 3-9°C with snowdrops and crocuses breaking through in the Borders and the Lake District. Edinburgh's cultural calendar begins stirring, and the Northumberland coast is hauntingly beautiful without summer crowds.",
    4: "Daffodils carpet the Lake District at 5-12°C—Wordsworth wasn't exaggerating. Edinburgh's gardens green up, York's medieval walls are walkable without tourist bottlenecks, and the days stretch noticeably.",
    5: "Lovely at 8-15°C with bluebells flooding the Lake District woodlands and Edinburgh sparkling in the spring sunshine. The Yorkshire coast's whitby goth weekend and Hadrian's Wall walking season are in full swing.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 10-17°C with impossibly long northern evenings and Edinburgh's Old Town looking magnificent in the evening light. The Lake District and Yorkshire Dales offer superb hiking with wildflower-filled meadows.",
    7: "The warmest month at 12-19°C brings peak hiking conditions across the Pennines and Lake District fells. Edinburgh prepares for August's festival onslaught, and the Northumberland beaches are warm enough for the brave.",
    8: "Edinburgh Festival and Fringe transform the city into the world's largest arts event at 12-19°C—every spare room is a venue, every street corner a stage. Book accommodation months ahead or don't bother trying.",
    9: "The Festival hangover gives way to golden autumn at 10-16°C with Edinburgh returning to its residents and the Lake District draped in russet and amber. The Yorkshire food festivals showcase the region's excellent produce.",
    10: "Autumn colour peaks at 7-13°C across the Lake District, Yorkshire Dales, and Scottish Borders. Halloween in Edinburgh is atmospheric beyond measure—the city practically invented gothic. Whisky season begins.",
    11: "Dark and dramatic at 3-8°C with Edinburgh's Christmas market opening and Bonfire Night celebrations lighting up the northern skies. The Lake District goes moody and magnificent under heavy cloud.",
    12: "Festive season at 2-6°C brings Edinburgh's Hogmanay preparations—the world's greatest New Year's celebration builds through December with torch-lit processions and ceilidh dancing. Northern England's Christmas markets are intimate and genuine.",
  },
  'gb-scotland': {
    1: "The Highlands are at their most raw and dramatic at 1-6°C, with snow on the Cairngorms, roaring fires in remote bothies, and the Northern Lights occasionally dancing over Caithness. Midges are mercifully absent.",
    2: "Still winter-wild at 1-7°C with excellent skiing at Glencoe and Cairngorm when conditions cooperate. The west coast gets battered by Atlantic storms that are genuinely thrilling to watch from a warm pub window.",
    3: "Hints of spring appear at 2-8°C as red deer descend from the high ground and the first lambs dot the glen floors. Inverness and the Great Glen are uncrowded and the castle ruins feel properly ancient.",
    4: "Spring greens the glens at 4-11°C while snow still caps the Munros—a beautiful contrast that makes for spectacular hiking. Osprey return to their nests at Loch Garten, and the whisky distillery tours run without queues.",
    5: "The Highlands bloom at 7-14°C with rhododendrons exploding in colour around the great houses and lochs. The infamous midges haven't arrived yet, making this the secret sweet spot for Highland exploration.",
    6: "Long days at 9-15°C with sunset past 10 PM and the landscape at peak green make June magnificent, but the midges arrive in force. Pack repellent, stick to breezy ridgelines, and the rewards are extraordinary.",
    7: "The warmest month at 11-17°C brings the Highland Games season—tossing cabers, pipe bands, and heavy drinking in equal measure. Midges are hellish in calm conditions but the scenery compensates magnificently.",
    8: "Still warm at 11-17°C with the Edinburgh Festival's energy rippling north. The west coast's white-sand beaches (yes, really) are stunning when the sun appears, and whale-watching off the Hebrides peaks.",
    9: "Autumn colour begins its spectacular Highland display at 9-14°C with golden birches against purple heather. The midges retreat, red deer rutting season begins with dramatic roaring across the glens, and the light turns extraordinary.",
    10: "The Highlands at peak autumn colour (6-11°C) are heart-stoppingly beautiful—amber glens, dark lochs, and the first dustings of snow on the peaks. Whisky festival season runs across Speyside, and storms provide dramatic theatre.",
    11: "Dark, wild, and atmospheric at 3-8°C with gales battering the coast and snow settling on the higher ground. The Northern Lights season intensifies, and the whisky seems to taste better when the wind is howling.",
    12: "The Highlands go full Scottish winter at 1-6°C with short days, possible snow, and Hogmanay celebrations building toward the year's end. Edinburgh's famous street party and the Highland tradition of first-footing make New Year unforgettable.",
  },
  'gb-wales': {
    1: "Wales and the Southwest hunker down at 3-8°C with wild winter surf on the Pembrokeshire coast and cozy pubs in the Brecon Beacons. Snowdonia might actually have snow, and the lack of crowds is the real luxury.",
    2: "Still raw at 3-9°C with daffodils beginning to appear—fitting for the land of the leek and the dragon. St David's Day on March 1st (just next month) inspires early celebrations, and Six Nations rugby electrifies Cardiff.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 5-11°C with St David's Day celebrations on the 1st, daffodils carpeting every hillside, and the Pembrokeshire Coast Path coming alive with wildflowers. Cornwall's pasty shops reopen their terraces optimistically.",
    4: "Lovely at 7-13°C with bluebell woods across the Gower Peninsula and spring lambs everywhere you look. The Southwest's surf season picks up, and Snowdon's summit views clear after months of cloud.",
    5: "The Pembrokeshire coast is spectacular at 10-16°C with puffins returning to Skomer Island, wildflowers rioting along the cliff paths, and the sea warming enough for wetsuit-clad adventurers. Devon cream teas beckon.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 12-18°C with the Hay Festival of literature drawing bookworms to the Welsh borders and the Gower beaches finally earning their 'Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty' title. Daylight lasts until 10 PM.",
    7: "Peak season at 14-20°C brings families to the Pembrokeshire beaches and hikers to Snowdonia's ridges. The Royal Welsh Show celebrates agricultural life, and Cornwall's fishing villages are at their most picturesque.",
    8: "Warm at 14-20°C with the National Eisteddfod—Wales's extraordinary festival of poetry, music, and culture—moving to a different location each year. Cornwall and Devon beaches are packed; head to Ceredigion for breathing room.",
    9: "The crowds evaporate at 12-18°C, leaving the Pembrokeshire Coast Path peaceful and the Brecon Beacons draped in early autumn gold. Seal pup season begins on Ramsey Island—adorable and uncrowded.",
    10: "Autumn colour sweeps through the Wye Valley and Brecon Beacons at 9-14°C, and the surfing on the Gower picks up with autumn swells. Dylan Thomas festivals honour Swansea's literary hero around his October birthday.",
    11: "Dark and atmospheric at 5-10°C with Guy Fawkes bonfires lighting up November 5th and the first Christmas markets opening in Cardiff and Bath. The coast goes dramatically stormy—bring waterproofs and embrace the wildness.",
    12: "Festive Wales at 4-8°C means Welsh male voice choirs in candlelit chapels, Cardiff's Winter Wonderland, and Bath's magnificent Christmas market in the shadow of the Abbey. A genuinely charming corner of Britain at Christmas.",
  },
  'gd-grenada': {
    1: "The Spice Isle is in its dry-season prime at 24-30°C with trade winds keeping the humidity bearable and Grand Anse Beach living up to its reputation. Nutmeg, cinnamon, and cocoa perfume the mountain air on plantation tours.",
    2: "Dry and gorgeous at 24-30°C—perfect conditions for sailing the Grenadines, snorkeling Molinière's underwater sculpture park, and hiking to Seven Sisters Falls. Independence Day on February 7th brings calypso and colour.",
    3: "Peak dry season at 25-31°C with the driest month offering clear visibility for diving and the most reliable sunshine for beach days. The interior's rainforest trails are in prime condition for the Grand Etang hike.",
    4: "Still dry and warm at 25-31°C as the shoulder season approaches. Easter celebrations blend Caribbean and Catholic traditions, and the fishing boats at Gouyave bring in the freshest catch for the island's famous fish Fridays.",
    5: "Transition month at 26-31°C as brief afternoon showers return without ruining the beach vibe. Prices drop, crowds thin, and Grenada's authentic Creole culture—spice markets, rum shops, cocoa estates—is easier to access.",
    6: "Wet season begins at 26-31°C with regular tropical showers that keep the volcanic interior spectacularly green. The nutmeg processing stations welcome visitors, and the chocolate-making experiences are world-class.",
    7: "Rainy at 26-31°C but Grenada's size means you can drive from a downpour to sunshine in twenty minutes. The island's rum distilleries offer excellent tours, and the underwater sculpture park glows in the summer light.",
    8: "Hurricane season's peak at 26-31°C keeps some visitors away, but Grenada sits south of the main hurricane belt—it's hit less often than most Caribbean islands. The Spicemas (carnival) in August is spectacular.",
    9: "Still in hurricane season at 26-31°C, but Grenada's southern location provides relative protection. The rainforest is at maximum lushness, and diving conditions can be excellent between passing weather systems.",
    10: "Rain tapers at 26-31°C as the wet season begins its retreat. The nutmeg harvest is in full swing, and the fishing village of Gouyave's Friday night fish fry is a genuine cultural institution worth planning around.",
    11: "Transition back to dry at 25-30°C with showers becoming less frequent and the diving visibility improving weekly. Grenada's boutique hotel scene has grown impressively—this is Caribbean luxury without the pretension.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 24-30°C with Christmas celebrations that blend Caribbean warmth with small-island intimacy. The sailing season opens in the Grenadines, and Grenada's New Year's jab jab celebrations are delightfully raucous.",
  },
  'ge-svaneti': {
    1: "Svaneti is buried under deep snow at -10 to -2°C, with the medieval tower villages of Mestia and Ushguli looking like something from a frozen fairy tale. Backcountry skiing is emerging, and the isolation is absolute and beautiful.",
    2: "Still deep winter at -8 to 0°C with the Hatsvali and Tetnuldi ski areas offering surprisingly good terrain without the crowds or prices of the Alps. Traditional Svan feasting continues through the long evenings.",
    3: "Snow lingers at -5 to 3°C as the first hints of lengthening days appear in the high valleys. Late-season skiing can be excellent, and the tower-house villages are atmospheric under their winter blanket.",
    4: "Spring begins its slow arrival at 0-8°C, but high passes remain snowbound and many trails are impassable. Lower Svaneti greens up, and the wildflowers begin their spectacular Caucasian display at lower elevations.",
    5: "The thaw accelerates at 5-14°C, though high mountain passes may still be closed. Wildflowers carpet the lower meadows, and the rivers run wild with snowmelt—a dramatic time to visit with limited hiking options.",
    6: "Summer arrives in the high Caucasus at 10-20°C, opening the spectacular trekking routes between Mestia and Ushguli. Wildflower meadows beneath 5,000m peaks create scenery that rivals anything in the Alps or Himalayas.",
    7: "Peak trekking season at 12-22°C with the Mestia-to-Ushguli trail in prime condition and the tower villages accessible by road. The Caucasian peaks gleam with snow against impossibly blue skies, and the guesthouses overflow with hikers.",
    8: "Still excellent at 12-22°C for high-altitude trekking, with the Koruldi Lakes and Ushba glacier trails offering world-class mountain scenery. The Svan hospitality—endless toasts of chacha, communal feasts—is as memorable as the peaks.",
    9: "Autumn begins gilding the valleys at 7-16°C while the high trails remain open. The crowds thin dramatically, and the harvest brings traditional Svan bread, cheese, and honey to the guesthouse tables.",
    10: "Golden autumn at 3-12°C with the birch and beech forests ablaze against the snow-capped Caucasus. Many trails remain passable, and the shoulder season means you might have Ushguli's medieval towers entirely to yourself.",
    11: "Winter arrives swiftly at -3 to 5°C with the first heavy snows closing the high passes. The ski season begins to stir at Hatsvali, and the tower villages hunker down with supplies of cheese, bread, and chacha.",
    12: "Deep winter at -8 to 0°C transforms Svaneti into a snow-globe wonderland. Skiing picks up, the traditional New Year celebrations (Lamproba) involve torchlit processions, and the isolation gives this place its timeless magic.",
  },
  'ge-tbilisi': {
    1: "Tbilisi's winter hovers at 0-6°C with occasional snow dusting the Old Town's balconied houses and the sulphur baths in Abanotubani steaming invitingly. Wine flows freely in the qvevri-stocked cellars, and churchkhela hangs in every market.",
    2: "Still cold at 1-7°C, but Tbilisi's café culture thrives with strong Georgian coffee and khachapuri that could warm the coldest soul. The city's eclectic architecture—Art Nouveau, Soviet, medieval—looks dramatic under winter skies.",
    3: "Spring emerges at 5-12°C with almond blossoms along the Mtkvari River and the first outdoor tables appearing on Shardeni Street. The wine bars of the Old Town are less crowded than summer, and prices reflect it.",
    4: "Lovely at 10-18°C as Tbilisi's parks burst into bloom and the city's energy shifts outdoors. Easter is massive in Orthodox Georgia—midnight church services, painted eggs, and family feasts that last for days.",
    5: "Gorgeous at 14-23°C with the Botanical Garden lush above the Old Town and the rooftop bars opening for the season. Tbilisoba food culture is at its most vibrant, and day trips to Mtskheta and the wine country are ideal.",
    6: "Warm at 18-27°C with long evenings perfect for strolling the Old Town's winding streets and dining alfresco on Leselidze Street. The heat hasn't peaked yet, making this perfect for exploring the city on foot.",
    7: "Hot at 22-32°C—Tbilisi earns its name ('warm place') as the city bakes and locals retreat to the sulphur baths or escape to the mountains. Evening dining on vine-draped terraces is the social centre of life.",
    8: "Peak heat at 22-33°C drives the action indoors during midday, but the Mtatsminda amusement park catches evening breezes with panoramic city views. Rtveli (grape harvest) preparations begin in Kakheti wine country.",
    9: "The heat eases to 17-27°C as Rtveli grape harvest transforms Kakheti into a working celebration—stomping grapes, feasting, and toasting with amber-coloured qvevri wine. Tbilisi's cultural season reignites.",
    10: "Tbilisoba city festival celebrates with food, wine, and music at 11-20°C while autumn gilds the hillsides above the city. The wine country is in its golden hour, and the light on the Old Town is painterly.",
    11: "Cooling to 5-13°C with autumn fog drifting through the Mtkvari gorge and the city's cultural calendar running full. Georgian cuisine—khinkali, mtsvadi, lobiani—is at its most soul-warming as the cold settles in.",
    12: "Winter returns at 1-7°C with Christmas approaching on January 7th (Orthodox calendar) and New Year's being the main December celebration. The Old Town twinkles with lights, and the sulphur baths are perfection after a cold day.",
  },
  'gh-ghana': {
    1: "Harmattan haze from the Sahara gives Accra a dusty, dry edge at 25-32°C, but the beaches at Labadi and Kokrobite are golden and warm. The Elmina and Cape Coast castles are powerful and uncrowded, a necessary pilgrimage.",
    2: "Still dry and hazy at 26-33°C as the Harmattan fades and the coast clears. The Kakum National Park canopy walkway offers sweaty but spectacular rainforest views, and Accra's Chale Wote street art festival brings creative energy.",
    3: "The hottest month at 27-33°C before the rains arrive, with the coast at peak beach weather. Kwame Nkrumah Memorial Park and the vibrant Makola Market give Accra's history and hustle a vivid introduction.",
    4: "The first rains arrive at 26-32°C, greening the Volta Region's hills and bringing relief from the dry-season dust. The Adae Festival celebrations at Kumasi's Manhyia Palace showcase Ashanti royal culture in gold-draped splendour.",
    5: "Proper rainy season at 25-31°C with heavy afternoon downpours that keep the forests lush and the waterfalls thundering. Wli Waterfalls in the Volta Region—West Africa's tallest—are at their most impressive now.",
    6: "Peak rains at 24-29°C make roads to remote areas challenging, but Accra functions normally and the cultural scene thrives. Homowo festival preparations begin among the Ga people of Greater Accra.",
    7: "A relative dry spell at 23-27°C provides a brief window of easier travel. The Homowo harvest festival brings drumming, dancing, and sprinkled kpokpoi through Accra's oldest neighbourhoods—a genuinely unique cultural experience.",
    8: "Cool for Ghana at 23-27°C with the rains pausing—the 'little dry season' makes August surprisingly pleasant for travel. The Chale Wote Street Art Festival (if it falls here) transforms James Town into an open-air gallery.",
    9: "Rains return at 24-29°C for their final push, keeping the north's Mole National Park green and its elephants concentrated around waterholes. The south's cultural festivals continue in force.",
    10: "The rains taper at 25-30°C as the country transitions to dry season. The Aboakyir deer hunt festival in Winneba is one of Ghana's most spectacular traditional celebrations, and the coast clears for beach weather.",
    11: "Dry season settles in at 26-32°C with comfortable humidity and clear skies perfect for beach time, castle visits, and the arts scene in Accra's Osu neighbourhood. Panafest and Emancipation Day draw the diaspora home.",
    12: "Dry and warm at 26-32°C with Harmattan dust just beginning to arrive from the north. Christmas celebrations are exuberant across this predominantly Christian nation, and the beach bars at Kokrobite keep the music flowing.",
  },
  'gm-gambia': {
    1: "Peak dry season delivers 24-34°C with cloudless skies and the Gambia River at its lowest, concentrating birdlife spectacularly. The beaches of the Atlantic coast are gorgeous, and the all-inclusive resorts hum with European sun-seekers.",
    2: "Dry and hot at 24-36°C with the best birdwatching on the West African coast—Abuko Nature Reserve alone hosts 270+ species in a remarkably compact area. The Roots Festival celebrates heritage with music and storytelling.",
    3: "The hottest time at 26-38°C before the rains, with the river's banks alive with basking crocodiles and nesting birds. Kachikally Crocodile Pool in Bakau offers surreal close encounters, and the beach scene stays lively.",
    4: "Scorching at 27-40°C as the dry season reaches its crescendo and the landscape turns parched and golden. The coast catches Atlantic breezes that make beach-side lodges bearable, but inland travel requires serious heat tolerance.",
    5: "Transition month at 27-39°C with the first tentative rains and building humidity. Tourism winds down, prices drop, and the Gambian hospitality—famously warm even by West African standards—becomes more personal.",
    6: "The wet season arrives at 26-35°C with dramatic afternoon thunderstorms that turn the river delta vivid green. Tourism essentially pauses, but the birdlife shifts to breeding plumage and spectacular aerial displays.",
    7: "Heavy rains at 25-33°C transform the Gambia into a lush, flooded landscape that's challenging for travel but incredible for nature. The river rises dramatically, and rice paddies fill with egrets and herons.",
    8: "Peak rains at 25-32°C keep most tourists away, but the countryside is at maximum African beauty—impossibly green under dramatic grey skies. Accommodation is cheap, and the cultural interactions feel deeply authentic.",
    9: "Rains continue at 25-32°C with the countryside still lush and the river running full. The harvest season approaches, and village life is vibrant with preparation. Mosquitoes are at their worst—malaria prophylaxis is essential.",
    10: "The rains ease at 25-33°C as the dry season approaches and birdlife begins its spectacular winter migration arrivals. The landscape remains green, and the shoulder season offers good value with improving conditions.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25-34°C with migratory birds arriving in massive numbers from Europe and the beaches clearing up beautifully. The tourist season opens, and the riverboat excursions upstream to Janjanbureh resume.",
    12: "Peak season at 24-34°C with perfect beach weather, outstanding birding, and comfortable temperatures for exploring upriver villages by boat. Christmas draws festive celebrations from Gambia's multi-faith communities.",
  },
  'gn-guinea': {
    1: "Dry season grips Guinea at 24-34°C with Harmattan haze filtering over Conakry and the Fouta Djallon highlands dry and walkable. The sandstone plateaus offer trekking without the mud, and the waterfall network, while reduced, remains scenic.",
    2: "Still dry and dusty at 25-36°C with the landscape baked golden. The Fouta Djallon's villages are accessible and welcoming, and the traditional Fula culture of the highlands makes for rich cultural immersion.",
    3: "The hottest month at 26-37°C before the rains, with Conakry sweltering and the beaches at Îles de Los providing essential cooling offshore escapes. The mango season begins, flooding markets with fragrant fruit.",
    4: "Heat builds to 27-36°C as the first rains tease the southern forest region. Guinea's music scene—the birthplace of Afrobeat's roots—pulses through Conakry's nightclubs with live balafon and kora performances.",
    5: "The rains arrive at 26-33°C, first in the south and rolling north. The Fouta Djallon begins greening spectacularly, and the waterfalls of Kinkon and Kambadaga start building toward their rainy-season splendour.",
    6: "Wet season intensifies at 25-31°C with daily tropical downpours making travel challenging but the landscape transformative. The Fouta Djallon's waterfalls thunder to life, and the forest zone is at peak biodiversity.",
    7: "Heavy rains at 24-29°C make Guinea's roads treacherous—a 4x4 and patience are essential. The waterfalls are spectacular, the rice paddies fill with brilliant green, and the air is thick with tropical humidity.",
    8: "Peak rainfall at 24-28°C essentially pauses tourism in much of the country, but Conakry's cultural life—music, markets, street food—doesn't stop for weather. This is Guinea at its most raw and authentic.",
    9: "Rains continue at 24-29°C with the country at maximum lushness. The wetlands attract spectacular birdlife, and the rivers run full through the highland gorges. Travel remains challenging but the rewards are real.",
    10: "Rains taper at 25-31°C as the landscape retains its green glory but the trails begin drying. The Fouta Djallon is magnificent in the transitional light, and the harvest festivals begin in rural communities.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25-33°C with clear skies and improving roads. The highland trekking opens up, and Guinea's artisan markets—hand-dyed textiles, carved masks, gold jewellery—are at their most active.",
    12: "Dry and comfortable at 24-33°C with the Fouta Djallon's terraced hillsides golden in the winter light. Christmas celebrations mix with local traditions, and Conakry's live music scene offers unforgettable evening entertainment.",
  },
  'gp-guadeloupe': {
    1: "Dry season brings 24-28°C perfection to this French Caribbean butterfly-shaped archipelago. Basse-Terre's volcanic rainforest is lush but manageable, and the beaches of Grande-Terre glow white against turquoise water. Expect French bakeries with a Creole twist.",
    2: "Carnival season explodes across Guadeloupe at 24-28°C with elaborate Mardi Gras parades, costumed dancers, and the unique tradition of black-and-white dress days. The weather is impeccable for combining beach and volcano hiking.",
    3: "Still dry and gorgeous at 24-29°C with Carnival's energy lingering into early March. La Soufrière volcano hike offers cloud-forest immersion, and the rum distilleries of Marie-Galante island make for an excellent day trip.",
    4: "Transition month at 25-30°C as brief showers begin but don't dampen the experience. Easter brings the tradition of crab hunting (matoutou de crabe), and the Saintes archipelago offers postcard-perfect sailing conditions.",
    5: "Wet season creeps in at 26-31°C with afternoon showers that rarely last long. The Jacques Cousteau Reserve offers world-class diving off Pigeon Island, and mango season fills the markets with fragrant fruit.",
    6: "Rainy season at 26-31°C with lush, humid conditions that supercharge the volcanic rainforest's waterfalls. Fewer tourists mean the beaches of Sainte-Anne are less crowded, and Creole cooking classes are more available.",
    7: "Hot and humid at 27-32°C with regular tropical showers. The Festival de Gwo Ka celebrates Guadeloupe's African-rooted drum music with workshops and performances—a cultural highlight unique to this island.",
    8: "Hurricane season's peak at 27-32°C keeps some visitors away, but Guadeloupe's mountainous terrain provides some protection. The Fête des Cuisinières (female cooks' festival) in August is a colourful celebration of Creole gastronomy.",
    9: "The wettest month at 27-32°C with the highest hurricane risk, but prices are at rock bottom and the island functions normally most days. The volcanic hot springs at Bains Jaunes are especially inviting in the rain.",
    10: "Rains begin easing at 26-31°C as the transition toward dry season starts. The diving remains excellent, and the rum punches at beachside lolos (food shacks) taste better when you have the place to yourself.",
    11: "Shoulder season at 25-30°C with decreasing rain and building anticipation for the winter tourist season. The Route du Rhum yacht race (biennial) brings sailing excitement, and the harvest of sugarcane begins.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 24-29°C with Christmas festivities blending French and Creole traditions—chanté Nwel (Christmas caroling) fills the streets with unique Antillean harmonies. Peak season begins, and the island sparkles.",
  },
  'gq-equatorialguinea': {
    1: "The dry season brings 24-30°C to mainland Río Muni and Bioko Island, with clearer skies and reduced rainfall making this the best time for exploration. Malabo's colonial architecture and the Monte Alén rainforest are at their most accessible.",
    2: "Dry and warm at 24-30°C—prime conditions for trekking to the stunning Ureka waterfall on Bioko's southern coast, where leatherback turtles nest on black-sand beaches. The Gran Caldera de Luba is spectacular.",
    3: "Brief transition at 25-31°C as the first rains approach. Bioko's endemic primates—drill monkeys and Pennant's red colobus—are easier to spot in the dry canopy. The Spanish colonial influence makes Malabo feel curiously European.",
    4: "Wet season arrives at 25-31°C with heavy equatorial downpours transforming the already dense rainforest into a wall of green. The roads get challenging, but the biodiversity is extraordinary for those prepared to get muddy.",
    5: "Full wet season at 25-30°C with relentless rain on Bioko Island, which receives some of Africa's highest rainfall. The mainland's Monte Alén National Park is difficult but rewarding—gorillas, elephants, and forest buffalo roam here.",
    6: "Rainy at 24-29°C with reduced visibility but maximum forest lushness. Equatorial Guinea remains one of Africa's least-visited countries, and the few who make it find genuine adventure and zero tourist infrastructure.",
    7: "A slight dry interlude at 23-28°C on the mainland offers a brief window for easier travel, though Bioko stays wet. The oil wealth creates a surreal contrast between gleaming Malabo hotels and untouched jungle.",
    8: "Cooler and drier at 22-27°C in the mainland's brief second dry season, making August one of the better months for visiting. Bioko's marine turtle nesting begins on the southern beaches.",
    9: "Rains return at 23-28°C for the second wet season. Turtle nesting intensifies on Bioko's remote southern beaches—conservation programs welcome dedicated volunteers willing to rough it in basic camps.",
    10: "Heavy rains at 24-29°C make travel challenging but the forest is at its most alive. The cultural blend of Spanish, Fang, Bubi, and Ndowé traditions creates unique festivals and cuisine found nowhere else.",
    11: "Rain begins easing at 24-30°C as the year's second transition begins. Leatherback turtle nesting peaks on Bioko, and the improving conditions allow for better rainforest exploration on the mainland.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 24-30°C with clearer skies and more accessible roads. Christmas celebrations blend Spanish Catholic traditions with indigenous customs, and the beaches of Corisco Island offer pristine tropical escape.",
  },
  'gr-athens': {
    1: "Athens in winter is a revelation at 7-13°C—the Acropolis without crowds, neighbourhood tavernas full of locals eating hearty stews, and museum visits in blissful quiet. Rain comes in short bursts between sunny Mediterranean spells.",
    2: "Still mild at 7-14°C with almond blossoms appearing around the ancient ruins and the Apokries (carnival) celebrations building toward Clean Monday. Plaka's narrow streets feel like a village, and the souvlaki is just as good in winter.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 10-16°C with wildflowers blooming on Filopappou Hill and the Attic light that inspired classical civilisation sharpening the Parthenon's marble columns. Greek Independence Day on March 25th brings parades and patriotic fervour.",
    4: "Gorgeous at 12-20°C with Orthodox Easter transforming the city—midnight candlelit processions, fireworks, and whole lambs roasting on spits across every neighbourhood. The rooftop bars with Acropolis views open for the season.",
    5: "Warm and brilliant at 16-25°C with the summer energy building and the open-air cinemas flickering to life across the city. The Athenian Riviera's beaches start beckoning, and the archaeological sites are perfect before the heat peaks.",
    6: "Hot and sunny at 21-31°C as Athens shifts into its summer rhythm—late dinners, rooftop bars, and the Athens Epidaurus Festival bringing ancient drama to the Odeon of Herodes Atticus. Hydrate constantly.",
    7: "Full summer at 24-34°C with searing heat that makes midday Acropolis visits inadvisable—go at opening time or sunset. The coast at Vouliagmeni and Sounion offers cooling escapes, and the nightlife runs until dawn.",
    8: "The hottest month at 24-35°C as many Athenians flee to the islands, leaving the city quieter but scorching. The Assumption of the Virgin on August 15th is a massive celebration, and evening-only sightseeing is the wise move.",
    9: "The heat eases to 20-29°C, and Athens finds its groove again—the sea is still warm, the light is golden, and the cultural calendar reignites. This is arguably the best month for Athens: warm, uncrowded, and radiant.",
    10: "Pleasant at 16-23°C with occasional rain showers that clear the air and leave the marble glowing. The Athens Marathon (in November) approaches, and the neighbourhood markets overflow with autumn produce and chestnuts.",
    11: "Mild at 11-18°C with the Athens Authentic Marathon running the original course from Marathon to the Panathenaic Stadium. The tavernas switch to winter menus of slow-cooked meats and hearty bean soups.",
    12: "Cool at 8-14°C with festive lights stringing across Syntagma Square and the Christmas market at Stavros Niarchos Foundation Cultural Center drawing families. Athens does winter charm with surprising warmth—both meteorological and human.",
  },
  'gr-crete': {
    1: "Crete's winter is mild at 9-15°C with green hillsides, snow-capped mountains, and almost zero tourists. The south coast catches winter sunshine, and the raki flows freely in village kafeneia where you'll be the only foreigner.",
    2: "Still quiet at 9-15°C with almond and orange blossoms adding fragrance to the Cretan countryside. Carnival celebrations in Rethymno bring masked parades and traditional music to this Venetian-harbour town.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 10-17°C with wildflowers beginning to carpet the Lassithi Plateau and the Samariá Gorge preparing for its May opening. Orthodox traditions build toward Easter, and the hiking is excellent without the heat.",
    4: "Lovely at 13-20°C with Easter celebrations transforming every village—midnight liturgies, fireworks over harbours, and whole-lamb feasts that last for days. The Cretan countryside is at peak wildflower glory, emerald green under blue skies.",
    5: "The Samariá Gorge opens for the season at 16-24°C, and Crete's beaches shift from empty to inviting. The south coast's Preveli and Matala beaches are stunning without July's crowds, and the Minoan palaces at Knossos are comfortable to explore.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 20-28°C with the north coast beaches warming up and the Venetian harbours of Chania and Rethymno alive with evening strollers. The Cretan diet—olive oil, wild greens, local cheese—is at its freshest.",
    7: "Full Mediterranean summer at 23-31°C with every beach chair occupied and the Blue Flag beaches of Elafonissi and Balos packed with admirers. The mountains offer cooler escape, and the stargazing in the White Mountains is otherworldly.",
    8: "Peak heat at 23-31°C draws the biggest crowds to Crete's spectacular coastline. The Renaissance Festival in Rethymno and the Yakinthia Festival in Heraklion bring music and theatre to ancient settings.",
    9: "The golden month at 20-28°C as crowds thin, the sea stays warm at 24°C, and the grape harvest fills the villages with winemaking activity. Crete is at its most generous—fewer tourists, warmer hospitality, better prices.",
    10: "Mild at 17-24°C with the sea still swimmable and the first autumn rains greening the parched landscape. The chestnut and olive harvests begin, and the tsikoudia (raki) distillation season brings village celebrations called kazania.",
    11: "Cooling to 13-19°C with intermittent rain and the tourist infrastructure winding down. The olive harvest is in full swing across the island, and participating in the pick alongside local families is a memorable experience.",
    12: "Mild winter at 10-16°C with the mountains dusted in snow and the harbours quiet except for local fishing boats. Christmas celebrations are warm and family-centred, and the Cretan table—laden with cheese pies, lamb, and raki—welcomes all.",
  },

  'gr-dodecanese': {
    1: "Winter quiet descends on Rhodes and Kos with temps around 10-14°C and frequent rain—most tavernas shutter, but archaeological sites are yours alone. A good month for history buffs who don't need a beach towel.",
    2: "Still cool at 11-15°C with occasional storms rolling through, but almond trees start blooming across the hillsides. Ferries run reduced schedules, so plan island-hopping carefully.",
    3: "Spring creeps in at 13-17°C and wildflowers carpet the inland valleys of Rhodes and Patmos. Tourist infrastructure begins reopening, and you'll find bargain rates on the few hotels that stayed open.",
    4: "Gorgeous shoulder season—18-22°C, minimal crowds, and the sea warming enough for the brave. Easter celebrations on Patmos are legendary, with the Monastery of St. John at their spiritual center.",
    5: "Warm days of 22-26°C, crystal-clear water, and the full ferry network back in action make this arguably the best month. Bougainvillea erupts across whitewashed villages and the diving season kicks off.",
    6: "Summer arrives properly at 26-30°C with reliable sunshine and calm seas perfect for sailing between islands. Crowds are building but haven't peaked—the sweet spot before July's onslaught.",
    7: "Peak season hits hard: 30-34°C, packed beaches, and ferry tickets that sell out days ahead. The meltemi wind provides some relief and superb windsurfing conditions off Karpathos.",
    8: "The hottest and busiest month at 31-35°C—every sunbed on Rhodes has a reservation and prices are at their zenith. But the nightlife in Kos Town is electric if you can handle the heat.",
    9: "The cognoscenti's favorite month: 26-30°C, thinning crowds, and sea temps at their annual peak around 25-26°C. Symi and Kastellorizo return to their sleepy charm.",
    10: "Still warm at 22-26°C with occasional rain showers that green up the parched landscape. Many operators start winding down, but the weather is often better than northern Europe's summer.",
    11: "Autumn sets in at 16-20°C with more frequent rain and reduced ferry schedules. Rhodes Old Town feels wonderfully moody and medieval without the cruise-ship crowds.",
    12: "Cool and quiet at 12-16°C—most resort islands are effectively closed, but Rhodes Town keeps ticking with local life. Expect rain but also luminous winter light on ancient stone.",
  },
  'gr-ionian': {
    1: "The greenest Greek islands earn that title now—heavy rainfall at 10-14°C keeps Corfu lush but empties its beaches entirely. Venetian old town cafes become your living room.",
    2: "Carnival season brings Corfu's famous festivities, rivaling Venice with masked processions through rain-slicked streets at 10-15°C. The island's cultural life peaks even as tourism stays dormant.",
    3: "Spring arrives early at 12-17°C with wildflowers and citrus blossoms perfuming the air. Hiking the Corfu Trail is spectacular now, with green hills and zero crowds on the paths.",
    4: "Corfu's Easter is Greece's most dramatic—pot-throwing from balconies, massive processions, and genuinely moving liturgy at 15-20°C. Kefalonia and Zakynthos start stirring from winter sleep.",
    5: "Perfect conditions at 20-25°C: warm enough to swim, empty enough to breathe, and the olive groves at their silvery best. Boat trips to hidden coves on Paxos feel like a private charter.",
    6: "Summer settles in at 24-29°C with long golden days and the first wave of package tourists hitting Zakynthos. Navagio Beach looks exactly like the postcards, minus the crowds of July.",
    7: "High season peaks at 28-33°C—Shipwreck Beach queues get absurd and Kavos becomes a bass-thumping British colony. Escape to Ithaca or southern Lefkada for the real Ionian experience.",
    8: "Hottest month at 29-34°C with wall-to-wall sunshine and maximum tourist density. Sea kayaking the coast of Kefalonia is glorious if you start at dawn before the heat hammers down.",
    9: "The exodus begins and sanity returns at 25-30°C with the Ionian Sea still bathwater-warm. Grape harvest kicks off on Kefalonia's Robola vineyards—taste the wine where it's made.",
    10: "Pleasantly warm at 20-24°C with increasing rain showers that restore the islands' emerald character. Still swimmable, still sunny enough, and hotel prices drop by half.",
    11: "Rainy season arrives in earnest at 14-18°C—the Ionians get more rainfall than anywhere in Greece. Corfu's cultural scene compensates with concerts and local theater in the old town.",
    12: "Wet and cool at 11-15°C, but the islands glow with holiday decorations and Corfu Town's Liston arcade feels like a Venetian Christmas card. Come for atmosphere, not for sun.",
  },
  'gr-ne-aegean': {
    1: "These far-flung islands—Lesvos, Chios, Samos—feel genuinely remote in winter at 8-12°C with strong winds and rain. Ouzo distilleries on Lesvos welcome visitors when tavernas won't.",
    2: "Still chilly at 9-13°C, but Lesvos's hot springs at Polichnitos offer natural thermal bliss in the cold. Carnival traditions here are older and wilder than the mainland's polished affairs.",
    3: "Spring migration begins and Lesvos transforms into a birdwatcher's paradise at 11-16°C. Over 300 species pass through the island's salt pans and olive groves—bring binoculars, not beach gear.",
    4: "Warming to 15-20°C with the famous mastic trees of Chios coming into bloom. Medieval villages like Pyrgi and Mesta are enchanting without a tour bus in sight.",
    5: "Ideal conditions at 20-25°C—warm, uncrowded, and the hiking trails through Samos's pine forests lead to hidden waterfalls. These islands never get truly mobbed, but May is especially serene.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 25-30°C and the beaches fill with Greek vacationers rather than international crowds. Chios's mastic harvest preparations begin—this resin has flavored the Mediterranean for millennia.",
    7: "Hot at 28-33°C with the meltemi winds ripping through, making Ikaria's north coast exciting for windsurfers. Ikarians' legendary longevity might rub off if you adopt their late-night dining schedule.",
    8: "Peak heat at 30-34°C but the NE Aegean never feels overrun like the Cyclades. Panigiri village festivals erupt across every island with roast goat, local wine, and dancing until 4 AM.",
    9: "Gorgeous at 25-30°C with warm seas and dwindling crowds—arguably the best month for these islands. Lesvos's olive harvest begins, painting hillsides with activity and filling the air with woody fragrance.",
    10: "Still warm at 20-24°C with rain beginning to return. Birdwatchers get a second migration window, and the forests of Samos turn amber and gold.",
    11: "Cooling to 14-18°C with heavier rainfall and reduced ferry connections. The mastic villages of Chios are hauntingly beautiful in the grey light, and ouzo tastes better when it's cold outside.",
    12: "Winter arrives at 10-14°C—most tourist operations close but local life continues with festive markets and holiday gatherings. These islands are for the traveler who doesn't need anyone else around.",
  },
  'gr-northern': {
    1: "Thessaloniki buzzes with post-holiday sales and cultural life at 3-9°C while the mountains of Macedonia wear heavy snow. Skiing at Vasilitsa or Kaimaktsalan is surprisingly good and absurdly cheap.",
    2: "Carnival explodes across northern Greece—Naoussa's Genitsaroi festival is raw, ancient, and nothing like sanitized tourism at 4-10°C. Bundle up for the best people-watching in Greece.",
    3: "Spring thaw begins at 7-14°C with wildflowers pushing through snow at higher elevations. Thessaloniki's food scene—arguably Greece's best—needs no sunshine to justify a visit.",
    4: "Lovely at 12-19°C with Orthodox Easter turning villages into open-air feasts of spit-roasted lamb. The Prespa Lakes come alive with pelicans and the landscape shakes off its winter grey.",
    5: "Warm and green at 17-24°C—the mountains are lush, the Halkidiki beaches uncrowded, and Thessaloniki's waterfront perfect for the evening volta. Wildflower season in the Vikos Gorge is breathtaking.",
    6: "Summer heat builds to 22-30°C and the three peninsulas of Halkidiki become northern Greece's Riviera. Mount Olympus hiking season opens fully—summit attempts are best this month or next.",
    7: "Hot at 25-33°C with Halkidiki's beaches packed and Thessaloniki's residents fleeing to the coast. The Sani Festival brings world-class jazz and classical music to a pine-fringed peninsula.",
    8: "Peak summer at 26-34°C—the interior shimmers with heat but the coast delivers. Meteora's monasteries are stunning but punishing in the midday sun; go at first light.",
    9: "Cooling to 20-28°C with the Thessaloniki International Film Festival warming up and beach crowds thinning. Wine harvest in Naoussa's Xinomavro vineyards makes this Greece's answer to Burgundy in autumn.",
    10: "Crisp autumn at 14-22°C—Thessaloniki's cultural calendar hits full stride and the forests of Drama turn spectacular shades of copper. Mushroom foraging in the mountains is a local obsession.",
    11: "Cool and atmospheric at 8-15°C with fog rolling through mountain villages and the first dusting of snow on peaks. Thessaloniki's covered markets—Modiano and Kapani—are worth the trip alone.",
    12: "Winter settles in at 4-10°C with festive Thessaloniki glowing beautifully along its waterfront. Mountain villages near Metsovo offer cozy stone lodges, fireside tsipouro, and early-season skiing.",
  },
  'gt-antigua': {
    1: "Dry season perfection at 14-22°C in Antigua Guatemala, with crystalline skies framing the trio of volcanoes. Coffee harvest is in full swing—visit a finca for beans picked that morning.",
    2: "Still dry and mild at 14-23°C with lengthening days. Pre-Lenten celebrations build across the highlands, and the indigenous markets at Chichicastenango blaze with color every Thursday and Sunday.",
    3: "Warm and dry at 15-25°C as Semana Santa preparations transform Antigua into an open-air art studio. Locals spend weeks creating alfombras—elaborate sawdust carpets destined to be walked on once.",
    4: "Easter week in Antigua is one of the world's great spectacles—purple-robed processions over flower carpets through colonial streets at 16-26°C. Book months ahead or don't bother trying.",
    5: "The rainy season begins with afternoon thunderstorms at 16-26°C, but mornings stay clear and the landscape turns electric green. Crowds thin dramatically and prices soften across the highlands.",
    6: "Afternoon rains become reliable at 15-24°C, keeping the volcanic slopes impossibly lush. Hiking Pacaya or Acatenango between storms offers drama you can't buy—clouds, eruptions, and solitude.",
    7: "The canícula—a brief dry spell—sometimes interrupts the rains around mid-July at 15-24°C. Highland markets continue rain or shine, and the wool textiles you'll want to buy are actually useful now.",
    8: "Steady afternoon rains at 15-24°C keep tourist numbers low but the cultural richness high. Lake Atitlán's villages are misty and mysterious, with fewer backpackers competing for lakeside hammocks.",
    9: "The wettest month at 15-23°C, with roads occasionally washing out in remote areas. But the highlands glow green, waterfalls rage, and you'll have Antigua's cobblestone streets largely to yourself.",
    10: "Rains begin tapering at 15-23°C and the Día de los Muertos preparations start—kite festivals in Sumpango feature enormous hand-built creations. Moody skies make for unforgettable photography.",
    11: "The transition month at 14-23°C—rains diminish, the giant kite festival on November 1st in Sumpango is jaw-dropping, and the highland air turns crisp. Ideal for market-hopping and volcano hikes.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 13-22°C with festive posadas and cool highland nights perfect for hot chocolate. The coffee regions are gorgeous now, and Antigua's Christmas atmosphere is genuinely magical.",
  },
  'gt-tikal': {
    1: "Dry season brings clear skies and 20-32°C heat to the Petén lowlands, making temple exploration comfortable by early morning. Howler monkeys are particularly vocal and wildlife congregates near water sources.",
    2: "Excellent visiting conditions continue at 21-33°C with low humidity and good trail access. Sunrise over Temple IV—watching mist lift off the jungle canopy—is a once-in-a-lifetime dawn.",
    3: "Heating up to 22-35°C but still dry, with the jungle thinning enough to spot toucans and spider monkeys more easily. This is peak season, so expect other visitors at the main temples by midmorning.",
    4: "The hottest month at 24-37°C—bring serious water supplies and start your Tikal visit at 6 AM. The first rain showers may appear late in the month, bringing welcome relief and dramatic skies.",
    5: "Rainy season begins in earnest at 23-35°C with afternoon downpours that cool the jungle and thin the crowds. Trails get muddy but the forest comes alive with amphibians and fresh growth.",
    6: "Heavy rains and 23-33°C heat create a steamy, primal atmosphere in the ruins. Fewer visitors means you might have a temple complex to yourself, but bring waterproof everything.",
    7: "Rains continue at 23-33°C but the canícula sometimes brings a dry window. The jungle is at maximum lushness and bird activity is intense—ocellated turkeys strut through the plazas.",
    8: "Wet and warm at 23-33°C with the jungle absolutely bursting with life. Yaxhá and El Mirador see almost no visitors, so if you want to feel like an explorer, this is your month.",
    9: "Peak rainfall at 22-32°C can make some remote sites inaccessible, but Tikal's main trails are well-maintained. Jaguar sightings are rare but most likely now as animals range more widely.",
    10: "Rains begin easing at 22-32°C and the forest is at its most photogenic green. A sweet spot for those who want the lush jungle without the worst of the downpours.",
    11: "Transition to dry season at 21-31°C with decreasing rainfall and increasing visitors. The birding remains superb and trails start firming up—ideal for multi-day treks to El Mirador.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 20-30°C with comfortable humidity and excellent wildlife viewing. Holiday visitors arrive but the park is vast enough to absorb them—New Year's sunrise from the temples is unforgettable.",
  },
  'gw-guineabissau': {
    1: "Deep in the dry season at 24-34°C with the Harmattan haze filtering the sun and drying everything out. The Bijagós Archipelago is accessible and calm, with traditional ceremonies happening in remote villages.",
    2: "Hot and dry at 25-35°C—the landscape is parched brown but wildlife concentrates near remaining water. Carnival in Bissau is West Africa's wildest, with elaborate masks, parades, and a week of celebration.",
    3: "The hottest and driest stretch at 26-36°C before the rains arrive. Cashew trees begin flowering, hinting at the harvest that drives the national economy and flavors the local cashew wine.",
    4: "Scorching at 27-37°C with the first tentative rains possible late in the month. Hippo and manatee spotting in the Bijagós is excellent now as animals cluster in shrinking waterways.",
    5: "The rains begin at 26-35°C, transforming the dusty landscape almost overnight. Cashew harvest peaks—the fruit and nut are everywhere, and fresh cashew juice is something you won't find anywhere else.",
    6: "Rainy season builds at 25-32°C with regular heavy downpours and rising rivers. Travel becomes challenging on unpaved roads, but the green transformation is dramatic and the birding is extraordinary.",
    7: "Full monsoon at 24-30°C—roads flood, boats replace cars, and the country operates on a different rhythm. The Bijagós become harder to reach but sea turtle nesting season begins on some islands.",
    8: "Peak rains at 24-30°C make overland travel nearly impossible in parts, but the archipelago's marine life thrives. This is off-the-grid travel at its most authentic—come only if you embrace uncertainty.",
    9: "Still very wet at 24-31°C, but the rains begin to ease late in the month. Green sea turtles nest on the Bijagós beaches—one of West Africa's most important nesting sites.",
    10: "Rains taper off at 25-32°C and the landscape is lush and alive. Roads start drying out and travel becomes easier—a transitional month that rewards the flexible traveler.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25-34°C with clear skies and accessible roads. The Bijagós Archipelago is prime for visiting now, with calm seas, traditional fishing, and villages welcoming curious outsiders.",
    12: "Comfortable dry heat at 24-34°C with excellent conditions for exploring this tiny, unvisited nation. Festive season in Bissau is low-key but genuine—expect grilled oysters, palm wine, and warm hospitality.",
  },
  'iq-iraq': {
    1: "Kurdistan's mountains are snowcapped and stunning at 2-10°C while Baghdad shivers at an atypical 5-16°C. The marshlands of southern Iraq are hauntingly beautiful in winter light, though chilly for boat tours.",
    2: "Similar conditions at 4-13°C in Kurdistan with occasional heavy snow in the mountains. Sulaymaniyah's bazaars are perfect for warming up with chai and fresh flatbread from ancient tandoor ovens.",
    3: "Spring arrives gloriously at 8-18°C in Kurdistan with wildflower-covered mountains and Nowruz celebrations lighting up every hillside on March 21st. The Kurdish new year is one of the region's great spectacles.",
    4: "Perfect conditions at 12-24°C—Kurdistan is green, Erbil's citadel glows golden, and the weather is ideal for hiking in the Zagros foothills. Baghdad warms quickly but remains pleasant.",
    5: "Warming to 18-32°C with long sunny days ideal for exploring Erbil's ancient bazaar and the mountain villages of Duhok province. Baghdad's heat starts becoming serious—the window is closing.",
    6: "Kurdistan remains tolerable at 22-36°C but Baghdad becomes a furnace at 30-44°C. Mountain resorts like Shaqlawa and Amadiya fill with Iraqi families escaping the lowland inferno.",
    7: "Extreme heat grips the lowlands at 34-48°C—Baghdad and Basra are among the hottest inhabited places on Earth. Kurdistan's mountains offer refuge at 26-38°C with cool evenings.",
    8: "Still scorching at 33-48°C in the south while Kurdistan stays relatively bearable. The Zagros mountain villages are buzzing with domestic tourists and pomegranate season approaches.",
    9: "Heat begins easing to 28-42°C but remains intense in Baghdad. Kurdistan's pomegranate and walnut harvests begin, and the mountains turn golden—a beautiful shoulder season up north.",
    10: "Much more comfortable at 20-34°C across the country. Autumn in Kurdistan is spectacular with foliage, harvest festivals, and comfortable hiking weather returning to the gorges and valleys.",
    11: "Cool and pleasant at 12-22°C—arguably the best month for Mesopotamian archaeology as the sites are comfortable and uncrowded. Kurdistan's first snows dust the highest peaks.",
    12: "Winter returns at 5-14°C in Kurdistan with cozy teahouse culture in full effect. Baghdad is mild at 7-17°C, and the marshlands offer stark, beautiful winter landscapes.",
  },
  'ir-isfahan': {
    1: "Isfahan's legendary bridges span a usually-dry riverbed at 0-9°C, but the city's tile-covered mosques glow even under grey skies. Bundled-up locals gathering in Naqsh-e Jahan Square make for atmospheric winter scenes.",
    2: "Still cold at 1-11°C but the worst of winter lifts. The bazaar's caravanserais are warm with carpet merchants serving chai, and you'll have the Sheikh Lotfollah Mosque's dazzling interior nearly to yourself.",
    3: "Nowruz (Persian New Year, March 21) transforms Isfahan at 6-16°C—parks burst with picnicking families and the Zayandeh-rud sometimes flows again. Spring arrives with apricot blossoms and genuine festive joy.",
    4: "Perfect visiting weather at 10-22°C with gardens greening up and the famous Si-o-se-pol bridge looking its finest. The desert towns of Kashan and Abyaneh are comfortable for day trips.",
    5: "Warm and glorious at 15-28°C—long golden light on turquoise tiles makes photographers weep with joy. Rosewater distillation season in Kashan fills entire valleys with intoxicating fragrance.",
    6: "Hot at 20-35°C but dry enough to manage with early starts and long lunch breaks in the Persian tradition. The desert settlements of Varzaneh and Mesr are best visited at dawn or dusk.",
    7: "Properly hot at 23-38°C—Isfahan bakes and the central desert becomes genuinely punishing. Stick to shaded bazaars, underground water museums, and evenings on the bridges watching the sunset.",
    8: "Peak heat at 22-37°C continues, but Isfahanis carry on with characteristic grace. Ice cream from traditional shops and the cool interiors of 400-year-old mosques provide welcome relief.",
    9: "Heat eases to 17-33°C and the pace quickens as autumn approaches. The pomegranate harvest begins around Saveh, and the desert light turns impossibly golden in late afternoon.",
    10: "Excellent at 11-25°C with crisp air and stunning light on Isfahan's architecture. The city's gardens put on an autumn show, and the bazaar buzzes with the new season's dried fruits and nuts.",
    11: "Cooling to 5-17°C with occasional rain enhancing the tile-work's colors. Tourist numbers drop significantly, making this a fine month for unhurried exploration of one of the world's great cities.",
    12: "Cold at 1-10°C with short days but magical atmosphere in the bazaars. Yalda Night (December 21) celebrates the winter solstice with pomegranates, poetry readings, and Iran's longest dinner parties.",
  },
  'ir-shiraz': {
    1: "Shiraz earns its 'City of Gardens' title with winter rains at 2-13°C keeping everything green. The tombs of Hafez and Saadi are contemplative without crowds, and the oranges are at peak sweetness.",
    2: "Mild at 3-14°C with continued rain nurturing the gardens. Persepolis, just an hour away, is comfortable to explore without the summer heat that makes those stone terraces unbearable.",
    3: "Nowruz transforms Shiraz at 7-18°C—the Haft Sin tables appear in every home and Eram Garden explodes with spring color. This ancient city knows how to celebrate a new year.",
    4: "Stunning at 11-24°C with the famous Nasir ol-Molk Mosque's stained glass throwing rainbow light across its floor at sunrise. The rose harvest in nearby gardens is intoxicating.",
    5: "Warm at 16-30°C and the rose season peaks—Shiraz's rosewater and rose-petal ice cream are legendary for a reason. Persepolis at dawn, before the heat and buses arrive, is unforgettable.",
    6: "Hot at 21-36°C but manageable in this city built for heat, with deep-set gardens and wind-catching architecture. Evening strolls through the Vakil Bazaar are a sensory masterpiece.",
    7: "Seriously hot at 24-39°C—Persepolis at midday is punishing, but Shiraz's garden courtyards and underground qanat-cooled spaces offer brilliant natural air conditioning.",
    8: "Peak heat at 23-39°C continues, but the city's rhythm adapts—life happens at dawn and after dark. The pomegranate orchards on the outskirts begin showing fruit that will ripen in autumn.",
    9: "Heat recedes to 19-35°C and the first hints of autumn arrive. Grape harvest in the surrounding vineyards (yes, pre-revolution Shiraz gave the world the grape variety) begins in earnest.",
    10: "Lovely at 13-28°C with comfortable days and cool evenings perfect for the outdoor teahouse culture. Persepolis and Pasargadae are magnificent in the autumn light without summer's brutal glare.",
    11: "Cooling to 7-20°C with occasional rain returning. Tourist numbers thin and the city's literary culture comes to the fore—poetry readings at Hafez's tomb feel genuinely moving.",
    12: "Cool at 3-14°C with Yalda Night celebrations on the solstice bringing families together over pomegranates and Hafez's poetry. The pace slows beautifully and the gardens rest under grey skies.",
  },
  'ir-tehran': {
    1: "Tehran shivers at -2 to 7°C with snow on the Alborz mountains creating a dramatic backdrop. The ski resorts of Dizin and Shemshak are in full swing—surprisingly excellent skiing at bargain prices.",
    2: "Still cold at -1 to 9°C but the skiing is at its peak and Tehran's world-class museums offer warm refuge. The National Museum and contemporary art collections rival anything in the region.",
    3: "Nowruz fever grips the city at 4-14°C—Tehran empties as millions head to the countryside, but for visitors, it means uncrowded museums and a rare chance to see the capital at rest.",
    4: "Spring bursts through at 9-20°C with gardens blooming and the Darband hiking trail above the city buzzing with picnicking families. Air quality improves and the Alborz snows begin melting dramatically.",
    5: "Warm and vibrant at 14-26°C—Tehran's parks are packed, the teahouses along Darakeh valley are idyllic, and the Caspian coast (3 hours north) turns lush and green.",
    6: "Hot at 20-33°C but Tehran's elevation keeps it drier than the Gulf. The bazaar-e-bozorg is an air-conditioned universe unto itself—you could spend days lost in its labyrinth.",
    7: "Summer heat peaks at 24-37°C, driving Tehranis north to the Caspian or up to mountain villages. Tochal peak (3,964m) offers cool hiking above the smog line with staggering city views.",
    8: "Still hot at 23-36°C—the city's northern neighborhoods in the foothills stay noticeably cooler. Evening life on Darband's restaurant-lined trail is a uniquely Tehran experience.",
    9: "Heat fades to 18-31°C and the cultural season reignites with gallery openings and theater. The Alborz turns golden-brown and the air quality typically improves with autumn winds.",
    10: "Crisp and lovely at 12-23°C—Tehran's tree-lined boulevards put on an autumn color show and the bazaar fills with fresh walnuts, pomegranates, and quince. Best city-exploring weather of the year.",
    11: "Cooling to 6-15°C with the first snowfall likely on the Alborz peaks. Tehran's cafe culture is at its coziest, and the contemporary art scene is among the Middle East's most dynamic.",
    12: "Cold at 1-9°C with Yalda Night (Dec 21) the social highlight—families gather around tables piled with pomegranates and watermelon, reading Hafez by candlelight. Ski season opens on the peaks above.",
  },
  'is-north': {
    1: "Dark, cold, and magnificent at -5 to 1°C with only 3-4 hours of twilight. Northern lights dance over Akureyri and Mývatn, and the silence of the frozen landscape is almost spiritual.",
    2: "Still deep winter at -4 to 1°C but daylight stretches past 8 hours by month's end. The frozen Goðafoss waterfall is a sculpture of ice, and whale watching from Húsavík operates year-round.",
    3: "Light returns dramatically at -3 to 3°C with 12+ hours of daylight by the equinox. Skiing at Akureyri's Hlíðarfjall is excellent, and the aurora season hasn't quite ended.",
    4: "Spring edges in at 0-6°C with snow melting from lower elevations and migratory birds returning to the cliffs. The highland roads remain firmly closed, but coastal drives are increasingly accessible.",
    5: "The great thaw at 3-10°C—puffins arrive at their colonies, the midnight sun approaches, and the Arctic Botanical Garden in Akureyri bursts into improbable bloom. A transitional month of long, luminous days.",
    6: "Midnight sun arrives at 8-15°C with 24-hour daylight bathing the landscape in surreal golden light. Whale watching in Húsavík is at its peak with humpbacks reliably feeding in the bay.",
    7: "The warmest month at 10-16°C with endless daylight and full access to highland roads. Diamond Circle route—Dettifoss, Ásbyrgi, Húsavík—is one of Europe's greatest road trips. Book ahead.",
    8: "Still mild at 9-15°C with the first hints of darkness returning late at night. Berry picking on the moors, whale watching, and hiking around Mývatn's otherworldly lava formations are all prime.",
    9: "Autumn arrives swiftly at 5-11°C with the landscape turning russet and gold. Northern lights season begins again, and the summer crowds vanish almost overnight from even the most popular sites.",
    10: "Getting cold at 1-6°C with snow possible on higher ground and aurora activity ramping up. Akureyri's cultural life picks up as the town hunkers down for winter. Daylight shrinks rapidly.",
    11: "Winter takes hold at -2 to 3°C with significant snowfall and only 6-7 hours of daylight. Northern lights displays can be extraordinary, and the hot springs at Mývatn Nature Baths steam in the dark.",
    12: "Deep winter at -4 to 1°C with 3 hours of dim light and powerful auroras. Christmas in Akureyri is charming with the Yule Lads visiting children and the town glowing in the Arctic darkness.",
  },
  'is-reykjavik-south': {
    1: "Dark and dramatic at -1 to 3°C with about 5 hours of usable daylight and frequent storms. Northern lights are stellar, the Blue Lagoon steams against black skies, and Reykjavík's nightlife warms from within.",
    2: "Marginally brighter at -1 to 3°C with daylight stretching past 8 hours. The south coast's frozen waterfalls—Seljalandsfoss and Skógafoss—are draped in ice, and the ice caves in Vatnajökull are at their most stable.",
    3: "Light floods back at 0-4°C with 12+ hours by month's end, making this one of the best months for combining aurora chances with actual daytime sightseeing. Golden Circle without summer crowds is sublime.",
    4: "Spring stirs at 2-7°C with puffins arriving at Dyrhólaey and the landscape caught between snow and thaw. Shoulder season prices and lengthening days make this a savvy traveler's sweet spot.",
    5: "Long days at 5-10°C with wildflowers (Arctic lupins, controversially) painting the south coast purple. Midnight sun approaches, whale watching from Reykjavík harbor picks up, and highland roads begin opening.",
    6: "Midnight sun at 8-13°C with 24 continuous hours of light—surreal and slightly unhinged energy pervades everything. The south coast is fully accessible and Landmannalaugar's technicolor rhyolite mountains finally emerge from snow.",
    7: "Peak season at 10-15°C with every waterfall, geyser, and glacier crowded but spectacular. The Laugavegur hiking trail is fully open—four days through painted mountains, glacial rivers, and volcanic desert.",
    8: "Still warm at 9-14°C with the first taste of darkness returning and berry season beginning in the highlands. Festival season in Reykjavík peaks, and the interior roads offer a few more weeks of access.",
    9: "Autumn bites at 6-11°C with stunning golden-brown tundra colors and northern lights returning to the darkening skies. Tourist numbers plummet and prices follow—a brilliant shoulder season month.",
    10: "Getting cold at 3-7°C with real darkness returning and aurora season in full swing. Reykjavík's cultural calendar—Iceland Airwaves festival, galleries, and geothermal pools—compensates for the shrinking daylight.",
    11: "Winter at 0-4°C with storms, limited daylight (6-7 hours), and the ice caves beginning to form again in the glaciers. Northern lights viewing is excellent on clear nights, and the city gets cozy.",
    12: "Dark and festive at -1 to 3°C with Reykjavík's holiday lights creating warmth against 4 hours of daylight. New Year's Eve is legendary—the entire city launches fireworks from every backyard simultaneously.",
  },
  'is-westfjords': {
    1: "Iceland's most remote region is truly isolated at -3 to 2°C with many roads impassable and towns accessible only by the hardiest 4x4s or small planes. Arctic foxes roam the snow-covered cliffs in haunting solitude.",
    2: "Still deeply wintry at -3 to 2°C with very short days, but the northern lights here—far from any light pollution—are among Iceland's most vivid. Only come if you're comfortable with genuine remoteness.",
    3: "Light returns at -1 to 3°C but snow still dominates. Cross-country skiing in the Westfjords feels like exploring another planet, and Ísafjörður's tiny but spirited cultural scene keeps locals sane.",
    4: "Thawing begins at 1-6°C with some coastal roads reopening. The dramatic fjord landscapes emerge from white to reveal staggering cliff formations, and Arctic foxes are increasingly active with spring.",
    5: "The Westfjords awaken at 4-9°C with roads slowly opening and the Látrabjarg bird cliffs coming alive with millions of seabirds. Puffin season begins—the cliffs here host one of Europe's largest colonies.",
    6: "Midnight sun at 7-12°C makes the Westfjords accessible and surreally beautiful with light painting the fjords at all hours. The Dynjandi waterfall, freed from ice, is Iceland's most majestic cascade.",
    7: "The only truly reliable month at 9-14°C when all roads are open and the weather cooperates (relatively). This is Iceland's final frontier—empty, dramatic, and worth every kilometer of gravel road.",
    8: "Still good at 8-13°C with berry-picking, sea kayaking in mirror-calm fjords, and some of Iceland's best hiking along ancient cliffside trails. Catch it before the weather window closes.",
    9: "Autumn arrives fast at 5-10°C with roads starting to close and weather becoming unpredictable. The solitude intensifies and the autumn colors against dark fjord walls create stark, magnificent compositions.",
    10: "Winter's advance is rapid at 2-6°C with many roads closing for the season and services winding down. Northern lights return to the darkened skies, and the few remaining visitors have the landscapes to themselves.",
    11: "Deep isolation at -1 to 4°C—most tourist infrastructure closes and the region returns to its few thousand residents. Only the most intrepid travelers venture here, rewarded with raw, untouched winter beauty.",
    12: "Full winter at -2 to 2°C with the Westfjords at their most remote and inaccessible. Ísafjörður celebrates Christmas with fierce local pride, and the Arctic darkness is broken only by stars and auroras.",
  },
  'it-aeolian': {
    1: "These volcanic islands north of Sicily are quietly spectacular at 10-14°C with storms rolling across empty landscapes. Stromboli erupts nightly to an audience of approximately nobody—winter's privilege.",
    2: "Still cool at 10-14°C with intermittent rain, but the absence of crowds makes Lipari's archaeological museum and Salina's caper-covered hillsides feel wonderfully private. Ferry schedules are sparse.",
    3: "Spring edges in at 12-16°C with wildflowers blanketing the volcanic slopes. The islands stir from hibernation as restaurants reopen and boat operators prepare for the season ahead.",
    4: "Lovely at 14-19°C with mild weather perfect for hiking Vulcano's sulfurous crater or exploring Panarea's Bronze Age village. The sea is still bracing but the land walks are superb.",
    5: "Warm and uncrowded at 17-23°C—the sweet spot before summer chaos arrives. Swimming becomes comfortable, Malvasia wine flows freely on Salina, and the boat tours of sea caves are magical.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 21-27°C with the islands filling up but not yet overwhelmed. The Stromboli night hike to watch eruptions from the summit (if allowed) is one of Italy's most thrilling experiences.",
    7: "Peak season at 25-31°C—every yacht in the Tyrrhenian seems to anchor off Panarea and Stromboli's trails are conga lines. But the swimming is divine and the volcanic sunsets are unreal.",
    8: "Ferragosto madness at 26-32°C—Italians claim every inch of beach and prices peak to eye-watering levels. Stromboli's eruptions against the darkening August sky remain objectively magnificent.",
    9: "The informed traveler's month at 23-28°C—summer crowds evaporate, the sea is at its warmest (26°C), and Salina's grape harvest for Malvasia wine is in full swing. Pure Mediterranean bliss.",
    10: "Still warm at 20-24°C with occasional rain showers and dwindling services. The volcanic landscapes take on moody autumn tones and the few remaining visitors are fellow island-obsessives.",
    11: "Quieting rapidly at 16-20°C with heavier rains and reduced ferry connections. Lipari stays open year-round, but the smaller islands feel genuinely remote as winter approaches.",
    12: "Cool and stormy at 12-16°C—most islands are effectively closed for tourism, but Lipari's small town retains a warm local character. Stromboli erupts to an audience of goats and fishermen.",
  },
  'it-amalfi': {
    1: "The Amalfi Coast without the chaos—12-14°C, many hotels closed, but Ravello's gardens are green and Positano's pastel cascade is yours without a single tour bus. Naples buzzes regardless of season.",
    2: "Carnival in Naples is chaotic and wonderful at 8-13°C with sfogliatelle from every bakery. The coast itself remains sleepy, but the archaeological treasures of Pompeii and Herculaneum are crowd-free.",
    3: "Spring breaks through at 10-16°C with lemon blossoms perfuming the terraced hillsides. The Path of the Gods hiking trail reopens informally and the coastal towns begin their annual awakening.",
    4: "Gorgeous at 13-19°C with wisteria draped over every pergola and the sea turning from grey to turquoise. Easter on the coast features candlelit processions through medieval streets—book now.",
    5: "The perfect month at 16-23°C—warm enough to swim, quiet enough to find a table at Da Adolfo without a reservation. Lemons the size of softballs hang from every trellis along the coast.",
    6: "Summer begins at 20-27°C and the crowds arrive with it, but the long evenings dining above the sea in Praiano are worth every winding road. The Blue Grotto is reliably accessible.",
    7: "Peak madness at 24-31°C—the coastal road becomes a parking lot and Positano's beach shrinks to a towel-width per person. But the nightlife, the food, and the swimming are undeniably spectacular.",
    8: "Ferragosto fever at 25-32°C—all of Italy descends on the coast for the August 15th holiday. Escape to Ravello's mountaintop concerts or take a boat to the Li Galli islands for sanity.",
    9: "The coast exhales at 22-28°C—summer's fury subsides, the sea is warm, and the grape harvest in Furore's cliffside vineyards produces wines you can't find anywhere else. Magical month.",
    10: "Still lovely at 18-23°C with occasional autumn rain showers enhancing the dramatic coastline. Chestnut and mushroom season transforms the menus, and the light turns amber and cinematic.",
    11: "Quieting down at 13-18°C with more frequent rain and many hotels closing for winter. But Naples is eternal—its street food, underground catacombs, and operatic daily life never pause.",
    12: "Cool at 10-15°C with Christmas markets in Naples and the famous presepi (nativity scenes) of San Gregorio Armeno drawing craftsmanship pilgrims. The coast sleeps, but the city sings.",
  },
  'it-milan': {
    1: "Foggy and cold at 0-6°C with Milan's fashion and design scenes at full intensity. The lakes are misty and romantic, La Scala's opera season is in glorious mid-stride, and nebbiolo tastes better when it's grey.",
    2: "Milan Fashion Week erupts at 1-8°C, turning the city into a runway of impractical outerwear. Como and Garda are still quiet—lakeside walks in the fog feel like stepping into a Romantic painting.",
    3: "Spring teases at 5-13°C with magnolias blooming in Brera and the first hints of warmth. The Navigli canals come alive with aperitivo culture as daylight stretches into evening.",
    4: "Beautiful at 9-18°C with Milan's parks bursting into flower and Lake Como's gardens reaching peak bloom. Bellagio and Varenna are lovely without summer's boat-queue chaos.",
    5: "Warm and luminous at 13-22°C—the lakes are irresistible with snow still capping the surrounding Alps. Milan itself is vibrant with outdoor dining and the tail end of the cultural season.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 17-27°C and Lake Como fills with the international set—George Clooney's neighbors, basically. Milan empties on weekends as everyone heads north to the water.",
    7: "Hot and humid at 20-31°C—Milan bakes and the lakes become essential rather than optional. Thunderstorms over Garda are theatrical, and gelato consumption becomes a survival strategy.",
    8: "Ferragosto empties Milan at 20-30°C as the entire city relocates to the lakes. If you're in town, you'll have the Last Supper practically to yourself—silver lining of the summer exodus.",
    9: "Milan stirs back to life at 16-25°C with fashion week returning and the wine harvest in Franciacorta and Valtellina in full swing. The lakes are warm, quiet, and absolutely stunning in autumn light.",
    10: "Gorgeous autumn at 10-18°C with the foliage around the lakes turning gold and the truffle and porcini season elevating every restaurant menu. Milan's galleries and theaters reopen for the cultural season.",
    11: "Fog returns at 5-12°C, wrapping the lakes in atmospheric haze. La Scala's new season opens (December 7 tickets sell out months ahead), and risotto alla milanese warms from within.",
    12: "Cold and festive at 1-7°C with Milan's Duomo square glittering with Christmas lights and panettone wars raging between bakeries. The lakes are misty and magical for those who don't need sunshine.",
  },
  'it-rome': {
    1: "Rome at 4-12°C is a revelation—short lines at the Vatican, moody light on the Forum, and carbonara that hits different when it's cold outside. Rain is possible but rarely ruins a day.",
    2: "Carnival and early spring at 4-13°C with almond trees blooming in the parks. The city's rhythm is local and unhurried—Romans reclaim their trattorias from the tourist hordes.",
    3: "Spring arrives beautifully at 7-16°C with wisteria appearing on ancient walls and the Spanish Steps blooming with azaleas. Shoulder season perfection with manageable crowds and pleasant temperatures.",
    4: "Glorious at 9-19°C—Easter brings the Pope to St. Peter's Square and the city buzzes with pilgrim energy. Roman artichokes (carciofi) are at their peak and deserve a special trip.",
    5: "Warm and vibrant at 13-24°C with long evenings perfect for passeggiata along the Tiber. Roses bloom in the sunken garden on the Aventine, and the gelato season is officially open.",
    6: "Summer heat builds to 18-29°C and the tourist season hits full stride. The Roman Forum at sunset—all golden stone and long shadows—justifies the daytime crowds. Evening opera at the Baths of Caracalla begins.",
    7: "Hot at 21-32°C with Romans fleeing to the coast and tourists claiming the sweltering city. The outdoor cinema season and night museum openings make the heat bearable—embrace the late schedule.",
    8: "Ferragosto at 22-32°C—half of Rome's restaurants close as the city surrenders to tourists and heat. But there's something magical about having the Pantheon nearly to yourself at 7 AM.",
    9: "Rome's best-kept secret at 18-28°C—the crowds thin, the heat mellows, and the cultural season roars back with gallery openings and Roma Europa Festival. Sea breezes reach the city on good days.",
    10: "Gorgeous autumn at 13-23°C with golden light that makes every travertine facade glow. Porcini mushrooms and new-vintage olive oil transform menus, and the queues at the Colosseum finally become humane.",
    11: "Cool and atmospheric at 8-17°C with occasional rain that empties the piazzas beautifully. Rome's churches—all 900 of them—are at their most contemplative, and the opera season is in full swing.",
    12: "Festive Rome at 5-13°C with Piazza Navona's Christmas market, midnight mass at St. Peter's, and the city dressed in holiday lights. Cold enough for a coat, warm enough for walking.",
  },
  'it-sardinia': {
    1: "Sardinia's interior is wildly underrated in winter at 6-14°C—empty hiking trails through granite gorges, shepherds making pecorino in mountain huts, and Cagliari's trattorias serving the real deal.",
    2: "Carnival in Mamoiada features terrifying Mamuthones masks in an ancient ritual that predates Rome at 7-14°C. The wild, mountainous interior is the anti-beach Sardinia most visitors never imagine.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 9-16°C with wildflowers carpeting the countryside and the Costa Smeralda still blissfully empty. The Nuragic stone towers—Sardinia's mysterious Bronze Age heritage—are atmospheric without crowds.",
    4: "Lovely at 11-19°C with the sea warming up and the maquis-covered hills fragrant with wild herbs. Easter celebrations in rural Sardinia are deeply traditional and genuinely moving.",
    5: "The insider's month at 14-23°C—beach weather without beach crowds, warm seas, and the flamingos at Molentargius wetland near Cagliari in full pink splendor. Pecorino with honey season peaks.",
    6: "Summer begins at 18-28°C and the Costa Smeralda starts filling with mega-yachts. But Sardinia is huge—the wild east coast and interior gorges of Supramonte offer adventure far from the glamour.",
    7: "Hot at 21-32°C with the beaches justifying their Caribbean comparisons. La Pelosa and Cala Luna are stunning but packed—rent a boat and find your own cove, they're everywhere.",
    8: "Peak Ferragosto madness at 22-32°C—every beach has a price tag and every road a traffic jam. But the crystalline water, the grilled seafood, and the sunset aperitivi are genuinely world-class.",
    9: "September is Sardinia's sweet spot at 20-28°C—the sea is bathtub-warm, the crowds melt away, and the Cortes Apertas autumn food festivals begin in mountain villages. Heaven.",
    10: "Still swimmable at 16-24°C with autumn rain greening the parched landscape and mushroom season beginning in the cork oak forests. The island returns to the Sardinians.",
    11: "Cooling to 11-19°C with more frequent rain and the olive harvest in full production. The Autunno in Barbagia festival opens mountain villages to visitors for food, crafts, and genuine hospitality.",
    12: "Mild winter at 8-15°C—Sardinia doesn't get truly cold, and the holiday season in Cagliari and Alghero is cheerful without the mainland's frenzy. Come for the food, stay for the solitude.",
  },
  'it-sicily': {
    1: "Sicily's winter at 8-14°C is a masterclass in off-season travel—Palermo's street food sizzles year-round, Etna wears a snow cap, and the Valley of the Temples is gloriously empty.",
    2: "Almond blossom season near Agrigento at 8-15°C is one of Italy's most beautiful natural spectacles. Carnival in Acireale features elaborate papier-mâché floats through baroque streets.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 10-17°C with wildflowers and comfortable temperatures for exploring Siracusa's Greek ruins. The island wakes from its brief nap and the markets overflow with blood oranges.",
    4: "Gorgeous at 12-20°C with Easter processions in Trapani that are among Italy's most dramatic—hooded figures carry enormous wooden sculptures through candlelit streets. Sicily does pageantry like nowhere else.",
    5: "Perfect at 15-24°C—warm enough to swim in the south, uncrowded enough to enjoy the Aeolian Islands, and the food markets piled high with artichokes, fava beans, and wild fennel.",
    6: "Summer heat builds at 19-28°C and the beach towns fill with Italian families. Etna is hikeable to the summit craters, and the Greek theater at Taormina hosts performances against a volcano-and-sea backdrop.",
    7: "Hot at 23-33°C with the Strait of Messina shimmering and the beaches packed. Palermo's street food—arancini, panelle, sfincione—tastes even better eaten standing on a sun-baked corner at midnight.",
    8: "Peak heat at 24-34°C with Ferragosto turning every beach into a sardine can. But the evening passeggiata in Cefalù, gelato in hand, with the Norman cathedral lit up, is pure Italian cinema.",
    9: "The cognoscenti's Sicily at 21-29°C—summer crowds gone, sea still warm, and the grape harvest painting the hillsides with activity. Marsala wine country is at its most rewarding.",
    10: "Lovely at 17-24°C with autumn rains bringing mushrooms and the olive harvest in western Sicily. The light turns golden on baroque Noto and Ragusa, and you can eat everything without a reservation.",
    11: "Cooling to 13-19°C with citrus season beginning—Sicily's blood oranges, lemons, and mandarins are legendary. Palermo's Ballarò market in autumn rain is sensory overload in the best way.",
    12: "Mild at 9-15°C with Christmas markets in Palermo and Catania, and Etna often dusted white. Cassata and cannoli reach peak perfection, and the island's baroque churches glow with nativity scenes.",
  },
  'it-tuscany': {
    1: "Tuscany in winter at 2-10°C is for those who want the real thing—truffle hunting in San Miniato, empty Uffizi galleries, and ribollita soup by the fire in a stone farmhouse.",
    2: "Still quiet at 3-11°C with the cypress-lined hills stark against grey skies and Carnival celebrations in Viareggio featuring enormous satirical floats. Chianti tastes better without competing for a table.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 6-15°C with early wildflowers in the Val d'Orcia and Siena's Palio preparations beginning. The countryside shifts from brown to green almost overnight—photographers, sharpen your lenses.",
    4: "Exquisite at 9-18°C with wisteria draped over every stone wall and the hilltop towns of Montalcino, Montepulciano, and Pienza looking like Renaissance paintings. This is the Tuscany of your dreams.",
    5: "Warm and verdant at 12-23°C with poppies blazing red across wheat fields and the cultural season in full swing in Florence. The Chianti vineyards are impossibly green and open for tastings.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 16-28°C with the Luminara di San Ranieri lighting up Pisa's riverfront with candles. Outdoor dining in Florentine piazzas and Umbrian hill towns becomes the nightly ritual.",
    7: "Hot at 19-33°C with Florence's cobblestones radiating heat and the Palio di Siena (July 2) delivering Italy's most thrilling 90 seconds. The countryside offers relief—agriturismi with pools are essential.",
    8: "Peak heat at 19-33°C and Ferragosto empties the cities. The Tuscan hills shimmer gold, sunflower season ends, and the vendemmia (grape harvest) begins in earnest—volunteer if you can.",
    9: "Harvest season at 15-27°C—the vendemmia is in full swing, porcini mushrooms appear in every market, and the light turns that famous Tuscan gold. Crowds thin and the living is easy.",
    10: "Glorious autumn at 11-21°C with olive harvest, chestnut festivals, and the Val d'Orcia's vineyards turning crimson and gold. New-vintage olive oil on bruschetta is a religious experience.",
    11: "Cool and atmospheric at 6-14°C with truffle season peaking in San Miniato and new olive oil flowing. Umbria's Spoleto and Orvieto are hauntingly beautiful in the autumn mist.",
    12: "Winter returns at 3-10°C with Christmas markets in Florence's Piazza Santa Croce and Siena's panforte earning its place on holiday tables. The Uffizi in winter is the way Botticelli intended.",
  },
  'jm-jamaica': {
    1: "Dry season paradise at 22-30°C with the north coast beaches in top form and reggae pulsing from every corner of Montego Bay. Peak season means peak prices, but the sunshine is guaranteed.",
    2: "Continued dry perfection at 22-30°C—Bob Marley's birthday (Feb 6) turns the island into one massive celebration. The Blue Mountains are cool and clear, perfect for hiking to the peak at dawn.",
    3: "Warm and dry at 22-31°C with spring breakers joining the regular crowd. Negril's Seven Mile Beach is Jamaica's headliner, and the jerk chicken in Boston Bay sets the global standard.",
    4: "Shoulder season begins at 23-31°C with occasional showers that barely interrupt the sunshine. Carnival season brings soca and dancehall to the streets, and the tourist crowds start thinning nicely.",
    5: "The rains arrive at 24-31°C but come as brief, dramatic afternoon showers followed by sunshine. Room rates drop, the mountains turn impossibly green, and the waterfalls at Reach Falls rage beautifully.",
    6: "Rainy season proper at 24-32°C, but Jamaica's rain usually cooperates—mornings are sunny, afternoons see a downpour, evenings clear. Off-season rates make beachfront luxury surprisingly affordable.",
    7: "Warm and occasionally wet at 24-33°C with the Reggae Sumfest in Montego Bay bringing the island's biggest music festival. Hurricane season is technically here but July rarely sees direct threats.",
    8: "Hot at 24-33°C with the highest hurricane risk approaching. The flip side: empty beaches, locals-only vibes, and prices that make the Caribbean accessible. Portland parish is lush and uncrowded.",
    9: "Peak hurricane season at 24-32°C—travel insurance is non-negotiable and flexibility is key. But the snorkeling off the south coast is excellent, and rum bars don't close for weather.",
    10: "Rains continue at 24-32°C but hurricane risk fades through the month. The Blue Mountains' coffee harvest begins—tour the plantations for some of the world's most coveted beans.",
    11: "The transition back to dry at 23-31°C with decreasing rainfall and the island shaking off the rainy season. Early birds for winter season get great rates with improving weather.",
    12: "Dry season returns gloriously at 22-30°C with holiday festivities, the Junkanoo street parade on Boxing Day, and every beach chair spoken for. Jamaica at Christmas is joyful, loud, and unforgettable.",
  },
  'jo-aqaba': {
    1: "Wadi Rum is at its most dramatic at 8-16°C—cold desert nights under a sky dense with stars, warm days for camel treks and jeep tours through sandstone canyons. Aqaba's Red Sea is a mild 21°C.",
    2: "Similar conditions at 9-18°C with comfortable desert hiking and excellent Red Sea visibility for divers. The desert flowers briefly if winter rains were generous—a rare and magical sight.",
    3: "Warming nicely at 12-22°C with perfect conditions for multi-day Wadi Rum treks. Aqaba's coral reefs are teeming—the Japanese Garden and Cedar Pride wreck dive are world-class.",
    4: "Ideal at 16-27°C—warm enough for the beach, cool enough for desert exploration, and the light in Wadi Rum turns the sandstone every shade of red and orange. Book Bedouin camps ahead.",
    5: "Getting hot at 21-33°C with Wadi Rum comfortable only in early morning and late afternoon. Aqaba's water temperature rises to 23°C, and the diving remains excellent with great visibility.",
    6: "Seriously hot at 25-38°C—Wadi Rum becomes a furnace by midday and only dawn/dusk activities are comfortable. Aqaba's beach and underwater world become the main attraction.",
    7: "Extreme heat at 27-40°C makes desert exploration unwise during daylight hours. Aqaba is Jordan's beach escape, and the diving is superb—warm water, clear visibility, and uncrowded sites.",
    8: "Peak heat at 28-41°C—this is survival territory in Wadi Rum, but Aqaba's Red Sea is paradise at 27°C for snorkelers and divers. Night camping in the desert is possible if you can handle the day.",
    9: "Heat recedes slightly to 25-37°C with the desert becoming marginally more hospitable. Aqaba's water is still bath-warm, and the autumn diving season brings excellent conditions.",
    10: "Much better at 20-31°C—Wadi Rum returns to comfortable exploring territory and Aqaba's beach season extends with warm water and sunny skies. The sweet spot returns.",
    11: "Pleasant at 14-24°C with cool desert nights perfect for stargazing and campfire dinners in Wadi Rum. The Red Sea cools slightly to 24°C but remains excellent for diving.",
    12: "Cool at 9-18°C with crisp desert days and cold nights—Bedouin tents with blankets and tea feel genuinely welcoming. Aqaba's water at 22°C is still warmer than most summer destinations.",
  },
  'jo-petra': {
    1: "Petra in winter at 4-12°C is genuinely cold—the Treasury glows in low-angled sun but the canyon drafts bite. Amman's cafe culture thrives with mint tea and mansaf, and crowds are minimal.",
    2: "Still chilly at 5-14°C with possible rain that makes the Siq's sandstone walls gleam. The Dead Sea, an hour from Amman, offers warm(er) floating at 18-20°C air temperature.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 8-17°C with wildflowers blooming in the hills around Petra and Dana Nature Reserve. Hiking the back trails to the Monastery without crowds is a spiritual experience.",
    4: "Perfect conditions at 12-23°C—warm days, cool nights, and Petra looking its absolute finest in spring light. The Jordan Trail's southern sections are prime for multi-day hiking.",
    5: "Warm at 17-28°C with long sunny days ideal for the full Petra experience (two days minimum). Amman's rooftop restaurants come alive, and the Dead Sea's mineral-laden waters beckon.",
    6: "Hot at 21-33°C—Petra's afternoon heat can be brutal in the exposed areas, so start at dawn and retreat by midday. Amman cools pleasantly in the evenings at its 800m elevation.",
    7: "Very hot at 23-35°C with Petra best experienced at 6 AM when the Siq is still shadowed and cool. The Dead Sea at -430m is one of the hottest places on Earth—go for the float, not the tan.",
    8: "Peak heat at 23-36°C—only the truly committed tackle Petra's back trails now. Amman's hilltop neighborhoods offer evening breezes, and the Roman theater hosts occasional summer concerts.",
    9: "Heat easing at 21-32°C with autumn light transforming Petra's sandstone palette. The crowds thin after summer, and multi-day treks through Dana Biosphere Reserve become comfortable again.",
    10: "Excellent at 16-26°C with comfortable temperatures and beautiful light. Petra's colors intensify in the lower sun, and the olive harvest across Jordan's hills adds pastoral charm to every drive.",
    11: "Cool and clear at 10-19°C—ideal hiking weather for Petra's back trails and the Dana to Feynan trek. Amman's cultural season picks up with galleries and the occasional film festival.",
    12: "Winter returns at 5-13°C with Petra's tourist numbers at their lowest and the Siq's acoustics amplified by cold air. Amman's holiday atmosphere is warm despite the chill—Arabic coffee and knafeh help.",
  },
  'jp-alps': {
    1: "Deep powder season at -5 to 3°C—Hakuba, Nozawa Onsen, and Myoko are buried in some of the world's most consistent snowfall. After skiing, sink into a rotenburo (outdoor hot spring) while snow falls on your head.",
    2: "Peak ski conditions continue at -4 to 3°C with Japan's famous 'Japow' delivering pillow-soft runs through birch forests. The Nozawa fire festival (Jan 15) is one of Japan's most dramatic winter events.",
    3: "Still excellent skiing at -2 to 7°C in upper elevations while spring hints arrive in the valleys. The shoulder season between snow sports and cherry blossoms offers great value and fewer crowds.",
    4: "Cherry blossoms reach the Alps at 5-15°C—later than Tokyo by 2-3 weeks, they're no less spectacular against snowy mountain backdrops. The Takayama Spring Festival features stunning float processions.",
    5: "Gorgeous spring at 10-20°C with snow retreating up the peaks and alpine meadows emerging in electric green. The Tateyama Kurobe Alpine Route opens with its famous 20-meter snow corridor walls.",
    6: "The rainy season (tsuyu) arrives at 15-24°C with frequent overcast skies and steady rain. Matsumoto Castle reflects beautifully in the wet, and the onsen towns are at their most atmospheric.",
    7: "Summer heat at 20-28°C but the altitude keeps it bearable. The Northern Alps hiking season opens fully—the Kamikochi valley is Japan's Yosemite, with pristine rivers and 3,000m peaks.",
    8: "Obon festival season at 21-29°C with the mountains bustling with Japanese hikers. The Gujo Odori dance festival runs all month in Gujo Hachiman—join locals dancing in the streets until 5 AM.",
    9: "Early autumn at 15-23°C with the first hints of foliage at higher elevations. The crowds thin after Obon and the hiking is magnificent—clear skies, cool temps, and the larch trees starting to turn.",
    10: "Peak foliage season at 8-17°C—the Japanese Alps turn crimson and gold in one of the world's great autumn displays. Kamikochi, Hakuba, and the Norikura highlands are staggeringly beautiful.",
    11: "Late autumn fading to early winter at 2-11°C with the last leaves falling and the first snow dusting the peaks. Onsen season begins in earnest, and Takayama's morning markets sell the autumn harvest.",
    12: "Winter arrives at -3 to 5°C with ski resorts opening and the mountains transforming into a snow kingdom. Traditional ryokan stays with kaiseki dinners and private onsen are Japan at its most refined.",
  },
  'jp-hokkaido': {
    1: "Japan's powder paradise at -8 to -1°C—Niseko, Furano, and Rusutsu receive meters of champagne powder from Siberian weather systems. The Sapporo Snow Festival preparations are underway across the city.",
    2: "The Sapporo Snow Festival (early Feb) draws millions to marvel at building-sized ice sculptures at -7 to 0°C. Skiing remains legendary, and the seafood—hairy crab, uni, scallops—is at winter peak.",
    3: "Still deep winter at -4 to 3°C with excellent late-season skiing and drift ice visible off the Okhotsk Sea coast at Abashiri. The Shiretoko Peninsula is a frozen wilderness of staggering beauty.",
    4: "Spring thaw begins at 2-11°C—much later than mainland Japan—with cherry blossoms not arriving until late April or May. The snow retreats, rivers swell, and brown bears emerge from hibernation.",
    5: "Cherry blossoms finally arrive at 7-17°C, weeks after the rest of Japan, creating a second chance at hanami. The lavender fields of Furano begin planting, and Hokkaido's famous road trips become possible.",
    6: "Comfortable at 12-21°C with the Yosakoi Soran Festival filling Sapporo's streets with 30,000 dancers. The countryside is impossibly green, and the seafood shifts to summer's sea urchin and squid bounty.",
    7: "Hokkaido's glorious summer at 17-25°C—while the rest of Japan swelters, Hokkaido is perfectly temperate. The Furano and Biei lavender fields hit peak bloom, creating purple horizons against blue mountains.",
    8: "Still pleasant at 18-26°C and mercifully free of the mainland's oppressive humidity. Hiking in Daisetsuzan National Park—Japan's largest—offers alpine flowers, volcanic peaks, and brown bear territory.",
    9: "Autumn begins early at 14-22°C with Daisetsuzan's peaks showing Japan's first fall colors by mid-month. Salmon run upstream in dramatic spawning displays, and the farm harvest fills every market stall.",
    10: "Peak foliage at 7-16°C with Hokkaido's forests turning every shade of fire. The seafood season intensifies with salmon, ikura (salmon roe), and the first of the winter crab arriving.",
    11: "Early winter at 1-8°C with the first snowfall and ski resorts preparing to open. The onsen (hot spring) culture becomes essential, and the hearty food—miso ramen, genghis khan lamb BBQ—fortifies against the cold.",
    12: "Full winter arrives at -5 to 2°C with ski resorts opening to the world's powder pilgrims. Sapporo's illumination festivals light up the snowy city, and Christmas markets feel surprisingly European.",
  },
  'jp-miyako-yaeyama': {
    1: "Japan's subtropics at 17-21°C—cool by local standards but still warmer than most of Japan. The coral reefs are quiet, humpback whales pass through the channel, and the islands feel wonderfully remote.",
    2: "Warming slightly to 17-22°C with whale watching at its peak as humpbacks breed in the warm Okinawan waters. The beach season hasn't started, but snorkeling is already rewarding at these latitudes.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 19-24°C with the official beach opening ceremonies (kaibiran) held across the islands. Miyako-jima's impossibly turquoise lagoons start filling with early swimmers and paddleboarders.",
    4: "Beautiful at 21-26°C with the sea warming and visibility excellent for diving. The Yaeyama Islands—Ishigaki, Iriomote, Taketomi—feel like a different country from mainland Japan, with Ryukyu culture and jungle rivers.",
    5: "Rainy season (tsuyu) begins at 24-28°C with humid, overcast days and occasional heavy downpours. The reefs are alive with spawning coral and marine activity—divers shouldn't be deterred by topside weather.",
    6: "Still rainy season at 26-30°C, but it clears by late June and the sea becomes crystal-clear. Iriomote's mangrove kayaking is spectacular, and the subtropical jungle is at maximum lushness.",
    7: "Full tropical summer at 27-32°C with blazing sunshine, cobalt seas, and the beaches in full swing. Miyako-jima's Yonaha Maehama beach rivals anything in the Maldives—white sand, no reefs to stub your toes.",
    8: "Peak summer at 27-32°C with typhoon season the main concern. Between storms, the diving is world-class—manta rays gather at Ishigaki's cleaning stations, and the visibility can exceed 30 meters.",
    9: "Still hot at 26-31°C with typhoon risk peaking. When the weather cooperates, the snorkeling and diving are exceptional. Taketomi Island's traditional Ryukyu village is a step back in time.",
    10: "Warm at 24-29°C with typhoon risk diminishing and the summer crowds gone. The sea is still bathwater-warm, and the islands' pace slows to something genuinely restorative. Excellent diving month.",
    11: "Pleasant at 21-26°C with comfortable humidity and warm seas. The last reliable month for beach activities, and the autumn light on these coral islands is gorgeous. Crowds are minimal.",
    12: "Cool by island standards at 18-23°C but still mild enough for snorkeling on calm days. The pace of life is deliciously slow, and the Yaeyama soba, tropical fruit, and awamori spirit keep spirits high.",
  },
  'jp-okinawa-main': {
    1: "Winter in Okinawa is a relative term — expect 17°C and dry skies while mainland Japan shivers. Whale watching season is in full swing off Zamami Island, and you'll have the beaches nearly to yourself. Cherry blossoms actually start blooming here in late January, weeks before anywhere else in Japan.",
    2: "Temperatures hover around 17-19°C with occasional rain, but the cherry blossoms at Nakijin Castle are spectacular. It's the quietest month for tourism, meaning better deals on resorts along the west coast. Divers enjoy excellent visibility in the coral-rich waters around the Kerama Islands.",
    3: "Spring arrives properly with temps climbing to 20-22°C and humidity still manageable. The beaches aren't officially open yet, but the hiking and cultural sites are blissfully uncrowded. Okinawan festivals start picking up, and the food scene — think taco rice and soki soba — is year-round stellar.",
    4: "Beach season officially opens in April, making Okinawa the first place in Japan where you can swim. Temperatures reach a pleasant 23°C with increasing sunshine. Golden Week hasn't hit yet, so you'll beat the domestic tourist rush by a few weeks.",
    5: "Golden Week in early May brings a surge of mainland visitors, then rainy season (tsuyu) typically starts mid-month. Expect 25°C and rising humidity, with tropical downpours becoming frequent. Book well ahead for the first week, then enjoy post-holiday calm if you can handle the rain.",
    6: "Peak rainy season delivers heavy, warm downpours with temperatures around 27°C and stifling humidity. It's the least popular month, but the lush green landscapes and empty dive sites have their own appeal. Dragon boat races (hari) liven up fishing villages across the islands.",
    7: "Rainy season typically ends by mid-July, unleashing blazing sunshine and 30°C+ heat. The ocean turns impossibly turquoise and beach season hits full stride. Crowds swell with summer vacationers — book Kerama Island ferries and resort stays well in advance.",
    8: "The hottest month at 31-32°C with intense sun and warm ocean waters perfect for snorkeling. Obon festival brings peak domestic tourism and premium prices across the islands. Eisa dance festivals are electrifying, with drum-pounding processions lighting up towns every weekend.",
    9: "Still hot at 29-30°C with typhoon season in full force — check forecasts religiously before island-hopping. Crowds thin out after summer holidays, and diving conditions remain excellent between storms. September is statistically the highest-risk month for typhoons, so travel insurance is non-negotiable.",
    10: "Typhoon risk gradually decreases while temperatures settle to a comfortable 26°C. It's a sweet spot — warm enough for swimming, uncrowded enough to enjoy it. The Naha Great Tug-of-War festival draws huge crowds for one of the world's largest rope-pulling events.",
    11: "Gorgeous autumn weather arrives with 22-24°C temps and low humidity — arguably Okinawa's best month. Diving visibility peaks, and the islands feel relaxed and unhurried. You can still swim comfortably while the rest of Japan bundles up in autumn layers.",
    12: "Temperatures drop to 18-20°C and the beaches quiet down, but it's still mild by any standard. Whale watching season begins again in late December off the Kerama Islands. Holiday illuminations sparkle across Naha's Kokusai Street, mixing tropical and festive vibes.",
  },
  'jp-tokyo-kanto': {
    1: "Tokyo in January is crisp and clear with temperatures around 2-10°C and minimal rainfall. Hatsumode shrine visits pack Meiji Jingu and Sensoji in the first week, then the city settles into a quiet rhythm perfect for museum-hopping. Winter sales (fukubukuro lucky bags) offer the best shopping deals of the year.",
    2: "Still cold at 3-11°C but with lengthening days and early plum blossoms at Yushima Tenjin and Koishikawa Korakuen. Valentine's Day is a massive commercial event with department store chocolate displays that are genuinely works of art. It's low season for international tourists, meaning shorter queues at teamLab and Tsukiji Outer Market.",
    3: "Cherry blossom fever builds through March as temperatures reach 8-15°C and the city buzzes with anticipation. Late March typically brings the first blooms, transforming Ueno Park and Chidorigafuchi into pink-canopied wonderlands. Book everything months ahead — this is Tokyo's most popular season and hotel prices spike accordingly.",
    4: "Peak sakura season in early April delivers 12-19°C weather and hanami parties under every available tree. The atmosphere is electric — millions of locals and tourists picnic in Yoyogi and Shinjuku Gyoen until the petals scatter. Golden Week approaches at month's end, so plan around the national holiday surge.",
    5: "Golden Week (late April to early May) is Japan's biggest holiday stretch — expect packed trains and booked-solid hotels. Post-holiday May is delightful: 18-24°C, azaleas blooming at Nezu Shrine, and the humidity hasn't arrived yet. The Sanja Matsuri at Asakusa is one of Tokyo's wildest and most authentic festivals.",
    6: "Tsuyu rainy season hits with persistent drizzle, 20-26°C temps, and humidity that will ruin your hair. Carry an umbrella everywhere, but enjoy hydrangeas blooming magnificently at Meiji Jingu and Hakone. Crowds are thinner and you can snag better hotel rates if you don't mind getting damp.",
    7: "The rain clears but gives way to brutal summer heat — 25-32°C with suffocating humidity. Fireworks festivals (hanabi taikai) light up the Sumida River and offer unforgettable summer evenings. Mount Fuji's climbing season opens, and the Fuji views from the Kanto plain shimmer in the haze.",
    8: "Tokyo's hottest month at 26-34°C demands air-conditioned refuge between outdoor excursions. Obon week sees locals leave the city, but tourists fill the gap at a slightly reduced pace. The Awa Odori in Koenji and Asakusa Samba Carnival bring explosive street energy to otherwise sweltering neighborhoods.",
    9: "Temperatures ease to 22-30°C but typhoons can disrupt travel plans — keep itineraries flexible. The humidity starts to break late in the month, and autumn menus appear at restaurants across the city. Sumo's September tournament at Ryogoku Kokugikan is one of the most electrifying sporting events you'll ever witness.",
    10: "Autumn arrives properly with 15-23°C weather, clear skies, and a collective citywide exhale after summer. It's one of Tokyo's best months — comfortable for walking, gorgeous light for photography, and fall fashion takes over Omotesando. Nikko's autumn foliage is a spectacular day trip just ninety minutes north.",
    11: "Peak autumn color hits Tokyo's gardens with temperatures at 10-18°C and reliably dry weather. Rikugien and Koishikawa Korakuen stage evening illuminations of their maple trees that are utterly stunning. This is arguably Tokyo's most underrated month — beautiful weather, manageable crowds, and the city at its most photogenic.",
    12: "Winter settles in at 4-13°C with dazzling illuminations across Marunouchi, Roppongi, and Shibuya. Year-end markets, bonenkai parties, and New Year preparations give the city a festive buzz. The Tsukiji and Ameya-Yokocho markets overflow with locals stocking up for osechi New Year feasts.",
  },
  'ke-masaimara': {
    1: "January brings dry, warm weather at 15-28°C with golden savannah landscapes and excellent game viewing. The wildebeest calving season begins in the southern Serengeti, and predator action around the Mara is intense. It's high season with premium lodge prices, but the wildlife spectacle justifies every shilling.",
    2: "Hot and dry continues at 16-29°C — this is peak calving season and arguably the best time for predator-prey drama. Cheetah and lion hunts are almost daily occurrences as thousands of wildebeest give birth across the plains. Lodges are fully booked, so reservations months in advance are essential.",
    3: "The long rains begin arriving late March, turning the landscape dramatically green almost overnight. Temperatures stay warm at 16-27°C, and while some roads become challenging, bird watching is extraordinary with migratory species arriving. Prices drop and crowds thin — a good trade-off if you don't mind afternoon showers.",
    4: "Heavy rains transform the Mara into a lush, muddy wonderland with temperatures around 15-25°C. Many camps close or offer deep discounts, and game drives can be challenging on waterlogged tracks. The upside: dramatic storm-lit skies, newborn animals everywhere, and a raw, untouristed wilderness experience.",
    5: "The long rains taper off but the landscape remains spectacularly green and the rivers are full. Temperatures sit at 14-25°C with decreasing rainfall through the month. Resident game is plentiful and the lack of safari vehicles means more intimate encounters with wildlife.",
    6: "Dry season begins in earnest with cooling temperatures of 12-24°C and increasingly clear skies. The grass starts drying out, concentrating animals around water sources and improving visibility. Early arrivals of the Great Migration herds from the Serengeti begin — the anticipation is palpable across the conservancies.",
    7: "The Great Migration arrives in full force, with hundreds of thousands of wildebeest and zebra streaming into the Mara. Temperatures are cool at 11-23°C, and the first dramatic river crossings at the Mara River begin. This is absolute peak season — expect premium prices and book six months ahead minimum.",
    8: "Peak migration month with massive herds and spectacular Mara River crossings that define the bucket-list safari experience. Temperatures hover at 12-24°C under crisp, dry skies perfect for photography. Every lodge and camp is at capacity; this is the most sought-after wildlife spectacle on Earth.",
    9: "Migration crossings continue with enormous herds still moving through the Mara ecosystem. Days warm to 13-26°C with virtually no rain and excellent game-viewing conditions. The sheer density of wildlife — millions of animals across the plains — makes this month consistently extraordinary.",
    10: "The short rains typically begin mid-to-late October, and migration herds start their southward return. Temperatures reach 14-26°C with afternoon thunderstorms becoming frequent. Crowds thin slightly from peak season while wildlife remains abundant — a smart time for value-conscious safari-goers.",
    11: "Short rains bring afternoon showers but mornings are usually clear and warm at 14-25°C. The landscape greens up again and resident wildlife is spread across the ecosystem. It's shoulder season with better rates and fewer vehicles, though some secondary roads may be muddy.",
    12: "Rain eases through December with temperatures at 14-27°C and the savannah in beautiful green condition. Holiday season brings a brief tourist spike around Christmas and New Year with corresponding price increases. The bird life is exceptional with over 450 species present, including European migrants.",
  },
  'ke-mombasa': {
    1: "Mombasa sizzles at 24-32°C with high humidity and blazing sunshine along the Indian Ocean coast. It's peak beach season with warm, calm seas perfect for snorkeling at Watamu Marine Park. European holiday crowds linger into early January, keeping Diani Beach resorts buzzing and prices elevated.",
    2: "The hottest month with temperatures hitting 25-33°C and minimal rainfall — sunscreen is survival gear. The ocean is bathtub-warm and visibility excellent for diving the coral reefs off Malindi. It's still high season, and the Old Town's narrow streets shimmer with heat and Swahili cultural energy.",
    3: "Heat and humidity peak at 25-33°C as the long rains begin approaching from the south. Late March sees the first heavy showers, but the coast often stays drier than the highlands. Kitesurfing conditions pick up along Diani Beach as seasonal winds shift direction.",
    4: "The long rains hit the coast hard with 24-31°C temps and heavy, persistent downpours through the month. Many beach resorts offer significant discounts, and some smaller operations close entirely. The rain brings a lush beauty to the coastal forests, and Mombasa's Fort Jesus museum is perfect for wet-day exploring.",
    5: "Still solidly in rainy season with 23-29°C temperatures and frequent tropical downpours. The coast is at its emptiest and cheapest — a genuine opportunity for budget travelers who don't mind wet weather. The Swahili food scene in Old Town is year-round outstanding, rain or shine.",
    6: "Rains ease significantly through June with temps at 22-28°C and the Kaskazi trade winds bringing drier air. The coast shakes off its wet-season sleepiness and resorts begin reopening and refreshing. It's a lovely shoulder season — good weather returning, prices still reasonable, beaches uncrowded.",
    7: "Dry season proper with comfortable 21-27°C temperatures and the southeast monsoon creating excellent conditions for dhow sailing. The ocean can be rougher on the south coast, but north of Mombasa stays calm and clear. Cultural events and Swahili food festivals enliven the coastal towns.",
    8: "Cool and dry at 21-27°C — the most comfortable month on the coast with low humidity and clear skies. Peak European summer means resorts fill up again, particularly Diani and Watamu. Whale sharks appear off the coast, offering once-in-a-lifetime snorkeling encounters.",
    9: "Gorgeous weather continues at 22-28°C with calm seas and excellent diving visibility. The short rains haven't arrived yet, and the coast basks in reliable sunshine. It's a sweet spot between the July-August rush and the October rains — well-priced and uncrowded.",
    10: "The short rains begin mid-October with temperatures warming to 23-30°C and afternoon thunderstorms. The showers are usually brief and dramatic rather than the all-day soaking of April. Kite season kicks off at Diani Beach with consistent winds drawing an international crowd.",
    11: "Short rains continue with 24-31°C temps and intermittent showers that rarely ruin a beach day. The coast greens up beautifully and the reef systems thrive with nutrient-rich waters. Turtle nesting season at Watamu brings conservation volunteering opportunities along the beach.",
    12: "Rains taper off and the holiday season begins, pushing temperatures to 24-32°C with rising humidity. Christmas and New Year bring peak prices and packed beaches at Diani and Nyali. The warm Indian Ocean and festive Swahili-Christmas fusion atmosphere make it one of the coast's most vibrant months.",
  },
  'ke-nairobi': {
    1: "Nairobi enjoys warm, dry weather at 12-26°C with clear highland skies perfect for exploring the city's emerging cultural scene. The Nairobi National Park is excellent for game viewing as animals congregate near water sources. It's high season, so Giraffe Centre and the elephant orphanage are busy — go early morning.",
    2: "The driest and warmest month with 13-27°C and relentless sunshine at 1,700m elevation. Nairobi's restaurant and nightlife scene has exploded in recent years, and this is perfect weather to explore it. Day trips to Hell's Gate or Lake Naivasha are stunning under February's clear blue skies.",
    3: "The long rains begin arriving in late March with temperatures at 14-26°C and dramatic afternoon thunderstorms. The city turns green almost overnight, and the jacaranda-lined streets of Westlands are lovely despite the wet. Traffic congestion worsens in the rain — plan extra time for everything.",
    4: "Peak rainy season dumps heavy showers daily at 14-24°C, turning the city lush but muddy. Many travelers skip Nairobi now, but the National Museum, Karen Blixen Museum, and Kazuri Beads factory are perfect rainy-day activities. Hotel rates drop significantly, making this a budget-savvy choice for culture-focused visitors.",
    5: "Rains continue but start easing by late May with temperatures at 13-23°C — the coolest of the wet months. The highland countryside around Nairobi is spectacularly green and the Ngong Hills hiking trails, while slippery, offer moody panoramic views. Pack layers — evenings can dip below 12°C.",
    6: "The long rains end and a cool, dry period begins with 11-22°C temperatures — bring a jacket for Nairobi evenings. The city feels energized as safari season ramps up across the country, with Nairobi serving as the launchpad. The Maasai Market rotates through different locations and is worth seeking out.",
    7: "Cool and dry at 10-21°C — the coldest month in this highland city, and surprisingly so for equatorial Africa. Locals bundle up in puffers and scarves while visitors are often caught off guard. It's peak safari departure season, and Wilson Airport buzzes with bush plane flights heading to the Mara.",
    8: "Still cool at 11-22°C with dry conditions continuing and Nairobi functioning as the gateway to Great Migration safaris. The arts and food scenes in neighborhoods like Kilimani and Westlands are thriving year-round. Nairobi National Park offers the surreal sight of lions with skyscrapers in the background.",
    9: "Warming up to 12-25°C with dry skies and the occasional dust haze over the city. The short rains are still weeks away, and the dry landscape makes for excellent game viewing even in the city's national park. Nairobi's craft beer and coffee scenes have become genuinely world-class.",
    10: "Short rains arrive mid-month with temperatures at 14-25°C and afternoon showers that green up the parks and gardens. The Kenya International Film Festival and other cultural events enliven the city. The rain usually falls in sharp, short bursts — mornings are typically clear and pleasant.",
    11: "The wettest of the short-rain months with 14-24°C and regular downpours, though rarely all-day affairs. The city is beautifully green and the Karura Forest walks are at their most atmospheric. It's low season for tourism with excellent hotel deals in the city's luxury properties.",
    12: "Rains ease through December with 13-25°C and the holiday season bringing festive energy to the capital. Many Kenyans travel up-country for Christmas, giving the city a mellower feel. The Nairobi Street Food scene and holiday markets make this an increasingly popular month for visitors.",
  },
  'kg-kyrgyzstan': {
    1: "Deep winter in Bishkek means -5 to 3°C with snow blanketing the Tien Shan mountains surrounding the city. Ski touring and backcountry adventures at Karakol and Too-Ashuu are exceptional for those equipped for serious cold. The bazaars serve steaming bowls of beshbarmak and lagman — cold-weather fuel at its finest.",
    2: "The coldest month with temperatures dropping to -8 to 2°C and heavy snowpack across the mountains. Karakol's ski base and the emerging freeride scene attract a small but dedicated international crowd. Bishkek's Osh Bazaar is a sensory wonderland of dried fruits, spices, and smoked meats — perfect for a frigid morning.",
    3: "Winter begins loosening its grip with -2 to 8°C temps and the first hints of snowmelt in lower valleys. The mountains remain firmly in winter mode, but Bishkek starts to thaw and outdoor cafe culture tentatively resumes. It's still very much off-season, meaning rock-bottom prices and zero tourist crowds.",
    4: "Spring arrives dramatically with 6-18°C temperatures and the Chuy Valley erupting in wildflowers. The mountains are still snow-capped and stunning, but lower-elevation hiking becomes possible. Nooruz (Persian New Year) celebrations in late March carry festive energy into April with horse games and feasting.",
    5: "The countryside explodes into green at 10-23°C with shepherds moving their flocks to jailoo (summer pastures). Son-Kul Lake is still frozen, but lower lakes like Issyk-Kul become accessible and achingly beautiful. Horseback riding through the flower-carpeted valleys is peak Central Asian magic.",
    6: "Summer arrives properly at 14-29°C and the trekking season opens across the country. Son-Kul Lake thaws and the yurt camps set up for the season, offering unforgettable nomadic stays at 3,000m. Community-based tourism operations are in full swing — this is responsible travel at its most authentic.",
    7: "Peak season with 17-34°C in Bishkek and perfect conditions in the mountains at 15-25°C. The World Nomad Games legacy keeps traditional sports alive with kok-boru and eagle hunting demonstrations. Trek to Ala-Kul Lake or through the Jyrgalan Valley for world-class scenery without Patagonia-level crowds.",
    8: "The hottest month in the lowlands at 16-33°C, but the mountains remain a perfect 12-25°C escape. Issyk-Kul Lake becomes Central Asia's Riviera, with Kyrgyz families and a growing international crowd. The bazaars overflow with melons, stone fruits, and fermented mare's milk (kumys) — try it, seriously.",
    9: "Autumn gold begins spreading across the walnut forests of Arslanbob at 10-26°C. The trekking is still excellent with fewer hikers and the mountains turning amber and crimson. Harvest festivals celebrate the walnut and apple crops that make southern Kyrgyzstan so uniquely beautiful.",
    10: "Temperatures drop to 5-18°C and the mountains receive their first dustings of fresh snow. Most yurt camps close up, but Bishkek and Karakol remain lively with autumn food markets and cultural events. The low-angle autumn light makes the Tien Shan look like they're on fire at sunrise.",
    11: "Winter approaches fast with -2 to 9°C and the first real snowfall in the valleys. The tourist season is firmly over, but Bishkek's growing cafe and arts scene offers unexpected urban pleasures. Warm up in a traditional banya (bathhouse) and eat your weight in manti dumplings.",
    12: "Full winter at -6 to 3°C with heavy snow in the mountains and ski season underway at Karakol. Bishkek's New Year celebrations are the biggest party of the year, with festive lights along Chuy Avenue. The city empties of tourists but fills with warmth — Kyrgyz hospitality runs deep, especially in the cold months.",
  },
  'kh-phnompenh': {
    1: "Dry season bliss with 22-32°C temperatures, low humidity, and clear skies over the Mekong. The Royal Palace and Silver Pagoda gleam in the sunshine, and evening river cruises are magical. It's peak tourist season, so book the better boutique hotels in the BKK1 neighborhood early.",
    2: "Slightly warmer at 23-34°C and still bone-dry — one of the best months to visit the capital. The Central Market's Art Deco dome is a marvel, and the street food scene around Russian Market is extraordinary. Chinese New Year brings vibrant celebrations to the city's sizable Sino-Khmer community.",
    3: "Heat intensifies to 24-35°C as the hot season approaches, but it's still dry and manageable with early starts. The Tuol Sleng Museum and Killing Fields are sobering but essential visits best done in the relative cool of morning. Mango season arrives, making the smoothie stalls along the riverfront irresistible.",
    4: "The hottest month at 25-36°C with humidity building ahead of the monsoon — it's genuinely sweltering. Khmer New Year (Chol Chnam Thmey) in mid-April is the country's biggest celebration, with water fights and temple festivities. Many businesses close for the holiday, so plan accordingly.",
    5: "The wet season begins with afternoon thunderstorms and 25-35°C temperatures, but mornings are usually clear. The Mekong starts its annual rise, and the countryside greens up dramatically. Crowds vanish and hotel prices drop — savvy visitors trade a daily downpour for genuine local atmosphere.",
    6: "Full monsoon with daily tropical downpours and 25-33°C — the rain is warm and dramatic rather than miserable. The streets flood briefly during heavy storms but drain quickly, and life carries on unbothered. The food markets are less crowded and the vendors more chatty — some of the best eating happens now.",
    7: "Rain continues steadily at 25-32°C with the Mekong swelling and the floodplain agriculture in full swing. The city has a quieter, more authentic rhythm without the tourist crowds. The rooftop bars along the riverfront are spectacular during sunset thunderstorms.",
    8: "Peak monsoon month with 25-32°C temps and almost daily heavy rain, though mornings are often surprisingly clear. The countryside is lush and impossibly green, and the Tonle Sap begins its remarkable annual reversal. Phnom Penh's contemporary art scene in galleries along Street 240 is a perfect rainy-day pursuit.",
    9: "Heavy rains persist at 25-32°C with the Tonle Sap Lake at its maximum — a unique hydrological phenomenon. The Mekong is massive and powerful, making river-watching from the promenade genuinely dramatic. Pchum Ben (Ancestors' Day) is one of Cambodia's most important spiritual festivals.",
    10: "Rains begin easing late in the month with 24-32°C temperatures and the humidity starting to relent. The Water Festival (Bon Om Touk) celebrating the Tonle Sap reversal is Cambodia's most spectacular event, with dragon boat races on the river. Book accommodation weeks ahead if your visit coincides.",
    11: "The dry season returns with 23-32°C, cooling breezes, and dramatically clearer skies. It's the start of the best weather window, and tourists begin filtering back to the capital. The Independence Day celebrations on November 9th add a patriotic buzz to the already energized city.",
    12: "Perfect dry-season weather at 22-31°C with cool evenings and low humidity — the most comfortable month. Holiday tourists swell the boutique hotels and riverside restaurants, but the atmosphere is festive rather than overcrowded. Sunset drinks on the Sisowath Quay promenade with the Mekong gleaming is pure gold.",
  },
  'kh-siemreap': {
    1: "Peak dry season with 21-32°C and reliably clear skies — ideal for temple-hopping across the Angkor complex. Sunrise at Angkor Wat is busy but utterly transcendent, and the cooler morning temperatures make cycling between temples a pleasure. Book sunrise passes and tuk-tuk drivers the day before — competition is fierce.",
    2: "Dry and warming to 23-34°C with the landscape turning dusty brown around the temples. The moats at Angkor Wat stay full, reflecting the towers beautifully despite the dry conditions. Pub Street is at peak buzz with backpackers and upscale travelers mingling over fifty-cent draft beers.",
    3: "Hot season arrives at 24-36°C, and temple visits after 10am become genuinely punishing. The key strategy is dawn starts, long midday breaks by the pool, and late-afternoon returns to the ruins. The emerging fine-dining scene on Sok San Road offers creative Khmer cuisine that rivals Bangkok.",
    4: "The hottest month at 25-37°C — even hardened travelers wilt under the Angkor sun by midmorning. Khmer New Year transforms the town into a joyful water-splashing celebration, but many services pause. If you can handle the heat, the temples are emptier than any other month except deep monsoon.",
    5: "Monsoon rains begin with dramatic afternoon storms and 25-35°C temperatures that bring blessed relief from the heat. The jungle around Ta Prohm steams magnificently as the roots and stones get their dramatic wet-season patina. The moats and barays fill, making the temples even more photogenic.",
    6: "Full wet season at 25-33°C with daily rains that typically hit in the afternoon and last an hour or two. The jungle temples are at their most atmospheric — moss-covered stones glistening, empty corridors echoing. Hotel rates drop 30-50%, making luxury stays at Amansara-level properties suddenly approachable.",
    7: "Rain continues at 25-32°C but mornings are usually clear enough for temple visits until early afternoon. The Tonle Sap Lake begins swelling, and floating village tours become increasingly dramatic. The wet season light through temple doorways and over the jungle canopy is a photographer's dream.",
    8: "Steady monsoon at 25-32°C with lush, impossibly green landscapes surrounding the ancient stone complexes. The temples feel mysterious and primordial wrapped in mist and dripping vegetation. Visitor numbers are at their lowest — you might have Bayon's smiling faces entirely to yourself at dawn.",
    9: "Still rainy at 25-32°C, but the countryside is spectacularly beautiful with flooded rice paddies stretching to the horizon. Pchum Ben ceremonies at the temples add a living spiritual dimension to the ancient ruins. The roads can be muddy on the outer circuit, so stick to the main temple routes.",
    10: "Rains ease through the month at 24-32°C and the moats and barays are gorgeously full and reflective. The Tonle Sap is at maximum flood, making the floating villages accessible and fascinating. It's a transitional month with improving weather and still-low prices — arguably the best-value month.",
    11: "Dry season returns with 23-32°C, clear mornings, and refreshed, green landscapes around the temples. Tourist numbers tick up but haven't reached peak levels yet. Angkor Wat's west-facing facade catches golden afternoon light perfectly, and the reflection in the full moat is postcard material.",
    12: "Beautiful dry weather at 22-31°C with cool mornings and comfortable temple-exploring temperatures. High season is in full swing with the holiday crowd arriving, pushing hotel prices up. The Christmas-New Year period is the busiest of the year — book three months ahead or prepare to compromise.",
  },
  'ly-libya': {
    1: "Winter in Tripoli means 9-17°C with occasional rain showers and a Mediterranean chill that surprises most visitors. The Roman ruins at Leptis Magna are hauntingly empty and magnificent under grey skies. Travel here remains complex due to ongoing security concerns — thorough research and local contacts are essential.",
    2: "Temperatures climb slightly to 10-18°C with decreasing rainfall and longer sunny spells. The coastal cities are pleasant for walking, and the old medina of Tripoli rewards those who can access it. Independent travel remains extremely challenging; organized specialist tours with security arrangements are the realistic option.",
    3: "Spring arrives at 12-20°C with wildflowers blooming across the Jebel Nafusa mountains. The Saharan south starts heating up, making this a good window for desert excursions to Ghadames. The political situation continues to shape all travel plans — check current advisories obsessively.",
    4: "Lovely coastal weather at 14-23°C with clear Mediterranean skies and warm sunshine. The ancient Greek ruins of Cyrene on the eastern coast are among the most impressive and least-visited in the ancient world. Desert temperatures become uncomfortable, so northern coastal sites are the focus.",
    5: "Warming to 17-27°C with reliable sunshine and the Mediterranean Sea becoming swimmable. Sabratha's seaside Roman theater is one of the most dramatic ancient monuments anywhere. The ghibli (hot Saharan wind) can blow in, coating everything in fine sand and pushing temperatures skyward.",
    6: "Summer heat arrives at 20-31°C along the coast, with the Saharan interior becoming brutally hot at 40°C+. The coast remains manageable with sea breezes, and Tripoli's cafe culture is best enjoyed in the evening. Ramadan timing varies — if it falls here, expect adjusted hours and a transformed social rhythm.",
    7: "Peak summer at 22-33°C on the coast and scorching 45°C+ in the desert — the Sahara is off-limits to sensible travelers. The Mediterranean beaches near Tripoli offer relief, though facilities are limited. Evening promenades along the Tripoli corniche are a genuine local tradition worth experiencing.",
    8: "The hottest month at 23-34°C along the coast with relentless sunshine and warm seas. The interior is an inferno, but the coast catches enough breeze to remain tolerable. This is the quietest month — even local tourism pauses in the heat.",
    9: "Heat begins easing to 22-32°C with the Mediterranean still warm and the light turning golden. The desert gradually becomes approachable again toward month's end. September marks a subtle shift — the oppressive summer lifts and the country feels like it exhales.",
    10: "Autumn brings relief at 18-27°C with comfortable temperatures for exploring both coast and interior. The Saharan oases of Ghadames and Ubari are accessible again, with warm days and cool desert nights. Rain returns occasionally to the coast, greening up the landscape.",
    11: "Cooling to 14-22°C with increasing rainfall along the coast and perfect desert weather at 15-28°C. The Acacus Mountains in the southwest reveal extraordinary prehistoric rock art in perfect trekking conditions. This is one of the few optimal months for Saharan exploration.",
    12: "Winter arrives with 10-18°C and Mediterranean storms bringing rain to Tripoli and the coast. The Roman ruins at Leptis Magna are atmospheric under dramatic winter skies and virtually tourist-free. The Sahara offers pleasant daytime temperatures but nights drop near freezing — pack accordingly.",
  },
  'ma-agadir-atlantic': {
    1: "Agadir's winter is the envy of Europe — 10-20°C with 300+ sunshine days per year keeping the Atlantic coast bright. The beach is calm and uncrowded, perfect for long walks and surf lessons at the gentler breaks. Argan oil cooperatives in the surrounding countryside make for fascinating day trips.",
    2: "Similar mild weather at 11-21°C with slightly more rainfall than January but still predominantly sunny. The surf picks up with consistent Atlantic swells drawing international surfers to Taghazout and Tamri. The souks are relaxed and unhurried — perfect for leisurely shopping without the summer hustle.",
    3: "Spring warmth arrives at 13-22°C and the surrounding countryside blooms after winter rains. It's an ideal month for combining beach time with excursions to Paradise Valley and the Anti-Atlas mountains. The almond trees blossom spectacularly in the Ameln Valley, about two hours east.",
    4: "Beautiful at 14-23°C with warm sunshine, calm seas, and the first properly warm beach days. European charter tourists start arriving, but the coast never feels overwhelmed. The seafood at the port grill restaurants is extraordinary year-round — whole grilled fish, chermoula prawns, and tagine by the water.",
    5: "Warming nicely to 16-24°C with the Atlantic still refreshing for swimming — wetsuits are optional now. The coast enters a sweet spot of warm weather, manageable crowds, and reasonable hotel prices. Kitesurfing season begins at Essaouira-area beaches with the alizee trade winds building.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 18-26°C but the Atlantic breeze keeps Agadir cooler than inland Morocco. The beach scene livens up with both European and Moroccan domestic tourists. The Timitar music festival brings Amazigh and world music acts to stages across the city.",
    7: "Peak summer at 20-28°C with the coast providing welcome relief from Marrakech's scorching inland heat. The beaches are busy but the coastline stretches for miles — solitude is always findable. The sardine and seafood catches peak, making waterfront dining a nightly ritual.",
    8: "The warmest month at 21-29°C with warm ocean water and wall-to-wall sunshine. Moroccan and European vacationers pack the resort strip, so book ahead for the better beachfront hotels. The nightlife scene heats up with rooftop bars and beach clubs running until late.",
    9: "Summer lingers at 20-28°C with thinning crowds and the ocean at its warmest and most inviting. Surfers return as autumn swells start building, and Taghazout village buzzes with board-carrying international visitors. It's arguably the best month — perfect weather, fewer tourists, warm water.",
    10: "Cooling slightly to 17-26°C with the first autumn rains possible but still predominantly sunny. The surf season kicks into gear with powerful Atlantic swells arriving consistently. The argan harvest happens in the surrounding countryside, and the oil is at its freshest.",
    11: "Autumnal at 14-23°C with increasing chances of rain but still many sunny days. European snowbirds start arriving for long winter stays, giving the town a relaxed, residential feel. The Paradise Valley waterfalls are flowing again after the first rains — a gorgeous half-day excursion.",
    12: "Mild winter at 11-20°C with Agadir feeling like a warm refuge while northern Europe freezes. The Christmas and New Year period brings a brief tourist spike but the atmosphere stays laid-back. Spectacular sunsets over the Atlantic make the clifftop kasbah ruins the place to be at golden hour.",
  },
  'ma-fes-imperial': {
    1: "Fes in January is cool and quiet at 5-15°C with occasional rain soaking the medina's cobblestones. The ancient tanneries and medersas are crowd-free, allowing you to absorb the medieval atmosphere in peace. Pack layers — the riads can be chilly, though most now have heating in the rooms.",
    2: "Temperatures hover at 6-16°C with continued rain possible and the surrounding hills turning green. The Fes medina, the world's largest car-free urban area, is at its most atmospheric when wet and steamy. Almond blossoms appear in the Middle Atlas foothills, signaling spring's approach.",
    3: "Spring arrives beautifully at 8-19°C with wildflowers carpeting the hills around Meknes and Volubilis. The Roman ruins at Volubilis are magnificent under clear March skies with green fields as a backdrop. Tourist numbers start climbing but the medina still feels genuinely local and lived-in.",
    4: "Gorgeous weather at 10-22°C with warm sunshine and the gardens of Meknes and Fes in full bloom. The Fes Festival of World Sacred Music (some years) transforms the city into a global cultural destination. This is one of the best months — comfortable temperatures, manageable crowds, peak beauty.",
    5: "Warming to 13-26°C with dry conditions and longer, sun-drenched days. The medina's labyrinthine alleys provide welcome shade as afternoon temperatures climb. Ifrane in the nearby Middle Atlas offers cool mountain escapes with cedar forests and Barbary macaques.",
    6: "Summer heat arrives at 16-32°C and the medina becomes a furnace by midday — plan around siestas. Morning visits to the Bou Inania Medersa and the tanneries are essential before the heat peaks. The rooftop restaurants and cafes come alive in the cooler evenings.",
    7: "Hot at 18-36°C with the medina baking under relentless sun — hydration and shade are survival strategies. The Moulay Idriss moussem (pilgrimage festival) near Meknes is one of Morocco's most important religious events. Escape to the Middle Atlas where temperatures at altitude hover around 25°C.",
    8: "The hottest month at 19-37°C — the medina's thick walls actually help, keeping interiors surprisingly cool. Tourist numbers thin in the extreme heat, and riad prices drop accordingly. Evening food tours through Rcif and Bab Boujloud are the way to experience Fassi cuisine without melting.",
    9: "Heat eases to 17-33°C as summer loosens its grip on the imperial cities. The first autumn light gilds the medina's minarets and creates magic in the narrow alleyways. Pomegranate season arrives, and the fresh juice stalls are impossible to pass without stopping.",
    10: "Autumn is lovely at 13-26°C with comfortable walking weather and the olive harvest underway in the surrounding countryside. The medina buzz picks up with returning tourists but never feels overwhelmed like Marrakech. Day trips to Moulay Idriss and the cedar forests are at their autumnal best.",
    11: "Cooling to 9-20°C with the first real rains returning and the medina taking on a moody, atmospheric quality. The Fes Culinary Festival (some years) showcases the city's claim to Morocco's finest cuisine. Fewer tourists means more genuine interactions with artisans and shopkeepers in the souks.",
    12: "Winter settles in at 5-16°C with rain common and the medina quiet with a contemplative energy. The riads glow with lantern light and the hammams are at their most welcoming — a hot steam bath on a cold Fes night is perfection. New Year brings a brief uptick in visitors but the pace stays unhurried.",
  },
  'ma-marrakech-atlas': {
    1: "Marrakech in January is cool and clear at 6-18°C with snow-capped Atlas Mountains providing a dramatic backdrop. The medina souks are mercifully uncrowded, and the Jemaa el-Fnaa food stalls steam into the chilly evening air. Ski touring at Oukaimeden, Africa's highest ski resort, is a surreal two-hour day trip.",
    2: "Slightly warmer at 7-19°C with almond blossoms transforming the Atlas valleys into pink-and-white fantasies. The Majorelle Garden is beautiful year-round but particularly pleasant without summer's suffocating crowds. Riad prices are at their lowest — luxury stays that would cost $400 in April go for half.",
    3: "Spring hits perfectly at 10-23°C with the city bursting into color and the Atlas foothills carpeted in wildflowers. Trekking to Imlil and the Toubkal region is magnificent with snow still on the peaks and green valleys below. Tourist numbers climb steadily — book the signature riads early.",
    4: "Beautiful at 12-26°C with warm days, cool evenings, and the roses blooming in the Dades Valley. The Kelaat M'Gouna Rose Festival celebrates the harvest with processions, music, and rosewater everything. This is peak season — prices match demand, but the experience justifies every dirham.",
    5: "Warming to 15-30°C as summer approaches and the medina starts to shimmer with heat by afternoon. The Ourika Valley offers cool relief with waterfalls and Berber villages just an hour from the city. Late-afternoon tagine at a Jemaa el-Fnaa stall as the call to prayer echoes is quintessential Marrakech.",
    6: "Hot at 18-35°C with the famous Marrakech furnace starting to fire up — plan outdoor activities for early morning. The rooftop terraces of the medina come alive at sunset when the temperature drops to bearable levels. The Atlas peaks are now snow-free and trekking at altitude offers escape from the lowland heat.",
    7: "Scorching at 21-39°C — midday in the medina is genuinely dangerous without water and shade. The city takes on a languid, siesta-paced rhythm that has its own appeal if you lean into it. Toubkal summit attempts are best done now with stable, dry conditions at altitude.",
    8: "Peak heat at 21-40°C makes this the most challenging month for visitors — even locals retreat indoors by noon. Hotel and riad prices hit rock bottom, and the Jemaa el-Fnaa is oddly compelling in the extreme heat. Night markets and hammam visits become the core experience.",
    9: "Heat eases to 18-33°C and Marrakech collectively sighs with relief as the worst of summer passes. The city comes back to life in the evenings, and the Atlas trekking conditions remain excellent. Dates and figs appear in the souks as the late-summer harvest comes in.",
    10: "Gorgeous at 14-28°C with golden autumn light and the first rains freshening up the dusty city. Tourist crowds return in force, and the medina buzzes with energy without summer's punishing heat. The Ouzoud Waterfalls, two hours northeast, are flowing strongly and surrounded by Barbary macaques.",
    11: "Cooling to 10-22°C with shorter days and occasionally dramatic rainstorms that clear quickly. The city feels more authentically Moroccan as summer visitors depart and local rhythms reassert themselves. The hammams are essential — a hot scrub and massage after a day exploring the souks is the ultimate reset.",
    12: "Crisp winter weather at 7-19°C with clear skies and the Atlas gleaming with fresh snow behind the pink walls. The holiday season brings a festive international crowd to the riads and restaurants. New Year's Eve on a medina rooftop with champagne and the minaret-studded skyline is unforgettable.",
  },
  'ma-sahara': {
    1: "Winter in the Sahara near Merzouga means cool days at 5-18°C and genuinely cold nights that can drop near freezing. The Erg Chebbi dunes glow amber at sunrise without a single footprint marring the sand — blissful solitude. Pack serious layers for overnight desert camps; the stars will keep you awake regardless.",
    2: "Slightly warmer at 7-20°C with continued cold nights and crystal-clear desert skies. The morning light on the dunes is extraordinary, and camel treks to remote camps are the quintessential experience. Sandstorms are rare this month, making it one of the most reliable windows for desert photography.",
    3: "Spring warmth arrives at 10-24°C with comfortable daytime temperatures and the desert blooming briefly after any winter rain. Gnawa music festivals in nearby Khamlia showcase the spiritual musical traditions of the Saharan communities. The shifting sands take on different colors throughout the day as the sun arcs higher.",
    4: "Pleasant at 14-28°C with warm days and mild nights — this is peak desert season before the summer oven ignites. The nomadic Amazigh camps are accessible, and 4x4 excursions to Erg Chigaga offer an even more remote dune experience. Sunrise camel rides are the golden ticket, literally.",
    5: "Heating up at 18-33°C as the Sahara starts flexing its thermal muscles. The dunes shimmer in the midday heat, and sandstorms (chergui) become more frequent. It's the last comfortable month for desert exploration before summer makes it inadvisable.",
    6: "Hot at 22-38°C and getting genuinely uncomfortable — only early morning and late evening are pleasant for outdoor activities. Most tourist camps still operate, but the experience is defined by heat management. The night sky is spectacular with zero light pollution and bone-dry desert air.",
    7: "Scorching at 25-42°C — the Sahara earns its fearsome reputation and all but the most determined visitors postpone. Desert camps offer reduced rates for the brave few who venture out. The silence of the empty dunes at 3am under the Milky Way is otherworldly, if you can handle the heat.",
    8: "Peak heat at 25-43°C with the sand hot enough to blister skin through shoes — this is genuinely extreme environment. Only a handful of camps remain open, operating exclusively in the early morning and after sunset. The Perseid meteor shower over the dunes is worth the suffering for stargazers.",
    9: "Heat begins receding to 22-38°C, but summer's grip is still firm through most of September. Late in the month, the desert becomes approachable again for afternoon explorations. The transition brings dramatic light and occasional dust devils dancing across the erg.",
    10: "Autumn relief at 16-30°C brings the return of comfortable desert exploration and the tourist season. Camel treks, dune boarding, and luxury desert camps reopen at full capacity. The temperature differential between blazing noon and chilly midnight makes layering essential.",
    11: "Cool and beautiful at 10-24°C with cold nights returning and the dunes at their most photogenic. The Imilchil Marriage Festival in the nearby Atlas celebrates Amazigh matchmaking traditions with genuine cultural depth. This is prime desert season — book ahead for the better tented camps.",
    12: "Cold nights at 4-19°C and short, clear days make this a dramatic time in the Sahara. New Year's Eve desert camps offer a uniquely magical way to ring in the year under infinite stars. The winter sun sits low, painting the Erg Chebbi dunes in deep gold and burnt orange.",
  },
  'mc-monaco': {
    1: "Monaco's winter is mild by European standards at 6-13°C with the Riviera sunshine still making appearances. The Casino de Monte-Carlo is less frenetic, and the Oceanographic Museum offers world-class marine exhibits without summer queues. Off-season hotel rates in this tiny principality make even the Hotel de Paris almost approachable.",
    2: "Similar to January at 6-13°C with slightly more rain, but the mimosa blooming on the hillsides adds golden warmth. The Monte-Carlo Rally in late January often spills into February excitement. The harbor is full of mega-yachts getting prepped for the season — billionaire bird-watching at its finest.",
    3: "Spring edges in at 8-15°C with longer days and the first outdoor terrace dining becoming pleasant. The Printemps des Arts festival brings classical music and contemporary art to venues across the principality. The rooftop bar at the Fairmont offers Riviera views even before the weather fully cooperates.",
    4: "Warming to 10-17°C with the Riviera transitioning from quiet elegance to buzzing anticipation for the May madness. The Japanese Garden and Princess Grace Rose Garden bloom spectacularly. Practice sessions for the Monaco Grand Prix begin setting up barriers along the harbor circuit.",
    5: "The month Monaco lives for — the Grand Prix transforms the principality into the world's most glamorous racetrack at 14-21°C. Hotel prices reach astronomical levels for race weekend, and the atmosphere is electric with champagne-fueled excess. If the F1 isn't your thing, stay away entirely — the whole place is consumed.",
    6: "Post-Grand Prix calm at 17-24°C with summer settling in and the beaches at Larvotto filling up. The warm Mediterranean beckons, and the beach clubs compete to be the most outrageously luxurious. Monte-Carlo's restaurants shift to alfresco dining, and the evening harbor promenade is pure Riviera theater.",
    7: "Peak summer at 20-27°C with wall-to-wall sunshine and Monaco at its most glamorous and crowded. The Monte-Carlo Summer Festival and Sporting Club concerts bring international headliners to intimate venues. Yacht-watching from the port becomes a competitive sport — the boats just keep getting bigger.",
    8: "The hottest month at 21-28°C with the Riviera in full hedonistic swing. The principality is packed with the international jet set, and prices reflect the demand. The Red Cross Gala is one of the most exclusive events on the social calendar — if you can get an invitation, that is.",
    9: "Summer lingers beautifully at 19-26°C with the crowds thinning but the weather remaining gorgeous. The Monaco Yacht Show in late September is the world's premier superyacht event, drawing extraordinary vessels. It's a more relaxed, genuinely enjoyable time than the frenzy of July-August.",
    10: "Autumn arrives gently at 14-21°C with warm days, cooling evenings, and the last of the summer swimming. The cultural season shifts indoors with ballet and opera at the Salle Garnier. The light over the harbor turns golden and the whole Riviera softens into its most photogenic season.",
    11: "Cooling to 10-17°C with occasional rain but many clear, crisp Mediterranean days. Monaco's restaurants and cafes settle into a more intimate rhythm, and the crowds disappear almost entirely. The National Day celebrations on November 19th bring the Grimaldi family and a parade through the old town.",
    12: "Mild winter at 7-14°C with festive decorations adorning the Casino Square and harbor area. The Monte-Carlo Christmas Village and circus festival bring family-friendly entertainment to the principality. New Year's Eve here is predictably extravagant — champagne, fireworks over the harbor, and price tags to match.",
  },
  'md-moldova': {
    1: "Deep Eastern European winter at -5 to 1°C with snow covering the rolling Moldovan countryside. Chisinau is quiet but the wine cellars at Milestii Mici — the world's largest — are the perfect underground escape at a constant 12°C. Warming up with a bowl of zeama soup and a glass of local red is the national winter ritual.",
    2: "The coldest month at -6 to 0°C with heavy snow and short, grey days across the country. The wine cellars at Cricova offer guided tours through 120km of underground tunnels filled with vintage bottles. Moldovan hospitality shines brightest in winter — home-cooked meals and tuica (plum brandy) ward off the chill.",
    3: "Winter slowly retreats with -1 to 7°C and the first hints of spring in the orchards and vineyards. Martisor celebrations on March 1st see everyone wearing red-and-white spring talismans — it's charming and deeply traditional. The ice on the Dniester River begins breaking up in dramatic fashion.",
    4: "Spring arrives properly at 6-16°C with the vineyards budding and Orthodox Easter bringing elaborate celebrations. The rolling hills around Orheiul Vechi — one of Moldova's most spectacular sites — turn vivid green. Chisinau's parks fill with families enjoying the warming sunshine and blossoming trees.",
    5: "Lovely at 11-22°C with the wine country in full leaf and the countryside at its most beautiful. The Orheiul Vechi cave monastery set in a dramatic limestone gorge is a must-visit in perfect May weather. Wine tourism is emerging as Moldova's signature draw — tastings here cost a fraction of Western European equivalents.",
    6: "Warm summer at 15-26°C with long days and the vineyards in vigorous growth. The Moldovan countryside is spectacularly green and pastoral — think undiscovered Tuscany at Eastern European prices. Chisinau's outdoor cafes and rooftop bars come alive with a social energy that surprises most visitors.",
    7: "The warmest month at 17-29°C with occasional thunderstorms punctuating otherwise sunny days. The sunflower fields reach full bloom, creating golden seas across the Moldovan steppe. Swimming in the lakes around Vadul lui Voda is the local summer tradition — pack a picnic and join in.",
    8: "Hot at 17-29°C with the grape harvest beginning in late August — the vineyards buzz with activity. Wine festivals start popping up across the country, offering tastings of Moldova's increasingly impressive vintages. The Nistru River beaches near Vadul lui Voda are packed with Chisinau locals escaping the city heat.",
    9: "Harvest season at 12-24°C with the National Wine Day festival (first weekend of October, but prep starts now) building excitement. The vineyards turn gold and the winemakers invite visitors to join the grape picking. This is arguably the best month — perfect weather, peak wine culture, autumn colors emerging.",
    10: "Golden autumn at 7-17°C with the National Wine Day transforming Chisinau into a massive open-air tasting event. The countryside is draped in red and amber, and the fresh must (grape juice) appears in every market. Moldova's finest wines — its dessert wines and rare Feteasca Neagra reds — are best appreciated now.",
    11: "Late autumn chill at 2-10°C with rain and fog settling over the vineyards and the tourist season winding down. The wine cellars become the main attraction again as outdoor activities become less appealing. Moldovan comfort food — placinte pies, mamaliga, and sarmale — is at its hearty, warming best.",
    12: "Winter returns at -3 to 3°C with snow and festive preparations across the country. Christmas (celebrated January 7th by most Moldovans, Orthodox calendar) means the December holiday atmosphere is relaxed and genuine rather than commercialized. The mulled wine at Chisinau's modest Christmas market uses local vintages and is genuinely excellent.",
  },
  'me-durmitor': {
    1: "Deep winter in the Montenegrin highlands at -7 to 2°C with heavy snowpack across the Durmitor massif. The ski resort at Savin Kuk offers modest but charming runs with virtually no lift lines. Zabljak town is cozy and quiet — hearty Montenegrin lamb dishes and local rakija by the fireplace.",
    2: "The snowiest month at -6 to 2°C with the Tara Canyon buried under meters of white powder. Cross-country skiing and snowshoeing through the frozen Black Lake (Crno Jezero) landscape is magical. The mountain huts offer basic but warm accommodation for those who want genuine alpine solitude.",
    3: "Winter holds firm at -4 to 5°C but days are lengthening and the first signs of spring appear in sheltered valleys. Skiing continues through March, and the avalanche conditions require careful route planning for backcountry exploration. The Tara River bridge, Europe's highest concrete arch, is dramatic against the snowy gorge.",
    4: "Spring arrives at 1-10°C with snowmelt swelling the rivers and waterfalls thundering through the canyons. The Tara Canyon starts becoming accessible for the first exploratory hikes. Wildflowers push through retreating snow at lower elevations, creating striking alpine meadow scenes.",
    5: "The mountains awaken at 5-15°C with most hiking trails clearing of snow and the Tara River running high and wild. Whitewater rafting season begins on Europe's deepest canyon — the 1,300m-deep Tara gorge is staggering. The national park's 18 glacial lakes start thawing, each more beautiful than the last.",
    6: "Summer hiking season hits full stride at 8-20°C with wildflower meadows, clear mountain lakes, and long golden evenings. The Durmitor peaks (Bobotov Kuk at 2,523m) are accessible to experienced hikers, offering panoramic views across Montenegro. Rafting the Tara is at peak excitement with snowmelt keeping the rapids fierce.",
    7: "Peak season at 10-24°C with perfect trekking conditions and the glacial lakes warm enough for a bracing swim. The mountain lodges and camps are at capacity — book ahead for Black Lake and Zabljak accommodation. Stargazing at altitude is extraordinary with zero light pollution across the national park.",
    8: "Warm and busy at 10-24°C with the hiking trails at their busiest and the Tara River calming to its summer flow. Thunderstorms can roll in quickly at altitude — start hikes early and watch for afternoon buildup. The mountain cheese and meat markets in Zabljak are worth a morning of serious grazing.",
    9: "Autumn begins at 7-18°C with the beech forests turning spectacular shades of gold and crimson. The crowds disappear almost overnight after European holidays end, leaving the trails blissfully empty. Rafting season continues, and the autumn colors reflected in the canyon walls are stunning.",
    10: "Cool at 3-13°C with peak autumn foliage and the first frosts hitting the higher elevations. Black Lake surrounded by golden larches is one of the most beautiful sights in the Balkans. Mountain huts start closing, so plan carefully and check availability before setting out.",
    11: "Winter approaches at -1 to 7°C with the first snowfall on the peaks and hiking season ending. The national park takes on a stark, dramatic beauty as the last leaves fall. Zabljak settles into pre-ski-season quiet — a contemplative time for those who appreciate mountain solitude.",
    12: "Full winter returns at -5 to 2°C with reliable snow for early-season skiing at Savin Kuk. The Durmitor massif under fresh snow is postcard-perfect, and the tiny ski village atmosphere is charmingly unpretentious. New Year's in Zabljak means wood-fired warmth, local wine, and mountains — no glitz, all substance.",
  },
  'me-kotor': {
    1: "Winter on the Bay of Kotor is surprisingly mild at 3-12°C, though rain is frequent and the surrounding mountains channel dramatic storms. The medieval old town is hauntingly empty — you'll have the fortress walls and cat-filled alleys largely to yourself. The baroque churches echo with your footsteps rather than tour group chatter.",
    2: "The Kotor Carnival in February brings masked revelry to the old town at 4-12°C — think Venice's Carnevale but intimate and affordable. Rain remains common, but the fjord-like bay surrounded by cloud-draped mountains is atmospheric beyond belief. Fresh seafood and Montenegrin wine in the old town's stone restaurants is winter bliss.",
    3: "Spring creeps in at 6-15°C with longer days and the bay's waters turning from grey to deep blue. The hillside towns of Perast and Dobrota awaken from winter slumber, and Our Lady of the Rocks island gleams in the spring light. Hiking the fortress walls above Kotor is pleasant without summer's punishing heat.",
    4: "Lovely at 9-18°C with wildflowers, warm sunshine, and the cruise ship season just beginning. The bay is spectacular under clear skies, and the kayaking and swimming season starts for the hardy. It's the sweet spot before the summer invasion — genuine Montenegrin atmosphere with improving weather.",
    5: "Warming to 14-23°C with the first really warm beach days and the Adriatic becoming inviting. The Lovcen National Park above the bay offers panoramic views from the road of 25 hairpin bends. Cruise ships increase in frequency, but the old town absorbs them better than Dubrovnik, just 90 minutes south.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 17-27°C with long sunny days and the bay's waters turning turquoise and inviting. The old town buzzes with life — open-air concerts, waterfront dining, and the evening korzo (promenade) in full swing. Book accommodation well ahead; the bay's intimate scale means supply is limited.",
    7: "Peak summer at 20-31°C with the bay at its most spectacular and the crowds to match. Swimming directly from the old town walls into the crystal-clear bay is one of the Adriatic's great pleasures. The heat can be intense in the stone streets — plan your fortress climb for dawn or dusk.",
    8: "The hottest month at 21-32°C with the bay's tourist density at its maximum. Boat trips to the Blue Cave and around the bay offer relief from the crowded streets. The Boka Night festival sees the bay lit with thousands of floating lanterns and fireworks — truly magical.",
    9: "Summer lingers at 17-28°C with the crowds thinning and the bay settling into a more relaxed rhythm. The swimming is still excellent, and the light turns golden and cinematic on the old stone walls. It's increasingly considered the best month — peak beauty, reasonable crowds, warm seas.",
    10: "Autumn at 12-22°C brings cooler temperatures, occasional rain, and a return to Montenegrin normalcy. The bay's waters remain swimmable for much of the month, and the surrounding mountains show autumn colors. The old town's restaurants shift to heartier, colder-weather menus — grilled meats and heavy red wines.",
    11: "Cooling to 8-16°C with increasing rain and the tourist season firmly over. The bay is moody and magnificent under grey skies, and the medieval atmosphere intensifies without the crowds. Hotel prices drop dramatically, and the old town's genuine residents and stray cats reclaim their territory.",
    12: "Mild winter at 4-13°C with rain common and the occasional stunning clear day revealing snow on the mountains above the bay. Christmas lights twinkle in the old town's narrow streets, and the holiday atmosphere is intimate and authentic. The bay's fjord-like drama is arguably at its most impressive in winter weather.",
  },
  'mg-coast': {
    1: "Peak cyclone season on Nosy Be means 24-31°C with heavy tropical rains and occasional storm systems. The island is lush and spectacularly green, but diving visibility suffers from runoff. Whale sharks are still present in the waters, and the rain-soaked ylang-ylang plantations perfume the entire island.",
    2: "The wettest month at 24-31°C with cyclone risk at its highest — travel insurance is non-negotiable. When the rain pauses, the island is paradise with empty beaches and bioluminescent plankton lighting up the night waters. Most serious divers and beach-goers skip this month, but the brave are rewarded with rock-bottom prices.",
    3: "Still solidly in wet season at 24-31°C with heavy rains gradually beginning to ease late in the month. The surrounding islets like Nosy Komba and Nosy Tanikely remain accessible on calmer days. Lemurs on Nosy Komba are particularly active, and the absence of tourists means more intimate encounters.",
    4: "Transitional month at 24-30°C as the rains decrease and the skies start clearing. Diving conditions improve markedly with visibility increasing throughout the month. The island starts shaking off its wet-season drowsiness, and the first wave of dry-season visitors trickles in.",
    5: "The dry season begins in earnest at 22-30°C with clear skies, calm seas, and excellent diving visibility. Whale shark season kicks off, and the snorkeling around Nosy Tanikely Marine Reserve is extraordinary. Accommodation opens up across the island's range from backpacker bungalows to boutique lodges.",
    6: "Beautiful dry weather at 21-29°C with the southeast trade winds keeping humidity manageable. The diving is world-class with clear waters revealing coral gardens and sea turtles. The island's famous rum (made from local sugarcane) tastes best enjoyed on the beach at sunset — as everything does here.",
    7: "Cooler dry season at 19-28°C with the trade winds at their strongest, creating choppy conditions on exposed coastlines. The sheltered western beaches remain calm and gorgeous, and the fishing is excellent. Humpback whale season begins with the first mothers and calves arriving from Antarctic waters.",
    8: "Peak whale watching at 19-28°C as humpback whales fill the channels between Nosy Be and the mainland. Boat trips to see breaching whales and singing males are the highlight — book with responsible operators. The dry, sunny weather and whale spectacle make this one of the island's best months.",
    9: "Still prime whale season at 20-29°C with excellent diving and the island at its most popular with international visitors. The baobab trees and ylang-ylang plantations are gorgeous under clear blue skies. September brings the Donia music festival, Madagascar's biggest music event, to Nosy Be.",
    10: "Warming at 22-30°C with whale season winding down and the last humpbacks departing for southern waters. The dry season holds firm with beautiful beach weather and improving water temperatures. Late October sees the first tentative rain showers, but they're brief and welcome.",
    11: "The wet season returns gradually at 23-31°C with afternoon showers becoming more frequent. The island remains beautiful and functional between rains, with green returning to the landscape. Dive operators still run regular trips, and the combination of warmth and fewer tourists is appealing.",
    12: "Full wet season at 24-31°C with heavy tropical rains and the beginning of cyclone season. The island is dramatically lush and prices drop significantly for accommodation and tours. Christmas on Nosy Be has a uniquely Malagasy-French colonial charm — tropical flowers, seafood feasts, and warm rain.",
  },
  'mg-highlands': {
    1: "Rainy season in full force at 15-26°C with daily afternoon downpours turning the highlands impossibly green. The rice paddies around Antsirabe and Ambositra are flooded and stunning, with farmers knee-deep in planting. Roads can be challenging but the landscape is at its most dramatic and photogenic.",
    2: "Peak rains continue at 16-26°C with cyclone systems occasionally affecting the highlands with heavy winds and flooding. The Ranomafana National Park is lush and the lemurs are active, though trails can be muddy. Travel here requires flexibility and patience — Madagascar operates on mora mora (slowly, slowly) time.",
    3: "Still rainy at 15-26°C but the intensity begins easing toward month's end. The terraced rice paddies glow emerald green against the red laterite soil — a color combination unique to Madagascar. The Avenue of the Baobabs near Morondava is accessible and spectacular in the wet-season light.",
    4: "Transition month at 14-25°C as rains decrease and the highlands dry out. The autumn harvest begins, and the countryside buzzes with agricultural activity. Antsirabe's thermal baths and the artisan workshops along the Route Nationale 7 are excellent touring in the improving weather.",
    5: "Dry season arrives at 11-23°C with cooler temperatures and clear highland skies. The Route Nationale 7 from Tana to Tulear is at its most traversable, and the Isalo National Park beckons with sandstone canyons and natural pools. Lemur watching in Ranomafana improves as animals come to sun themselves in the cooler mornings.",
    6: "Cool and dry at 9-21°C — bring layers for chilly highland mornings, especially above 1,500m. The Malagasy highlands feel a world apart from the tropical coast — think red-earth villages, eucalyptus groves, and terraced hillsides. Antananarivo's markets are at their most vibrant with the full range of harvest produce available.",
    7: "The coolest month at 8-20°C with frosty mornings possible in the higher valleys. The landscape is golden-brown and dry, with excellent visibility for photography across the highland plateau. Andasibe-Mantadia's indri lemurs are easiest to spot and hear now, their eerie calls echoing through the forest at dawn.",
    8: "Still cool and dry at 9-21°C with the highland air crisp and invigorating. The fire season begins with farmers burning fields for next season's planting, creating hazy but dramatic sunsets. Whale watching on the east coast is at its peak, making an east-west highland-coast combo trip ideal.",
    9: "Warming gradually to 11-24°C with the dry season holding firm and spring energy returning. The jacaranda trees begin blooming purple across Antananarivo's hills, creating stunning urban landscapes. It's one of the best months for wildlife and trekking, with comfortable temperatures and dry trails.",
    10: "Spring at 13-26°C with the first rains possible late in the month and the highlands starting to green up. The orchids in the eastern rainforests begin their spectacular blooming season. Tourist numbers are modest, making for uncrowded national park visits and more personal guiding experiences.",
    11: "Wet season begins at 15-27°C with increasing afternoon showers and dramatic thunderstorms over the highlands. The rice paddies are plowed and flooded for the new season, creating mirror-like reflections across the valleys. Chameleon and reptile enthusiasts arrive for breeding season when these remarkable creatures are most visible.",
    12: "Full rainy season at 16-27°C with daily downpours and the highlands at their most lush and vivid. Christmas and New Year see domestic travel peak, with Malagasy families heading to ancestral villages. The famadihana (turning of the bones) ceremonies happen during the wet season — witnessing one with local permission is profoundly moving.",
  },
  'mh-marshall': {
    1: "The dry season delivers 26-30°C with lower humidity and the best diving conditions of the year. The atolls shimmer under clear Pacific skies, and the WWII wrecks at Bikini Atoll are accessible in the calmest seas. Getting here is half the adventure — flights are infrequent and accommodations basic but authentic.",
    2: "Driest month at 26-30°C with consistent sunshine and the trade winds providing natural cooling. Majuro Atoll's lagoon is mirror-calm and turquoise, and the outer islands feel genuinely end-of-the-world remote. The Marshallese stick chart navigation tradition is a unique cultural experience — sailors still use these wave maps.",
    3: "Continuing dry at 27-31°C with excellent visibility for snorkeling the pristine coral reefs. The Marshall Islands' nuclear testing history is sobering — the National Nuclear Testing Remembrance Day on March 1st is a significant cultural moment. The outer atolls offer some of the most untouched marine environments on Earth.",
    4: "Transitional at 27-31°C with humidity building and the first rain showers appearing. The diving remains excellent, and the warm waters host manta rays and reef sharks year-round. Majuro's Robert Reimers Hotel is the social hub, and the Marshallese friendliness makes every visitor feel welcomed.",
    5: "Wet season begins at 27-31°C with increasing rainfall but temperatures remaining constant year-round. The coconut crabs are enormous and surprisingly approachable on the quieter atolls. Transportation between atolls remains infrequent — build flexibility into any island-hopping plans.",
    6: "Solidly wet at 27-31°C with frequent tropical showers and higher humidity. The rain is warm and usually passes quickly, leaving behind spectacular rainbows over the lagoons. Outrigger canoe culture is alive and well — joining a local crew for a sail is one of the Pacific's great experiences.",
    7: "Continued rain at 27-31°C with the wettest conditions of the year approaching. Typhoon risk is minimal this far north in the Pacific, but heavy rain systems can stall over the atolls. The bioluminescence in the lagoons during dark, rainy nights is otherworldly.",
    8: "Near-peak rainfall at 27-31°C but the warmth and the stunning lagoon colors compensate for the wet weather. The annual Constitution Day celebrations bring traditional dance, canoe racing, and feasting. Hotel availability is almost never an issue — this is one of the world's least-visited countries.",
    9: "Still wet at 27-31°C with heavy showers common, though mornings are often clear for beach and diving excursions. The marine life is incredibly diverse with over 1,000 fish species and pristine coral gardens. The remoteness is the point — if you've come this far, you're exactly the kind of traveler who gets it.",
    10: "Rainfall begins decreasing at 27-31°C as the wet season starts its transition. The water clarity improves, and diving conditions get progressively better through the month. Manit Day (the last Friday) celebrates Marshallese culture with traditional foods, crafts, and performances.",
    11: "Transitioning to dry at 27-31°C with decreasing rain and improving visibility for water activities. The tuna fishing is excellent, and the Marshallese fishing culture is deeply ingrained in daily life. The sunsets over the lagoon — vivid oranges and purples reflecting off calm water — are consistently extraordinary.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 26-30°C with clear skies and calm seas perfect for atoll exploration. The Christmas celebrations blend Marshallese and American cultural traditions in a unique Pacific way. It's a special time to visit — the community gatherings and shared feasts embody the generous island spirit.",
  },
  'mk-ohrid': {
    1: "Winter in Ohrid means 0-6°C with the ancient lakeside town wrapped in atmospheric mist and occasional snow. Lake Ohrid, Europe's oldest and deepest, takes on a steely grey beauty, and the Byzantine churches stand silent and frost-dusted. The old town is virtually tourist-free — exploring the 365 churches feels genuinely contemplative.",
    2: "Coldest month at -1 to 6°C with snow possible in the hills around the lake and short, grey days. The monastery of St. Naum, 30km south, is hauntingly beautiful in the winter stillness. Ohrid's traditional cuisine — grilled trout from the lake, tavche gravche beans — warms you from the inside out.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 2-11°C with the first warming days and the lake's color shifting from grey to deep blue. The almond trees around the old town start blossoming, and the local fishermen return to their boats. It's shoulder season at its most peaceful — the town belongs to its residents and the occasional curious traveler.",
    4: "Pleasant at 6-16°C with spring in full bloom and the lakefront promenade coming to life. The views from the Samuil Fortress are breathtaking with snow-capped mountains reflected in the deepening blue lake. Orthodox Easter celebrations at the Church of St. Sophia feature stunning medieval frescoes as backdrop.",
    5: "Lovely at 11-22°C with warm sunshine, blooming wildflowers, and the first brave swimmers testing the lake. The Ohrid Summer Festival preparations begin, and the open-air Ancient Theater hosts its first performances. This is an excellent month — warm enough to enjoy, uncrowded enough to absorb the UNESCO heritage.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 14-27°C with the lake warming up and the town's beaches filling with regional visitors. The Ohrid Summer Festival launches with music, theater, and dance performances in historic venues across town. The Church of St. John at Kaneo, perched on a cliff above the water, is North Macedonia's most photographed site.",
    7: "Peak summer at 17-30°C with the lake at swimming temperature and the old town buzzing with Balkan holiday energy. Boat trips across the lake to St. Naum monastery combine swimming stops with cultural visits. The nightlife along the harbor picks up, with open-air bars and restaurants serving late into the warm evenings.",
    8: "The warmest month at 17-31°C with the lake at its most inviting and the town at full tourist capacity. The Ohrid pearls — a local handicraft tradition — make for distinctive souvenirs from the old-town workshops. Balkan tourists dominate in August, creating a lively, family-friendly atmosphere.",
    9: "Summer lingers at 14-27°C with the crowds departing and the lake still warm and swimmable. The light turns amber and cinematic on the old stone streets and lakefront churches. Wine harvest celebrations begin in the surrounding Tikves region, and the local Vranec reds are bold and excellent.",
    10: "Autumn at 9-20°C with golden foliage around the lake and crisp, clear days perfect for hiking. The Galicica National Park between Lake Ohrid and Lake Prespa offers stunning ridge walks with twin-lake panoramas. The trout fishing season peaks, and the lakeside restaurants serve it impossibly fresh.",
    11: "Cooling to 4-13°C with rain more frequent and the tourist season firmly over. The old town's museums and churches are uncrowded and meditative. The annual Ohrid Film Festival brings arthouse cinema to this ancient setting — an unexpected cultural bonus for November visitors.",
    12: "Winter descends at 1-8°C with short days and occasional snow dusting the old town's red rooftops and church domes. The lakefront is moody and magnificent, and the handful of open restaurants serve hearty Macedonian comfort food. New Year's celebrations are intimate and genuine — this is not a party destination, it's a soul destination.",
  },
  'ml-mali': {
    1: "The cool, dry harmattan season brings comfortable 18-33°C temperatures and hazy Saharan dust over Bamako. Djenne's famous Monday market and the Great Mosque — the largest mud-brick building on Earth — are spectacular in the dry season. Security concerns in the north remain serious; stick to Bamako and the southern Mande region.",
    2: "Dry and warming to 20-36°C with the harmattan haze gradually clearing to reveal brilliant Sahelian skies. The Festival au Desert, when it runs, brings Tuareg blues and desert rock to the dunes near Timbuktu. Travel in the north requires current security assessment — the situation remains fluid and complex.",
    3: "Getting hot at 23-38°C as the pre-monsoon heat builds across the Sahel. The Niger River is at its lowest, and pirogue (wooden boat) trips near Mopti and Segou are intimate and beautiful. The Dogon Country, one of West Africa's most remarkable cultural landscapes, is accessible but requires experienced guides.",
    4: "Approaching peak heat at 25-40°C with the landscape baking under relentless sun before the rains arrive. The mango trees explode with fruit, and the markets overflow with the country's incredible variety. This is the toughest month for comfort, but the cultural experiences — music, dance, storytelling — are year-round.",
    5: "Pre-monsoon tension at 26-41°C with the first thunderstorms teasing the parched landscape. The heat is extreme but the anticipation of rain creates palpable energy across rural Mali. The Bamako art and music scene — griots, kora players, and contemporary artists — thrives regardless of season.",
    6: "The rains arrive with dramatic storms at 24-37°C, transforming the dusty landscape almost overnight. The Niger River begins rising, and the Sahel greens up with astonishing speed. Roads deteriorate rapidly in the south — 4x4 vehicles become essential rather than optional.",
    7: "Full monsoon at 23-33°C with daily heavy rains and the countryside turned emerald green. Travel becomes challenging as many roads flood, but the landscape is spectacular. Bamako's live music venues — the city is one of Africa's great music capitals — are the rainy-season highlight.",
    8: "Peak rains at 22-32°C with rivers swollen and the inner Niger Delta flooding to create vast, bird-rich wetlands. The rice paddies and millet fields are in full growth, and rural Mali is at its most beautiful. Overland travel is at its most difficult — plan carefully and expect delays.",
    9: "Rains taper off at 23-33°C with the landscape at maximum green and the rivers still running high. The harvest preparations begin, and the sense of renewal across the countryside is tangible. The roads slowly dry out and the travel season starts to reopen.",
    10: "Post-monsoon at 23-36°C with the rains ending and the harvest in full swing — a celebratory time across rural Mali. The Niger River is high and perfect for boat travel between Mopti and Timbuktu (security permitting). The Festival sur le Niger in Segou may run this month, bringing music to the riverside.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 20-36°C with comfortable evenings and clear, dust-free skies. The harmattan hasn't kicked in yet, making this arguably the best weather month. The cultural events and music festivals that define Mali's global reputation start their season in earnest.",
    12: "Cool and dry at 18-33°C with the harmattan beginning to blow fine Saharan dust across the landscape. Christmas celebrations in Mali's Christian minority communities are joyful and welcoming. The Segou Festival and other events make December one of the best months for experiencing Mali's extraordinary musical heritage.",
  },
  'mm-bagan': {
    1: "Peak dry season at 15-30°C with clear skies and comfortable temperatures for exploring Bagan's 2,000+ temples. Hot-air balloon rides at sunrise over the temple-studded plain are the defining experience — book weeks ahead. The Irrawaddy River is low, and the dusty plain glows golden in the morning light.",
    2: "Warming to 17-33°C with continued dry weather and the temple plain starting to shimmer in the midday heat. The crowds are at their peak, but Bagan's sheer scale means you can always find a quiet temple to yourself. Electric bikes (e-bikes) are the best way to explore — cheap, easy, and covering enormous distances.",
    3: "Hot season intensifies at 20-37°C, and temple visits after 10am require serious heat management. The Irrawaddy drops further, revealing sandy beaches along its banks perfect for sunset walks. Morning visits to the key temples (Ananda, Dhammayangyi, Sulamani) are essential before the heat becomes punishing.",
    4: "Peak heat at 22-40°C — Bagan becomes a furnace, and the dusty plain radiates heat like an oven. Thingyan Water Festival in mid-April brings joyful chaos to nearby towns and cities with water-throwing celebrations. Many travelers avoid this month, but the empty temples and dramatic heat-haze views have their appeal.",
    5: "Pre-monsoon tension at 24-39°C with the first storms possible late in the month. The humidity builds and the landscape yearns for rain. The temple plain takes on an otherworldly quality in the heavy, hazy air — it's cinematic if you can handle the conditions.",
    6: "The monsoon arrives with afternoon storms at 24-35°C, turning the dry plain surprisingly green. The rain brings blessed relief from the heat, and the temples look dramatic against thundercloud skies. Tourist numbers drop significantly, and prices follow — it's contrarian but rewarding travel.",
    7: "Full monsoon at 24-34°C with daily rains greening the landscape and the Irrawaddy rising steadily. Balloon flights are suspended for the season, but the atmospheric temple-and-storm photography opportunities are extraordinary. The mud paths between temples can be tricky — stick to paved routes or embrace the adventure.",
    8: "Continued monsoon at 24-33°C with the heaviest rainfall and the Irrawaddy at its most powerful. The plain is a lush green patchwork with temples rising like islands from the vegetation. Visitor numbers are at annual lows — some temples feel genuinely undiscovered.",
    9: "Rains begin easing at 24-33°C with the green landscape at its peak beauty. The Irrawaddy is high, and boat trips between Bagan and Mandalay are at their most scenic. This is a transitional month with improving weather and still-low tourist numbers — excellent value.",
    10: "Post-monsoon at 23-33°C with decreasing rain and the landscape retaining its vibrant green. The light through clearing storm clouds creates dramatic temple silhouettes. Balloon flights resume late in the month, and the combination of green plains and golden temples is stunning.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 19-32°C with clear skies, comfortable temperatures, and the tourist season ramping up. The temple plain is still lush from the monsoon rains, creating the best combination of good weather and green landscape. Balloon flights are fully operational — sunrise over the temples is pure magic.",
    12: "Cool dry season at 16-30°C with perfect temple-exploring weather and the holiday crowd arriving. The morning mist that settles over the temple plain and then burns off as the balloons rise is one of Southeast Asia's most iconic sights. Book accommodation and balloon rides well ahead for the Christmas-New Year period.",
  },
  'mm-inle': {
    1: "Cool dry season at 8-25°C with chilly mornings that demand a fleece for dawn boat trips on the lake. The leg-rowing Intha fishermen are silhouetted against misty sunrises that photographers live for. The floating gardens, stilted villages, and weaving workshops make this one of Myanmar's most unique destinations.",
    2: "Warming slightly to 10-28°C with continued dry weather and the lake at its lowest and clearest. The pagoda festivals begin, with Phaung Daw Oo being the most spectacular on the lake. The Shan Hills surrounding the lake are dry and golden, offering excellent hiking from Kalaw to Inle (a classic 2-3 day trek).",
    3: "Hot season builds at 13-32°C with the lake starting to shrink and the floating gardens concentrated in smaller channels. The morning mists are less reliable but the warm afternoons are perfect for exploring the lake's many monasteries and workshops. Red lacquerware and Shan textiles make for excellent, lightweight souvenirs.",
    4: "Hot at 16-34°C with the pre-monsoon heat settling over the Shan Highlands. Thingyan Water Festival transforms lakeside towns into joyous water battles. The lake's shallow edges dry out, and the fishing boats concentrate in deeper water — the iconic fisherman photos require earlier starts.",
    5: "Pre-monsoon at 18-33°C with the first showers possible and the humidity building in the highlands. The Kalaw-to-Inle trek remains possible but gets increasingly muddy toward month's end. The lake level is at its annual minimum, and some channels become too shallow for boat traffic.",
    6: "Monsoon arrives at 19-30°C with regular afternoon rains and the lake beginning to refill. The Shan Hills turn vivid green, and the floating tomato gardens flourish in the rising water. Tourist numbers drop sharply, meaning more authentic interactions with the Intha communities.",
    7: "Full monsoon at 19-29°C with daily rains and the lake expanding across its floodplain. The leg-rowing fishermen work through the rain with practiced nonchalance, and the scene is atmospheric if wet. Many guesthouses offer significant discounts, and the lack of tourist boats makes the lake feel more genuine.",
    8: "Peak rains at 19-28°C with the lake at its largest and deepest. The surrounding rice paddies are flooded and the hills are impossibly green. Travel around the lake is actually easier now — the deeper water opens up channels that are impassable in the dry season.",
    9: "Still rainy at 19-29°C but with occasional clear spells that reveal the Shan Hills in stunning clarity. The floating markets rotate between villages, and the rainy-season produce is abundant. The Phaung Daw Oo Pagoda Festival (dates vary) is one of Myanmar's most important, with golden barges crossing the lake.",
    10: "Rains ease at 17-29°C with the landscape retaining its green beauty. The lake level starts its slow retreat, and the fishing intensifies. The post-monsoon light is golden and soft — photographers consider this the most beautiful month at Inle.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 13-28°C with cool mornings and clear skies over the shimmering lake. The Taunggyi Balloon Festival (Tazaungdaing) launches fire balloons over the Shan Hills in a spectacular display. Tourist numbers climb steadily, and the morning boat trips fill up — book with your guesthouse the evening before.",
    12: "Cool and dry at 9-26°C with crisp mornings that turn the lake into a mirror reflecting the surrounding hills. The holiday season brings peak visitor numbers, but the lake's many villages and channels absorb them well. Dawn on the lake with the mist lifting, fishermen rowing, and pagoda spires catching the first light is unforgettable.",
  },
  'mm-yangon': {
    1: "Dry season beauty at 18-33°C with Yangon's parks green from the monsoon and the Shwedagon Pagoda gleaming in clear skies. The golden stupa at sunset, surrounded by praying devotees and the buzz of the city, is Southeast Asia's most magnetic sight. Street food — mohinga noodle soup, tea leaf salad — is life-changing at any corner stall.",
    2: "Warming to 19-35°C with zero rain and the city at its most accessible and pleasant. The colonial architecture downtown — crumbling grandeur along Pansodan Street — rewards hours of walking. The Bogyoke Aung San Market offers gems, lacquerware, and textiles in a beautiful Art Deco building.",
    3: "Hot season arrives at 22-36°C with the heat becoming assertive but the rain still weeks away. The Shwedagon Pagoda Festival draws thousands of pilgrims and is one of Myanmar's most vibrant religious events. Early mornings and late afternoons are the sweet spots for exploring the city's fading colonial core.",
    4: "Peak heat at 24-37°C — Yangon swelters and the pre-monsoon humidity is oppressive. Thingyan Water Festival transforms the city into a massive, joyful water fight for four days — everyone gets soaked and nobody minds. It's the biggest party of the year, and experiencing it in Yangon is unforgettable chaos.",
    5: "Pre-monsoon tension breaks with the first serious storms at 24-34°C — the rain is warm and welcome. The city's drainage struggles with the initial downpours, and streets flood dramatically but briefly. The Sule Pagoda area and Chinatown are best explored in the dry morning hours.",
    6: "Full monsoon at 24-31°C with heavy, almost daily rainfall and the city at its wettest and most atmospheric. The rain transforms Yangon's parks into tropical jungle and keeps the temperature more bearable than the scorching dry months. The tea shops — Myanmar's social institutions — are packed with rain-avoiding locals deep in conversation.",
    7: "Peak monsoon at 24-30°C with the heaviest rainfall of the year and the streets regularly flooding. Yangon takes on a dreamy, waterlogged quality that has its own beauty. The Martyrs' Day commemoration on July 19th is a significant national event honoring independence heroes.",
    8: "Still solidly monsoon at 24-30°C with daily downpours and the tropical vegetation in rampant growth. The Shwedagon Pagoda in the rain — glistening gold against dark storm clouds — is perhaps even more dramatic than in sunshine. Tourist numbers are minimal, and the city feels genuinely local and unhurried.",
    9: "Monsoon continues at 24-31°C with the rain easing slightly as the season reaches its final stretch. The full moon of Tadingyut is one of Myanmar's most beautiful festivals, with thousands of candles and lights illuminating pagodas across the city. The Yangon waterfront along the Hlaing River is spectacular at dusk.",
    10: "Post-monsoon at 24-33°C with decreasing rainfall and the city emerging from its wettest period. The Thadingyut Festival of Lights sees homes and temples illuminated with candles and fairy lights — the atmosphere is magical. The parks are lush, the air is clearing, and Yangon starts feeling energized again.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 21-33°C with comfortable humidity and the city at its most pleasant. The colonial walking tours downtown are perfect in the cooler, drier air. The Shwedagon Pagoda's evening ceremonies, with monks chanting as the golden stupa catches the last light, are transcendent.",
    12: "Cool dry season at 18-32°C with clear skies and the best weather of the year. Christmas is celebrated by Yangon's Karen and Chin Christian communities with genuine warmth. The holiday period brings more visitors, but Yangon's sprawling scale absorbs them easily — this is still one of Southeast Asia's most authentic great cities.",
  },
  'mq-martinique': {
    1: "Dry season on this French Caribbean gem means 22-28°C with northeast trade winds and lush green mountains rising from turquoise waters. The beaches along the southern coast — Grande Anse des Salines, Anse Dufour — are stunning without peak-season crowds. French Creole cuisine here is extraordinary: accras de morue, colombo, and proper rum arrangé.",
    2: "Carnival season transforms the island at 22-28°C with elaborate parades, costume competitions, and non-stop zouk music. Vaval (the carnival king) presides over weeks of revelry that climax on Ash Wednesday with a mock funeral. It's the most vibrant time to visit, though accommodation books up fast for carnival week.",
    3: "Late dry season at 22-29°C with the driest conditions and the best diving visibility around Diamond Rock and the coral reefs. The landscape starts showing signs of the dry season — slightly less lush, but the skies are reliably blue. Mont Pelee volcano can be hiked in clear weather, offering views across the entire island.",
    4: "Transitional at 23-30°C with the first rain showers arriving and the humidity ticking up. The flowers — hibiscus, heliconia, bougainvillea — are explosive across the island's gardens and roadsides. The rum distilleries in the north (Clement, Depaz, Saint-James) offer fascinating tours and excellent AOC agricultural rum.",
    5: "Wet season begins at 24-30°C with afternoon tropical showers that are warm and usually brief. The rainforest interior around Mont Pelee is at its most dramatic, with waterfalls running full. Prices drop as the tourist season winds down, making the boutique hotels and gites more accessible.",
    6: "Full wet season at 24-31°C with daily rain and the island at its most tropically lush. The hiking through the rainforest is spectacular — fern-draped trails, crayfish streams, and hummingbirds everywhere. Hurricane season officially begins, though June is typically quiet; insurance is advisable regardless.",
    7: "Continued rain at 24-31°C with the island in full tropical mode — everything grows at double speed. The beaches remain beautiful between showers, and the snorkeling at Anse Noire (black sand) and Anse Dufour is excellent. The pace slows to a languid Caribbean rhythm that's intoxicating if you embrace it.",
    8: "Peak hurricane season at 25-31°C — statistically the highest risk month, so monitor weather forecasts carefully. The island is quiet tourism-wise, with the best accommodation deals of the year. The volcanic black-sand beaches of the north coast are dramatic and almost always empty.",
    9: "Wettest month at 25-31°C with heavy tropical rains and continued hurricane risk. The landscapes are at maximum lushness, and the waterfalls in the interior are thundering. September is the deepest off-season — you'll share the island primarily with locals, which has its own authentic charm.",
    10: "Rains continue at 24-31°C with hurricane risk decreasing through the month. The Yole Ronde traditional sailing regattas are spectacular events with brightly painted boats and serious inter-village rivalries. The market at Fort-de-France sells the island's incredible tropical fruits — mangoes, guavas, passion fruit.",
    11: "Transition month at 23-30°C with rains decreasing and the dry season approaching. The island starts its tourist-season preparations, and the vegetation is at peak green beauty. Toussaint (All Saints' Day) on November 1st sees cemeteries illuminated with candles in a beautiful cultural tradition.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 22-29°C with trade winds, sunshine, and the holiday season bringing European (especially French) vacationers. Christmas celebrations blend French and Creole traditions with midnight mass, Christmas ham, and ti' punch flowing freely. The beaches and restaurants hit peak form — Martinique at its most polished and festive.",
  },
  'mr-mauritania': {
    1: "Cool, dry harmattan season at 14-28°C along the coast and colder inland — Nouakchott is pleasant and dust-free. The ancient caravan town of Chinguetti, a UNESCO site crumbling beautifully in the desert, is at its most accessible. Mauritania remains extremely off-the-beaten-path; basic French and preparation for minimal infrastructure are essential.",
    2: "Warming slightly to 16-30°C with continued dry conditions and excellent desert visibility. The Adrar Plateau offers stunning canyon scenery and prehistoric rock art in comfortable temperatures. The overland journey from Nouakchott to the Adrar is an adventure in itself — bring patience and a sense of humor.",
    3: "Getting warmer at 18-33°C as the Saharan sun strengthens but remains manageable for desert exploration. The Richat Structure (Eye of the Sahara) is one of Earth's most bizarre geological formations — visible from space and reachable by 4x4. The iron ore train from Nouadhibou, one of the world's longest, is a legendary transport experience.",
    4: "Hot at 20-36°C with the interior desert becoming uncomfortable by midday. The Atlantic coast around Nouadhibou offers cooler temperatures and the Banc d'Arguin National Park — one of the world's most important shorebird habitats — is extraordinary. Millions of migratory birds stop here on their flyway routes.",
    5: "Summer heat arrives at 22-38°C with the Saharan interior becoming genuinely punishing. The coast is tempered by Atlantic breezes, and the fishing villages of the Banc d'Arguin operate traditional sailing boats called lanches. Travelling south toward the Senegal River brings slightly more hospitable conditions.",
    6: "Hot at 24-38°C with occasional dust storms and the beginning of the pre-monsoon tension. The Sahara is off-limits to casual travelers at these temperatures, and even Nouakchott bakes. The camel market on the outskirts of the capital is a fascinating window into nomadic Moorish culture that persists year-round.",
    7: "Peak heat at 25-40°C in the north, with the southern regions receiving the first rains from the West African monsoon. The brief rainy season transforms the Sahel strip along the Senegal River into a green oasis. Travel is restricted to coastal areas and the far south — the interior is an inferno.",
    8: "Monsoon rains reach their peak in the south at 24-38°C while the northern desert remains scorching and dry. The Senegal River floods, creating wetlands that attract birds and wildlife. Nouakchott's humidity spikes, making the coastal capital uncomfortable despite the ocean proximity.",
    9: "Rains ease at 24-38°C with the southern Sahel still green and the heat starting its slow retreat. The desert remains hot but temperatures have peaked, and the first signs of the cool season appear in evening breezes. The dates harvest begins in the oases of the Adrar region.",
    10: "Cooling to 22-36°C with dry conditions returning and the interior becoming more approachable. The date harvest festival in the oasis towns is a genuine cultural event — the fresh dates are incredibly sweet. The Saharan landscapes start looking inviting again for 4x4 expeditions.",
    11: "Comfortable at 18-32°C with the cool season establishing itself and the desert at its most welcoming. Chinguetti, Ouadane, and Tichitt — the ancient library towns of the Sahara — are best visited now. The night skies over the desert are among the clearest and most star-filled anywhere on Earth.",
    12: "Cool and dry at 15-28°C with the best weather of the year for Saharan exploration. The harmattan dust is minimal early in the month, and the desert landscapes are at their most photogenic. The overland crossing to Morocco via the legendary border at Guerguerat is an adventure for the truly intrepid.",
  },

  'mt-malta': {
    1: "Winter in Malta hovers around 12–15°C with occasional rain, but the crowds have vanished and Valletta's baroque streets feel like your private museum. Off-season hotel rates plummet, making it ideal for culture vultures exploring megalithic temples without the crush.",
    2: "February stays cool at 12–16°C with intermittent showers, but Carnival explodes across the islands with grotesque floats and feathered costumes. The almond trees bloom early, and diving visibility is surprisingly excellent in the cooler waters.",
    3: "Spring arrives gently at 14–18°C, wildflowers carpet the countryside, and the festa season begins warming up. It's a sweet spot before summer's invasion — perfect for coastal walks along the Dingli Cliffs and lazy lunches in Marsaxlokk.",
    4: "Temperatures climb to 17–22°C and rain becomes rare as Malta shakes off winter entirely. Easter processions wind through every village with theatrical intensity, and the water is just warm enough for the first brave swimmers.",
    5: "A glorious 20–26°C with long sunny days and manageable crowds before the June stampede begins. The garrigue scrubland is fragrant with wild thyme, and you can still snag a table at waterfront restaurants without a reservation.",
    6: "Summer kicks in hard at 25–31°C with relentless sunshine and the party scene cranking up in St. Julian's and Paceville. The historic festa season hits its peak with fireworks that would make any pyrotechnician weep with envy.",
    7: "Peak season roars with 28–34°C heat, packed beaches, and prices to match the mercury. The Blue Lagoon on Comino becomes a sardine tin of day-trippers, but evening dining in Mdina's silent city remains magical.",
    8: "The hottest month at 29–35°C with the sirocco wind occasionally blasting Saharan heat across the archipelago. Santa Marija feast on August 15th is the big one — every town competes with fireworks, brass bands, and religious fervor.",
    9: "Temperatures ease to 25–30°C and the sea is bath-warm at its annual peak, making this arguably Malta's best swimming month. The summer hordes thin out but the weather stays gorgeous — a true insider's pick.",
    10: "A pleasant 21–26°C with the first autumn rains greening the parched landscape. Notte Bianca lights up Valletta with art and music, and the diving season extends beautifully with warm water and improving visibility.",
    11: "Cooler at 17–21°C with increasing rain, but the island's pace slows to something wonderfully Mediterranean. It's olive harvest season, restaurant menus shift to hearty rabbit stew, and you'll have the archaeological sites nearly to yourself.",
    12: "Winter settles in at 13–17°C with short days and periodic storms, but Valletta's Christmas decorations and nativity scenes (presepji) add genuine warmth. Hotel prices crater, and the fortified cities feel especially atmospheric under grey skies.",
  },
  'mu-mauritius': {
    1: "Peak summer heat at 27–33°C with high humidity and the odd tropical downpour — this is cyclone season, so keep an eye on forecasts. The beaches are stunning but hotel prices reflect peak demand from European winter escapees.",
    2: "The wettest and warmest month at 27–33°C, with cyclone risk at its highest and afternoon thunderstorms a daily ritual. Lush tropical vegetation explodes in green, and the diving is surprisingly good on the western lee side.",
    3: "Summer lingers at 26–32°C with gradually decreasing rainfall as cyclone season winds down. The sugarcane fields are impossibly tall, and the south coast's wild waves attract surfers while the north lagoons stay calm.",
    4: "Autumn arrives gently at 24–30°C with noticeably drier days and the trade winds picking up. It's an excellent shoulder month — prices drop, the water stays warm, and the island's Hindu temples host vibrant Diwali-adjacent festivals.",
    5: "Cooling to 22–28°C as winter approaches, with comfortable humidity and clear skies becoming the norm. Big-game fishing season kicks into gear off the west coast, and the underwater visibility starts reaching its annual best.",
    6: "Winter settles at 20–25°C — which by Mauritian standards means pleasantly warm with low humidity and minimal rain. It's whale-watching season as humpbacks pass through, and the southeast trade winds make kite-surfing at Le Morne world-class.",
    7: "The coolest month at 19–24°C with brisk trade winds and the driest conditions of the year. The plateau towns like Curepipe can feel genuinely crisp at night, but the coast remains perfect for long beach days.",
    8: "Still cool and dry at 19–24°C with the trade winds blowing steadily — ideal hiking weather for tackling Le Pouce or the Black River Gorges. Hotel prices are at their lowest, making this a budget-savvy traveler's dream.",
    9: "Spring begins tentatively at 20–26°C with the winds easing and the water temperature at its annual minimum around 22°C. The island's endemic flora starts blooming, and the dive sites are crystal clear.",
    10: "Warming to 22–28°C with longer days and the first hints of summer humidity returning. The deep-sea fishing remains excellent, and the Chamarel seven-colored earth glows particularly vivid in the strengthening sunlight.",
    11: "Summer builds at 24–30°C with increasing humidity but still relatively dry conditions. The flame trees burst into spectacular red bloom across the island, and the water warms enough for comfortable snorkeling without a wetsuit.",
    12: "Full summer at 26–32°C with rising humidity and the first cyclone-season rains arriving late in the month. Christmas on the beach is a genuine Mauritian tradition, and the mango and lychee season makes every roadside stall irresistible.",
  },
  'mw-malawi': {
    1: "Deep in the rainy season with temperatures at 22–30°C and daily downpours turning everything emerald green. Roads can become challenging, but Lake Malawi's warm waters (28°C) are perfect for swimming, and the birdlife is extraordinary.",
    2: "Still solidly rainy at 22–30°C with lush vegetation and swollen rivers feeding the lake. It's the toughest month for overland travel, but the Zomba Plateau's misty forests are hauntingly beautiful and virtually tourist-free.",
    3: "The rains begin tapering at 22–29°C, though afternoon storms remain common. The lake's fish eagle population is nesting, and the freshwater snorkeling among cichlids at Cape Maclear is surprisingly world-class.",
    4: "Transition month at 21–28°C as the wet season winds down and the landscape remains green but increasingly accessible. It's a secret sweet spot — lodges are empty, prices are low, and the sunsets over the lake are theatrical.",
    5: "Dry season begins in earnest at 18–26°C with cool mornings and crystal-clear skies. The bush starts thinning, making wildlife viewing in Liwonde National Park increasingly rewarding as animals concentrate near water.",
    6: "Cool and dry at 15–24°C with chilly nights, especially on the plateaus where temperatures can dip to 5°C. Majete Wildlife Reserve offers excellent game drives, and the lake's calm waters are ideal for kayaking.",
    7: "The coolest month at 14–23°C with bone-dry conditions and crisp air that makes the mountain hiking superb. Lake Malawi's beach lodges are at peak season with warm-hearted Malawian hospitality that consistently stuns first-time visitors.",
    8: "Dry and warming at 16–26°C with the bush now parched and wildlife congregating dramatically around remaining water sources. Liwonde's elephants and hippos put on a daily show along the Shire River.",
    9: "Heating up at 20–30°C as the dry season reaches its peak — it's hot, dusty, and excellent for game viewing. The Lake of Stars music festival (when scheduled) draws a loyal crowd of backpackers and music lovers.",
    10: "The hottest month at 23–33°C with scorching days and the first tentative rains sometimes arriving late. Mangoes ripen everywhere, and the lakeshore communities prepare for the coming wet season with visible anticipation.",
    11: "Rainy season returns at 22–32°C with dramatic thunderstorms and the landscape rapidly greening. Roads deteriorate but the birding becomes spectacular, with migratory species arriving to join the resident flocks.",
    12: "Full wet season at 22–30°C with regular heavy rains and high humidity. The lake rises, the waterfalls on Mount Mulanje roar back to life, and Christmas celebrations in Malawi carry a uniquely warm communal spirit.",
  },
  'mx-baja': {
    1: "Gray whale season hits its stride with 15–22°C days and cool Pacific nights in the low teens. Guerrero Negro and San Ignacio Lagoon offer face-to-face encounters with these gentle giants — it's genuinely life-changing.",
    2: "Still prime whale-watching at 15–23°C, with mothers and calves filling the lagoons in staggering numbers. The desert wildflowers begin tentatively, and the off-season means you'll have pristine beaches near Todos Santos largely to yourself.",
    3: "Whale season's grand finale at 16–24°C, with the last mothers heading north and spring settling over the peninsula. The Sea of Cortez side warms faster, and sport fishing starts picking up around Loreto.",
    4: "Warming to 19–28°C with clear skies and the desert cacti beginning to bloom in surreal displays. It's shoulder season perfection — La Paz's malecón is lively but not packed, and the water beckons snorkelers.",
    5: "Comfortable at 21–31°C with minimal rain and the Sea of Cortez warming to swimmable temperatures. Whale sharks gather near La Paz in growing numbers, and the fishing becomes genuinely world-class around Cabo.",
    6: "Summer heat arrives at 24–35°C with scorching days in the cape region but refreshing breezes up north. The Sea of Cortez is a snorkeler's paradise, and Cabo's nightlife scene shifts into high gear despite the heat.",
    7: "Hot at 26–38°C with the first hints of hurricane season moisture and occasional thunderstorms in the southern cape. The water is bathtub-warm and manta rays cruise the Sea of Cortez in impressive numbers.",
    8: "Peak heat at 27–39°C with tropical storms a real possibility in the cape region and humidity spiking. It's off-season pricing territory, and the brave are rewarded with empty beaches and spectacular electrical storms over the desert.",
    9: "Hurricane season peaks at 26–37°C with the greatest storm risk and periodic heavy rains transforming the desert. The waterfalls at Sierra de la Laguna appear almost magically, and the air smells of wet creosote.",
    10: "Cooling slightly to 23–33°C as hurricane season fades and the autumn fishing season produces legendary catches. Dorado, marlin, and tuna are running strong, and the desert starts its slow return to golden brown.",
    11: "Pleasant at 19–28°C with dry conditions returning and the first gray whales of the season beginning to arrive. It's an underrated month — the crowds haven't materialized yet and the weather is close to perfection.",
    12: "Cool and crisp at 16–24°C with the whale-watching season ramping up and holiday visitors filling Cabo's resorts. The northern Baja wine region around Valle de Guadalupe hosts cozy harvest dinners under desert stars.",
  },
  'mx-mexico-city': {
    1: "Dry season sunshine at 8–22°C with crisp mornings and brilliantly clear skies that reveal the snow-capped volcanoes. The city buzzes with post-holiday energy, museum lines are short, and the street food scene never sleeps.",
    2: "Still dry and warming to 9–24°C with some of the year's clearest air and longest sunny stretches. It's pre-Lent season, so markets overflow with preparation, and the jacaranda trees begin their spectacular purple takeover.",
    3: "The jacarandas explode across the city at 11–26°C, turning every boulevard into a purple tunnel of blossoms. Late dry season means perfect walking weather for Roma, Condesa, and Coyoacán, though pollution can spike on still days.",
    4: "Warming to 13–27°C with the first tentative afternoon showers appearing late in the month. Semana Santa empties the city of locals headed to the coast, leaving cultural attractions blissfully uncrowded for savvy visitors.",
    5: "Rainy season begins at 13–27°C with afternoon thunderstorms that arrive like clockwork around 4 PM and clear by evening. Mornings remain sunny and perfect for exploring, and the city's parks burst with fresh green.",
    6: "Full rainy season at 14–25°C with daily afternoon deluges that locals barely acknowledge. The rain cools the city and scrubs the air clean, and the culinary scene hits its stride with seasonal ingredients flooding the markets.",
    7: "Cool and wet at 13–23°C — the rainiest period turns the city lush and keeps temperatures remarkably mild for a megalopolis. Chapultepec Forest gleams emerald, and the covered markets of Mercado Roma and La Merced offer perfect rainy-day refuge.",
    8: "Similar pattern at 13–24°C with heavy afternoon rains and gorgeous mornings that reward early risers. The Assumption celebrations on August 15th bring special menus and festivities, and summer hotel rates are surprisingly reasonable.",
    9: "Still rainy at 13–23°C with the wettest month of all delivering dramatic storms and occasional flooding in low-lying areas. It's Mexican Independence season — September 15th's Grito ceremony in the Zócalo is electrifying.",
    10: "Rains taper at 12–23°C and the air turns crystalline as the dry season approaches. Día de los Muertos preparations begin in earnest, with cempasúchil marigolds flooding every market in waves of orange.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 9–22°C with cool mornings and the afterglow of Día de los Muertos still lingering in cemetery ofrendas. The city's cultural calendar kicks into high gear with film festivals and gallery openings.",
    12: "Crisp and clear at 7–21°C with holiday markets, piñata vendors, and ponche caliente warming every corner. The Posadas processions wind through neighborhoods nightly, and the city sparkles with a festive energy that feels genuinely communal.",
  },
  'mx-oaxaca': {
    1: "Dry season perfection at 12–28°C with sunny days, cool highland nights, and the mezcal-scented air of the Central Valleys at its most inviting. Post-holiday calm settles over the markets, and artisan workshops welcome unhurried visitors.",
    2: "Warm and dry at 13–30°C with the driest skies of the year and brilliant light that makes the colonial architecture glow. Carnival celebrations erupt with comparsas dancing through the streets in elaborate costumes.",
    3: "Heating up at 14–32°C with relentless sunshine and the zapote trees flowering across the valleys. The pre-Easter craft markets in surrounding villages — Ocotlán, Tlacolula — are treasure troves without the tourist markup.",
    4: "The hottest month at 16–34°C with parched landscapes and Semana Santa bringing elaborate processions and sawdust carpets to the cobblestone streets. Hierve el Agua's petrified waterfalls shimmer in the intense spring light.",
    5: "Still hot at 16–33°C with the first rains arriving tentatively late in the month. The mango and mamey season peaks, making every market visit a sensory overload, and the zapotec ruins of Monte Albán feel mythic in the haze.",
    6: "Rainy season begins at 17–31°C with afternoon storms that cool the city and green the surrounding sierra. The famous Guelaguetza festival preparations begin, and the mezcalerias stay busy regardless of weather.",
    7: "The Guelaguetza festival dominates at 16–30°C, with indigenous dance troupes from across the state converging for Oaxaca's most spectacular cultural event. Book months ahead — the city fills to capacity and the energy is extraordinary.",
    8: "Rainy at 16–30°C with lush green valleys and daily storms that locals navigate with practiced nonchalance. The cooking classes and market tours are at their best with peak-season produce, and hotel rates ease slightly post-Guelaguetza.",
    9: "The wettest month at 16–28°C with heavy rains that can cause road closures in the sierra. The highland fields of corn and squash are magnificent, and the cozy mezcal bars of the centro feel especially welcoming.",
    10: "Rains diminish at 15–28°C and preparations for Día de los Muertos begin electrifying the city. Marigold fields blaze orange across the valleys, and the markets stock chocolate, pan de muerto, and mole negro in anticipation.",
    11: "Día de los Muertos in early November is Oaxaca's crown jewel at 13–28°C — cemetery vigils, comparsas, and altar-building make this one of Mexico's most profound cultural experiences. The dry season returns with perfect weather.",
    12: "Cool and festive at 11–27°C with the Noche de Rábanos (Night of the Radishes) on December 23rd delivering one of Mexico's most wonderfully eccentric traditions. The holiday markets pulse with black pottery, textiles, and alebrijes.",
  },
  'se-gothenburg': {
    1: "Dark and cold at -3 to 3°C with about six hours of grey daylight and frequent rain or wet snow off the Kattegat. The city compensates with cozy fika culture, world-class seafood restaurants, and the warm glow of Liseberg's winter lights.",
    2: "Still raw at -3 to 3°C but the days lengthen noticeably and the West Swedish coast has a stark, brooding beauty. It's prime season for booking a seafood safari to the Gothenburg archipelago — oysters, lobster, and bracing sea air.",
    3: "Spring teases at 0–7°C with lengthening days and the first crocuses breaking through in Trädgårdsföreningen park. The rain eases slightly, and the city's famously innovative food scene — from market halls to Michelin stars — shines brightest now.",
    4: "Warming to 3–12°C with genuine spring energy as outdoor cafés cautiously set up tables. The archipelago ferries resume full schedules, and the canal boats return to Gothenburg's waterways with a palpable sense of relief.",
    5: "Lovely at 8–17°C with long, bright evenings and the city shedding its winter layers for outdoor dining and park lounging. The Gothenburg Culture Festival often starts the cultural season, and the coast beckons for day trips.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 12–21°C with near-endless daylight and the Swedes migrating to their stuga cottages in the archipelago. Midsommar celebrations bring flower crowns, herring, schnapps, and dancing around the maypole — quintessentially Swedish.",
    7: "Peak summer at 15–23°C with the longest days and the west coast at its most appealing — granite islands, seafood shacks, and skinny-dipping at sunset. Gothenburg buzzes with outdoor concerts and the Way Out West festival.",
    8: "Still warm at 14–22°C with the crayfish season (kräftskiva) bringing Swedes together for lantern-lit feasts of dill-boiled crayfish and snaps. The archipelago swimming is at its warmest, and the cultural calendar stays full.",
    9: "Autumn creeps in at 11–17°C with the birches turning gold and the tourist crowds dissolving. The Gothenburg Book Fair — Scandinavia's largest literary event — draws bibliophiles, and the seafood season shifts to oysters and mussels.",
    10: "Cooling to 6–12°C with moody skies and the first autumn storms rolling in off the North Sea. The city's indoor market halls come alive with seasonal produce, and the cozy bar and restaurant scene feels like a warm embrace.",
    11: "Dark and damp at 2–7°C with sunset before 4 PM and the Scandinavian hygge instinct in full force. The Christmas markets begin appearing, and Gothenburg's famous julbord (Christmas buffet) season launches with gravlax and meatballs.",
    12: "Deep winter at 0–4°C with Liseberg's Christmas market transforming the amusement park into a twinkling wonderland. The darkness is real (sunrise after 8:30 AM), but the mulled wine, saffron buns, and candlelit restaurants make it genuinely magical.",
  },
  'se-lapland': {
    1: "Polar night lingers with temperatures from -25 to -10°C and barely a hint of blue twilight around midday. This is prime aurora season — the northern lights dance overhead with spectacular intensity, and dog-sledding across frozen lakes is unforgettable.",
    2: "Still brutally cold at -22 to -8°C but the light returns with increasing drama, painting the snow-covered fells in shades of pink and gold. The Jokkmokk Winter Market, a 400-year-old Sámi tradition, is a cultural highlight worth every frozen toe.",
    3: "Cold but brightening at -15 to -3°C with longer days making this the best month for ski touring and snowmobile expeditions. The snow conditions are at their most reliable, and the ICEHOTEL in Jukkasjärvi still stands in full glory.",
    4: "Spring skiing at -8 to 4°C with almost endless daylight as the Arctic sun refuses to set for increasingly long stretches. The snow crust is perfect for cross-country touring, and the reindeer herds begin their spring migration north.",
    5: "The thaw arrives at 0–10°C with ice breaking up on rivers and lakes in dramatic fashion. The midnight sun begins around mid-month in the far north, and the birch forests burst into luminous green almost overnight.",
    6: "Midnight sun in full effect at 5–18°C with 24-hour daylight enabling hiking, fishing, and midnight golf on courses that never close. The mosquitoes arrive with enthusiasm, so pack serious repellent for wilderness adventures.",
    7: "The warmest month at 10–22°C with endless daylight, wild blueberries ripening in the forests, and world-class fly-fishing in pristine Arctic rivers. The landscape is impossibly lush, and the Sámi cultural festivals showcase reindeer herding traditions.",
    8: "Still mild at 8–18°C with the first hints of autumn color appearing on the fell tops and the berry-picking season at its absolute peak. Cloudberries, lingonberries, and mushrooms carpet the forest floors in abundance.",
    9: "The ruska (autumn colors) explode across the tundra at 3–12°C in one of Europe's most underrated natural spectacles. The aurora season returns as darkness reclaims the night sky, and the hiking is superb with fewer mosquitoes.",
    10: "First snow often arrives at -5 to 5°C, transforming the landscape and launching the aurora viewing season in earnest. The tourist infrastructure gears up for winter, and the silence of the frozen wilderness is almost spiritual.",
    11: "Polar night descends at -15 to -2°C with the sun barely rising above the horizon before disappearing for weeks. Aurora activity peaks, and the first dog-sledding and snowmobile tours of the season launch across fresh powder.",
    12: "Deep polar night at -20 to -8°C with just a faint blue glow at midday and the northern lights as your primary illumination. Christmas in Lapland feels mythically appropriate — the Sámi markets, reindeer encounters, and snow-covered forests deliver genuine wonder.",
  },
  'se-stockholm': {
    1: "Cold and dark at -5 to 1°C with about six hours of pale daylight and the city blanketed in snow that makes Gamla Stan look like a fairy tale. The museums are blissfully uncrowded, and the warm cinnamon-bun culture provides essential sustenance.",
    2: "Still frigid at -5 to 1°C but the light creeps back perceptibly, lifting spirits across the city. Semla season hits its peak — every bakery competes for the best cardamom-cream bun, and ice skating on natural lakes is a local ritual.",
    3: "Thawing begins at -2 to 5°C with noticeably longer days and the Stockholmers emerging from hibernation. The waffle day tradition (Våffeldagen) on March 25th is charmingly earnest, and the archipelago ice starts breaking up.",
    4: "Spring arrives at 2–11°C with cherry blossoms in Kungsträdgården and the outdoor café culture tentatively resuming. The Vasa Museum and ABBA Museum see lighter crowds than summer, and the city feels fresh and optimistic.",
    5: "Gorgeous at 7–17°C with long bright evenings and the Stockholm archipelago reopening for boat excursions. The city's parks burst with lilacs and apple blossoms, and the restaurant terraces along Strandvägen fill with sun-starved locals.",
    6: "Summer at 12–22°C with nearly 19 hours of daylight and the Midsommar exodus emptying the city as Swedes head to their country cottages. If you stay, you'll have Stockholm's waterfront, islands, and rooftop bars practically to yourself.",
    7: "Peak summer at 15–25°C with the archipelago in full swing — 30,000 islands accessible by ferry for swimming, kayaking, and seafood picnics. The city buzzes with outdoor concerts, and swimming from the city's beaches is genuinely excellent.",
    8: "Warm at 14–23°C with the crayfish party season bringing Stockholmers together for boisterous outdoor feasts under paper lanterns. The cultural calendar revs back up, and the late-summer light has a golden quality painters adore.",
    9: "Autumn settles at 10–17°C with the birches turning gold and the cultural season launching with gallery openings and theater premieres. The Stockholm archipelago quiets beautifully, and the restaurant scene shifts to hearty seasonal menus.",
    10: "Cooling to 5–11°C with crisp air, falling leaves, and increasingly dramatic skies over the waterways. The Fotografiska museum hosts blockbuster exhibitions, and the cozy wine bars of Södermalm become the city's social hubs.",
    11: "Dark and chilly at 0–5°C with Stockholm's famous Christmas markets beginning to twinkle across Gamla Stan and Skansen. The city embraces the darkness with candlelight, glögg (mulled wine), and a cultural warmth that feels deeply genuine.",
    12: "Deep winter at -3 to 2°C with the Nobel Prize festivities adding glamour to an already festive December. Julbord season means epic holiday buffets at every restaurant, and the snow-dusted old town is pure Scandinavian postcard perfection.",
  },
  'sg-singapore': {
    1: "Northeast monsoon season brings 24–31°C temperatures with frequent afternoon downpours and the city still sparkling from New Year and Chinese New Year preparations. The hawker centres steam year-round, and the rain is no excuse not to eat your way through them.",
    2: "Warm and wet at 24–32°C with Chinese New Year (when it falls here) lighting up Chinatown in spectacular red and gold. The rain can be persistent, but the air-conditioned malls, museums, and food halls make it irrelevant.",
    3: "Transitioning at 25–32°C with the monsoon easing and humidity hovering around its perpetual 80%. The heat builds, but Gardens by the Bay's climate-controlled domes offer orchid-scented refuge, and the late-night supper culture thrives.",
    4: "Heating up at 25–33°C during the inter-monsoon period, which brings spectacular thunderstorms and occasionally the year's hottest days. Ramadan transforms Geylang Serai with an enormous pasar malam bazaar of Malay street food.",
    5: "One of the hottest months at 25–33°C with blazing sunshine punctuated by dramatic evening storms. The Great Singapore Sale traditionally kicks off, and the Vesak Day celebrations add lantern-lit temple ceremonies to the calendar.",
    6: "Southwest monsoon arrives at 25–32°C with drier conditions than you'd expect and hazy skies from regional agricultural burning. The Singapore Food Festival celebrates the city-state's obsessive culinary culture — which honestly needs no festival to shine.",
    7: "Warm and relatively dry at 25–32°C with the National Day preparations building patriotic fervor across the island. The haze can be a nuisance, but the indoor attractions — from the National Gallery to Jewel Changi — are world-class rain or shine.",
    8: "National Day on August 9th brings spectacular parades and fireworks at 25–32°C, with the entire city draped in red and white. The Hungry Ghost Festival fills the streets with opera performances, paper offerings, and smoky incense.",
    9: "Still warm at 25–32°C with the haze season potentially lingering and the F1 Singapore Grand Prix turning Marina Bay into a floodlit racetrack. The night race is genuinely one of motorsport's most visually stunning events.",
    10: "The northeast monsoon approaches at 24–32°C with increasing rainfall and dramatic late-afternoon downpours. Deepavali lights up Little India in a dazzling display of color, and the mid-autumn festival brings mooncakes and lanterns to every neighborhood.",
    11: "Wet season intensifies at 24–31°C with some of the year's heaviest rainfall, though the showers rarely last more than an hour or two. Christmas decorations go up absurdly early on Orchard Road, creating a tropical winter wonderland.",
    12: "Peak monsoon at 24–31°C with frequent rain and the entire Orchard Road corridor transformed into a glittering Christmas light tunnel. The year-end food festival scene is extraordinary, and the city's rooftop bars buzz with holiday energy.",
  },
  'si-adriatic': {
    1: "Cold and quiet at 2–8°C along the short Adriatic coast, with the karst landscape stark and beautiful under winter skies. Piran's Venetian architecture feels hauntingly empty, and the Škocjan Caves maintain their eternal 12°C regardless of season.",
    2: "Still wintry at 3–9°C with occasional bora wind gusts that can be genuinely fierce along the coast. The Kurentovanje carnival in nearby Ptuj is one of Europe's wildest pre-Lenten celebrations — fur-clad figures driving out winter with cowbells.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 6–13°C with almond blossoms appearing along the Adriatic and the first hikers venturing into the Karst region. The olive groves show fresh growth, and Koper's market days bring the first local asparagus and artichokes.",
    4: "Warming nicely to 10–18°C with wildflowers carpeting the limestone karst and the coastal towns waking from hibernation. The Lipica stud farm's white Lipizzaner horses are especially photogenic against the spring-green pastures.",
    5: "Lovely at 14–23°C with warm enough days for coastal walks and the first brave swimmers testing the Adriatic. The Vipava Valley wine region produces stunning orange wines that pair perfectly with local prosciutto and sheep cheese.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 18–27°C with the turquoise Adriatic reaching swimmable temperatures and the Portorož beach scene heating up. The coastal restaurants serve impossibly fresh seafood, and the Strunjan salt pans glitter in the long evening light.",
    7: "Peak season at 21–30°C with the Adriatic coast packed and the karst interior offering cooler refuge in limestone caves and shaded vineyard trails. Piran's jazz festival fills the Tartini Square with music and Mediterranean atmosphere.",
    8: "Hot at 21–30°C with the warmest sea temperatures and every inch of Slovenia's 46 km of coastline claimed by sunbathers. The seafood festivals and outdoor cinema screenings keep the coastal towns lively well past midnight.",
    9: "Warm at 17–25°C with thinning crowds, still-warm seas, and the wine harvest beginning across the Karst and Vipava regions. It's arguably the best month — golden light, fewer visitors, and the figs and grapes are at their peak.",
    10: "Cooling to 12–19°C with autumn colors transforming the karst and the olive harvest in full swing. The coast turns contemplative, and the Škocjan Caves feel especially dramatic as the underground Reka River swells with autumn rain.",
    11: "Chilly at 7–13°C with increasing rain and the martinovanje wine festival marking St. Martin's Day with must-to-wine ceremonies. The coast is quiet but atmospheric, and the trattorias serve hearty game and truffle dishes.",
    12: "Winter returns at 3–9°C with festive lights strung across Piran's narrow lanes and the smell of fritule (doughnuts) wafting from market stalls. The Postojna Cave hosts a spectacular living nativity scene deep underground.",
  },
  'si-ljubljana': {
    1: "Cold at -3 to 3°C with snow often blanketing the city and the Julian Alps glowing white on the horizon. Ljubljana's charming old town is quiet, prices are rock-bottom, and the thermal spas scattered across Slovenia become essential destinations.",
    2: "Still frigid at -2 to 5°C with reliable snow in the Julian Alps making this prime ski season at Kranjska Gora and Vogel. Prešeren Day on February 8th celebrates Slovenian culture with free museum entries and poetic fervor.",
    3: "Spring begins at 2–11°C with snowdrops and crocuses in Tivoli Park and the snow line retreating up the Alps. The city's legendary café culture emerges onto the Ljubljanica riverbanks, and the ski season still has weeks to run.",
    4: "Warming to 6–17°C with the Julian Alps transitioning from ski to hiking season and Lake Bled looking impossibly picturesque with spring blossoms framing the island church. Ljubljana's open-air market overflows with wild garlic and asparagus.",
    5: "Gorgeous at 10–22°C with long days, blooming linden trees, and the Dragon Bridge looking particularly fierce against blue skies. The Soča River turns emerald green, and the Via Ferrata routes in the Julian Alps open for the season.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 14–26°C with Ljubljana's riverside bars and restaurants in full swing and Lake Bohinj offering crystal-clear Alpine swimming. The Ana Desetnica street theater festival animates the old town with performers from across Europe.",
    7: "Peak summer at 16–28°C with the Julian Alps at their most accessible for high-altitude hiking and the Soča Valley becoming an adventure-sports paradise. Ljubljana Festival brings opera, theater, and concerts to the castle courtyard.",
    8: "Warm at 15–28°C with thunderstorms common in the Alps but the valleys remaining largely sunny. The Radovljica chocolate festival and the Bled Days festivities with floating candles on the lake are distinctly Slovenian summer highlights.",
    9: "Golden at 12–22°C with autumn colors beginning in the higher elevations and the grape harvest underway in the Goriška Brda wine region. The hiking is superb with stable weather, thinner crowds, and mushroom foraging in the beech forests.",
    10: "Cooling to 7–15°C with spectacular fall foliage around Lake Bled and the Ljubljana wine route offering cellar tastings with chestnuts and new wine. The city's cultural season launches with galleries and theaters in full program.",
    11: "Chilly at 2–9°C with fog often settling in the Ljubljana basin and the first snow dusting the Alpine peaks. St. Martin's Day celebrations bring must-to-wine rituals, roast goose, and a cozy slide into the winter season.",
    12: "Cold at -1 to 4°C with Ljubljana's Festive Fair transforming the city center into a magical Christmas market. Prešeren Square glows with lights, the mulled wine flows, and the Julian Alps offer early-season skiing with holiday atmosphere.",
  },
  'sk-bratislava': {
    1: "Cold and grey at -3 to 3°C with the Danube sometimes partially frozen and the old town eerily quiet. It's the cheapest time to visit, and the bryndzové halušky (sheep-cheese dumplings) in a warm cellar restaurant is pure comfort.",
    2: "Still wintry at -2 to 5°C but the city's Fasiangy (Carnival) celebrations bring masked balls and street festivals. The castle looks striking against winter skies, and the thermal baths just outside the city provide steamy refuge.",
    3: "Spring arrives tentatively at 2–11°C with crocuses in the Danube parklands and the café terraces cautiously opening. The city punches well above its weight for a European capital, with excellent restaurants and galleries at a fraction of Vienna prices.",
    4: "Warming to 7–17°C with the old town flowering and the Danube cycling paths becoming irresistible. Day trips to Devín Castle, perched dramatically above the Danube-Morava confluence, are especially rewarding in spring light.",
    5: "Lovely at 12–22°C with long evenings on the Danube promenade and the city's coronation history coming alive through festivals. The Little Carpathians wine route just north of the city produces surprisingly excellent whites and rosés.",
    6: "Summer settles in at 15–26°C with the city's outdoor concert season launching and the Danube warm enough for river beach days on the south bank. Bratislava's craft beer scene has exploded, and the rooftop bars offer castle views.",
    7: "Warm at 17–28°C with occasional thunderstorms and the city at its most vibrant with outdoor festivals and evening markets. The UFO Bridge observation deck offers sunset panoramas over the old town that justify every step.",
    8: "Peak summer at 17–29°C with Bratislava quieter as locals head to the mountains or lakes, but the Danube-side scene remains lively. The grape harvest begins in the surrounding Little Carpathian vineyards, and wine-tasting tours flourish.",
    9: "Pleasant at 13–22°C with the wine harvest festival (Vinobranie) in Modra and Pezinok drawing crowds to celebrate new wine with roast goose. The city's university students return, energizing the bar and restaurant scene.",
    10: "Cooling to 7–15°C with golden autumn light on the castle and the old town's cobblestones. The International Film Festival brings global cinema to the city, and the hearty Slovak cuisine — kapustnica, lokše — feels perfectly seasonal.",
    11: "Chilly at 2–8°C with the first Christmas market stalls appearing on Hlavné námestie and the smell of medovníky (honey cookies) filling the air. The city is small enough to walk everywhere, which is precisely its charm.",
    12: "Cold at -2 to 4°C with one of Central Europe's most charming Christmas markets lighting up the main square. The mulled wine is cheap, the handcrafts are authentic, and the proximity to Vienna's holiday markets makes a twin-city trip irresistible.",
  },
  'sk-tatras': {
    1: "Deep winter at -10 to -2°C with excellent snow cover and the ski resorts of Tatranská Lomnica and Jasná in full swing. The High Tatras are the smallest alpine range to earn the name, but they deliver genuinely dramatic scenery at bargain prices.",
    2: "Still prime ski season at -9 to -1°C with reliable powder and fewer crowds than the Alps at a fraction of the cost. The frozen waterfalls in the Kvacianka Valley offer ice-climbing adventures that feel genuinely wild.",
    3: "Late winter at -5 to 4°C with long ski days and the spring sun beginning to soften the snowpack. The mountain huts open their terraces for Svařák (mulled wine) in the sunshine, and the cross-country trails are in prime condition.",
    4: "Transition at -1 to 9°C with the snow retreating to upper elevations and the valleys bursting with spring wildflowers. The hiking season begins tentatively, and the Belianske Tatry's dolomite cliffs look especially striking against blue skies.",
    5: "Spring at 5–15°C with the high trails still snow-covered but the lower valleys green and inviting. The alpine meadows bloom with crocuses and gentians, and the thermal parks at Bešeňová and Liptovský Ján offer warm pools with mountain views.",
    6: "Summer approaches at 9–19°C with most hiking trails open and the mountain lakes beginning to thaw. The Tatra National Park's chamois and marmot populations are active, and the light stays long enough for ambitious summit attempts.",
    7: "Peak hiking season at 12–22°C with all trails open and the High Tatras' craggy ridgelines beckoning experienced trekkers. The Štrbské Pleso lake glistens like glass, and the mountain huts serve hearty bryndzové halušky to hungry hikers.",
    8: "Warm at 11–21°C with afternoon thunderstorms common at altitude — start hikes early and be off the ridges by noon. The wildflower meadows are at their peak, and paragliding from Chopok offers bird's-eye views of the range.",
    9: "Autumn gold at 7–16°C with the larch forests turning brilliant yellow and the hiking crowds thinning dramatically. It's one of the finest months for mountain photography, and the weather often delivers a stable high-pressure spell.",
    10: "Cooling to 2–10°C with the first snowfalls on the peaks and the valleys ablaze in autumn color. The mushroom-picking season draws locals into the forests with baskets, and the mountain huts begin closing for the season.",
    11: "Early winter at -4 to 4°C with snow settling on the peaks and the ski resorts preparing for their opening. The thermal spas become essential destinations, and the quietude of the mountains is almost meditative.",
    12: "Full winter at -8 to 0°C with the ski season launching and the High Tatras dressed in fresh powder. Christmas in the mountain villages brings traditional Slovak celebrations with lokše, kapustnica, and carol-singing around the tree.",
  },
  'sl-sierraleone': {
    1: "Deep dry season at 25–32°C with Harmattan haze drifting in from the Sahara and the beaches of the Freetown Peninsula at their most pristine. River Number Two Beach is regularly cited among West Africa's finest — and in January, you might have it entirely to yourself.",
    2: "Hot and dry at 26–33°C with the dusty Harmattan lingering and visibility sometimes poor. The Tacugama Chimpanzee Sanctuary is active in the dry season, and the journey up to Leicester Peak above Freetown offers panoramic coastal views.",
    3: "Heating up at 27–34°C as the driest period reaches its peak and the risk of bush fires increases. The Banana Islands off the coast offer snorkeling over coral reefs and colonial-era ruins — an otherworldly escape with zero crowds.",
    4: "The hottest month at 27–34°C with the first tentative rains appearing late and humidity climbing. Freetown's music scene thumps with Afrobeats and traditional palm wine guitar, and the cotton tree downtown remains the city's spiritual anchor.",
    5: "Rainy season begins at 26–32°C with increasingly frequent downpours that turn the forested hills emerald. The Outamba-Kilimi National Park's wildlife becomes more elusive but the landscape transforms into something lush and primordial.",
    6: "Full rainy season at 24–30°C with heavy daily downpours and rivers swelling rapidly. The beaches are less practical but Freetown's indoor scene — vibrant markets, music venues, and roadside cookshops — carries on regardless.",
    7: "Peak rains at 23–28°C with some of the heaviest rainfall in West Africa pummeling Freetown's hillsides. Roads become challenging and many upcountry areas are difficult to reach, but the city's resilient energy remains infectious.",
    8: "Still very wet at 23–28°C with the rains relentless and the countryside so green it almost hurts to look at. This is the lowest tourist season, but the warmth and generosity of Sierra Leonean hospitality never takes a day off.",
    9: "Rains begin easing at 24–29°C with occasional dry spells hinting at the coming change. The Freetown peninsula's waterfalls are at their most spectacular, and the surfing at Bureh Beach offers consistent breaks for the adventurous.",
    10: "Transition month at 25–30°C with decreasing rainfall and the landscape still lush from months of rain. The roads improve, wildlife becomes more visible, and the beach scene starts gearing up for dry season visitors.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25–31°C with the humidity dropping and the beaches gleaming after their rainy-season reset. The Tiwai Island Wildlife Sanctuary offers primate encounters that rival anything in East Africa at a fraction of the price.",
    12: "Beautiful at 25–31°C with dry conditions, comfortable humidity, and Freetown's holiday celebrations blending Christian and traditional festivities. The beaches are world-class, the seafood is spectacular, and Sierra Leone remains one of West Africa's great undiscovered destinations.",
  },
  'sm-sanmarino': {
    1: "Cold at 0–7°C with fog often shrouding Mount Titano and the three towers emerging dramatically above the clouds. The world's oldest republic is virtually tourist-free, and the medieval streets feel like a private time machine.",
    2: "Still wintry at 1–8°C with occasional snow dusting the fortress walls and the Romagna plain stretching grey below. San Marino's quirky museums — from torture instruments to curiosities — provide indoor entertainment with eccentric charm.",
    3: "Spring stirs at 4–12°C with the first warmth coaxing wildflowers from the limestone cliffs. The views from the Guaita tower stretch to the Adriatic on clear days, and the tax-free shopping starts attracting weekend visitors from Rimini.",
    4: "Warming to 8–17°C with April showers greening the hillsides and the outdoor cafés reopening along Via del Pianello. The Investiture of the Captains Regent ceremony on April 1st is a charmingly earnest display of microstate pageantry.",
    5: "Lovely at 12–22°C with clear skies offering jaw-dropping panoramas from all three towers. The crowds haven't arrived yet, the walking paths along the ridgeline are carpeted with wildflowers, and the Sammarinese cuisine — piadina, passatelli — satisfies.",
    6: "Warm at 16–27°C with the summer tourist season beginning in earnest and day-trippers flooding up from the Adriatic beaches. Early morning or late afternoon visits to the towers reward you with golden light and thinner crowds.",
    7: "Hot at 19–30°C with peak tourist season and the tiny streets genuinely packed during midday hours. The Medieval Days festival brings jousting, flag-throwing, and crossbow competitions that suit the fortress setting perfectly.",
    8: "Peak summer at 19–30°C with every Italian beach-goer seemingly making the pilgrimage up Mount Titano for duty-free shopping. Beat the heat and crowds with a dawn visit — the sunrise from the Guaita is worth the early alarm.",
    9: "Cooling to 16–25°C with the summer hordes departing and the quality of light turning painterly. The San Marino Grand Prix period (nearby Misano circuit) brings motorsport fans, and the hilltop dining terraces are at their romantic best.",
    10: "Autumn at 11–19°C with morning mist and golden foliage creating atmospheric conditions that photographers adore. The Investiture of the Captains Regent on October 1st repeats, and the chestnut and truffle season transforms the menus.",
    11: "Chilly at 5–12°C with the tourist season winding down and San Marino returning to its quiet microstate rhythms. The fog rolling through the valleys below while you stand in sunshine above is one of Italy's most surreal experiences.",
    12: "Cold at 1–8°C with Christmas decorations adding sparkle to the medieval streets and the duty-free shops doing brisk holiday trade. The mulled wine and roasted chestnuts at the small Christmas market feel intimate and genuine.",
  },
  'sn-senegal': {
    1: "Dry and warm at 18–27°C with the Harmattan breeze bringing hazy skies and comfortable humidity. Dakar buzzes with its legendary music scene — mbalax rhythms pour from every neighborhood — and the Lac Rose glows its famous pink.",
    2: "Pleasant at 18–28°C with continued dry conditions and the Saint-Louis Jazz Festival (when scheduled) drawing musicians and fans to the colonial-era island city. The bird life at Djoudj National Park is at its migratory peak.",
    3: "Warming to 20–30°C with the dry season holding firm and the beaches of Cap Skirring and the Petite Côte at their most inviting. The fishing pirogues returning to Kayar beach at dawn are one of West Africa's most vivid scenes.",
    4: "Hot at 22–32°C as the dry season reaches its peak and the inland areas become parched. The Casamance region stays greener than the north, and its distinctive culture, cuisine, and palm-wine traditions make it worth the journey south.",
    5: "Heating up at 24–34°C with the first humid air masses hinting at the coming rainy season. The Dakar art scene — from the Biennale to the village des arts — positions the city as West Africa's creative capital.",
    6: "Hot and increasingly humid at 25–34°C with the first rains arriving in the south. The mangoes are extraordinary, the thiéboudienne (fish and rice) is Senegal's national dish for good reason, and the surf breaks at Ngor get consistent.",
    7: "Rainy season begins in earnest at 25–33°C with daily afternoon storms and the landscape rapidly greening. The Gorée Island UNESCO site has fewer visitors, and the baobabs across the landscape start leafing out majestically.",
    8: "Peak rains at 25–32°C with heavy downpours and the countryside transformed into a verdant patchwork of rice paddies and millet fields. Roads can be challenging upcountry, but Dakar's restaurant and nightlife scene never misses a beat.",
    9: "Still rainy at 25–32°C with the wettest conditions and occasional flooding in low-lying areas. The landscapes are at their most photogenic — impossibly green against red laterite soil — and the wrestling (la lutte) season generates passionate crowds.",
    10: "Rains taper at 25–33°C with the humidity starting to ease and the bird populations exploding across wetland reserves. The harvest season begins, and the roadside fruit stands overflow with mangoes, papayas, and cashew fruits.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 22–31°C with comfortable conditions and the tourist season ramping up. The Grand Magal de Touba religious pilgrimage (date varies) is one of the world's largest annual gatherings — millions converge with remarkable devotion.",
    12: "Cool and dry at 19–28°C with the Harmattan settling in and holiday festivities mixing Senegalese, Muslim, and Christian traditions. The fishing season peaks, Dakar's legendary nightclubs pulse until dawn, and the Lac Rose shimmers under clear skies.",
  },
  'so-somalia': {
    1: "Dry Jilaal season at 25–33°C with minimal rainfall and dusty conditions across most of the country. The Somali coastline stretches pristine and largely untouched, though travel requires careful security planning and experienced local guides.",
    2: "Still dry at 26–34°C with the northeast monsoon winds easing and the coastal areas more accessible. Somalia's camel culture — the country has the world's largest camel population — is on full display at rural markets and watering points.",
    3: "Heating up at 27–35°C as the Jilaal gives way to the Gu rainy season's first hints. The ancient port city of Mogadishu shows increasing signs of revival, with new restaurants and cafés opening along the Lido Beach waterfront.",
    4: "Gu rains begin at 26–33°C, bringing the first green to the parched landscape and a sense of renewal. The pastoralist communities celebrate the coming grass, and the Indian Ocean coast offers warm-water swimming for the adventurous.",
    5: "Rainy season at 25–31°C with the heaviest Gu rains greening the inter-riverine region between the Juba and Shabelle. Travel is restricted to secure corridors, but the emerging Somali diaspora tourism sector shows genuine promise.",
    6: "Cooling to 24–29°C as the Gu rains end and the Hagaa season brings cool, dry conditions with overcast skies. The port of Berbera in Somaliland is increasingly accessible, with its Ottoman architecture and pristine beaches drawing cautious pioneers.",
    7: "Cool Hagaa season at 24–28°C with overcast skies and the coolest temperatures of the year in Mogadishu. Somaliland operates as a separate entity with better security infrastructure, and the Laas Geel cave paintings are genuinely world-class prehistoric art.",
    8: "Still cool at 24–28°C with dry conditions and the Somali tea culture (shaah) providing warmth on grey mornings. The livestock markets are a fascinating window into the pastoralist economy that has sustained Somali life for millennia.",
    9: "The short Deyr rains begin at 25–30°C with sporadic showers reviving the landscape. The frankincense-producing regions of Puntland carry an ancient trade heritage that connects to Egyptian pharaohs and Biblical narratives.",
    10: "Deyr rainy season at 25–31°C with moderate rainfall and the countryside greening for the second time this year. The Somali coast has some of the world's richest marine biodiversity, though infrastructure for tourism remains minimal.",
    11: "Rains taper at 26–32°C with the landscape at its lushest and the pastoral communities at their most active. The ancient trading ports along the coast — Zeila, Berbera, Merca — whisper of Somalia's pivotal role in Indian Ocean commerce.",
    12: "Dry Jilaal returns at 26–33°C with clear skies and the country's legendary hospitality on display during holiday gatherings. Somalia remains a frontier destination requiring specialist operators, but its cultural richness and coastal beauty are undeniable.",
  },
  'sr-suriname': {
    1: "Short dry season at 24–31°C with slightly less rain than the wet months, though tropical showers remain a daily possibility. Paramaribo's wooden colonial center — a UNESCO World Heritage site — gleams after rain, and the Javanese, Creole, and Indian food scene is dizzying.",
    2: "Short dry season continues at 24–31°C with the most reliably dry weather of the year. The Suriname River runs high and brown through the capital, and the Central Market offers a bewildering fusion of cultures — Dutch colonial, Javanese, Maroon, Amerindian.",
    3: "Transition at 24–31°C as the long rainy season approaches and humidity climbs. The Brownsberg Nature Park offers waterfall hikes through primary rainforest that feels genuinely primeval, with howler monkeys providing the soundtrack.",
    4: "Long rainy season begins at 24–31°C with daily heavy downpours that don't so much interrupt life as punctuate it. The interior Maroon communities along the upper Suriname River are accessible by dugout canoe — a journey into another world.",
    5: "Full rainy season at 24–31°C with the rivers swelling and the rainforest at its most alive with wildlife. The birdwatching is extraordinary — Suriname hosts over 700 species — and the Raleighvallen Nature Reserve's cock-of-the-rock leks are mesmerizing.",
    6: "Rains peak at 24–30°C with some of the heaviest precipitation of the year turning forest trails into streams. Sea turtle nesting season on the Galibi coast begins, with leatherbacks and green turtles hauling ashore at night.",
    7: "Short dry season returns at 24–30°C with the most popular window for interior travel and wildlife viewing. The Central Suriname Nature Reserve — one of the world's largest protected tropical forests — offers pristine wilderness accessible by small aircraft.",
    8: "Dry and pleasant at 24–31°C with the best conditions for exploring the interior and visiting Maroon and Amerindian communities. The Voltzberg granite dome hike rewards the effort with 360-degree views of unbroken jungle canopy.",
    9: "Still dry at 24–32°C with the warmest temperatures of the year and excellent wildlife viewing as animals concentrate near water sources. The Brokopondo Reservoir offers fishing and bird-watching in a surreal flooded-forest landscape.",
    10: "Transition at 24–32°C with the short rainy season beginning and afternoon storms returning. The Commewijne River plantation district is accessible by ferry and bicycle, revealing Suriname's complex colonial history through ruins and restored estates.",
    11: "Short rainy season at 24–31°C with increasing precipitation but nothing that prevents travel. Suriname's Independence Day on November 25th brings parades and celebrations that highlight the country's remarkable ethnic diversity.",
    12: "Rainy season continues at 24–31°C with the holiday period bringing Paramaribo's party scene to life. The city's nightlife blends Kaseko, Caribbean beats, and Dutch-influenced pop in a way that exists nowhere else on Earth.",
  },
  'ss-southsudan': {
    1: "Dry season at 25–38°C with scorching temperatures in the north and wildlife concentrating around remaining water sources. The Sudd wetland — one of the world's largest — contracts dramatically, and the pastoral Dinka and Nuer communities move cattle to the receding rivers.",
    2: "Extreme dry heat at 27–40°C with some of the highest temperatures in East Africa. The annual cattle camps along the Nile are a photographer's dream if you can arrange access with experienced local guides and proper security.",
    3: "Still dry and blistering at 28–40°C as the landscape awaits the rains with visible desperation. The wildlife in Boma National Park — if accessible — includes some of the last great African migrations, though infrastructure is virtually nonexistent.",
    4: "Rainy season begins at 26–36°C with the first storms bringing dramatic relief and the landscape greening almost overnight. Travel becomes increasingly difficult as unpaved roads turn to mud, but the ecological transformation is astonishing.",
    5: "Rains intensify at 24–33°C with daily downpours and the Sudd wetland beginning its massive annual expansion. South Sudan's cultural richness — the Dinka, Nuer, and dozens of other groups — remains largely inaccessible to conventional tourism.",
    6: "Full rainy season at 23–31°C with heavy precipitation and much of the country effectively inaccessible by road. The world's youngest nation continues its fragile peace process, and travel requires specialist conflict-zone operators.",
    7: "Peak rains at 22–29°C with the Sudd at its maximum extent, creating one of the planet's great wetland ecosystems. The birdlife is extraordinary for those who can arrange access, with shoebill storks among the prized sightings.",
    8: "Still rainy at 22–29°C with the landscape at peak green and the agricultural communities planting sorghum and millet. The country's potential for wildlife tourism is immense but remains largely unrealized due to ongoing instability.",
    9: "Rains begin easing at 23–31°C with the first dry spells allowing tentative overland movement. The cultural festivals of the various ethnic groups — wrestling matches, dance ceremonies — offer extraordinary experiences for the few visitors present.",
    10: "Transition at 24–33°C with decreasing rainfall and improving road conditions. The Nimule National Park along the Ugandan border offers some of the most accessible wildlife viewing, with hippos and crocodiles along the White Nile.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25–36°C with the landscape drying rapidly and the cattle camps reforming along seasonal waterways. Juba's small but growing restaurant and hotel scene caters primarily to NGO workers and diplomatic staff.",
    12: "Dry and hot at 26–37°C with clear skies and the Christmas season bringing celebrations to the predominantly Christian south. South Sudan remains firmly in frontier-travel territory, requiring serious preparation and experienced operators.",
  },
  'st-saotome': {
    1: "Gravana (dry season) at 24–30°C with lighter rains and the cocoa plantations (roças) at their most accessible and aromatic. These twin volcanic islands in the Gulf of Guinea are Africa's second-smallest nation and one of its most beguiling secrets.",
    2: "Warm and relatively dry at 24–31°C with the equatorial sunshine intense but manageable under the forest canopy. The Pico de São Tomé hike through cloud forest reveals endemic orchids and bird species found nowhere else on Earth.",
    3: "Transition at 24–31°C as humidity climbs and the rains begin returning. The colonial-era roças — sprawling cocoa plantations turned eco-lodges — offer atmospheric stays with creaking wooden floors, tropical gardens, and farm-to-table chocolate.",
    4: "Rainy season begins at 24–30°C with afternoon downpours feeding the waterfalls and filling the rivers that tumble through primary forest. The snorkeling around Ilhéu das Rolas — straddling the equator — is pristine and virtually unvisited.",
    5: "Full rainy season at 23–29°C with daily storms and the islands at their most lush and wild. The humpback whales begin passing through the deep waters between the islands, and the beach at Praia Jalé offers nesting sea turtles.",
    6: "Heavy rains at 23–28°C with the wettest conditions keeping some trails impassable but the forest alive with endemic birds and amphibians. São Tomé's chocolate — some of the world's finest single-origin cacao — tastes best straight from the source.",
    7: "Gravana dry season returns at 22–28°C with the coolest, driest conditions of the year and the best window for hiking and exploring. The Obo National Park covers 30% of the main island and feels like a lost world.",
    8: "Dry and pleasant at 22–28°C with the clearest skies and calmest seas making this the ideal month for visiting. Whale-watching boat trips, cocoa plantation tours, and beach time on the black-and-gold volcanic sand fill the days effortlessly.",
    9: "Still dry at 23–29°C with the gravana holding and the diving conditions at their annual best. Príncipe island, designated a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve, offers pristine forest and reef with accommodations that are rustic but deeply charming.",
    10: "Transition at 24–30°C as the short rainy season approaches and humidity builds. The sea turtle nesting season on the southern beaches is in full swing, with volunteers welcome at several conservation projects.",
    11: "Short rains at 24–30°C with increasing precipitation but still plenty of sunny mornings for exploration. The islands' Creole culture — a fusion of Portuguese, African, and indigenous traditions — expresses itself through music, food, and festival.",
    12: "Rainy at 24–30°C with the holiday season bringing festive energy to São Tomé city's pastel-colored waterfront. The chocolate harvest is underway, the tropical fruit is extraordinary, and these forgotten islands remain one of Africa's most enchanting escapes.",
  },
  'sv-elsalvador': {
    1: "Dry season at 20–32°C with blue skies, Pacific surf at its most consistent, and the coffee harvest in full swing in the western highlands. El Tunco beach draws surfers from across the Americas, and the pupusa stands never close.",
    2: "Warm and dry at 21–33°C with the driest conditions of the year and excellent visibility for hiking Cerro Verde and the Santa Ana volcano. The Ruta de las Flores village trail is blooming with bougainvillea and alive with weekend markets.",
    3: "Hot at 22–34°C as the dry season peaks and the Pacific coast towns buzz with Semana Santa anticipation. The surf remains excellent, the black-sand beaches are striking, and the ceviche de concha is a coastal revelation.",
    4: "Hottest month at 23–35°C with Semana Santa celebrations transforming every town with elaborate sawdust carpets and solemn processions. The rainy season approaches, making this the last window for reliably dry highland hiking.",
    5: "Rainy season begins at 22–32°C with afternoon storms arriving with clockwork regularity and the volcanic highlands turning emerald. The mangoes are extraordinary, and Suchitoto's colonial charm on Lake Suchitlán deserves a multi-day stay.",
    6: "Full rainy season at 21–30°C with daily downpours that locals barely notice. The countryside is impossibly green, the waterfalls in Parque Nacional El Imposible are roaring, and the pupusa remains Central America's most satisfying street food.",
    7: "Rainy at 21–31°C with a brief canícula (dry spell) sometimes offering a mid-season respite. The Pacific surf stays consistent year-round, and the beach town of El Zonte has emerged as an unlikely Bitcoin Beach experiment.",
    8: "Wet at 21–30°C with heavy rains and the agricultural valleys at peak green. The annual festivals of each town's patron saint bring processions, fireworks, and community feasts that welcome visitors with genuine warmth.",
    9: "The wettest month at 21–30°C with the heaviest rains and occasional flooding concerns in low-lying areas. The dramatic volcanic landscapes are at their most verdant, and the coffee fincas in Apaneca offer misty highland retreats.",
    10: "Rains ease at 21–30°C with the landscape lush and the Halloween-adjacent celebrations beginning. Lake Coatepeque, nested in a volcanic caldera, is stunning year-round but especially so when the surrounding hills are this green.",
    11: "Transition at 20–31°C with decreasing rainfall and the dry season approaching. The Día de los Muertos traditions blend indigenous and Catholic elements, and the Pacific surf season produces some of the year's best swells.",
    12: "Dry season returns at 20–31°C with comfortable temperatures and festive celebrations filling every town square. The coffee harvest begins in the highlands, the surf keeps pumping, and El Salvador's compact size makes multi-stop itineraries a breeze.",
  },
  'sy-syria': {
    1: "Cold and wet at 4–12°C with rain and occasional snow in the mountain regions and Damascus's old city wearing winter grey. The country's archaeological heritage — among the world's richest — has been devastated by conflict, and travel remains extremely restricted.",
    2: "Still cold at 4–13°C with the almond trees beginning to bloom across the war-scarred landscape. Damascus, one of the world's oldest continuously inhabited cities, maintains pockets of life in its ancient souqs despite years of conflict.",
    3: "Spring begins at 7–17°C with wildflowers carpeting areas where the conflict has subsided. The jasmine-scented courtyards of Damascus's old houses hint at the extraordinary cultural heritage that Syria hopes to rebuild.",
    4: "Warming to 10–23°C with the steppe east of Homs turning green and the Orontes River valley at its most beautiful. Pre-war, Syria offered one of the Middle East's richest travel experiences — from Palmyra to Krak des Chevaliers.",
    5: "Pleasant at 14–28°C with dry conditions and the ruins of ancient cities baking under a strengthening sun. Reconstruction efforts continue in some areas, but Syria remains a destination that requires specialist knowledge and extreme caution.",
    6: "Hot at 18–34°C with the summer heat settling over the inland desert regions. The Mediterranean coast around Lattakia offers some normality, with its beaches and Crusader castles drawing domestic visitors during relative calm.",
    7: "Peak summer at 20–37°C with scorching inland temperatures and the coast providing the only refuge. Syria's culinary traditions — among the Arab world's finest — survive in diaspora communities and in the resilient restaurants of Damascus.",
    8: "Blazing at 20–38°C with relentless heat and the longest days of the year. The ancient trade routes that once made Aleppo the jewel of the Silk Road now trace paths through a city slowly rebuilding from catastrophic destruction.",
    9: "Cooling to 17–33°C with the summer heat easing and the first hints of autumn in the mountain regions. Syria's future as a travel destination depends entirely on the peace process, but the potential remains extraordinary.",
    10: "Pleasant at 13–26°C with comfortable temperatures and the olive harvest beginning in the coastal mountains. The ruins of Palmyra, Apamea, and Bosra — damaged but not destroyed — await the day they can safely welcome visitors again.",
    11: "Cooling to 8–19°C with the first autumn rains greening the landscape and Damascus's famous sweets shops preparing for holiday seasons. The Damascus rose gardens, when accessible, are hauntingly beautiful in their resilience.",
    12: "Cold at 4–13°C with winter rains and snow on Mount Hermon. Syria at Christmas carries a particular poignancy — the country's ancient Christian communities maintain traditions stretching back nearly two millennia despite unimaginable hardship.",
  },
  'sz-eswatini': {
    1: "Summer heat at 18–28°C with afternoon thunderstorms and the lowveld thick with green. The Hlane Royal National Park offers excellent Big Five game viewing, and the traditional homesteads bustle with the agricultural season's demands.",
    2: "Still warm and wet at 18–28°C with the landscape at peak green and the rivers running full. The Mlilwane Wildlife Sanctuary offers safe mountain biking among zebras and wildebeest — one of Southern Africa's most unique experiences.",
    3: "Late summer at 17–27°C with rains easing and the aloe plants beginning their spectacular red bloom across the highveld. The Swazi cultural traditions — still deeply woven into daily life — are more visible here than in most African nations.",
    4: "Autumn arrives at 14–25°C with cooling temperatures and the bushveld starting its slow golden transformation. The Mantenga Cultural Village offers authentic glimpses of traditional Swazi life, complete with sibhaca dancing and craft demonstrations.",
    5: "Cool at 10–23°C with dry conditions settling in and the game viewing improving as vegetation thins. The highveld's pine forests and waterfalls around Piggs Peak offer excellent hiking, and the glass-blowing workshop at Ngwenya produces stunning work.",
    6: "Winter at 6–20°C with cold nights — especially in the highveld where frost is common — but sunny days that are perfect for outdoor activities. The Malolotja Nature Reserve's hiking trails wind through pristine montane grassland.",
    7: "Coldest month at 5–19°C with crisp, dry conditions and the game viewing at its annual best as animals gather at water sources. The Ezulwini Valley (Valley of Heaven) lives up to its name with clear mountain air and panoramic views.",
    8: "Dry and warming at 7–22°C with the first hints of spring and the iconic Umhlanga (Reed Dance) ceremony typically held late in the month. Tens of thousands of Swazi maidens dance for the King — it's one of Africa's most spectacular cultural events.",
    9: "Spring arrives at 10–25°C with wildflowers erupting across the highveld and migratory birds returning. The Incwala (Kingship) ceremony, when held, is Eswatini's most sacred ritual — deeply meaningful and rarely witnessed by outsiders.",
    10: "Warming to 13–27°C with the first spring rains reviving the landscape and the jacaranda trees blooming purple in the towns. The craft markets at Ezulwini and Malkerns sell beautiful handwoven sisal baskets and batik fabrics.",
    11: "Summer building at 15–28°C with increasing afternoon storms and the countryside rapidly greening. The Big Game Parks properties offer excellent value compared to neighboring South Africa, with fewer tourists and a more intimate atmosphere.",
    12: "Full summer at 17–28°C with holiday energy filling this tiny kingdom and the festive season blending Christian and traditional celebrations. Eswatini proves that Africa's smallest mainland country packs an outsized cultural and natural punch.",
  },
  'tc-turks-caicos': {
    1: "Dry season at 23–27°C with the trade winds keeping humidity manageable and Grace Bay Beach living up to its perennial best-beach rankings. Whale-watching season begins as humpbacks pass through the Turks Island Passage on their winter migration.",
    2: "Perfect at 23–27°C with minimal rain, clear turquoise waters, and peak whale-watching as humpbacks congregate between Grand Turk and Salt Cay. The Valentine's Day wedding crowd descends, and resort prices reflect the flawless conditions.",
    3: "Still ideal at 24–28°C with dry conditions and the diving visibility at its absolute best — wall dives along the 7,000-foot dropoff are heart-stopping. The Annual Music and Cultural Festival often falls around this period.",
    4: "Warming to 25–29°C with the driest month of the year and the islands at their most polished for the peak-season finale. The bonefishing in the shallow flats of North and Middle Caicos is world-class — gin-clear water over white sand.",
    5: "Shoulder season begins at 26–30°C with slightly increasing humidity and the first chance of afternoon showers. Prices drop meaningfully, and the snorkeling at Smith's Reef and the Bight Reef remains spectacular without the winter crowds.",
    6: "Hurricane season officially begins at 27–31°C, though early June is usually fine with warm, calm seas and the lowest prices of the year. The kiteboarding conditions at Long Bay Beach are consistently excellent through the summer months.",
    7: "Hot at 28–32°C with increasing humidity and the genuine possibility of tropical weather systems. The islands are noticeably quieter, resort deals abound, and the water temperature is bathtub-warm for effortless snorkeling.",
    8: "Peak hurricane season at 28–33°C with the highest risk of tropical storms and the most affordable rates. The diving remains world-class, and the conch season — Turks & Caicos' culinary obsession — delivers cracked conch and conch salad at every beach shack.",
    9: "Still hurricane season at 28–32°C with September and October representing the highest storm risk. The brave are rewarded with empty beaches, dramatic skies, and ocean temperatures warm enough to spend entire days in the water.",
    10: "Late hurricane season at 27–31°C with the storm risk gradually diminishing and the autumn light casting the turquoise water in impossibly vivid hues. The Conch Festival on Provo celebrates the islands' beloved mollusk with tastings and competitions.",
    11: "Dry season returns at 25–29°C with falling humidity, growing crowds, and the islands polishing up for high season. The Thanksgiving week brings American visitors, and the sunset cocktail hour on Grace Bay is a daily institution.",
    12: "Peak season launches at 24–28°C with holiday visitors filling the resorts and the trade winds keeping conditions perfect. The Christmas and New Year celebrations are subdued but elegant — this is a barefoot-luxury destination that doesn't try too hard.",
  },
  'td-chad': {
    1: "Dry season perfection with temps around 25–35°C and zero rain—ideal for exploring Zakouma National Park before the herds scatter. The Saharan north is at its most tolerable, though nights can dip near freezing. Crowds are nonexistent; you'll have the Ennedi Plateau's sandstone arches to yourself.",
    2: "Still bone-dry and heating up toward 38°C in N'Djamena, but Zakouma's wildlife viewing hits its stride as animals cluster around shrinking waterholes. Harmattan dust can haze the skies, so pack eye drops and a decent lens cloth. Tourism infrastructure remains sparse—embrace the adventure.",
    3: "Temperatures push past 40°C in the south and the pre-rain humidity starts creeping in. Lake Chad's shores offer birdwatching as migratory species linger before heading north. This is your last comfortable window before the furnace of April truly ignites.",
    4: "Brutally hot at 42–45°C across much of the country—only the truly committed visit now. Early rains may tease the south, turning dust to mud on unpaved roads. Zakouma closes for the season, so pivot to cultural experiences in N'Djamena if you must.",
    5: "The wet season arrives in the south with dramatic thunderstorms and temperatures easing to 35°C. Roads become challenging outside major highways, and many parks are inaccessible. Lush greenery transforms the Sahel—beautiful but logistically punishing.",
    6: "Full monsoon mode in southern Chad with heavy rains and flooded plains. N'Djamena's streets can flood, and overland travel outside the capital is a gamble. On the bright side, the landscape is impossibly green and the Saharan north remains dry and scorching.",
    7: "Peak rainy season dumps 200mm+ on the south, making most safari destinations unreachable. Lake Chad swells to its annual maximum, and fishing communities come alive. Unless you're a researcher or an extreme traveler, this is skip-it season.",
    8: "Rain continues relentlessly in the south while the desert north bakes at 40°C. Mosquitoes are at their worst—malaria prophylaxis is non-negotiable. Cultural festivals in some regions offer a reason to visit, but infrastructure challenges remain formidable.",
    9: "Rains begin tapering in the south, though mud lingers on rural roads. Temperatures hover around 32–36°C with oppressive humidity. Zakouma starts prepping for reopening, and the Sahel's ephemeral lakes attract flamingos and other waterbirds.",
    10: "The dry season returns to southern Chad and Zakouma reopens with lush post-rain landscapes and refreshed waterholes. Temps settle to a pleasant 30–35°C, and wildlife viewing improves weekly. This is the sleeper month for safari value.",
    11: "Prime time begins—dry skies, 28–34°C temps, and animals increasingly concentrated around water. The Ennedi Plateau is accessible again with comfortable desert camping conditions. Tourism numbers tick up from 'nobody' to 'almost nobody.'",
    12: "Dry season is fully established with cool-ish mornings around 18°C and warm days near 32°C. Zakouma is excellent for elephants and big cats, and the Saharan north offers perfect trekking weather. Holiday travelers are rare here, so solitude is guaranteed.",
  },
  'tg-togo': {
    1: "Dry harmattan winds sweep south with hazy skies and temps of 27–34°C, making this ideal for exploring Lomé's voodoo markets and Koutammakou's UNESCO clay towers. Humidity is low by West African standards, and the coast stays warm for swimming. Don't miss the Epe festival if timing aligns.",
    2: "Still dry and warming up to 35°C—perfect conditions for hiking in Kpalimé's lush hills before the rains green everything up. The Fazao-Malfakassa National Park offers decent wildlife spotting with thinning vegetation. Beaches near Lomé are uncrowded and breezy.",
    3: "The first rains threaten the south while the north stays dry and hot at 36°C+. This transitional month offers a mix of dusty savanna and early blooms. Lomé's nightlife picks up as the city shakes off harmattan lethargy.",
    4: "Rainy season kicks off properly in the south with afternoon downpours and 28–32°C temps. Roads to rural villages can get muddy, but waterfalls near Kpalimé reach their photogenic peak. The voodoo culture scene remains vibrant year-round.",
    5: "Heavy rains hit the coast and southern hills—expect 150mm+ and muggy conditions around 30°C. Mosquitoes ramp up, so antimalarials are essential. The upside: waterfalls are thundering, and market life in Lomé continues rain or shine.",
    6: "Peak rainfall in the south with daily storms, though mornings are often clear for exploring. Northern Togo stays drier and makes a better bet for overland travel. Temps hover at 27–30°C with humidity that'll have you changing shirts twice daily.",
    7: "A brief relative dry spell hits the south coast—the 'little dry season'—offering a surprising window for beach time and coastal exploration. Temps stay around 25–28°C, cooler than you'd expect. The north enters its own rainy season, so stick to the coast.",
    8: "The little dry season continues along the coast with overcast but mostly rain-free days around 25°C. This is actually a hidden gem month for Lomé and the coastal lagoons. Northern rains intensify, keeping Kara and the Tamberma Valley muddy.",
    9: "Rains return to the south with force while the north gets its heaviest downpours of the year. Everything is spectacularly green but challenging to navigate off tarmac. Expect 28–31°C and pack waterproof everything.",
    10: "Rains ease across the country with lingering showers and 29–33°C temps. The landscape is at peak lushness, and birdwatching is superb in the transitional forests. Tourist numbers remain low, offering excellent value at Lomé's beachfront hotels.",
    11: "Dry season returns with dropping humidity and comfortable 28–34°C temps. This is prime time for the full Togo experience—coast to savanna in a single day's drive. Koutammakou's fortified compounds look stunning against golden grass.",
    12: "Solidly dry with harmattan haze beginning and temps of 26–33°C. Perfect for overland travel from Lomé to Dapaong, hitting waterfalls, hills, and UNESCO sites along the way. Holiday festivities blend Christian, Muslim, and animist traditions in uniquely Togolese fashion.",
  },
  'th-andaman-coast': {
    1: "Peak season paradise with 30–32°C, zero rain, and calm turquoise seas perfect for diving the Similan Islands. Phuket, Krabi, and Phi Phi are packed—book months ahead and expect premium prices. The sunsets over the Andaman are worth every baht.",
    2: "Still gloriously dry with underwater visibility hitting 30m+ at premier dive sites. Crowds remain thick at major beaches but thin out on islands like Koh Lanta and Koh Yao Noi. Temps hover at 31–33°C; the heat is real but the sea breeze helps.",
    3: "The tail end of high season brings slightly fewer crowds and the first hints of humidity building. Water temps are bathtub-warm at 29°C, and the diving is still excellent. Prices start softening—savvy travelers book now for the sweet spot.",
    4: "Shoulder season arrives with occasional afternoon showers and 33°C heat that tests your resolve. Most dive operators still run trips, and hotel rates drop 20–40%. Songkran (Thai New Year) water fights turn every street into gleeful chaos mid-month.",
    5: "The southwest monsoon arrives with serious afternoon downpours and choppy seas. Similan Islands close for the season, and some Phi Phi speedboats scale back. Hotel prices plummet and the crowds vanish—if you don't mind rain, this is budget paradise at 30°C.",
    6: "Full monsoon with heavy rain, rough seas, and 29–31°C temps. Many island resorts shutter or go skeleton-crew. The upside: Phuket Old Town, cooking classes, and temple visits don't need sunshine, and prices are rock bottom.",
    7: "Wettest month on many Andaman beaches with 300mm+ of rain and swells that close boat routes. Not the time for island-hopping but fine for mainland Krabi's jungle and hot springs. Rainy sunsets can be dramatically beautiful if you're the glass-half-full type.",
    8: "Monsoon continues but some days surprise with sunshine and swimmable conditions. Surfers flock to Kata and Kalim for the only real waves Thailand offers. Temps sit at 28–30°C with prices at their annual low.",
    9: "Still officially wet season, but September delivers more sunshine breaks than July-August. The jungle is at peak emerald, and waterfalls in Khao Lak and Krabi rage magnificently. Diving reopens tentatively at nearer sites.",
    10: "Rains begin easing, especially in the northern Andaman near Khao Lak. Dive sites start reopening with good visibility returning, and hotel prices remain low. A smart month for deal-hunters willing to gamble on a few wet afternoons at 30°C.",
    11: "The monsoon retreats and high season creeps back with sunny mornings and occasional evening showers. Similan Islands reopen around mid-month to huge excitement. Crowds build but haven't peaked—this is the Goldilocks window.",
    12: "Full high season with 30°C perfection, glassy seas, and every beach bar buzzing. Christmas and New Year pricing reaches annual highs at Phuket and Phi Phi. The diving is pristine, the sunsets legendary, and the whole coast hums with tropical energy.",
  },
  'th-bangkok-central': {
    1: "Cool season's grand finale with 22–32°C, low humidity, and Bangkok's rooftop bars at their most pleasant. The Grand Palace and Chatuchak Market are busy with tourists but manageable on weekdays. Ayutthaya day trips are comfortable without the usual sweat-drenching heat.",
    2: "Temperatures start climbing toward 33°C but humidity stays moderate—still a great window for temple-hopping and street food marathons. Chinese New Year lights up Yaowarat (Chinatown) with dragon dances and legendary feasting. Book river hotels early for the festivities.",
    3: "The hot season announces itself at 35°C+ and the city shifts into air-conditioned survival mode. Mall culture peaks as locals and tourists alike seek refuge between sightseeing bursts. Evening floating markets and rooftop cocktails become the rhythm.",
    4: "Bangkok's hottest month regularly hits 37–40°C with stifling humidity building toward monsoon. Songkran mid-month transforms the city into the world's greatest water fight—gloriously chaotic and utterly drenching. Schedule temple visits for early morning or skip them entirely for splash zones.",
    5: "Monsoon rains arrive with dramatic afternoon thunderstorms that cool temps to a still-warm 32–34°C. Flash flooding on some streets is part of the Bangkok experience—waterproof your bag and roll with it. Crowds thin and hotel rates drop noticeably.",
    6: "Steady rains, 30–33°C, and humidity that makes walking between Skytrain stations an athletic event. This is peak time for indoor Bangkok: cooking schools, massage courses, and the city's incredible shopping malls. Canal boat rides in the rain have their own moody charm.",
    7: "One of the wetter months with daily downpours but also sunny mornings perfect for early temple visits. The heat is less punishing than April at 30–32°C, and tourist sites are mercifully uncrowded. Ayutthaya's ruins in rain carry a haunting beauty.",
    8: "Rain continues but Bangkok barely slows down—the BTS and MRT keep the city navigable regardless. Temps hold at 29–32°C and the street food scene is year-round spectacular. Mother's Day (Aug 12) sees the city draped in blue and celebrations across the capital.",
    9: "Often Bangkok's wettest month with potential for significant flooding in low-lying areas. The Chao Phraya runs high and brown, and some riverside restaurants elevate their seating. At 30–32°C with saturated air, carry an umbrella like a local.",
    10: "Rains begin tapering with longer dry spells between storms. The Vegetarian Festival brings spectacular street food to Chinatown, and temps ease to a pleasant 29–31°C. This shoulder month offers good value before high season pricing kicks in.",
    11: "Cool season arrives like a gift—humidity drops, temps settle to 24–31°C, and Bangkok becomes genuinely pleasant for walking. Loy Krathong sees thousands of candlelit lotus floats launched on waterways citywide. Tourist numbers climb but the weather makes it worthwhile.",
    12: "Peak season perfection at 21–31°C with crisp mornings and golden afternoon light. The city buzzes with holiday energy, night markets expand, and rooftop bars fill up with sunset chasers. Book everything well in advance—Bangkok in December is deservedly popular.",
  },
  'th-chiang-mai-north': {
    1: "Cool season bliss with 15–28°C and mountain mornings that actually require a light jacket—a novelty in Thailand. The Bo Sang umbrella festival adds color to already stunning temple scenery. Hill tribe treks and elephant sanctuaries are at their most comfortable.",
    2: "Still cool and dry at 17–32°C but the burning season begins—farmers clear fields and smoke haze can blanket the valleys. Air quality may dip, so check AQI before booking. Chinese New Year festivities add vibrant energy to Chiang Mai's old city.",
    3: "The notorious haze season peaks with agricultural burning pushing AQI to unhealthy levels on bad days. Temps climb to 35°C and the combination of heat and smoke makes this the worst month to visit. If you must come, stick to higher elevations like Doi Inthanon.",
    4: "Haze typically clears by mid-April as the first pre-monsoon rains wash the air. Songkran is celebrated here with more intensity than anywhere in Thailand—the old city's moat becomes a massive water war zone. Temps hit 36–38°C between soakings.",
    5: "Monsoon arrives with afternoon thunderstorms that drop temps to a pleasant 28–33°C and wash the mountains emerald green. Rice paddies begin flooding, creating Instagram-perfect landscapes. Crowds are thin, prices are low, and the air is finally fresh.",
    6: "Rainy season settles in with daily showers and 27–32°C temps. Waterfalls around Chiang Mai are at their most spectacular, and the surrounding hills glow an almost unrealistic green. Trekking is still possible with a good rain jacket and flexible attitude.",
    7: "Steady monsoon rains with lush landscapes and 26–31°C. The night bazaar continues rain or shine, and cooking class operators are happy to have you. This is when Chiang Mai feels most like a local city rather than a tourist hub.",
    8: "Similar to July with reliable afternoon rains and morning sunshine. Coffee culture thrives in Chiang Mai's hip cafes, and this is prime time to settle into a digital nomad rhythm. Temps stay comfortable at 25–31°C with cool mountain nights.",
    9: "The wettest month in Chiang Mai with potential for road flooding in rural areas. Rice terraces near Mae Chaem are at peak beauty with golden-green stalks before harvest. Hardy travelers enjoy waterfall pools at their most thunderous.",
    10: "Rains ease dramatically by late October and the countryside glows golden as rice harvest begins. Temps drop to a delightful 22–30°C, and the famous Yi Peng lantern festival sometimes falls this month. The air is clean and the crowds haven't arrived yet.",
    11: "Cool season begins in earnest with 18–28°C and mountain mornings that feel crisp and fresh. Yi Peng and Loy Krathong create magical evenings of floating lanterns and candlelit waterways. This is arguably Chiang Mai's most enchanting month.",
    12: "Peak season perfection with 15–27°C, zero rain, and crystal-clear mountain views. Christmas markets pop up alongside traditional Thai festivities, and every guesthouse in the old city fills up. Doi Inthanon may dip near freezing at summit—pack layers.",
  },
  'th-gulf-coast': {
    1: "Post-monsoon clarity on Koh Samui and Koh Phangan with 26–30°C and calming seas—a great alternative to the pricier Andaman side. The northeast monsoon's tail delivers occasional showers but mostly sunny days. Full Moon Parties resume their monthly madness on Phangan.",
    2: "Arguably the Gulf's best month—dry, sunny, 27–31°C with calm waters and excellent visibility for Sail Rock diving. Koh Tao's dive schools are busy but not overwhelmed. This is when the Gulf outshines the Andaman in both weather and value.",
    3: "Dry season continues with rising temps hitting 32°C and the beaches at their most pristine. Chumphon and Surat Thani's coastal areas are less touristed alternatives to the islands. Water temps are bathwater-warm and perfect for snorkeling.",
    4: "Hot and humid at 33–35°C but still largely dry on the Gulf coast. Songkran celebrations on the islands are more relaxed than Bangkok's urban warfare. Shoulder season pricing starts on Samui as some resorts transition to green season rates.",
    5: "Intermittent rain begins but the Gulf coast stays drier than the Andaman, making it the better bet for beach time. Temps hover at 30–33°C with building humidity. Koh Tao remains diveable, and the famous Full Moon Party stays on schedule.",
    6: "Surprisingly decent beach weather with scattered showers and plenty of sunshine at 29–32°C. While the Andaman is getting hammered by monsoon, the Gulf offers a sunny escape. Prices are moderate and crowds are manageable.",
    7: "The Gulf's driest monsoon-season month—ironic given the rest of Thailand is soaked. Temps at 29–31°C with occasional rain but nothing that ruins a beach day. This is the Gulf's secret weapon for summer travelers seeking Thai islands without monsoon drama.",
    8: "Similar to July with mostly fine weather and 29–31°C temps. Koh Samui is at its most livable, with moderate crowds and good rates. Ang Thong National Marine Park runs reliable day trips with calm enough seas for kayaking.",
    9: "Rain picks up as the Gulf's wet season begins its slow build. Seas can get choppier, but diving continues at most sites. Temps hold at 28–31°C and the islands take on a quieter, more local atmosphere.",
    10: "The Gulf's serious monsoon month arrives with heavy downpours and rough seas. Some ferry routes reduce schedules, and Koh Tao can feel isolated during storms. Flooding risk exists on Samui's west coast—check conditions before booking.",
    11: "Peak monsoon on the Gulf coast with the heaviest rains of the year and swollen seas. This is genuinely not the time for the Gulf islands—roads flood, ferries cancel, and beaches disappear under storm surge. Head to the Andaman instead.",
    12: "Monsoon retreats by mid-December and the Gulf coast bounces back fast. Christmas and New Year bring crowds and premium pricing to Koh Samui and Phangan. Late December offers 27–30°C with increasingly reliable sunshine.",
  },
  'tj-pamir': {
    1: "Deep winter buries the Pamir Highway under snow with temps plunging to -20°C or below at altitude. Most passes are closed and guesthouses in remote villages operate on survival mode. Only hardcore overlanders with serious 4x4 capability should even consider it.",
    2: "Still frozen solid with short days and extreme cold across the eastern Pamirs. Murghab sits under snow, and the Wakhan Corridor is largely impassable. The beauty is otherworldly if you can handle the conditions—think frozen rivers and diamond-sharp stars.",
    3: "Spring hints arrive in Dushanbe at 12–18°C, but the Pamir remains locked in winter above 3,000m. Snow begins melting on lower passes, creating mudslide risks on unpaved sections. Planning for a summer trip starts now—book shared jeeps early.",
    4: "The high Pamirs begin thawing with daytime temps reaching 5–10°C at altitude, though nights still freeze. Lower sections of the highway become navigable, and Khorog wakes up with spring markets. Road conditions are unpredictable—patience is your best travel companion.",
    5: "The highway opens in earnest with passes clearing and wildflowers erupting across alpine meadows. Daytime temps at altitude reach 10–18°C, and Dushanbe warms to 25°C+. This early window offers stunning scenery without summer's dust clouds.",
    6: "Prime season begins with 15–25°C at moderate altitudes and long daylight hours for epic driving days. The Wakhan Corridor is accessible, and Yashilkul Lake gleams an impossible blue. Homestay families are ready and the shared jeep network runs smoothly.",
    7: "Peak summer with the best road conditions and 20–28°C in valleys, though altitude keeps the eastern Pamirs cool at 10–15°C. The Roof of the World delivers in July—crystalline skies, 7,000m peaks, and some of the most dramatic road scenery on Earth. Book ahead; this is when everyone comes.",
    8: "Still excellent conditions with warm days and cool mountain nights. The Murghab-to-Osh stretch is at its most reliable, and yurt stays on the Alichur plateau are unforgettable. Occasional afternoon thunderstorms add drama but rarely close roads.",
    9: "Autumn gold creeps into the valleys with 10–20°C temps and the first snow dusting high peaks. The highway remains open but road crews wind down for the year. Fewer travelers mean more intimate homestay experiences and easier jeep bookings.",
    10: "The window closes fast as snow returns to passes above 4,000m. Lower Pamir and Dushanbe enjoy pleasant 12–18°C autumn weather, but the high route becomes a gamble. Travelers caught by early snow face real logistical challenges.",
    11: "Winter arrives with conviction—most of the Pamir Highway is impassable or extremely dangerous. Dushanbe cools to 8–12°C and shifts to urban exploration mode. The Ismaili cultural centers and bazaars offer a warm alternative to frozen passes.",
    12: "Full winter with -15 to -25°C at altitude and heavy snowpack blocking the high route. Dushanbe's teahouses and Central Asian cuisine become the attraction. Start planning your summer Pamir expedition—the best adventures require winter daydreaming.",
  },
  'vc-stvincentgrenadines': {
    1: "Dry season sunshine with 26–30°C and trade winds keeping things comfortable across the Grenadines. The Tobago Cays are at their turquoise best for sailing and snorkeling. It's peak season, so Bequia and Mustique fill up with yachties and the jet set—book moorings early.",
    2: "February delivers the driest weather of the year with brilliant skies and 27–30°C. Carnival season brings calypso, steel pan, and costumed parades to Kingstown. The Grenadines' anchorages are busy but the water is so clear you'll forgive the crowds.",
    3: "Still solidly dry with 28–31°C and excellent sailing conditions across the island chain. Bequia's Easter Regatta begins drawing sailing enthusiasts from across the Caribbean. Humpback whale season means occasional spectacular sightings from Bequia's shores.",
    4: "The tail of dry season with temps climbing to 30°C and the first hint of humidity building. Crowds begin thinning as North American and European visitors head home. Great value month for the Grenadines without sacrificing much in weather quality.",
    5: "Rainy season starts with afternoon showers and 29–31°C temps, though mornings typically stay bright. The volcanic peaks of St. Vincent get the most rain, while the southern Grenadines stay drier. Prices drop across the board—shoulder season deals abound.",
    6: "Properly wet with daily showers and 28–31°C humidity that coats everything. Hurricane season officially begins, though June rarely sees action this far south. Diving conditions can still be excellent between rain bands, and Union Island's kitesurfing picks up with stronger winds.",
    7: "Wet and warm at 28–31°C with lush green hillsides on St. Vincent. Tourist numbers hit their annual low, making this ideal for budget travelers and those seeking authentic Caribbean pace. La Soufrière volcano hikes are dramatic in the misty rain.",
    8: "Peak hurricane awareness month, though the Grenadines' southern location offers some protection. Rain is regular, temps hover at 28–31°C, and the sailing community largely relocates south of the hurricane belt. Restaurants and bars remain open with a locals-only vibe.",
    9: "Statistically the highest hurricane risk month—check forecasts obsessively if you visit. Rain is heavy, seas can be rough, and some businesses take the month off. That said, storm-free days offer empty beaches and the warmest water temps of the year at 29°C.",
    10: "Hurricane season begins winding down with rains persisting at 28–30°C. The islands start waking up for the approaching high season, and late October can offer excellent deals. Grenadines sunsets take on a particularly dramatic quality with building cumulus clouds.",
    11: "The transition month—rains ease, humidity drops, and the first winter visitors arrive. Temps at 27–30°C are lovely, and the water clarity improves weekly. Yacht charter companies launch early-bird season rates that represent genuine value.",
    12: "Dry season returns with 26–30°C, sparkling seas, and the Grenadines at their magazine-cover best. Christmas week brings the yachting elite to Mustique and the Tobago Cays, with prices to match. Nine Mornings Festival on St. Vincent adds uniquely local pre-dawn celebrations.",
  },
  've-angelfalls': {
    1: "Dry season means reduced flow at Angel Falls—it may thin to a misty veil rather than the thundering cascade of brochure photos. Gran Sabana's tepuis are accessible with clear skies and 25–30°C at lower elevations. This is reliable trekking weather, even if the waterfall disappoints slightly.",
    2: "The driest month turns some rivers too low for the traditional boat approach to Angel Falls. Canaima Lagoon is still beautiful, and scenic flights over the tepuis offer jaw-dropping aerial perspectives. Expect 26–32°C with brilliant blue skies over the ancient plateau.",
    3: "Transitional month as early rains begin teasing the Gran Sabana, slowly replenishing rivers. Angel Falls starts regaining flow, and the red-rock landscapes shimmer in afternoon storms. Temps at 27–32°C with increasing humidity.",
    4: "Rains pick up and Angel Falls begins its transformation into the roaring spectacle it's famous for. River levels rise enough for reliable motorized canoe access from Canaima. At 26–30°C with daily showers, pack waterproof gear and prepare for mud on trails.",
    5: "Wet season establishes with heavy daily rains and Angel Falls at impressive volume. The canoe journey up the Churún River is reliable, and the surrounding jungle explodes with wildlife. Expect 25–29°C, leeches, and some of the most primordial scenery on Earth.",
    6: "Full monsoon delivers Angel Falls at near-peak flow—the 979m plunge is absolutely thunderous. Trails are muddy and river crossings can be challenging, but this is the spectacle you came for. Clouds frequently shroud the summit, building suspense before dramatic reveals.",
    7: "Peak rainy season with Angel Falls at maximum fury and the Gran Sabana's rivers swollen and fast. Some trails may close due to flooding, and flight cancellations to Canaima are common in heavy weather. When skies clear, the views are unmatched at 24–28°C.",
    8: "Still very wet with lush green tepuis and dramatic daily storms. Angel Falls remains spectacular, and the relative lack of visitors means intimate viewing experiences. Canaima's indigenous Pemón guides navigate high water with expert confidence.",
    9: "Rains begin easing slightly, though the landscape remains saturated and rivers high. Angel Falls stays powerful, and clearer skies offer better photography windows. This shoulder month balances impressive falls with improving logistics at 26–30°C.",
    10: "A sweet-spot month—Angel Falls still flows strongly while skies clear more frequently. The Gran Sabana's waterfalls and swimming holes are at their most inviting. Temps of 26–31°C with pleasant afternoons between diminishing showers.",
    11: "Dry season returns with Angel Falls gradually reducing flow but still impressive early in the month. The tepuis' flat summits host unique endemic species best observed now. Trekking conditions improve dramatically with drier trails and 27–32°C heat.",
    12: "Solidly dry with clear skies ideal for scenic flights over the tepuis and photography of Angel Falls' misty descent. River levels drop, so boat access can become limited late in the month. The Gran Sabana feels like a lost world at 26–31°C—because it essentially is one.",
  },
  've-caracas': {
    1: "Dry season blankets the coast and Caracas with 24–30°C sunshine and the Ávila mountain backdrop looking sharp under blue skies. Coastal beaches at Choroní and Los Roques are at their best with calm Caribbean waters. Security concerns remain real—travel with local guidance and stay informed.",
    2: "Carnival explodes across Venezuela with Caracas and coastal towns hosting vibrant parades and street parties. Temps hold at 25–31°C on the coast with near-zero rain. Los Roques archipelago offers some of the Caribbean's clearest water for bonefishing and snorkeling.",
    3: "Still dry and warm at 26–32°C with excellent beach conditions along the central coast. Choroní's cacao country combines beach time with chocolate-making visits. International visitor numbers remain low due to the political situation, which means empty paradise for the intrepid.",
    4: "Transitional month as humidity builds and the first rain showers arrive. Caracas stays pleasant at 22–28°C in its mountain valley perch. Easter week (Semana Santa) sees Venezuelans flood coastal towns—book well ahead for domestic travel peaks.",
    5: "Rainy season begins with afternoon downpours and 24–30°C temps across the coastal range. Caracas can experience flash flooding in some barrios during heavy rains. The coast stays swimmable, and Morrocoy National Park's mangrove-fringed cays remain beautiful between showers.",
    6: "Full rainy season with daily storms, though mornings are often clear and hot at 28–32°C on the coast. Mountain roads to Colonia Tovar and highland towns can get slippery. Avocado, mango, and tropical fruit season makes every market visit a sensory feast.",
    7: "Steady rains persist but rarely wash out an entire day. Caracas at 2,800 feet stays cooler at 20–27°C, and the mountain hiking is lush if misty. The coast gets rain too, but Caribbean beach days remain viable with flexibility.",
    8: "Similar to July with wet afternoons and 28–31°C coastal heat. Los Roques sees less rain than the mainland and remains viable for turquoise-water escapes. The domestic tourism low season means beaches feel spacious and accommodations negotiate.",
    9: "Often the wettest month with heavy rains causing occasional landslides on mountain roads. Caracas gets about 100mm and the Ávila slopes are at peak jungle density. Not the best time for road trips, but urban exploration and coastal dips work fine at 24–30°C.",
    10: "Rains begin easing with improving conditions week by week. The coast warms to 30°C and the water stays bathtub-perfect. This is a good month to plan if you want value without the worst of the wet season.",
    11: "Dry season returns to the coast and Caracas with clear skies and 23–29°C. The birding community descends on Henri Pittier National Park as migratory species arrive. This shoulder month offers peak conditions at pre-peak prices.",
    12: "Holiday season in Venezuela means gaitas music blasting from every window, hallacas wrapping parties, and beach pilgrimages to the coast. Temps of 24–30°C with dry skies make it perfect for Los Roques or Choroní. Domestic tourists fill coastal spots—book early or befriend a local.",
  },
  'vn-da-nang': {
    1: "Winter's tail with occasional drizzle and 20–25°C—cool by Vietnamese standards but fine for exploring the Marble Mountains and Dragon Bridge. The beach isn't ideal for swimming due to choppy seas and overcast skies. This is low season, so hotel deals along My Khe Beach are excellent.",
    2: "The driest winter month with 21–26°C and increasing sunshine. Da Nang starts warming up, and the Hai Van Pass is stunning on a clear day by motorbike. Tet (Lunar New Year) transforms the city with flower markets and dragon dances—timing varies annually.",
    3: "Spring arrives properly with 23–28°C and longer sunny stretches. The beaches become swimmable, and Ba Na Hills' Golden Bridge is photogenic without summer's humidity haze. A sweet spot month before the heat and crowds of summer.",
    4: "Warming to 25–31°C with plenty of sunshine and calm seas—the beach season is on. Surfers find small but fun waves, and seafood restaurants along the coast are in full swing. Da Nang feels vibrant but not overwhelming.",
    5: "Beach perfection at 27–33°C with hot days, warm water, and long evenings. This is when Da Nang hits its stride as Vietnam's beach capital. The fireworks festival lights up the Han River on weekends, and the nightlife scene buzzes.",
    6: "Peak summer heat at 29–35°C with intense sunshine and the driest weather of the year. My Khe Beach and An Bang earn their 'best beach in Vietnam' reputations. Sunburn risk is real—Vietnamese locals swim fully clothed at dawn for a reason.",
    7: "Still blazing hot at 28–35°C with occasional afternoon storms that provide dramatic relief. The coast is busy with domestic Vietnamese tourists on summer holiday. Ba Na Hills offers cooler mountain air as an escape from beach-level heat.",
    8: "Hot and increasingly humid at 27–34°C as the wet season slowly builds. Storms become more frequent but rarely last long. Vietnamese families pack the beaches, making this a lively if crowded time to experience local beach culture.",
    9: "The monsoon transition begins with more regular rain and 25–32°C temps. Typhoon season starts—check forecasts seriously, as Da Nang sits in the crosshairs. Between storms, the city functions normally and autumn light is gorgeous on the river.",
    10: "Peak typhoon risk month with heavy rains possible and flooding in low-lying areas. The coast can see 400mm+ of rain and rough seas. Honestly, this is the month to skip Da Nang—head south to Saigon or Phu Quoc instead.",
    11: "Still quite wet with lingering monsoon rains and 22–28°C. Flooding can affect the old town areas and outlying beaches. The rains start easing by late November, and the city begins its recovery for dry season. Deals are abundant if you're flexible.",
    12: "Transition month with decreasing rain and 20–26°C. The beaches aren't quite beach weather, but the city's food scene—banh mi, mi quang, bun cha ca—is reason enough to visit year-round. End-of-year festivities bring local warmth to match the improving skies.",
  },
  'vn-hanoi-delta': {
    1: "Winter in Hanoi means 15–20°C drizzly days that give the Old Quarter a moody, romantic atmosphere. Hot pho becomes a survival necessity rather than a tourist activity. Ha Long Bay is misty and ethereal—fewer boats mean more dramatic limestone karst scenery.",
    2: "Still cool and overcast at 16–21°C with persistent light rain that Hanoians call 'mua phun'—a fine mist that soaks you before you notice. Tet (Lunar New Year) is the city's biggest event, but many shops close for days. Time it right for incredible cultural immersion, wrong for logistics.",
    3: "Spring arrives with 18–24°C and improving skies, though humidity builds fast. The countryside rice paddies start glowing green, and Perfume Pagoda pilgrimage season fills boats on the Yen River. Hanoi's café culture is at its coziest.",
    4: "Warm and humid at 22–28°C with occasional downpours. This is lovely Hanoi—warm enough for bia hoi on tiny plastic stools, cool enough for walking the lake. Ha Long Bay weather improves significantly, making this a strong shoulder month.",
    5: "Summer heat arrives at 28–34°C with afternoon thunderstorms that turn streets into rivers for an hour. The Old Quarter's narrow lanes offer natural shade, and egg coffee tastes even better when you're sheltering from rain. Trang An and Ninh Binh are lush and uncrowded.",
    6: "Full summer with 30–35°C and muggy conditions that test your devotion to sightseeing. Ha Long Bay gets storms but also spectacular clearing-sky moments. Pack light cotton and accept that you'll shower three times a day.",
    7: "One of Hanoi's hottest months at 30–36°C with monsoon humidity that hits like a wall. The Red River Delta's rice harvest turns paddies golden—stunning from a drone, punishing at ground level. Dawn and dusk become your activity windows.",
    8: "Monsoon peaks with heavy rains and flooding risk in the delta lowlands. Temps at 28–34°C feel hotter with saturated air. Ha Long Bay trips may face cancellations in severe weather, but calm days between storms offer moody, photogenic conditions.",
    9: "Rains ease slightly and Hanoi enters its most unpredictable weather month—glorious sunshine one day, typhoon spillover the next. Temps drop to 27–32°C and the autumn light begins its legendary transformation. Mid-Autumn Festival fills the Old Quarter with lanterns and mooncakes.",
    10: "Autumn in Hanoi is widely considered the city's most beautiful season—clear skies, 22–28°C, and golden light filtering through French colonial tree-lined boulevards. This is peak Hanoi with good reason. Ha Long Bay sparkles, and the countryside glows amber.",
    11: "Gorgeous autumn continues with 18–25°C and low humidity. The Old Quarter buzzes without summer's oppressive heat, and Ninh Binh's limestone landscape looks like a painting. Tourist numbers build but the weather rewards every visitor.",
    12: "Winter creeps in with 14–20°C and grey skies that give Hanoi a Parisian melancholy. Layer up for motorbike rides and seek out bun cha joints where the charcoal grills double as heaters. Ha Long Bay is cold but hauntingly beautiful in winter mist.",
  },
  'vn-ho-chi-minh': {
    1: "Dry season rules with 28–33°C and brilliant sunshine making this one of the best months for Saigon and the Mekong Delta. Cu Chi Tunnels visits are intense but manageable in the heat. The city's rooftop bar scene is in full swing with clear skyline views.",
    2: "The driest month delivers 30–34°C with virtually zero rain—perfect for motorbike day trips to Tay Ninh and the delta. Tet celebrations transform the city with flower streets on Nguyen Hue Boulevard. Some businesses close for the holiday, so plan around it.",
    3: "Still dry and hot at 30–35°C with humidity starting to build. Saigon's nightlife district is buzzing, and the War Remnants Museum demands a visit despite the heat. Late March brings the first hint of afternoon thunderstorm potential.",
    4: "The heat peaks at 32–36°C and the first monsoon showers arrive, offering dramatic afternoon relief. Saigon transitions from dry to green, and the Mekong Delta's floating markets become even more photogenic with storm-lit skies. Carry a poncho at all times.",
    5: "Monsoon season kicks off properly with daily afternoon deluges and 29–34°C. Saigon's streets flood briefly but drain fast, and locals barely blink. The rain makes everything greener and cooler—plus it thins the tourist crowds considerably.",
    6: "Full monsoon with regular heavy rain, though mornings are usually dry and sunny. Temps hold at 28–32°C and the Mekong Delta is lush and swollen with water. Street food tastes better in the rain—huddling under a tarp with banh mi is quintessential Saigon.",
    7: "Steady rains with 27–32°C and shorter dry windows. HCMC's incredible indoor attractions—museums, markets, cooking classes—shine in wet weather. The Ben Thanh Market night scene and Bui Vien backpacker strip party regardless of precipitation.",
    8: "Similar monsoon pattern with morning sunshine and afternoon storms at 27–32°C. This is budget season for Saigon hotels, and the city feels authentically local without peak tourist crowds. Independence Day (Sep 2 prep) adds patriotic flair to the streets.",
    9: "One of the wettest months with 300mm+ of rain and the highest flooding risk. The Mekong Delta's water levels peak, creating dramatic boat journey conditions. At 27–31°C, the rain is warm, and the coffee culture provides excellent shelter.",
    10: "Rains begin their retreat with shorter storms and more sunshine breaking through. The tail of monsoon season offers good value at 27–31°C. The Mekong Delta harvest season adds golden accents to the green delta landscape.",
    11: "The dry season transition brings noticeably less rain and 27–32°C sunshine. Saigon's outdoor terrace scene reawakens, and day trip conditions improve weekly. This shoulder month offers the best balance of weather, crowds, and pricing.",
    12: "Dry season arrives with 26–32°C and festive energy as the city gears up for Christmas (yes, Vietnam does Christmas lights spectacularly) and the approaching Tet season. The Mekong Delta is bone-dry and perfect for boat tours. Saigon buzzes with year-end celebration.",
  },
  'vn-hoi-an': {
    1: "Winter lingers with 20–25°C and occasional drizzle, but the ancient town's lantern-lit streets are magical in any weather. Tailor shops are less frantic, meaning better attention on your custom silk suit. Beach days are hit-or-miss, but the culinary scene is always on.",
    2: "Dry and mild at 21–26°C with the town recovering from rainy season. This is prime tailoring and cooking class season without the summer crowds or monsoon drama. Tet transforms the Japanese Bridge area into a flower-draped wonderland.",
    3: "Spring warmth arrives at 23–28°C with increasing sunshine and beach viability. The countryside rice paddies glow vivid green, and bicycle rides through Tra Que vegetable village are idyllic. Crowds are moderate—the Goldilocks zone for Hoi An.",
    4: "Lovely pre-summer weather at 25–31°C with long sunny days perfect for beach mornings and ancient town afternoons. An Bang Beach comes alive with beach bars and surf lessons. The full moon lantern festival on the 14th lunar day is unmissable.",
    5: "Summer heat hits 28–34°C with dry conditions and buzzing energy across the old town. Cham Island snorkeling trips run reliably, and the street food scene peaks with cao lau and white rose dumpling vendors in full force. Book evening cooking classes to avoid midday heat.",
    6: "Peak summer at 29–35°C with scorching beach days and occasional afternoon storms. Domestic Vietnamese tourists arrive in droves, adding lively energy if less tranquility. The Thu Bon River's evening boat rides offer cool relief and gorgeous golden-hour light.",
    7: "Hot and busy at 28–35°C with Hoi An's tourist numbers near their peak. The beaches are packed but stunning, and the ancient town's narrow lanes offer shade between tailor fittings. Full moon nights see the town lit exclusively by lanterns and candles.",
    8: "Still hot at 27–34°C with increasing rain as monsoon approaches. The summer crowd thins slightly, and Hoi An feels more manageable. Late August storms can preview what October has in store—watch forecasts if extending into September.",
    9: "The monsoon curtain begins falling with more regular heavy rain and 25–32°C. Flooding risk rises in the low-lying ancient town—it's a real concern here. Early September can still offer decent beach days, but the trend is firmly toward wet.",
    10: "Peak monsoon month when Hoi An's charming riverside setting becomes a liability—flooding regularly submerges ground floors of ancient town buildings. Rain can dump 500mm+, and An Bang Beach disappears under storm waves. This is the month to avoid.",
    11: "Flooding risk continues through mid-November before conditions gradually improve. At 22–28°C with lingering rains, the ancient town dries out slowly. Late November rewards patient visitors with improving weather and genuine post-monsoon tranquility.",
    12: "The wet season fades with 20–26°C and occasional light rain. Hoi An rebuilds its allure with lantern-lit evenings and quieter streets before the holiday rush. Christmas brings a blend of Vietnamese and Western festivities that somehow works perfectly in this ancient setting.",
  },
  'vn-phu-quoc': {
    1: "Dry season perfection with 27–31°C, calm emerald waters, and Phu Quoc at its tropical island best. Long Beach and Sao Beach are postcard-perfect, and the night market overflows with grilled seafood. Peak season means higher prices and advance booking is essential.",
    2: "Still gloriously dry with 28–32°C and excellent snorkeling visibility around the southern islands. The island's fish sauce factories offer pungent but fascinating tours. This remains high season, so expect full resorts and lively beach scenes.",
    3: "Late dry season with rising heat to 33°C and the first whispers of humidity building. Water visibility is at its annual peak for diving and snorkeling. A great month to visit before the crowds thin and the rains arrive—best of both worlds.",
    4: "The hot transition month hits 33–35°C with occasional pre-monsoon thunderstorms that offer dramatic sunset theater. Prices start dropping from peak, and you can actually get a lounger on Sao Beach without a fight. Sunset at Dinh Cau Rock Temple is especially fiery.",
    5: "Rainy season begins with afternoon downpours and 29–33°C. Mornings stay sunny enough for beach time, and the island's interior forests come alive with cascading streams. Phu Quoc's developing culinary scene offers excellent wet-weather eating.",
    6: "Full monsoon with daily heavy rain and 28–31°C. The western beaches catch the worst of the southwest monsoon, while eastern shores stay somewhat calmer. Budget travelers rejoice—five-star resorts drop rates by 50%+ and the island feels wonderfully uncrowded.",
    7: "Wet and warm at 27–31°C with persistent rain that keeps casual tourists away. Spa days, cooking classes, and pepper plantation visits fill the rain gaps. The island's Vietnamese visitors thin out, leaving restaurants intimate and unhurried.",
    8: "Monsoon continues with the heaviest rainfall of the year—400mm+ is normal. Some diving operators reduce schedules, and the rougher beaches are off-limits for swimming. If you come for solitude and seafood at rock-bottom prices, August delivers.",
    9: "Rain remains heavy but begins showing cracks of dry weather by late September. Temps at 27–30°C feel comfortable between downpours. The island's new cable car to Hon Thom operates rain or shine with thrilling stormy-sky views.",
    10: "The monsoon wanes with less intense rain and more sunny mornings. Phu Quoc starts its annual comeback with 28–31°C and improving seas. Smart travelers book now for November arrival, locking in transitional-month pricing for dry-season weather.",
    11: "Dry season returns with dramatically improving conditions—clear skies, calm waters, and 27–31°C. The island springs back to life as resort pools fill and dive boats resume full schedules. This is the sweet spot before December's holiday premium.",
    12: "Peak season is back with 27–31°C, crystalline seas, and every beach bar and seafood shack at full throttle. Christmas and New Year pricing hits annual highs, but the island delivers on its tropical promise. Book months ahead for waterfront accommodation.",
  },
  'vn-sapa-highlands': {
    1: "Freezing fog blankets the terraces with temps dropping to 2–10°C—yes, Vietnam gets cold. The rice terraces are bare and brown but dusted in atmospheric mist. Homestay families keep charcoal fires burning, and the markets sell more scarves than souvenirs.",
    2: "Still bitterly cold at 5–12°C with heavy fog that can close Fansipan cable car for days. Cherry blossoms and peach blossoms burst into color around Hmong villages, creating surprising springlike moments. Tet celebrations here have a distinctive highland character.",
    3: "Spring arrives with 10–18°C and the terraces beginning to fill with water for rice planting. The famous mirror-like paddy reflections start appearing—photographers rejoice. Trekking conditions improve, though mud remains on steeper trails.",
    4: "Warming to 15–22°C with clearer skies and the mountains emerging from winter clouds. The terraces shimmer with shallow water and young rice shoots. This is excellent trekking season—comfortable temps, improving visibility, and fewer visitors than summer.",
    5: "The rice grows vigorously with 18–26°C and building humidity. Lush green carpets the mountainsides, and the highlands feel genuinely tropical for the first time. Afternoon rain is common but mornings offer stunning trek conditions.",
    6: "Summer monsoon arrives with heavy rain and 20–28°C. The terraces are a deep, vivid green that defies photography—you simply can't capture how green it gets. Trails can be dangerously slippery; hire local guides who know the safe routes.",
    7: "Peak monsoon with heavy rain, fog, and occasional landslides on mountain roads. At 21–29°C, the warmth makes the rain almost pleasant. Muong Hoa Valley is at its most spectacular when clouds break, but road access can be disrupted.",
    8: "Still very wet but the rains create thundering waterfalls throughout the highlands. Temps peak at 22–29°C and the rice terraces begin turning from green to golden. Late August offers early glimpses of harvest season's famous amber palette.",
    9: "The golden season begins as rice terraces ripen to spectacular yellows and oranges at 18–26°C. This is Sa Pa's most photographed month for good reason—the contrast of golden paddies against green mountains is breathtaking. Book homestays weeks ahead.",
    10: "Harvest season peaks with 15–23°C and farmers cutting rice across the terraced hillsides. The air cools noticeably and morning mist creates dreamy valley scenes. Post-harvest, the terraces take on a stubbled, rustic beauty before winter browns set in.",
    11: "Late autumn cool settles in at 10–18°C with increasingly bare terraces and clear mountain air. Fansipan may get its first frost, and highland markets shift to warm stews and corn wine. Fewer tourists mean more authentic interactions in minority villages.",
    12: "Winter returns with 5–12°C and thick fog that can confine you to your homestay (where the rice wine flows freely). Some years bring frost or even snow to Fansipan's summit, drawing excited Vietnamese tourists. The terraces sleep under grey skies, waiting for spring.",
  },
  'vu-vanuatu': {
    1: "Peak wet season with tropical downpours, 26–31°C temps, and cyclone risk that demands respect. The jungle is impossibly lush and waterfalls are at full force on Efate and Espiritu Santo. Swimming in Champagne Beach between storms is a surreal treat, but keep an eye on weather bulletins.",
    2: "The wettest month with 300mm+ of rain and the highest cyclone probability. Temps at 26–31°C with suffocating humidity. If a cyclone tracks toward the islands, evacuation plans are essential—this is not the time for remote island visits without contingency.",
    3: "Cyclone season continues through March with heavy rain and muggy 26–31°C heat. The upside: brilliant-green landscapes, empty resorts, and rock-bottom pricing. Diving at the SS President Coolidge wreck in Santo is still viable between weather systems.",
    4: "Wet season begins its retreat with lighter, less frequent showers. Temps hold at 25–30°C with gradually improving conditions. The Millennium Cave trek on Santo is at its most dramatic with high water levels and surging rivers. Crowds start building.",
    5: "The transition month where dry season starts asserting itself with 23–28°C and noticeably less rain. Visibility improves underwater, making this a strong diving month. Pentecost Island's famous land diving (naghol) ceremonies typically start around this time.",
    6: "Dry season arrives with 22–27°C and trade winds keeping the air fresh. This is when Vanuatu reveals its true magic—crystal-clear water, comfortable trekking, and active volcanoes (Yasur on Tanna) under starry skies. Tourism picks up but never feels crowded.",
    7: "Prime visiting month with 21–26°C, dry conditions, and excellent underwater visibility. Yasur volcano's nighttime eruptions are best viewed under clear winter skies. Port Vila's restaurants and cultural shows cater to increasing visitor numbers without losing their charm.",
    8: "Peak dry season perfection at 21–26°C with the driest weather and calmest seas of the year. The SS President Coolidge dive has 30m+ visibility, and snorkeling in the blue holes is transcendent. Book popular accommodations and dive operations early.",
    9: "Still excellent with 22–27°C and low rainfall. The land diving season on Pentecost may extend into September—check locally for ceremony dates. Humpback whales pass through Vanuatu's waters, adding marine wildlife encounters to an already stacked itinerary.",
    10: "Late dry season with 23–28°C and rainfall slowly increasing. Conditions remain very good for all activities, and shoulder-season pricing kicks in as operators prepare for wet season. Santo's Champagne Beach and Nanda Blue Hole are stunning.",
    11: "The wet season begins its return with afternoon showers and 24–29°C. Cyclone season officially starts November 1, though early storms are rare. This transitional month offers good weather at lower prices—a calculated gamble that usually pays off.",
    12: "Wet season establishes with 25–30°C and daily tropical downpours. Cyclone risk increases, and remote island travel requires more planning. Holiday visitors from Australia and New Zealand fill Port Vila's resorts, creating a festive atmosphere between rain bands.",
  },
  'ws-samoa': {
    1: "Wet season with heavy tropical rain, 27–31°C, and cyclone risk that shouldn't be taken lightly. The to-sua ocean trench and Piula Cave Pool are at their most dramatic with swollen water levels. Samoan hospitality shines rain or shine—fale stays with ocean views are magical even in storms.",
    2: "The wettest and most cyclone-prone month with 300mm+ of rain and 27–31°C humidity. Travel insurance with cyclone coverage is non-negotiable. Between downpours, the islands' volcanic beaches and lush rainforest are stunningly beautiful in their saturated greens.",
    3: "Rains remain heavy but cyclone risk begins diminishing. Temps hold at 27–31°C with the islands looking their most tropical. Samoan village life continues regardless of weather—attend a Sunday umu (earth oven feast) for one of the Pacific's great culinary experiences.",
    4: "Transitional month as the wet season loosens its grip. Rainfall drops and sunshine periods lengthen at 26–30°C. The Teuila Festival preparations begin, and the reef-protected lagoons become more reliably swimmable. A good month for adventurous travelers seeking value.",
    5: "Dry season begins with 25–29°C and increasingly blue skies. The ocean calms, snorkeling visibility improves, and Samoa's famous blowholes on Savai'i perform spectacularly with residual swells. Tourism is pleasantly low—you'll have beaches to yourself.",
    6: "Proper dry season with 24–28°C and trade winds creating perfect tropical conditions. Savai'i's lava fields and Afu Aau waterfall are accessible and uncrowded. This is when Samoa delivers its promise: empty beaches, warm lagoons, and the world's most genuine Polynesian culture.",
    7: "Peak dry season and prime visiting conditions at 24–27°C. The cooler, drier air makes hiking to Robert Louis Stevenson's hilltop grave comfortable. Samoan fire-knife dancing shows are mesmerizing, and village stays offer profound cultural immersion.",
    8: "Still excellent dry season weather at 24–27°C with minimal rain and comfortable trade winds. This is arguable Samoa's best month—every beach, waterfall, and reef is at its accessible best. The Teuila Festival (date varies) celebrates Samoan culture with dancing, tattooing, and canoe races.",
    9: "Late dry season with 25–28°C and the first whispers of returning humidity. Conditions remain superb for diving, snorkeling, and beach life. Samoa's unique fa'a Samoa culture is ever-present in village life—learn the protocols and you'll be welcomed warmly.",
    10: "Transition month as moisture builds and occasional showers return at 26–29°C. Seas may get rougher, but reef-protected beaches remain calm. Accommodation prices haven't hit wet-season lows yet, but crowds are thin. The to-sua trench is Instagram-perfect.",
    11: "Wet season approaches with increasing afternoon showers and 27–30°C humidity building. Cyclone season officially starts, though November storms are uncommon. Late-season dry spells still deliver beautiful beach days with fewer visitors.",
    12: "Wet season arrives with regular heavy rain and 27–31°C. Cyclone awareness is important, though Christmas in Samoa is a deeply joyful, church-filled celebration worth experiencing. The tropical downpours can be intense but pass quickly, leaving rainbows over turquoise lagoons.",
  },
  'xk-kosovo': {
    1: "Deep Balkan winter with -2 to 5°C and snowfall blanketing the Sharr Mountains. Brezovica ski resort offers affordable skiing with improving infrastructure (don't expect Alpine polish). Pristina's buzzing café culture provides warmth—the macchiato scene here rivals Italy's.",
    2: "Still cold at -1 to 6°C with reliable snow for skiing and cozy indoor exploration. Kosovo's Ottoman-era mosques and Serbian monasteries carry extra atmospheric weight under grey winter skies. Independence Day (Feb 17) brings patriotic celebrations and Pristina's infectious energy.",
    3: "Spring thaw begins with 5–12°C and the first café terraces reopening. Prizren's old bazaar and fortress start emerging from winter hibernation. The countryside mud season isn't glamorous, but the shoulder-season solitude at the stunning Deçan Monastery is worth it.",
    4: "Proper spring with 10–18°C and wildflowers carpeting the rolling hills. Pristina's newborn monument and vibrant street art scene are best explored on foot in mild weather. The café-to-bar pipeline kicks into gear as Kosovars embrace outdoor living.",
    5: "Gorgeous spring weather at 15–23°C with green valleys and mountain views from Prizren's fortress. DokuFest preparations begin in Prizren, and the food scene—burek, flija, and kebabs—is reason enough to visit. This is Kosovo's sweet spot: warm, uncrowded, and affordable.",
    6: "Summer arrives at 20–28°C with long days perfect for hiking in the Rugova Valley and swimming in Mirusha Waterfalls. Kosovo's hospitality is legendarily generous, and you'll be invited for Turkish coffee at every turn. Pristina's nightlife rivals cities ten times its size.",
    7: "Peak summer at 25–33°C with hot days and warm evenings spent in Pristina's bustling pedestrian zone. DokuFest transforms Prizren into the Balkans' coolest film and music festival. The Sharr Mountains offer high-altitude hiking relief from lowland heat.",
    8: "Still hot at 24–32°C with occasional thunderstorms breaking the heat. Bear Sanctuary Pristina is a heartwarming visit, and the Rugova Canyon's river activities peak. Kosovo's lake beaches at Batllava and Badovci are popular local escapes.",
    9: "Early autumn brings 18–26°C and golden light over Prizren's riverside Ottoman architecture. The grape harvest means fresh wine and raki in abundance. Tourist numbers (already modest) thin further, leaving Kosovo's emerging wine country to the curious few.",
    10: "Autumn colors paint the Sharr Mountains spectacular at 12–20°C. Pristina's café culture shifts from iced to warm beverages, and the cultural calendar fills with exhibitions and concerts. This is an underrated month for the Balkans' most underrated destination.",
    11: "Late autumn chill at 5–12°C with the first snowflakes possible on mountain passes. Kosovo's hearty cuisine—tavë kosi, sarma, and grilled meats—hits differently in cold weather. The monastery circuit is hauntingly beautiful under bare trees and grey skies.",
    12: "Winter returns with 0–6°C and holiday markets popping up in Pristina and Prizren. Early snow at Brezovica gets the ski crowd excited. New Year's Eve in Pristina is a surprisingly massive party—the city punches well above its weight in celebrations.",
  },
  'ye-yemen': {
    1: "Winter brings the most comfortable conditions at 20–28°C in Sana'a (at altitude) and cooler nights in the highlands. The Old City of Sana'a's tower houses are hauntingly beautiful, though the ongoing conflict severely limits safe access. Travel is effectively restricted to very few areas—expert guidance is essential.",
    2: "Still cool and dry in the highlands at 18–27°C, though conditions vary dramatically by region. Socotra Island, if accessible, offers its most comfortable weather with dry conditions and stunning dragon blood tree landscapes. Security assessments must drive every decision.",
    3: "Warming to 22–30°C with the highlands remaining pleasant and the coast heating up. The Hadhramaut Valley's mud-brick skyscrapers of Shibam are a UNESCO wonder, though access depends entirely on security conditions. Yemen's architectural heritage is extraordinary where reachable.",
    4: "Temps climb to 25–35°C on the coast while the highlands stay moderate. Socotra's endemic species are most active, and the island represents the most accessible Yemen destination. The mainland remains extremely challenging for tourism due to the ongoing conflict.",
    5: "Hot season begins on the lowlands at 30–40°C while Sana'a stays more moderate at 25–30°C. The khareef (monsoon) hasn't arrived yet, leaving the country dry and dusty. Very few international travelers visit mainland Yemen under current conditions.",
    6: "Extreme heat on the coast at 35–42°C makes lowland travel brutal. The highlands offer some relief at 25–32°C. Socotra sees its monsoon winds pick up, making boat travel to the island unreliable. Current conflict makes most of Yemen inaccessible to tourists.",
    7: "Monsoon winds batter Socotra, effectively closing the island to visitors. Mainland Yemen endures 35–42°C coastal heat while highland areas receive some rain. Tourism effectively pauses countrywide—this is the most challenging month on every front.",
    8: "Socotra remains closed by monsoon winds and seas. The mainland sees some monsoon moisture in the west with 30–38°C. The historical and architectural riches of Yemen await a future when sustainable tourism can return safely.",
    9: "Monsoon retreats from Socotra by mid-September, and access may resume. Mainland temps ease slightly to 28–35°C. The transition toward cooler weather begins in the highlands, and the ancient frankincense routes take on a golden autumn quality where accessible.",
    10: "Post-monsoon clarity returns with 25–32°C and improving conditions across the country. Socotra's alien landscape of bottle trees and dragon's blood trees is accessible again. Mainland travel remains heavily restricted, but Socotra operators cautiously resume.",
    11: "Comfortable at 22–30°C with dry conditions and clear skies over the highlands. The architectural treasures of Sana'a and Shibam are at their most photogenic under autumn light. Access and safety remain the overriding considerations for any Yemen travel.",
    12: "Cool and dry at 18–26°C in the highlands with comfortable conditions across most elevations. This would be prime visiting season in peaceful times—the mud-brick cities, terraced mountains, and Red Sea coast are extraordinary. Travel remains severely constrained by the security situation.",
  },
  'za-cape-town': {
    1: "Midsummer bliss with 25–30°C and long, sun-drenched days on Camps Bay and Clifton beaches. Table Mountain is at its clearest (the famous 'tablecloth' cloud behaves), and the Winelands are harvest-ready. Peak holiday season means crowds and prices—locals fled to the coast weeks ago.",
    2: "Still hot and dry at 24–30°C with consistently gorgeous beach weather. The Cape Town Carnival brings color to the streets, and the wine estates host harvest festivals worth a drive. Watch for the southeaster wind—locals call it the 'Cape Doctor' for clearing the air.",
    3: "Late summer delivers 23–28°C with the first subtle hints of autumn. Vineyards glow with harvest activity, and the beaches start clearing of holiday crowds. This is the insider's month: great weather, lower prices, and the languid end-of-summer energy Cape Town does best.",
    4: "Autumn arrives with 20–25°C and the Winelands putting on a spectacular show of red and gold foliage. Rain showers begin, but they're intermittent and the city sparkles after them. Restaurant season peaks as outdoor dining remains viable and the food-and-wine culture hits its stride.",
    5: "Winter approaches with 15–20°C and increasing rain, but Cape Town in the rain has a moody charm. The whale migration begins along the coast—Hermanus becomes the front-row seat. Green season rates kick in, and the Winelands are stunning under brooding skies.",
    6: "Winter settles in with 12–17°C and regular Atlantic frontal systems bringing rain and wind. Table Mountain wears its cloud tablecloth more often, and cozy Winelands fireside tastings replace beach days. Storm watching from Kalk Bay is a legitimate activity.",
    7: "The coldest month at 10–16°C with the heaviest rainfall—but between fronts, crisp winter days reveal Cape Town's dramatic mountain-meets-ocean beauty. Whale watching peaks as southern rights calve in Walker Bay. Rates are at their lowest; value is extraordinary.",
    8: "Still winter at 11–17°C with persistent rain, though wildflower season begins on the West Coast. The first fields of orange and white daisies carpet Namaqualand, and whale encounters are almost guaranteed. Pack layers and a waterproof jacket.",
    9: "Spring arrives with 14–20°C and the West Coast wildflower explosion reaching full glory. The gardens around Kirstenbosch burst with proteas and other fynbos species. Penguin colony at Boulders Beach is active with chick-rearing season underway.",
    10: "Gorgeous spring weather at 17–23°C with wildflowers fading and beach season approaching. The southeaster winds can be fierce but the days are long and sunny. This shoulder month offers excellent value with improving weather and thin crowds.",
    11: "Summer is back with 20–26°C and the beaches calling. Kirstenbosch sunset concerts begin, and the outdoor lifestyle shifts into high gear. Early booking for December-January accommodation is essential—Cape Town's high season fills months in advance.",
    12: "Peak summer with 24–29°C and the festive season turning the Mother City into a party. Long Beach sunsets, Christmas markets at the V&A Waterfront, and NYE celebrations on Camps Bay draw crowds from worldwide. Prices soar but the energy is infectious.",
  },
  'za-durban-kzn': {
    1: "Peak summer on KZN's subtropical coast with 28–32°C and afternoon thunderstorms that keep everything brilliantly green. The Golden Mile beaches are packed with holiday-makers, and the warm Indian Ocean averages 25°C for swimming. Curry culture here rivals anything in the subcontinent—bunny chow is mandatory.",
    2: "Still hot and humid at 27–32°C with regular rain that nourishes the Valley of a Thousand Hills' dramatic landscape. Drakensberg hiking is spectacular but afternoon storms demand early starts. Durban's beachfront promenade buzzes with joggers, surfers, and fishermen.",
    3: "Late summer heat at 26–30°C with the lushest vegetation of the year. The Midlands Meander offers art galleries and craft beer between subtropical gardens. iSimangaliso Wetland Park's hippos and crocs are active in warm waters. Mosquito precautions are wise.",
    4: "Autumn arrives subtly at 23–28°C with less rain and increasingly comfortable conditions. The Drakensberg's trails dry out, and Hluhluwe-iMfolozi Game Reserve offers good wildlife viewing as vegetation thins. Easter sees Durban swell with domestic visitors.",
    5: "KZN's dry season begins with 20–25°C and crisp mornings in the Midlands. The Drakensberg is stunning under clear blue skies, and San rock art sites are accessible on drier trails. Game viewing improves as animals concentrate around water sources.",
    6: "Winter brings clear, dry days at 17–23°C—perfect for hiking the Drakensberg amphitheater and exploring Zulu heritage sites. Sardine run excitement builds along the coast as massive shoals migrate north. Night temperatures can drop to 5°C inland, so pack warm layers.",
    7: "The sardine run peaks with predator-rich marine action off the KZN coast—dolphins, sharks, and whales create a marine spectacle. Days are sunny and dry at 17–23°C. The Drakensberg offers snow-capped drama and excellent clear-weather hiking. This is KZN at its adventurous best.",
    8: "Dry and warming at 18–24°C with spring on the horizon. Whale watching from the coast improves as humpbacks pass close to shore. The game reserves are prime for wildlife spotting with sparse vegetation and concentrated water sources. Wildflowers begin appearing in the Midlands.",
    9: "Spring arrives with 20–26°C and the first rain showers regreening the landscape. Jacaranda season turns Pietermaritzburg purple, and the Drakensberg wildflowers bloom. Birdwatching picks up as migratory species return to the wetlands.",
    10: "Warming to 22–27°C with increasing thunderstorm activity. The subtropical coast comes alive with spring energy, and Durban's outdoor scene ramps up. Game drives remain good in the early morning before the heat, and baby animals start appearing.",
    11: "Summer returns properly at 24–29°C with afternoon storms and building humidity. Durban Botanic Gardens are stunning, and the beaches warm up for swimming season. The Comrades Marathon (May/June route reversal) dominates KZN's athletic calendar—check dates early.",
    12: "Full summer heat at 27–31°C with daily thunderstorms and festive holiday energy. The Golden Mile is shoulder-to-shoulder, and Umhlanga Rocks fills with upmarket vacationers. iSimangaliso's turtle nesting season begins—guided night walks to see loggerheads laying eggs are unforgettable.",
  },
  'za-garden-route': {
    1: "Midsummer along the Garden Route with 22–28°C and the least rainfall of the year. Plettenberg Bay's beaches are perfect, Tsitsikamma's storms river mouth is inviting for kayaking, and every B&B is booked solid with holiday crowds. The indigenous forests are lush and the birdlife spectacular.",
    2: "Still warm at 21–27°C with long days ideal for the Otter Trail hike (book a year ahead) and bungee jumping at Bloukrans Bridge. Knysna's oyster festival preparations begin, and the lagoon glints under summer sun. Crowds thin slightly after the January rush.",
    3: "Late summer delivers 20–26°C with increasingly golden afternoon light. The forests around Wilderness and Nature's Valley are perfect for trail running and mountain biking. Whale calves born off the coast are growing, and dolphin pods surf the shore break.",
    4: "Autumn's first cool fronts arrive with 17–23°C and the Garden Route's forests turning subtle shades of amber. Rain increases but remains moderate, and the lack of crowds makes hiking trails feel private. Knysna's waterfront restaurants transition to fireplace season.",
    5: "Cool and green at 14–20°C with regular rain that deepens the forests' emerald palette. This is excellent hiking weather for those who don't mind drizzle—Tsitsikamma's big tree trail is atmospheric in the mist. Off-season pricing makes luxury lodges surprisingly accessible.",
    6: "Winter arrives with 12–18°C and the wettest conditions, though the Garden Route's rain is rarely all-day. Storms River Adventures runs year-round, and the forests are hauntingly beautiful in fog and drizzle. Whale watching season begins at Plettenberg Bay as southern rights arrive.",
    7: "Cold and wet at 10–17°C, but the whales make it worthwhile—southern right whales breach and spy-hop spectacularly from shore viewpoints. The Outeniqua Pass between George and Oudtshoorn is dramatic in winter weather. Warm up with Karoo lamb and local wines.",
    8: "Similar to July at 11–18°C with whale season in full swing. The Cango Caves near Oudtshoorn offer weather-proof adventure, and ostrich farms make quirky rainy-day diversions. Spring wildflowers start teasing in sheltered spots.",
    9: "Spring begins with 13–20°C and the landscape reawakening with fynbos blooms. Whale watching remains excellent, and the forest trails dry out for more reliable hiking. The shoulder season sweet spot—good weather, fewer visitors, lower prices.",
    10: "Warming to 16–22°C with longer days and the Garden Route shaking off winter. Knysna's lagoon sparkles, Plettenberg Bay's beaches invite early swimmers, and the forests are alive with birdsong. This is an underrated gem month.",
    11: "Spring warmth at 18–24°C with the beaches becoming proper beach weather. The Robberg Peninsula hike near Plettenberg Bay offers seal colonies and ocean panoramas. Book December accommodation now—the Garden Route is South Africa's premier holiday road trip.",
    12: "Peak summer begins with 21–27°C and the annual migration of South Africans heading for the coast. The Garden Route hums with holiday energy from Mossel Bay to Storms River. Book everything months ahead, embrace the festive chaos, and explore the world-class coastline.",
  },
  'za-kruger': {
    1: "Midsummer in the bushveld with 25–35°C, dense green vegetation, and afternoon thunderstorms. Wildlife is dispersed and harder to spot in the thick foliage, but newborn animals abound. Birdwatching is at its peak with migratory species from Europe and Asia. Malaria precautions are essential.",
    2: "Still hot and green at 24–34°C with reliable afternoon rain. The bush is lush and beautiful but challenging for game viewing—animals don't need to gather at waterholes when water is everywhere. Night drives reveal nocturnal predators active in the humid darkness.",
    3: "Late summer with 23–32°C and the rains tapering. The bush begins its slow transformation from green to gold as grasses dry. Elephant herds are active, and the Olifants River lookout offers sunset views that stop time. Crowds thin post-school holidays.",
    4: "The sweet transition month at 20–29°C as the dry season establishes. Vegetation retreats, visibility improves, and game drives start producing consistent sightings. Morning drives are comfortable without summer's oppressive heat. This is when safari magic begins building.",
    5: "Dry season asserts with 15–26°C and crisp mornings that demand a fleece on open safari vehicles. Animals increasingly concentrate around rivers and shrinking waterholes—leopard, lion, and elephant sightings improve weekly. The golden grass and blue skies are classic Kruger.",
    6: "Winter in Kruger with 8–23°C and bone-dry conditions. The bush is skeletal and visibility is extraordinary—there's nowhere for animals to hide. Night drives are freezing but rewarding, with warm blankets and hot chocolate standard issue. This is prime Big Five territory.",
    7: "Peak dry season with 7–22°C and the best game viewing of the year. Waterholes become theaters of predator-prey drama, and the major rivers attract massive herds. Malaria risk drops significantly, and the clear, dust-gold light is a photographer's dream.",
    8: "Still excellent at 9–24°C with dry conditions and reliable wildlife encounters. The bush feels vast and exposed, with animals visible at distances impossible in summer. Early wildflowers hint at spring's approach. Book premium lodges months ahead—this is Kruger's headliner month.",
    9: "Spring arrives with 13–27°C and the first Jacaranda blooms in gateway towns. Wildlife viewing remains excellent as the last waterholes concentrate animals. The bush starts greening with the first rains, and migrant birds begin arriving. A stellar month.",
    10: "The first meaningful rains transform the landscape at 16–30°C. Impala lambing season creates a feast-or-famine spectacle as predators target newborns. The bush greens up fast, but game viewing is still strong before vegetation thickens. Thunder builds dramatically each afternoon.",
    11: "Summer returns with 20–31°C and increasing rain. The bush is lush and green, and birdwatching becomes incredible as migrants arrive in full force. Game drives are warm and productive in the early morning. Malaria precautions resume as mosquitoes multiply.",
    12: "Hot and wet at 22–33°C with daily thunderstorms and the bush at full tropical density. Wildlife disperses into the thickened vegetation, making sightings more challenging but rewarding. Holiday season brings South African families—book a year ahead for December at Kruger.",
  },
  'zm-zambia': {
    1: "Deep green season with 22–30°C and daily downpours that keep the bush emerald and the roads challenging. Victoria Falls is building toward its thundering peak, and the Zambezi runs higher each week. The Emerald Season offers lower lodge rates and dramatic storm-lit skies over the falls.",
    2: "Rain continues heavily at 22–30°C with Zambia's parks largely inaccessible due to flooded roads. Victoria Falls gains power daily—spray columns visible from 30km away. Birding is exceptional with summer migrants in residence, and the landscape is staggeringly green.",
    3: "The wettest month with 21–29°C and most safari camps closed for the season. Victoria Falls approaches peak flow with a roar audible from the town. The Devil's Pool (edge of the falls) is closed—the current would sweep you into oblivion. Focus on the falls viewing and cultural experiences.",
    4: "Rains ease and the bush starts drying at 20–28°C. Victoria Falls hits peak flow—a curtain of water spanning 1.7km with spray rising 300m. You will get soaked viewing it. Walking with elephants and cultural tours in Livingstone fill the gap while safari camps prepare to reopen.",
    5: "Dry season begins with 16–26°C and improving road access. Victoria Falls remains at impressive flow, and some safari camps reopen in Lower Zambezi and South Luangwa. The bush transitions from green to gold, and wildlife viewing improves daily. This is the turning point month.",
    6: "Winter arrives with 10–24°C and the dry season firmly established. South Luangwa National Park hits its stride with walking safaris that are among Africa's finest. Victoria Falls' volume decreases but remains spectacular. Night drives reveal leopards and hyenas in Luangwa's ancient riverbed.",
    7: "Peak winter at 8–23°C with cold mornings that make hot bush coffee a sacrament. South Luangwa's walking safaris are legendary—following wild dogs on foot is a life-altering experience. Victoria Falls settles to a photogenic medium flow revealing the rock face. Dry skies, zero mosquitoes.",
    8: "Dry season perfection at 10–26°C with wildlife concentrating along the Luangwa and Zambezi rivers. Canoe safaris on the Lower Zambezi are world-class, with hippos and elephants as constant companions. Victoria Falls' volume drops enough to open the Devil's Pool for the brave.",
    9: "Warming to 15–30°C with the driest conditions and most intense game viewing. Luangwa's lagoons shrink into wildlife magnets, and the concentration of predators around water is breathtaking. Devil's Pool is at its safest (relatively speaking), and the falls show their basalt face.",
    10: "Hot and dry at 20–35°C—the bush feels like a furnace but the wildlife spectacle is unmatched. Thornicroft's giraffes, unique to Luangwa, are easily spotted against bare mopane woodland. The first storms of the season provide dramatic photo backdrops but rarely disrupt safaris.",
    11: "The first serious rains arrive at 22–33°C, greening the bush and dispersing wildlife. Some camps begin closing for the wet season. Victoria Falls starts rebuilding flow—the trickle-to-torrent transformation begins. Emerald Season rates offer outstanding value at lodges still operating.",
    12: "Green season returns with 22–31°C and increasing rain. Most safari camps close, but Victoria Falls remains accessible and impressive as flow rebuilds. Livingstone's adventure activities—rafting, bungee, zip-lining—operate year-round and are less crowded. A festive, rain-washed gateway to Zambia.",
  },
  'zw-zimbabwe': {
    1: "Green season drenches the bush at 22–30°C with daily thunderstorms and impossibly lush landscapes. Victoria Falls is building toward its April peak with increasing spray and thunder. Hwange's elephants disperse to seasonal pans, and walking safaris in Mana Pools pause for the rains.",
    2: "Peak rains at 22–30°C with muddy roads limiting access to remote parks. Victoria Falls grows more powerful daily, and the rainforest walk guarantees a complete drenching. Zimbabwe's baobabs are in full leaf, and the birdlife—including carmine bee-eaters—is spectacular. Low season pricing is the silver lining.",
    3: "Still very wet at 21–29°C but the rains begin easing by month's end. Victoria Falls approaches peak flow—this is one of the most powerful waterfalls on Earth at its maximum, and it shows. Matobo Hills' rock art sites are accessible and atmospherically beautiful in the rain.",
    4: "The transition month with 19–28°C and rapidly improving conditions. Victoria Falls peaks with a wall of spray that creates permanent rainbows. Mana Pools begins reopening, and Hwange's waterholes start their annual role as wildlife gathering points. The timing is everything.",
    5: "Dry season locks in at 15–25°C with blue skies and the bush rapidly yellowing. Hwange's huge elephant herds begin their dramatic waterhole pilgrimages—some pools attract 200+ elephants at sunset. Victoria Falls remains powerful and photogenic. Safari season is officially on.",
    6: "Winter brings 8–22°C with cold mornings and warm, sunny days. Mana Pools' legendary canoe safaris launch on the Zambezi, with elephants and buffalo on the floodplain. Hwange's photographic hides produce stunning close-up encounters. Victoria Falls drops to a beautiful mid-flow state.",
    7: "Peak winter at 7–21°C with frost possible in the highveld and world-class wildlife viewing across the lowveld. Mana Pools' walking safaris—tracking wild dogs and lions on foot—are bucket-list experiences. Victoria Falls reveals more rock face as flow reduces, allowing lunar rainbow viewing.",
    8: "Warming to 10–25°C with consistently outstanding game viewing. Painted wolves (African wild dogs) in Mana Pools are denning, making sightings reliable and intimate. The Zambezi canoe trail is at its most magical with hippo pods and fish eagle calls. Victoria Falls opens the Devil's Pool.",
    9: "Hot and dry at 15–30°C with the bush at its barest and wildlife viewing at maximum intensity. Mana Pools' bull elephants stand on hind legs to reach winterthorn pods—an iconic Zimbabwe sight. The Zambezi dries to create sandy beaches perfect for riverside camping.",
    10: "The furnace month at 22–35°C with tension building before the first rains. Wildlife is desperate for water, creating dramatic concentrated sightings at Hwange's pumped waterholes. Mana Pools' elephants are skeletally lean but powerfully present. The storms that break the heat are operatic.",
    11: "First rains arrive at 22–32°C, transforming the parched landscape overnight. Migrant birds pour in, and the bush explodes with new growth. Some safari camps close, but Hwange and Victoria Falls remain operational. The falls begin rebuilding toward their wet-season crescendo.",
    12: "Green season with 22–31°C and regular afternoon storms. Victoria Falls' flow increases visibly week by week, and Matobo Hills' granite domes look dramatic under thunderhead skies. Holiday pricing lifts at Victoria Falls, but the bush camps offer genuine green-season value.",
  },
  'mv-atolls': {
    1: "Dry season perfection with 28–31°C, minimal rain, and underwater visibility that'll make you weep through your dive mask. The northeast monsoon brings calm seas to the eastern atolls and prime conditions for manta ray encounters at Hanifaru Bay. Peak season means overwater villa prices at their most eye-watering.",
    2: "The driest month with brilliant sunshine and 28–31°C. Whale sharks cruise the South Ari Atoll with near-guaranteed sightings on snorkeling excursions. The water is so clear it looks Photoshopped—it isn't. Valentine's season makes the Maldives' romance premium even more premium.",
    3: "Still dry and gorgeous at 29–32°C with the tail end of the northeast monsoon delivering calm conditions. Diving is world-class across all atolls with visibility regularly exceeding 30m. The surf season begins on the outer reef breaks—the Maldives has a secret surf scene.",
    4: "Transitional month as the dry monsoon fades and humidity builds to 30–32°C. The first rain showers arrive, but they're brief and the sunshine dominates. Shoulder-season pricing begins at some resorts—the savvy traveler's window for five-star at four-star prices.",
    5: "The southwest monsoon arrives with increasing rain and 29–31°C. Western atoll surf breaks light up for experienced surfers. Diving shifts to the eastern side of atolls for better visibility. Manta rays begin their migration to plankton-rich channels. Resort rates drop 20–30%.",
    6: "Full wet season with afternoon rain, greyer skies, and 28–30°C. The Maldives is still beautiful—rain passes quickly and the water remains warm and inviting. Diving conditions on the eastern reefs are excellent, and whale shark encounters remain possible in South Ari. Value season is in full effect.",
    7: "Monsoon continues with reliable afternoon rain and 27–30°C. Surf season peaks on the outer reef breaks, and manta ray cleaning stations in the central atolls are busy. Some resort restaurants offer rain-season promotions. The overwater villas have covered decks for rain-watching in luxury.",
    8: "Similar wet-season conditions at 27–30°C with occasional stronger storms. Hanifaru Bay's manta ray aggregation can be spectacular when plankton blooms coincide with lunar tides. Diving visibility is reduced on western reefs but solid on the east. The Maldives in budget mode is still paradise.",
    9: "Wet season continues with the most unsettled weather at 27–30°C and potential for heavier storms. Surfing remains excellent, and the marine life doesn't care about rain—reef sharks, turtles, and mantas are reliably present. This is the deepest discount month for resort stays.",
    10: "The monsoon transition begins with improving conditions and 28–30°C. Rain becomes less predictable—some days are gloriously sunny, others bring dramatic squalls. Diving conditions improve across all atolls, and late-season manta encounters are possible. Prices start climbing toward peak.",
    11: "Dry season returns with 28–31°C and calming seas. The northeast monsoon establishes, bringing the crystal-clear visibility the Maldives is famous for. Resort occupancy ticks up and rates rise accordingly. Whale sharks reappear in the southern atolls. The turquoise transition is underway.",
    12: "Peak season launches with 28–31°C, glassy calm lagoons, and the underwater world at its most accessible. Christmas and New Year in the Maldives is the ultimate luxury splurge—celebrity-spotting on private islands is practically a sport. Book six months ahead minimum; dream about it the rest of the year.",
  },
}
